<HEADER>
A2597 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BCS-FORMULA-AZR &LR;      12-04 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BCS-FORMULA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BCS STILL IMPERFECT SOLUTION  
 3 UNBEATEN TEAMS CAUSING QUANDARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Bowl officials never openly root for a football team
to lose. They do, however, quietly pray on occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are the pants of Fiesta Bowl officials are becoming a
bit worn at the knees these days. Life would be much simpler for
them if one of the top three teams in the country, all of which are
undefeated, were to lose Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   If Tennessee, UCLA and Kansas State win, the possibility of a
split national championship exists, which would raise the cry of
those who think a playoff is the only rational way to choose the
nation's best team.
</P>
<P>
   If those three teams finish undefeated, a complicated formula
comprised of polls, computer rankings, records and strength of
schedule will determine which teams will meet in the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   And football, the game of inches, will have been turned into one
of decimal points.
</P>
<P>
   The only people happy about that would be mathematicians,
computer geeks and the fourth-grade teachers who warned that we
would someday have to know fractions and decimals.
</P>
<P>
   Early this season, Fiesta Bowl Executive Director John Junker
took offense with a suggestion in ``Sports Illustrated'' that the
national championship could be won by a team playing in a bowl
other than the Fiesta.
</P>
<P>
   Junker offered to bet the magazine $1,000 that the national
championship would be settled in the Fiesta Bowl. Magazine
officials took him up on it, and the loser will send the money to
charity.
</P>
<P>
   Should he lose, Junker, who was traveling and unavailable for
comment, will at least be able to write it off as a tax deduction.
</P>
<P>
   Entering today's games, Tennessee is No. 1 in the BCS standings,
followed by UCLA and Kansas State. Jeff Sagarin, whose computer
ranking is one of three used in the BCS formula, predicts that
Kansas State and UCLA will play in the Fiesta Bowl if all three
teams win Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee enters Saturday's games with a lead of .04 over UCLA,
which is 1.28 points ahead of Kansas State. The Volunteers beat
Vanderbilt, 41-0, last week but saw their lead shrink by .60
because their strength of schedule rating dropped 15 spots to 29.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State would benefit from a huge boost in strength of
schedule because the Wildcats are in the Big 12 title game against
Texas A&AMP;M, which is rated higher than the other two opponents in
Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Sagarin is projecting Kansas State's strength of schedule will
improve from 62nd to 39th no matter the outcome of the Big 12 game.
That's a gain of .92.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA, which plays Miami, and Tennessee, which plays Mississippi
State in the Southeastern Conference title game, should gain, but
not that much.
</P>
<P>
   If Kansas State can move up from third in the computer rankings
of the ``New York Times'' or the ``Seattle Times,'' it should be
enough to jump into the top two slots.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, more to it than that. Strength of schedule
takes into account not only a team's opponents, but also the
opponents' opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee fans should root for Marshall to beat Toledo because
Marshall played South Carolina, which played Tennessee. And the
Vols should also hope that Brigham Young beats Air Force in the
Western Athletic Conference title game because Alabama, a Tennessee
opponent, played BYU.
</P>
<P>
   If Kansas State and UCLA meet in the Fiesta Bowl, the Volunteers
would go to the Sugar Bowl, where they probably would play Florida
State. If that happens, Tennessee fans will complain louder than
they did last year when Peyton Manning didn't win the Heisman.
</P>
<P>
   The Vols, however, would still have a chance to win a share of
the national title.
</P>
<P>
   The Fiesta Bowl, its sponsor, Tostitos, and the network that
televises the four BCS games, ABC, have been promoting the game as
a national championship. But it would be hard for AP voters to
overlook the Vols, ranked No. 1 in that poll, should they win their
bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State, ranked No. 1 in the coaches' poll, also could
share part of the national title if it went to the Sugar Bowl and
beat Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   This whole process is confounding to many and invites the
question: Is this a better system than existed before?
</P>
<P>
   It is but it will never be as definitive as a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first year the Rose Bowl has joined a bowl alliance,
making the Big Ten and Pac-10 teams available to the BCS. Just last
year, UCLA would have gone to the Rose Bowl instead of the Fiesta.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS, however, has not eliminated back-room dealing among
bowls, which more than ever need to fill seats.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS bowls _ the Fiesta, Sugar, Orange and Rose _ will rotate
as hosts of the game featuring the top two teams. In other years,
they will have conference affiliations. The Big 12 champion will
come to the Fiesta under most circumstances. The SEC champion will
go to the Sugar, and the Orange will have its choice of the
Atlantic Coast or Big East champion, with the other assured of a
spot in the BCS.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves two at-large teams, and bowls don't have to pick the
highest-rated available team. A team's drawing power at the gate
will be the No. 1 factor in those selections.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Fiesta Bowl chose Kansas State over UCLA last
year, and that's why the Orange Bowl is expected to take No. 7
Florida, with two losses, over No. 5 Ohio State, which has lost
once.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket sales are more important than ever to bowls. Under the
BCS, all money from sponsorship goes to ABC. The bowls still must
pay about $4 million apiece to be a part of the BCS, and the No. 1
way to raise that money is through ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Kansas State, whose fans travel by the thousands to
see their team, is more attractive to the Sugar Bowl than Ohio
State.
</P>
<P>
   The bowls need the money to survive, but fans want to see the
best teams play each other. Those two desires have clashed since
bowls became big business.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS arrangement looks less like a destination and more like
another way station on the way to a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to be patient because it's better than what we
had,'' said Jim Livengood, Arizona's athletic director. ``I'm going
to give it a chance. But I'm not sure it's not driving us quicker
to a playoff.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
