</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-SEX-OFFENDER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON MAY BE RETURNED TO PRISON  
 NO-CONTEST PLEA COULD VIOLATE PROBATION TERMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 and SUSIE STECKNER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Tyson resumed training at Phoenix's Madison Square Garden
on Thursday as his probation officer in Indianapolis said he will
file papers next week that could result in the former heavyweight
champ's return to prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm well,'' Tyson said after a closed workout. He had no
further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Before his workout, Tyson registered as a sex offender with the
Maricopa County Sheriff's Office and plans to ``abide by the law
and train to win'' while in Arizona, his attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the small gym near 17th Avenue and West Van Buren
Street, Tyson didn't answer any questions while he signed
autographs for a small crowd.
</P>
<P>
   A member of Tyson's entourage said he would not do interviews
Thursday. His publicist, Dean Delorean of New York, said Tyson was
``dealing with legal issues.'' Delorean said he wouldn't have
anything to say until the issues were resolved.
</P>
<P>
   George Walker, the chief probation officer for Marion Superior
Court, told the Associated Press in Indianapolis that Tyson might
have violated terms of his probation as a result of his no-contest
plea Tuesday to misdemeanor assault charges in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson has been on probation since he was released in 1995 after
three years of a 10-year sentence on a rape conviction. The
probation expires in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge can do everything from nothing all the way to
imposing the originally suspended sentence, and anything in
between,'' said Walker, who intends to file papers in court on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said his petition would not be a recommendation for
possible prison time.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we actually say on the petition is to give the facts, the
facts we all read in the paper,'' Walker said. ``We want to go
ahead and get this on the record.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson started the day at the Maricopa County Sheriff's Office
being photographed and fingerprinted as part of the sex-offender
registry requirement. He listed a Scottsdale address, according to
a source. He said last week he was living in Scottsdale, but that
he would look for a different residence in the Valley, which he
said is his new home.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's local attorney, Darrow Soll, said it was unclear whether
Tyson was legally required to register.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statute seems to imply that you have to be continually
present (in the state), and he's a person who travels often,'' Soll
said. ``Nonetheless, he wanted to be law-abiding, so he decided to
err on the side of caution.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson returned to Phoenix two days after his court appearance in
Maryland in an attempt to re-establish a training regimen for a
projected fight on Jan. 16 against South African Frans Botha at Las
Vegas' MGM Grand. An official announcement of the bout had been
expected this week, possibly Thursday, at a news conference in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   According to an Associated Press report in Las Vegas, the
announcement was rescheduled for Tuesday. However, Delorean said
nothing is planned.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson intends to train at the central Phoenix gym until Dec. 26
for his first bout since he bit Evander Holyfield's ears on June
28, 1997. He then would move his training camp to Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear whether there will be an immediate decision in
Indiana on Walker's petition.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson entered his plea on Maryland charges that were filed as
the result of a scuffle with two men after a minor auto accident in
August. An out-of-court settlement was reached. A sentencing date
in Maryland has not been set. Tyson adviser Shelly Finkel expects
it to be scheduled for early next year.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesperson for the Marion County prosecutor's office in
Indianapolis said Tyson's no-contest plea complicated the probation
questions. In Indiana, there is no such plea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it would be wise to wait and see what happens with
his sentencing in Maryland,'' Beverly Phillips said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
