<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRUE HOMECOMING GAME FOR UCLA'S JOYCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Cody Joyce wanted UCLA to reschedule the Miami
game, but for a different reason than his coaches and teammates.
Today's trip to South Florida is a homecoming for Joyce, a redshirt
freshman receiver who was raised in Clermont, Fla., before moving
to Newhall four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a chance for me to see my buddies,'' Joyce said. ``My
dream was always to play for or against Miami. They were such a
powerhouse when I was growing up. I just wanted to be on the same
field with those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Clermont is five hours from Miami, but Joyce was transfixed by
the Hurricanes' success and style. He had Miami posters on his
bedroom walls. He sketched Miami players on his school folders, and
he had a Hurricanes helmet on his keychain.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they lost to Alabama (in the 1993 Sugar Bowl), I thought
I was going to cry,'' he said. ``I liked the style of the
Hurricanes. They had pizzazz. They were ornery. It wasn't good
sportsmanship, but it was fun to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes recruited Joyce after he moved to Newhall and
enrolled at Hart High for his sophomore year, but he opted for UCLA
and has one catch for 6 yards this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided this was the place I could win the national
championship,'' he said. ``And now we have a chance to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Look-alikes: In its athletes and aggression, Miami's defense is
similar to USC's. The Hurricanes attack out of a standard alignment
and yield just 344 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their front is better (than USC's), the linebackers are a
push, but SC's secondary is better,'' UCLA offensive coordinator Al
Borges said.
</P>
<P>
   Miami has one senior starter on defense, but he's a good one:
end Derrick Ham, who has 12 sacks and will be matched against UCLA
All-American Kris Farris, who has not allowed a sack this season.
</P>
<P>
   BCS update: The Bowl Championship Series formula may change next
season, according to co-creator Charles Bloom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll fiddle with it in the offseason, maybe add another
computer poll or two, like The Sporting News,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if BCS executives are pleased with the developments, Bloom
said: ``We felt all long the two best teams would play in the
Fiesta Bowl. This is the best way to do it without a playoff.''
</P>
<P>
   James Gang: Miami's junior tailback, Edgerrin James, is one of
the best the Bruins have faced this season. He's not in Ricky
Williams' class, but he's probably as good as Oregon's Reuben
Droughns and Arizona's Trung Canidate. James is averaging 111.7
yards per game. In the last five, he's gained 749 yards and scored
12 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Short stuff: Receiver Jon Dubravac missed most of the week with
a strained right hamstring but said Thursday that he will play....
Cade McNown is one of three finalists for the Davey O'Brien Award,
given to the nation's top quarterback. The others: Kansas State's
Michael Bishop and Kentucky's Tim Couch.... Coach Bob Toledo was
named Region 5 Coach of the Year by the American Football Coaches
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Practice schedule: With dead week followed by finals week, the
Bruins will practice on Friday and Saturday only (Dec. 11-12 and
18-19). They'll also practice Dec. 21-23 before breaking for
Christmas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
