<SLUG> BC-FBN-OFFICALS-CONTROVERSY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN'T ANYONE CALL THIS GAME?  
 BAD CALLS BY NFL REFS PILING UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Oakland Raiders executive Bruce Allen thinks it's
a cop-out that his team blamed the officials for the 13-10 loss at
Baltimore last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told (Coach Jon) Gruden, `You say you prepare your team and
you weren't ready for them having 13 guys (players) on the field _
the dreaded 5-3-5,' '' Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   At least he can laugh about it.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo Bills owner Ralph Wilson felt like crying last Sunday
when two questionable calls in the final six seconds cost the Bills
a 25-21 game at New England. ``We got robbed,'' Wilson said. ``It
was awful. This was the worst. It was embarrassing to the league.''
</P>
<P>
   League officials answered back Thursday by fining Wilson $50,000
for criticizing the officials.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the NFL can't fine the many fans who are in a frenzy over
the recent rash of bad calls. Everything from a coin flip to a
``Hail Mary'' pass has been botched.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL hasn't announced any fines for referee Phil Luckett
blowing the coin toss in overtime of the Pittsburgh-Detroit game on
Thanksgiving Day. But it did change the coin-toss policy, requiring
the call to be made before the coin is thrown into the air and
instructing the back judge and field judge to accompany the referee
to midfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the how they fix the officiating problem,'' one Pro
Bowl player said. ``Only in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have been victimized as much as any team. Wide
receiver Rob Moore was involved both times, and in each case the
league wrote back that ``we're wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, Moore caught an apparent touchdown pass with 8:33
left, but after a conference, referee Larry Nemmers signaled that
Moore landed out of bounds and that the pass was incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was beyond bad,'' Cardinals deep snapper Trey Junkin
said. ``It was ridiculous _ pathetic.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the officials knew they had blown the call before the
league announced ``we're wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``An official came to our sideline and told our doctors,
thinking they were coaches, `I don't know how that got overruled.
He was clearly in bounds,' '' a Cardinals assistant said.
</P>
<P>
   The many blown calls have some crying for the return of instant
replay. It has been out of the league since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals owner Bill Bidwill remains opposed to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe the game should be left on the field,'' he
said. ``In our game (in Kansas City), the official on the spot
called it a touchdown. He apparently was talked out of it.
Everybody makes mistakes _ players, coaches and officials. But the
tempo of the game should stay at its current pace and leave the
game on the field.'' &QL; 
Full-timers needed &QL; 
Others want the NFL to hire full-time officials.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit Coach Bobby Ross is in favor of hiring 16-18 full-time
officials, and each referee would be responsible for preparing and
handling his crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say they can't get anyone to do it, but that's baloney,''
Ross said. ``You have to pay them good money, but the league has
the money to do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Oakland owner Al Davis thinks the league should establish an
academy for officials where they would learn fitness and training.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there are those who want the current crop of officials to
be fined, dumped or tar and feathered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they throw the flag, sometimes they don't,'' Raiders
wide receiver Tim Brown said. ``I don't think there's anything the
league can do besides fining these guys and making them responsible
when they miss plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Tim Brown is constantly doing the wrong thing, then sooner
or later Tim Brown is not going to have a job. If they don't take
that attitude with officials, it's going to keep going downhill.'' &QL; 
League tap dance &QL; 
NFL executives maintain that criticism of officiating happens every
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like ``Groundhog Day'','' league spokesman Greg Aiello
said. ``It's very predictable. During a season, there will be
controversial calls, and everyone focuses on it for the week. This
is that week.''
</P>
<P>
   What a week it has been. It started in the Thanksgiving game
when Lions defensive back Robert Bailey recovered a fumble and
intercepted a pass but wasn't given either call by Luckett's crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like every time you look up at the replay on the
scoreboard, you were disappointed again,'' Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in overtime, Luckett thought he heard one of the Steelers'
captains say, ``heads-tails'' before the coin flip. Television
replays showed that running back Jerome Bettis called ``tails,''
meaning the Steelers should have been given the ball. Instead, it
went to the Lions, who scored on their first possession to win. &QL; 
Bunglers were busy &QL; 
Before last Sunday had ended, the officials had botched the Moore
touchdown and cost the Bills a game. First, they allowed Patriots
wide receiver Shawn Jefferson to make a fourth-down catch out of
bounds with six seconds left. The grab kept the Patriots' winning
drive alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Thursday), they can't hear the coin toss; this week they
can't see the guy out of bounds,'' Bills defensive end Marcellus
Wiley said. ``They're losing all their senses. What's next, they
won't be able to feel someone run into them?''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson then predicted the officials would call pass interference
on the Bills when Patriots quarterback Drew Bledsoe threw into the
end zone on a ``Hail Mary'' play. He was right.
</P>
<P>
   Bills safety Henry Jones was called for going over the back of
wide receiver Terry Glenn's chest, giving the Patriots a first down
at the 1. They scored the winner on the next play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could call the stock market that well,'' Wilson
said. &QL; 
He's been there &QL; 
Cardinals defensive coordinator Dave McGinnis said he could feel
for the Bills coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gut-wrenching,'' he said. ``What if you went through what
the Pittsburgh Steelers went through with the coin toss? It's too
hard to win in this league, anyway. It gives you a helpless,
helpless, helpless feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   But McGinnis' boss, Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin, said he just
wants consistency on the calls, particularly on pass interference,
where every officiating crew seems to interpret it differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen a penalty called on a `Hail Mary' play before,
but if a penalty is made, it should be called _ whether it's on the
first play or the last play,'' Tobin said. ``If you can't have a
penalty on a `Hail Mary' play, you should tackle the receiver and
not let him off the line of scrimmage.'' &QL; 
Enough with the grades &QL; 
Pittsburgh owner Dan Rooney blames NFL administrators for the
officiating problems. He said they have caused officials to be more
concerned about their grades than making the right calls,
``bureaucratic stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're gun-shy now. If they make some little mistake and they
don't call something, they're going to be graded down,'' Rooney
said. ``You're considered a good official or bad official on the
grades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they work at taking judgment away from the officials,
and I think the officials should have judgment for what they're
doing.'' &QL; 
Accountability, please &QL; 
Tim Brown said they need to be held accountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what anybody says, there's no way those guys in
striped shirts should be a reason a team wins or loses,'' he said.
``It's happening too much in the league _ two or three times with
us and God knows how many other times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (the officials) are doing it on purpose so they can
get full-time jobs. Otherwise, they have to make some serious
changes in the off-season.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
