<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWANN SAGA SHOWS NFL'S SEEDY SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Inside Eric Swann's knee is a lot of bone, very
little cartilage and a big, fat excuse.
</P>
<P>
   For the Cardinals, a convenient reason to gripe and moan.
</P>
<P>
   A convenient reason to lose.
</P>
<P>
   They can do us all a favor. They can stand behind one of their
best players, trust in his decision, see the future as well as a
tenuous present. They can look in the mirror and find a way without
him.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they allow Swann to drift alone in the winds of
conjecture and doubt.
</P>
<P>
   It is times like this when you are afforded a window into the
brutal realities of the NFL. How medical opinions can be skewed to
short-term benefits. How coaches are blinded by the immediacy of
their jobs. How legs and limbs matter only if they're available for
the next game. How useless you are if they're not.
</P>
<P>
   So before you question Swann's heart, examine your own.
</P>
<P>
   Six times, they have operated on his knees. Twice on his left,
four times on his right. And here he is, 28 years old, crawling
from game to game, prodded by the coaching staff to suck it up for
the team.
</P>
<P>
   And here is one of the most respected orthopedists in the nation
telling Swann that his career might be over if he listens to his
employers.
</P>
<P>
   Who are you going to believe? And who's looking out for the good
of whom?
</P>
<P>
   If Swann tried to play this season, he might blow out his knee
for good. Even if he did return, the Cardinals are not going to the
Super Bowl in 1999. But if this surgery works, they might get there
in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   It always gets back to vision.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when it comes to pain tolerance, Swann is no warrior.
Not a member of the wrap-it-up, tape-it-up, shoot-it-up fraternity.
He doesn't have unconditional acceptance because he's never fought
through an injury. He doesn't help himself by hiding out, talking
through agents.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a long jump from there to the damning perception that
Swann is taking the selfish and cowardly route to next season
because that's who he is.
</P>
<P>
   If this were anybody else, the team would be signing get-well
cards. But this is Eric Swann, and his reputation is clouding
everything. A reputation the Cardinals are doing their best to
exploit.
</P>
<P>
   On Thanksgiving, they released a statement saying Swann was
considering ``elective'' surgery and had ``solicited'' a second
opinion. Implicitly, they were indicting their own player.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Cardinals are upset because Swann broke
protocol. He flew on his own to Colorado, listened to Dr. Richard
Steadman, then phoned in his decision. He denied the request for a
third opinion.
</P>
<P>
   They are upset because Swann had the gall to question Simeon
Rice's work ethic in training camp. Upset because he's making so
much money, more than the combined salaries of eight defensive
starters. Upset because he doesn't have to practice and, with all
these concessions, he still won't keep the door open on a possible
return this season.
</P>
<P>
   They are also embarrassed because Steadman's diagnosis makes
their doctors look insensitive and short-sighted. On Thursday, in a
session of spin control, Dr. Russell Chick finally spoke. He
claimed the team's procedure on Oct. 28 is nearly identical to
Steadman's course of action, a claim Steadman disputed. Chick added
that Swann wasn't cleared to play anyway, and wasn't going to be
until after this week's game against the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Swann should trust their procedure, that the
pain might alleviate soon and he might be able to help the
Cardinals in their push for the playoffs. In a year that will
determine the future of the head coach, some of his staff and a
stadium that exists on blueprint.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he's not the brightest bulb in the chandelier, it
doesn't take much to spot motive. And if I'm Swann, I'm off to see
an independent specialist, too.
</P>
<P>
   And if I'm Swann, I'm wondering about loyalty, back-stabbers and
an organization that should be building a future, not risking it
all for the benefit of now. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-04-98 0014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
