<HEADER>
A2606 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-KEILBACK-     12-04 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-KEILBACK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADIO VOICE SEES COYOTES' POTENTIAL  
 KEILBACK'S BEEN THERE SINCE '79 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ After 20 years behind the mike with the same
team, Curt Keilback has seen a lot of hockey as the play-by-play
voice of the Winnipeg Jets/Phoenix Coyotes. And a lot of ``bad''
hockey at that.
</P>
<P>
   He's been with the organization as long as anyone, since the day
the franchise first joined the NHL in 1979. Along the way, after
broadcasting some 1,600 games, there were very few shining seasons
to remember.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, the Desert Dogs from Phoenix are making Keilback
forget about the dog days in Winnipeg.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all that time, the two teams that stand out in my mind are
this one right here, and the 1984-85 team,'' Keilback said. ``But
they were as different as night and day from this team. This team
wins games, 2-1. Those guys won games, 6-5.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet both teams share similar traits 14 years removed from
one another.
</P>
<P>
   The 1984-85 Winnipeg Jets won a club-record nine straight games.
The 1998-99 Coyotes had won eight in a row before losing a wild one
in Edmonton on Wednesday, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets also had a 13-game unbeaten streak in which they went
10-0-3 and finished with a club-record 96 points for second place
in the old Smythe Division. This season, the Coyotes did them one
better, going 14 straight games (12-0-2) without a loss until
running into the Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That '85 Jets team actually went 15 games unbeaten,'' said
Keilback, whose father, Jim, was the broadcast voice of the
Roadrunners during their days in the Western and Central hockey
leagues. ``It was the last 13 games of the season, and then they
won the first two games of the playoffs against Calgary.''
</P>
<P>
   After dispatching the Flames, who just happen to be the Coyotes'
next opponent Saturday night in Calgary, the Jets got swept in four
games by Edmonton in the second round of the playoffs. The
franchise has only made it out of the first round one time since,
in 1987, when the Oilers knocked the Jets out again, this time in
five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The '85 club had a chance, but the Oilers were in their heyday
with (Wayne) Gretzky and all those guys and were just too
dominating to beat,'' Keilback said. ``The Jets had plenty of
offense, though. They had six guys on that team who scored 30
goals, including their third-line center.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what really hurt them was Dale Hawerchuk went down with
broken ribs in the third game of the playoffs against Calgary and
that just killed them.''
</P>
<P>
   The six players and their goal totals: Hawerchuk (53), Paul
MacLean (41), Laurie Boschman (32), Brian Mullen (32), Doug Smail
(31) and Thomas Steen (30). They were one of only three teams to
ever accomplish the feat, and so far, they've been the last to do
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is fun to watch for different reasons,'' Keilback
said, ``but that Jets team played just a wide open, let-'em-go
style and that was exciting hockey. Barry Long, the coach of the
team, that was his philosophy. He used to always say, `Hockey's
supposed to be entertaining. It's not supposed to be dull and
boring.' ''
</P>
<P>
   This year's Coyotes team has practiced and preached defense
first, and they've played it almost to perfection. In 17 out of 19
games, the Coyotes have not allowed an opponent to score more than
two goals. On Wednesday in Edmonton, the club gave up four goals,
but it limited the Oilers to only 22 shots on goal and only nine
legitimate scoring chances.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Coyotes borrowed a page from the 1984-85
Jets, playing some fast-break hockey of their own by peppering the
Oilers with a season-high 48 shots. The fans got their money's
worth, according to both head coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone left this building and wasn't thoroughly
entertained, I'm not sure you're a hockey fan,'' Oilers Coach Ron
Low said. ``I don't know if there's enough entertainment in the
game. A lot of people walk away a lot of nights feeling cheated out
of the money they paid.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes captain Keith Tkachuk, however, couldn't care less if a
game appears dull and boring _ as long as his team keeps playing
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure (Low) and a lot of people like to see it wide open,
but I don't like that,'' Tkachuk said. ``If we're going to be
successful, we can't play a wide-open game. We've done that over
the years and look at the results we've gotten out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring, of course, to the dog days in Winnipeg, the
times Keilback remembers well but would just as soon love to
forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a feeling about this team, though,'' Keilback said.
``It's early, but this is definitely one of the best teams I've
seen play.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-04-98 0015EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
