<HEADER>
A2607 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-ESCAPEE-DEAD-1S     12-04 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-ESCAPEE-DEAD-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH ROW ESCAPEE IS FOUND DEAD
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout)   (sw) 
 By RICX LYMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Two off-duty corrections officers fishing at a bridge
on a creek leading to the Trinity River late Thursday afternoon
came across the body of Martin Gurule, the convicted murderer who
had been the target of a statewide manhunt since Friday, when he
became the first inmate to escape from death row in Texas since
1934.
</P>
<P>
   Gurule's body, still clad in prison-issue clothes and shoes, was
found at 5:30 p.m. caught in the current outside the town of
Riverside, about a mile from the Texas prison system's Ellis Unit.
The maximum security facility, surrounded by farms, dense piney
woods and the Trinity River, is 15 miles northeast of Huntsville
and is home to the largest population of condemned inmates in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   It took prison officials only a short time to confirm what
seemed obvious, that the body, which the authorities said had been
in the water for a while, was indeed that of the 29-year-old Corpus
Christi man. Gurule was sentenced to death in the 1992 murder of a
restaurant owner and a cook during a robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Fitzgerald, spokesman for the Texas Department of Criminal
Justice, said of Gurule, ``We do not have a cause of death but we
suspect drowning.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the body was found with cardboard wrapped around
the chest, which the authorities believed was used to help Gurule
get across the razor wire in his escape.
</P>
<P>
   Gurule was one of seven inmates who plotted to escape from the
largest death row in the nation by cutting through a fence
surrounding a prison recreation yard and moving onto a nearby roof.
At 12:20 a.m. Friday, the men dropped to the ground and began to
move toward the two perimeter fences surrounding the Ellis Unit
when officers in two guard towers 200 feet away opened fire.
</P>
<P>
   All but Gurule surrendered. Grule made it over the two 10-foot
fences, topped with razor wire, and into the woods that flank the
facility on three sides.
</P>
<P>
   Police dogs later lost his scent down a nearby road and the
authorities began a six-day manhunt that included guards posted
along all roads near the prison, boat patrols on the Trinity River
and teams of officers on horseback and officers with dogs picking
through the woodlands.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend one dog team found the two-inch piece of
hacksaw blade that Gurule and the others apparently used to cut
their way through the fence. But before the discovery of the body
on Thursday, there was no sign of what had become of the escaped
inmate, which led to growing speculation that he had slipped past
the officers and out of the rough woods surrounding the prison.
</P>
<P>
   The long manhunt transformed Gurule, before his escape a
little-known inmate on Texas' death row, into a nationally known
fugitive, and there were many reported sightings of him throughout
the state. What might have happened to him became a hot topic of
conversation. There was speculation that he was still hiding in the
woods or that he had made it past the police lines and forced his
way into a passing car.
</P>
<P>
   All the time, though, prison spokesmen said they remained
convinced that Gurule was still somewhere in the woods, largely
because they had no hard evidence that he was not and because the
vast majority of escapees are caught before getting more than a few
miles from prison.
</P>
<P>
   As tension mounted and pressure built on officials to explain
what had happened and where Gurule had gone, Allan Polunsky, the
chairman of the Texas Board of Criminal Justice, said prison
officials intended to bring Gurule back ``dead or alive, and it
really doesn't make any difference in my opinion which it will
be.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, officials changed their tactics, easing up on the
dog and horse patrols into the woods, hoping to make Gurule believe
that the pressure was easing and it was safe for him to move.
Still, there was no sign of him.
</P>
<P>
   So earlier on Thursday, as the manhunt moved into its sixth
morning, prison officials announced a reward for information
leading to Gurule's capture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-04-98 0017EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
