<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2609 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-SWANN-AZR &LR;      12-04 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-SWANN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTOR DEFENDS SWANN'S TREATMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Russell Chick, the Cardinals orthopedic surgeon, broke his
silence about the knee problems of tackle Eric Swann on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   And Chick said the procedure he performed on Swann's arthritic
right knee in October is essentially the same thing that Dr.
Richard Steadman is scheduled to do Monday in Vail, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   But Steadman said that Swann's agent, Steve Zucker, was truthful
when he said that Steadman had told Swann he had ``very little
choice'' but to have the second procedure, and that playing this
season on the knee as it is could cause further injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I'd say that's accurate,'' said Steadman, who maintains
his method is different.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the controversy is whether Swann, who already
has had six knee operations, could play again this season without
further surgery, or whether he would be risking his future by
trying help the Cardinals in their playoff run.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sensitive topic for both sides, and Steadman said there
is ``no right or wrong in this.''
</P>
<P>
   One aspect both definitely agree upon is that the 28-year-old
Swann has a bad problem, degeneration of the cartilage in both
knees.
</P>
<P>
   Swann is tentatively scheduled to undergo a full microfracture
procedure by Steadman, and then undergo six to seven months of
rehabilitation. The Cardinals had hoped that, with Chick's
procedure, Swann might play this season.
</P>
<P>
   The team initially announced that Chick''s Oct. 28 procedure was
an ``arthroscopic flush'' of Swann's right knee. Chick revealed for
the first time Thursday that he also did a ``microfracture''
procedure, in which holes are drilled in the bone near the area of
the defect.
</P>
<P>
   Chick said he and Steadman are in agreement on the treatment,
but disagree on whether the six-week interval between the last
procedure and the next is enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically what Dr. Steadman told (Swann), his recommendation
was to continue his rehabilitation and if he didn't improve, and
continued to have problems, that he might consider having the same
procedure done over again using a little different technical spin.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that he would protect him on crutches for nine to 10
weeks. Same procedure, exactly the same procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   Steadman confirmed that he told Swann to continue his
rehabilitation until the end of the six weeks. But he said it is
his experience that if progress hasn't occurred after four weeks,
it won't. Steadman said his method provides the possibility of
long-term relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different procedure,'' he said. ``The same concept, but
a different procedure. It's a long shot to believe the procedure in
October is going to make a cartilage cap on the bone with the
rehabilitation done the way it was done.
</P>
<P>
   ``My interpretation is, when Dr. Chick operated about five weeks
ago, he was just trying to do as much as possible to decrease the
pain and actually let (Swann) continue playing through the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``In doing so, he made some holes in the caps of the bone in a
way that allows the bone marrow to come out of the bone and it also
decompresses the bone. A lot of times the pain comes from increased
bruising in that area of the bone where cartilage is missing.''
</P>
<P>
   Steadman said that when he examined Swann, the Cardinals tackle
could not get into a correct stance and push off without pain. He
told Swann to continue his rehabilitation for two more weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Dr. Chick did was try to make it work out for the
season,'' said Steadman, who was asked if Swann could continue to
play with the knee as it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a couple of negatives about doing that,'' he said.
``One is, at least when I saw him, he couldn't really do anything
physically with the knee bent more than about 35 or 40 degrees. If
his position could be played with his legs almost straight, then he
could do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't really push off, he can't come from that position
with power and be competitive. That's one factor. The second factor
(is) the bone that doesn't have any cartilage cap on it. If it's
successful, what Dr. Chick did, the blood comes out and it feels
fine; but I think there's a potential for weakening that area with
the drilling.''
</P>
<P>
   Steadman said there could be a risk of bone fractures in the
area that was drilled. And he said his procedure offers a 70
percent chance of improvement.
</P>
<P>
   However, some members of the orthopedic community dispute
Steadman's claims.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Tom Carter, who is the orthopedic surgeon for Arizona State
and has done extensive research on the subject, said a study done
in Europe failed to support Steadman's data. Carter said the
``fibro-cartilage'' that is created by the microfracture procedure
is not as durable as normal cartilage.
</P>
<P>
   Simply, there are no miracles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people are looking for someone to give them the same knee
their parents game them,'' Carter said. ``We can't do that. There
are no magic cures.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
