<HEADER>
A2630 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VINCE-GILL04-COX     12-04 1301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VINCE-GILL04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Good boy Gill brings his charm, sincerity to music
 &HT;    By Carol Simmons
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Vince Gill, a six-time winner of the Grammy Award
for best male country vocal performance, didn't have a great deal
of formal musical training as a child, but what he got apparently
had substantial effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took some violin lessons,'' he said recently from his home
in Nashville, Tenn. But they didn't last long. ``I can't read
music. But I can kind of see where things are, and I know the
rudimentary stuff, like `Every Good Boy Does Fine.' ''
</P>
<P>
   An often-used mnemonic device to remember note names E, G, B, D
and F on the musical staff, the phrase seems to have sunk into
Gill's psyche on a deeper, more essential level.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Oklahoma, the singer-songwriter-instrumentalist is
generally thought of as an all-around nice guy, not only by fans
who respond to his seemingly open, ``oh, shucks'' demeanor, but
also by colleagues who appreciate his apparent willingness to share
the spotlight with fellow musicians.
</P>
<P>
   And as a good boy of note, Gill _ who's bringing his new
Christmas show to Wright State University tonight _ has done very
fine indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Having learned to play by ear, and seemingly able to play any
hand-held string instrument put in front of him, Gill is a bona
fide country star _ down home enough to tap into the hearts and
minds of listeners who connect with his lyrics and personal style;
skilled enough to earn multiple awards for his musicianship and
stage acumen; and yet smooth enough to become the unofficial
perpetual host of the Country Music Association's annual televised
awards show.
</P>
<P>
   The spotlight didn't turn on Gill right away, though. He started
out as a sideman in such bands as the Bluegrass Alliance and Byron
Berline's Sundance, becoming the lead singer for the group Pure
Prairie League in 1979. He performed PPL's hits Let Me Love You
Tonight and Still Right Here in My Heart in 1980-81, but then
returned to sideman work in the Cherry Bombs with Rodney Crowell
and Roseanne Cash.
</P>
<P>
   A move to Nashville in 1984 coincided with his first country
recording contract _ with RCA Records _ but most of his work still
came from backing others in the studio or hitting the road with
Emmylou Harris. His own solo career didn't really take off until
1990 _ on the MCA Nashville roster _ with the release of the hit
single ``When I Call Your Name,'' soon followed by the equally
plaintive ``Never Knew Lonely.''
</P>
<P>
   Spirited, up-tempo singles, such as ``Liza Jane,'' ``One More
Last Chance'' and ``What the Cowgirls Do,'' climbed the charts
throughout the '90s between the release of such aching ballads as
``Look at Us,'' ``Pocket Full of Gold,'' ``I Still Believe in You''
and ``Whenever You Come Around.''
</P>
<P>
   The sincerity of Gill's straining tenor gives his songs, the
ballads especially, a truthful twang that seems to come from lived
experience. But assuming they have any particular autobiographical
meaning is a mistake that causes Gill some distress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seem to be (autobiographical), seem to be,'' he said. ``
`Seem' is the operative word.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, ``The Key to Life,'' on his recently released album
``The Key,'' is about his father, who died summer before last. And
``Go Rest High on That Mountain,'' from the year before, was
inspired by the memory of his late brother. But Gill insists his
songs are primarily fictional.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's painful,'' he said, especially when stories
appear in the tabloids claiming to have information about his
personal life. ``They think everything's verbatim to my life.''
When Gill's marriage to Janis Oliver Gill _ who with her sister,
Kristine Arnold, make up the country-music duo Sweethearts of the
Rodeo _ ended less than two years ago, a wire story circulated
suggesting that fans should have seen the breakup coming based on
the songs he'd released. Gill scoffs at the idea. ``They don't know
when a song was written.''
</P>
<P>
   He concedes, however, that misrepresentation and mistaken
understanding of his work is part of being in the public eye. You
see people on television, hear them on the radio, and you feel like
you know them, even though you really can't. On the flip side, he
said he has felt the disappointment of ``loving somebody's work,
and then meeting them, you find out they're a jerk.''
</P>
<P>
   He also realizes that people may hear meanings in songs based on
their own life experiences. ``It's all about perception,'' he said.
``I'm not going to whine about that. People live their lives
through some of these songs. I've seen some of the power of some of
these songs.''
</P>
<P>
   And a lot of that power comes from the other musicians who bring
the songs to life, Gill said. ``The way I approach records is the
way you might cast for a movie. Every bit of the process is equally
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Known for his collaborative spirit in the studio, Gill has
reportedly sung and/or played with more than 400 different
musicians, including a bevy of fabulously voiced female backup
singers. ``I'm a fan,'' he said simply of the singers, many of whom
were just getting a foothold in Nashville when he brought them on.
One recent find, Sonya Isaacs, formerly of the Middletown-based
gospel group the Isaacs, will soon release her debut solo album,
which Gill is producing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My ego is such that I don't want to be the star,'' he said.
``The guitar player, the banjo player, they all bring to the table
something special, and that makes music matter to me. All those
people have different voices, different souls.''
</P>
<P>
   For tonight's show at WSU's Ervin J. Nutter Center, one of 12
stops on the entertainer's two-week ``A Christmas To Remember''
tour, Gill said he'll bring along an eight-piece band; three backup
singers; and Grammy-winning performer, songwriter and producer
Michael Omartian, who'll conduct a ``Holiday Orchestra'' of about
30 Dayton-area musicians contracted for the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they'll perform a three-hour program of seasonal music
culled from Gill's two Christmas albums _ the just-released
``Breath of Heaven'' and the 1993 platinum-selling ``Let There Be
Peace on Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a lot of elements to merge together from one city to the
next, but Gill says he trusts the musical abilities of the hired
instrumentalists. ``That's the neat thing about people who know how
to play (sheet) music and can sight read,'' he said, noting his own
inability to do either.
</P>
<P>
   He really only has one big fear about the show: ``I just pray I
can fit into the tuxedo,'' he said with a chuckle, referring to his
continuing, but far from lost, battle with weight.
</P>
<P>
   Weight issues aside, the tuxedo represents the distinctive
character of the holiday show, which while not formal in nature,
certainly doesn't aspire to the rowdiness of a honky-tonk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like `What the Cowgirls Do,' '' he said. ``It's very
different. The audience is, well, just the response is different.
The applause seems to last longer, and there's not as much
cheering. There's a reverence.''
</P>
<P>
   Gill toured a holiday show in 1993 that included half seasonal
music and half country hits. This time, with two albums of material
to draw from, it's all holiday-related.
</P>
<P>
   He said he finds the program personally inspirational on many
levels: ``musically, spiritually, all kinds of ways. I really enjoy
the content of so many of the (traditional) songs. It kind of makes
you stop and think.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he's happy to focus the entire show on Christmas music,
he knows some fans might be disappointed about not hearing their
favorite hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope nobody goes away mad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Always the good boy trying to do fine.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
