</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAC-10 AWAITS BIG PAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For three months, they were UCLA's fiercest
rivals, hoping to knock the Bruins from their first-place perch.
But for three hours Saturday, when the Bruins face Miami in the
Orange Bowl, they'll be UCLA's biggest fans.
</P>
<P>
   From Tucson to Pullman and all points between, the Pac-10 will
be rooting for 76 players and 10 coaches in powder blue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ended our (Thursday) morning staff meeting with a `Go
Bruins' cheer,'' said Arizona athletic director Jim Livengood, who
expects the Wildcats' first-ever Rose Bowl berth if UCLA advances
to the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll all be watching and cheering for UCLA,'' said Oregon
athletic director Bill Moos, whose team's Holiday Bowl invitation
depends on the Bruins. ``Once we realized we weren't going to the
Rose Bowl, we became great UCLA fans. The Bruins have unified the
conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's stakes begin with UCLA's 20-game winning streak and
skyrocket from there:
</P>
<P>
   _ A probable berth in the Fiesta Bowl, against either Tennessee
or Kansas State, for the national championship on Jan. 4;
</P>
<P>
   _ A potential recruiting windfall for every UCLA sport;
</P>
<P>
   _ $6 million in unbudgeted money to be split among the Pac-10
schools;
</P>
<P>
   _ Unprecedented exposure and prestige for a conference fighting
its time zone and the eastern bias;
</P>
<P>
   _ Arizona's berth in the Rose Bowl instead of the Holiday and
Oregon's berth in the Holiday instead of the Aloha.
</P>
<P>
   And because it all depends on UCLA getting to the Fiesta Bowl,
not winning it, Saturday's game is perhaps the most important event
in conference history.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can certainly make that argument,'' Pac-10 commissioner
Tom Hansen said. ``It's as big a football game as I can remember,
and same with other events.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Section 18 is nestled in the southwest corner of Arizona
Stadium, across the aisle from the seats given to visiting fans.
For 16 years, a group of 40 Wildcats supporters have been the
vanguard of Tucson, defending Arizona's honor in victory and
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Once, during a particularly bad performance against hated
Arizona State, a Section 18 member bit the toe of a Sun Devil party
doll, deflating it and salavging a morsel of pride.
</P>
<P>
   Section 18 members have been interviewed on local television.
Last week, on the eve of the ASU game, a few received permission to
watch highlights of past Arizona-Arizona State games in the
athletic director's box of an otherwise dark and empty stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Section 18 will gather at an east-side sports bar and
bleed powder blue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be as big a UCLA fans as we are Arizona fans,''
said Jay Gonzales, a Tucson native and Arizona graduate (1981).
``(The Miami) game is as important to us as if it were
Arizona-Arizona State. It's an extension of our season.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is the only Pac-10 school never to participate in the
Rose Bowl. But if UCLA advances to the Fiesta, the 11-1 Wildcats
are expected to receive an at-large bid to play Wisconsin in
Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   It would instantly join the 1997 NCAA basketball title as the
primary sources of pride for a college town forever in the shadows
of Phoenix, its big brother to the north.
</P>
<P>
   The potential recruiting benefits are enormous as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be able to tell recruits, `You can go to Arizona and
go to the Rose Bowl,' '' Livengood said. ``That's been hanging on
us. People say, `(Dick Tomey) is a good coach, and the kids love
him, but . . .'
</P>
<P>
   ``It would disprove more things than it would prove.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as UCLA making the Fiesta puts Arizona in the Rose, it also
catapults Oregon to the Holiday Bowl in San Diego, probably against
Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins lose and the Pac-10 bowl deck collapses, then UCLA
goes to the Rose Bowl, Arizona would play Nebraska in the Holiday
Bowl and Oregon would go to the Aloha Bowl and probably face
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The primary issue for Oregon is not pride or money, but six days
of recruiting exposure. The Ducks have 30 players from Southern
California, including tailback Herman Ho-Ching (Long Beach) and
receivers Tony Hartley (Los Alamitos) and Damon Griffin (Monrovia).
Also, quarterback Akili Smith is a San Diego native. Continuing
that pipeline is essential if they hope to compete with the Pac-10
elite in coming years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Holiday would be very important for us, not just for the
national exposure but because we recruit very heavily in Southern
California,'' Moos said. ``It's an opportunity to showcase our
program and do some recruiting during the allowable windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all going to be watching UCLA for a variety of reason,
perhaps us and Arizona more than the rest of the conference.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The six Bowl Championship Series member conferences (Pac-10,
ACC, Southeastern, Big Ten, Big 12 and Big East) are guaranteed at
least one participant in the four BCS games (Rose, Fiesta, Orange,
Sugar). They'll receive approximately $11.5 million to be
distributed among the member schools after expenses. In addition,
there are two at-large spots in the BCS worth $6 million to
whichever conferences fill the slots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to spread the money,'' Pac-10 assistant
commissioner Jim Muldoon said. ``The BCS schools didn't want to
make a second participating spot worth $11.5 million because that
would be an overwhelming financial windfall for one or two
conferences.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Pac-10 is guaranteed $11.5 for the Rose Bowl, whether
it's Arizona or UCLA, and the schools budgeted accordingly last
spring. The Bruins' berth in the Fiesta would bring an additional _
and unbudgeted _ $6 million. After expenses, approximately $4.5
million would be divided equally among the schools.
</P>
<P>
   For UCLA, which begins a $19 million Adidas contract in July,
the additional $450,000 won't make much difference.
</P>
<P>
   For Oregon and Arizona, the Fiesta money would help replenish
cash reserves depleted in recent years by facility upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   But no school needs the money more than Oregon State, which has
an $8 million deficit because of poor management, tuition increases
and sagging football attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would help a great deal,'' Oregon State athletic director
Mitch Barnhart said. ``I don't know where it would go specifically.
We'd have to see where it settled into the finances, but we've got
to reduce that deficit.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UCLA won its only national title in 1954 but did not play in a
title game because of the Rose Bowl's no repeat rule. (UCLA lost to
Michigan in the 1953 game.) Bing Crosby tried to organize an
unsanctioned UCLA-Ohio State game, but the NCAA rejected his
proposal. As football games go, the Bruins have never experienced
anything like this season's Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   What of the school's first basketball title in 1964? Financial
benefits were meager, and not only wasn't it televised, it wasn't
on national radio.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA athletic director Peter Dalis and former assistant Jim
Milhorn were attending a conference in Berkeley at the time. After
huddling in a car and futilely tuning the radio dial, they called
home to Los Angeles to get the final score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told (the players) this is the biggest game of their life,''
UCLA coach Bob Toledo said. ``It might be the biggest game in the
history of UCLA. We have the opportunity, if we win, to do
something special.''
</P>
<P>
   Hansen believes the most important football game in Pac-10
history was Washington's 44-8 victory over Wisconsin in the 1960
Rose Bowl. It signalled the conference's national emergence, he
said, and foretold the dominance of USC and Washington for three
decades.
</P>
<P>
   But for exposure and monetary reward, it cannot match next
month's Fiesta Bowl. Even USC's best teams had to share their Rose
Bowl victories with other Jan. 1 bowl game winners, and none
generated $6 million for the league.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Jan. 1 games are over, the national spotlight will
descend on the Fiesta Bowl for three days. All UCLA has to do is
get there, and everything else _ including the respect and prestige
it covets _ will follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a college football fan from the midwest or
southeast, there's probably a biased feeling toward the Pac-10,''
said former Ohio State quarterback and current ESPN analyst Kirk
Herbstriet. ``Fans are so brainwashed in those parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``For people who don't respect the Pac-10, then UCLA making the
Fiesta Bowl is a golden opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   In more ways than one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-04-98 0052EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
