r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-KANSAS-STATE-RETU     12-04 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KANSAS-STATE-RETURNER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS STATE PUNT RETURNER HAS ALWAYS BEEN TOUGH, FAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The jukes and jives of the NCAA's most
prolific punt returner began to blossom on Littlejohn Avenue in
southeast Fort Worth, where David Allen regularly joined neighbors
in an exercise called ``sideline kill.''
</P>
<P>
   The rules were simple: Street football games were of the touch
variety up and down Littlejohn, unless the man with the ball veered
toward the curb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, you were fair game,'' said Chris Freeman, 25, a Fort
Worth truck driver. ``If you ran toward the sideline, the other
guys could lay you out in the grass in somebody's yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Problem was, nobody ever laid out David Allen. Although he was
the youngest participant in those games of roughly a decade ago, he
was also the fastest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even then, nobody could catch him,'' said Freeman, who is five
years older than Allen. ``And if you did get in a good lick, he was
a tough little kid. His nose would be bleeding, but he'd just wipe
it off on his shirt sleeve and keep playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Testimonials about Allen's elusiveness and toughness do not
surprise teammates at Kansas State, who have watched him return an
NCAA record-tying four punts for touchdowns this season. Allen's
713 yards in punt returns have been a major factor in helping the
Wildcats, 11-0 and ranked second in The Associated Press poll, land
a berth opposite No. 10 Texas A&AMP;M (10-2) in tomorrow's Big 12
championship game in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   To put that in perspective, Allen has 185 more yards in punt
returns than any other NCAA Division I-A ``team'' in 1998. His
22.3-yard average is a Big 12 record, as is his 172-yard
performance in a 48-7 rout of Texas that included a career-best,
93-yard touchdown return.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, who moved from Fort Worth to Liberty, Mo., before
entering junior high school, is such a factor in the Wildcats'
arsenal that A&AMP;M punter Shane Lechler said he would alter his
normal approach in tomorrow's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't kick any balls straight to him,'' said Lechler, an
All-American who averages 43.5 yards per punt. ``I'll make him
handle everything on the run or just kick it out-of-bounds. The
last time I did something like that was against \RFlorida State's\S
Peter Warrick. And this guy is a couple of notches above Warrick.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum said Allen, 20, is ``as good as I've
seen'' as a punt returner at the college level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time he touches the ball, it's, `Look out,''' Slocum
said. ``This week will be a big challenge for our coverage team.''
</P>
<P>
   Proper deployment of Allen could prove to be a dilemma for
Kansas State coach Bill Snyder as well. The 5-foot-9, 185-pound
sophomore normally is the Wildcats' No. 4 tailback. But starter
Eric Hickson is doubtful with an ankle sprain, and backup Marlon
Charles is out with a fractured hip.
</P>
<P>
   If Hickson does not play, the Wildcats' tailback duties will be
shared by Allen (29 carries, 171 yards) and Frank Murphy (54
carries, 253 yards).
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I'll get a few more carries this week,'' said Allen,
who rushed for 1,471 yards and 19 touchdowns as a high school
senior. ``I came here to play running back.''
</P>
<P>
   But it has been as a punt returner that Allen has found his
niche. Snyder, in turn, doesn't want to wear down his special-teams
standout with carries that might make him ineffective as a return
man.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very valuable to our football team because he has a nice
knack for what he does,'' Snyder said. ``Everyone tries to do
something to limit his opportunities ... but 700 yards is an
incredible figure.''
</P>
<P>
   It represents a number Allen considered unreachable when he
volunteered to return punts last season as a replacement for the
departed Chris Canty, a first-round pick of the New England
Patriots in the 1997 NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just looking for a way to get on the field,'' said
Allen, who returned a few punts in high school but not on a regular
basis. ``I tried it and did well at it. So I set a few goals for
myself. But I never expected them to be this high or at this level.
My success has been a big surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen points to good blocking and natural instincts as his
primary survival tools. He also listed something else, a trait he
might have developed during his days as a 10-year-old playing with
teen-agers on Littlejohn Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having no fear,'' Allen said. ``Nothing bothers me back there.
Regardless of where the ball is, I want to catch every punt. And
every one I touch, I have the mind-set I want to score with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who fail to score, after all, are in danger of being
reduced to ``sideline kill'' by the bigger guys in the
neighborhood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
