<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-OLDER-LINE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRITTY OLD MEN: STARS BUILD SENIOR CITIZENS LINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ Guy Carbonneau said he doesn't
feel 38, so why should he play that way.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, the guy is willing to drop the gloves and throw a few
punches if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever it takes,'' said Carbonneau, with the sly smile that
shows the wear and tear of having played 1,194 NHL games.
</P>
<P>
   That's the attitude Stars coach Ken Hitchcock has taken with the
most veteran members of his veteran-heavy team. The Stars have the
second-oldest roster in the NHL, but instead of trying to hide the
age, Hitchcock is reveling in it. Recently, he sent out a line that
composed of Carbonneau, Brian Skrudland, 35, and Dave Reid, 34.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics can insert their Geritol jokes here, but opponents
aren't laughing. And neither is Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   The coach said he's studying the Stars' senior citizens as an
anchor line in a plan that could see the ``second'' and ``third''
lines shuffled slightly, with Jamie Langenbrunner possibly moving
from left wing to center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most teams around the league have really strong play from
their top three lines and then their fourth line has definition,''
Hitchcock said. ``That's what we want from Reid, Skrudland and
Carbonneau. We can play that line as a checking line, and we can
play them a lot or a little depending on the score. They give us a
lot of versatility.''
</P>
<P>
   While the geriatric trio isn't about to speed past an opponent
or light up the scoreboard _ not one of the three has scored a goal
this season _ they know all about the hard work it takes to stay in
an NHL lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Reid was left unprotected in the preseason waiver draft and was
shuffled around during training camp. Yet, he has been a healthy
scratch only twice this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave Reid saw the challenge and he took it head on,''
Hitchcock said. ``He didn't want to lose his spot, and he fought
hard to get it back''
</P>
<P>
   Reid beat out younger legs such as those of Jamie Wright, now
with the Stars' International Hockey League affiliate in Kalamazoo,
Mich., and Jason Botterill.
</P>
<P>
   ``After last year, they didn't need to bring anyone in to
challenge me _ I knew I hadn't played well,'' Reid said. ``But I
worked hard and I have to continue to work hard. There's still a
lot that I can do better.''
</P>
<P>
   Skrudland, likewise, said he has to improve. He was scratched
for two consecutive games in November and had a heated chat with
Hitchcock about his role on the team. Now, he's back playing center
and enjoying the challenge, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau, who ranked third in the NHL in faceoff winning
percentage last season, has had to move to the right wing for the
first time in his 17-year NHL career. But that's part of the
sacrifice of playing for a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never done it before, but I will do it,'' he said.
``Everyone on the team has to do this, do whatever it takes to make
things work.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Stars' most veteran line understands that as well as
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``That line has real chemistry right now, and we don't want to
take away from that,'' Hitchcock said. ``They're making a
difference for us.''
Chambers hurt
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Shawn Chambers left Wednesday night's game against
San Jose in the second period after the index finger on his right
hand was broken by a slash by Sharks winger Owen Nolan, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers, who missed 25 games with four separate hand injuries
last season, is expected to be out at least two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Defensemen Dan Keczmer or Sergey Gusev are likely replacements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
