<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-CLEMENS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODRIGUEZ AGENT SAYS CATCHER OPPOSES TRADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers may or may not be willing to
trade catcher Ivan Rodriguez to the Toronto Blue Jays for
right-hander Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Let this, though, be known: Rodriguez does not plan on playing
for the Blue Jays beyond the 1999 season should the seven-time
All-Star be sent to the Great White North.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, who signed a five-year contract extension worth $42
million on July 31, 1997, would demand a trade if sent to the Blue
Jays while in the midst of this multiyear contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine the Rangers would trade the best catcher in
baseball after the commitment the two made to each other,'' said
Jeff Moorad, who represents Rodriguez. ``However, in the event
there was a trade ... a Trade I demand would be filed before these
trade papers were even finalized. It would be a no-brainer.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers general manager Doug Melvin spoke yesterday with Blue
Jays general manager Gord Ash in Chicago, but he declined to
elaborate on whether his colleague inquired about Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not commenting on any players in regard to Clemens,''
Melvin said last night after returning to his home in Southlake.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin declined to divulge whether the Rangers made an offer for
Clemens or whether common ground exists between the organizations
for a potential trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. It's hard to say,'' Melvin said. ``I'm probably
not going to talk much about anything in regard to Roger Clemens.
It's best not to and let it take care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's stance against this potential trade could chill the
Blue Jays' interest if the Rangers' plans include offering the
27-year-old catcher as part of any deal for Clemens. Rodriguez
could demand a trade after the 1999 season and force the Blue Jays
into their plight now.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who lives in the Houston suburb of Katy, informed the
Blue Jays of his desire to be traded to an organization closer to
his home or a playoff contender. The Rangers, Houston Astros, New
York Yankees and Cleveland Indians appear to be the most interested
suitors for the 36-year-old pitcher, a five-time Cy Young Award
recipient.
</P>
<P>
   One piece of information suggests that the Rangers might not be
too far along in their discussions with the Blue Jays. Melvin has
not discussed the matter with manager Johnny Oates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any team would love to have Roger Clemens,'' Oates said last
night from his home in Virginia, ``but sometimes you just don't
have enough bullets to get the deal done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers would be in need of a catcher should the
organization trade Rodriguez. The organization lacks a minor-league
catcher ready to play at the major-league level, and Gregg Zaun _
who this past season hit only .188 _ is the only other catcher on
the major-league roster.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Steinbach, Scott Servais, Tom Lampkin, Mike Macfarlane,
Joe Oliver, Kirt Manwaring and Chad Kreuter represent the best the
free-agent market bears.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Rangers do not appear to be the leading
candidate to acquire Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Yankees have the most to offer,'' one major-league
official said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, according to one Blue Jays official, offered
right-hander Ramiro Mendoza, second baseman Homer Bush and one of
the following three pitchers _ left-hander Andy Pettitte or
right-handers Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez and Hideki Irabu _ for
Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Astros discussed parting with some combination of
right-hander Scott Elarton, right fielder Derek Bell, center
fielder Richard Hidalgo and left-hander Mike Hampton in their
attempt to acquire Clemens before the July trade deadline this past
season.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation regarding a Clemens-for-Rodriguez trade leaves the
Rangers' seven-time Gold Glove Award recipient distressed,
according to friends. Rodriguez bypassed his opportunity for free
agency after signing his five-year contract extension with the
Rangers. The Rangers planned to trade Rodriguez to the Yankees at
the July 1997 trade deadline had the two parties not reached an
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   That contract ensures Rodriguez $8 million annually for each of
the next three seasons and $9 million for 2002. Rodriguez also will
receive $2 million in severance pay from the organization upon his
departure from the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's sad right now,'' said Luis Mayoral, the Rangers' liaison
for Latin American players. ``He's not happy. He loves the Rangers.
He wants to die a Ranger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
