<SLUG> BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRYSTAL CLEAR: UCLA DESTINED TO FACE TENNESSEE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ We don't need an MIT graduate with no apparent
life to gaze at computer spreadsheets and tell us which teams will
play for the national title in Tempe, Ariz. Not when a high
priestess of alchemy already has a crystal-clear picture of the
Fiesta Bowl matchup.
</P>
<P>
   Madame Bea C. Ess eschews computers for her crystal ball,
logarithms for tarot cards and slide rules for star-gazing. We hear
she's also a pretty fair fortuneteller.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, Madame Bea C. Ess is convinced she has the Fiesta Bowl
wired. All of her empirical research points to the divine:
</P>
<P>
   It'll be UCLA versus Tennessee for all the chips.
</P>
<P>
   She needed no magic formula to figure this out, she smugly
informed us. She could have done it even without her advanced
degree in the occult, she said matter-of-factly.
</P>
<P>
   We humored her with a smile, then tried gently explaining to her
that nothing possibly can be set in stone until after the outcome
is known of Saturday's games pitting the Volunteers against
Mississippi State and the Bruins against Miami.
</P>
<P>
   At which point Madame Bea C. Ess cut us off with a cackle.
Heavens to Bea, she said, some people just can't see the writing
for the wall.
</P>
<P>
   And then she spelled it out for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell me,'' she whispered conspiratorially, ``when did UCLA's
20-game winning streak start?''
</P>
<P>
   ``On Sept. 13, 1997, in a 66-3 blowout at Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And who did the Bruins play the week before that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tennessee,'' we said.
</P>
<P>
   The picture she was painting was starting to take form.
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' Madame Bea C. Ess's voice was singsong now, ``do you
remember what happened?''
</P>
<P>
   ``But of course. The Bruins fell behind hyped-to-the-heavens
Peyton Manning and the rest of the Rocky Top gang, 24-3, in the
first half before mounting a creditable counterattack and losing
30-24.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Precisely,'' Madame Bea C. Ess said, triumphantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, OK,'' we said, conceding her point. ``So assuming the
Bruins get by Miami this weekend, there would be a certain, well,
celestial symmetry to UCLA playing for its first national football
championship against the last team that defeated it. An unbeaten
Vols team, at that. But then there's unbeaten Kansas State...''
</P>
<P>
   ``But nothing,'' Madame Bea C. Ess cut us off again sharply. Her
eyes narrowed and her tone turned serious. ``There's more to it
than that, don't you see? Think about it. How did Tennessee turn
back Florida?''
</P>
<P>
   ``In overtime,'' we replied, ``after the Gators missed the
game-winning field goal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And how did the Bruins beat Oregon?''
</P>
<P>
   ``In overtime, after UCLA place-kicker Chris Sailer missed the
game-winning field goal in regulation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right,'' she said. ``Now answer me this. What iced Tennessee's
win over Arkansas?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Arkansas quarterback Clint Stoerner's fumble.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And what iced UCLA's win over Stanford?''
</P>
<P>
   We had to admit, the pattern was starting to scream at us. It
was as though we were seeing it on one of sportscaster Chris
Berman's sports coats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stanford receiver Jeff Allen's fumble,'' we said, sheepishly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good.'' Madame Bea C. Ess beamed at us as a mother would after
extracting the desired-upon response from an obdurate child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now then,'' she continued, ``what potentially crippling loss
did the Bruins suffer in the second game, at Houston?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's easy,'' we said. ``Their big-play receiver/kick
returner Freddie Mitchell fractured his leg.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right.'' Madame Bea C. Ess squirmed in her seat as she
mentally replayed the hit that caused Mitchell's injury. ``And what
about Tennessee? What calamity befell its offense?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah,'' we said. ``Quarterback Tee Martin has played so
well it's easy to forget the Vols lost their starting tailback
Jamal Lewis in their fourth game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Speaking of Tee Martin,'' Madame Bea C. Ess said, ``aren't his
stats just so-so?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, yes,'' we said, ``but the thing about him that doesn't
show up in his numbers is his knack for making big plays.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that what you've been saying all season about UCLA's
quarterback, Cade McNown?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Touche,'' we said, grinning.
</P>
<P>
   ``One more thing,'' Madame Bea C. Ess said. ``Did you catch what
Kentucky coach Hal Mumme said about the Vols before his Wildcats
played them?''
</P>
<P>
   We did. ``He said Florida was the better team but that Tennessee
seemed to be getting all the breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Madame Bea C. Ess could hardly contain herself. ``Remind you
of anybody else?'' she asked gleefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``You betcha. It was just like when USC coach Paul Hackett
called Oregon the best team in the Pacific-10 right after the Ducks
had lost to the Bruins. He insinuated that UCLA got lucky because
Oregon basically fumbled the game away.''
</P>
<P>
   Madame Bea C. Ess stared at her polished nails for a few
seconds. She said nothing, giving us a chance to cogitate.
</P>
<P>
   At length she spoke:
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, then, doesn't it seem perfectly clear that UCLA and
Tennessee are on a championship collision course?''
</P>
<P>
   We had to admit, it certainly does. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-04-98 0056EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
