<DOCNO> NYT19981204.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2639 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-CLEMENS-HNS &LR;      12-04 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CLEMENS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Saying his club has a ``tremendous appetite'' for the situation,
Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. pledged Thursday a
bend-but-don't-break approach in the pursuit of five-time Cy Young
Award winner Roger Clemens.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Astros won't be alone, as at least a handful of clubs,
including the Texas Rangers, are among the front-runners to land
the 36-year-old righthander, considered one of the most dominating
pitchers of the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Potential buyers beware: If Toronto has its way, any club with
remote interest in landing the Rocket will have to promise the moon
and the stars in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you the tremendous appetite we have for this, but
it has to be reasonable,'' said McLane, who along with general
manager Gerry Hunsicker attended a special meeting Thursday in
Chicago regarding escalating player salaries. ``We have to be
careful. Last time we talked with (Toronto last July), they wanted
most of our outfield and one or two good pitchers. It can't be an
unreasonable trade. Getting a player like Roger would be
phenomenal, but you have to be careful not to lose three or four
key players.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens set off a wave of inquiries after Wednesday's
announcement that he wanted to exercise a trade option from Toronto
because of the club's lack of commitment to spend money to build a
contender. By Thursday, several clubs had made preliminary contact
with Toronto GM Gord Ash, including the Astros, who plan to hold
further discussions today.
</P>
<P>
   Ash said he would like to formalize a deal within seven to 10
days, although some baseball insiders believe the process could
last longer as Toronto's asking price isn't expected to be cheap.
The Blue Jays are taking a ``star-for-a-star'' approach in dealing
Clemens, reportedly asking about such marquee names as Astros
second baseman Craig Biggio and Rangers catcher Ivan Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker acknowledged Thursday's brief discussion with Ash was
fact-finding and to ``let them know we had interest exploring the
possibly of acquiring his (Clemens') services.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to approach this trade like another other. Does it
make sense?'' Hunsicker said. ``Is it going to make the team
better? We're trying to win in 1999. If we have the chance to
improve ourselves via this particular trade, we're going to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   While the New York Yankees, Cleveland Indians and Rangers have
the resources with their thick-wallet tactics, don't count out the
Astros, who have one important factor working in their favor _
location, location, location. Clemens has made his preference known
that he would like to remain in Texas, playing for either the
Astros or Rangers. If that can't be arranged, he wants to play for
another contender.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros were among four teams _ the Yankees, Cleveland and
Texas were the others _ who made formal offers for Clemens prior to
the July 31 trading deadline last season. Each time, Toronto
rejected the offer, only to make counteroffers that were shot down
by the respective clubs because of the hefty asking price.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays' biggest needs include a power-hitting outfielder;
a starting pitcher, preferably a lefthander; a designated hitter;
and a third baseman.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the Blue Jays asked the Astros for Shane Reynolds, a
19-game winner last season, and outfielders Derek Bell and Richard
Hidalgo. Toronto later asked for righthander Scott Elarton instead
of Reynolds, but the two sides still could not reach agreement and
the Astros sent three minor-league prospects to Seattle for
lefthander Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Bell (.314, 22 home runs, 108 RBIs in 1998) has been the center
of trade talk on several occasions the past few seasons and could
be a key figure in a possible package that would include Elarton
and minor-league outfielder Daryle Ward. The Astros could also
offer infielder Russ Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto Star also reported Thursday, citing unidentified
sources, a ``mega-deal'' between the Astros and Toronto could be in
the works. The Astros have interest in outfielder Shannon Stewart,
although the Blue Jays are pushing Jose Cruz Jr., whose father is
an Astros coach. Hunsicker declined to specifically name players
who could be involved in a trade.
</P>
<P>
   One of the primary issues the Astros will address is avoiding
any unnecessary disruptions that could come as a result of
subtracting too many players off the current big-league roster,
Hunsicker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start subtracting, you have to be careful not to end
up less competitive,'' he said. ``When you're trying to trade one
of the best pitchers in the game, you try and get somebody to
overpay. I would try to, too. You have to try and be careful and
not get caught up with the intangibles.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees appear to have the most to offer Toronto, with third
baseman Mike Lowell, outfielders Chad Curtis, Ricky Ledee and Shane
Spencer and pitcher Ramiro Mendoza, among others, as trade bait.
</P>
<P>
   And wherever the Yankees are, you can almost certainly expect
the Indians to be right behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's much more available now than a week ago,'' Cleveland GM
John Hart said. ``I now have the Jays' number on my speed dial.''
</P>
<P>
   The phone isn't expected to stop ringing any time soon. There
will be plenty of interest in Clemens, who went 41-13 with two Cy
Youngs in two seasons with the Blue Jays. Last season, Clemens went
20-6 with a 2.65 ERA, going 15-0 in his last 22 starts after
beginning the season 5-6. He led the AL in ERA and strikeouts and
tied for the lead in wins after finishing first in all three
categories in 1997. Clemens earns $8 million each of the next two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, teams such as the Astros will begin lining up
for the chance to obtain Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a waiting game when Toronto will get to the point
they are ready to make a deal,'' said Randy Hendricks, one of
Clemens' Houston-based agents. ``Until then, there isn't anything
overly urgent to talk about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
