<SLUG> BC-FBC-MIAMI-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI LOSES ITS SWAGGER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most extraordinary thing about the University of Miami
football program over the years isn't the four national
championships it won in a nine-year period, or the 18 first-round
NFL draft choices it produced since 1987, or the NCAA-record,
58-game home winning streak it built at the Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   What's most remarkable is that the Hurricanes have worn white
helmets all these years.
</P>
<P>
   The villains, after all, are supposed to wear black hats.
Nobody's played that role better or badder than the 'Canes.
</P>
<P>
   Pregame brawls, taunts and cheap shots were identifiable with
the program as much as winning. If the Hurricanes wanted to tell
the world who was No. 1, they often had a hard time deciding which
finger to use.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, thanks to NCAA sanctions that cost Miami 31
scholarships over three seasons, the swagger has been replaced by a
stagger.
</P>
<P>
   That point was driven home last week when the 'Canes were
thumped by Syracuse, 66-13. It dropped Miami's record against
ranked teams to 1-7 over the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the alumni have taken the head-in-the-sand approach
about the probation,'' said Miami coach Butch Davis, whose team has
rebounded from its first losing season since 1979. ``Certainly last
Saturday was a little bit of a reminder. When we climbed to 7-2 and
18th or 19th in the country a lot of people said, `Oh, well, we're
out of the woods. Everything's back to normal.'''
</P>
<P>
   If it were, the Hurricanes would be playing for something more
than pride Saturday when they host No. 3 UCLA at the Orange Bowl in
a makeup of the game scheduled for Sept. 26 that was postponed by
Hurricane Georges.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in the team isn't what it used to be, although this
game is selling better because of the attention surrounding the
Bruins and their national title shot. Attendance last year fell to
an average of fewer than 29,000 _ less than half the Orange Bowl's
capacity and a 17-year low. The Hurricanes are drawing better this
season, but only their game against Florida State was watched by
more than 42,000.
</P>
<P>
   Miami hasn't just lost the once-raucous crowd, but also its
edge. After going nearly 10 years without a loss at the Orange
Bowl, the Hurricanes have lost eight of their last 14 games there.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a former assistant under Jimmy Johnson at Miami and with
the Dallas Cowboys, is in his fourth season as the head coach. He
says it's no mystery why the Hurricanes are suffering.
</P>
<P>
   ``You lose 31 scholarships over three years and it's pretty
difficult to just snap your fingers and bring not only the talent
level, but the depth and experience to where it was,'' Davis said.
``If we had 10 more seniors, 10 more juniors and 10 more
sophomores, we'd probably be a little different football team than
we are today. But we are where we are and there's nothing we can do
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Davis can do something about is the Hurricanes' image,
which he's trying to change from Miami Vice to Miami Nice.
</P>
<P>
   The taunting and trash talking has been muted. Players are more
involved in community service and academic support has been stepped
up. Davis has stood firm when it's come to discipline, kicking off
defensive tackle Chad Pegues, a two-year starter, for breaking an
undisclosed team rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a mandate,'' Davis said of his attempt to soften
Miami's image. ``It was just something that went along with the
staff's personality and my personality and I think clearly even the
football players were ready for a change.''
</P>
<P>
   The departments' low point came in the 1991 Cotton Bowl when
Miami whipped Texas, 46-3, despite piling up 202 yards in
penalties, the majority for unsportsmanlike conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people were saying, `These boys are nothing but a
bunch of thugs and clowns,''' said receiver Darryl Jones, a native
of Dallas. ``The whole state of Texas was pretty upset the way they
were out there clowning. When the referees came around our high
school to talk about the new rules (against taunting), they called
it `The Miami Rules'.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes' off-the-field behavior did little to alter this
image, succinctly summarized on T-shirts for the heated Notre
Dame-Miami rivalry in the late '80s: Catholics vs. Convicts.
</P>
<P>
   Jammi German, a former receiver, once punched a track athlete
for calling him a gay epithet. Players were cut deals by boosters
on living arrangements or rental cars. Some obtained loaned cars or
money through agents.
</P>
<P>
   As the 1993 season was beginning, rap star Luther Campbell, a
Miami native, threatened to tell the NCAA who on the team was
receiving money if Ryan Collins, a black quarterback, wasn't named
the starter ahead of Frank Costa, who is white.
</P>
<P>
   The program was finally brought down by academic adviser Tony
Russell, who landed Miami in trouble with the NCAA for falsifying
Pell Grant applications for 91 students, including 57 football
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all very upset and frustrated,'' said offensive line
coach Art Kehoe, who played at Miami in the late '70s and has been
a part of the coaching staff since. ``We just about got the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``What irritates me is that we got on probation because of the
Pell Grants and people try to make us out to be some hood program,
where there was cheating and that we were a vagabond, run-amok
program. We certainly did some things that we weren't proud of, but
we were never out-and-out buying kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we've had some bad kids, but I don't care where you go,
some of 'em aren't going to be angels. I'll tell you what, though,
we didn't win four national titles because we had a bunch of
punks.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami forged 8-3 and 9-3 seasons in Davis' first two years,
getting by on the available talent. But this year's senior class,
the first of the probation era, has produced only four starters.
The Hurricanes start eight underclassmen on defense and have
started a pair of redshirt freshmen on the offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows up in a lot of areas,'' Davis said. ``Practice-wise,
not having full scholarships like everyone else, our scout teams
are never quite as physically talented and gifted as you'd like 'em
to be to try to get your players ready during the course of the
week. You end up playing a lot of kids in starting offensive and
defensive positions (and) sometimes it waters down the special
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The country has gotten two glimpses of just how far Miami has
fallen. The Syracuse loss and last October's 47-0 walloping by
Florida State were the 'Canes worst defeats since 1944 and both
were on national TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll bet there are a lot of people who aren't losing sleep
over what happened to us,'' said quarterback Scott Covington, a
fifth-year senior from Dana Hills and the only scholarship
Californian on Miami's roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there are some people out there who see us and hope
for ill will. It's the same situation here as at a place like Notre
Dame. When anyone can beat a Notre Dame or kick 'em when they're
down, they will. I think it's similar here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes, despite the sanctions, have still been able to
attract some of the nation's top recruits. Jones, the receiver from
Dallas, and linebacker Nate Webster, both true sophomores, are
former prep All-Americans. So is the quarterback of the future,
redshirt freshman Kenny Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, the Hurricanes will field a team with 85 scholarships
for the first time since 1993 when they finished No. 3 in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We truly believe we've made great strides and that we have
some very good young football players,'' Davis said. ``In the next
couple years I think we're going to field a very good football team
and bring Miami's credibility back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
