A2641 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-04 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John P.Lopez
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE clock is winding down, the season is on the line, and it
doesn't take a JumboTron to know the score in this NBA lockout
game.
</P>
<P>
   History 101, NBA players 99.
</P>
<P>
   This is the moment the NBA owners probably have been waiting for
all along. This battle has reached that gut-wrenching point of
desperation when the biggest stars in basketball must step up and
do something huge. Somebody must take a last-second shot at saving
the NBA season.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, many of the NBA's richest and most heralded
somebodies _ Patrick Ewing, Alonzo Mourning, David Robinson,
Dikembe Mutombo and even Michael Jordan in a surprise and
well-choreographed appearance Thursday _ arrived in New York and
went back to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   They swooped in moments before the final buzzer of this forsaken
season like the heroes they are, apparently finally ready to make
their big moves and save the day. They came hoping to put an end to
this labor dispute, although Thursday's long session ended with the
ball hanging menacingly in the air.
</P>
<P>
   But the significance of the league's superstars showing a
renewed commitment toward giving and taking, toward honest
negotiating and ultimately finding a resolution, should not be lost
on anyone. Neither should it be lost why this is happening now,
after both sides walked away frustrated with one another after
their last formal meeting Nov. 20.
</P>
<P>
   As much as owners also want to have some semblance of an NBA
this year, they realize it is the players who know the score that
matters most.
</P>
<P>
   History 101.
</P>
<P>
   Any history professor will tell you the majority of uprisings in
this world have occurred only when the masses became hungry. We can
only assume this is that moment for NBA players, and this is what
the owners have been waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   Time-changing moments always hinge more on growling stomachs and
bare feet than political or philosophical differences. Uprisings
usually occur only when the great unwashed begin to feel cheated,
forgotten and mistreated, but mostly when they're out of money and
food.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the NBA's low-end players, those who earn $1 million or
less a year and account for nearly 40 percent of the players
union's population, are beginning to hear their stomachs growl.
</P>
<P>
   NBA players missed their second paychecks of the season this
week. And this one the majority of players had to have felt, which
is why the biggest stars headed back to New York looking for peace
and a way to settle the rank-and-file grumblings.
</P>
<P>
   The likes of Jordan, Ewing, Robinson, Mutombo and Mourning
average nearly $20 million per year and still have not
significantly felt the lost paychecks, but many others have.
</P>
<P>
   No NBA player figures to go hungry or shoeless, of course, but
when you make more, you usually spend more. Christmas still should
be Christmas for the rank and file, but some of them figure to get
their cranberries out of a can this year.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, dissent from the NBA's low-end players is rising and
the union's leadership is feeling it. Why else do you think
super-agent David Falk, who is pushing most of the buttons for the
players in this standoff, had Jordan show up for Thursday's
session?
</P>
<P>
   And Jordan arrived in dramatic style _ in a New York taxicab, no
less _ as reporters swarmed and cameras clicked. For years, Jordan
has been a noted limousine patron whether that city was New York or
New Braunfels. He even has his own limousine and personal driver in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday's appearance by Jordan was one made for the
simmering masses, a posed picture of the players' leader marching
to the union's beat. Had Jordan stepped out of a limousine while
the Tim Leglers and Matt Maloneys of the NBA world watched, it
might have been too much to handle.
</P>
<P>
   It has been for some, although few have gone public. Most
recently, Washington's Legler complained about the Nike-dragging in
the negotiations, saying: ``The (superstars) are the ones who are
going to feel it if we sign the (current) offer. That's why the
deal is not signed.''
</P>
<P>
   The private anguish of such players will only grow as the
lockout drags on. The low-end players have watched their checks all
but torn to pieces. Twice.
</P>
<P>
   An increasing number of these players seem to be wondering if
the superstars leading their cause are looking out for the entire
league or only for that 50 to 60 percent that stand to gain the
most from the issues most often discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Those issues have to do with revenue percentages, escrow
accounts, the Larry Bird exception, drug testing and others.
</P>
<P>
   But the end of this lockout might come down to something
simpler. It might be a study in History 101. The rank and file is
tired, worn and hungry. And that's never good for a cause.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
