<HEADER>
A2642 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXASA&AMP;M-HALL-HNS     12-04 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXASA&AMP;M-HALL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
COLLEGE STATION _ It was as though Texas A&AMP;M running back Dante
Hall had been grazed by a runaway tractor-trailer rig and left
wandering the highway.
<TEXT>
<P>
   HallFriday, the senior tailback had been denied 1,000 yards
rushing for the second straight year in a regular-season finale. As
a team, the Aggies had been held to minus-seven yards rushing. And
by Texas, whose defense had been shaky against opposing runners
most of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Hall never envisioned any team handling the Aggies' runners in
such a manner, especially the Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not like that,'' Hall said Tuesday. ``You can contain (the
running game). But we averaged like one yard a carry. That was
awful. Besides Kansas State last year, I don't think we've ever had
anything that bad. I didn't think that would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The scary news is that having been belted in the chops by the
Longhorns, the Aggies must regroup and face Kansas State, which has
the nation's second-best defense, on Saturday in the Big 12
Championship Game in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean anything to me,'' Hall said. ``Our defense
was ranked No. 2 going into the Texas game. Look what they did to
us. It's just a matter of going out and finding a way to beat that
defense. Every defense has a way to be beaten; you have to find it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas found the ways to beat our defense. Just because of
(Kansas State's) stats, it doesn't mean anything. Most of that
probably came against not-too-good teams anyway. So it doesn't mean
anything. That's paper stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Aggies can convince themselves by game time Saturday
at the Trans World Dome.
</P>
<P>
   But the Wildcats have been a load this season. Versatile
quarterback Michael Bishop has turned the offense into one of the
most dangerous, diversified attacks in the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   David Allen's brilliance returning punts and kickoffs and Martin
Gramatica's outstanding kicking has the Wildcats' special teams
rated among the nation's best.
</P>
<P>
   With a linebacking corps of high-caliber players such as Jeff
Kelly, Mark Simoneau and Travis Ochs, K-State is ranked No. 2 in
scoring defense, No. 6 in pass-efficiency defense and No. 7 in rush
defense. Opponents have averaged 95.5 yards on the ground against
the Wildcats, 156.1 through the air and 11.2 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Aggies are optimistic. Win, and the Big 12 South
champs will have salved the wounds of the bitter 26-24 loss to
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing for all the chips here,'' said wide receiver
Chris Cole. ``We're playing for a big-time bowl bid. We're playing
for the league championship. As far as our confidence, (the
Wildcats are) just a little obstacle in the way to a bigger goal.''
</P>
<P>
   With a win, the Aggies would capture the Big 12 championship and
perhaps position themselves for an invitation to a Bowl
Championship Series event, all while providing Hall the chance to
reach his goal of 1,000 yards. Statistics from Saturday's game will
count toward regular-season totals. Hall, a junior from Nimitz,
needs 89 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``If me getting the amount of yards to get 1,000 and we win,
I'll take that,'' he said. ``But at the same time, at this point in
time, getting 1,000 yards is not even close to my mind. I just want
to win to go to one of those big-time bowls, more than anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies are convinced the trauma of Friday's loss at Texas is
a thing of the past. Similarly, they believe the adjustments needed
to get the offense out of its rut and a defense that gave up nearly
500 yards back on track are attainable, despite facing No. 2 Kansas
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing for us is we don't necessarily look at our
opponent this week as much as we look at ourselves,'' said
offensive coordinator Steve Kragthorpe. ``We've got to get
corrected the things that we need to do. And that's throwing and
catching the football and being able to sustain some running plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at any football team. You go out and rush for
minus-seven yards, I don't know very many football teams that are
going to win football games. We've got to certainly be better
running the football. And if the opportunity is there throwing the
ball, we've got to be better in terms of taking advantage of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   When A&AMP;M, then ranked No. 14, visited Kansas State (No. 20) last
year in Manhattan, the result was a 35-17 Wildcats win. Hall
carried one time for two yards but was injured on the first play
from scrimmage and did not return.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M was ranked fifth nationally in rushing (278 yards per game)
but was held to minus-35 yards. The longest run of the day was
three yards. Entering the game, the Aggies averaged 440 yards of
total offense but got only 90.
</P>
<P>
   The task Saturday might be even more difficult, given last
week's defeat. But Hall, who finished 1997 with 973 yards rushing
on 134 carries, has found a silver lining.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the good thing _ we've got a quick turnaround,'' he
said. ``It's unfortunate that we lost to Texas, but it's not the
end of our season. We can still win the entire Big 12 championship
and go to a big-time bowl. That's the bright side, coming off a
loss like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bounced back from the Florida State game (a 23-14 loss in
the season opener). There should be no reason why we can't bounce
back from this game. Any good team does that. And I think we're a
very good team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
