<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS' HARD WORK NOT ENOUGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANATA, Ontario _ Their situation growing more dismal by the
day, the Kings decided Thursday morning to convene a 90-minute
players-only meeting to sort out their feelings and try to right
themselves before it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as day became night, the Kings stepped onto the ice at
the Corel Centre to face the Ottawa Senators and try to avoid their
10th loss in 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings made few defensive mistakes, limiting the Senators to
18 shots. At the other end, they peppered Ottawa goalie Ron Tugnutt
with 32 shots, many from close range. The Kings played with
emotion, and they played hard from opening faceoff to final buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the result was numbingly familiar _ their fourth straight
loss, and third in a row by a 3-1 margin on a trip mercifully at an
end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to tell you,'' said an extremely emotional
Luc Robitaille, who scored the Kings' goal 15 seconds into the
third period, briefly tying the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were going to win. They get a lucky (bleeping)
break and score. Everybody battled their hearts out. I'm so
disappointed. We played so hard. We were proud to be Kings tonight.
It was a good feeling to be a part of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings outshot the Senators, 25-10, in the first two periods,
but for the third consecutive game, they trailed, 1-0, after 40
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The first goal by the Senators (12-7-3), late in the opening
period by Andreas Johansson, resulted from the failure by
defensemen Mattias Norstrom and Sean O'Donnell to clear the puck
from their zone.
</P>
<P>
   In the third period, 10 minutes after Robitaille tied the score,
Alexei Yashin scored the game-winner when Philippe Boucher lost the
puck behind the Kings' net. Magnus Arvedson completed the scoring
with a last-minute empty-net goal.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if the Kings (6-16-3) wanted to think positively, it was
easier than after most of their setbacks. To a man, they said the
improved effort sprang from the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we talked about, we're going to keep it between the
guys,'' Norstrom said. ``It was good to see the veteran guys
stepping up and showing more leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the meeting, Robitaille said: ``We're dead last in
the (Western Conference). I think it was time.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in recent games, the Kings consistently drove to the net
and jumped on rebounds. As in recent games, their efforts went
mostly unrewarded. Eric Lacroix, Vladimir Tsyplakov, Ray Ferraro
and Yanic Perreault all were stopped by Tugnutt from point-blank
range.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had bang-bang plays,'' coach Larry Robinson said. ``They're
just not going in for us. We're all looking for an answer for why
the puck is not going in.... It's moved to the
is-it-ever-going-to-turn-around stage. It's tough to handle.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings got a major scare in the game when Ottawa defenseman
Wade Redden dropped center Jozef Stumpel with a knee-to-knee hit
late in the first period. Stumpel, who has missed 13 games with
assorted injuries, stayed down for several minutes but returned for
the last two periods despite a charley horse to his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Redden received a major penalty for kneeing, a game misconduct,
and a severe pounding from O'Donnell. The Kings came out of the
situation with a three-minute power play, but did not capitalize.
Their miserable power play, again a decisive factor despite more
scoring chances, went 0 for 5 and is 9 for 111 this season.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was heartened to see O'Donnell respond to Redden's hit,
and pleased with just about everything but the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``They stuck up for each other all night,'' he said. ``Sooner or
later, it's going to turn around. We can't do as many good things
as we did and not see some good results from it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
