<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRAT-CONVENTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS RETURNING TO L.A. FOR FINAL CONVENTION TALKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- An eight-member delegation of the Democratic
National Committee returns to L.A. this weekend for a two-day
session to determine if the city will play host to the party's
national convention in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving Sunday, the group has planned the meetings to explore
the budget of the L.A. Convention 2000 host committee as well as an
examination of the convention facilities and hotels available for
the event.
</P>
<P>
   At stake for Los Angeles, in its competition with Boston and
Denver for the right to host the convention, is the prospect of
seeing the city's economy boosted by $137 million.
</P>
<P>
   The committee has offered a $35.3 million package -- all
privately financed -- of security, transportation and other
services for the right to host the convention.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the hard review of figures and facilities, the
delegates also will meet with U.S. Sen. Barbara Boxer, L.A. Mayor
Richard Riordan and other local officials and members of the host
committee at a power breakfast Monday at the Pacific Dining Car in
downtown Los Angeles where they will be urged to select the city.
</P>
<P>
   One of the key features of the city's bid is the prospect of the
convention being held in the Staples Center sports arena. While it
is still under construction, it is ahead of schedule for its
October 1999 opening.
</P>
<P>
   Operators of the arena said they are willing to make changes in
their construction and design plans to accommodate the convention.
</P>
<P>
   A decision on where the event will be held is expected shortly
after the first of the year when the delegates visit the two
competing cities.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
