<HEADER>
A2651 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARHART-DISCOVERY?-IN     12-04 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARHART-DISCOVERY?-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THE MYSTERY OF AMELIA EARHART SOLVED?  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 1,000-word ``separate buy'' article is from The Independent
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 By ANDREW GUMBEL  
 c.1998 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ More than 60 years after the pioneering aviator
Amelia Earhart disappeared without a trace over the Pacific Ocean
during a round-the-world flight, a group of American academic
researchers believes it is close to cracking the much-debated
mystery of where and how she died.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with new archival and analytical evidence, The
International Group for Historic Aircraft Recovery (TIGHAR), a
nonprofit foundation based in Delaware, says Earhart and her
navigator, Frederick J. Noonan, almost certainly crashed on the
island atoll of Nikumaroro, which was uninhabited at the time. They
died either of thirst or starvation when rescue efforts failed to
locate them.
</P>
<P>
   Intriguingly, the group believes that key evidence in the case
was dug up by the British colonial administration in the Western
Pacific in 1940, three years after the crash, but was prevented
from coming to public attention because of forensic incompetence
and an insistence by the High Commission to keep the affair top
secret.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Commission's files, which TIGHAR has unearthed
in Fiji, London and Hanslope Park, the British administrator
charged with populating and governing Nikumaroro _ then called
Gardner Island _ discovered fragments of shoes, a sextant box, and
some human bones which made him immediately think of Earhart.
</P>
<P>
   The High Commissioner, Sir Harry Luke, swore him to secrecy on
the grounds that ``thinnest rumors which may in the end prove
unfounded are liable to spread.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of officials examined the evidence, but concluded that
the sextant was too old-fashioned to be used in modern aviation,
and that the bones belonged to a man, not a woman.
</P>
<P>
   According to TIGHAR, the British assessment was hasty and
inaccurate, assuming, for example, that Earhart was alone. Not only
was Noonan with her, but he had a habit _ according to evidence
garnered from his possessions _ of taking an old-fashioned sextant
box with him as a backup to a more modern aeronautical bubble
octant.
</P>
<P>
   As for the bones, they were examined by a medical officer on
Fiji called D.W. Hoodless whose competence, according to TIGHAR,
appears to have been limited.
</P>
<P>
   Two independent studies commissioned by TIGHAR with the benefit
of modern forensic know-how examined the measurements and other
figures provided by Dr. Hoodless and concluded that the bones in
fact belonged to a woman of Earhart's stature.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most dramatic archival and scientific evidence to
date about Earhart's fate,'' said Richard Gillespie, TIGHAR's
executive director, who returned from a week-long research trip to
the Foreign and Commonwealth Office facility in Hanslope Park at
the end of last month.
</P>
<P>
   What is still missing, however, is conclusive proof to crown
TIGHAR's painstaking detective work.
</P>
<P>
   The most compelling piece of evidence would be the bones
recovered from Gardner Island, but nobody knows where they are.
They were put into a kanawa wood coffin ordered into storage by the
British High Commission immediately after Dr. Hoodless's
examination but the trail of paperwork on them runs out on April
17, 1941.
</P>
<P>
   Earhart's fate has exerted an extraordinary fascination on
amateur historians and conspiracy theorists ever since she vanished
from the radar screens, aged 39, on the morning of July 2, 1937.
</P>
<P>
   Already famous as the first woman to pilot a plane across the
Atlantic, among other feats, she was attempting a perilous
2,500-mile flight from New Guinea to Howland Island, about 350
miles northeast of Nikumaroro, when she announced over her radio
that she was coming in to land. That was the last anybody heard
from her.
</P>
<P>
   A massive U.S. Navy search concentrated its efforts around
Howland Island. Over the following days planes flew over Gardner
Island, part of the Phoenix Group, and noticed signs of habitation.
But nobody noticed signs of a crash.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the wildest theories began to circulate, particularly after
the Japanese invasion of Pearl Harbor. Earhart had been captured by
the Japanese and executed as a spy, some said.
</P>
<P>
   Her disappearance was orchestrated by the U.S. military as an
excuse to fly over the Marshall Islands where the Japanese were
suspected of building weapons installations, cried others.
</P>
<P>
   A Hollywood movie expanding on the espionage theory, ``Flight
for Freedom,'' was made in 1943 with Rosalind Russell and Fred
MacMurray. As late as the 1960s, books were being written
suggesting that Earhart was alive and well and posing as a nice old
lady novelist in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   TIGHAR's own efforts to unearth the truth began 10 years ago,
and from the beginning Gillespie and his colleagues chose to
concentrate on Nikumaroro.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991 they found pieces of shoe including a replacement heel,
a rubber sole and a brass shoelace eyelet. These were subsequently
identified as coming from a woman's size nine blucher oxford of a
kind frequently worn by Earhart.
</P>
<P>
   TIGHAR also found some airplane fragments that may or may not
have come from Earhart's Lockheed Model 10E Special Electra.
</P>
<P>
   Every one of TIGHAR's findings has been fraught with
controversy, however, with members of Earhart's own family
contesting her shoe size and Lockheed employees failing to identify
the airplane parts as an Electra or any other model.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Aeronautics Department at the National Air
and Space Museum in Washington, Tom Crouch, remains skeptical of
TIGHAR's claims and says he wants to see a ``smoking gun'' before
shifting from his view that Earhart and Noonan simply ran out of
fuel and crashed into the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Gillespie of TIGHAR does not pretend to have answered
all the questions yet, and his group plans further field trips to
the Pacific and elsewhere in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the elements are there for a great mystery, and Amelia
Earhart has turned into an icon for many people,'' he said, ``so
anything we discover is bound to be controversial. But just because
we are criticized doesn't mean our evidence has been disproved.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
