<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2679 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      12-04 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEVER-ENDING BIG UNIT SAGA HAS NO WINNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The remarkable thing about the Randy Johnson story is
that it just keeps going, like the Starr investigation. Most people
don't want to hear any more, but it has its own life now, and we're
all powerless to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   The latest episode has the Mariner brass finally spitting back,
after many months of silence on the subject of how they could let
the game's dominant pitcher get away.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Johnson is secure with the Arizona Diamondbacks for
more money than it would take to put a retractable roof over the
Grand Canyon, the presumption is that the Mariners can tell their
side without looking silly and petty.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for them, it doesn't work. But now that Johnson
has achieved his agenda of having his ego and bank account
engorged, for just a 20-minute commute from home, he comes off as
duplicitous and even more unprofessional than when he last wore the
compass rose.
</P>
<P>
   Mariner president Chuck Armstrong contends that Johnson long has
wanted to play for the Diamondbacks, a claim generally dismissed by
those who believed there was no way Johnson would waste the final
years of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said Johnson's agents, Barry Meister and Alan Nero,
informed him of Johnson's intent at an August 1997 meeting, in
which they urged him not to pick up Johnson's one-year option for
1998, and don't bother with a contract extension offer. In a rare
bit of documentary evidence in the case, Armstrong's claim is
backed by a story in the Arizona Republic in February 1996, in
which Johnson flat-out says, ``I've got two years left (with the
Mariners), and then I'll be coming down, playing with the
Diamondbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day Johnson denied everything. But in hindsight, he was
telling the truth, albeit recklessly, in the Republic story. So
Armstrong's subsequent claim that the agents presented a plan to
get Johnson to Arizona in a trade has some credibility, even though
the D-backs officials deny any knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners spurned the advice of the agents and in September
1997 exercised their 1998 option for Johnson. That put the club in
a box with three weak options:
</P>
<P>
   -- Offer him a contract extension right away, which would have
to be around Greg Maddux's annual salary of $11 million. Two
problems: If the offer was low, the ultra-sensitive Johnson would
claim insult, however preposterously; if the offer was accepted,
ownership, panicked by ballpark-cost overruns, would have to pay
about a fifth of the club's payroll to a guy who plays in a fifth
of the games.
</P>
<P>
   -- Let him pitch through '98, win another division title and
hope good results would change his mind about staying.
</P>
<P>
   -- Trade him in the '97 offseason, and face the wrath of an
incredulous public trained that they gotta love these guys.
</P>
<P>
   As Seattle fans know, the Mariners chose Door No. 2. It turned
out to be a bag of donuts.
</P>
<P>
   Said one Mariner official: ``In nine out of 10 cases, the player
in his (final) contract year overachieves to get a new deal. This
was the one out of 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson didn't exactly quit on the Mariners, but his 9-10 record
and cranky moodiness belied his own written spring-training
statement that he would put contract issues aside.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Mo Vaughn, Bernie Williams, Kevin Brown and other quality
free-agents-to-be, Johnson was unprofessional, not to mention
deceitful. Obviously, that means little to him, especially now that
it got him what he wanted. It's just a shame he smeared an
otherwise sterling legacy in a Seattle baseball history that has so
few.
</P>
<P>
   As for club management, it now creates the appearance of seeking
a measure of victimhood. The problem with that is it concedes that
the tail, in this case Johnson's agents, wagged the dog.
</P>
<P>
   Agents can make all sorts of knotheaded demands. It's up to the
club to dictate policy and direction. If the Mariners ignored the
agents and made a bona fide $10 million, three-year offer that
Johnson rejected, they could have watched Johnson cry his crocodile
tears in front of a skeptical public.
</P>
<P>
   A trade in the winter of '97, while still controversial, likely
would have brought more to help in '98 and beyond than the
midseason swap with Houston. Even though clubs would know he had to
be traded, he was still at the top of his game, and his new team
would have him at least a full year.
</P>
<P>
   The worst that could have happened, from the Mariner view, was
that Johnson accepts a generous Seattle offer, pitches well for
three more years and management pays for the deal out of its
postseason take. But since management was already convinced he was
headed to Arizona no matter what, there was little risk he would
accept.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the possible permutations, the fact is the affair has
become one of those lose-lose deals where everybody comes out
looking bad.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it could be that all this was for naught, because
Johnson really left to get away from the Mariner bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   That's hardly an unreasonable position. If true, well, sorry
about the criticism, Randy.
</P>
<P>
   And good luck with those 72-win Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
