<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981204.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2681 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-TALKS-HNS &LR;      12-04 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-TALKS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Making his strongest statement to date on the possible cancellation
of the NBA season, commissioner David Stern emerged from a lengthy
negotiating session late Thursday night and proclaimed the season
unlikely to occur.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``As I stand here today, it's more likely we won't have a season
than we will have a season,'' Stern said. ``It may sound difficult
to believe, but we met for 10 or more hours and made little or no
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's meeting of owners and the players' union, the first
since Nov. 20, ended just before midnight EST, the longest session
of the lockout. There was no indication when the next meeting would
take place.
</P>
<P>
   Union leader Billy Hunter was unhappy with the continuing
stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are being oppressive, overreacting, and we are not
inclined to give in,'' said Hunter, whose request for mediation was
rejected by the owners. ``We're not turning back.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan was summoned for last-gasp heroics that perhaps
not even he can supply. After saving so many games for the Chicago
Bulls, Jordan is being asked to help save the NBA season, but that
might be difficult even for him.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was just one of the National Basketball Players
Association's big guns sitting across the table from NBA owners,
joining union president Patrick Ewing and vice president Alonzo
Mourning in New York in an effort to hammer out a
collective-bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's presence meant the union intended to take the
discussions as far as possible in an effort to reach an agreement
before the season slipped away. But neither side seemed interested
in presenting new ideas, apparently content to hold firm on
proposals that have been deemed unacceptable for 157 days and
counting.
</P>
<P>
   Stern said the two sides spent the first few hours ``feeling
each other out'' before breaking for lunch. They met again
afterward, with Stern's plea to the players to save the season
being the highlight of the day.
</P>
<P>
   After saying the season was unlikely, Stern softened somewhat,
saying, ``We don't say this is our last, final, no-holds-barred
offer.''
</P>
<P>
   So everything is pretty much where it was when all this started,
even though both sides agree the season probably will be canceled
if an agreement is not reached within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe something has changed, but right now I can't be very
optimistic,'' NBA deputy commissioner Russ Granik said upon his
arrival. ``We've taken a few (steps) back since our last meeting,
so we'll see. There's a sense of urgency, but the owners have said
they won't operate our business in a way that makes no financial
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   There is hopeful talk the bargaining sessions could mirror those
in the 1994-95 NHL lockout, which wasn't settled until mid-January.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a possible result here,'' Granik said. ``Obviously, our
seasons are not that different.''
</P>
<P>
   The NHL played a reduced 48-game schedule, and sources say the
NBA has a 56-game schedule drawn up, with play beginning in early
January, if a settlement is reached.
</P>
<P>
   Progress had been made in the previous full bargaining session
Nov. 20, with owners coming up to 53 percent from their proposal of
a 50-50 split of basketball-related income, and the players
relenting on their demand for a 60-40 split, dropping to 57
percent. But the league has a problem with the players asking for
57 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our problem is not with individual issues; it's with the
entire mindset,'' Granik said. ``If the players really believe that
they have to receive 57 percent, or anything like it, then we can't
make a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   They were close to a deal in that Nov. 20 session, but a
misunderstanding of how to implement a complicated escrow system _
one that would have had players withholding 10 or 15 percent of
their paychecks to give back to owners should spending on overall
player salaries exceed an agreed-upon percentage of revenues _
caused all the progress in that meeting to be erased. So one of the
first items on Thursday's agenda was whether to scrap the escrow
system, which would be in place for the final three or four years
of a six- or seven-year agreement. The players would like the
owners to share the burden of overspending, with a tax levied on
the highest-spending teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been skeptical of this whole escrow system for a while,''
Granik said. ``We just might have to start over with something
else.''
</P>
<P>
   The sides remain far apart on other issues, such as the owners'
proposal for a change in the ``timing rules,'' which would force
teams that sign another team's free agent to forfeit the right to
go over the salary cap to re-sign their own Larry Bird-exception
free agents.
</P>
<P>
   It is a change the players refuse to accept.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
