<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2686 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI &LR;      12-04 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS' SHAWN SPRINGS HOPES TO MAKE STATEMENT IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ As NFL trash talkers go, there aren't many
better than Keyshawn Johnson and Shawn Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Each is young and talented, and will likely let the other know
about it Sunday at Giants Stadium when Springs, the second-year
cornerback for the Seahawks, matches up against Johnson, the
third-year wide receiver for the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   These two grew up around the game, Springs as the son of former
Dallas Cowboys running back Ron Springs and Johnson as a ballboy
for six years at USC. They entered the NFL through the penthouse
door, Johnson as the first pick overall in the 1996 draft and
Springs as the No. 3 pick last year.
</P>
<P>
   They know the game. They know there are few who play it better.
</P>
<P>
   But their mutual respect for each other's games prompted some
bland comments this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shawn is a good player,'' Johnson said. ``Obviously he's
probably going to be looking to get some revenge from last year,
because we won that game and I caught some passes on him. But he's
a real talent and he's going to be for a long time in this league.
He'll have some Pro Bowls down the line. He's on his way.''
</P>
<P>
   Countered Springs, ``Keyshawn is a good player. Any time you get
a chance to go up against a young player who's an up-and-coming
receiver like Keyshawn, you've got to get up for a game like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Yawn. If only they could be miked on the field Sunday. Springs
and Johnson consider trash talking a part of the game, and each
believes it makes the game more enjoyable.
</P>
<P>
   Springs is more concerned about making a statement of another
kind this week. He believes he's having a Pro Bowl season. He knows
others agree. He just hopes there are enough to send him to Hawaii
for the NFL all-star game in February.
</P>
<P>
   This week's matchup with Johnson in the glare of the New York
spotlight is one last chance for Springs to impress players and
coaches before they cast their votes next week. The AFC and NFC Pro
Bowl squads will be announced Dec. 17.
</P>
<P>
   And Springs will shadow the 6-foot-3 Johnson, just as he did in
Dallas two weeks ago against the Cowboys' 6-2 Michael Irvin.
Normally, the Seahawks have their cornerbacks play sides of the
field _ Springs on the left and Willie Williams on the right. But
Williams is 5-9, as is nickel-back Fred Thomas. At 6-foot, Springs
is not only the best option against the growing number of big
receivers in the league, but the only option. It's the biggest
reason they traded up in last year's draft to get him.
</P>
<P>
   Springs has come up huge for the Seahawks this season,
especially for a player who missed six games during his rookie
season with a fractured thumb.
</P>
<P>
   He not only has five interceptions, he has returned two for
touchdowns and came close to scoring with a third. But the
touchdown returns came in the first two games of the season, and
against NFC opponents. Since then, teams have not thrown to
Springs' side as much, limiting his opportunities to make more big
plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the price you pay,'' he said with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Springs has allowed only one touchdown pass this season, when
6-5 Mikhael Ricks out-jumped him for a pass in the end zone during
the Seahawks' Week 8 victory over the San Diego Chargers. Springs
also has a club-high 16 passes defensed and has improved his play
against the run, as evinced by his 59 tackles that rank fifth on
the team.
</P>
<P>
   But is it enough?
</P>
<P>
   New England's Ty Law leads the AFC with seven interceptions and
Miami's Sam Madison and Terrell Buckley each have six. Five other
corners also have five picks _ including the Jets' Aaron Glenn, who
was voted to the Pro Bowl last year; Baltimore's Rod Woodson, a
seven-time Pro Bowl selection while with the Steelers who will draw
votes for his reputation and out of respect for his comeback from a
serious knee injury; and Pittsburgh's Dewayne Washington, who like
Springs and Woodson has two returns for touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shawn is right there in the hunt,'' said veteran cornerback
Terry McDaniel, a five-time Pro Bowl selection while with the
Raiders who joined the Seahawks in September. ``He has made the
plays that drew attention to him early and has continued to play
well each week. To get over the hump, you have to make the big
plays that get you noticed. Then it's a matter of playing
consistently well.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Brown agrees, especially with the comment about
consistency. He is the only Seahawks cornerback ever voted to the
Pro Bowl. That was in 1984. Brown now coaches the position for the
Seahawks and knows players don't always make the Pro Bowl the first
year they deserve it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shawn is having a much-improved year. Whether it's a Pro Bowl
year, I don't know,'' Brown said. ``We have four games to play in
the season, and it's this time of year that the Pro Bowl players
usually come on. It takes being consistent for a full year, not
just a couple of good games.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Shawn is progressing right along.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, that is Springs' ultimate goal. To become the best,
one step at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all I really try to do,'' Springs said, ``is get better
each game and every time I get on the field.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
