<HEADER>
A2856 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRJOY-COLUMN-CORRECTI     12-04 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRJOY-COLUMN-CORRECTION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVIDED OVER THE FAMILY CHRISTMAS REUNION
</HEADLINE>
  (Adds city and state signatures to questions.) 
 FOR USE FRI., DEC. 4, OR ANYTIME THEREAFTER. 
 By DR. JOY BROWNE 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUESTION: It's that home-for-the-holidays season that's supposed
to bring us joy, but it's really tough this year. Both sets of
parents live fairly close and want us with them for the holidays.
My wife thinks we should go to her family's celebration, but I say
let's be with my mom, who is alone this year for the first time. I
know my wife doesn't like Mom, but I think she's being callous and
unreasonable. _ Miami, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: I suspect this problem has been going on for a long
time, but this is the year it's chosen to roost. It sounds as
though neither of you has worked out the ``where do we spend
holidays'' blues. You have been able to finesse it so far, but
finesse time is over. If you had started with a plan, you wouldn't
be in today's pickle.
</P>
<P>
   So let's get to it: With both families close by, holidays and
weekends can be negotiated by spending Christmas Eve with one and
Christmas Day with the other. Do a Thanksgiving/Easter tradeoff.
One year you can give one family first choice and the next the
other set of in-laws. Scheduling may be a pain in the neck, but it
can avert hurt feelings, nagging and fights.
</P>
<P>
   What's changed for you this year is your mom's status. She's
lonely, sad and needy. Your wife is afraid she'll never see her
folks on holidays again. You may view it as a temporary change, but
odds are that neither your mom nor your wife is looking at it that
way. What to do now? Sit down with your wife and work out that
holiday/weekend schedule which will reassure everyone. You don't
even have to stress your mom's special needs right now if your
schedule shows your willingness to be fair and open to both your
wife's and her parents' needs.
</P>
<P>
   Since we're so close to Christmas Day, you may even be able to
negotiate a special, one-time-only joint celebration for both sides
of the family, and if you're really lucky, everybody will have such
a great time it may become an annual event!
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: My wife and I have been married for 12 years and
unhappy for the last 5. We've talked divorce, but we decided to
stay together for the sake of the kids. If we have agreed that's
the only reason we're still married, is an affair legal? _ Los
Angeles
</P>
<P>
   DR.JOY: Trust me, nobody stays together for the sake of the
kids. People stay together because they're afraid to be alone, or
because it's cheaper to support one household than two, or because
they're afraid of losing contact or status or money or friends, and
sometimes because they really care for one another.
</P>
<P>
   People who say they are staying together for the sake of the
kids are kidding themselves. Kids are almost always aware of the
tension, the whispers, the fights, the secret phone conversations
and the lies.
</P>
<P>
   So let's face it: Neither of you is staying together for the
kids. To pretend that you are uses them as chess pieces and more
importantly allows both of you to ignore your real feelings, so
nothing will get resolved. You and your spouse must sit down and be
honest with yourself first and then with each other about what each
of you wants and what each of you is willing to offer in return.
</P>
<P>
   Because you do have children in common, you will always have a
bond with each other, so the more honest you can be now, the better
your long-term prospects for calm and dignified interaction and
THAT is for the sake of the kids as well as one another.
</P>
<P>
   As for an affair, no-fault divorce has made affairs less
dangerous if both of you can agree and a great deal more dangerous
if you can't. The point is an affair is only going to complicate
matters now. Work on your marriage or junk it, but don't lie to
yourself or to each other about why you're together. And involving
someone else in this mess is just plain nasty!
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: I hate my body and there's lots of it to hate. I've
tried every diet known and I still look like the Titanic. My
husband nags me, my mother chides and I eat and eat and eat. Short
of having my mouth glued shut, is there any good way for me to lose
weight? _ Pelham, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: From the sound of it, you are a professional dieter.
You know better than almost anybody how to lose weight, but the
problem is keeping it off. To do that, you need a better
understanding of why you eat, what you eat, when you eat, how you
eat.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing you have to understand is that you can't lose
weight for anybody but yourself. When it's just you and that jelly
doughnut, eyeball to eyeball, there is no amount of Mom or husband
that is going to keep you from blinking. It's you and only you. Ask
yourself if you are eating to assert your independence? Or to put a
buffer between you and the world? Is your weight giving you an
excuse for not finding a job or friends or clothes or being sexual?
</P>
<P>
   Start writing down everything, and I mean everything, before you
put it in your mouth. The very act of writing it down will force
you to ask yourself whether you really want it and help you
document when, why and how you eat. And put a picture of yourself
thin OR heavy on the refrigerator door for motivation (a naked
photo is best if there aren't kids around). Wait a half-hour to eat
whatever you were thinking of engulfing. Keep only good stuff _
that means non-fattening _ in the house, so you and your family
won't snack on trash. Think about getting out of the house. When
we're bored we are more likely to think about food.
</P>
<P>
   We put on weight when we take in more calories than we burn and
lose weight when the opposite is true. The former means better
eating habits, the latter means exercise. Exercise not only makes
you feel more in contract of your body and your life, but it gets
you away from the demon refrigerator and helps you metabolize food
more efficiently. If you think this is an argument for less dieting
and more exercise, you've read me loud and clear.
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
<P>
   Questions may be sent to Dr. Joy Browne, c/o The New York Times
Syndication Sales Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, NY 10168 or to
drjoy &LR; nytsyn.com. Questions of general interest will be answered in
this weekly column. Dr. Joy regrets that unpublished letters cannot
be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   Copyright 1998 by Dr. Joy Browne Distributed by New York Times
Special Features
</P>
