<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARTER-FAULDER-DEATHROW05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rubin Carter urging Gov. George W. Bush to delay execution
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Former boxer Rubin ``Hurricane'' Carter, who
spent 20 years fighting to erase his own wrongful conviction in a
murder trial, is heading to Austin to make the case for a Canadian
man on Texas Death Row.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, like U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, is
urging Gov. George W. Bush to delay the scheduled Dec. 10 execution
of Joseph Stanley Faulder.
</P>
<P>
   Albright and Carter, director of the Toronto-based Association
in Defense of the Wrongly Convicted, say Texas may have violated an
international treaty by not notifying Faulder of his right to
contact Canadian consular officials after his arrest in the 1975
death of Inez Phillips in Gladewater.
</P>
<P>
   A similar argument was raised unsuccessfully last year prior to
the execution of Mexican national Irineo Montoya.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder's case once again brings international scrutiny to Texas
and the unprecedented pace of its executions.
</P>
<P>
   Texas officials say they didn't know that Faulder, a former
Alberta resident, was Canadian. He was imprisoned for 15 years
before the Canadian government and his family, who believed he was
dead, learned of his whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder, 61, would be the first Canadian executed in the United
States since 1952. He was convicted twice for the slaying of
Phillips, matriarch of a wealthy oil family in Gladewater.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder was arrested nearly two years after the murder on
unrelated offenses in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, whose case was a 20-year cause celebre, said Faulder is
entitled to further review of his case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that the Canadian government didn't know of his
situation for 15 years is a clear violation of the treaty,'' he
said. ``That is the starting point from which all else flows.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that Governor Bush will listen. We hope the parole
board will listen. We are not coming down there to disturb or
disrupt. We just want to slow this thing down,'' he said. ``From
all the evidence that we have gathered we think there is a very
strong likelihood that perhaps you have the wrong man.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter's conviction drew national attention after the
publication of his 1974 book ``The Sixteenth Round'' and a Bob
Dylan song entitled ``Hurricane.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, while he was among the world's top middleweight boxers,
Carter was arrested after three people were gunned down at a
Patterson, N.J. bar. He was sentenced to life in prison in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Supreme Court overturned the conviction in 1976.
A retrial led to a second conviction. But Carter was cleared in
1988 when the U.S. Supreme Court affirmed a New Jersey federal
judge's ruling that prosecutors committed ``grave constitutional
violations'' in a case that led to convictions based on ``racism
rather than reason and concealment rather than disclosure.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's office confirmed that Margaret Wilson, his general
counsel, is scheduled to meet with the Canadians on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Albright expressed her concerns in a Nov. 27 letter to Bush,
saying, ``The consular-notification issues in this case are
sufficiently troublesome that they may provide sufficient grounds
for according discretionary clemency relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush responded with a Thursday letter saying the Board of
Pardons and Paroles, which is now reviewing the case, has had
sufficient time to consider the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Short of a board recommendation for clemency, Bush's only power
is to grant a 30-day delay in the execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board has had sufficient time to review Mr. Faulder's
petition in detail and should not require additional time to
examine the issues raised in the petition,'' Bush told Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Also pending is a case brought on behalf of Faulder and other
Death Row inmates by Austin lawyers who claim the clemency process
is illegal because the Board of Pardons and Paroles does not meet
in open session to review cases. State District Judge Paul Davis,
in a preliminary order that does not block the execution, sided
with Faulder and the other inmates this week.
</P>
<P>
   At a Thursday press conference, Bush offered up little sympathy
for Faulder's claim, noting that the consular-communication claim
has been raised unsuccessfully in other cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is in our state people get treated fairly,''
said Bush. ``But on the other hand we are going to uphold the laws
of Texas. People can't just come in our state and cold-blood murder
somebody. That's unacceptable behavior regardless of their
nationality.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
