<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Man files lawsuit in battle to build fence
 &HT;    By Wes Hills
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Joseph L. Howard became disabled by
post-traumatic stress disorder after three tours of duty in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to find peace and privacy behind a 6-foot-high fence
around his Beavercreek home.
</P>
<P>
   The city's refusal to grant him a zoning variance to build the
fence has turned into another battle for Howard, who retired after
27 years with the U.S. Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't allow people to have stockade fences all the way to
the front of their property,'' said Beavercreek City Manager Dan
Dubruiel.
</P>
<P>
   Dubruiel was responding to a lawsuit Howard filed recently
against the city in U.S. District Court in Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   The battle for the fence began on Aug. 10, 1997, when Howard
sought a variance to a zoning code that states, ``No fence, wall or
hedge shall rise over 3 feet in height within any required front
yard.''
</P>
<P>
   To justify the fence at his home, Howard attached a statement
from his physician detailing his condition and need for such a
fence.
</P>
<P>
   At a May 14 meeting before the Board of Zoning Appeals, Howard
said, he described how ``his handicap mandated that he have a
6-foot privacy fence to prevent him from injuring himself in
response to harassment by his neighbors which exacerbated both his
post-traumatic stress disorder and his heart affliction,''
according to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Furthermore, the excessive amount of leaves that blew on to
his property from his neighbors yard that was causing him to rake
his yard was dangerous to his previously diagnosed heart
condition.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit claims the BZA's refusal to let Howard build the
fence violates the handicap discrimination provisions of the
federal Fair Housing Act.
</P>
<P>
   Dubruiel said he has not seen the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Howard also wanted to build his fence to the
street while fences are usually set back 30 to 50 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks $1.1 million in damages and an order barring
the city from preventing Howard from building the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
