<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UT-ENDOWMENT05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Low oil prices means lost funds for universities
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Cheap oil prices are a boon for consumers at the
gas pump, but they are a bust for a Texas university endowment that
earns money from selling oil and gas leases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough time,'' said Dan Burck, executive vice chancellor
for business affairs at the University of Texas System. He
estimated that endowment income from oil and gas leases is down 35
percent this year, especially after the most recent lease sale
attracted few buyers and low bids.
</P>
<P>
   Construction projects and educational programs at the UT and
Texas A&AMP;M University systems are the beneficiaries of the $7.2
billion Permanent University Fund, which is made up of 2.1 million
acres of oil and gas lands in 19 West Texas counties. In past
decades, money from oil and gas revenues contributed the lion's
share of the money in the Permanent University Fund. That money was
invested in stocks and bonds, primarily, and today, oil and gas
income is about $3 billion of the overall fund, Burck said.
</P>
<P>
   An overall strong stock market this year will compensate for the
loss in oil and gas revenues, he added. A semi-annual lease sale
Nov. 18 raised$577,821 compared with $7.75 million a year ago. Only
31 oil and gas leases were sold covering 8,948 acres compared with
93 leases on 30,690 acres a year ago. The average winning bid per
acre this time was $64.58 compared with $252.56 a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happened is people are simply not prepared to spend
money leasing land for oil and gas exploration when the price of
oil is so low,'' said Pam Bacon, a UT System attorney and secretary
to the Board for Lease of University Lands. ``The companies simply
can't afford to spend more and make a profit.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said she was not surprised by the poor sale. The price of
oil is down to about $11 a barrel, its lowest level in a dozen
years.
</P>
<P>
   While UT would like to have the lease money it earned last year,
she said, several million dollars won't break a fund that's in the
billions. ``Given the size of the fund, the $7 million is not
critical,'' Bacon said. UT officials, however, are concerned about
the oil market and have been trying to drum up interest in the oil
and gas leases by cutting the minimum lease price and reducing
royalty payments if operators meet certain conditions, Burck said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are searching and striving to work with industry to
maintain a level of activity, but we also recognize the operators
are in dire straits right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One bright spot is the Board for Lease managed to stimulate
interest in unexplored territory in West Texas, he said. It sold
leases on frontier land in Hudspeth County for the first time in
July. In all, 414 oil leases were awarded, bringing $2 million into
the university fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really had sales that were 10 times better than we thought
they would be,'' Burck said. ``But now we've kind of hit the
wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
