<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MTV-STAMOS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MTV host: `It's not about being beautiful' (Yeah, right)
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ So it's Tuesday afternoon and supermodel
Rebecca Romijn-Stamos is sitting in Miami Beach with an aloe leaf
stuck to her chest. California girl and swimsuit model gets
sunburn. ``You think I'd know by now,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She has been outside all day filming a fashion show for MTV's
House of Style, of which she is the host. She has maybe three hours
before bedtime. She goes to bed at 7 or 8 every night. That's
beauty sleep.
</P>
<P>
   It's no problem for her husband of two months, actor John
Stamos, because he does the same thing. (By the way: He proposed to
her in the buff, she reports, after a ``very intimate moment.'')
</P>
<P>
   She has a few minutes before dinner to talk about model life.
Here goes:
</P>
<P>
   Age: 26.
</P>
<P>
   Background: Modeling for eight years. Was a student at UC-Santa
Cruz when a modeling agent in San Francisco talked her into moving
to Paris. Her first ``gig'' was the cover of French Elle. You might
have seen her in the Sports Illustrated swimsuit issue, or in Tommy
Hilfiger ads, or J. Crew catalogs. She's been the House of Style
host for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Now lives in: Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   What's going on: Just shot the upcoming SI swimsuit issue and
can't talk about it, except to say they are doing something ``very
tantalizing'' they've never done before.
</P>
<P>
   Going topless? ``Not necessarily.''
</P>
<P>
   Location of shoot: A secret.
</P>
<P>
   Penalty for talking about it: Getting her photos cut out of the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Worst photo shoot ever: ``A horrible, horrible shoot for a
Japanese car ad with a German photographer who did not let us sleep
for three days. We were in the Mojave Desert and drove roughly nine
hours a day, and we slept roughly from 1 to 4 a.m. with no
breakfast. I kept trying to walk off the job, but there was nowhere
to go. I finally walked up to him and said, `This is insane.' He
didn't care.''
</P>
<P>
   How to tell if it's going to be a bad shoot: No communication
between the people in charge and the ``talent.'' No respect.
</P>
<P>
   Best shoot: ``The SI shoot in Kenya last year. We took a safari
every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Number of safaris on this year's shoot: ``I can't say.''
</P>
<P>
   Number of deep-sea diving excursions on this year's shoot: ``I
can't say.''
</P>
<P>
   Is modeling something you have to practice? ``It's something you
learn. If I look at my early pictures I go, `Oh my God, I can't
believe I worked the light that way.' You learn your good side.''
</P>
<P>
   Her good side: The right side. ``My nose is crooked, and it
looks smaller from the right.''
</P>
<P>
   Tattoos: A little one on her left ankle of the letters ``j,''
``r,'' ``s'' and ``e'' intertwined. She and her three best friends
got the identical tattoos when she was 18. The initials stand for
``Jennifer,'' ``Rebecca,'' ``Susannah'' and ``Elizabeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Plan to prevent aging: ``I'm looking forward to aging. It's not
something scary to me. I've seen some models stop working at 25 and
let their lives dwindle away.''
</P>
<P>
   Famous people she'd like to see as models: ``The thing is,
everyone can be on a magazine cover these days. The face of fashion
has changed so much. It's not about being beautiful anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Number of people with braces she's seen on magazine covers:
Zero.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast: Three eggs, two waffles.
</P>
<P>
   Workout: Three hours of Pilates a week.
</P>
<P>
   Last thing she checks in mirror before making an appearance:
``First I make sure nothing is coming out of my nose. Then I check
that my eyebrows are not messy. And I check my teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Kids: Going to wait a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   Swimsuit-wearing advice: Work out. Black is always a good color.
Don't necessarily follow swimsuit fashion. ``I just wore a monokini
_ a bikini attached down the middle with a tiny strip. I didn't
find that very flattering. And if you have any bosom at all,
bandeau tops are deadly.''
</P>
<P>
   Advice on how to keep a swimsuit bottom from riding up: None,
unfortunately.
</P>
<P>
   Worst elementary-school photo: ``My dad used to get me and my
sister ready for school every morning, and he would come to me with
a handful of those little plastic barrettes and ask which ones I
wanted to wear. I would say, `All of them.' I took my kindergarten
picture like that. And in second grade I had my hair in Princess
Leia buns, with a cold sore on my lip.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
