u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHOTO-TIPS05-COX     12-04 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-TIPS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Another year, another Christmas card picture: Make it memorable
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Nicole Piscopo
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The annual Christmas picture. Chase the
kids around and force them into their best holiday clothes. Stand
them in front of . . . in front of . . . something and click off a
few frames. Then fetch the pictures from Walgreens and wonder why
everyone looks as joyful and relaxed as British beefeaters.
</P>
<P>
   Photographers at The Post aim to spread a little good cheer with
a few picture-taking suggestions. The tips are point-and-shoot
friendly (even the pros use those in their spare time) and useful
all year around.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, just about every ``rule'' is broken at some point,
often with wonderful results, says photo editor Mark Edelson. ``But
there are some basic pointers beginners can keep in mind that will
usually improve the quality of their pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   1. Choose a clean background that doesn't distract from your
subject.
</P>
<P>
   2. Use outdoor light, if possible, but time your shoot for
earlier in the day and later in the afternoon (before 10 a.m. or
around 4 p.m., this time of the year.) Northern light is always the
softest, but cross light _ when a ray skims across a person's face
_ can be flattering, too. Avoid sun directly in your subject's
face.
</P>
<P>
   3. Shoot a lot of film. ``Four pictures won't cut it,'' photo
editor Mark Edelson says. ``Shoot an entire roll or more. The
relative expense is tiny.'' The more you shoot, the better the
likelihood there will be of at least one really good shot of
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   4. Shoot children at their level. ``So many of us adults tend to
point down our cameras,'' says Photo Director Pete Cross. ``In my
daughter's case, she was too young to stand so I laid her down on
the rug, then shot her from a ladder overhead. But we're at the
same eye level.''
</P>
<P>
   5. Look at everything. Don't focus so much on the kids that you
forget to eyeball what's around them. ``If there's a part of the
frame that has someone's foot, or telephone lines in it, or
whatever, it will also appear in your card,'' says Cross. ``Look at
everything before you press the button to avoid that mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, just bending down six inches or a foot can make a
big difference in cleaning up what's in your picture,'' says
Edelson.
</P>
<P>
   6. Make faces prominent. For the most part, it's best to avoid
standing back and shooting full length. And ``amateurs tend to put
people's heads in the middle of the frame, leaving a lot of space
at the top.'' says photographer Sherman Zent. ``But if there's
really nothing interesting at the top of the frame, put your
subject's head there.''
</P>
<P>
   7. Avoid filling the frame entirely. Mass processing almost
always ensures part of the image will be lopped off, and card
frames shave off more of the image. (Edelson recommends composing
the picture you like and then stepping back a foot.)
</P>
<P>
   8. Experiment. ``Shoot what you think is a person's best angle,
then try a few more,'' says Edelson. Hint: Shooting up the nostrils
is almost always unflattering.
</P>
<P>
   9. Bribe. Clown around and be silly. Have treats standing by.
Commanding everyone to smile won't work, unless you like a stiff,
frozen look. ``The goal is to make everyone happy,'' says Edelson.
``You can always punish them later!''
</P>
<P>
   10. Avoid the ``say cheese'' rut. On the other hand, every
picture doesn't have to include smiling children. Children cry.
Children get cranky. ``Get some shots of them looking natural,''
says Zent. ``If you don't, every photo you have will be of your kid
smiling.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
