<HEADER>
A2881 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-LOVE-DEVIL05-C     12-04 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-LOVE-DEVIL05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REVIEW: `Love is the Devil'
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If ever a painter's surname hinted at the flavor
of his work, Francis Bacon's came bloody close. For instance, when
I think bacon, I think slaughtered farm fauna and greasy slabs of
livid meat. When I think Bacon, I get the same image, though
without the side of home fries.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's ``Love Is the Devil,'' an ultra-bleak biopic of the
late British artist, which has sufficient blood but little meat _
literally and narratively. Bacon's estate barred the use of his
work in the film, so we never see those apocalyptic canvases, those
fetid visions of exalted morbidity: riven carcasses, screaming
human figures and molested crucifixes, all dunked in the bruised
hues of viscera.
</P>
<P>
   We do see Derek Jacobi's courtly Bacon slather goopy globules of
pigment across canvases in convulsive herks and jerks. But, like
these hinted-at paintings, the story of Bacon and his turbulent
love affair with a troubled young man remains fractured and
incomplete. The film is almost totally devoid of engaging drama,
let alone a clear portrait of Bacon's life and career, relying too
much on visual pyrotechnics and one or two interesting character
sketches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Devil,'' written and directed with conceptual exuberance by
John Maybury, is in dizzy, implacable love with the voluptuous.
Maybury caresses textures, wringing from them the metaphorical.
Some of the images _ the fun-house mirror reflections of characters
in water and metal surfaces, disquieting fish-eye close-ups _
become key visual motifs.
</P>
<P>
   Maybury scrapes Bacon's id, not his ego, and this makes for
mounds of inscrutable psychological doodling and scarce coherence.
The whole thing, as striking and haunting as it is, shivers in the
clammy, disjointed rhythms of a fever-dream. It's a phantasmagoria
of sex (largely homosexual), squalor, death, art and epic
dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am optimistic about nothing,'' says Jacobi in voice-over,
and then the film might cut to a naked man who looks freshly
skinned, bent on all fours atop a perilously thin plank, yowling
into the void. Part of a Bacon painting? The primal scream of the
artist's inner demon? Bad gas?
</P>
<P>
   This opaque sequence, and the many like it, revel in baroque
artifice, which tantalizes us as it wears. Linear clarity is often
sacrificed for the fantastical: When Bacon's face is splattered
with blood from a boxing ring, he is seized by glassy-eyed rapture,
deriving an erotic charge from the bloodbath. Bun(tilde)uel would
be proud.
</P>
<P>
   Hiccups of story tell how George Dyer, Bacon's lover and model
of seven years, enters the cantankerous artist's life (with a
dramatic crash) and how the couple emotionally batter one another
until Dyer attempts suicide. Yet Dyer (an elusive Daniel Craig)
exerts a galvanizing effect on the older man, who in turn tries to
assimilate the youth into his coterie of bibulous friends, whom he
dubs his ``concentration of camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobi's vain and bitchy Bacon bubbles with Wildean wit, but his
doling out of tidy epigrams at will _ ``Champagne for my real
friends, real pain for my sham friends'' _ becomes schematic and
implausible.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the dazzle Maybury lavishes on his tale, we never get
to know Bacon's casually cruel monster, nor decipher his abstract
love for Dyer, who seems little more than a trophy beau, an X-ray
in Bacon's bright light.
</P>
<P>
   Cinematically, ``Love Is the Devil'' has a great deal to
recommend it, and I do. I relished its horrible beauty, even as its
sensorial feast left me hungry.
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Derek Jacobi, Daniel Craig, Tilda Swinton
</P>
<P>
   Director: John Maybury
</P>
<P>
   Screenwriter: John Maybury
</P>
<P>
   MPAA rating: Not rated; contains violence, nudity, substance
abuse, profanity
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
