A2882 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIMPLE-CHRISTMAS05-CO     12-04 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-CHRISTMAS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keep your Christmas simple
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Don Andrus is doing his part to turn a
shop-worn cliche into reality.
</P>
<P>
   The seasonal Jupiter resident peddles bumper stickers every
December urging all to ``Keep Christ in Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrus, 68, distributes about 3,000 stickers through his modest
crusade in Guilford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping seems to be the principal culprit that threatens to
shut Christ out of his own birthday party.
</P>
<P>
   The season's endless list of gifts to buy and cards to address
exhausts the faithful and perverts the holiday. The poor and
outcast for whom Christ was born are often unable to take part in
the extravagant celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Even Jews suffer from a commercial Christmas madness that
ripples into their Hanukkah celebration.
</P>
<P>
   But, like the message of Christmas itself, there is hope. For
some, the shopping orgy has peaked, and they are shaping new ways
to keep Christmas centered on Christ.
</P>
<P>
   A few courageous souls do no holiday shopping at all. Others buy
gifts through the year and resist the lure of the mall in December.
</P>
<P>
   Still others make original gifts or give the best presents of
all: themselves, their time and attention.
</P>
<P>
   The brave send fewer Christmas cards, learn to say no to some
parties and concentrate on their families.
</P>
<P>
   More people are trying to plan the holiday around family, food
and faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing we want most of all, maybe, is a greater sense of
the divine,'' said Bill McKibben, author of a ``Hundred Dollar
Holiday, The Case for a More Joyful Christmas'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
1998, 96 pages, $12.) ``It's a shame that Christmas is so
surrounded by other stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   McKibben spreads a gospel that Christmas doesn't come from a
store and urges people to consider spending no more than $100 for
the holiday. Give fewer gifts or make your own presents, he
suggests.
</P>
<P>
   The best present of all may be a gift certificate that is a
claim on your time to take a walk, read a book or do the dishes for
someone.
</P>
<P>
   McKibben claims that many American Christmas customs were shaped
in the 19th century when the country was poor and hard working.
What made the holiday special then was having a lot of gifts.
</P>
<P>
   But, in this time of affluence that is no longer true. Many
people have all they need and more than they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make Christmas really special to have a heap of
presents,'' McKibben said.
</P>
<P>
   Now we want time with family and opportunities to build
relationships and talk with one another.
</P>
<P>
   We should shape our Christmas traditions to meet those needs, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital chaplain Kenneth Bowling agrees. He will not waste time
or money shopping in December. He has children and grandchildren,
but he buys them things all through the year, he said. Christmas is
not about gift-giving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I refuse to go to the mall,'' said Bowling, 50, a chaplain at
Good Samaritan Medical Center in West Palm Beach. ``We do Christ a
disservice when we get caught up in gift-buying, even though He is
the ultimate gift.''
</P>
<P>
   Families with young children have a particular challenge to
focus on the meaning of the Christmas event often dominated by
Teletubbies, a red-nosed reindeer and Santa Claus.
</P>
<P>
   Haley Locke, 7, and her sister Shelley, 4, share Christmas
stories in December with their parents. They read a children's
devotional Bible every night before bed, said their father, the
Rev. Dale Locke. He is pastor of Community of Hope United Methodist
Church in Royal Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The Lockes take advantage of the largely forgotten church season
of Advent to hold at bay the secular forces that start Christmas
celebrations in November.
</P>
<P>
   The four-week period of anticipation and preparation before
Christmas is often marked with a wreath of greens and four candles.
</P>
<P>
   Each night a family member lights a candle, reads a portion of
Scripture and offers a prayer. An additional candle is lighted to
mark each week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've built an Advent wreath through the month,'' Locke said.
``Another year we opened a different little gift each night, an
angel, a wise man, to hang on the tree.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lockes keep a tight budget and buy nothing on credit for
Christmas. That helps stem the temptation to spend too much.
</P>
<P>
   A few people have given up Christmas traditions completely, trim
no tree, give no presents, accept no invitations, prepare no
banquets and do not worship, but they love Christmas, they say.
</P>
<P>
   They use the holiday for reflection and retreat from the busy
world and as a time to serve their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We changed our focus,'' said Elaine St. James, author of
``Simplify Your Christmas'' (Andrew McMeel, 1998, 270 pages,
$14.95) ``We began to look at what we can contribute to the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   St. James admits most people do not want to discard Christmas
completely as she has. Her book includes 100 ways to make the
holiday simpler.
</P>
<P>
   Many of her suggestions are about resisting the urge to shop.
Turn off the television in December, stop reading women's magazines
and shut out the commercial cry that shopping is the only way to
celebrate the birth of Jesus, she writes.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas gift-giving even challenges Jews who try to mark
Hanukkah.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-day holiday begins on Dec. 13 this year and is
burdened by its proximity to the Christmas madness.
</P>
<P>
   Many Jews celebrate that festival of religious freedom by
capitulating to Christmas trees, cards and presents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pay attention to what the holiday is,'' said Susan Levine, a
member of Temple Judea in West Palm Beach. ``It is a celebration of
rededication and religious freedom. Don't get caught up in the
gift-buying frenzy.''
</P>
<P>
   The demands of gift-giving that mean spending inordinate time,
energy and money shopping can make the faithful lose sight of the
reason for the holiday. The celebration becomes a contradiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe there is possibly something demonic in the huge toy
stores,'' said the Rev. Fred LaCrone, pastor of Grace Episcopal
Church in West Palm Beach. ``I wonder what we are teaching our kids
_ to be frantic and acquisitive? That's the opposite of what Christ
teaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Give a gift to your church or to a homeless shelter or soup
kitchen in honor of Jesus' birth, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And recover Advent as a way of preparing for Christmas with
expectation rather than exasperation. We can do that, he said, by
saying yes to fewer parties and no to more gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, LaCrone loves the joy, even the frenzy, of the holiday.
He would never favor a return to colonial times when Christmas
celebration was banned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all in favor of celebration and parties and jumping
around,'' said LaCrone. ``I think the Puritan Christmas must have
been terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
