<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New books just in time for Christmas
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sterling Publishing Co. is out with two very handsome
new books for woodworkers, just in time to make some Christmas
lists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fine Decorative Boxes'' by Andrew Crawford ($19.95 in
softcover) and ``Making Shaker Woodenware'' by Kerry Pierce ($17.95
in softcover) both concern the construction of small things, and
both are handsomely-made books, but the similarities fade after
that.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford's book offers 10 projects preceded by a 17-page
discourse on tools and techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford's designs for the projects range from the very elegant
to the somewhat inelegant. The box carcases are constructed of
high-quality 3/8-inch plywood and covered with fine veneers, which
are then detailed with various inlays.
</P>
<P>
   Much use is made, in the more successful designs, of curved lids
and sides.
</P>
<P>
   The last section of the book is a gallery, and to many
woodworkers it will be the best part. There are some simply
incredible pieces here, some made by the world's premier box makers
such as Po Shun Leong and Michael Brolly. The only piece I don't
care for in the entire gallery is an otherwise very nice box by
Fiona McVey whose sides are joined with clunky machine-made
dovetails.
</P>
<P>
   You will find no machine-made dovetails in Pierce's book.
</P>
<P>
   If there is an American style of woodworking, it would have to
be Shaker. Its simplicity has to appeal to virtually every
woodworker, but its inherent elegance is not so easily achieved.
Shaker cabinetmakers were masters of the just proportion.
</P>
<P>
   The first half of the book is taken up with discussions of
Shaker woodworking techniques, design principles and tools as well
as a brief explanation of this strange sect, which never numbered
much more than 6,000, and which is, of course, now utterly defunct
because they were committed to celibacy.
</P>
<P>
   There follow 13 projects, all within the reach of a careful and
committed beginning craftsman. Kitchen projects include several
scoops and dippers and a couple of very typical high-sided serving
trays.
</P>
<P>
   There's a section on items for the sewing room, including
clothes hangers and a lovely little two-step stool.
</P>
<P>
   Items for the workroom are mostly boxes and carriers, which are
just boxes with handles and no lids.
</P>
<P>
   The book concludes with the ubiquitous oval bentwood boxes.
These are easily the most difficult pieces in the book, requiring
molds around which the soaked sides are bent, and delicetly scarfed
joints.
</P>
<P>
   If you admire the Shaker style and want to try your hand at
simple iterations of it, this is an excellent place to start. You
get a taste of the idiom and the reasoning behind it as well as the
technique.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
