<SLUG> BC-12-HOLIDAY-COOKIES05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On the first day of christmas, my true love gave to me . . . a
big plate of cookies
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ True holiday bakers know you can't make
just one kind of cookie. So how about 12? Here are a dozen ideas to
go with the Christmas carol. And don't forget to sing while you're
at it!
</P>
<P>
   12 drummers drumming
</P>
<P>
   Linzer tarts with raspberry filling
</P>
<P>
   11 pipers piping
</P>
<P>
   Rolled lace cookies
</P>
<P>
   10 lords a leaping
</P>
<P>
   Ginger cutouts
</P>
<P>
   9 ladies dancing
</P>
<P>
   Lace cookie skirts
</P>
<P>
   8 maids a milking
</P>
<P>
   Cheesecake bars
</P>
<P>
   7 swans a swimming
</P>
<P>
   Meringue
</P>
<P>
   6 geese a laying
</P>
<P>
   Coconut nests with candy-covered almonds
</P>
<P>
   5 golden rings
</P>
<P>
   Coconut macaroons
</P>
<P>
   4 calling birds
</P>
<P>
   Cinnamon-sugar dusted linzer cutouts
</P>
<P>
   3 french hens
</P>
<P>
   Ginger cookies
</P>
<P>
   2 turtle doves
</P>
<P>
   Caramel, pecans and chocolate on vanilla wafer
</P>
<P>
   A partridge in a pear tree
</P>
<P>
   Linzer tart with raspberry filling
</P>
<P>
   TRY THESE DELECTABLE COOKIES FOR MEMORABLE HOLIDAY TREAT
</P>
<P>
   Use these holiday cookies only as a guide _ we suggest
variations, but there are many more you could try. For the cut-out
cookies, we created the designs free-form _ only the French hen and
cow cookies were made with cutters, available from Wilton, the
cake-decoration company. Cutters can be found at most stores that
carry kitchen equipment, as well as in kitchenware shops or by
mail-order from baking companies.
</P>
<P>
   Linzer tarts are classic at the holidays, and with festive red
raspberry filling, they are lovely with any cutout you choose. The
same dough is used for cookies No. 1 (the pear cookie with
partridge cutout); No. 4 (calling birds, with drizzled icing); and
No. 12 (small drums, also with icing).
</P>
<P>
   LINZER TARTS
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup unsalted butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla or almond extract
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon milk
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 jar seedless raspberry jam (or your choice of filling _ see
below)
</P>
<P>
   Cream the butter, sugar and egg until soft and creamy. Beat in
vanilla and milk. Mix flour, baking powder and salt in separate
bowl; stir with whisk. Stir dry mixture into creamed ingredients to
make a uniform dough.
</P>
<P>
   Knead several times in the bowl, then flatten dough to a
3/4-inch thick rectangle and wrap in plastic wrap. Refrigerate for
2 hours or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Roll the chilled dough to 1/3-inch thick on a lightly floured
surface. (Keep unrolled dough in refrigerator to prevent dough from
becoming sticky.)
</P>
<P>
   For partridge and pear cookies, and calling bird cookies, cut
out six 7-inch tall pears. From three of the pears, cut out
partridge shapes. From dough scraps, cut out three leaves.
</P>
<P>
   For drum cookies, cut out rectangle drum and strips for drum top
and bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Place cookies on lightly greased baking sheet. Bake cookies at
350 degrees for 12 to 15 minutes or until edges just begin to
brown. Cool on sheets one minute before transferring to wire rack
to cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   To sandwich cookies: Spread uncut pear or drum bottom with
preserves. Top with cutout pieces. Dust with powdered sugar or use
icing as desired.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 7-inch partridge-in-pear cookies.
</P>
<P>
   For the calling birds: Bake the partridge cutouts at the same
time as you bake the pears. Use icing of choice, or dust with
cinnamon-sugar for a snickerdoodle taste.
</P>
<P>
   For the drums: Cut out squares for the bottom layer, and small
half-moons or strips for the drum. Bake the dough and spread with
preserves. Use a squeeze-on icing for the x's.
</P>
<P>
   Variations and suggestions: Change the flavor and color of the
filling as desired; use any fruit preserves. Pear preserves are a
good choice for flavor; mint jelly for appearance. You also can
sandwich these cookies with chocolate, or roll nuts or coconut into
the dough. Add 1/4 cup cocoa powder to half the dough to create
black-and-white layered cookies.
</P>
<P>
   (Above recipe and design adapted from Ladies Home Journal
magazine, December 1998.)
</P>
<P>
   The turtle doves of the song inspired us to bend the song a bit,
and make turtle-shaped cookies. Our version of the holiday favorite
has a realistic shape, thanks to the vanilla wafer ``shell.''
</P>
<P>
   TURTLE COOKIES
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces semisweet chocolate
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon butter-flavored shortening (to prevent chocolate from
seizing)
</P>
<P>
   38 caramels, unwrapped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   25 vanilla wafers
</P>
<P>
   125 pecan halves, (about 1 pound), toasted
</P>
<P>
   Grease a foil-lined cookie sheet. Arrange five pecan halves for
each turtle, placing one pecan for the head and four others for
legs.
</P>
<P>
   Melt caramels with cream in double boiler. Or melt in
microwave-safe bowl on high power for 20 seconds. Remove and stir,
then microwave again on high for 15 seconds, repeating as needed to
completely melt candies.
</P>
<P>
   Drizzle enough caramel to hold pecans together _ about 1/2
teaspoon. Add a vanilla wafer to the top of each set of pecans,
press to adhere.
</P>
<P>
   Dollop about a teaspoon of caramel on top of the vanilla wafers.
Swirl the caramel, but try not to let it drop onto foil. Rinse
spoons in hot water as needed. Re-melt the caramel in microwave in
15-minute increments as needed to keep it workable.
</P>
<P>
   Place chocolate in zip-top plastic bag. Place bag in bowl of hot
water; allow to melt. Knead bag with fingers to make sure all
pieces are melted. Keep chocolate warm until needed.
</P>
<P>
   Snip corner of bag containing chocolate and gently squeeze out
dots or circle of chocolate on top of each turtle. Spread with fork
tines to create turtle-shell design.
</P>
<P>
   Chill to set.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 25 turtles.
</P>
<P>
   (Recipe adapted from Rose's Christmas Cookies, Morrow, 1990).
</P>
<P>
   The yellow French hens and cute leaping lords are made from a
ginger-dough cutout. They're decorated with sugar icing that's been
made with lemon juice for extra flavor. Color the chicken with
yellow food coloring, and use tuxedo colors for the lord. (Note:
Black food coloring is available at stores that carry
cake-decorating supplies, or you can combine other colors to create
a dark blue or dark red for a more festive lord.)
</P>
<P>
   GINGER CUT-OUT DOUGH
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup solid vegetable shortening
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dark molasses
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup firmly packed dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons baking soda dissolved in 2 tablespoons hot water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground mace
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon orange extract
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   4 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   For icing:
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons meringue powder _ see note
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups powdered sugar, sifted
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons lemon juice (more as needed for consistency)
</P>
<P>
   Melt shortening and transfer to a large mixer bowl. Add
molasses, brown sugar and dissolved baking soda; blend. Add spices,
orange extract and salt; blend again. Gradually add flour and mix
well, using hands if needed to work in all the flour. Wrap the
dough in plastic, refrigerate until ``ripened'' for best flavor _
at least overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Divide dough into fifths and
refrigerate all but one portion. Place dough on floured surface and
lay a large piece of plastic wrap on top to roll out to 1/4-inch
thickness.
</P>
<P>
   Cut out the dough into shapes with cutter or free-form. Transfer
dough to parchment-covered cookie sheets and bake until very light
brown, 4 to 5 minutes, watching carefully to prevent overbrowning.
</P>
<P>
   Allow cookies to remain on sheet for 2 minutes before
transferring to wire rack to cool.
</P>
<P>
   Continue rolling and baking as above. Store cooled, iced cookies
in tins.
</P>
<P>
   Note: This dough can be formed into logs, chilled very well, and
sliced very thin for simple, round Morovian-style cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Mix icing ingredients in small bowl. Use more sugar or lemon
juice to produce correct consistency for piping.
</P>
<P>
   Decorate cooled cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 8 dozen French hens, or 2 dozen leaping lords.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Meringue powder is available wherever cake-decorating
supplies are sold.
</P>
<P>
   (Recipe adapted from Christmas in the Heartlands by Marcia
Adams, 1992, Clarkson Potter.)
</P>
<P>
   The five golden rings and geese nests were made from the same
coconut macaroon dough. The one trick to these cookies is baking on
a day with low humidity. The dough, and cookies, will be very
sticky if made on a humid or rainy day.
</P>
<P>
   COCONUT MACAROON WREATHS AND NESTS
</P>
<P>
   2 egg whites
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   Dash salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon almond extract
</P>
<P>
   2 cups grated coconut _ fresh is preferred, see note
</P>
<P>
   Decorations:
</P>
<P>
   Cinnamon candies
</P>
<P>
   Candy-covered almonds
</P>
<P>
   Note: If using canned pre-sweetened flaked coconut, reduce the
sugar in the recipe to 1/4 cup.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 325 degrees. Grease and lightly flour cookie sheet.
In medium bowl, beat egg whites until frothy. Add sugar, flour,
salt and almond extract; mix well. Stir in coconut; drop by
tablespoonfuls 2 inches apart onto greased and floured cookie
sheet.
</P>
<P>
   To make wreaths, press dough into round shape and using the
handle of a wooden spoon, make a hole in center.
</P>
<P>
   Bake at 325 degrees for 13 to 17 minutes or until set and light
golden brown. Immediately remove from cookie sheet.
</P>
<P>
   For nests, press thumb into center of each cookie. Add 2 or 3
Jordan almonds to each. For wreaths, add cinnamon candies to
represent holly berries.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 12 cookies.
</P>
<P>
   (Recipe from Pillsbury: Best Desserts, 1998, Clarkson Potter.)
</P>
<P>
   Lovely meringue swans can grace your dessert tray _ if you're a
confident baker. Piped into delicate shapes, these are the most
fragile of all cookies and baking them is a test of patience.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to make them the easy way _ and they're a nice
addition to the dessert tray for those who cannot have flour or
gluten _ you can merely drop the mounds of meringue onto a baking
sheet and hollow them to fill with a favorite flavor.
</P>
<P>
   MERINGUE SWANS
</P>
<P>
   3 egg whites, room temperature
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of cream of tartar
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup superfine sugar, or granulated sugar, sifted
</P>
<P>
   For coconut-whipped cream filling:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy whipping cream, chilled
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup powdered sugar, sifted
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sweetened flaked coconut
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 250 degrees (cq); move both racks toward center
of oven. Line two cookie sheets with parchment paper or lightly
grease and flour sheets.
</P>
<P>
   In medium bowl, whip egg whites until stiff. Add cream of tartar
and salt. With beaters on high speed, add sugar a little at a time,
beating well after each addition. Test results by rubbing meringue
between fingers _ if grainy, continue beating. Beat until smooth
and mixture is shiny.
</P>
<P>
   Using a pastry bag and small star tip, pipe meringue onto cookie
sheets lined with lightly greased parchment paper (or drop by
dollops if desired).
</P>
<P>
   The swan necks and bodies are created separately. To make the
necks, pipe out the figure ``2.'' Using a large serving spoon, form
an oval mound shape for the bodies, and pull spoon up at one end
for the tail.
</P>
<P>
   Place cookie sheets in oven and bake for 1 hour. Turn off oven
and allow to bake 1 to 2 more hours; watch to prevent browning.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, make filling: Whip cream until stiff. Add sugar and
whip until incorporated. Fold in coconut.
</P>
<P>
   Handling carefully, remove cookie sheets from oven. Carefully
remove swan bodies and necks one at a time from sheet and place on
work surface. With tip of very thin, sharp knife, cut a small oval
from top of body. Hollow body slightly with knife. With teaspoon,
mound coconut filling into swan body. Place swan neck in front,
pushing carefully into filling. Use cut-out oval pieces from swan
body to make wings; set into filling in swan's back.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 small swans.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Best when eaten right away if filled; if left plain, they
can be stored for a month in an airtight container.
</P>
<P>
   (Recipe adapted from The Joy of Cooking by Marian S. Rombauer.)
</P>
<P>
   A cookie cutter was used to create the cheesecake cow,
representing eight maids a-milking. A much simpler, and just as
pretty design, is to cut them into diamond shapes right in the pan.
</P>
<P>
   EASY CHEESECAKE BARS
</P>
<P>
   For crust:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cup graham cracker crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   For filling:
</P>
<P>
   2 large packages cream cheese (16 ounces total)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   For topping:
</P>
<P>
   1 pint sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Mix crust ingredients and press
firmly into bottom of 13-by-9-inch pan.
</P>
<P>
   Mix filling ingredients and beat until very smooth. Pour over
crumbs. Bake at 375 degrees for 25 minutes. Remove and cool 15
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Mix together topping ingredients. Spoon and smooth on top of
filling. Return to oven for 10 more minutes. Remove and cool;
refrigerate. Chill very well if attempting to cut into shapes.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 24 bars or diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   (Recipe from Boca Cooks, compilation of Sabra Hadassah of Boca
Raton, 1987.)
</P>
<P>
   These delicate lace cookies, shaped into ladies' dancing skirts
and rolled into pipes, are also called Florentines. They are
elegant and the perfect accompaniment to a cup of hot espresso.
Don't let the kids help with these _ the hot-sugar dough can burn
the skin.
</P>
<P>
   LACE COOKIES
</P>
<P>
   1 stick plus 2 1/2 tablespoons butter (don't substitute
margarine)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup packed dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup light corn syrup (grease measuring cup for easy pouring)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons almond extract
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Move oven racks to center thirds of
oven.
</P>
<P>
   In heavy bottomed saucepan, mix and bring to a boil butter,
sugar and syrup. Remove from heat, but keep warm. Whisk in flour,
salt and extract. Dough will be thick liquid. Keep pan warm so
mixture remains pourable.
</P>
<P>
   Using nonstick cookie pans, or lightly greased parchment-lined
pans, drop 1 tablespoon liquid dough onto greased pan. Note:
mixture spreads widely; make only four cookies per pan. (You must
work fast to complete shaping of cookies once they are taken from
oven; do not make more than six cookies per batch.)
</P>
<P>
   Bake, watching carefully. When cookies are beginning to brown
around edges and are slightly brown in center, remove pan from
oven. Cool one minute only _ or until cookies do not wrinkle as you
slide spatula under them.
</P>
<P>
   Working quickly, roll up around chopstick to form pipes, or
drape over neck of funnel or around curve of wine bottle to form
curved shapes.
</P>
<P>
   CAUTION: Both liquid dough and cookies are extremely hot _ keep
ice water for dipping fingers in after handling to prevent burns.
</P>
<P>
   Cookies will become crisp in a matter of seconds. If cookies
become hard before you can shape them, return them to the oven
briefly to soften for shaping.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 18 large rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Variations: Add 1/3 cup finely chopped almonds to dough. Form
into shells by shaping on the back of muffin tins and fill with
cream cheese, whipped cream and sliced fruits for a formal dessert.
Dip edges of rolled cookies into melted chocolate and crushed nuts.
</P>
<P>
   DO'S AND DOUGHS
</P>
<P>
   Here are tips to make cookie baking easier.
</P>
<P>
   _ Get the weather forecast before baking. South Florida's
humidity will wreck cookies made with cooked sugar, and those made
with egg whites. It also kills effectiveness of yeast, baking
powder and baking soda; replace those after three months.
</P>
<P>
   _ Always preheat the oven unless otherwise stated in a recipe.
Move the oven racks as close to the center as possible.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wipe and regrease cookie sheets between batches. Allow sheets
to cool to room temperature before washing and before dropping
dough onto them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chill rolled doughs for best results. Freeze slice-and-bake
doughs for uniform cutting. Use dental floss or fishing line to
make thin slices from the rolls, and to cut cheesecakes cleanly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Almost all drop cookie doughs can be made into bars. Press
into a greased pan and bake at 350 degrees until done. A 9-by-9 pan
takes about 20-30 minutes at 350.
</P>
<P>
   _ Freeze most cookie doughs for up to three months. Drop cookies
or slice dough onto waxed paper-lined cookie sheets; freeze the
dough until hard and remove to pack into freezer containers and use
individually.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use meringue powder instead of raw egg whites for royal icing.
It's available where cake decorating ingredients are sold.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
