A2885 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MALICK-RETURNS05-COX     12-04 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALICK-RETURNS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Director Terrence Malick not worthy of buzz surrounding his
return
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Ever since ``Days of Heaven,'' his slow,
minimalist paean to wounded hearts, wheat and small prairie
animals, director Terrence Malick has worn an oversized halo
presented by critics and industry types who routinely confuse
breathtaking cinematography for genius.
</P>
<P>
   Malick, an off-and-on Austinite since his youth, has made two
very good movies, ``Badlands'' in 1973 and ``Days of Heaven'' in
1978. These are his only films to date. He is considered one of the
greatest filmmakers of his generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Badlands,'' a hypnotically brutal drama, stars Martin Sheen
and a wraithish Sissy Spacek as killers on the lam making it up as
they go. ``Days of Heaven'' is a maddeningly elliptical film about
our place vis-a-vis the planet's natural order. Gassy with pretty
pictures, it plays like a National Geographic meditation,
fetishized images, sober narration and all.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. I like both films. I think ``Badlands'' is
the better one; its narrative engine is strong, its flavor for
people and place unerring, its sidelong wit great fun. Conversely,
``Heaven'' is poky and ponderous, a fugue in wide-screen.
</P>
<P>
   Malick's 20-year hiatus from film ends Dec. 25 when his
massively anticipated World War II epic ``The Thin Red Line'' is
released in New York and Los Angeles. (It opens in Austin on Jan.
15.) A giddy Hollywood and fans are scheduling their lives around
its opening, awaiting the Second Coming of Malick, ready to embrace
the well-buzzed movie like a sacrament.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with everyone from Stanley Kubrick and J.D. Salinger to
God (why not Godot?), Malick's famous reclusiveness _ no press
interviews, no sanctioned photographs, a spotty work ethic _ has
won him mythological status. He made two fine movies, and then
vanished. A myth is born. Since then, his reputation has been fired
and inflated like a hot-air balloon.
</P>
<P>
   Has ever an artist been canonized for doing so little?
</P>
<P>
   Malick isn't playing fair. He seems to me a cowardly artist, a
too-proud perfectionist mortally afraid of making a misstep. He's
hit two home runs and, worried about blowing his streak, has
declined another at-bat. That's a reductive presumption, of course:
Malick's labors on other (aborted) projects, as well as his script
doctoring over the decades, are well-documented.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I'm reluctant to extol an artist who hasn't a body of
work _ ranging context that could provide a sort of full-figured
profile of the artist at his best and worst.
</P>
<P>
   A Malick associate was quoted in Vanity Fair as saying, ``Terry
had this notion of wanting to make the perfect movie. If he
couldn't, there was no point.''
</P>
<P>
   That's noble thinking, but does an artist have that luxury?
Surely it's a prerogative any craftsperson recognizes and perhaps
wishes for but also knows is foolhardy. Mistakes, gaffes and
disasters are the growing pains of creativity. All the great
filmmakers, from Chaplin to Scorsese, have detonated their share of
stinkbombs. Risks were taken, and occasionally the sublime was
struck.
</P>
<P>
   I'm loath to ascribe Malick's success to luck. He's a
demonstrably gifted filmmaker with profound ideas, visionary flair
and enormous originality. But as someone who so methodically
rejects the artistic spirit _ ``Produce, produce, for the night is
coming,'' one writer has implored _ Malick, I believe, has not
earned his station in the pantheon.
</P>
<P>
   And if for any reason, it is the prospect of artistic risk that
``The Thin Red Line'' should be awaited with bated breath.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
