</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Where's the info aisle?
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ It's amazing how many people work in retail sales
jobs but don't know anything about the products they sell.
</P>
<P>
   They are happy to hover next to you and to ring up a purchase.
But they know precious little about the merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have any of these in blue?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have them in red and black.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see you have them in red and black in this display. But
do you have any in blue?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would imagine if we had any in blue they would be on
display.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not Kenneth Starr. Do you know that you don't have any of
these in blue?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure that they even make them in blue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they make them in blue, either. But in case
they do make them in blue, and in case you happen to have them in
blue, and if I could see one, I just might buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had any in blue, I'm sure they would be here on
display.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when store clerks told me that they didn't have
a particular item that I assumed they were right. Of course, there
was a time when that would have been a safe assumption. No more.
</P>
<P>
   Lazy sales clerks who don't know their store's inventory now
often deflect questions they can't answer by telling customers that
they don't carry that particular item.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have any Model 500 Widgets?''
</P>
<P>
   A ``yes'' answer probably means the store has Model 500 Widgets
in stock.
</P>
<P>
   A ``no'' answer could mean that the store doesn't have any Model
500 Widgets. It also could mean that you've gotten the brush-off
from a lazy sales person who doesn't know the answer to your
question and doesn't want to ask for fear of being told to learn
the store's inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Safeway Stores Inc. has stirred up dissension among some of its
employees for the company's ``Superior Service'' rules that attempt
to be more helpful and friendly to shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Safeway executives are trying to build a loyal customer base in
the highly competitive industry by having employees make eye
contact with customers, smile, offer greetings and help shoppers
locate items they can't find, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds good to me, and, according to Safeway officials, to
most of their customers. The employees who don't like the policy
think it is too forced and artificial. They also don't like the
idea that Safeway sends in ``mystery shoppers'' who monitor the
employees on a 19-point ``friendliness'' report.
</P>
<P>
   Friendly is fine. But frankly, I'd trade all the forced smiles
for helpfulness, which has to include knowledge of the merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a problem I've experienced in grocery stores. Other
than asking the location of some item, I don't have any questions
that require answers.
</P>
<P>
   Many stores employ sales people who are perfectly friendly but
appear totally clueless.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the battery life on this laptop computer?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The batteries on most laptops run between two to three
hours.'' Big smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about this particular one?''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are good batteries or we wouldn't sell them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What type of batteries are they? Are they nickel metal hydride
or lithium ion?''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our newest model so I'm sure it has top-of-the-line
batteries.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, thanks a lot. I think I'll just look around.''
</P>
<P>
   When was the last time you have been sold a product by a sales
person who knew the product inside and out, who made you want the
product, who made you happy that you bought the product and who
made you want to do business again in that store?
</P>
<P>
   When you find sales people like that, stick with them. They are
a dying breed.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNethaol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
