<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The best toy to put in your kids' Christmas stocking
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that almost all of you have missed out on getting Furbys
(which, when you say it like that, sounds more like a disease than
a toy), you may be wondering what to get your kids for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   No one has asked my advice on this matter yet, though I have a
great deal of experience in buying children's toys. For a fact, I
have learned the perfect toy for all children regardless of age.
</P>
<P>
   This knowledge has come to me because I have, during the course
of the last 16 Christmases, made every toy purchase mistake one can
make. I know everything not to get and, when you remove the culls,
only one toy is left for the buying.
</P>
<P>
   But more about that in a minute. First, you need to know all the
toys to
</P>
<P>
   avoid at all costs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Anything educational. Think about it. Aren't your children
already smarter than you are? Do you really want them to get even
further ahead in the game? I don't think so. Toys that make
learning fun are just going to make it more difficult for you to
fool your children in the future.
</P>
<P>
   _ Anything that takes batteries. Unless you want to be feeding
the Energizer Bunny for the rest of your days, stay away from toys
powered by batteries. However, if you have a pile of used
batteries, you can think of painting them and giving them as
slightly irregular round blocks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Video game systems. Let's think about your typical video game
for a moment, shall we? These games teach your child cunning and
stealth mixed with creative ways of ending the lives of various
unearthly creatures. It is not too far a leap for your children to
think of mother and father as they are playing Rip-a-Gut II. No, we
don't need to instruct our children in the ways of violence, lest
they use it against us.
</P>
<P>
   _ Books. Books contain ideas. Our children need no new ideas.
See the first item above.
</P>
<P>
   _ Crayons. This also goes for paints, markers, pencils and pens
of any kind or shape. You will only have to spend hours cleaning
off your floors and walls from the errant artists.
</P>
<P>
   _ Anything that makes any sort of noise whatsoever. Do I really
need to explain this?
</P>
<P>
   _ Small plastic figures. You know the kind of thing I am talking
about: diminutive dinosaurs, army men, cowboys and Indians, space
aliens. These seem fine _ after all, they make no noise _ until you
are going to the bathroom in the middle of the night sometime and
step on a little Sitting Bull or triceratops.
</P>
<P>
   By now you probably think that I have eliminated every toy on
the market
</P>
<P>
   but not so. One toy still stands out as the perfect, if not the
only, Christmas gift for children.
</P>
<P>
   Little round foam balls.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the little round foam ball fits all the parental criteria.
You can't learn anything from a foam ball. It does not take
batteries. It cannot be used to create any mark. It makes no sound,
even when you bounce it off the wall, and, if you step on it, it
almost has a pleasant feel. It doesn't hurt at all.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but little round foam balls are nontoxic. Your
kids can munch on them between meals and not get so much as a tummy
ache. They come in every color in the rainbow and you can buy a
year's supply for the cost of one video game. Of course, little
round foam balls don't wear out all that often.
</P>
<P>
   And for some reason I can't explain, the aisle with all the
little round foam balls is the the clearest throughout the
Christmas season. You can get all your shopping done in minutes and
not even need help carrying your purchases to the car.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect. Stock up now before the secret gets out and they have
to start auctioning little round foam balls like Furbys.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (TX) News
Messenger. His email is platham(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
