<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reminiscing on the downtown of holidays past
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It's a time warp, a bittersweet one, strolling
past the Santaland animated display in the abandoned Lazarus
building. As I stand before the charmingly dated figures, with
their Twiggy eyelashes and herky-jerky movements, I can close my
eyes and almost take myself back to 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Almost. That bustling mechanical universe reminds me of all the
fun I had downtown as a kid _ but it also reminds me there was once
a bustling universe inside the store as well.
</P>
<P>
   Now the sign hanging above the display window trumpets, ``This
Space for Lease.'' Event posters from 1996 are taped to dusty
doors. A graffiti artist proclaims, cryptically, ``Downtown exposed
for can of corn it really is.''
</P>
<P>
   If only a time warp could take us back to the days when the
window display was the latest in animated technology. Shopping
downtown was the big outing of our family Christmas season. That
holiday department store smell _ a hybrid of perfume, candy and
evergreen _ hit you like intoxication the minute you walked into
Rike's. We waited in long lines to sit on Santa's lap; we
thoughtfully budgeted our purchases. How to buy gifts for everyone
with our fistful of money? A certain enterprising sister came up
with the solution: a package of combs, a practical gift for the
entire family.
</P>
<P>
   It was the perfect day.
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean to be ungrateful _ the display windows are nice and
nostalgic, and the city is trying _ but there's something
depressing about having a Santaland window, but no Lazarus. And no
Santa. For Santa, you have to go to the 'burbs, or to the downtown
Elder-Beerman on the weekends.
</P>
<P>
   We're told we're lucky to have a downtown department store left.
The specter of Elder-Beerman's closing its Courthouse Plaza store
looms over us like the Ghost of Christmas Yet to Come.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this is America and we have the right to shop where we
please. But it's tough to make the argument that we're a big league
city and we deserve a minor league baseball team and a flourishing
Riverscape if we can't sustain even one downtown department store.
</P>
<P>
   Fight those mall crowds all you want. I'm heading downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Reason No. 1: It's pleasant. You don't have to park several
football fields away from the store. You don't lose your Christmas
spirit elbowing crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Reason No. 2: You can make shopping an outing, an adventure,
with your kids. You can bribe them into good behavior with a visit
to the model train display in the lobby of the Kettering Tower, or
a visit to Elder-Beerman's Tike's Shop (yes, another relic from the
old Rike's).
</P>
<P>
   ``We make it an event with our kids,'' says Maureen Pero,
director of the Downtown Dayton Partnership. ``We go for a horse
and buggy ride and buy tickets for The Nutcracker. My kids hate
shopping, but if we say, `Lets go downtown,' for them it's a
Christmas event. It's more of a celebration of the holiday.''
</P>
<P>
   Reason No. 3: There are cool shops that aren't standard-issue
mall offerings, like the artists' gallery at DVAC or arty home
furnishings at Go Home. ``Downtown isn't the mall, and it's not
going to be the mall,'' Pero says. That's not all bad.
</P>
<P>
   Reason No. 4: Downtown needs us, and we need downtown.
</P>
<P>
   We can gripe all we want that city leaders aren't doing enough
to revitalize downtown, but they can't do it without us. The
throngs of families who enjoy the Grande Illumination on Courthouse
Square every year are a reminder of what the holidays downtown once
were.
</P>
<P>
   And could be again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
