<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sandwiched by tradition
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNY, Ga. _ One of the obvious effects of global
warming is that years are a lot shorter than they used to be. When
I was growing up and waiting on another visit from Santa Claus,
Christmases were at least as far apart as world wars.
</P>
<P>
   Now a year is nothing but the Fourth of July, Labor Day,
Thanksgiving and Christmas all run together, not counting birthdays
and all the other days merchants set aside for special sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to start planning for Christmas,'' my wife said as
soon as she picked up the pre-Thanksgiving Sunday newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't be,'' I replied, thinking that the carcass of last
year's Christmas tree is still hidden behind the shop where she
can't see it. I've been meaning to take it to the dump first chance
I get.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would you like for Christmas dinner?'' she asked.
``Pimento or tuna?''
</P>
<P>
   ``What in the world are you talking about?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm talking about a modern Christmas meal for a change,'' she
answered. ``Turkey and dressing is old-fashioned. Sandwiches are
in, turkey is out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Christmas without turkey and dressing wouldn't be Christmas,''
I said. ``Who ever heard of sandwiches for Christmas dinner! Where
do you get those crazy ideas?''
</P>
<P>
   ``From the newspaper,'' she replied. ``It says here that a
fourth of the people who have Christmas dinner at home eat
sandwiches.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe it,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   She handed me the newspaper. There it was, on the front page.
</P>
<P>
   ``... According to a study in American Demographics, 25 percent
of Christmas home diners eat sandwiches, 11 percent eat pasta, and
10 percent beef.'' Probably hamburgers from McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you believe it now?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may be what somebody found out in a survey,'' I answered,
``but I can't believe they put stuff like that in the newspaper,
much less on the front page.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see why not,`` she said. ``I think it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it is true, the newspaper shouldn't print it,'' I
said. ``When I worked for the newspaper we had responsible,
patriotic editors. We'd never put something detrimental to the
country on the front page.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is printing a change in holiday eating habits detrimental
to the country?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because families are the fabric of the nation, and it's
destroying the fabric of families,'' I explained. ``Christmas
dinners with turkey and dressing, mashed potatoes, giblet gravy,
English peas, fruitcake and ambrosia with plenty of coconut and
cherries are one of the fundamental traditions that have made this
country great.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't think this is a real threat to society as we know
it,'' I continued, ``just look at the ideas that story put in your
head. What you are talking about is doing away with Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   I reminded her of Christmas at Aunt May's house in Fayetteville,
Ga., where the extended family gathered for all-day togetherness.
We started early with Uncle Harry's eggnog, followed by three
shifts at the dining room table and then cigars in the living room
for the men while the ladies washed dishes and napped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine Aunt May serving pimento cheese and tuna
sandwiches?'' I asked. ``She'd have died a slow and painful death
before she'd do that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That may be, but I think the new menu will appeal to a lot of
grandmothers,'' she replied. ``I spend at least three days cooking
and baking for our Christmas dinner. Then it's gobbled up in a half
hour so you and the boys can get back to either watching a football
game on television or working on an old tractor. I don't get
through washing dishes and putting things up until after
suppertime. I wonder if it's worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it's worth it!'' I exclaimed. ``It's so festive.
It's spiritual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can just imagine,'' I sneered, ``all us sitting around the
dining room table, holding hands and saying the blessing over
pimento and tuna sandwiches.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't want sandwiches. we could call Domino's and have
pizza delivered,'' she suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to talk this way,'' I said, ``but I think there is a
good possibility God will punish us if we have sandwiches or pizza
for Christmas dinner. Christmas is supposed to be a religious
holiday, and I don't see how we can be religious or respectful if
we don't have turkey and dressing like God intended. I think it
says somewhere in the Bible that it's illegal to serve sandwiches
for Christmas dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Since you feel so strongly,'' she said, ``we'll stick with the
traditional turkey and all the trimmings for another year, provided
you make a few Christmas resolutions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like peeling the potatoes, helping set the table, peeling the
oranges and grating the coconut for the ambrosia and helping wash
the dishes.''
</P>
<P>
   I agreed. I didn't have a choice. I wasn't going to surrender to
sandwich makers who stole Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor in chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
