<HEADER>
A2993 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMMENTARY-BJT1205-CO     12-04 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMENTARY-BJT1205-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Saturday, December 5 and Sunday,
December 6, 1998 are moving today to clients of the New York Times
News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN _ Betsy Hall Hutchinson, age not disclosed, of
Tucson, Ariz., takes us roaring down memory lane on in-line skates.
Here's her story. (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED THURSDAY FOR
SATURDAY.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ ATLANTA _ I got zapped by somebody's BMW
horn the other day for, apparently, having committed an egregious
civility. I had paused to let a marooned driver take a left in
front of me. This, to paraphrase Churchill, is an insult up with
which a BMW driver will not put. What the heck's the use buying a
luxury car if you can't drive over someone whenever you want?
(Rosenfeld, Cox News Service) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SATURDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ The House impeachment hearings are vacillating
between farce and slow-motion attempted coup. For farce, there was
the Judiciary Committee's vote to expand its inquiry into
fund-raising for the Clinton re-election _ on the day when Federal
Elections Commission auditors recommended record paybacks from both
the Clinton and the Dole campaigns for similar irregularities. (Tom
Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED
THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ MIAMI _ It may seem only minor that baseball
took away the 2000 All-Star game from South Florida and awarded it
to Atlanta. But beneath it lies something that should concern any
city with a major league team, or one hoping to get one. It's about
a new stadium. (Howard Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox
Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ What would have happened if Augusto
Pinochet had chosen to have his back surgery done in New York
instead of London? How would President Clinton have fielded a
request from the Spanish court that wants the former Chilean
dictator to face charges of murder, torture and genocide? (Andy
Glass is a columnist for Cox News Service in the Washington
bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ It's amazing how many people
work in retail sales jobs but don't know anything about the
products they sell. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ If only a time warp could take us back to the
days when the window display was the latest in animated technology.
Shopping downtown was the big outing of our family Christmas
season. But now, there's something depressing about having a
Santaland window, but no Lazarus. And no Santa. For Santa, you have
to go to the 'burbs, or to the downtown Elder-Beerman on the
weekends. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ Here are a few jokes I've been saving up for a
slow holiday week just like this. (Borders, Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MILNER-COLUMN _ At the Third Annual Book Fair in Austin, Texas,
recently it was like old home week for me and a rabble of my old
running buddies. (Milner, Cox News Service) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ Now that almost all of you have missed out on
getting Furbys (which, when you say it like that, sounds more like
a disease than a toy), you may be wondering what to get your kids
for Christmas. (Latham, Marshall News Messenger) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ One of the obvious effects
of global warming is that years are a lot shorter than they used to
be. When I was growing up and waiting on another visit from Santa
Claus, Christmases were at least as far apart as world wars. Now a
year is nothing but the Fourth of July, Labor Day, Thanksgiving and
Christmas all run together, not counting birthdays and all the
other days merchants set aside for special sales. (Minter, Cox News
Service) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ If you spend half your life
making change so you can park downtown, you've probably got several
questions about the new City of Austin policy that exempts Texas
lawmakers from being ticketed at parking meters. Like, for example,
how do you get a cushy deal like this? Simple. Run for office.
(Kelso, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
