 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories for release Saturday, December 5 and
Sunday, December 6, 1998, are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   BUYING-GLASSES _ It's almost the end of the year, and you have
funds left in your Flexible spending account for health? One of the
best ways to spend it is new eyeglasses. What to look for in an eye
exam and in glasses. (Lore, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH
PHOTO. FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ ATLANTA _ Sterling Publishing Co. is out with
two very handsome new books for woodworkers, just in time to make
some Christmas lists. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
FOR SATURDAY.
</P>
<P>
   RADKO-ORNAMENTS _ In just over 10 years, Christopher Radko, the
nationally renowned designer of Christmas ornaments, has turned a
part-time job into a multi-million dollar business. He designs
traditional glass ornaments that are sold throughout the United
States and found in the homes of celebs, too. Radko's has collected
such a following that there's a collectors club whose members
number more than 10,000. We talk to some local collectors about his
appeal. Radko also has donated a tree, valued at $50,000, for this
year's Atlanta Festival of Trees, which opens Dec. 5. (Flanders,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   ORNAMENTS-TIPS _ Tips from Radko on decorating with ornaments _
other than on the tree. (Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   PHOTO-TIPS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Photographers at The Post
aim to spread a little good cheer with a few picture-taking
suggestions. (Piscopo, Palm Beach Post) WITH PHOTOS. MOVED FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   12-HOLIDAY-COOKIES _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ True holiday bakers
know you can't make just one kind of cookie. So how about 12? Here
are a dozen ideas to go with the Christmas carol. And don't forget
to sing while you're at it! (Norris, Palm Beach Post) WITH PHOTOS.
MOVED FOR SATURDAY.
</P>
<P>
   ARKANSAS-PIES _ DE VALLS BLUFF, Ark. _ Tasting the South visits
one of the South's legendary sweet spots, the Family Pie Shop of De
Valls Bluff, Ark. It's a little cinder-block building with ``Pie
Shop'' spray-painted on the front, like some neat graffiti, but
locals and travelers on I-40 alike find Mary Thomas' humble
business _ especially this time of year. (Auchmutey, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED TUESDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   w/ARKANSAS-PIES-RECIPES _ Some favorite pies.
</P>
<P>
   NY-HOLIDAYS _ NEW YORK _ 10 ways to enjoy New York for the
holidays, including the Rockefeller Plaza Christmas tree and
skating, Radio City Music Hall, Neapolitan Creche at Metropolitan
Museum, exhibits at the Jewish Museum and a big Kwanzaa
extravaganza. (Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
WEDNESDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   w/NY-HOLIDAYS-CHELSEA _ NEW YORK _ West Chelsea is changing at
lightning speed. No sooner did a few major galleries, like Paula
Cooper and Matthew Marks, transform a couple of garages into
elegant white boxes two years ago than a Gold Rush-like migration
began. Already, some 80 galleries occupy storefronts and low-rise
buildings in the area running from 14th to 26th streets between
10th Avenue and the Hudson River. Can Dolce &AMP; Gabana be far behind?
(Fox, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED WEDNESDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   NY-HOLIDAYS-CHELSEAHOTEL _ NEW YORK _ A few blocks from the
burgeoning gallery district of West Chelsea, in Chelsea proper, are
two hotels that are about as similar as Sister Wendy and Madonna.
The Leo House is not really even a hotel, but a nonprofit Catholic
guest house. For an experience in contrast, check out (or into) the
Chelsea Hotel, the domain of the creative spirit for a century,
which exudes a shabby, bohemian air. (Fox, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED WEDNESDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   NY-HOLIDAYS-SOHO _ NEW YORK _ The SoHo Grand Hotel is the kind
of place where those often surreal encounters one has in New York
are an inevitable experience, part of the script. In the hotel's
chi-chi Canal House restaurant, for example, you might run into, as
we did one recent afternoon, Icelandic rock queen Bjork and famed
7-Up pitch-mon Geoffrey Holder. (Longino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED WEDNESDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   FUR-Q&AMP;A _ ATLANTA _ Q&AMP;A on fur fashion's rebound with the
Swedish husband-wife design team for Bisang . (Walton, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED TUESDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-CHRISTMAS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ More people are
putting the ``Christ in Christmas'' by making the holiday less
complicated. That means fewer gifts and more time with loved ones.
(Gushee, Cox News Service) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MOSES _ He's the man of the season, that Hebrew Bible character
who floated through the bullrushes as a baby and parted the Red Sea
as an adult. With the opening of the Dreamworks movie ``The Prince
of Egypt,'' nicknamed Zion King, Moses is drawing attention. We
look at the Jewish and Christian views of this fellow who argued
with God, challenged pharoah, and led his people to their Promised
Land but was not allowed to enter it himself. (White, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   ARTS/ENTERTAINMENT
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-PSYCHO _ ``Psycho,'' the remake of Hitchcock's classic.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MTV-STAMOS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ An interview with MTV House
of Style host and model Rebecca Romijn-Stamos. (Anna, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-LOVE-DEVIL _ AUSTIN, Texas _ ``Love Is the Devil'' is an
ultra-bleak biopic of the late British artist Francis Bacon. It has
sufficient blood but little meat _ literally and narratively.
(Garcia, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MALICK-RETURNS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Movie director Terrence Malick
is back with the anticipated ``The Thin Red Line.'' But is he worth
all the hoopla? He seems to me a cowardly artist, a too-proud
perfectionist mortally afraid of making a misstep. (Garcia, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   JAZZ-KRALL _ Profile of jazz vocalist Diana Krall, whose fourth
album, ``Love Scenes'' (Impulse), has hit the 500,000 sales mark.
The native of British Columbia has become something of a crossover
star, singing a vintage repertoire of romantic jazz standards.
Along the way she's popped up in some un-jazzy places, like
``Melrose Place'' and the Lilith Fair, while cutting the figure of
a sophisticated blonde out of a '40s movie. As it happens, the diva
in Donna Karan is just a regular gal, one who likes her steaks rare
and still remembers what it's like to play a hotel piano lounge for
an audience of one. (Dollar, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR
SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAYFILMS _ What's ahead in the movie theaters from now until
the end of the year? Any trends? Can it compare with last year's
offerings - ``As Good as It Gets,'' ``Good Will Hunting? (Vejnoska,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-COLUMN _ Two years ago, a man named Alan Sokal lured the
emperor into the public square and, by speaking in a mysterious
tongue, goaded him into removing every stitch of clothing he had
on. He stood there buck naked, the whole world laughing. It's still
laughing, and the emperor doesn't know why. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED WEDNESDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
