<HEADER>
A3022 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-DATA-$ADV06-CO     12-04 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-DATA-$ADV06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With SOCIAL-SECURITY. For release Sunday, Dec. 6.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Those who wish to assure Social Security's
financial soundness for decades to come have suggested a variety of
ways to do so. But each of the solutions involve trade offs which
may make them unpopular.
</P>
<P>
   The four main components of reform plans being discussed are:
allowing individuals to privately invest their payroll taxes;
raising the retirement age beyond 67 or accelerating the schedule
for reaching 67; raising payroll taxes or cutting benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the drawbacks to each proposal:
</P>
<P>
   PRIVATE INVESTMENT OF SOCIAL SECURITY FUNDS
</P>
<P>
   Over a 10-year period, the value of money invested in the stock
market may climb or fall. Here are changes in the value of the Dow
Jones Industrial Average over two different 10-year periods,
measured from the first trading day of each year.
</P>
<P>
   ......................................................Percentage
change
</P>
<P>
   1965...(869.78)....1975 (632.04)....... -27.3
</P>
<P>
   1988 (2015.25)....1998 (7965.04).... +295.2
</P>
<P>
   RAISING THE RETIREMENT AGE
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Americans have been choosing to take Social
Security retirement benefits at a steadily earlier age. Raising the
eligibility age would buck that trend.
</P>
<P>
   ...........Average age
</P>
<P>
   1940....68.8
</P>
<P>
   1945....69.6
</P>
<P>
   1950....68.7
</P>
<P>
   1955....68.4
</P>
<P>
   1960....66.8
</P>
<P>
   1965....65.8
</P>
<P>
   1970....64.4
</P>
<P>
   1975....64.0
</P>
<P>
   1980....63.9
</P>
<P>
   1985....63.7
</P>
<P>
   1990....63.7
</P>
<P>
   1994....63.6
</P>
<P>
   Source: U.S. Labor Department
</P>
<P>
   RAISING PAYROLL TAXES
</P>
<P>
   The maximum amount an employee is taxed each year for old age,
survivors and disability insurance (OASDI) has risen sharply over
the decades.
</P>
<P>
   1940 .... $30
</P>
<P>
   1950 .... $45
</P>
<P>
   1960 .... $144
</P>
<P>
   1970 .... $327.60
</P>
<P>
   1980 .... $1315.72
</P>
<P>
   1990 .... $3180.60
</P>
<P>
   1999 .... $4501.20
</P>
<P>
   Source: Social Security Administration
</P>
<P>
   CUTTING BENEFITS
</P>
<P>
   Social Security is the major source of income for almost
two-thirds of beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Social security provides.....percentage of income....to this
share of beneficiaries
</P>
<P>
   ......................................100
percent.................18 percent
</P>
<P>
   .......................................90-99
percent.............12 percent
</P>
<P>
   .......................................50-89
percent.............36 percent
</P>
<P>
   .......................................less than 50
percent.....34 percent
</P>
<P>
   Source: Social Security Administration
</P>
