<DOCNO> NYT19981204.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3026 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-PROBLEM-$ADV06     12-04 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-PROBLEM-$ADV06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOW BAD IS THE SOCIAL SECURITY CRISIS?
 &HT;    With SOCIAL-SECURITY. For release Sunday, Dec. 6.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There are doom-and-gloomers who say Social Security
will go bust in 15 years. But there are also optimists who say the
system has no problem at all.
</P>
<P>
   The way people view Social Security's financial future says much
about how, or whether, they think the federal retirement and
disability system should be changed.
</P>
<P>
   The most widely accepted view is that of the Social Security
trustees _ three Cabinet secretaries, two members of the public and
the Social Security administrator. Every year they take the
system's pulse and make three predictions about its future for the
next 75 years: a pessimistic view, an optimistic view and something
in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   The middle one, used as the official prediction, is that the
Social Security trust fund financed by years of excess payroll
taxes won't be depleted for 34 years. At that time, they estimate,
the 12.4 percent payroll tax from workers and employers would pay
only 75 percent of current benefits, and the tax would have to
increase 2.2 percentage points to pay all the bills.
</P>
<P>
   Those who think the system needs major reform _ generally
conservative research groups, Republicans and some moderate
Democrats _ note payroll taxes alone won't pay all benefits by
2013. The program then will have to start redeeming the trust
fund's special Treasury bonds that represent the Social Security
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, these folks say, the money to redeem the bonds
is being spent to run the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   By 2030, Social Security will have to redeem $750 billion worth
of bonds, said Michael Tanner, director of the Cato Institute's
Project on Social Security Privatization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether that's a crisis for Social Security, it certainly is a
crisis for whomever is around trying to come up with $750
billion,'' Tanner said.
</P>
<P>
   If no other funding reforms take place and the trustees' middle
estimate is correct, Tanner said, the payroll tax rate would have
to increase from 12.4 percent to 18 percent. If the trustees'
pessimistic scenario occurs, which Tanner suggests is more likely,
taxes would need to more than double to 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even that might be too optimistic because the trustees' estimate
of how long people will live may be two years too low, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get a cure for cancer in the next 10 years, the whole
thing definitely falls apart,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The pessimists, with strong Wall Street backing, want to reform
the system by letting everyone invest some of their payroll taxes
in individually controlled accounts.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side are those _ primarily progressive economists _
who argue that even the trustees' rosiest prediction is too
pessimistic. They say nothing should be done to Social Security now
because the economic growth will solve the problem on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Baker, senior economist with the Economic Policy Institute,
said the trustees' prediction of 1.4 percent annual economic growth
was ``very conservative.'' He predicted it would grow at a faster
pace, allowing the program to pay full benefits until at least
2050.
</P>
<P>
   Baker and Mark Weisbrot, research director of the Preamble
Center, another economic research group, argue that even if taxes
have to be raised 2.2 percentage points as the trustees envision,
that can be easily absorbed.
</P>
<P>
   Such an increase would be less than the payroll tax increases of
the 1960s, '70s and '80s, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, they said, the average person's wealth should
increase by 35 to 40 percent by about 2030, so the tax increase
would not be too difficult to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Radical reforms are ``not something people need to be talking
about for 10, 15, 20 years,'' Weisbrot said, calling economic
predictions three decades in the future ``fortune telling.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
