NYT-12-04-98 1058EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981204.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3027 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-$ADV0     12-04 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-$ADV06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHITE HOUSE CONFERENCE COULD START SHAPING SOCIAL SECURITY
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Dec. 6. With SOCIAL-PROBLEM and SOCIAL-DATA.
In addition, SOCIAL-RADIO, a spot report on the Clinton and GOP
radio addresses, will move Saturday.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even as President Clinton and Congress prepare for
the national trauma of an impeachment vote, they begin a task this
week that could prove even longer and more painful for many
Americans _ reforming Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead is a contentious debate over who will provide the
trillions of dollars in savings needed to keep the federal
retirement and disability system running through the next century.
</P>
<P>
   It begins with a White House-sponsored conference Tuesday and
Wednesday that the administration expects to produce not a
solution, but a chance to get all the major players talking about
the problem and whether there might be common ground for a
solution.
</P>
<P>
   But there are loads of obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   The conference _ one day of public talks at a Washington hotel,
and a second behind closed doors at the White House _ comes after a
year of bitter partisanship overshadowed by the Clinton sex
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Even without the scandal, the politics of Social Security is
filled with partisanship and distrust. Long called the ``third rail
of politics'' _ touch it and you die _ politicians are wary of
being seen as harming the system that benefits nearly 45 million
elderly or disabled Americans and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Clinton nor Republican congressional leaders want to
show their hand prematurely, particularly since any proposal is
likely to be unpopular.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was badly burned when his detailed plan to reform health
care was shredded by special interest groups four years ago. Many
blamed the Democrats' loss of their congressional majority on the
health care debacle.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Republicans were accused of trying to wreck Medicare
in 1996 after suggesting market-based reforms, and charges that
they were trying to raid the surplus from Social Security for tax
relief was a factor in their November election losses.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that Republicans are demanding Clinton put a
Social security plan on the table first. The administration is
declining to do so, claiming that would polarize positions and
discourage negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's public session will likely highlight the widely
differing approaches to shrinking the funds gap. The audience of
about 250 people has been selected by the White House to include a
broad spectrum of views on reform.
</P>
<P>
   There will be three public panels, including one moderated by
First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton on how various reforms would
affect different segments of the population. Another will look at
the financial picture, while a third explores options for reform
espoused by leading economic and policy research groups.
</P>
<P>
   But the adminstration hopes Wednesday's private sessions will
give lawmakers a chance to explore ways to save Social Security as
well as how to proceed politically, said Gene Sperling, the
president's chief economic adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Early next year, the administration plans to start negotiations
with Congress in hopes of adopting a plan before the 2000
presidential election stifles action. Basically, Social Security's
problem is demographic. There are more people, they're living
longer, and having smaller families to support them in their old
age.
</P>
<P>
   The 77 million baby boomers born between 1946 and 1964 will
begin reaching their normal retirement ages in 2011. Meanwhile, the
number of workers supporting each one of those retirees will fall
from 3.3 to two by 2030.
</P>
<P>
   The first question for the conference is how real, and how
severe, the Social Security problem is.
</P>
<P>
   The government predicts the Social Security trust fund, built up
over the years with excess payroll taxes, will be depleted by 2032.
After that, taxes would pay only 75 percent of benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts say the crisis will arrive as soon as 2013, while
others say there won't be a crisis at all.
</P>
<P>
   The question likely to get the most attention is whether the
system should be reformed by investing in the private securities
markets. That would be a break from Social Security's 63-year
history of paying benefits out of payroll taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Three investment options are being considered:
</P>
<P>
   _ Individual accounts financed by a portion of payroll taxes.
This has the potential to provide higher rates of return on
investments. But it's riskier than the current system and would
result in wide differences in retirement security. Supported by the
financial services industry and most congressional Republicans, it
is opposed by organized labor and Democratic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   _ Government investment of the surplus in private markets. This
could improve the system's overall rate of return while minimizing
the risk to individuals. Critics warn that it would result in
government control of business through stock ownership.
</P>
<P>
   _ Personal accounts in addition to the payroll tax. Mixed
poltical support as a way of giving people more money at
retirement, but also opposed as an added tax which would hit the
poor hardest.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has ruled out ``radical privatization'' _ diverting all
or most payroll taxes to personal investment accounts, but has left
the door open to using a small portion of payroll taxes for that
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Another proposed reform would raise the eligibility age for full
benefits. It's already scheduled to increase gradually from 65 to
67 by 2027. Some plans suggest boosting the age to 70. Others
suggest reaching the 67 age limit sooner.
</P>
<P>
   But a poll by Princeton Survey Research Associates found that
three-fourths of Americans oppose raising the age limit to 70.
</P>
<P>
   Two other potential reforms would be to increase the payroll tax
or cut benefits. Neither has much support, although both are being
discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has virtually ruled out hiking the 12.4 percent payroll
tax rate shared by workers and employees, but has indicated a
willingness to consider raising the cap on wages subject to the
tax. The cap is $72,600 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Some plans propose reducing guaranteed benefits and replacing
them with expected income from personal investments. Critics of
those plans warn they could be particularly harmful to elderly
women, 20 percent of whom live in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
