<HEADER>
A3075 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-SIGNS-$ADV06-     12-04 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-SIGNS-$ADV06-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW CHURCHES CAN ATTRACT THE THOROUGHLY MODERN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several years ago I wrote a simply brilliant column suggesting
that if churches hope to appeal to modern media-savvy folk, they
need to create better advertising slogans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because my job is to be helpful _ well, that and occasionally to
knock some heads together in an annoying sort of way _ I suggested
such outstanding ideas as: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``So Forgiven We Feel Guilty.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Where You, Too, Can Get a Life.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Church: It's Not Just for Sundays Anymore.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Steeple People.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``After 2,000 Years, Still Under the Same Management.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Great Death Benefits.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My notion was that slogans like these would appear in church
bulletins, newsletters and advertising and immediately attract
folks who hadn't been to a worship service since Jimmy Carter was
the nation's chief priest. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But, as often happens, my ideas were far ahead of their time
and, as far as I know, have pretty much been ignored by nearly
everyone _ even by my own church, which settled for a considerably
more serious slogan. (Something about how hell probably isn't all
it's cracked up to be.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And yet most of a decade later, there is evidence that my plea
for church-slogan whimsicality has been resurrected, though in a
slightly different guise _ catchy signs outside churches bearing
clever and appealing (if slightly off-plumb) messages. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a clergyman I know has written a new book about how to
create church signs that work. It's called ``Signs for These
Times'' (Concordia Publishing House) by the Rev. Ronald T.
Glusenkamp, once a Kansas City pastor, now minister at Gethsemane
Lutheran Church in St. Louis. His church sits near a south side
intersection there with lots of passing traffic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Glusenkamp, whose enthusiasms include bicycling and reading lots
of different newspapers every day (one reason I like him), is onto
something. He's been telling me about his slick, pop-cultury signs
for years, occasionally even sending me photos of his hottest new
signs outside his church. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I remember one that said: ``BETTER THAN KARAOKE,/COME SING WITH
US.'' Well, it wouldn't win the Nobel prize in literature, but it
might convey the idea that not everyone inside Glusenkamp's church
wanders around with long, sad faces all day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And when Jerry Seinfeld quit making new TV shows Glusenkamp came
up with this one: ``SO LONG, JERRY/FANS DON'T WORRY/THE BIBLE IS
SIGN-FILLED!'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So now Glusenkamp has collected a batch of these changing signs
in his new book. It also includes a lot of do's and don'ts for
novice church sign makers, based on mistakes he's made or at least
thought about making. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he confesses that this church sign occurred to him
in the last year: ``THE SERMONS HERE ARE/MORE UPLIFTING/THAN
VIAGARA!'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But he thought better of it, proving to me that members of my
Presbyterian denomination don't have a corner on fun-squashing
discernment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Glusenkamp seems to be at his best at Easter, based on these
signs: JOANNA, MARY &AMP;/MARY MAGDALENE/THE ORIGINAL SPICE GIRLS! and
EASTER:/MORE THAN SOMETHING/TO DYE FOR! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But not all provocative church sign ideas are in his book. For
instance, here's one I'd like to see this shopping-crazy time of
year: IF JESUS HADN'T BEEN BORN/THE CHAMBER OF COMMERCE/WOULD HAVE
TO INVENT HIM. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This column for use Sunday, Dec. 6, and thereafter.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
