<SLUG> BC-SOFTWARE-GIFTS-FOR-KIDS-(HOLIDAYS)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP PICKS IN CHILDREN'S SOFTWARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article it must be purchased. For purchase
information, call New York Times Syndicate sales representative
Nirdi Relis at (800) 972-3550 or (212) 499-3333.)  
 &HT;    
 By ANN ORR  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    For kids with computers, there's no better gift this holiday
season than new software. The children's software market has
exploded this year, with more exciting and innovative programs than
ever before. Kids can raise their own virtual dragon, play a
scavenger hunt game with the cast of Blue's Clues and even learn
about physics as they build their own pinball machines.
 &HT;    There's a new crop of gizmos and gadgets, too, that extend
computer technology beyond the PC. Lego Mindstorms, for instance,
lets your children construct and program real, moving robots out of
Legos. This is a great time to be a kid!
 &HT;    Here's the scoop on the hottest children's software of the year,
along with some shopping and installation tips.
 TODDLERS AND PRESCHOOLERS  
 &HT;    Reader Rabbit's Toddler 2.0
 &HT;    A perfect introduction to the computer, this program offers nine
playful activities that even the youngest techies can master. The
program's thoughtful design insures success _ any movement of the
mouse or press of a key causes something exciting to happen on the
screen. Runs on: Win/Mac. The Learning Company, 800-716-8506, ages
1 1/2-3, $29.95.
 &HT;    JumpStart Preschool '99
 &HT;    One of our all-time favorite programs has been completely
revised and now offers 20 play areas that teach 30 early learning
skills. From counting to colors and shapes to sequencing, the
activities both teach and entertain. Runs on: Win/Mac. Knowledge
Adventure, 800-542-4240, ages 2-4, $30.
 &HT;    Tonka Workshop CD-ROM Playset
 &HT;    One of those new-fangled gadgets mentioned above, this is a
plastic tool bench that easily straps onto the keyboard of your PC.
Once the accompanying software is installed, children can
manipulate the tools to build all kinds of onscreen projects. Kids
loved sawing and hammering to make houses, robots and more. Runs
on: Windows. Hasbro Interactive, 800-683-5847, ages 3 and up,
$39.95.
 &HT;    Blue's Birthday Adventure
 &HT;    Young ``Blue's Clues'' fans will be delighted with this CD-ROM
version of the popular children's television show. Steve and the
gang go on a scavenger hunt to prepare for Blue's big birthday
bash. Kids help out by exploring and playing games. Runs on
Win/Mac. Humongous Entertainment, 800-499-8386, ages 3-6, $29.99.
 &HT;    Dr. Seuss Kindergarten
 &HT;    There's a new zoo in Seussville. Of course, you won't see the
usual zoo fare. Instead you'll find exotic creatures like
Barbaloots and Birthday Pets, just to name a few. Children help
find the zoo's animals by playing eight reading and math games. In
addition to providing skills practice, this CD offers a rich
Seussian language experience, complete with original songs. Runs on
Win/Mac. Broderbund Software, 800-521-6263, ages 4-6, $19.95.
 ELEMENTARY-AGE CHILDREN  
 &HT;    Pajama Sam 2: Thunder and Lightning Aren't So Frightening
 &HT;    We first met Pajama Sam in a CD-ROM adventure in which he
valiantly overcame his fear of darkness. Now he's conquering his
nervousness about stormy weather. Children help out by exploring
the World Wide Weather headquarters, finding helpful items and
solving problems by using their logic and memory skills. A favorite
of our child-testers. Runs on: Win/Mac. Humongous Entertainment,
800-499-8386, ages 3-8, $39.95.
 &HT;    Quest for Camelot
 &HT;    Although there are a total of seven engaging activities in this
movie-based program, the best is a great ``dragon-rearing'' game in
which kids must raise a cute little dragon from birth through
adolescence. They must feed the critter, entertain him, teach him
to walk and keep him from developing bad habits. Kids just loved
it. Runs on: Win/Mac. Knowledge Adventure, 800-542-4240, ages 5-10,
$20.
 &HT;    Backyard Soccer
 &HT;    Ideal for young soccer players, this simulation stars 30
adorable neighborhood kids, each of whom has a different
personality and athletic ability. Your child first picks the team
members, and then uses the mouse to control the action. The
play-by-play is called by two kid commentators and stats are kept.
Runs on: Win/Mac. Humongous Entertainment, 800-499-8386, ages 5-10,
$19.99.
 &HT;    Make a Masterpiece
 &HT;    If you're looking for a program that children will return to
time and time again, invest in a high-quality draw and paint
program like this one. Using dozens of art tools and hundreds of
stamps, kids can create to their hearts' content. Wild special
effects let them paint with foaming shaving cream, or turn their
artwork into impressionist style masterpieces. Runs on Win/Mac. IBM
Corp., 800-426-7235, ages 5-12, $19.95.
 &HT;    Barbie Riding Club
 &HT;    Girls who love horses are sure to enjoy this fun set of
equestrian-themed activities. The kids' first task is to choose a
realistic-looking horse to care for _ they name him, groom him and
feed him snacks. Then they ``ride'' their horse on missions in 3D
landscapes. Runs on: Windows. Mattel, 800-628-8359, $34.99.
 &HT;    My First Amazing History Explorer
 &HT;    Time travel awaits a youngster when he or she plays this
entertaining and educational program. Kids journey back in time to
solve a mystery, exploring amazing places and eras like Ancient
Egypt, The Industrial Age and the Roman Empire. Runs on: Win/Mac.
DK Multimedia, 888-342-5357, ages 6-10, $29.95.
 &HT;     'TWEENS AND TEENS  
 &HT;    The Way Things Work: Pinball Science
 &HT;    A perfect balance of learning and fun, this program teaches
children physics concepts as they construct their own pinball
machines. Using an inventor's journal, they research and answer
questions about energy and motion, and then earn components like
levers, rockets and ramps for their pinball games. The completed
pinball simulations are very realistic and create a powerful
incentive to keep working. Runs on: Windows. DK Multimedia, 888-342
5357, ages 9-14, $29.95.
 &HT;    Where in the World is Carmen Sandiego? Deluxe Edition
 &HT;    This revised classic is better than ever. With danger lurking at
every corner, kids travel the globe tracking down criminals. Along
the way, they'll learn about world geography and culture and get
introduced to phrases in 12 foreign languages. Runs on: Win/Mac.
Broderbund Software, 800-521-6263, ages 9-14, $39.
 &HT;    Star Wars DroidWorks
 &HT;    A combination construction set and strategy game, this
innovative program asks kids to apply scientific principles in
order to succeed. First, players must make a ``droid'' by combining
robotic parts. Next, they test their invention in 3D maze missions.
Runs on: Win/Mac. Lucas Learning, 888-532-4263, ages 10 and up,
$39.95.
 &HT;    French for the Real World
 &HT;    Spanish for the Real World
 &HT;    These CD-ROMS make learning a foreign language fun and easy.
Children take part in a road rally across France or Spain and along
the way they must use the language to barter with the locals,
follow directions and ultimately win the race. Runs on: Win/Mac.
Knowledge Adventure, 800-542-4240, 11 and up, $30 each.
 &HT;    LEGO MindStorms
 &HT;    With this package of parts and software, kids can build and then
program an actual robotic device _ a car, for instance, that moves
just how you tell it to. Included in the kit is a small portable
computer in the form of a large LEGO block, 700 LEGO pieces, an
infrared transmitter, a CD-ROM, two motors, light and touch sensors
and an idea book. An outstanding learning experience. Runs on:
Windows. LEGO Americas, 800-527-8339, 11 and up, $200.
 &HT;    Creatures 2
 &HT;    Teens can raise their own species in this captivating life
simulation game. Little beings called Norns can be taught to
understand commands and follow directions. With a little luck,
they'll even breed! Runs on: Windows. Mindscape (The Learning
Company), 800-234-3088, ages 15 and up, $40.
 FOR THE WHOLE FAMILY  
 &HT;    Hoyle Board Games
 &HT;    No more lost dice and game pieces. There's something for
everyone in this fun set of 14 board games that includes Snakes &AMP;
Ladders, Chess, Backgammon, Battling Ships and more. Runs on:
Windows. Sierra On-Line (Cendant Software), 800-757-7707, ages 6
and up, $29.95.
 &HT;    Microsoft Encarta Reference Suite 99
 &HT;    The ultimate set of references, this five-CD package includes
Encarta Encyclopedia 99 Deluxe, Encarta Virtual Globe 99 and
Bookshelf 99. Great for the entire family. Runs on: Windows.
Microsoft Corp., 800-426-9400, ages 9-adult, $109.
 &HT;    PrintMaster Platinum 7.0
 &HT;    It's a snap to make colorful, professional-looking greeting
cards, newsletters, banners and more with this easy to use print
program. Its 8,000 ready-made templates let you make all kinds of
nifty projects, or you can design your own from scratch. Runs on:
Windows. Mindscape (The Learning Company) 800-234-3088, ages
10-adult, $69.
 &HT;    
 SIDEBAR: SHOPPING AND INSTALLATION HINTS  
 &HT;    + Avoid impulse buys. Don't be fooled by fancy packaging. Do
your homework first by reading reviews and talking to friends.
 &HT;    + Check system requirements. Make sure you are buying something
your computer can handle. Minimum system requirements are always
listed on the boxes.
 &HT;    + Try before you buy. Many companies will let you play limited
versions of their programs on their websites or will send you a
demo CD. Call the company's 800 number for details.
 &HT;    + Install the software prior to the gift-giving. If at all
possible, install the software on your computer beforehand, make
sure it runs then rewrap the gift. Potential Christmas morning
disaster averted!
 c.1998 Ann Orr  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ann Orr is the Senior Editor of Children's Software Revue, a
bimonthly publication that reviews and rates children's software.) &LR; 
