<HEADLINE>
IN WEST BELFAST, DISARMAMENT IS NOT KEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ Here on the streets of West Belfast, where all the
trouble started 30 years ago, the people who urged the Irish
Republican Army and their loyalist counterparts to stop fighting
are noticeably less enthusiastic about asking them to turn in their
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way the IRA should decommission as long as the
Brits don't,'' said Brian Kennedy, a 24-year-old Catholic voicing a
common refrain in the nationalist Turf Lodge neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of West Belfast, Protestants on the loyalist
Shankill Road are equally adamant that the paramilitary groups
which spring from their community should keep their guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we decommissioned, the British government would walk away
and the republicans would slaughter us,'' said one heavily tattooed
man who acknowledged being an ex-loyalist prisoner but nothing
else.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of paramilitary weapons has become such an obstacle in
the peace process that it threatens the progress made by April's
political settlement, the Good Friday Agreement, which was
overwhelmingly endorsed by voters on both sides of the border in
May.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, British Prime Minister Tony Blair made his
second trip in as many weeks to Belfast, seeking compromise on the
weapons impasse with Catholic nationalists who aspire to unity with
Ireland and Protestant unionists who want to remain British,
underscoring how seriously the British and Irish governments take
the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Blair and his Irish counterpart, Bertie Ahern, who has also
engaged in shuttle diplomacy in Belfast, may be rewarded for their
perseverance with an agreement on cross-border authorities and the
composition of the cabinet for the new power-sharing local
government.
</P>
<P>
   But unionists seem as determined as ever to bar Sinn Fein, the
IRA's political representatives, from sitting in that cabinet until
the IRA begins turning in its arsenal. And the IRA appears equally
determined to hold on to its weapons. Loyalists, meanwhile, say
they will keep their guns even if the IRA decommissions.
</P>
<P>
   It was the ordinary people, who supply the republican and
loyalist groups with recruits and, more crucially, the logistical
and moral support, who convinced them to end their violence and
give politics a chance.
</P>
<P>
   But a series of interviews in Catholic and Protestant sections
of West Belfast suggest that it is the ordinary people who seem
unconvinced of the need for mutual disarmament. They also find it
absurd to suggest that the peace process will collapse unless the
paramilitary groups disarm. They echo Blair, who last week when he
became the first British prime minister to address the Irish
parliament said, ``We have come too far to go back now.''
</P>
<P>
   While most of the middle class demands disarmament for relative
safety, the poor of both sides who have borne the brunt of
suffering these past 30 years oppose it out of fear for their
safety. Nationalists mention Brian Service, a Catholic who was shot
dead at random in North Belfast by a loyalist gang last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could have been me,'' said one man, who believes the IRA
should keep its guns to deter widespread loyalist attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Many loyalists say they trust neither the republicans nor the
British government. While they insist that they are committed to
the peace process, they still consider their guns to be the
ultimate guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   Police suggest that the paramilitaries are wary of giving up
their weapons because without them they could no longer control
their neighborhoods or their money-making racketeering activities.
</P>
<P>
   Many ordinary people scoff at such talk, saying the
paramilitaries can beat you with a bat or smash your legs with
cement blocks just as easily, and more cheaply, than shooting you.
And many regular folk seem to accept the claims from both sides
that they are committed to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you leave the guns alone, they won't be taken out,'' said
Agnes Moore, wheeling her young daughter through Andersonstown, an
IRA stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream, middle-class Protestant unionists disagree. They say
they cannot accept the word of the IRA, which has brutally killed
members of its community for three decades. David Trimble, the
Northern Ireland Assembly's first ministerand the leader of the
Ulster Unionist Party, says Sinn Fein cannot participate in the
government until the IRA begins disarming.
</P>
<P>
   But in a recent interview, Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams stressed
there is nothing in the agreement that links Sinn Fein's
participation in government with IRA disarmament. Most objective
observers agree with him. Under the agreement, Irish republican and
British loyalist paramilitary groups are to begin turning in their
weapons within two years. Adams suggested the IRA, in particular,
and republicans, in general, are growing disillusioned because
``the unionists are trying to rewrite the agreement, to create
preconditions that aren't in the agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time that the IRA concluded it had been given an
arbitrary precondition, it broke its cease-fire in 1996, setting
the peace process back two years. The IRA had called a cease-fire
in 1994 after the British government said Sinn Fein could join
negotiations after a truce. But then the British demanded the IRA
begin disarming as a precondition to talks. The IRA responded with
a bomb that devastated the Docklands section of London.
</P>
<P>
   As with anything in Ireland, history weighs heavily in this
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   To the IRA, weapons are sacred. Thirty years ago, Catholic
neighborhoods were overrun by Protestant loyalist mobs, unhindered
by the police. At that time, the IRA was largely a spent force and
had few guns. Locals began derisively suggesting that IRA stood for
``I Ran Away.''
</P>
<P>
   The heavy-handed response by police and the British army against
nationalists, however, breathed life back into the IRA, which vowed
never to be caught unarmed again.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the IRA and its supporters complain they are being
singled out and expected to compromise unlike any other similar
group. Over the past century, none of the IRA's incarnations has
been forced to turn in weapons before entering the political
mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say the IRA should not give up its arms until the
British army and the Royal Ulster Constabulary, the Northern
Ireland police force that is 93 percent Protestant, disarm.
Unionists counter that it is preposterous to compare the legitimate
forces of the state to an illegal insurgency group.
</P>
<P>
   But the IRA and its supporters do not accept Northern Ireland as
a legitimate state, saying it was created by fiat against the
express wishes of the Irish people in a 1918 referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a kitchen in West Belfast, a leading IRA figure shook
his head when asked if he saw a day when his organization would
turn in its arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never,'' he said. ``That's surrender.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
