<HEADLINE>
BRUINS GOALIE DAFOE ASSUMES PLACE WITH HOCKEY ELITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Mass. _ Byron Dafoe's numbers keep falling, which is
the kind of thing that sends Wall Street into a dither, but daily
dropping averages play just right on FleetStreet.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe was once a No. 2 goalie, but now he's clearly the No. 1
man in the Bruins' net. And these days, he has an ever-diminishing
goals-against average, a stingy 1.76, ranking him ahead of such
star NHL backstops as Dominik Hasek and Curtis Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel last year was my breakthrough season,'' said Dafoe
after Thursday's workout here in preparation for Saturday's visit
to the FleetCenter in Boston by the Penguins. ``My goal was to get
in the top 20, and I was happy to establish that. This year my goal
is to be in with the elite goalies of the game _ to have my name
mentioned with them _ and I think that's happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we have a game now with Joseph or Hasek in the other net,
I feel I'm on a par with those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers certainly support that case. Dafoe's 1.76 is only
0.01 higher than Phoenix's Nikolai Khabibulin. The only better
backstop is Jim Waite, Khabibulin's backup, who has fashioned a
1.15 in only six games _ less than one-third of Dafoe's workload.
Dafoe ranks second overall in save percentage with a .938 and is
tied with the Islanders' Tommy Salo for the league lead with four
shutouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers speak for themselves,'' said Dafoe when asked to
provide his definition of an elite goalie. ``You've got to be among
the best in wins, goals-against average, shutouts, and save
percentage. But to stay in that group, it's also what kind of wins
you have _ in other words, you've got to establish yourself as a
winning goalie in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins haven't had a netminder finish with the league's best
goals-against average since Pete Peeters turned in a 2.36 in
1982-83, when he won the Vezina Trophy. They haven't had as sure a
hand in net since discharging Andy Moog in the spring of '93 and
bringing in Jon Casey and the Amazing Technicolor Five-Hole. For a
season-plus, Dafoe has been the answer to what had been the club's
No. 1 problem for four consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming in this year as the No. 1, that gave me a lot of
confidence right off the bat,'' said Dafoe, who has yielded the net
only five times this year to Rob Tallas (owner of a not-so-shabby
1.85 GAA). ``I take a lot of pride in that goals-against average
and like seeing it under 2.00. Trying to keep it under 2.00 really
helps me, too. Say it's late and we've got a game won _ well, I'll
bear down more than maybe I have to because a late goal that
doesn't mean anything to the game will mean something to your
average. It can take only one bad game to send it up over 2.00.
Then it seems like you need three or four great games to get it
back under 2.00.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe undoubtedly will be back in net against the Penguins, who
are led by Jaromir Jagr and the recently acquired Alexei Kovalev,
the former Ranger swapped to Steeltown in the Petr Nedved exchange.
</P>
<P>
   What's brought Dafoe's game to such rarefied heights that he now
can be mentioned with the likes of Hasek and Joseph? The added game
experience is part of it, he says, along with mental preparation.
Working with Fred Neff, the team psychologist, he's become a
practitioner of mental visualization, taking time before each game
to imagine himself in net, facing shot after shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt my skill level has changed much in years,'' said
Dafoe. ``But my mental game, I'd say, has grown in leaps and
bounds. Working with Fred's been very helpful. I got to a point a
couple of years ago, I'd be so nervous before . . . I was just a
basket case. If I played great, then after the game, I was OK. But
if we lost, look out. It was awful.''
</P>
<P>
   The blending of relaxation and visualization has helped Dafoe
craft his mental game. Between periods, he keeps up the cerebral
gymnastics, imagining shooters racing down the slot, firing off the
wing. He sees them shoot. He sees himself turning each puck away
with blocker, glove, and stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want to do next is get into yoga,'' said Dafoe, who
took a couple of yoga classes this past summer in California. ``You
know, it's a big thing in LA, and I found it pretty interesting. I
just dabbled in it a little, but you know, it could help. Who
knows, I might be here in the room doing my yoga exercises between
periods.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins went through their customary workout without coach
Pat Burns, who took the day off in hopes of sleeping off a nagging
case of the flu. Assistants Jacques Laperriere and Bobby Francis
directed the workout. ``We wanted to get in some scrimmage time,''
said Francis. ``We haven't had a heavy load of games, so it was
important to get in some of that time.'' . . . Jason Allison
(charley horse) and Dmitri Khristich (pulled neck muscle)
participated in the full workout and will be in uniform Saturday
night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
