<HEADLINE>
COWHER HANDING IT TO BLEDSOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Bill Cowher has told the Pittsburgh media that he
is ``not sure how broken is (Drew Bledsoe's) broken finger,'' but
the Steelers coach was high in his praise of the New England
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember watching that Monday night game a few weeks ago
(against Miami),'' said Cowher. ``It almost looked like he wasn't
sure he could throw the ball. Yet the throw he made on the
(winning) touchdown was pretty accurate and a pretty good football
throw.''
</P>
<P>
   What the last two weeks have shown, Cowher went on, is that
Bledsoe ``is a tough guy. He's proven that through the years. His
degree of toughness, the hits that he's taken, the way he's been
able to come back from it, I have tremendous respect for the guy, I
really do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe ``had his growing pains early,'' said the coach, but he
``has become a leader for that football team.'' The two last-minute
drives against the Dolphins and Bills were ``very impressive. He's
always been a top football player in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Flip flop
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers, of course, were involved in an even hotter
officiating controversy than the Patriots in their last game, and
the coin flip for overtime possession in the Thanksgiving game at
Detroit is still a fiery topic here. NFL commissioner Paul
Tagliabue was in Pittsburgh Tuesday night for a United Way event,
and it so happened that the Steelers' Jerome ``Heads-Tails'' Bettis
was also there. Tagliabue and Bettis staged a mock coin flip for
the TV cameras. Cowher, though, is still holding (and biting) his
tongue in the wake of the official ruling that mistakenly awarded
the ball to the Lions, who promptly marched for the winning field
goal. ``I better not say anything,'' said Cowher. The coach said he
is in favor of adopting the NCAA's format in overtime, letting both
teams have at least one possession . . . Fullback Tim Lester
(ankle) is very doubtful for Sunday's game against the Patriots,
while running back Chris Fuamatu-Ma'afala (hamstring) is
questionable. But wide receiver Courtney Hawkins (knee) promises he
will play. Jon Witman likely will start for Lester at fullback . .
. Wide receiver Charles Johnson downplayed the Patriots' pass
coverage problems: ``All that stuff is just statistics. They still
have three-fourths of the secondary that went to the Super Bowl,
don't they?'' . . . Safety Darren Perry is of the same mind as
virtually all defensive backs in the NFL after the pass
interference call against the Bills on New England's Hail Mary pass
last Sunday. ``I don't think you're going to see the officials call
that one again,'' said Perry . . . The Steelers are 12-4 against
the Patriots and have won seven of the last eight meetings, even
though many of the games have been close.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-04-98 1319EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
