<HEADLINE>
A SNAPSHOT OF A PROSPEROUS AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Cable and sneakers and day-care providers; flex
time and soft drinks and cohabitation; movies and Web sites and
cell phones that ring, these are a few of our favorite things.
</P>
<P>
   If that was not already obvious, the federal government
confirmed it Dec. 4 with the delivery of its massive, annual
Statistical Abstract of the United States, the official national
snapshot, circa 1998, of who we are, what we like, how we live and
work, and where we spend money.
</P>
<P>
   The tome, compiled by the Census Bureau from dozens of sources
using the latest statistics available, features all of the old
standards (``Death Rates, by leading causes'') as well as about 100
new charts of turn-of-the-century territory, from the number of
telecommuters to one with the provocative title ``Number of Male
Sex Partners in Lifetime, by Selected Characteristics.''
</P>
<P>
   The portrait of America that emerges is of a population that by
and large is living well (it cannot get big enough homes or
vehicles) _ if not living a bit beyond its means (1.2 million
personal bankruptcies filed last year). It is enjoying every fruit
of the technological revolution, from answering machines (58
million own them) to ATM cards (11 billion transactions in 1997).
</P>
<P>
   According to the abstract, Americans say they are observing
traditional and community values by attending religious services
(60 percent say they belong to organized religions) and
volunteering, which 49 percent of adults profess to do every week.
</P>
<P>
   The data also tend to confirm some of the most important trends
of the decade. In 1997, 63.6 percent of married women with children
under age 6 worked full time or part time, compared with 18.6
percent in 1960. Some 60 percent of the nation's children under 6
get out-of-home child care, with nearly one-third of them in
day-care centers.
</P>
<P>
   More than one-quarter of all American workers, men and women
alike, now take advantage of some flexible working arrangements,
according to 1997 data. Another big trend is the growth of
home-based businesses. In 1997 more than 4.1 million people were
self-employed at home, more than half of them men. In 1991, 19.9
million Americans were able to do job-related work at home,
primarily by telecommuting. In 1997 the number was 21 million.
</P>
<P>
   The hottest occupations are computer specialists and computer
engineers. The data book projects both fields will grow by more
than 100 percent by the year 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Surfing the Internet is by far the biggest national craze. More
than 62 million Americans now have access to the Internet at home
or at work, and 43 million say they have used it in the last 30
days. Some 35 million Americans own personal computers, and the
percentage of schools with Internet access is at 78 percent,
projected to grow to 95 percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Gadgets are big. According to the abstract, the number of
cellular phone subscribers has jumped to 55 million today from 5
million in 1990. Some 63 million Americans pay for cable TV, and 79
million have VCRs. People in this country spent $10.5 billion on
computer software in 1996 and $9.9 billion on compact discs.
</P>
<P>
   Americans love their leisure. In 1997, 66 percent of adults
attended movies, 41 percent watched a sporting event, and 57
percent went to an amusement park. Travel and tennis and bowling
are up; boating and playing golf were off slightly in 1996, but
going to professional baseball games and watching college women's
basketball are attracting bigger crowds than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Facts little known about Americans, outside of the federal
abstract, are that:
</P>
<P>
   --Herb gardening is more popular than lawn care.
</P>
<P>
   --10 percent of all adults sing in groups, 5 percent go to the
opera, and 1 percent play classical music.
</P>
<P>
   --31 percent of all households own a dog, 27 percent have a cat,
and 4.6 percent have pet birds.
</P>
<P>
   --Americans made 734 million visits to doctors in 1996, an
average of 2.8 visits per person.
</P>
<P>
   Health, appearance, and personal care are near obsessions with
many Americans, the data show. Last year they spent $65 billion on
prescription drugs, $57 billion on personal care products, and $262
billion on clothes and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the same year only 14 percent of people said they engaged
in regular and vigorous physical exercise, and 50 percent said they
drank alcohol regularly. Americans spent $50 billion on tobacco
products, and consumed, per capita, 51 gallons of soft drinks. In
1994, 34 percent of all men and 36 percent of women were rated
overweight, according to the data, and another 25 percent of the
men and 44 percent of the women believed they were overweight, even
when they were not.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are also somewhat accident-prone. In 1995
emergency-room treatment was required for 87,000 injuries related
to hand and power saws; 66,000 trampoline accidents; and 978,000
mishaps on stairs, according to the abstract.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's concern with sexually transmitted diseases and the
focus on fertility treatments this year opened another area of data
analysis by the Census Bureau, which decides what goes into the
abstract, said Lars Johanson, the bureau statistician in charge of
the data book.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the abstract includes data on the number of
unmarried women who have had intercourse in the last 12 months
(12.7 million, or 60 percent of all unmarried women.) Among that
group, 31 percent reported that a partner used a condom every time
during intercourse, while 32 percent said condoms were never used.
</P>
<P>
   Among all women 15 to 44 years old, 41.1 percent have cohabited
with a man outside of marriage, and 7 percent said they were
currently cohabitating, the data show. As for male sexual partners,
23.5 percent of women in that age bracket said they had had one;
12.3 percent said they had had two; 8.1 percent said five partners;
and 15.5 percent said 10 or more partners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
