<HEADLINE>
BAFFERT HITS JACKPOT _ AND ISN'T FINISHED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was all Bob Baffert all weekend as Churchill Downs concluded
its lucrative meeting over Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert, who has guided his stable to purse earnings of more
than $14 million this year to easily lead the national trainer
standings, took the $444,800 Clark Handicap with Silver Charm
Friday, then won the $216,600 Goldenrod Stakes with Silverbulletday
and the $227,000 Brown &AMP; Williamson Stakes with Exploit Saturday.
The Baffert outfit is so powerful that all three horses were
odds-on favorites, with Silver Charm at 3-10 ($2.60 to win),
Silverbulletday at 1-10 ($2.20), and Exploit at 2-5 ($2.80).
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm had to work hard to win by a head under 124 pounds,
but he got the job done by coming back with Gary Stevens to haul in
38-1 shot Littlebitlively, who had passed Silver Charm in the
stretch with Calvin Borel but couldn't hold on under 111 pounds.
Wild Rush, who had dead-heated with Silver Charm in the Kentucky
Cup at Turfway in September and was off at 3-1 under 117 pounds and
Pat Day, was third after battling Silver Charm early. The time for
the 1 1/8 miles was 1:49.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert almost accomplished the impossible by stealing the Horse
of the Year Award from Skip Away with Silver Charm. The top Eclipse
Award was all but conceded to Skip Away after he won his first
seven races of the year. But had Awesome Again not passed Silver
Charm coming to the wire in the $5.12 million Breeders' Cup
Classic, in which Skip Away ran poorly, Silver Charm would have won
the award.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert knows he came close. After all, Silver Charm did earn
far more money than Skip Away this year, $4,696,506 to $2,740,000,
and had a similar record, 9-6-2-0 to 9-7-0-1. However, Silver Charm
did not run between winning the $4 million Dubai World Cup March 28
and losing to Awesome Again in the Stephen Foster at Churchill June
13, and he did not do quite enough as Skip Away took every race he
entered from February through September.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things,'' said Bafffert. ``He's going to
kill (owner) Bob Lewis with a heart attack with those close
finishes. We'll take him back to California after this. We may race
in the Big Cap (the Santa Anita Handicap March 6) or maybe the Donn
Handicap (at Gulfstream Jan. 30), but I just can't think that far
ahead. I'd like to get Horse of the Year with him, but because of
the Eastern media, you have to win in New York for consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   The good thing is that Lewis, who loves the game, is bringing
Silver Charm back to race as a 5-year-old. The gray colt has a
career record of 19-11-7-0 and has won $6,613,006. Skip Away, who
has been retired, earned $9,616,360, just missing Cigar's all-time
record of $9,999,815. Assuming good health, it could well be that
Silver Charm becomes the first thoroughbred to earn $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert is a nose short of having won three straight Kentucky
Derbies (Cavonnier lost by a nostril to Grindstone in '96, then
Silver Charm and Real Quiet won), but he may go on to be a nose
short of winning four in a row if 2-year-old filly Silverbulletday
and 2-year-old colt Expolit are as good as they look.
</P>
<P>
   Silverbulletday, a daughter of Silver Deputy, out of a Tom Rolfe
mare, is scary. She won the $1 million Breeders' Cup Juvenile
Fillies in impressive fashion and took the Goldenrod by 10 lengths.
She has won six of seven starts, and the only time she lost, her
stablemate, Excellent Meeting, who ran second in the Breeders' Cup,
won the race. Silverbulletday is owned by Mike Pegram, who also
owns Real Quiet, and already Baffert is deflecting questions about
putting her in the Kentucky Derby, which has been won by a filly
only three times in 124 runnings (Regret in 1915, Genuine Risk in
'80, and Winning Colors in '88). The Goldenrod and the Brown &AMP;
Williamson are both run at 1 1/16th miles. Silverbulletday ran the
distance in 1:43 4/5 under triple wraps, while Exploit was in a
drive under Chris McCarrron to win by less than 2 lengths in 1:44.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is just a professional,'' said Stevens. ``She set a stakes
record and I just asked her to run the final eighth. She's further
advanced than the best fillies I've been on in my career. She'll be
something to deal with in next year's Breeders' Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert knows Silverbulletday clinched an Eclispe Award with her
Breeders' Cup victory; the Goldenrod was just icing on the cake.
``Mike and I never really worried about the Eclipse,'' said
Baffert. ``I told Mike only some drastic bad luck would keep her
from winning. It doesn't matter now. We are definitely looking at
the Kentucky Oaks (run the day before the Derby). The only way I
would look at the Derby is for her to be doing great and the colts
to be sucking wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Exploit may well keep Baffert from putting Sillverbulletday in
the Run for the Roses. Owned by Lewis, the son of Storm Cat, out of
a My Dad George mare, opened eyes when he won the $100,000 Iriquois
Stakes on the Breeders' Cup undercard and he is 4 for 4 after going
wire to wire in the Brown &AMP; Williamson. Answer Lively, who won the
$1 million Breeders' Cup Juvenile, will probably get the Eclipse
Award, but Exploit will receive some votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the kind of colt who gawks if he is by himself,'' said
McCarron. ``He was a bit green running down the backstretch and
drifted out a little. After he straightened out and turned for
home, he was fine. He has all the ingredients of a colt with the
Triple Crown in his sights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to stay at Santa Anita and run him there,'' said
Baffert. ``He is not the kind of horse you want to haul around a
lot. He's like a keg of dynamite.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A losing `Quest'
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It looks as if Real Quiet will win an Eclipse Award as the top
3-year-old colt, giving Baffert and Pegram two statues. That was
pretty much settled Saturday when Coronado's Quest, who had won the
Haskell and Travers and set the pace in the Breeders' Cup Classic
before fading, finished fourth in the $300,000 Cigar Mile at
Aqueduct. Coronado's Quest, who was ridden by Kent Desormeaux, was
the 4-5 choice in the last start of his career, but he had a wide
trip and tired late as 8-1 shot ($19 to win) Sir Bear caught the
speed under Jerry Bailey in the time of 1:34. Trainer Shug
McGaughey still hopes that Coronado's Quest can win the Eclipse
Award, but the chances are remote as Real Quiet fell only a nose
short of capturing the Triple Crown when beaten by Victory Gallop
in the Belmont Stakes. ``The speed wasn't holding, so he laid back
a little,'' said McGaughey. ``He went wide so as to not run head to
head with another horse. The turn took something out of him. I
still think he's a prime contender for the 3-year-old
championship.''. . . In another race featuring combatants from the
Breeders' Cup, Military turned the tables on Hawksley Hill and took
Saturday's $300,000 Citation Handicap at Hollywood Park. Military
had run 12th in the $1 million Breeders' Cup Mile, while Hawksley
Hill had been narrowly beaten by Da Hoss. However, Military was
better at the 1 1/8-mile distance of the Citation, winning by 2 1/2
lengths at 9-1 ($20.60) under G.K. Gomez, while Hawksley Hill
finished seventh at 9-10 with Alex Solis. The turf course was wet,
which didn't help Hawksley Hill.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from publicity departments at various tracks and from the
Daily Racing Form was used in this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
