<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS RETURNING TO SOX? IN THEIR DREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Imagine what Mo Vaughn would say, upon hearing that
Roger Clemens is demanding a trade, if he were still a member of
the Red Sox. He'd be practically guaranteeing a pennant if general
manager Dan Duquette could somehow find a way to bring the Rocket
back into the Red Sox' orbit.
</P>
<P>
   But Vaughn lives in Disneyland now, and anyone who thinks that
the Sox have a shot at Clemens is inhabiting Fantasyland, judging
by the initial reports of what the Blue Jays want from the teams
clamoring for Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   From Houston, All-Star second baseman Craig Biggio.
</P>
<P>
   From Texas, All-Star catcher Pudge Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   From Cleveland, 95-mile-an-hour pitcher Bartolo Colon.
</P>
<P>
   From the Yankees, maybe Cuban pitcher Orlando Hernandez or Andy
Pettitte or Ramiro Mendoza, plus a fistful of top prospects.
</P>
<P>
   True, Toronto probably will have to settle for less, but where
would the Red Sox even begin to fashion a proposal to Blue Jays GM
Gord Ash? They don't have the marquee talent, on either the big
league or minor league level, to compete with the major bidders for
Clemens's services.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Clemens has demanded a trade to a contender. As they
are presently constituted, is there anyone this side of Duquette
who envisions the Mo-less Sox as a better team than the one Clemens
is demanding to leave? And can anyone imagine Clemens approving a
return to the Red Sox without Vaughn?
</P>
<P>
   Ash has been quoted as saying he'd like to move Clemens in 7-10
days. A likelier scenario is that the Jays will push to do a deal
when baseball's winter meetings begin next Friday in Nashville and
have something wrapped up no later than Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox inquired about Clemens before the trading deadline
in July, and they almost certainly have conveyed their interest to
Ash this go-round, too. No harm in imagining a top three with eight
Cy Young Awards among them: Clemens (5), Bret Saberhagen (2), and
Pedro Martinez (1). But a far likelier scenario is that Clemens
will wind up with the Yankees, who could spare a starting pitcher
as well as kids like Homer Bush and Mike Lowell in return.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens has expressed a desire to work closer to his home in
Texas, and both the Rangers, who could have had him in July for
Rusty Greer, and the Astros, who just lost Randy Johnson, can be
expected to make big plays for him.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams, in a conference call Thursday with
reporters, stated the obvious Sox position regarding Clemens. ``You
guys know what I think about pitching,'' Williams said. ``He
certainly hasn't slowed down. He's way up there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine there are a lot of teams that would like to have
him. He certainly knows how to get to Fenway.''
</P>
<P>
   The only Red Sox news Thursday was that third base coach Wendell
Kim has not lost his job after all, even though departed Pawtucket
manager Ken Macha said he was offered the position before taking a
coaching job with the Oakland A's. Williams's staff returns intact,
with one recycled addition: With Dick Pole leaving to become Angels
pitching coach, John Cumberland will become bullpen coach.
Cumberland was the Sox' pitching coach for much of 1995 and was the
PawSox' pitching coach the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Kim had come under fire for two controversial decisions, one
that took place in March, the other in October. During an
exhibition in Bradenton, Fla., Kim waved home pitcher Butch Henry,
who subsequently stopped short, pulled his left hamstring, and
weeks later tore the anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee.
In the division playoffs, Kim waved home John Valentin, who was
easily cut down at the plate by Indians left fielder David Justice.
</P>
<P>
   There was no news on the Will Clark front Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a day-in, day-out competitor,'' Williams said of the free
agent first baseman who is being considered as Vaughn's
replacement. ``He played a lot of years and still has skills.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
