<HEADLINE>
LETTERS FROM IMPEACH-LAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is our 222-year-old system of government really so fragile that
it can come unhinged by one president's priapic propensity? I don't
think so. But many do. I've previously proposed my Iodine Theory of
Impeachment, to wit: The further you live from saltwater, the more
likely you are to favor having President Clinton impeached, if not
castrated.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence? Election results, poll numbers, and the bile level
on talk radio in the Bible Belt and the Rugged West. The further
south or west, it seems, the more likely you are to dislike
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Folks south or out that-away seem genuinely convinced that
Clinton's fall from grace will have a terrible impact on the
country _ a belief I do not share, because this nation does not
fall if the president pantaloons are caught down around his ankles.
</P>
<P>
   Since remarks in this space are typically too sulfurous to bear
repeating in papers below the Mason-Dixon Line, I can't give you
much of a mail sample from Down Below, as we Northerners think of
the Old Confederacy. But I have a swatch from Out There, the Far
West, courtesy of some papers that give this bird-cage-liner an
occasional airing. A sample:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The UnGodly Liberal Left spent another 12 hours viciously
attacking DON QUIXOTE de la Starr. Anything other than impeachment
and conviction is a joke. We all know it. You, Sir, are one of the
UGLL _ sounds like ``ruggle'': The UnGodly Liberal Left. When we
need a Moses to lead us through this tragic desert, we get a
literate blind man who tinkers with words . . . Happy Thanksgiving.
Cordially, Max Huber, North Hills, CA.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Max: May I gurgle, on behalf of the UGLL: Thanks and Merry
Christmas?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You lost me as soon as I read (of Starr): ``. . . his doughy
countenance, his unappealing voice.'' Assuming you have movie star
looks, Greek-God physique and a melifluous voice, your personal
attacks stopped only when you ran out of adjectives . . . You have
a pervasive penchant for the alliterative `P'. Since when is
`pedantically professorial demeanor' a bad thing? Your style is too
bombastic . . . sophomoric. _ Rosa Arunas, Camarilo, CA.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Rosa: You have me cold: the looks, physique, voice, and
bombast.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Your stupid comments on the Republican Party in today's Tucson
Star are beyond belief. You Democrats are all alike, retarted (sic)
&AMP; no good like old Slick Willie. If that (----) Clinton don't get
off his skirt chasing, we will lose our Social Security. Of course
all of you men are quilty of what Clinton has done, he has degraded
our country beyond repair . . . by the way, I am a descendent of
Gen. Robert E. Lee, also of Pokohones (sic). Do me a favor along
with thousands of other folks here in Arizona, don't write any
more. Non respectfully, Lorraine Tompkins, Sierra Vista, AZ.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dear Lorraine: Social Security will be around long after I quit
writing and Clinton quits skirt-chasing, you can count on it.
Regards to Pocahontas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A gloomy un-American spirit has descended over the most
pro-American city in the US: Boston, Mass. Your Boston Globe
columnist, David Nyhan, would make a good reporter for arousing
feelings of unrest in Cuba or Iran. His bashing of Newt Gingrich in
the Fresno Bee was totally un-American and un-called for. There is
no political administration that could equal the dishonesty and
chaos of the Clinton regime!'' _Jim Moore, Fresno, CA.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Jim: I have no doubt that what I do for a living would cost
me my head in Iran or my freedom in Cuba. One more reason why this
is a great country.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Earth to Mr. Nyhan: The White House is not a whore house
either. Wake up. All Americans can lie to grand juries, commit
perjury, lie to the American people, break the law. If the media
condone it for Pres. Clinton, they condone it for all Americans. If
President Clinton does not have to obey the law, then no American
does either. _ Mary Myers, Santa Ana, CA.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dear Mary: So he lied about the monkey business. He got in big
trouble for that. There's not a 10-year-old in the land who doesn't
now know that even the most powerful people get in terrible hot
water for lying over trivial but embarrassing things. I cannot
believe the country has to come apart over this tawdry Lewinsky
matter. And it won't.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's all just political ``Fizzics'' to Charles Skelley Jr. of
Bellflower, CA. ``Since the Divine Right of Kings seems on the
upswing, perhaps someone could get the voters a candidate they can
trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Charles: People will begin voting on just that question in
13 months. I was pleased to see your card bore an old three-cent
postage stamp of a pensive Abe Lincoln and his prayer ``that
government of the people, by the people, for the people, shall not
perish from the earth.'' It won't.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not all my correspondents out west were beefing. My farewell to
Newt ran in the Tri-City Herald, prompting John J. Wick Jr. of
Kennewick, Wash., to take word-processor in hand. ``Thank you for
making my day. I particularly liked the bit about Newt being shoved
out the fuselage without a parachute.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear John: We aim to please. Even from 30,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
