<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACADEMIC'S CLOUD HAS SILBER LINING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A friend of mine at Boston University posed the question: Who is
the most disgraced individual in American academe? I had no idea.
Harvard Business School's Robert Merton, whose whiz-bang trading
theories helped sink Long-Term Capital Management? Harold Bloom?
(Wait a minute, I like Harold Bloom.) Then he reminded me _ Dr.
Peter Diamandopoulos, the recently cashiered president of Adelphi
University on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Not a household name in these parts, Dr. D assumed the helm at
Adelphi in 1985 with a mission to revitalize the school. Alas, the
former Brandeis dean made a hash of the job. The New York State
Board of Regents removed 18 of Adelphi's trustees last year, ruling
that they had neglected to properly review Diamond Pete's
performance and compensation. The regents then installed a new
board, which fired Diamandopoulos.
</P>
<P>
   Always at issue was the D-man's ``lavish lifestyle,'' as The New
York Times called it. Adelphi bought him a $1.3 million Manhattan
apartment, and his half-million-dollar salary rivaled only that of
. . . John Silber at BU. (It is surely no accident, as the Marxists
liked to say, that Silber, one of the 18 displaced Adelphi
trustees, sat on Diamandopoulos's compensation committee.)
</P>
<P>
   So where is Dr. D now? BU, of course! A spokesman for the
university confirms that ``Dr. Diamandopoulos has indeed accepted a
position with us, as special assistant to the president (Jon
Westling). Westling has known him for nearly 20 years, and respects
him as a brilliant teacher as well as a thoughtful observer of
history and current trends in higher education. He will be working
on special projects in the president's office in the areas of
development, international education, and educational policy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The toast
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One should always expect the unexpected at SilberWorld, but even
jaded BU profs were taken aback two weeks ago when Chilean native
Claudio Veliz, who organizes the pompous ``Conversazione''
seminars, proposed a rather unorthodox toast.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of a colloquium on democracy, of all things, Veliz
announced to the assembled notables that ``we have good news from
England'' _ a British court had rejected an extradition request
that would have sent former Chilean dictator Augusto Pinochet
abroad to face trial for human rights abuses. Veliz then proposed a
toast to Pinochet. The assembled dignitaries, including Supreme
Court Justice Stephen Breyer, sat in stunned, stony silence.
</P>
<P>
   Veliz is a bit cheesed that participants in the off-the-record
seminar blabbed about his toast, and allows that, yes, the liberal
professorate was nonplused by his action. Like millions of his
countrymen, he's pro-Pinochet and proud of it. ``I'm made of
stainless steel when it comes to this kind of stuff,'' he told me.
``Pinochet is not Mother Teresa with trousers on,'' Veliz
explained, an apparent allusion to the thousands of left-wing
Chileans who were ``disappeared'' under the former dictator. ``But
the idea that this man is a monster is ridiculous. He restored
democracy to Chile and he should be toasted frequently.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Leftovers
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Want to sit out the tiresome Y2K ``crisis,'' when your bank
account mysteriously craters and your credit dries up? A friend
calls my attention to the Y2K Sanctuary (www.y2krefuge.com), a
haven in the Appalachian Mountains of West Virginia. A Mr. C. R.
Brown is leasing out 20 recreational vehicle sites, far from the
maddening cyber-crisis. ``The cost of the lease is $5,000 paid up
front. For this sum you will have one fine vacation spot until June
2001, or a sanctum until the Y2K chaos is over, whatever date that
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet another friend (yes, there are two) passes along the ne plus
ultra of Christmas catalogs from a company called U.S. Cavalry
(1-800-333-5102.). Much of the merchandise is your run-of-the-mill,
gutting-and-garroting paraphernalia, but U.S. Cav does have a few
original twists, like the ladies' SEAL dive watches. Better not
order the $15 Subversion Slingshot, though. As you probably know,
slingshots cannot be sold to individuals in Malta, Australia, and .
. . the Commonwealth of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
