<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SHATTERED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SHATTERED' NEVER REALLY COMES TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chilean-born, French-based filmmaker Raul Ruiz has been moving
from long, impenetrable surrealist meditations to films that are
shorter and more playful, yet just as filled with fairy-tale
delicacy and reality shifts. But ``Shattered Image,'' Ruiz's first
collision with Hollywood, isn't among these frothy latter-day
entertainments. It's understandable that Ruiz should have been
hired to direct this two-track film about a woman who is either a
hired killer living in Seattle or a honeymooner in Jamaica. Few
directors have liberated themselves more completely from linear
narrative pushing off a defining event.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the woman's got William Baldwin's enigmatic smiler
hanging around. He's clearly a schemer in each of the parallel
lives. But Anne Parillaud's character doesn't know which of the
dual worlds between which she shuttles is the real thing and which
is the unreal one. Understandably, she looks exhausted in both
locales, and sleeps a lot. We vote for the hit woman alternative,
if only because it gives Parillaud a chance to reprise her ``Femme
Nikita'' thing by sauntering into a restaurant and shooting a male
quarry dead in the men's room.
</P>
<P>
   As the honeymooner, she's too much the helpless victim to be
appealing, too much at the mercy of Baldwin's snaky manipulator. He
scarcely bothers to conceal his interest in a blond acquaintance as
he positions Parillaud's dread-filled bride for something bad that
only she fails to see, although she is overwhelmed by a feeling
that a brooding painting hanging on the wall of her suite is an
ominous portent. The painting is too obviously a stand-in for the
film, which is filled with teasing tendrils of imagery that hint at
revelations to come. Not that they do.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Parillaud is in such great shape as the assassin,
either, possibly because she's stuck with the worst-looking raggedy
black wig in movies this year. After a while, it's hard to care
which plot strand is real, or whether they can be made to converge
in a dramatic payoff. Ruiz's surrealistic playfulness deserts him,
possibly having been frightened off by Duane Poole's hackneyed
script, which harks back to antique Hollywood gothica. The attempt
to trade on Parillaud's ``Femme Nikita'' mode wears thin. The
unstable honeymooner's unraveling under the influence of her sleazy
spouse is old hat, too. ``Shattered Image'' doesn't so much fall
apart as fail to ever come together.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
