<HEADER>
A3263 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS &LR;      12-04 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDEN SMOG: THE ROCKER'S ALTERNATIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though it is a part-time project, a sideline gig for those
involved, many fans consider Golden Smog to be the standard-bearer
of the so-called ``no depression,'' or alt-country, movement.
Golden Smog comprises a lot of folks from a whole lot of other
bands. It has singer-songwriters Dan Murphy from Soul Asylum, Jeff
Tweedy from Wilco, Gary Louris and Marc Perlman from the Jayhawks,
and Kraig Johnson from Run Westy Run. Its new drummer _ the Smog
runs through drummers like Spinal Tap did _ is Jody Stephens of Big
Star. But you may not want to call Golden Smog an Al Kooper-esque
supergroup. Better, suggests Murphy on the phone from Minneapolis,
to call it a ``stuporgroup.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy explains his preferred term. ``With our group,'' he says,
``the only real standard is you gotta be a music fan. And we all
dig each other's bands, grew up listening to each other. We don't
have high aspirations. Look at our careers: None (of our main
bands) have been all that super. We just want to play music with
our friends and not embarrass ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The zephyrs of what became Golden Smog started swirling around
the late-'80s. It began as a bit of a joke. The band covered songs
by bands from the Rolling Stones to Three Dog Night. Murphy took
the name from the Flintstones _ the Mel ``Velvet Fog'' Torme of
Bedrock was called the Golden Smog.
</P>
<P>
   This Golden Smog was, and remains, a side project for the
various people involved. When they made a semiformal debut in 1995
with a five-days-in-the-making recording session-cum-frat party
disc called ``Down By the Old Mainstream,'' the musicians used fake
names, created a fake bio, and took blowhard credit for nonexistent
records.
</P>
<P>
   ``People's expectations were so low,'' says Murphy, about the
subsequent tour. ``They thought they'd come and see a goofy band
like They Might Be Giants.'' They got, he says, a pretty raucous
band playing covers (Bowie, Velvet Underground) and originals. ``It
went smashingly.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Smog has a lot of sad songs in its repertoire because
_ as Elton John once sang, sad songs say so much _ the musicians
tend to rip it up in concert. ``There's quite a lot of
introspective stuff,'' Murphy says of the compositions, especially
those on the latest disc, ``Weird Tales.'' The album ``wasn't as
much fun to make, but it's a better album and therefore worth it.
The songs are more serious, darker. Sometimes (artists) are
clearest when they're going through (hard) things, asking those
questions. On this album, there's a more collective identity.''
Graybeard rock fans might hear echoes of Buffalo Springfield and
the Byrds.
</P>
<P>
   One of the things that makes Golden Smog work, suggests Murphy,
is the relative lack of pressure. The members talked to some major
labeIs, but if they were signed to a bigger label than the
Salem-based Rykodisc, Murphy says, ``I don't think we could live up
to (sales) expectations. . . . The mentality of the Smog is this:
Songs that are fairly simple, in a good way. Not tuneless, but easy
to pick up and play. What you do is try and capture the spark of
what you were thinking when you wrote the song.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ben Carr, tell us about your job: ``I think there's very few
like it,'' says the (mostly) nonsinging/nonmusician member of the
Mighty Mighty Bosstones. ``It started when I went to high school
with Nate (Adderley) and Joe (Gittelman) and they were putting
together a band, and I didn't play anything. I was just there
hanging out. As they started developing the Bosstones with Dicky
(Barrett) and Tim (Burton), I still didn't play anything. I was the
eighth man, the roadie. I was never onstage during the early days,
but I was the best-dressed roadie in Boston. In the mid-'80s, at
one show, Dicky said to me, `You know all the lyrics, why don't you
come up and help me sing the song?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Such began Carr's career as the Mighty Mighty Bosstones dancer
and (very) minimal backup singer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It developed,'' Carr continues, of his career arc, ``so that I
didn't leave the stage. . . . It's not us _ a band _ vs. an
audience. We're (about) audience participation. I kinda show that.
I could be any of them and they could be me.''
</P>
<P>
   As to the Throwdown, Carr says, ``I've run into fans that say,
`Are you gonna do it?' and I say, `Of course, we're doing it.'
There's a special reason we're doing it: No matter how big the band
ever gets we'll still be here at the Middle East. It's the central
point of music in Boston. (Owners) Joseph and Nabile (Sater) go out
of their way to make people feel at home.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rhode Island-based Combustible Edison was at the forefront
of the neo-lounge movement in the early '90s. It intends to range
beyond the form as the nebulous post-lounge future beckons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me, I come from a jazz background,'' says vibraphonist Mike
Connors, ``and was never into the rock scene too much. I approach
this in more of a jazz way.''
</P>
<P>
   The suave Edison formed from the ashes of the Boston-based
punk-psychedelic band Christmas by guitarist-singer Michael Cudahy
and drummer (now singer/percussionist) Liz Cox. Cudahy calls
himself ``the Millionaire,'' Cox calls herself ``Miss Lily
Banquette.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to play music when I was 18 and did a lot of growing
up onstage,'' says Cox. ``With the Combustible Edison original, it
was like I was playing a character, but lo and behold, I am much
less of a rock chick than ever, and that's more comfortable for me
now. I've started studying music after all these years of just
going up there. It's the challenge of learning more about what I do
and putting it to use.''
</P>
<P>
   Combustible Edison's music has been featured in about 10 movies,
the latest being Terry Gilliam's ``Fear and Loathing in Las
Vegas.'' As to the band's soft-core exotica and lovers' rock vibe,
Cox coos, ``There's nothing to be mad about anymore. Even Alanis
has figured it out: Get naked and love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see we're all getting older,'' adds Connors, ``except
for Liz _ she looks beautiful all the time. But I was thinking it's
cool we're playing this and I don't feel like `Oh my God, I'm doing
the job of an 18-year-old.' '' It has sophistication and life
experience behind it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
