A3269 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      12-04 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYOFF THE ONLY REMEDY FOR BOWL CHAMPIONSHIP SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's the bottom line on the Bowl Championship Series bashing
that is growing each day. True, it's not the best system in the
world. But it is better than what was in place a year ago, because
it allows teams from every conference to be included in the mix
without regard to bowl tie-ins and it has created tremendous
interest in the sport for the past month.
</P>
<P>
   But the real problem cannot be solved by any system short of a
playoff.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this. Three unbeaten teams _ Kansas State, UCLA,
Tennessee. Two slots for the national title game, the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't a human panel or a computer printout sheet that can
solve the problem. Three won't go into two.
</P>
<P>
   So even if there were no BCS or computerized numbers and
quartile rankings and strength-of-schedule factors that have many
people upset, the fact is that when you have three unbeaten teams
(and we're not even counting Tulane, which was not invited to the
BCS party) and only room for two of them, someone is going to be
left out.
</P>
<P>
   What happens if Kansas State beats Texas A&AMP;M, UCLA beats Miami,
and Tennessee beats Mississippi State in Saturday's showdown games?
The computers and the pollsters will decide.
</P>
<P>
   If this were basketball, where the tournament selection
committee considers every facet of each team's season, the call
would undoubtedly come down to a number of tie-breakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, it would be UCLA and Tennessee hands down,'' said
one source familiar with the workings of the NCAA basketball
selection committee. ``It would come down to strength of schedule,
who teams played in nonconference games. Kansas State didn't (play
tough nonconference foes). The others did.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a tough late-season schedule against Nebraska, Missouri,
and Texas A&AMP;M, Kansas State cannot escape the perception that it
has ducked people by scheduling lowly regarded teams such as
Northern Illinois, Indiana State, and Northeast Louisiana;
meanwhile, UCLA was playing more high-profile teams such as Texas,
Houston, and Miami, and Tennessee was facing Syracuse and Houston
(as well as Alabama-Birmingham, which could hurt the Volunteers in
the end).
</P>
<P>
   What it all comes down to, it seems, is that unless someone
loses, somebody will be unhappy Sunday, and that would have
happened with or without a BCS.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No snow jobs
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the spate of openings at big-time programs around the
country _ Auburn, Clemson, South Carolina, Iowa, Oklahoma _ there
could have been a feeding frenzy over the job openings. But this
time the athletic directors proved they had done their homework.
The ADs simply went to the short list of candidates they keep in
their desks and made quick and, it would seem at first blush,
reasonable hires. Clemson made a good move in hiring Tulane's Tommy
Bowden. Oklahoma hired the rising star among assistants, Florida
State defensive coordinator Bobby Stoops, and Auburn went across
state lines and hired Mississippi's Tommy Tuberville . . . The most
intriguing moves could be at Nevada-Las Vegas, which has hired
former Southern Cal and Los Angeles Rams coach John Robinson, and
South Carolina, where former Notre Dame coach Lou Holtz may resume
his coaching career. Holtz's decision is reportedly contingent on
the condition of his wife, Beth, who has been battling throat
cancer for two years. If Holtz decides to take the offer, which is
reportedly in the $1 million annual range, he must decide whether
to bring in his son Skip as offensive coordinator. Skip, who has
done a marvelous job in taking Connecticut to new heights at the
Division 1-AA level (the Huskies play Georgia Southern in the
national quarterfinals Saturday), could have a tough decision.
Should he stay at UConn and continue to build his reputation as the
program moves toward the 1-A level, then take the first decent 1-A
head post that comes along? Or should he go to South Carolina,
where he could be in line to succeed his father in a few years? . .
. The hiring of Tommy Bowden was refreshing in that everyone had
something nice to say, even Bowden's players at Tulane, who could
have expressed resentment at being abandoned by the coach who
recruited them. ``If the Clemson team does what he asks, they'll
get better in a hurry,'' said quarterback Shawn King . . . The
other interesting aspect of Clemson's hiring of Bowden is that it
sets up an annual family feud in the Atlantic Coast Conference
between the Tigers and Florida State, where Tommy's father, Bobby,
is a fixture. ``We're thrilled to have Tommy in our conference,''
said Bobby . . . Far removed from all the hoopla surrounding the
unbeaten teams in 1-A, the most powerful dynasty in college
football rolls on. Division 3 Mount Union has won 40 consecutive
games, the last two national championships, and three of the last
five. It's within two wins of another.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some three-for-alls
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Having three undefeated teams from different major conferences
at the end of a season is rare but not unprecedented. The last time
it happened was in 1993, when Auburn, which was on probation and
could not participate in a bowl, Nebraska, and West Virginia were
all unbeaten. West Virginia lost to Florida in the Sugar Bowl and
Nebraska lost to Florida State in the Orange Bowl, so the
once-beaten Seminoles won the national title. It also happened in
1992, when unbeaten Miami and Alabama met in the Sugar Bowl, which
turned out to be the national championship game, while unbeaten
Texas A&AMP;M lost to Notre Dame in the Cotton Bowl . . . The biggest
UCLA rooters in Florida could be the Central Florida Golden
Knights. Here's why: If UCLA beats Miami and earns a Fiesta Bowl
bid, Central Florida will play Air Force in the Oahu Bowl at
Honolulu. If UCLA does not make the Fiesta Bowl, UCF stays home
because UCLA would then go to the Rose Bowl, Arizona would drop
down to the Holiday Bowl, and Oregon would be bumped from the
Holiday to the Oahu . . . Arkansas fans had been all set to head to
Dallas for a Cotton Bowl meeting against onetime Southwest
Conference rival Texas. But Florida's apparent inclusion in the BCS
mix (the Orange Bowl against Syracuse) opened a slot in the Citrus
Bowl, which wanted a matchup between Ohio State and Arkansas . . .
As it looks now, Mississippi State will go to the Cotton if the
Bulldogs lose the Southeastern Conference title game against
Tennessee Saturday night . . . Ohio State is upset because it is
ranked fifth in the country with a 10-1 record and probably won't
go to a BCS game, while twice-beaten Florida and three-time loser
Syracuse will. Why? Contracts and fan support. Syracuse, as the Big
East champion, has a guaranteed BCS slot and Thursday accepted an
invitation to be the Orange Bowl host team. Florida figures to
bring more fans to the Orange Bowl than OSU, which disappointed
some bowl officials with its poor fan turnout at last year's Sugar
Bowl. The same thing happened to 10-1 North Carolina and unbeaten
Brigham Young last season. Those are the breaks of the game. When
it comes to bowls other than the national championship game, it's
not how many games you win or lose but how many television sets you
can turn on and how many fans you can bring with you.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-04-98 1331EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
