<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3274 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKC-TERRIERS-ART-BOS &LR;      12-04 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-TERRIERS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERENNIAL HOCKEY POWER BU STUMBLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They've been at the head of Eastern college hockey in
this decade, the envy of many programs, coaches, and players. Just
look at the record compiled by Boston University under feisty coach
Jack Parker: NCAA tournament berths every year, an amazing seven
appearances in the NCAA Final Four, a national championship in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, the seniors who departed last spring became the
first class to win four consecutive Beanpots, and the Terriers have
won seven of nine in the '90s. They've won or shared the Hockey
East regular-season championship each of the past five years,
captured five tournament titles, and appeared in the tournament
final six times.
</P>
<P>
   Only Michigan (286-75-24) had more wins than the Terriers
(253-83-24) since the 1989-90 season. Thirteen BU alumni have
played in the National Hockey League this year, and Chris Drury won
the Hobey Baker Award as the best player in the college game last
year.
</P>
<P>
   That's why this season is such a startling aberration. The
Terriers are off to their worst start in Parker's 26 seasons as
head coach _ 3-8-1 overall, 1-4-1 in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Inexperience, injuries, and disappointing production from some
veterans are at the root of the struggles, but the season is young
and there have been some bright spots: a 4-2 win over Boston
College, a win over St. Lawrence last Saturday night in Canton,
N.Y., and a tie at New Hampshire. Those are indications that BU can
turn it around. To an extent.
</P>
<P>
   Parker, a realist, feels more effort is required from the older
players, led by captain Albie O'Connell, a forward from Watertown,
and his assistants, defenseman Dan Ronan of Woburn and goaltender
Michel Larocque of Dieppe, New Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question this is the youngest team I've had since
the first team I coached,'' says Parker. ``That, combined with some
of the upperclassmen not playing up to their capabilities, we've
really struggled. We've had some games where we thought we've
played most of it, but that's the rub. We can't figure out how to
be more consistent in (our) play and to give a more consistent
effort. We're certainly young, but we certainly have enough talent
to win hockey games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have enough concerted effort. We played well at UNH
and against BC. In between those games, we just go through the
motions, like we did against Harvard (a 4-3 loss) last Tuesday.
It's baffling to see why they won't go hard all the time. We have
so many freshmen and sophomores, I'm sure we're going to see a much
better team in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might not be until Feburary or March. It might not be until
next year. I think the most difficult thing to accept is the lack
of effort, the lack of intensity that has always been a BU
trademark. We're not getting the leadership that's a BU legacy.
It's probably a combination of all those things.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't seem to get them to play with the intensity that
teams who have worn this uniform in the past have played with, and
that has nothing to do with talent or how old you are. It has to do
with the competitive spirit. That's the toughest thing to accept.
If we're getting great effort and losing, that would be one
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronan, who has played in 130 of a possible 131 games with the
Terriers, is pragmatic about this year's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our expectations were definitely higher when the season
started,'' he says. ``It wasn't that we were going to be one of the
best teams in the country, but higher than starting out 3-8-1. We
knew were going to struggle early, but we didn't think we were
going to struggle as much as we have. It's been disappointing, and
on the same token, it's been frustraing having played for teams the
last three years that have been in the Final Four two of those
years and an overtime away from a third.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a big adjustment. We've tried to help the younger
guys adjust and understand it's like growing pains. I think a tough
thing is having only seven upperclassmen. We have 15 or 16 guys who
are only freshmen or sophomores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the problem now is getting consistency out of the
younger guys, and the older guys haven't played consistently.
Michel had a tough start. I haven't played well at all, and Albie's
had injuries. We haven't had the consistency out of the older guys
as well. It's different for me. I'd be the fourth, fifth, or sixth
defenseman, and I've had to change that role.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can cover up the mistake a forward makes, but when a young
defenseman screws up, you can't cover it up. It's been part of our
problem. We have four defensemen who had to jump into Division 1
college hockey right away. It's not like we were playing the Little
Sisters of the Poor. We had UNH and BC right away. You had to test
their colors early.''
</P>
<P>
   Larocque, who owned a 43-10-6 record entering the season and led
the Terriers to the NCAA final as a sophomore, started off 0-4 with
a .792 save percentage and a 5.60 goals-against average. In his
last seven starts, his numbers are 3-3-1, .913, and a 2.83. ``We've
been inconsistent,'' he says. ``We've made some strides forward,
but then we've gone backward a couple of steps, and that's why
we're in the mess we are right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a slow start. I think part of it was adjusting to a new
team, a new style, a younger defense. It had to do with my trusting
my `D' and getting used to them. But now I feel great and I feel
great about who I have in front of me. I think everything's looking
pretty positive.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell believes the Terriers' struggles have been the result
of a perfect balance. A perfectly awful balance. ``We were letting
up a lot of goals,'' he says. ``We were getting some good offense,
but we weren't scoring much on the power play. Our special teams
have been a problem from the start of the season. We weren't
scoring power-play goals and we gave up a couple. We shot ourselves
in the foot in the first five games or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need the older guys to play well every game, and the
younger guys can feed off of us. We're trying to keep the morale of
the team up.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether the record will follow suit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
