<HEADLINE>
PREGAME SHOWS WILL THROW A FLAG ON THE NFL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just when you thought referee bashing was over, Sunday's NFL
pregame shows will put the officials under even more scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's Cris Collinsworth will interview George Young, the
league's vice president for football operations, about the impact
that several embarrassing recent calls have had on ressurecting
instant replay.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN will have Chris Mortensen talking about the problems and
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   And CBS's Armen Keteyian will make an interesting argument: that
well-intentioned pressure from the NFL to strive for perfection has
made the refs nervous _ and, as a result, worse.
</P>
<P>
   Game officials don't have the benefit of long-term, guaranteed
contracts. In fact, Keteyian reports, the turnover among refs
during the last eight years has surpassed 50 percent. Since 1990,
when the league had 112 officials, there have been 64 personnel
changes. Some of the turnover has been because of retirement and
attrition, but some has been directly related to on-field
performance.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's standards are high. Officials are expected to get at
least 90 percent of their calls rights. With the excpetion of
placekickers, no one else on the field is held to a higher
standard. If a quarterback completes 55 percent of his passes, he
is Hall of Fame material.
</P>
<P>
   Not so the men in stripes. After each weekend, league officials
spend as many as six hours reviewing the games, analyzing every
call and grading every game official.
</P>
<P>
   Keteyian points out that the grading process is flawed, largely
because it is based on a two-dimensional, frame-by-frame review
while the call actually was made at warp speed in three dimensions.
Given the sneakiness of, say, offensive holding, it's difficult to
see every infraction, and it would be even more painful to call
every penalty.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that referees don't make mistakes. For his
upcoming report, Keteyian said that he interviewed Jerry Seaman,
the senior director of officiating in the NFL. According to
Keteyian, Seeman told him that the two calls against the Buffalo
Bills that helped the Patriots win on the last play of last
Sunday's game were both ``mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Keteyian's point is still well taken _ and not unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh Steelers president Dan Rooney told USA Today that the
league is to blame for causing officials to be more concerned with
receiving good grades than making the right calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're so gun-shy right now, if they make some little mistake
and they don't call something, they're going to be graded down, ''
Rooney said. ``You're considered a good official or a bad official
based on the grades.''
</P>
<P>
   Making officials full time employees won't help. CBS analyst
Marcus Allen said that is the most ridiclous suggestion he has ever
heard. ``I was a full-time player and I made plenty of mistakes,''
Allen said. ``As long as the referees are human, there will always
be errors.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, a bad call shouldn't determine which team wins and
which loses. ESPN's Chris Berman said as much during halftime of
``Monday Night Football.'' As Berman said, giving the Patriots the
ball on the 1-yard line ``all but guaranteed a Patriots victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Berman added: ``Hey, it's the last second of the game. Call the
penalty, but don't give the team the ball at the 1. Make them still
win it. Assess a 5- or 10-yard penalty from the line of scrimmage,
and make them score.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ACC-Big Ten on ESPN
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPN has reached a multiyear agreement with the Atlantic Coast
and Big Ten conferences to air the ACC/Big Ten Challenge, a men's
basketball event that will begin next season.
</P>
<P>
   The series will match nine teams from each conference on the
first Tuesday and Wednesday following Thanksgiving. The games, to
be played at campus sites, will air on ESPN and ESPN2. ESPN will
manage and market the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always great to eliminate the Cupcake City games, and to
get two of the nation's marquee conferences together like this will
really whet the appetites of college hoop fans early in the
season,'' said ESPN's Dick Vitale. ``Take it to the bank: These
games will be Maalox Specials; they'll be nail-biters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
