<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS NOT WELL-GROUNDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Larry Kennan, then the offenive coordinator,
came to the same conclusion late last year that this Patriots
regime is likely reaching but isn't acknowledging publicly: The
team can't run and therefore will have to win on the strength of
Drew Bledsoe's right arm and the four healthy fingers on his right
hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to do what we have to do to win,'' said Bledsoe,
looking ahead to Sunday's game in Pittsburgh. ``And if it means
we're going to focus on the passing game, then that's what we're
going to do. There's no doubt that we have to run the ball more
effectively. That's an entire team thing that we have to work on.
It falls obviously on the guys up front. It falls on the receivers
blocking downfield. It falls on the backs hitting the holes
correctly. It falls on me to make the proper decision if I'm
checking off at the line of scrimmage. There are a lot of things
going there. And it's an entire team effort if we want to get that
thing going.''
</P>
<P>
   Center Dave Wohlabaugh concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to go with what works,'' he said. ``Lately, that's
been Drew getting the ball out to the receivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Pete Carroll is still not willing to concede that the running
game is a failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go with what's working in the game, we always feel
that way, but we want to be continuing toward the goal of a
balanced attack and trying to even it out so we can't get locked in
on one aspect,'' said the coach. ``We're certainly going to lean
toward what's working, but we have to get the ball moving on the
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   As Game 13 approaches, the Patriots have no idea where their
running game is. For a four-game stretch between Sept. 20 and
Oct.19, rookie running back Robert Edwards had 90 or more yards.
His best output since has been 70 yards on 23 carries at
Indianapolis Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice to say, the running game has regressed and Carroll is
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no consistency,'' he said. ``We have trouble getting
the line of scrimmage moving like we want to, and Robert has fallen
prey to it. He's trying to pick his way too much and not hitting
the line of scrimmage with more power and slashing like he can. We
continue to work at it. We emphasized it today in practice and
we'll continue to try and get it right.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not necessarily the fault of Edwards, who hasn't gotten
more than 14 carries in the past four weeks. It's probably more
attributable to the offensive line, which has undergone some
revamping with Damon Denson now starting at left guard and left
tackle Zefross Moss missing the last two games with an ankle
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line coach Paul Boudreau thinks his troops could do
the job if there was more of a commitment to the run. His preseason
challenge _ that fingers would be pointed at his linemen if Edwards
didn't get rolling _ hasn't stirred them up.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a new problem; the Patriots weren't a running team
even with Curtis Martin gaining 1,000 yards annually. That's why
Bledsoe threw more passes than any other quarterback in history his
first five years.
</P>
<P>
   Any time Bledsoe is asked about the running game, he shrugs. He
knows deep in his heart that he's not going to have one because
he's never had one.
</P>
<P>
   Can the Patriots win and not run? Traditionalists say no.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are sort of an aberration in that they are 7-5 and
would be in the the playoffs if they began today.
</P>
<P>
   They've done it with virtually no balance and despite injuries
to 15 regulars.
</P>
<P>
   They run the ball only 38.9 percent of the time, far short of
league leaders Denver (52.4 percent), Dallas (51.8), Buffalo
(50.5), and Pittsburgh (50.3).
</P>
<P>
   The only team that's worse running the ball is Carolina, which
is 2-10. The closest team to the Patriots with a winning record is
Miami, which ranks 15th in rushing.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, who are averaging 78.8 rushing yards per game (the
NFL average is 112), are next to last in average yards per carry
(3.3).
</P>
<P>
   Given that, it's not surprising that the Patriots rank so low in
time of posesstion _ 26th in ther league with an average of 28
minutes 22 seconds per game. And that doesn't help a defense that
has been banged up among its front seven, putting inordinate
pressure on the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards wants to do more.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the great running backs and they can't get going
until they have a few carries,'' he said. ``We've just been in
situations where I haven't got those carries. All running backs
want to get into a rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots deny that Edwards has hit a rookie wall in terms of
wearing down. After all, he hasn't had a lot of carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started trying to make things happen,'' he said. ``They were
putting a lot more people in the box and a lot of guys we couldn't
block. I was just trying to make them miss and make a big pay.''
</P>
<P>
   It was thought that when fullback Tony Carter returned to the
lineup following knee surgery, things would change. But Carter has
been back for two games, and the Patriots have trailed in both,
forcing them to throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes everything harder when you can't run the ball,'' said
Carter. ``There are certain games you can win without it, but all
of the great teams control the ball on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Patriots didn't have a 100-yard rusher in the
final seven games and went 5-2. They won a playoff game against
Miami without a 100-yard rusher and lost to the Steelers with one.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible to stay in the running without a running game,
and barring something unforeseen, that's what the Patriots will
have to do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
