<HEADER>
A3284 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      12-04 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN A DOUBLE-BARRELED NO. 1 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget this mania about Connecticut and its future as a football
state with the Patriots headed to Hartford and UConn talking about
moving up to the Division 1-A college level.
</P>
<P>
   That's years away and not a mortal lock.
</P>
<P>
   Let's talk about here and now. Play word association for a
minute. Connecticut. College basketball. No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Bingo. You've got it. As of Friday, the No. 1 team in men's
college basketball is UConn. The No. 1 team in women's college
basketball is . . . UConn.
</P>
<P>
   Think about that for a minute. We're not talking about the Big
East, where the Huskies of both genders have been dominant for
years. We're talking about the country, which includes Kentucky,
Duke, UCLA, North Carolina, Tennessee, Stanford, Louisiana Tech,
and the like.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking about a campus in Storrs, a town so small that
former Notre Dame football coach Lou Holtz once joked it should
have been named Storr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, it's great,'' said UConn athletic director Lew Perkins,
who was in Chicago the other night watching the Huskies men take
care of business in their Great Eight tournament game by beating up
Washington. ``I'd rather have us No. 1 in March, but we'll take
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perkins could also point with pride to a nationally ranked
football team that is in the Division 1-AA quarterfinals and a
nationally ranked soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   But basketball is the engine that drives UConn athletics, and
the Huskies are no longer considered a curiosity when it comes to
talking about the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the thing,'' said Perkins. ``We're No. 1 and nobody is
making a big deal like it's something unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor should they. The Huskies pulled off the rare double play
three years ago when the men and women also reached No. 1 status in
the same week.
</P>
<P>
   The odds of staying on top for an extended period are long. As
UConn coach Jim Calhoun and Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski, whose team
started the preseason No. 1, will tell you, being No. 1 in December
is a cosmetic award at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe on March 29 and 30, it will be important,'' said
Calhoun, who hopes this team will take him to his first Final Four,
in St. Petersburg, Fla., next March. ``But not now.''
</P>
<P>
   And who knows, UConn may lose to tough Michigan State Saturday
in Storrs and its ranking will drop.
</P>
<P>
   But its stature won't. UConn is one of the big boys in college
basketball now, thanks to Calhoun's skills as a coach and
recruiter, which measure up to anyone's.
</P>
<P>
   No one can argue that, and that's quite an accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Challenging format
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantic Coast Conference and Big Ten have set up a
two-year, nine-game challenge starting next year. That would seem
to be a problem if you do the math, since the Big Ten has 11 teams
and the ACC has nine. Not to worry. A scheduling conflict has taken
Ohio State temporarily out of the rotation, and Indiana coach Bob
Knight has told Big Ten officials he won't participate in the
series, which will be played the week after Thanksgiving for the
next two seasons . . . Don't underestimate Kentucky's chances of
winning its third national championship in four seasons. The
Wildcats took apart a decent Kansas team in the Great Eight.
Despite the fact that nine of this year's Wildcats are either
freshmen or sophomores, they have great senior leadership in guard
Wayne Turner and are capable of beating anyone . . . Kansas's point
total in its 63-45 loss to Kentucky was its lowest during the Roy
Williams era . . . Forgive next season's preseason No. 1 team if it
wants to pass on any games in November. When Duke lost to
Cincinnati in the Great Alaska tournament last week, it marked the
seventh consecutive season that the polls' preseason No. 1 had not
gotten into December without a loss . . . Temple may be one of the
best teams in the country, but the Owls will have a hard time
convincing people they are the best team in Pennsylvania. In the
span of eight days, coach John Chaney's team lost to Penn and Penn
State . . . It's early, but Florida Atlantic's 83-81 upset of No.
11 Oklahoma State in Stillwater, Okla., Tuesday may rank up there
with Temple beating Virginia Tech in football. Florida Atlantic
came into the game with a 1-3 record and was playing a team that
hadn't lost a nonconference home game since 1987 (80 games) . . .
Has anyone seen University of Massachusetts center Lari Ketner?
Just wondering. The Minutemen's slow start makes next week's game
against UConn at the Mullins Center even more important if UMass is
to have any confidence going into the Atlantic 10 season . . .
Anyone noticed what the Boston College ``alumni'' have been doing
lately? Maine's Andy Bedard is on a scoring binge. Ohio State's
Scoonie Penn has been named Big Ten Player of the Week and is a big
reason coach Jim O'Brien's Buckeyes have already won six games
after totaling eight victories last season. Kentucky's Mike Bradley
is starting and contributing for the Wildcats. Providence's Sean
Connolly has been a factor in the Friars' quick start. We could go
on and on. But that would only be more depressing for BC fans who
saw a Top 20 program dismantled before their eyes because of
arrogance, stupidity, stubbornness, or any other term you choose to
describe what happened to O'Brien and his recruits two years ago .
. . Speaking of Providence, Tim Welsh has shown that coaching does
count for something. The Friars aren't that good, but they're
winning games, a tribute to Welsh . . . Maryland gave coach Gary
Williams a contract extension through the 2005 season. Hmm. Some
schools do take care of coaches who come back to work at their alma
mater . . . Xavier's win over Miami of Ohio and Rhode Island's
victory over Utah stopped a bad Atlantic 10 skid after UMass
(College of Charleston), Temple (Penn), URI (Wisconsin), and Xavier
(Pittsburgh) lost in the past week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One from the heart
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The lockout has kept NBA coaches, scouts, and general managers
scrambling to keep busy. One NBA coach took a recent visit to a
college campus where the coach invited him to not only watch
practice but speak to the team. The NBA coach gave an inspirational
talk about how desire and hard work can overcome everything, which
naturally picked up the spirits of the team. But after he left the
building, the coach told a friend, ``They won't win five games.'' .
. . In Wednesday's win over Utah, URI's Lamar Odom didn't approach
the dazzling performance he put on in his collegiate debut against
Texas Christian, when he scored 19 points, pulled down 15 rebounds,
and dished out 9 assists, hitting the winning basket in the final
seconds for good measure. But the 6-foot-10-inch phenom again
proved that there aren't many better players in the country. With
15 points, 6 assists, and 6 rebounds overall, Odom took control in
the second half of URI's 70-63 win. ``I thought we guarded him,''
said Utah coach Rick Majerus, shaking his head in dismay. ``He hit
tough shots. I applaud him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
