<HEADLINE>
MUTUAL FUND FIRMS WORK TO PROTECT DIRECTOR SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Has the time-honored system of mutual fund directors served
shareholders well, providing an important independent watchdog for
investors' money? Or is there a connection between the six-figure
salaries the directors are paid and the fees that mutual fund
shareholders are charged?
</P>
<P>
   In the arcane world of mutual fund governance and fees, those
are questions more easily asked than answered. But this much is
clear: The mutual fund industry believes the current system works
and is moving to protect it, whether in the courts or the
legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Massachusetts' mutual fund companies last month
quietly secured final approval for state legislation that would
make it more difficult for unhappy shareholders and their lawyers
to challenge the independence of directors. The change, tacked on
as a two-sentence amendment to another bill, needed Governor
Cellucci's signature by Dec. 4 to become law.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation and a similar bill passed in Maryland, like
Massachusetts the legal home of a number of mutual fund complexes,
come as a handful of companies have been targeted in shareholder
suits challenging the independence of directors and the effect the
system has had on fund fees. So far suits have been filed against
Fidelity Investments, Prudential, T. Rowe Price, BlackRock, and BEA
Associates.
</P>
<P>
   The suits are considered a longshot, but they could add to the
drumbeat on fund fees. The Securities and Exchange Commission is
reviewing the role of independent directors in setting fees and
pressing for fuller disclosure requirements. SEC chairman Arthur
Levitt had this to say at an industry conference in May: ``Funds
whose directors forget for whom they represent won't be long for
the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Fees are always a contentious topic, and there is not even
agreement on whether they are rising or falling. Mutual fund assets
have quadrupled to $5 trillion this decade, offering chances for
economies of scale that critics say have not materialized.
Morningstar says the average expense ratio for an equity fund has
risen to 1.53 percent, or $1.53 per $100, from 1.25 percent, or
$1.25 per $100, in 1985. On the other hand, Kanon Bloch Carre, a
Boston consulting firm, says fees for all growth funds have
declined 5 percent in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever is right, it is the fund directors who must sign off on
these fees. While most investors know next to nothing about the
people who oversee their funds, the directors play a key role in
setting policies and, most important, negotiating the management
contract between shareholders and money management firms. As with
corporate boards, fund boards include company insiders, but by law
at least 40 percent of the fund boards must be independent
directors recruited from outside.
</P>
<P>
   Directors often sit on dozens or even hundreds of individual
fund boards within one fund company, a practice that has raised
questions about how independent directors _ who can easily make
$100,000 or more a year as part-timers _ really are. The industry
believes allowing directors to sit on multiple boards increases
their expertise and holds down costs; they say that directors set
their own salaries and cannot be fired by the companies.
</P>
<P>
   The recent spate of suits try to make a direct link between
``fee gouging and multiple directorships.'' In the Fidelity suit,
filed in October in US District Court in Boston, a New York
shareholder charges that directors serve on more than 200 boards
and receive ``significant compensation,'' frequently in excess of
$200,000 a year. The suit paints of picture of ``assembly-line''
board meetings that ``merely rubber-stamp'' Fidelity's proposals.
</P>
<P>
   The suit says fee gouging by Fidelity has been ``especially
dramatic.'' To quantify the claim, the suit says that Fidelity's
assets under management grew to $373 billion from $36 billion from
1985 to 1995; revenue grew to $4.3 billion from $388 million. Using
those numbers, the suit figures that revenues as a percentage of
assets under management grew to 1.146 percent from 1.085 percent in
that time. That kind of increase would have yielded Fidelity an
extra $228 million in compensation in 1995 alone, the suit says.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity has yet to file a response to the suit, but a
spokeswoman previously said the company would defend the suit
vigorously. Fidelity declined to comment Thursday on the suit or
its fees. A recent survey by Kanon Bloch Carre found Fidelity's
expenses were the sixth-lowest among 42 fund complexes.
</P>
<P>
   While the suits are all in federal court, the fund industry
appears to be trying to strike potential threats to the director
system on the state level. Both Massachusetts and Maryland acted
after a federal judge in May 1997 unexpectedly allowed a suit to
proceed after he found that the ``substantial remuneration''
directors received by sitting on multiple boards could call their
independence into question. The suit has since been dismissed on
different grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts legislation was designed to spell out that
outside directors continue to be considered ``independent'' even if
they serve on multiple boards. To challenge that independence,
shareholders must make ``an affirmative showing'' that the
directors' independence has been impaired by more than serving on
the boards, according to an analysis provided to legislators by the
House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Representative John H. Rogers (D-Norwood),
chairman of the Judiciary Committee, declined to say who requested
the proposed amendment. A Fidelity spokeswoman earlier told Mutual
Fund Market News, a trade publication, that the firm supported the
bill. Fidelity declined to comment to Boston Capital.
</P>
<P>
   While the Massachusetts bill attracted no attention, the similar
Maryland legislation was opposed by both plantiffs' attorneys and
organized labor, who complained the measure reduced shareholder
protections. T. Rowe Price cited the new provision, passed as an
amendment to a largely unrelated bill on the final day of the
Legislature's session in April, in its efforts to have the federal
suit against it dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, the Judiciary Committee synopsis supporting
the bill ends with a line that has been trotted out, in one form or
another, every time mutual fund legislation is considered: ``This
change would ensure that Massachusetts is not prejudiced when
investment companies are searching for a state to call their `legal
home.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
