<SLUG> BC-FANTASY-FOOTBALL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANTASY CAUSING BIG NIGHTMARES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - I dozed on the couch Monday night, watching the
wretched Giants flounder against the 49ers. My thoughts were filled
with fluttering passes and stumbling running backs, missed field
goals and blown coverages.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   As I drifted off, I thought about how all those bad teams had
turned my fantasy league into a disaster. How the Thursday night
game didn't include a single offensive player that anybody cared to
start on a fantasy team.
</P>
<P>
   Ick. Ptooey.
</P>
<P>
   And then I was dreaming. I sped down the field wide open, only
to have New York's Kent Graham throw the ball into triple coverage.
It bounced into the air, and was grabbed by Philadelphia
quarterback Koy Detmer, who broke into a premature celebration
dance before fumbling.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Swann scooped it up and started to run, only to pull up
lame and hop into a passing ambulance, driven by New Orleans
quarterback Kerry ``Tom'' Collins, who was immediately stopped by
the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a drinking problem,'' I could hear Collins
yelling as the ball rolled to Kansas City Coach Marty
Schottenheimer, who immediately subbed out Collins for Bam Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Morris grabbed the ball and stuffed it into his car trunk,
prompting St. Louis Coach Dick Vermeil to burst into tears.
Lawrence Phillips jogged by, his World League uniform glittering in
the fading twilight.
</P>
<P>
   In the gloaming, Derrick Thomas sprinted past, a face mask in
each hand. An angry mob of Chiefs fans chased him, brandishing
steaming brats and real tomahawks.
</P>
<P>
   I landed back on the field, only to see the New England Patriots
playing a game against nobody, scoring touchdown after touchdown,
as the distracted Buffalo Bills used grass and mud to build a
monument to Doug Flutie.
</P>
<P>
   A gaggle of officials wandered by, their white canes tapping out
a rhythm. They all carried two-headed quarters, and chanted, ``The
call was tails. The call was tails.''
</P>
<P>
   Boomer Esiason grabbed the ball and sprinted away, as Dan
Dierdorf called after him, ``You played some quarterback, didn't
you?''
</P>
<P>
   Boomer stopped, humbly scuffing the ground with his toe, ``Well,
shoot, I guess I did.''
</P>
<P>
   And then Chuck Bednarik blindsided him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That had to hurt,'' I heard Frank Gifford say, barely audible
in his plastic booth.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Berman grabbed me by the collar. ``You had the power to go
all the way home all the time. Just tap your heels, and say,
`There's no team like Denver. There's no team like Denver.' ''
</P>
<P>
   I jarred awake. Graham was throwing the ball out of the end
zone. All was right with the world.
</P>
<P>
   But the NFL still stinks on ice. &QL; 
Tip of the week
</P>
<P>
   A few playoff hints: Avoid quarterbacks who are playing in cold
weather. Though we in Arizona think of winter as a perpetual
70-degree day, it does get cold in other places, and that can gum
up a passing attack.
</P>
<P>
   Also, stick with your dependable starters. If those players were
good enough to get you to the playoffs, stay with them. Now is not
the time for experimentation.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, pay attention to overall records. Teams that
have everything clinched early may not play their starters for the
whole game. Keep that in mind. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Waiver wire
</P>
<P>
   I'd grab Packers wide receiver Bill Schroeder really quick.
Green Bay starters Antonio Freeman (broken jaw) and Robert Brooks
(hamstring) are ailing. With Indianapolis receiver Marvin Harrison
out for the year, Torrance Small's numbers should rise. Minnesota
running back Leroy Hoard should have some good numbers while Robert
Smith heals up from his sprained knee. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
One-hit wonder
</P>
<P>
   This week, it's Philadelphia receiver Jeff Graham, who scored
two touchdowns against Green Bay. Graham last crossed the goal line
during the Eisenhower Administration. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Muller can be reached at bill.muller(at)pni.com  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
