<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOES IT SEEM FAMILIAR? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It happened before, 19 years ago. A popular first
baseman finished a productive albeit short season for the Red Sox.
His contract was up. He was seeking a multiple-year deal. His agent
was a young attorney named Tom Reich.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Watson didn't especially want to bicker over terms. Yet, he
knew from experience that Boston general manager Haywood Sullivan
would do so.
</P>
<P>
   These were the Red Sox of the late Tom Yawkey. Who wouldn't want
to be in the same clubhouse with Hall of Famer Carl Yastrzemski,
Jim Rice, Dwight Evans, Butch Hobson, and Carlton Fisk? The 1979
Red Sox had posted a 91-69 record in the American League East but
finished a distant third behind Baltimore and Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Watson had been acquired in midseason from Houston, and
everything pointed to him re-signing with Boston. He had batted
.337 with 13 home runs and 53 RBIs in 84 games with the Sox. Fans
had voted him the Tenth Player Award. He was a gentleman, and his
teammates admired his professionalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed my time in Boston,'' Watson would say in later
years. ``The fans, the team, and the way I was accepted. But when
that season ended, I couldn't get the Red Sox to understand where I
was coming from.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I wanted just one offer. No bickering back and
forth. I told them to put their best offer on the table, and if it
was what I felt was fair, I would accept. They didn't believe me
and gave my agent a preliminary negotiating figure covering just
one year. I turned it down and signed a two-year deal with the
Yankees. I didn't have to bicker.''
</P>
<P>
   It would have been nice if someone had relayed that story to Dan
Duquette. Watson turned down the Red Sox in an era when Fenway Park
was known as a country club. The Sox had been one of the dominant
franchises in baseball in the '70s, but by 1981, they had lost
Fisk, Lynn, Burleson (and Watson) and were in a tailspin that would
not end until 1986. Only Rice and Evans survived the team's
self-destruction, which lasted until Sullivan passed the torch to
the ever-cheerful Lou Gorman.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 years from 1986-95 produced four division championships
and a future Hall of Famer in Roger Clemens. But you knew sooner or
later some player or agent would aggressively challenge the Red
Sox, no matter who represented management, to prove once again that
they belonged among baseball's elite clubs _ with the haves rather
than the have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox could have retained the services of Mo Vaughn _ as
they could have kept Watson _ had they decided as far back as 1995
to act with total commitment based on admittedly changing market
values. But they ignored the obvious and pretended that if
something was wrong, Gentle Tom Yawkey would come from his rooftop
office and somehow make things right.
</P>
<P>
   John Harrington is not Tom Yawkey, but Dan Duquette seems more
like Haywood Sullivan every day. He's stubborn but not dumb. He's
also fair, but nowadays it is the agents and players who dictate
the terms. If Duquette can't adjust, then he's no better than any
general manager of the past 30 years _ from Dick O'Connell to
Sullivan to Gorman. None of them achieved the ultimate goal of a
World Series title. All made mistakes along the way that were bad
enough to get them fired or forced into resignation. Duquette
should be next if he can't rebound from this mess.
</P>
<P>
   The mess didn't start with Duquette, although it's clear that
the day he agreed to pay pitcher Pedro Martinez $75 million with
Vaughn's future still in doubt ranks up there with Sullivan's bluff
being called.
</P>
<P>
   To their credit, O'Connell and Sullivan did develop one of the
best farm systems around, one that produced Fisk, Lynn, Rice,
Burleson, Evans, and Bill Lee.
</P>
<P>
   But after the death of Yawkey in 1976, the sale of the club a
year later to a group headed by Jean Yawkey, with Sullivan and
former trainer Buddy LeRoux as general partners, brought not only a
change in the operating chemistry, but also the realization that
the club had to win to remain out of debt. For a few years, the Sox
competed dollar for dollar. Suddenly, they fell behind.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan had played in the '50 and '60s and was used to dealing
with people from his own era. Dealing with agents was not his
favorite thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't blame the players one bit,'' Sullivan said in October
1979. ``They're seeking the best possible contracts. But I do know
you can't pay 25 players a half-million dollars apiece. No club
could survive that way. There is a limit to any deal, and we
reached it. It wasn't a matter of money. We are just one of four
clubs in all of baseball that is financially stable and that has no
debt service. We will fulfill the promises we made.''
</P>
<P>
   Those promises were to keep Fisk, Hobson, Lynn, and Burleson for
the 1980 season. But to retain profit margins and avoid huge
payrolls thereafter, Sullivan cleaned house. Hobson and Burleson
were traded to California in December 1980. Lynn was dealt there in
January. Fisk walked as a free agent in March, joining the White
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox went 59-49 in the strike-shortened 1981 season. They
didn't make it back to the playoff until 1986. By that time, Gorman
had replaced Sullivan as GM.
</P>
<P>
   For all of his success with the team, however, Gorman had
trouble maintaining the status quo. For the first 7-8 years of his
tenure, he was asked to avoid free agents, and he did. But a long
period of profit-making was about to end. Sox management didn't
fully realize it until it was almost too late.
</P>
<P>
   The farm system that had produced so magnificently ran dry.
Youngsters such as Phil Plantier and Carlos Quintana underachieved
or got hurt. In the winter of 1991, the Sox ended their
longstanding free agent boycott by signing Matt Young to a
three-year, $10 million contract despite his career record of
54-85. It was one of the worst signings in team history.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell, Sullivan, and Gorman all had something in common.
They were old-school GMs who operated with the philosophy that it
was a honor to wear a Red Sox uniform, and that, if nothing else,
was the reason for lower salaries. The strike of 1994 ended that
kind of thinking forever. When the amount of revenue available to
owners from sources other than attendance was revealed during
negotiations with the Players Association, players and their agents
set new goals _ and reached them easier than anyone dare imagined.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Clemens found out in 1996 when he heard Boston's
best offer, then went right out and found a better one, in Toronto.
In 1997, nobody thought any player was worth more than the $11.5
million the Braves paid Greg Maddux. Less than six months later,
the Sox topped that for Martinez. Funny how the marketplace
chances. Once, the Sox could have had Vaughn for $8 million-$9
million, easy. Now he will make $13.3 million in Anaheim, and there
won't be one word spoken about how it affects the future of the
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Don't blame this all on Duquette. He played the game carefully,
trying to avoid a bidding contest that you knew was going to happen
anyway after Mike Piazza signed with the Mets for $13 million.
Duquette works for Harrington, who is just as stubborn as Sullivan
and O'Connell.
</P>
<P>
   In the moment of truth, the Sox were used and abused by Reich &AMP;
Co., just as Sullivan was 19 years ago. Duquette's negotiating
style is to hang by the telephone, flipping out details and waiting
for an answer. Reich throws daggers at your heart. If one doesn't
draw blood, he throws another one.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox will find somebody. He won't be another Vaughn. The farm
system is there, and Duquette is supposed to know more about it
than any of his predecessors. But don't expect miracles.
</P>
<P>
   It has to hurt when a club admits it can't please a Mo Vaughn.
If you can appreciate what it means when a father cuts loose his
son, then you know all there is to know about what it is to see
Vaughn grow sour in the knowledge that everybody loves him but the
Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Some things you have to live with. Mo should do just fine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
