<SLUG> BC-CARDINAL-LAW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW UPBEAT ON 25TH ANNIVERSARY OF PRIESTHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As he prepares to celebrate 25 years as a bishop
Saturday, it would be hard to say say that Cardinal Bernard Law has
slowed down much.
</P>
<P>
   This week, he hosted the bishop of Tegucigalpa, Honduras to help
make sure that the devastation wrought by Hurricane Mitch wasn't
forgotten here. Then he dashed off to spend 24 hours with hundreds
of priests of the archdiocese of Boston talking about the future of
the local church.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday he was making plans to mark the anniversary of his
episcopacy this weekend. On Monday, he will fly to Cuba to preach
at the Havana Cathedral and give a speech to church activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the kind of person who likes to get a lot of things done _
and not today, but Thursday,'' says Law, 67, sitting at a large
wooden conference table inside the sprawling cardinal's residence
atop a small hill in Boton's Brighton section.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years ago, Law, who was born in Mexico and lived in
several Latin American countries before coming to the United States
to attend Harvard, was made bishop of Springfield-Cape Girardeau, a
sprawling diocese of under 50,000 Catholics in a southern corner of
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Law is the leader of more than 2 million Catholics across
greater Boston and one of the most influential voices in the Roman
Catholic Church in this country.
</P>
<P>
   He is a fiercely loyal ally of Pope John Paul II whose
unwavering and vocal defense of church teachings has brought
criticism from more liberal church voices.
</P>
<P>
   But through it, say supporters and foes, one trait has served
Law well _ an ability to disagree without being disagreeable. It
has proved especially valuable in one area that Law has made a a
top priority _ improving relations in the city among people of
diverse racial, ethnic, religious and economic lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to do that is not to be a bishop,'' said Law in a
wide-ranging interview. ``I didn't dream any of this up. Christ
did. I am very grateful for the great personal relationships that I
have with people who don't always agree with me and with whom I
don't always agree with.''
</P>
<P>
   This week's edition of the Pilot, the official archdiocesan
newspaper, is entirely dedicated to Law and includes tributes from
churchmen and churchwomen from across the world.
</P>
<P>
   It also includes complimentary commentaries from the Reverend
Diane Kessler, executive director of the Massachusetts Council of
Churches, an organization of Protestant denominations, and from
Leonard Zakim, executive director of the Anti-Defamation League of
New England.
</P>
<P>
   When he was first diagnosed with cancer, writes Zakim, one of
the first persons who called with words of solace and encouragement
was Law.
</P>
<P>
   More than 14 years after he was named to head the archdiocese,
Law says he still has the same enthusiasm for the job that he did
when first stepped inside the Cathedral of the Holy Cross on a
winter's day in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Even through the hard times _ having to close parishes,
confronting the explosive issue of clergy sexual abuse and
accusations that the church failed to properly deal with the issue,
and struggling with a dwindling number of priests _ Law says he
remains optimistic about the church's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``God knows I've had a lot of life experiences,'' says Law, 68.
``I've dealt with a lot of issues and there certainly wasn't a `how
to' book for bisihops that told you how to go through those things.
You do it on basis of experience, you consult with others, and then
you pray.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
