<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The economy added more jobs than
expected during November and the unemployment rate fell to 4.4
percent, the lowest level since May, as strength in services and
construction offset further job cuts in manufacturing. Workers'
average hourly earnings, a gauge of business costs, rose 0.2
percent, or 3 cents, in November, matching October's percentage
increase. Story will include a broader look at the recent wave of
layoffs. A second economic report issued this morning shows that
factory orders fell 1.6 percent in October, more than expected. By
Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:40 p.m., the industrial average was up
105 points and the Nasdaq index up 32 points. Elsewhere, prices
declined 0.4 percent in Tokyo and 0.8 percent in Hong Kong. They
were off 0.2 percent in Frankfurt, flat in London, up 0.8 percent
in Brazil and up 0.3 percent in Mexico. On the American debt
market, the long bond was down 9/32 point at midday, with the yield
at 5.02 percent. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-U.S. (Washington) _ Oskar Lafontaine, the German finance
minister, comes to Washington. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBLIC-APPOINT (Undated) _ Republic Industries hires a top
Sears executive, John Costello, as its president in an effort to
boost its marketing and brand strategy as it attempts to become the
world's biggest car retailer.
</P>
