<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVING MONEY INTO IRA WOULD BROADEN OPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I'm 41 and I changed jobs about seven years ago. I currently
have two 401(k) accounts, each worth about $85,000. I'm looking to
retire at age 65. Up until recently, both of the 401(k)s were doing
pretty well, but with current market conditions, I'm wondering how
I should be allocating my funds. In the 401(k) with my current
employer, I have $60,000 in T. Rowe Price Equity Index 500 fund and
the balance in the T. Rowe Price Value fund. The 401(k) from the
previous employer is with Fidelity and has $45,000 in Fidelity
Equity Income II and the rest in Spartan U.S. Equity Index fund. I
contribute about $6,000 a year to the current 401(k). I no longer
contribute to the Fidelity account. Should I retain it or roll it
over into the Price account? Do I have the right mix of funds? What
do you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   P.O., Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't think the state of the current market is a good cause
for a change in portfolio allocations, but I do think that you
should be more broadly diversified, whatever the market condition.
Of the four funds you're holding, three are large-cap stock funds,
the exception being T. Rowe Price Value, which holds a mid-cap
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   In your letter, you list the various options available in the
two 401(k) plans. My suggestion would be to provide yourself with
an unlimited menu of options by moving the money that's now in the
old 401(k) at Fidelity to a rollover IRA account. You could stay
with Fidelity through this move, and then avail yourself of all
Fidelity's investment options.
</P>
<P>
   Broadly speaking, I suggest you retain half of your total
savings in the large-cap market sector, dividing the balance among
international, mid-cap, small-cap and health care positions. You
would need to make no change in the holdings of the current 401(k)
with Price. If you chose Fidelity for the rollover IRA, you could
then put $25,000 in Fidelity Equity Income II and create three
positions of $20,000 each -- in Fidelity Select Health Care,
Fidelity Overseas, and Fidelity Low-Priced Stock.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, to maintain the portfolio balance, you should alter the
allocation of your ongoing contributions to the current 401(k) with
T. Rowe Price. I suggest that you direct that 50 percent of the
contributions go to the Price Equity Index 500 fund and the balance
be evenly divided among Price's Value, International Stock, and
Small-Cap Value funds.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, if you maintain savings at the current rate and if
you achieve average annual returns of 10 percent from your
retirement portfolio, the accounts would have a value of $2,426,789
by the time you are 65 years old.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 49 and self-employed. I have nothing in place for
retirement and no savings other than $18,000 invested in Vanguard
Windsor II fund and $180,000 in Janus fund. In my mind, this is my
retirement pool. I will also be eligible for Social Security
benefits. I have been adding about $2,000 a month to these funds,
and I can continue this until September of next year, when the
first of my four children goes to college. I then will have a child
in college for each of the next 12 years, so I will stop the $2,000
contributions during that time. Assuming I will not be able to add
much to my present savings, do you recommend any change? I expect
to retire in about 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   K.N., Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. First of all, you'll want to read the letter above, because
your situation is much like P.O.'s -- only moreso. You have 100
percent of your holdings in large-cap stocks, and the fact that the
Windsor II portfolio is value-oriented doesn't give me much
comfort. I suggest you reduce your reliance on the large caps to a
maximum of 60 percent of the portfolio, and I would be happier if
it were 50 percent. That's particularly so since you're a few years
P.O's senior, and should want to moderate risk. If you follow that
line of thinking, you might go further still, putting 50 percent in
large caps, 10 percent in each of the smaller market sectors
outlined to P.O., and finishing with a final 10 percent in a solid
balanced fund, of which Janus Balanced and Vanguard Balanced Index
funds are good examples.
</P>
<P>
   Second, unless you left something out, it appears all of this
money is in taxable accounts. If that's the case, I suggest you
begin the process of moving money into tax- deferred accounts. As a
self-employed person, you could establish a SEP-IRA or a Keogh
retirement savings plan that would defer taxes on the portfolio
accumulation until after the funds are withdrawn in retirement.
Another alternative, if you qualify, would be to move the
maximum.$2,000 a year into Roth IRA accounts. If you took the
SEP-IRA or Keogh alternatives, it would reduce your current tax
liability; if you went with the Roth, it would have no effect on
current taxes, but all the money would be tax-free when withdrawn
in retirement. The point is that as long as you have the earnings
to qualify for such plans, you can make the contributions -- the
funds can be withdrawn from these taxable accounts and then
reinvested in the same holdings, but now having a tax-deferred
status.
</P>
<P>
   Why is this important? Well, if you follow the plan you outline,
adding $2,000 a month for nine months and then leaving the pool to
grow with no contributions for another 171 months, assuming average
10 percent annual growth the accumulation would be $900,665.
</P>
<P>
   In the final year of this accumulation, the internal growth
would have grown to about $80,000, and such growth is likely to
cause some fairly hefty tax bills -- perhaps hefty enough that at
some point you'd find you had to invade the principal to satisfy
our mutual Uncle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 39 years old and my wife is 42 and we have children aged
three years and six years. We recently sold our house and cash, and
we have the $150,000 proceeds of that transaction. Because of plans
to relocate to Israel in a year or two, we are not sure what type
of investment is best for us now and for the future. What do you
suggest? M.I., Hillsborough, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I suggest extreme caution. Certainly with such a short
investment time frame, you don't even want to think about stocks or
high-yield bonds or anything that provides the prospect of
substantial returns. I'll suggest four options, although I think
the risks associated with one of them probably outweigh the
potential for gains. The slowest track would be a money market
fund. I called Vanguard to get representative yields from various
fixed-income funds, but you can find similar funds and similar
yields at most major mutual fund families.
</P>
<P>
   As this is written, Vanguard's Prime Money Market fund provides
a yield of 4.98 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping from the very slow track to the slow track, Vanguard's
Short-Term Corporate Bond fund offered a 5.84 percent yield. And
the fastest mover in this slow race is Vanguard GNMA, with a 6.52
percent yield. But to pick up those 68 basis points of interest (a
basis point is one one-hundredth of one percent), you are moving
from short- term investments into the intermediate term, and
assuming the attendant risk. For my money, the 5.84 percent of the
short-term bond fund looks like the best choice of these three.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you wanted to make things simpler still and get
federal insurance on your investment to boot, you could shop around
for the best CD rate available. As this is written, the nation's
best rate on a one-year CD was 5.5 percent. You can check in the
business pages of the New York Times to get the highest rate
currently offered among the nation's banks and the name of the
institution offering it. The advantage of a CD over the short-term
bond fund is not, in my mind, a question of risk but the fact that
with the CD you will have your rate locked in. You could then asses
your situation after the year's up, deciding whether to reinvest
for another year, for six months, or whatever seems best at that
time. But remember, if you go for a one-year CD and then suddenly
decide that you want to make your move to Israel in nine months,
you'll face a premature withdrawal penalty which will probably more
than wipe out any advantage you may have achieved over the money
market or short-term bond fund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
