A3308 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-HARD-CORE-BOS &LR;      12-04 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-HARD-CORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSE, EDGY `LOGO' HAS UNSCRIPTED FEEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no avoiding the fact that ``Hard Core Logo'' will invite
comparisons to ``This Is Spinal Tap.'' Like that classic 1984
mockumentary, this film follows the on-the-road exploits of a
fictional rock band well past its prime, but just too stubborn and
stupid to know it. Like the boys of Spinal Tap, the members of Hard
Core Logo love the rock 'n' roll life even if it no longer loves
them back.
</P>
<P>
   But any resemblances between the films pretty much ends there.
Whereas ``Spinal Tap'' was a satire, a jokey send-up of heavy metal
and its aging practitioners, ``Hard Core Logo'' is a far edgier
film, tense and tragic in its depiction of a regrouped punk band
spiraling dangerously out of control.
</P>
<P>
   The film takes its title from the name of the band, a hardcore
punk quartet featuring singer-ringmaster Joe Dick (Hugh Dillon),
lead guitarist Billy Tallent (Callum Keith Rennie), bassist John
Oxenberger (John Pyper-Ferguson), and drummer Pipefitter (Bernie
Coulson). They formed in Canada in 1978, played 1,000 shows,
released seven albums, and attracted a small but devoted following
before finally burning out in 1991. After years in small clubs, the
band was once on the brink of breaking through and signing a major
label deal. But Joe scotched the whole shebang when during a show
he jumped on a table and relieved himself in a record executive's
gin and tonic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Hey, see if you can sell that, you corporate
weasel,' '' recalls the bearish, drug-pumped Pipefitter. ``Talk
about game over!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally,'' deadpans Joe, ``you had to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   But that missed opportunity was a bitter pill for the other
members, especially the most ambitious, Billy, the band's pretty
boy. Joe, who won't surrender his ``down the republic'' punk poses,
condemns Billy's craving for mainstream success and magazine
covers. Says Joe, ``Billy just wants the models and the limousines,
and I'm happy with the hookers and taxicabs.''
</P>
<P>
   The lingering enmity between Joe and Billy should be reason
enough to keep the band permanently split. But the band reunites
for an ill-fated final tour, fueled by the success of a benefit
concert for their mentor, Bucky Haight (Julian Richings), who lost
a leg (or maybe two) after he was shot, by a possible stalker. Joe,
who hasn't done much since the band imploded, is the most eager for
the reunion. Billy isn't too keen on it, since he has his eyes on a
bigger prize _ becoming a member of a slick Los Angeles band,
Jenifur. John and Pipefitter hitch up for the tour, but John is
probably the most ambivalent. The last place John, a sweet-natured
former mental patient, needs to be is on the road living the life
that drove him into an asylum in the first place. Pipefitter is the
archetypal let-the-good-times-roll drummer _ he's a party waiting
to happen, and as dumb as a box of rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Onstage, the band is all spit, cuss words, and cigarettes,
packing as much snarl and macho stupidity as they can into their
slash-and-burn anthems. Offstage, they're a mess. Joe is so tweaked
on cocaine he can barely sleep, and he fights endlessly with Billy.
By the time, John loses his much-needed antipsychotic medication,
the tour is already speeding toward a violent end.
</P>
<P>
   Director Bruce McDonald has a keen eye for life on the road _
the lousy diners, the crappy tour bus with rotted floorboards, the
petty jealousies between members that often erupt. This is the kind
of film where one can forget the story is fiction; at times the
dialogue is so harshly real, it seems unscripted. What laughs there
are come mixed with chunks of ground glass. Uncompromising, this is
an arresting look at rock's unchecked excesses, and the sad
futility in trying to maintain the stance of angry young men as one
moves reluctantly toward middle age.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
