<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3309 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PSYCHO-FILM-REVIEW-HN     12-04 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSYCHO-FILM-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMITATION MAKES THE ORIGINAL `PSYCHO' ALL THE BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: With PSCYHO-CHART)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE BARNES  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As we did with ``Titanic,'' we know for certain what happens in
``Psycho.''
</P>
<P>
   The boat sinks. The blonde gets it in the shower because Norman
Bates has a problem with his mother.
</P>
<P>
   No mystery there.
</P>
<P>
   What is genuinely puzzling is the reaction of film fans _
ranging from up-arched eyebrows to shock, genuine shock! _ to the
news that the new version of ``Psycho'' is a scrupulous recreation
of Alfred Hitchcock's 1960 original.
</P>
<P>
   Gus Van Sant, director of ``Good Will Hunting'' and ``Drugstore
Cowboy,'' has said that when making the new ``Psycho'' he tried to
replicate Hitchcock's film, shot by shot, line by line, adding only
different actors, color film and more gore to the shower slaughter.
Otherwise, according to Van Sant, his movie is a homage to
Hitchcock, a literal reproduction.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are they, crazy?'' wondered Entertainment Weekly
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meddling,'' huffed a Los Angeles critic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arrogance,'' snorted another.
</P>
<P>
   Temper, temper. It's a movie, people. If Van Sant's ``Psycho''
is only half as good as Hitchcock's, it will still be worth seeing
_ superior entertainment to ``Psycho'' spawn ``I Still Know What
You Did Last Summer'' and ``Urban Legend.'' And if the new movie is
truly dreadful, for whatever reason, that won't diminish the
greatness of Hitchcock's achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a flop of a remake, especially one that uses the exact
elements of the first picture, will only reinforce the genius of
Hitchcock and his movie's ability to scare the heck out of us even
after four decades.
</P>
<P>
   Good movies last a lifetime in memory; bad movies last a couple
of hours, and then you forget about them. Ten years from now, it's
possible that ``Who played the lead roles in the 1998 remake of
`Psycho'?'' will be an obscure trivia question (answer: Anne Heche
and Vince Vaughn), while many people will know Janet Leigh was on
the receiving end of Anthony Perkins' knife in the Hitchcock film.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the pre-release ruckus about Van Sant's movie unspools
from the fact that critics weren't allowed to see it in advance.
The director chose to follow Hitchcock's example there, too: Like
the master 38 years ago, Van Sant refused to give reviewers an
early peek at his movie.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to compare, contrast, congratulate or crucify the new
film, the entertainment press instead attacked Van Sant for his
method. Some have suggested that remaking a movie shot by shot _
filming scenes on Hitchcock's original six-week schedule, requiring
actors to deliver their speeches at the same speed as their
predecessors _ is no different than retyping a great novel.
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense. Art is forever being remade. Copying successful past
performances is standard practice in music and dance. Great
symphonies by Mozart and Beethoven have been performed millions of
times, with many interpretations, for example.
</P>
<P>
   There are orchestras that perform Baroque music on period
instruments, the goal being to recreate the composition exactly as
it sounded when it was written. And the New York City Ballet
regularly remounts productions by having dancers precisely
reproduce choreography created decades ago by George Balanchine and
Jerome Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   What Van Sant is attempting is new for cinema, however, and
that's what makes it an audacious choice. The director's most
frequent explanation for filming his new ``Psycho'' as he did is,
``Because it's never been done before,'' which makes him sound like
a mountain climber looking at Everest and saying, ``Because it's
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Sant is being disingenuous. He's too intelligent, and
varied, a director to settle for a showoff stunt like merely
copying Hitchcock. He presumably was drawn to the material by a
reverence for Hitchcock, of course, but also by his affection for
oddballs and outcasts. From his first picture, the grimily
beautiful, emotionally deep ``Mala Noche,'' a black-and-white gay
love story he made for $25,000 in 1986, right up to the big-budget,
heterosexual wholesomeness of ``Good Will Hunting,'' Van Sant
identifies with outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   You don't get less mainstream than Norman Bates, a creepy,
Oedipal wacko in a junky motel.
</P>
<P>
   What's new for Van Sant in ``Psycho'' is a movie that requires
audience-manipulating horror. (His ``Even Cowgirls Get the Blues''
was horrible, but in another sense of the word.) Hitchcock, a far
superior technician than Van Sant, used his timing and talents to
torture audiences, sicken them with suspense. Van Sant is too
sympathetic, to audiences and characters, to apply the thumbscrews
of dread as nastily as Hitchcock did; the closest he gets is the
wicked black comedy of ``To Die For.''
</P>
<P>
   Copying Hitchcock exactly may be the best way to introduce a
great film to new audiences. Moviegoers have a prejudice against
black-and-white pictures, against old movies, against unfamiliar
actors. Case in point: Orson Welles' ``Touch of Evil,'' the recent
40th-anniversary rerelease, which hardly anyone went to see.
</P>
<P>
   The new ``Psycho'' is in color, has familiar actors and surely
will be scary. There's a crazy guy, a knife, a pretty girl. Sounds
like every other teen-shriek movie. But with the combined talents
of Hitchcock and Van Sant, it won't be. That much is for certain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-04-98 1350EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
