<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3311 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TRUTH-BOS &LR;      12-04 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TRUTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXORCISING FAMILY DEMONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN CLEGG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
TRUTH COMES IN BLOWS 
A Memoir 
By Ted Solotaroff 
Norton, 285 pp., $23.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although Ted Solotaroff is a verifiable success as a critic and
editor, his boyhood memories and visions of the hard life in
Elizabeth, N.J., don't simply haunt _ they inhabit. His father, in
particular, seems to sit inside him like a bitter seed, greedily
sapping resources and sprouting at the most inopportune times.
Founder of the New American Review and author of ``A Few Good
Voices in My Head,'' Solotaroff takes on his past, pathologies and
all, in a humane memoir that seems destined to be the first of a
series.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, this is no salacious tell-all. It is more Edmund
Wilson (as in ``The Fifties'') than Andrew Morton (as in ``Diana:
Her True Story''). Enriched by Solotaroff's sharp cultural
analysis, ``Truth Comes in Blows'' charts the cost of the
Depression and the rise of the postwar middle class through the
story of one family's struggle to win a psychic truce.
</P>
<P>
   Solotaroff begins at the end, with his father's noisy, miserable
last years. The two reconnect, with a momentary ``sweet rapport''
that rapidly dissolves. But the son can't abandon the father; the
writerly impulse takes over and the questions fall into place about
this ``self-made and self-unmade'' businessman. Giving the eulogy
at his father's funeral, Solotaroff wonders, ``Who was this man
who, even in death, could play my spirit like a pipe? How had the
holes been put in that he'd fingered? How had I managed to keep him
from breaking it, as he had tried to do?''
</P>
<P>
   From age 4 on, Solotaroff felt torn in two by the opposing
forces at home. If he was Little Benny, the boy who looked like his
father and hungered for attention, he was also a Weiss boy, scion
of his mother's creative, intellectual clan. Both mother and son
are subject to physical and emotional pummeling at home. Young Ted
never loses his spunk or capacity for outrage, but Rose frays badly
and descends into a state of permanent apology.
</P>
<P>
   At rare moments, a happy memory gleams through. On Sundays, Ted
tags along while his father plays paddle ball at the YMHA. He puts
away his fear and feels, finally, like a son in the intimacy of the
steam room. ``With a father who seemed proud of me and at one with
those beefy, half-naked, wisecracking Jewish men in their prime,
just like my uncles at Cream Ridge, I was grounded in what unity I
had between being my father's son and my mother's, between Little
Benny, the rough-and-tough wise guy, and the Weiss boy, who didn't
cry and always kept his head up.''
</P>
<P>
   Above all, there is The Shop. Ben Solotaroff is a glass
contractor, who works nights and weekends to pull the family out of
the industrial flats of Elizabeth to the more suburban, Gentile
end, where the sky isn't filled with smoke and where deep woods and
farmland begin. The Depression rages, but the family is able to
stay afloat. Solotaroff hates the work, however, and indeed, his
father seems to have pressed him into bondage early on. ``I knew by
now that none of this was for me _ not the glass business, not
Elizabeth, certainly not working with him. I hated this Shop that
had already kept me from my rightful life, and hated even more the
diminished, squelched sense of myself I often still had when I was
around him.''
</P>
<P>
   In suburban Elmora, Ted realizes he is an outsider in part
because he is Jewish. He recounts the rawest anti-Semitism and
wrestles with his identity throughout the book, pledging a Jewish
fraternity in high school and going to shul with his mother but
resolving to get a nose job. ``The great project that virtually
every one of my friends . . . shared was to become ever more
American to ourselves as well as to the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of that American identity came through literature, and
Solotaroff realized early on that he could transport himself by
reading. Books carry him through a checkered academic career and a
benighted tour in the Navy. But he seems destined to be forever
split in twos: the athlete and intellectual, the whoring sailor who
reads Thomas Wolfe, the Jew proud of his Zionist grandfather but
shamed by his own swarthy skin and unruly hair.
</P>
<P>
   Solotaroff makes much of the hash of his life, however, because
he maintains an elegant distance from it in the writing. He evokes
a strong sense of place and time, and has an eye for the internal
workings of character. His parents divorce and he heads to college
in Ann Arbor, Mich. ``Though I didn't know of William James's
concept at the time, I was bent on becoming one of the
twice-born,'' he writes toward the end of the book. He is also
headed for a life of the intellect, far from The Shop. Why, then,
does he keep one of his father's glass cutters on his desk, in a
jar that holds pens, pencils, and other tools of the editor's
trade? Perhaps it is because he recognizes how inextricable the
child and the father are. Solotaroff shows that it can be
satisfying to march deeply into the labyrinth and, finally, bag the
Minotaur.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
