<HEADLINE>
`PSYCHO' VS. `PSYCHO' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Old ``Psycho'' released: 1960
</P>
<P>
   Director: Alfred Hitchcock
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Janet Leigh, Anthony Perkins
</P>
<P>
   Writer: Joseph Stefano, based on Robert Bloch novel
</P>
<P>
   Music by: Bernard Herrmann
</P>
<P>
   Color: No
</P>
<P>
   Significance: Most sexual, violent film made in Hollywood up to
that point; influenced generations of film directors, motel guests,
showers
</P>
<P>
   Quote: The movie lets audiences ``dip a toe in the cold waters
of fear.'' _ Alfred Hitchcock. ``A spectacle of stomach-churning
horror.'' _ Time magazine, June 27, 1960.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New ``Psycho'' released: 1998
</P>
<P>
   Director: Gus Van Sant
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Anne Heche, Vince Vaughn
</P>
<P>
   Writer: Joseph Stefano, slightly modifying his original
screenplay
</P>
<P>
   Music by: Danny Elfman (``Batman''), from Bernard Herrmann's
original score
</P>
<P>
   Color: Yes
</P>
<P>
   Significance: First ever shot-by-shot remake of a film. Van Sant
says 95 percent of new picture is exactly like old; changes include
minor script updates and the opening scene, shot as Hitchcock
wanted but was unable to do for original
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``There (is) a whole generation of moviegoers who haven't
seen the original. I thought this was a way of popularizing a
classic, a way I'd never seen done before. It was like staging a
contemporary production of a play while remaining true to the
original.'' _ Gus Van Sant.
</P>
</TEXT>
