<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUNISH CRIMES, NOT THOUGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Maybe the anonymous guy who called me the other
day had a license to practice law.
</P>
<P>
   He was talking about Rudolph Berry and William Hines, the
20-year-old white guys from the Albany suburb of Rotterdam accused
of wounding a city woman with a rifle because she had the nerve to
be black. These rocket scientists went to Rotterdam's Schalmont
High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this demonstrates,'' the caller said, ``is that Schalmont
is crummy at teaching marksmanship.''
</P>
<P>
   That was either a very bad joke or a clever legal defense _
probably a defense, actually. That same day, the lawyer for these
two, Gaspar Castillo, was saying that this was all a prank gone
tragically awry _ that these good-hearted, high-spirited young men
aren't bigots and had never meant to hurt anybody.
</P>
<P>
   OK, sure, this is America, and everybody is innocent until a
jury says otherwise. And, OK, I didn't see this happen with my own
eyes. I therefore have no right to an opinion on what did or did
not happen in this incident.
</P>
<P>
   But let's assume that the Albany police are right. Let's assume
that these two white knuckle-draggers from a virtually all-white
suburb decided it would be cool to gun down a black person. And
let's assume that's what they were up to in Albany's poor, largely
black Arbor Hill neighborhood at 4 a.m. Let's assume, too, that
they really were the guys who came roaring by in a 7-year-old red
Mustang and pumped a 9 mm-bullet into the neck of Sonia Thompson,
38.
</P>
<P>
   Just what do you do with people like that?
</P>
<P>
   The Albany police have charged them with a long string of
serious felonies. If convicted, they'll go to prison for a long
time. Since most prisons have a 70-plus percent minority
population, these guys undoubtedly will meet some fascinating new
friends.
</P>
<P>
   But, for some people, that's not enough for a crime like this.
For some people, creeps who do things like this should be punished
not just for what they did but for what motivated them to do it in
the first place. Ann Pope, for example, runs the Albany NAACP. She
said that New York needs a bias law that would increase the penalty
for any crime committed because of the race, religion or sexual
orientation of the victim.
</P>
<P>
   New York Gov. George Pataki is for that. New York is one of only
11 states without such a law. The obstacle here is Joe Bruno, the
state Senate majority leader. He's nervous about punishing people
for what they think.
</P>
<P>
   And, basically, he's right. Here's the ugly truth: As an
American, you have a constitutional right to be a racist. You have
a right to be a homophobe. You have a right to be a sexist and an
anti-semite, too. You have a right to despise Catholics, Baptists,
atheists or sun-worshipers. You have a right to hate anybody you
want for whatever reason might strike your fancy. Your thoughts are
your business, not the government's.
</P>
<P>
   What you don't have a right to do is commit violence. And any
judge sentencing any body for violence or any other crime has both
a right and a duty to take the defendant's mindset into account _
and give that bias-motivated criminal the maximum sentence the law
allows on the very first offense. That's the way to handle this
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI says that roughly 9,500 hate crimes a year are committed
in this nation of 260 million souls. African-Americans are the
likeliest victims. But fully 40 percent of racially motivated
murders are committed by blacks, who are only 12 percent of the
population.
</P>
<P>
   Bias crime laws cut both ways, and a good many people pushing
for this in New York might not like the way they would end up
working. Bruno has the right idea. Punish the crime. Then let the
criminals explain their thinking to their fellow inmates.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
