<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CHRISTMAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTMAS RECORDINGS HAVE COME OF AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's Christmas in July when most artists make their holiday
albums. When Mariah Carey made hers a few years ago, she set up a
Christmas tree in the studio to simulate the winter season. Many
artists do the same thing to get in the mood, though Celine Dion
said this past summer that she didn't need such trimmings for her
new holiday CD because ``the songs are in my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Each singer has a different approach, but one thing is certain:
More and more are making holiday CDs.
</P>
<P>
   The payback can be huge _ witness platinum sales for seasonal
discs by Carey, Neil Diamond, and Gloria Estefan in recent years _
but the reasons go beyond sales.
</P>
<P>
   A holiday album allows an artist to bond with fans in ways not
possible with a typical studio CD. While it can be a corny path to
take, more are accepting the challenge and are transcending the
usual Christmas carols to add original compositions that make such
records must-buys for fans.
</P>
<P>
   In Dion's excellent new CD, ``These Are Special Times,'' she has
a duet with opera sensation Andrea Bocelli on an original tune,
``The Prayer,'' and another with R. Kelly on ``I'm Your Angel.''
And Brian McKnight's fine new ``Bethlehem'' CD has a soulful duet
with Boyz II Men, ``Let It Snow '98,'' with the zanily romantic
line: ``Pretend like I'm the tree and you're the star.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, the Christmas album has come of age, as artists often
add contemporary interpretations. They no longer just cover such
traditional holiday classics as ``O Come All Ye Faithful,'' ``O
Holy Night,'' or ``The Christmas Song (Chestnuts Roasting on an
Open Fire).'' Many still do those tunes, but the emphasis is on
writing new material or hiring a song doctor to do it, as Dion did
in having Diane Warren pen the ballad ``These Are the Special
Times,'' from which her album title was derived.
</P>
<P>
   This year's crop of holiday albums, while more plentiful, still
varies dramatically in quality. There are some clunkers, notably
Shawn Colvin's ``Holiday Songs and Lullabies.'' Colvin may have won
two Grammy awards last year, but her new album is far more somber
than need be. She made it during the ``scorching'' summer months in
Austin, Tex., as (as she writes in the liner notes), while she was
pregnant. But that doesn't explain the surprisingly lugubrious
results. If you're looking for a festive Christmas album, this
isn't it.
</P>
<P>
   Colvin starts with the traditional ``In the Bleak Mid-Winter,''
and that, unfortunately, sets the tone. She artfully experiments
with string and horn sections _ rather than playing her trademark
acoustic guitar _ and the music gets bogged down in a ponderous
stew. There's an unusual and unsatisfying arrangement of ``Silent
Night,'' with flugelhorn and French horn and trombone. The best
song is ``Little Road to Bethlehem,'' with some pedal steel guitar
and some much-needed pep.
</P>
<P>
   Other disappoinments are Etta James's ``12 Songs of Christmas''
(her versions of standard carols are pedestrian except for a
passionate ``O Holy Night'') and the Windham Hill compilation ``The
Colors of Christmas.'' It is an adult soul-schlock compilation
featuring Peabo Bryson, Sheena Easton, Jeffrey Osborne, Philip
Bailey, Oleta Adams, Roberta Flack, and Melissa Manchester. The
cast sounds interesting, but the music is absurdly gooey for the
most part _ and only Bailey and Flack survive the goo fest. Bailey
achieves a marvelous, high-tenor reach on ``Silent Night,'' while
Flack is her hypnotic self on ``O Come All Ye Faithful.''
</P>
<P>
   In the soul genre, the much better albums are McKnight's
``Bethlehem'' and the Jermaine Dupri-conceived ``12 Soulful Nights
of Christmas.'' McKnight writes many of his own songs, from the
Stevie Wonder-influenced ``Christmas Time Is Here'' to the
flamenco-influenced ``Bethlehem Tonight,'' with McKnight singing
``As sure as the stars are in the sky / The newborn king was born
in Bethlehem.'' He also colorfully embellishes the traditional
``First Noel'' and has Mrs. Nat King Cole come in for a spoken-word
message about the holidays: ``I hope you'll remember your family .
. . it's just so important.'' It's more stately than corny.
</P>
<P>
   Dupri served as executive producer on Motown's ``12 Soulful
Nights of Christmas,'' which finds multiple artists writing their
own material, along with covering some standards. Highlights
include Faith Evans's softly intoned ``A Christmas Lullabye,''
Gerald Levert's ``Christmas Without My Girlfriend'' (``I don't want
no expensive presents / I don't want no Christmas without my
girlfriend''), Chaka Khan's sultry ``Christmas Only Once a Year,''
and Jagged Edge's hip-hoppy ``This Christmas,'' with the yearning
line ``All I want this Christmas is to keep your body warm.'' It's
a long way from ``O Holy Night,'' but it works since it's genuine.
</P>
<P>
   Two offbeat records are worth noting. One is Shirley Caesar's
``Christmas with Shirley Caesar,'' in which her gospel roots make
for a sometimes disconcertingly intense journey through ``Hark the
Herald Angels Sing'' and ``We Three Kings of Orient Are,'' though
she excels on the operatic ``Ave Maria'' and a modern,
drum-programmed arrangement of ``Little Drummer Boy.''
Trans-Siberian Orchestra's ``The Christmas Attic'' has a symphonic
feel echoing Emerson, Lake &AMP; Palmer and other dinosaur-pomp acts.
Some of it is cliched, but some is quite affecting in a rock-opera
style that uses rotating singers, such as Luxx's Katrina Chester.
</P>
<P>
   For young listeners, the choice is N-Sync's ``Home for
Christmas,'' which is better than many people might expect. There
are pillowy lyrics and sugary, Beach Boys-like harmonies, but the
teen group does an inventive a cappella arrangement of ``O Holy
Night'' and holds its own elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The season's standout, though, is Celine Dion's new disc. Not
only does she perform a shimmering duet with Bocelli, but she has
another with R. Kelly on ``I'm Your Angel,'' which he wrote. Dion
has become a household name since scoring big on the ``Titanic''
soundtrack and continues to release work of high quality. She does
a dynamic version of ``O Holy Night,'' along with a songbird-level
treatment of ``Ave Maria'' and a pretty, acoustic-driven look at
Bryan Adams's poppy ``Another Year Has Gone By.''
</P>
<P>
   The red-hot Dion also regales listeners with a tasteful cover of
John Lennon and Yoko Ono's ``Happy Xmas (War Is Over).'' She wishes
people a happy new year in the song and adds, ``Let's hope it's a
good one without any fear.'' She even does the Elvis
Presley-identified ``Blue Christmas'' and invites her 13
Montreal-bred siblings to sing Jose Feliciano's ``Feliz Navidad.''
It's gushy, but the family spirit makes this a keeper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
