<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-LIGHTS-$ADV06-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECK THE HALLS, BUT BE WARY IN THE PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Dec. 6)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Festive lighting adds so much to the home around
the holidays. But care should be used when buying holiday
electrical lights.
</P>
<P>
   Last year there was a major national recall of more than 1.5
million sets of curtain-style, indoor/outdoor holiday lights, more
commonly known as icicle lights.
</P>
<P>
   But Yolanda Fultz-Morris, spokeswoman for the U.S. Consumer
Product Safety Commission, said there is no recall that the
commission is aware of so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's recall was a result of the problem with the splice
connector, where hot wires could come detached and cause a fire.
</P>
<P>
   According to Underwriters Laboratories (UL), unauthorized
holographic UL labels, located on each string near the plug, with
the following numbers identify the lights with splice connectors
that were recalled: E115759; E126258; E127357; E127522; E48723;
E64444; E65770; E97593.
</P>
<P>
   Curtain-style lights without splice connectors were not involved
in this recall.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers with questions about the lights that were recalled
should call or visit the retail store where they purchased the
lights, or contact CPSC's toll-free hot line at 800-638-2772.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
