<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-PREVIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREVIN LOOKS BACK ON HIS PIANO CONCERTO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Andre Previn always knew he was going to be some kind of
musician, but what kind of musician remained unclear for a very
long time _ even after he achieved celebrity in such diverse fields
as film music, jazz piano, and orchestral conducting.
</P>
<P>
   Previn is now 69, and his ultimate reputation may rest on the
most lasting musical achievement, composition. He has composed for
most of his life, but the piece that established him as a composer,
a music-theater collaboration with playwright Tom Stoppard, ``Every
Good Boy Deserves Favor,'' wasn't written until 1977. Only this
year did Previn produce his first opera, ``A Streetcar Named
Desire,'' which was premiered in San Francisco in September.
</P>
<P>
   This week's Boston Symphony programs bring the local premiere of
the Piano Concerto Previn wrote for Vladimir Ashkenazy in 1984-85,
a work that followed earlier concertos for horn and guitar. Previn
was originally supposed to conduct the Boston performances with
pianist Horacio Gutierrez, but withdrew when he was summoned to
Washington, D.C., where he will receive the Kennedy Center Honors
Saturday (12/5). Washington was kind enough to surrender its own
music director, Leonard Slatkin, for a week so that he could
conduct in Previn's place.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Previn spoke by telephone from his home in
New York about his Piano Concerto before setting out to conduct a
concert by the New York Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   The work obviously has its roots in his lifelong experience of
the piano. ``I wasn't a child prodigy, but a kid who played the
piano,'' Previn says. ``I played well, I understand, but my parents
were very smart and good. They did not allow me to perform in
public, so I didn't give any performances as a child, and I am
still very grateful for that. As an absolute child, I went to the
conservatory in Berlin, where I worked with a man called Professor
Breithaupt. This is no longer a name to be reckoned with, but
George Szell was astounded when I told him who I had studied with.
`He must have been a hundred years old,' Szell exclaimed, and he
may have been. Later on in Paris I had a few lessons in theory and
improvisation with the organist Marcel Dupre. I don't know how
seriously I took it all at the time. I always knew I'd wind up
being a musician, but the question was what kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Previn says he worked very hard at the piano and that an
important part of his musical education came from playing duets
with his father. ``He was a solicitor and an amateur pianist who
believed in my being a musician as opposed to being a pianist. He
had a huge collection of all the great symphonic and chamber-music
works arranged for piano, four-hands. And every night one of those
books would come out, and I would have to play through something by
Mozart or Beethoven or Brahms or Schubert or Schumann or
Mendelssohn with him, up to speed, and damn the mistakes. It gave
me a very good training in sight-reading, something I've used ever
since. My father was not a good pianist, but he made up for a lack
of technique with an endless enthusiasm _ and a hell of a lot of
loud pedal.''
</P>
<P>
   Previn is famous as an interpreter of the Mozart concertos, and
Philips will release some of his Mozart performances in its ongoing
examination of the 100 most important pianists of the century. But
he says he has played many concertos in public _ three of
Beethoven's, the Tchaikovsky, the Grieg, the Rachmaninoff Second,
and the ``Paganini'' Rhapsody _ and of course he has conducted all
of the repertory concertos with some of the most celebrated
pianists of our day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned the Brahms concertos,'' Previn says, ``but never
played them. I was never what I would call a Liszt pianist, and I
played dreadful Chopin. I love Chopin, but it didn't speak through
me when I played, and it still doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Previn says he doesn't know the extent to which his personal
experience of the piano literature influenced the creation of his
own concerto. ``I didn't model my concerto on anything, although I
may have been thinking more about the Prokofiev or the Bartok
concertos than any other pieces, although in a mild way. When the
composer Harold Shapero told me the first theme in my concerto
reminded him of the Bartok Third, I took it as a very great
compliment. I did know what I was writing for Vladimir Ashkenazy,
so I knew damn well that I could write anything. And I have to say
he played it with sickening ease. The piano part is very difficult,
and the orchestra part isn't easy either.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the premiere, the concerto has been taken up by other
pianists, including Andre Watts and Gutierrez. The composer
confesses that his memory of the piece is a bit hazy _ it's been
about six years since he's heard it. When asked about a fascinating
passage for alto saxophone, he says, ``I hear it in my own ear, but
I don't even remember what movement it's in! There's quite a lot of
stuff for the percussion, but unlike many of my colleagues, I got
over that _ and I never did write for an endless array of arcane
instruments.''
</P>
<P>
   Previn is still basking in the glow of ``Streetcar.'' ``It was a
great experience for me and renewed my adoration for being in the
opera house pit. I love writing for voices, and all the singers
seemed to like it a good deal. Renee Fleming, who sang Blanche, and
I have a lot of plans to work together over the next three years.
The recording will come out in mid-December on three Deutsche
Grammophon CDs, and there will be a telecast on Dec. 30. So far,
I've only seen the temporary mix of the television version, but
what I saw I liked very much, and the recording sounds very good.
I'm not saying I'm uniformly pleased by everything that I wrote,
but I was pleased by enough of it to warrant writing another opera,
and I've already done some sketches for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon it was time to head for Avery Fisher Hall. ``It's a nice
program tonight, the Dvorak Seventh, and a beautiful piece by Jacob
Druckman called `Aureole,' and Pamela Frank is playing Mozart's
Third Violin Concerto. Everything she does is so beautiful. We
worked on it as if it were a new and wildly complicated piece.
That's the way to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
