<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-OPOSITIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O POSITIVE ISN'T NEGATIVE ABOUT ITS DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We are,'' says O Positive singer-guitarist Dave Herlihy,
``back from the dead, momentarily.''
</P>
<P>
   The group _ which hasn't existed for three years _ plays its
farewell concert at Mama Kin Music Hall in Boston Saturday night
(12/5). After that, it's back to the rock graveyard for O Positive
_ Herlihy, singer-guitarist Dave Martin, guitarist-keyboardist Alan
Petitti, drummer Ken Hickey, and bassist David Ingham. But, you may
wonder, why was O Positive exhumed in the first place?
</P>
<P>
   Herlihy says T.T. the Bear's co-owner, Bonney Bouley, called in
September about reuniting the band to play one of the club's
25th-anniversary/charity shows. ``We had such a good feeling about
Bonney and the cause, so we said, `Let's do this,' '' says Herlihy.
``A couple of the guys thought it'd be a good opportunity to go
over tracks from '94 to put together a live CD. The show sold out a
week in advance and a lot of people couldn't get in, so we figured
we'd do one more show.''
</P>
<P>
   With a limited edition CD, ``O Positive Live,'' just out,
Herlihy calls the Mama Kin gig ``a CD release funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   O Positive was one of Boston's most melodic, intelligent
post-punk bands of the decade 1985-95. The group scored early with
the ``Only Breathing'' EP (featuring ``With You'') and then again
with another EP called ``Cloud Factory'' (featuring ``Talk About
Love''). The two EPs were combined into a CD in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, the members signed with Epic and released the CD
``Toyboat, Toyboat, Toyboat.'' O Positive didn't fly nationally for
a variety of reasons _ a lack of promotion being one of those.
``They were scaling back their commitment to baby bands,'' recalls
Herlihy. ``We walked in to do a video for the first single and they
pulled the plug. We stepped into the batter's box and we didn't
have a bat. We just watched the ball go by.''
</P>
<P>
   The band regrouped, kept moving, and solidified its local
audience. It released a final studio CD, ``Home Sweet Head,'' in
1993. By January '95, it was all over. Herlihy went full-time into
law, a profession he had trained for at Boston College. He is now
an entertainment business attorney. (Herlihy, Hickey, and Ingham
also play occasionally in a group called Toyboat, which appears at
T.T. the Bear's Dec. 11.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my midlife crisis at 24,'' says the 41-year-old Herlihy.
``I woke up as a lawyer and didn't want to see myself as a bald fat
attorney in my 50s never having gone for it. It was a pleasure to
be involved in something where everyone's going for it. I don't
have that nagging `what if . . .?' phase.
</P>
<P>
   ``O Positive gave it everything we had,'' Herlihy says. The Mama
Kin gig should ``be fun _ to do it without the pressure of the
business and do it for the joy. It's not like we're going in for
root canals. Having had some distance (from the material) gave me a
chance to approach the lyrics anew and not just sing them verbatim
or be on emotional auto-pilot. The material still stands up and it
is a joy to sing the songs and lose myself in them. It's good to
pick up on the love of it. I've almost come back to square one: Do
it for fun.'' It's a good feeling, Herlihy adds, ``not being hung
up on the holy grail of the record deal, a blessed relief not to be
subliminally fixated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
