<HEADLINE>
COHOES SAVINGS HOPES TO RAISE UP TO $80.5M THROUGH IPO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLAIRE HUGHES  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COHOES, N.Y. _ Cohoes Savings Bank hopes to raise $59.5 million
to $80.5 million through its initial offering of stock and may use
the money to build new branches or purchase other financial service
firms.
</P>
<P>
   While that may seem a hefty amount, it indicates what a
different world it is for banks ``going public'' now than it was in
the spring, when Cohoes Savings announced its intention to convert
from a mutual institution owned by depositors to a stock
institution owned by shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Then, bank President Harry L. Robinson said he hoped the stock
offering would raise more than $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The appraisal is based on the (stock) market, and the market
has re-valued bank stocks,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the same devaluation of bank stock caused Cohoes
Savings to cancel plans in October to purchase SFS Bancorp Inc.,
parent of Schenectady Federal Savings Bank. The purchase was
originally intended to coincide with Cohoes Savings' stock
offering.
</P>
<P>
   Bank stocks were flying high in the spring but were pummeled
when the market took a dive between August and October. Most have
rebounded some, but have not reached the peaks they held in the
spring, said Kevin Timmons, senior banking analyst for First Albany
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes perfect sense that (Cohoes Savings officials) would
expect to raise less than they would last May,'' Timmons said.
</P>
<P>
   Data the company issued in its offering prospectus suggest its
$10-a-share asking price might be a good deal. Its estimated book
value is $15.78 a share using a midpoint of 7 million shares sold.
</P>
<P>
   Depositors on record as of March 1997, trustees and officers of
the bank were mailed information on the offering last month,
Robinson said. They will be offered the stock first, through noon
on Dec. 16, with other depositors and the general public getting
dibs only if the shares aren't snatched up.
</P>
<P>
   Cohoes Savings has left open the possibility of issuing as many
as 9.3 million shares, to raise a total of $93 million, pending
regulatory approval. Whatever the total amount raised, the offering
must be approved by depositors as well as state and federal
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to using the money for growth, the bank intends to
fund a charitable foundation with 3 percent of the proceeds from
the sale. It will also fund a ``Recognition and Retention Plan''
that grants stock to officers, with $2.5 million to $3.3 million of
the proceeds. Such plans are fairly common in initial public
offerings of bank stock, Timmons said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a financial or business interest in your own
business ... you are going to perform, and you are going to stay,''
Robinson said. ``The purpose is to make (officers) owners.''
</P>
<P>
   Other employees will be offered the ability to buy shares
through an employee stock ownership plan.
</P>
<P>
   The bank will become a wholly owned subsidiary of the newly
formed Cohoes Bancorp Inc. and intends eventually to trade on the
Nasdaq National Market System under the symbol COHB. Cohoes is
located north of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of September, Cohoes Savings had assets of $551
million. It operates 17 full-service banking branches, and focuses
its business on residential mortgage lending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-04-98 1356EST &QL; 
