A3329 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-DISSIDENT-ART-B     12-04 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DISSIDENT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARRESTED CHINESE DISSIDENT'S DAUGHTER HAS SEEN IT ALL BEFORE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (i and a coding; originally moved on a.m. cycle without photo)   For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISA VALDES-RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Once again, Xu Jin is watching as her father is taken
from her.
</P>
<P>
   The first time, she was eight years old, standing in her
nightgown as Chinese soldiers dragged him off in the middle of the
night. What's wrong, she asked him. He smiled, trying to comfort
her. Nothing's wrong, he said, go back to sleep. The next day, he
was gone.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 12 years, she lived without him.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Xu, 26, watched on the news as her father, Xu Wenli,
one of China's leading dissidents, was dragged to prison in Beijing
this week. Xu is in Boston, where she is a graduate student at
Boston University, studying fine arts.
</P>
<P>
   Her father's crime: Creating a democratic political party.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not surprised,'' Xu said in an interview Thursday, her
eyes brimming with tears. ``He kept a bag filled with things like
his toothbrush behind the door. He expected this.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Carr, chairman of the advisory board for Harvard's Human
Rights Initiative, compares Xu Wenli to Nelson Mandela. Xu Jin said
Mandela is a friend of her father's, and said the two men agree
with the comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Even though she spent much of her childhood without her father's
direct presence, Xu said his letters to her, and his example,
taught her about standing up for your beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Following in his footsteps, she wrote a letter to the Chinese
government this week, condemning them for her father's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father has ideas about democracy and freedom but he has no
soldiers and no secret police,'' she wrote. ``He cannot hurt you.
Let him go.''
</P>
<P>
   Xu can't go home to be with her mother, He Xintong, because she
fears she will not be allowed to leave China again. Xintong can't
come to Boston to be with her daughter because she fears she won't
be allowed to return to China. Xu is an only child, and her mother
is very ill.
</P>
<P>
   Xu attends school in Boston because she is forbidden from
attending universities in China. ``It's not a written law,'' she
said. ``But it's understood that because of who my father is, I'm
not to be educated.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview Thursday, Xu recalled a very happy early
childhood. She remembered marching with her father in protests, and
dancing and entertaining adults who had gathered at her family's
house to hand-write and hand-publish a pro-democracy magazine
called April 5th Forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were always lots of people in the house,'' Xu said,
smiling with the memory. ``It was quite wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Xu's father was born and raised in Southern China, one of five
children. His father died when he was nine years old. Raised
alternately by his mother, an older sister, and his grandmother, Xu
Wenli became very interested in politics and history while he was
in high school, according to his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from high school, Xu Wenli made the decision
not to attend college, which broke his mother's heart. But he
believed ``he would learn more by studying the government and
talking to people,'' his daughter said.
</P>
<P>
   He served five years in the Chinese army, and then took a job as
an electrician at a factory in Beijing, where he met He Xintong, an
accountant, fell in love, and married.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Xu Wenli became involved with a fledgling democracy
movement, his daughter said. He began producing the magazine in his
house, and his daughter remembers how happy he seemed when he would
go with his wife and daughter to the central wall in Beijing to
sell the magazine on the street.
</P>
<P>
   It was around that time that Xu Wenli's friend Wei Ginsheng put
up a poster asking for democracy. He was arrested. Xu Wenli
organized a group of people to sneak a tape recorder into the
trial, and then published a transcript of the trial to show it was
unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Xu Jin's father was charged with stealing state secrets, and
taken away. It was a full year before Xu Jin or her mother even
knew if he was alive or dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother took me to every prison, everywhere she could think
of where he might be, asking for him,'' she said. ``I didn't want
her to know how scared I was, so when I started to feel afraid, I'd
say I was going to go outside to look at the cars.''
</P>
<P>
   After the first arrest, Xu Jin said, her elementary school
teacher harassed her, humiliated her in class and made sure ``I
didn't laugh so much anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Xu Jin's middle and high school teachers were more
understanding, she said. Nonetheless, she grew up very alone. Her
mother worked three jobs. After school, Xu came home to an empty
house. She had no close friends, because she could not let anyone
know about the truth of her father's imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would tell them he was on a business trip,'' she said. ``It
seemed safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Xu and her mother were allowed to visit her father in prison
every two months, for 40 minutes, with the exception of three years
in which he was allowed no visitors. It was the only human contact
he had for 12 years, as his captors were not allowed to speak to
him. For much of his sentence he was kept in a room ``not much
wider or longer than a coffin''.
</P>
<P>
   The first time Xu saw her father after his arrest, she said he
was huddled on the floor of a large room where 20 or so prison
officials sat at a large table.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't allowed to talk about politics, or the trial,'' she
said. ``And my mother wasn't allowed to touch him. When I was
little I could sit on his lap, but after a while that stopped
too.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Xu Wenli was released to house arrest after the United
States government demanded his release in exchange for economic
investment.
</P>
<P>
   When her father emerged from the prison, he was a changed man,
physically. ``His hair was white, his teeth were rotted out,'' said
his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   His spirit, however, remained intact. ``He just started talking
and wouldn't stop,'' his daughter said. ``I had cooked a whole
table of his favorite foods, but he wouldn't stop talking to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Xu had only a few months with her father after his release from
prison before she was to head to the United States, to attend Bard
College.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad, he's against college,'' she said. ``But he understood.
He wants me to have a better life.''
</P>
<P>
   Xu hopes to finish school, take a job in graphic design
somewhere in the United States, and continue to support her mother.
But her father's activism has also worn off on her.
</P>
<P>
   In her letter to the Chinese government, Xu said that computers
confiscated from her father's house were bought with money she
earned ``by washing dishes and waiting tables. Why are you afraid
of me and my father?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
