<HEADLINE>
GIRL WITH HIV ADMITTED TO BROWNIE TROOP AFTER SEVERAL REJECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LINDA TRISCHITTA  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUEENSBURY, N.Y. _ Eight-year-old Quashawn Donovan has been
placed with a Queensbury Brownie troop after being denied admission
to several troops last month because she is HIV positive.
</P>
<P>
   For James Caligiuri, a nurse who leads the Brownie troop that
includes his daughter, Quashawn's medical condition is no big deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had the education to deal with it, and I feel comfortable
dealing with it,'' Caligiuri said Wednesday. ``The HIV routes of
transmission do not occur at a Brownie meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Quashawn Donovan, the adopted daughter of Dianne and Timothy
Donovan of Queensbury, was invited to join troops in several
upstate New York towns, but they were too far from home, according
to her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Quashawn was aware that she was denied admission to some troops
because of her HIV status.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was her first lesson in HIV fear and discrimination,''
said Dianne Donovan, who estimated her daughter received 11
rejections for various reasons and that several were because of
HIV.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Adirondack Girl Scout Council held an HIV
training program for troop leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We train literally hundreds of people a year, whether in first
aid or programming or anything of interest to leaders and their
girls,'' said Kit Huggard, executive director of the Adirondack
Council, which has 3,500 girls in 375 troops led by 1,100 adults.
``You can be assured that this (HIV training) will be incorporated
into all of our training for our leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   HIV _ the human immunodeficiency virus _ can lead to AIDS, an
affliction in which the virus weakens the immune system, subjecting
the body to serious infection. AIDS is most often spread through
sexual contact, sharing contaminated needles and infected blood
products, but also can be passed to children from infected mothers.
</P>
<P>
   Huggard said that like other girls, Quashawn had been on a
waiting list to be placed with a troop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every kid needs their schedules catered to,'' Huggard said.
``Every year there are kids we can't place. HIV was probably in the
mix of her being denied a troop, but there are other things
involved, like finding adults to run the troops.''
</P>
<P>
   Quashawn was adopted by the Donovan's when she was 2 1/2 after
joining the family when she was eight months old; she has a brother
Danny, now 10, adopted when he was 4 who is also HIV-positive.
Donovan credited a family environment and drug cocktails with
keeping the children alive.
</P>
<P>
   Danny was admitted to a Cub Scout troop this fall, even though
his parents included his HIV status in the registration paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's more stressful living with a secret, but when
something like this happens you can understand why parents don't
let their kids go public,'' Donovan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-04-98 1358EST &QL; 
