<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATEWAY, DELL RAISE BAR FOR NOTEBOOKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are two ways to build a notebook computer _ make it
smaller and cut out features, or make it bigger and sacrifice
portability.
</P>
<P>
   Everything else is a compromise between these two extremes. In
my endless quest for the perfect notebook, there are candidates at
both ends of the spectrum, but the trade-offs inherent in each
design usually mean no model wins the crown.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway and Dell Computer Corp., the two top direct PC
companies, have taken opposite approaches. Each works in its own
way, but each also offers evidence of the built-in drawbacks to the
two approaches.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Solo 3100 _ $3,000, Gateway.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the rather boring Solo name that Gateway gives to its
notebook computers. The code name for this portable while it was
under development was FireAnt, and that label was trotted out for a
launch-week blitz of advertising. The moniker FireAnt was meant to
invoke something small but powerful.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, computer-makers in South Dakota have never had to
deal with fire ants. For us here in Texas, the nasty critters are
not something to take lightly. Any parent who's heard the screams
of his or her child after stepping barefooted in a fire ant mound
isn't going to have warm, fuzzy thoughts when they hear this name.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, this is indeed a small but powerful portable
computer. The Solo 3100 is about an inch thick and has a slightly
smaller footprint than most other full-featured notebook machines.
</P>
<P>
   The model I tried came with a mobile version of the
300-megahertz Intel Pentium II chip, 64 megabytes of memory, a
four-gigabyte hard drive, 56K voice and fax modem, a 12.1-inch
active matrix screen, USB and infrared ports and a Trackpoint-style
pointing device. It comes with an external floppy that attaches via
the parallel port.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its small size, the 3100 has a full-sized keyboard that
is comfortable to use. Unlike some of the competitive, ultra-thin
portable models, such as the Sony Vaio 505, the keys haven't been
reduced in size, even by a millimeter. Touch-typists will love it.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be put off by the small screen size, which is necessary
because of the smaller size of the case. The screen has a native
resolution of 800-by-600 pixels, which is fine for the most common
uses _ word processing, e-mail, Web surfing, spreadsheets. It's
also extremely bright, even in low-power mode.
</P>
<P>
   The 3100 I used came with a DVD-ROM drive. The DVD decoding was
handled by a PC card that fits into the computer's lone PC-card
slot. You can connect an adapter to the card, then connect it to a
TV set, turning the 3100 into a DVD movie player.
</P>
<P>
   Battery life was very good for a Pentium II-based notebook; I
routinely got three hours of power out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the FireAnt isn't the perfect notebook, though it
comes very close. It has only one PC-card slot, which means with
the DVD-decoder card in place, you can't add a network adapter
card, and you can't insert a Type III PC card, which takes up two
full Type II slots.
</P>
<P>
   It's also surprisingly heavy for a machine of its size _ 5.2
pounds. That's because of its oversized battery, which provides the
previously mentioned long battery life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Inspiron 7000 _ $3,500, Dell Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   If the Solo 3100 is a fine example of how to do a small computer
right, the Inspiron 7000 shows how to do a small computer ... big _
and still get it right.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first notebook computer to come with a 15-inch
active matrix display. That's about the viewable area of many
17-inch desktop monitors. For those who rely on their portable
computers for multimedia presentations, it's a dream machine.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's also a very big and heavy one. This is not a
notebook computer that you'll enjoy lugging through airports on the
run.
</P>
<P>
   The model I tried had a 300-megahertz Pentium II chip, 64
megabytes of memory, an eight-gigabyte hard drive, a DVD-ROM drive
and a 56K voice and fax modem. It uses a flat touchpad for a
pointing device, which took some tweaking before I was able to get
its sensitivity settings right.
</P>
<P>
   The star of this system, though, is the screen. It's a gorgeous
display, bright and crisp, and playing DVD-based movies on it is
nothing short of spectacular. If you've got kids, a minivan, a
penchant for long trips and a dashboard-lighter power adapter, this
could be the answer to a parent's prayer! Crank up the Disney and
let 'er rip!
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, you'll have to be a muscular parent. The 7000
weighs nearly 9 pounds with the 15-inch screen. Smaller 13.3- and
14.1-inch displays only take it down to the 8-pound range.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, the 7000 has a massive footprint _ I had
difficulty fitting it into my notebook carrying case. That's
compounded by the fact that the screen, when closed, extends about
a quarter inch beyond the confines of the case. It's like having a
cap on it that's slightly oversized.
</P>
<P>
   Battery life is not great as you'd expect in a system with as
big a display as this. I got two hours at best, and if I used the
DVD drive at all, that dropped quickly to below 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not the kind of machine you'd buy if you need long
battery life, anyway. It's a computer for people who need a
quality, full-sized display and no-compromise power in a portable
system.
</P>
<P>
   Being in good physical condition wouldn't hurt, either.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Send e-mail to dwight.silverman (at) chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
