<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASY WAY TO SORT TEXT IN HTML DOCUMENTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Do you know of any way to alphabetize links by title within
an HTML document? I have a listing of around 275 links on a U2 site
that I run, and I've simply added the newest ones to the top of the
page since starting the site back in 1994. Now I'd like the links
to be sorted alphabetically for easier browsing. However, I've been
unable to find any program at all for this purpose, and doing it by
hand would take hours upon hours of dragging and dropping.
</P>
<P>
   A. While I usually don't recommend using an everyday word
processor for creating and editing HTML documents, here's where one
comes in quite handy.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent versions of both Corel's WordPerfect and
Microsoft Word will read and write in HTML. And both include very
powerful routines for sorting lines of text.
</P>
<P>
   Open your U2 page in either one of these programs and find the
sort routine (look in the Help file for either program) and tell it
to run an alphabetical sort.
</P>
<P>
   When it is completed, be sure to do a Save As and tell the
program to save in HTML format.
</P>
<P>
   One bit of cleanup you may need to do _ both Word and
WordPerfect will add HTML tags to your document, presuming to be
``cleaning up'' your code. You may need to go into the document
with an HTML editor and remove these if they cause formatting
problems for you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Recently my Microsoft Outlook Express in-box started sorting
in subject order. How do I get it back to date/time sequence?
</P>
<P>
   A. This is one of these interesting little features of
Windows-style operating systems that many people don't use and
don't notice until their settings come undone.
</P>
<P>
   To get back to your favorite sorting scheme, go to the in-box in
Outlook Express and look at the header categories that run across
the top of your message list _ they are actually buttons you can
click.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is Received. Click on that, and it will sort your
message by date and time. Click once, and it is sorted in
descending order; click again, and it changes to ascending order.
</P>
<P>
   You can use these buttons to sort by subject, sender and other
categories. In fact, there are similar buttons that show up in many
lists in both the Macintosh and Windows platforms. For example,
open My Computer in Windows 95/98/NT, then open your hard drive's
icon. Click on View, then choose Details. Those fat file icons will
turn into tiny ones, each with details about its size, properties,
file type, and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   Click the Size button, and you can instantly see which are the
largest files in that folder. Want to know which are possibly
expendable text or temporary files? Click on any file with a TXT or
TMP extension, then click on the Type button, and all those files
will be brought together.
</P>
<P>
   You can even set up sortable, detailed lists in File Open and
Save dialog boxes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Where on your computer would you find the speed of the
microprocessor?
</P>
<P>
   A. The best place to find it is in your BIOS settings, which you
can access during the bootup procedure. Check your PC's manual to
see how to get into the BIOS setup screen, and be careful when you
do. Messing with these settings, if you don't know what you're
doing, can be painful.
</P>
<P>
   Another resource is a shareware utility called SiSoft Sandra,
which can give you all kinds of info about your system. Get it at
www.sisoftware.de-mon.co.uk/sandra/. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Send e-mail to dwight.silverman (at) chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
