<HEADER>
A3355 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAUNTED-HOLLYWOOD-2TA     12-04 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAUNTED-HOLLYWOOD-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAUNTED-HOLLYWOOD-2TAKES 
 
HOLLYWOOD HISTORIAN TELLS OF GHOST SIGHTINGS, STRANGE ENCOUNTERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the new version of ``Psycho,'' director Gus Van
Sant has resurrected Norman Bates, the amiable murderer with mother
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's the life-draining Norman, the knife-wielding Jason
or a stiff-legged Frankenstein's monster, Hollywood has always
liked a scary story.
</P>
<P>
   So from where springs all these horrific high jinks?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe central casting.
</P>
<P>
   It seems the City of Angels is congested with ghosts and scary
stories. Lovelorn suicides, ``accidental'' deaths and drug-induced
downfalls are a copious part of Tinseltown's history. In some
cases, traces of the past linger like the sulfuric perfume of an
extinguished match.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Hollywood historian Laurie Jacobson.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson came to Hollywood in the 1970s as a twentysomething.
``I was trying to be an actress and was mostly being a waitress,''
explains the petite brunette.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson was star-struck, but not by her celebrity pals at the
comedy club where she was honing her stand-up skills. No, she was
in awe of the city and the glamorous industry that gave it life.
The stories she collected were the basis of her first book
``Hollywood Heartbreak,'' which was published in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking to old-timers, and there were always ghost
stories attached to these tales,'' Jacobson says.
</P>
<P>
   In the introduction of her latest book ``Hollywood Haunted,''
she describes her first encounter with a ghost. It was in 1992 at
the famous Mann's Chinese Theater. A ghost, perhaps displeased with
her presence behind stage, began wildly shaking a velvet curtain.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson has been shaking out ghost stories ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spirits stick around for very human reasons,'' Jacobson says.
She believes that a person may be so attached to a loved one or
place that he sticks around after death. Other ghosts may be the
victims of crimes or a great injustice; they remain seeking
retribution or closure.
</P>
<P>
   Another theory relates to people who don't believe in an
afterlife. ``They become confused and just don't know where to
go,'' Jacobson explains.
</P>
<P>
   Her ideas are shared by many, including Dr. Barry Taft, a
parapsychologist and self-described ``expert on things that go bump
in the night.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A personal curiosity'' pushes Taft, who during his 30 years of
paranormal research has investigated more than 3,500 cases of
ghosts, hauntings and poltergeists. ``I do believe physical death
is just another change in life,'' says Taft, who is best known for
his work on the case on which the film ``The Entity'' is based.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phantoms fill the skies around you,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   And Hollywood is a hotbed of hauntings.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson recently led a group of jumpy journalists on a ghoul
tour sponsored by Infiniti. They rambled down Sunset Boulevard and
over Hollywood's hills in customized SUVs, chillingly labeled Dr.
Jekyll and Mr. Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   Although they saw no phantoms, they did hear some spirited
tales.
</P>
<P>
   So where are the ghosts in Hollywood?
</P>
<P>
   You can start with the theaters. Celebrity or would-be celebrity
ghosts love to relive the best times of their mortal lives, and
they are just not interested in taking that final bow.
</P>
<P>
   Employees of the Palace Theater, which opened as the Hollywood
Playhouse in 1927 and was the stage for ``Your Show of Shows,''
share many stories of apparitions, haunting music and numeric
messages left overnight on adding machines and cash registers.
</P>
<P>
   A security guard who had several strange after-hours encounters
once set a ghost trap at the theater. He put a plate on the floor
of the kitchen and then placed a wine glass on top of it. Later he
returned to the room only to find the plate resting atop the wine
glass.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few blocks away, Howard Hughes is believed to haunt the
Pantages Theater. Hughes moved his office into the art deco theater
in 1949 when he purchased RKO Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   People working in the theater today tell of seeing Hughes' ghost
in the hallways around his former office. Now a conference room, it
is oddly cold, and sometimes a faint breeze tinted with cigarette
smoke will emanate from the empty room.
</P>
<P>
   At Universal Studios, Lon Chaney Sr. is thought to haunt Stage
28, where ``Phantom of the Opera'' was shot. Universal, where the
films ``Dracula,'' ``Frankenstein'' and ``Psycho'' were filmed, is
a theme park as well as a studio. Its back-lot tram tour takes
visitors past the house from ``Psycho'' and the Bates Motel, where
visitors can get a glimpse of Norman Bates' famous ``mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Often, Jacobson says, a renovation project will awaken a
``sleeping'' ghost. Many a new owner has found his actions booed by
longtime spirits.
</P>
<P>
   After her death, Lucille Ball was spotted walking outside her
longtime home as it underwent renovations, Jacobson reports. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Argyle, a tony boutique hotel on Sunset Boulevard, made its
debut in 1929 as the Sunset Tower whose residents included Billie
Burke, Paulette Goddard and Howard Hughes. John Wayne even kept a
cow on his penthouse patio.
</P>
<P>
   The building, which has been featured in many films including
``Get Shorty'' and ``The Player,'' was renovated in the 1980s.
Spirits hate change, and they don't respect movie stars.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Argyle's Lara McGrath, martial artist
Jean-Claude Van Damme had a close encounter during a stay at the
hotel. The spirit so spooked the well-chiseled film star that Van
Damme ran through the lobby wearing just his boxer shorts and a
half-shaved face.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hollywood Roosevelt is the place to be for ghosts,
particularly the glamorous ones. The hotel is said to be haunted by
many spirits, including Marilyn Monroe and Montgomery Clift.
</P>
<P>
   Built it 1927, it was the city's first prestige hotel. Its
Blossom Room hosted the first Academy Awards banquet in 1929.
</P>
<P>
   Clift lived in the hotel for three months in 1952 during the
filming of ``From Here to Eternity.'' During his stay, Clift often
paced the short, narrow hallway near his room. He walked as he
rehearsed his lines and often paced as he practiced playing the
bugle _ a skill he needed for his role in the war drama.
</P>
<P>
   Unknowing guests today still call down to the front desk to fret
about someone playing a bugle in the hallway. Management is
reluctant to offer an explanation until the guest complains a
second time. (The hotel also has a couple of phantom children who
play noisily in the hallways, as well as a tuxedo-clad ghost who
enjoys playing the piano.) Clift's room, 928, has a couple of cold
spots, which often are associated with the presence of spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe's reflection or spirit has been seen appropriately in a
mirror at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   When Monroe was trying to break into show business, she would
hang around the celebrity-filled hotel. She frequently could be
found perched on a lounge chair, sipping 5-cent sodas, around the
hotel's pool. When she became a star, she often stayed at the
hotel, occupying her favorite suite, 1200. She stayed so often that
she bought an antique full-length mirror for the room.
</P>
<P>
   It hung there until her death in 1962. In 1984 when the hotel
underwent a massive $12 million renovation, the mirror was found in
the basement. Its pedigree earned it a place in the ``new'' hotel,
and it was hung in the manager's office.
</P>
<P>
   But about two weeks before the hotel's grand reopening, an
employee who knew nothing of the mirror's history reported seeing
the reflection of a blonde in the mirror. The employee was startled
because when she turned to address the woman she was not there. Yet
the blonde's reflection was still very much in the mirror. Since
then several others have reported seeing Marilyn's image in the
mirror. They report that it is a sad-looking reflection.
</P>
<P>
   If, as Taft says, ``phantoms fill the skies,'' they also hang
around one particular corner of Hollywood Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   At Hollywood and Sierra Bonita Avenue, three traffic accidents
in recent years have prompted some unusual claims by the drivers.
One man said a tomahawk was flying toward his windshield; another
swerved to miss a covered wagon; and yet another was shocked to see
Indians in war paint charging his vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   But leave it to the Californians to cope.
</P>
<P>
   At the Comedy Store, ghost stories are exchanged like badges of
honor. The well-known comedy club owned by Mitzi Shore (mother of
Paulie) originally was Ciro's, a hangout for mobsters, celebrities
and their hangers-on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I should be cordial and say hi to the ghosts,'' says
comic Cory Comeaux, sharing a story of being in the club after
hours when ``the place becomes Ciro's again.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Comeaux, he saw a headless man with top hat, who
tipped it and bowed. Also he saw dancers whirling around the dance
floor, and he heard glasses tinkling.
</P>
<P>
   Others do more than cope, explains Jacobson.
</P>
<P>
   David North proudly boasts of living with Mae West, who died in
1980. North acquired her penthouse home at the Ravenswood
Apartments, and she apparently is still living there.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, according to Jacobson, North tossed a 105th birthday
party for the Brooklyn-born vaudeville and film star. He invited
both his friends and hers. In a photo taken at the party, a bosomy
apparition appears to be standing next to North and resting its
hand on his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe West's famous quip should be ``It's not the ghost in your
life that counts. It's the life in your ghost.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
