<SLUG> BC-SHATTERED-FILM-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SHATTERED IMAGE' IS REAL _ REAL BAD, THAT IS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JEFF MILLAR 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When casting about for something snide to say about a terrible
movie, you don't expect to find it in the film's publicity packet.
</P>
<P>
   With remarkable candor, the packet for ``Shattered Image''
characterizes it a ``thriller evoking every doppelganger film from
`Vertigo' to `The Double Life of Veronique.' ''
</P>
<P>
   I can't put it any better than that.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of these films that seeks to entertain us by asking,
``Ah, but what is real?''
</P>
<P>
   We're introduced to Jessie (Anne Parillaud) in Seattle as she
performs a murder-for-hire. She's a professional assassin,
specializing in men.
</P>
<P>
   Then we're introduced to Parillaud as another Jessie _ let's
call her Jessie Two _ waking up from a dream in which she was
Jessie One, the assassin.
</P>
<P>
   Jessie Two, who has longer hair and doesn't wear as much makeup,
is the recent bride of Brian (William Baldwin), who, the film
suggests, might be a little too handsome for Jessie Two's good.
</P>
<P>
   Jessie Two and Brian are just arriving in lush Jamaica for their
honeymoon. Jessie Two is an heiress, and Brian keeps noodling
Jessie Two for a bit of cash so he can make some can't-miss real
estate investments.
</P>
<P>
   Then Jessie One wakes up from a dream in which she was Jessie
Two, just arriving in Jamaica for her honeymoon. Jessie One has a
new gig, in which she's been hired to kill a Seattle antiques store
owner _ another William Baldwin named Brian! And the client is a
woman who has the same face as a woman Jessie Two met at the
Jamaican hotel!
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with Duane Poole's tatty screenplay, this enterprise
evokes the cliches of every doppelganger film from ``Vertigo'' to
``The Double Life of ...'' is there an echo in here?
</P>
<P>
   Raul Ruiz's flaccid and mercilessly Eurostyle direction is
enough to consider raising cultural tariffs. The film is
cheaped-out and careless, from the inexpensive ham actors in small
roles to the firehose rainstorms that don't even make it to the
edges of the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Parillaud does both Jessie One and Jessie Two in a monotone that
_ giving her first the doubt she's earned by being very good in the
original ``La Femme Nikita'' _ might have been a bad creative
decision. Or it could be sheer laziness.
</P>
<P>
   When Ruiz asked ``Ah, but what is real?'' I answered with
another question: ``What's playing in the next auditorium?''
</P>
<P>
   Not another word on this. Avoid. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Shattered Image'' &QL; 
Starring: Anne Parillaud and William Baldwin &QL; 
Not rated &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-04-98 1404EST &QL; 
