<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMEOWNER ANXIETY REACHES THE SATURATION POINT 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As long as I can remember, I have loved waking
to the sound of rain. In my warm bed, usually with plenty of time
before I must get up, I've felt at once child-like and omnipotent.
You know, cozy and tucked in but invincible to all the wind and
water swirling around me.
</P>
<P>
   Since I bought a house, all of that has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Now the sound of rain _ pulling me from the fleece-lined depths
of sleep _ provokes major anxiety. My bed no longer feels secure
and wombish but like a foxhole just before an aerial bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Probably you are thinking: Oh, she has a leaky roof. But the
sick thing is, I don't. Not yet anyway. That I know of.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since I bought my house, I say ``Not yet anyway'' and
``That I know of'' all the time. It's like hanging garlic around my
neck to ward off vampires. I chant those phrases as a preventive
measure against everything from a busted hot water heater to a
shorted-out front porch light.
</P>
<P>
   I do this because other homeowners have made me paranoid and
superstitious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, you bought a house? Just wait,'' they all say. ``It's a
money pit. One thing after another. It never stops. Has your hot
water heater broken down? They're always the first to go.''
</P>
<P>
   No, not yet. That I know of.
</P>
<P>
   Last year during the storms of El Nino (when my roof was my
landlord's problem), I saw most of my homeowner friends spend the
winter gripped by fear. They roamed their houses with flashlights,
searching corners and seams for signs of seepage. They monitored
their basements. When leaks did spring, the drip, drip, drip of
rainwater into plastic buckets and dishpans was like Poe's telltale
heart, a sound that grew louder by the moment and drove them all
toward madness.
</P>
<P>
   When the skies cleared for a bit, those who could climb their
roofs slopped five-gallon cans of goop on the patches they thought
were suspect. Those who could not climb got in the long queue for
an audience with the most powerful person on Earth _ a professional
roofer.
</P>
<P>
   So, since Nov. 30, when 60 mph winds and heavy rains hammered
the San Francisco Bay area, I awoke at 6 a.m. in a mild panic.
</P>
<P>
   Where was that ``ping, ping, ping'' coming from? Inside the
bedroom or underneath the deck? Was that a car moving along the
street or torrents of water rushing down the basement steps? What
would I find upstairs under the skylight where a single drop of
water had fallen on my head?
</P>
<P>
   I turned on the lights and climbed out of my warm bed. I ran my
hands along the walls and followed the ping, ping, ping; it led
outside, underneath the deck. Prepared for the Ganges, I opened the
basement door and walked in; it was desert dry.
</P>
<P>
   I climbed the stairs and, cringing, turned on the kitchen light;
no mountain of shattered plexiglass lay on the hardwood floor. I
shuffled my bare feet all over and around the rag rug that lies
beneath the skylight. Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Not yet anyway. That I know of.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
