A3396 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PINOCHET-HNS &LR;      12-04 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINOCHET RULING PUTS HUMAN RIGHTS ABOVE POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN BLACK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Gen. Augusto Pinochet made a big mistake. His
previous secret visits to Britain for tea with former Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher, a fellow anti-socialist zealot, were
bound to be looked upon with great disgust by Tony Blair's new
Labor government.
</P>
<P>
   Before he got on the plane, the general should have checked who
was running the new British government. He would have been wise to
count the number of Scots who currently occupy the highest Cabinet
offices in the Blair government. The three top senior cabinet posts
_ the finance, foreign and defense ministers _ all cut their
ideological teeth in the Scottish Labor Party of the 1970s.
Socialist ideology was the bread and butter of the Labor Party at
that time and these young activists, now government ministers, were
radical.
</P>
<P>
   Chile was a cause celebre for Scottish leftists. The 1973
CIA-backed overthrow of the democratically elected leftist
government of Salvador Allende affirmed to Scottish socialists that
the United States was only interested in supporting democratic
winners if they were willing to toe the Washington line. Many who
were then in the Scottish Labor Party, including those now in the
Blair government, have not forgotten this travesty of democracy. In
Scotland, memories are long. Many see Pinochet's arrest as sweet
revenge and a satisfying boot in the face for the aging and
decaying Thatcher, the nemesis of the Scots.
</P>
<P>
   Thatcher's reign in Britain in the 1980s was characterized by
her ``English'' nationalism and her burning desire to ``turn back
the frontiers of socialism.'' Pinochet went a genocidal step
further. He eliminated it. Thatcher, as she has admitted, admires
the general and his policies. The British press has been filled
with speculation that Pinochet was lured to Britain by the new
Labor Foreign Ministry, in order that the police could arrest him
on a Spanish extradition warrant.
</P>
<P>
   Upon his appointment, Foreign Secretary Robin Cook promised that
British foreign policy would be motivated by a new standard in the
post-Cold War era. Respect for human rights would be the
cornerstone. Strategic interest would play a secondary role. Those
who thrived on the scraps from the post-war ideological battle
between communism and capitalism would no longer be allowed to
continue with their protected tyrannies. Those who hold power
through aggression and repression would be denied British
assistance and aid.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the Cold War has blown the cover off those dictators
who tortured, murdered and destroyed in the name of their
ideological creeds. The blame for the human rights catastrophe that
occurred during Pinochet's regime must be shouldered, to some
extent, by the U.S. government and its agencies. It is small wonder
that Washington has been nervous about Pinochet's case. The British
press has reported that the U.S. State Department has been applying
diplomatic pressure to gain the general's release. Should he ever
be brought to justice, old crusty pages from the CIA's files may be
reopened. ``Let sleeping dogs lie'' seems to be Washington's
preferred proverb.
</P>
<P>
   The British Law Lords' recent landmark ruling, denying Pinochet
immunity from prosecution as a former head of state, has elevated
international law to new heights. Tyrants can never feel safe
again. It is a positive step for the new century.
</P>
<P>
   When I was a child in Scotland, I remember bewildered Chilean
children coming as refugees to my elementary school in the early
1970s. Their parents had been killed or had fled the genocide in
their homeland. They sat in the classroom, unable to speak the
language. But they were safe and they were made welcome. Now,
finally, the victims and their families may get justice.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alan Black is the manager of the Edinburgh Castle Pub in San
Francisco.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
