<P>
   &UR; RADIATION AFFECTS NEIGHBORING CELLS &LR;  _ Scientists in Boston
have found that targeting low-level radiation on human cells causes
changes in levels of gene activity in neighboring cells. It is
possible that this bystander effect might be a mechanism to
minimize cell damage. By Rob Edwards. 500 words (slugged:
BC-RADIATION-AND-HUMAN-CELLS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOR YOUR EYES ONLY &LR;  _ An online magazine has been launched on
the Internet with security software that prevents subscribers from
passing electronic copies on to friends. By Barry Fox. 300 words.
(slugged: BC-ONLINE-MAGAZINES-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COULD A NASAL VACCINE FINALLY PUT AN END TO THE BLACK DEATH? &LR;  _
Nose drops based on a new vaccine can protect mice from bubonic
plague, say researchers at the University of Birmingham in England.
If clinical trials on humans are successful, it may allay fears of
a worldwide pandemic started by antibiotic-resistant plague
bacteria. By Debora MacKenzie. 500 words. (slugged:
BC-STOPPING-THE-BUBONIC-PLAGUE-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMPUTERS HELP CAR THIEVES &LR;  _ More than three million cars in
Britain and elsewhere can be unlocked easily by hackers using a
handheld computer. Using the right software, thieves can copy the
codes from infrared controls used for locking car doors. By Duncan
Graham-Rowe. 500 words. (slugged:
BC-COMPUTERS-AND-CRIME-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
