<HEADER>
A3412 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARS-MISSIONS-$ADV6-H     12-04 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS-MISSIONS-$ADV6-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARS-MISSIONS-$ADV6 
 
ROBOTS TO SEARCH, PROBE LANDSCAPE OF MARS 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 6) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Intrigued by evidence that water once flowed abundantly over the
now frigid, desert-like Martian landscape, the United States is
launching new and rather oddball robots in search of frozen
remnants on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   While the last such robot to thrill observers back on Earth
bounced onto the Mars surface and proceeded to send back images,
two spacecraft launched over the next few weeks will carry a soil
sniffer, a mechanical arm and a tiny oven and the instruments will
circle, dig and punch at the Red Planet.
</P>
<P>
   The launches represent the latest in a parade of small unmanned
probes that NASA and a budding international alliance plan to send
to Mars well into the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   The Mars Climate Orbiter and the Mars Polar Lander are to launch
Dec. 10 and Jan. 3, respectively, from NASA's Kennedy Space Center
in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance is building toward missions after the turn of the
century that will attempt to return Martian rock and soil samples
to Earth, a project in which the French plan to collaborate with
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably foremost among the goals are understanding the
biological potential of Mars _ really understanding the question:
Did life ever arise on Mars,'' said Carl Pilcher, who directs
NASA's solar systems exploration office from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It's been more than two years since a team of scientists from
NASA's Johnson Space Center and Stanford University said they found
fossil evidence of ancient microbial life in a Martian meteorite
recovered from the Antarctic.
</P>
<P>
   Roundly disputed by other scientists, their claim nonetheless
renewed interest in the larger issue of whether Mars once harbored
life. That prospect increases if water flowed and ponded in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists expect to gradually piece together an explanation for
what prompted the Martian climate to change so drastically from one
that experts believe was once so wet that massive floods exceeding
anything witnessed on Earth swept across some regions. Under
contemporary conditions, water on Mars could exist only as vapor or
ice. The atmosphere is thin and almost exclusively carbon dioxide.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to look for life, to look for water, we need to
understand the whole context of Mars as a planet, what controls the
behavior of the atmosphere over the course of a year, what controls
the behavior of water and carbon dioxide in the atmosphere and the
polar caps,'' said Bruce Jakosky, a planetary scientist from the
University of Colorado and a member of the mission research team.
</P>
<P>
   Jakosky is among those who believe that Mars harbors a complex
water cycle in which moisture is both pulled from and released into
the atmosphere by the permanent polar caps at different times of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   With its arrival at Mars in September, the Climate Orbiter will
function as a weather satellite charting the global migration of
water vapor, carbon dioxide and dust in the planet's lower
atmosphere as well as recording temperatures and pressures.
</P>
<P>
   The Polar Lander and a pair of small independent probes called
Deep Space 2 that share the same spacecraft will descend to the
South Pole in December 1999, inserting probes into the soil in
search of subterranean ice.
</P>
<P>
   At a combined $356.8 million, Climate Orbiter, Polar Lander and
Deep Space 2 will cost less than a single space shuttle launch.
</P>
<P>
   The latest expeditions come on the heels of the 1997 Mars
Pathfinder mission that landed in what appeared to be an ancient
equatorial flood basin amid rounded pebbles and other signs of past
water erosion.
</P>
<P>
   The Mars Global Surveyor, Pathfinder's orbital companion,
transmitted images of an apparent large, dry lake bed in the
northern hemisphere and detected the chemical signature of
soil-born mineral deposits commonly found in standing water on
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   What moisture there is on Mars may be found in the curiously
layered terrain of what appears to be dust and ice that surrounds
both polar caps.
</P>
<P>
   When it reaches Mars nine months after liftoff, the Climate
Orbiter will fire a braking rocket, slowing enough for the weaker
Martian gravity to pull the probe into a looping elliptical orbit
over the areas. Using a technique called aerobraking that was
employed by the Mars Global Surveyor mission, the Climate Orbiter
will dip into the planet's atmosphere periodically to lower its
altitude into a circular, 262-mile orbit.
</P>
<P>
   To augment the work of the Climate Orbiter, NASA will send the
Polar Lander and the two Deep Space 2 probes toward the layered
terrain at the South Pole.
</P>
<P>
   ``By digging in we hope to find a record of geologic change. By
digging half a meter or a meter into the surface we might be able
to examine 100,000 years of the Mars geologic record,'' said
Richard Zurek, a chief project scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving at Mars nearly two months after the Climate Orbiter,
the Polar Lander has been designed to make a high speed entry into
the atmosphere, using a heat shield to slow its initial descent, a
parachute and finally braking rockets to make a soft landing.
</P>
<P>
   Once on the surface, a 6 {-foot long mechanical arm on the probe
will attempt excavations. The material it scoops up will be
inserted into an instrument on the lander designed to analyze its
water and carbon dioxide content.
</P>
<P>
   If the analysis also produces chemical signatures of minerals
typically formed in liquid water, then scientists will gain even
more evidence that Mars once was much more hospitable.
</P>
<P>
   More experimental in their concept, the Deep Space 2 probes that
will accompany the lander will attempt similar findings.
</P>
<P>
   About the size of basketballs while encased in their protective
aeroshells, the Deep Space 2 probes were designed to crash into the
surface of Mars like Lawn Darts about 60 miles from the Polar
Lander. The 400 mph impact will shatter the protective aeroshells
exposing the grapefruit-sized top section of the two-part probe.
The bullet-shaped lower section is designed to respond to the force
of the impact by plunging from one to three feet into the subsoil.
</P>
<P>
   A small drill has been built into the side of the penetrators to
gather a small sample of the subsoil and channel it to a small oven
and analyzer within the penetrator. As the sample is warmed, the
sensor will look for signs of vaporized ice.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Polar Lander and the Deep Space 2 probes will rely on
the Climate Orbiter to function as a communications satellite,
relaying their findings back to Earth. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
