<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3413 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARS-MICROPHONE-$ADV6     12-04 0269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS-MICROPHONE-$ADV6-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARS-MICROPHONE-$ADV6 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A small privately-funded microphone installed aboard the Mars
Polar Lander will offer Earthlings their first opportunity to
sample extraterrestrial sounds.
</P>
<P>
   The $50,000 device was fashioned to record the sounds of the
Martian winds _ especially the acoustics of the sandstorms and the
twirling dust devils that dance across the bleak terrain of the Red
Planet. With any luck, the Mars Microphone may also pick up the
noises of the probe's robot arm as it crunches into the soil in
search of subterranean ice.
</P>
<P>
   If the experiment is successful, researchers plan to offer the
recordings to listeners over the World Wide Web. It was developed
by the Planetary Society, a California-based space advocacy group
whose founders include the late Carl Sagan, and the University of
California at Berkley.
</P>
<P>
   The microphone is the brainchild of researchers Janet Luhmann at
the University of California and David Juergens of NASA's Jet
Propulsion Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   They pitched the proposal to the Planetary Society, which raised
the funds for the project and orchestrated the arrangements to
fasten the palm-sized microphone and recording device to a
Russian-furnished scientific instrument called a lidar.
</P>
<P>
   The device was assembled from a hearing aid sensor, the sound
processor used in popular talking toys and a computer chip. The
equipment will record the noises it hears and transmit them back to
Earth with the probe's other data. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-04-98 1445EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
