<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3417 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARS-FACTS-$ADV6-HNS &LR;      12-04 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS-FACTS-$ADV6-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARS-FACTS-$ADV6 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 6) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mars Climate Orbiter
</P>
<P>
   Launch date: Dec. 10-25, 1998 on Boeing Delta II rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Arrival date: Sept. 23, 1999
</P>
<P>
   Science mission: Operating from an altitude of 262 miles, the
climate orbiter will record the distribution of water vapor, carbon
dioxide and dust in the lower atmosphere, measure temperature and
track cloud movement.
</P>
<P>
   Prime operations: March 2000 to January 2002
</P>
<P>
   Size: 7.6 feet tall, 5.4 feet wide with a single 18-foot long
solar power array and a launch weight of 1,387 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Instruments: Pressure Modulator Infrared Radiometer to scan the
atmosphere for dust, water vapor and clouds and to gather
temperature measurements; a pair of cameras called the Mars Color
Imager that will scan the terrain in multiple wavelengths.
</P>
<P>
   Contractor: Lockheed Martin Astronautics for NASA's Jet
Propulsion Laboratory
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mars Polar Lander
</P>
<P>
   Launch date: Jan. 3-27, 1999, on Boeing Delta II rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Arrival date: Dec. 3, 1999
</P>
<P>
   Science mission: Land a probe softly near the Martian south
pole. The lander's 6.5 foot long robot arm will dig a few inches
into the soil to gather a small sample that will be placed in an
oven-analyzer equipped to search for evidence of moisture in the
soil.
</P>
<P>
   Cameras and other instruments will photograph the surroundings,
chart temperatures and wind speeds. A first-ever recorder will
transmit the sounds of Mars to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Prime operations: 60 to 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   Size: 3.5 feet tall and 12 feet wide with a weight of 1,270
pounds. A pair of solar arrays extend 12 feet on either side at the
surface.
</P>
<P>
   Instruments: A stereo camera to survey the landing site; a small
furnace and gas analyzer to identify moisture and minerals in eight
soil samples, each weighing no more than 1/10th of a gram; a
weather station with wind and temperature sensors; a Russian laser
radar to monitor cloud conditions; a microphone to record the
planet's natural sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Contractor: Lockheed Martin Astronautics for NASA's Jet
Propulsion Laboratory
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deep Space 2
</P>
<P>
   Launch, Arrival Dates: Accompanies the Mars Polar Lander.
</P>
<P>
   Science Mission: Descend into the layered terrain that surrounds
the South Pole in search of ice locked in the soil beneath the
surface.
</P>
<P>
   Primary science mission: Six hours to three days.
</P>
<P>
   Size: Each lander is slightly larger than a grapefruit, with a
weight of 5.5 pounds, all encased in a protective basketball-sized
aeroshell.
</P>
<P>
   Instruments: A bullet shaped penetrator linked to the surface
section of the probe with a flexible data cable. A small heating
chamber and water detector for the soil samples within the
penetrator.
</P>
<P>
   Developers: JPL and others.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mission costs:
</P>
<P>
   $356.8 million total. Includes $193.1 million for the Climate
Orbiter and Polar Lander spacecraft and $29.2 million for Deep
Space 2; $91.7 million for two Delta rocket launchers; $42.8
million for mission operations. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
