<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3432 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-PRISONERS-$ADV     12-04 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PRISONERS-$ADV6-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL-PRISONERS-$ADV6 
 
ISRAELI PRISONER DETENTION, RELEASE OF COMMON CRIMINALS ARE OPEN
SORES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AIDA CAMP, West Bank _ For most of the last 17 years, Daoud
Azrak has journeyed twice a month from his home in this West Bank
refugee camp to one prison or another in Israel to visit his son
Khaled.
</P>
<P>
   When the Palestine Liberation Organization made peace with
Israel in 1993, Azrak figured his bimonthly treks would end. His
son had been imprisoned as a young cadre of Fatah, the mainstream
movement headed by Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Palestinian leader had signed peace accords, Azrak
thought, the foot soldiers of Fatah would be freed.
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, Azrak's monthly schedule has not changed. Like
hundreds of other relatives of prisoners, he awakes every two weeks
at dawn to pay a morning visit to his son, who is locked up in a
prison in Ashkelon, a city on Israel's Mediterranean coast.
</P>
<P>
   When the latest peace agreement was signed in October,
Palestinians had renewed hope that some of those who had led the
intifada, the seven-year uprising against Israeli rule in the West
Bank and Gaza, would be freed.
</P>
<P>
   During the negotiations, the two sides agreed verbally that
Israel would free 750 Palestinian prisoners by the end of January.
Last month, when Israel released the first batch of 250 prisoners
and included 150 common criminals, Palestinians fumed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there is a peace agreement, the first thing that happens
is that the political prisoners are freed,'' said Azrak, who has
seen four of his eight children imprisoned in Israel over the
years. Only Khaled remains in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is normal all over the world,'' he said. ``Why not
here?''
</P>
<P>
   Few things rile Palestinians like the issue of prisoners because
it hits home: Most families have had at least one member jailed
since the uprising began in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   For them, the prisoners' continued detention _ years after
peacemaking began _ and the insult they felt had been hurled at
them with the release of common criminals, are open sores.
</P>
<P>
   This week, they festered into violent demonstrations outside the
West Bank town of Ramallah, during which an Israeli soldier was
beaten by an angry mob. After the incident, Israel said it would
refuse to cede more West Bank territory until Palestinians accept
Israel's criteria for prisoner release.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials say the criteria exclude prisoners with
``blood on their hands'' _ that is, those whose activities harmed
or killed _ and those who belong to Hamas or other Palestinian
militant groups.
</P>
<P>
   Israel insists that Arafat agreed to these standards. And,
Israeli officials say, after freeing 7,000 prisoners since the
first peace accord was signed, not many of the mere hundreds they
say they are still holding can pass these tests and qualify for
release.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are less than 200 who meet these criteria,'' said David
Bar-Illan, political adviser for Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu. ``And 100 of them have already been released.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians deny that releasing common criminals was part of
the bargain. And they say that there are many more than 200
prisoners eligible for release, even using Israel's criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed Tibi, one of Arafat's advisors, says Israel is holding
2,150 prisoners and estimates that 1,200 of them belong to factions
of the PLO, particularly Fatah. Bassam Eid, a Palestinian human
rights activist, estimates that 300 prisoners were involved in acts
that harmed or killed anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the real figure, the war of words that has
characterized relations since the Wye agreement was signed on Oct.
23 seems likely to continue, particularly regarding this issue
since the deal was not in writing.
</P>
<P>
   To settle differences, Palestinians say they hope to appeal to
the Americans for help. ``We would like very much for the U.S. to
interfere in the issue of Palestinian prisoners,'' said Tibi.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Israel's threat this week to halt land-transfers,
Palestinians seem to have no plans to calm the frenzy over
prisoners. On Saturday, prisoners and their families began an open
hunger strike that they say will last until the last political
prisoner is freed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This peace process didn't bring us a just solution to the
prisoners,'' said Issa Karaka, head of the Palestinian Prisoners'
Club in Bethlehem and one of the organizers of the hunger strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agreement should have dealt with political prisoners,
especially those who have long sentences or who are sick or old,''
Karaka said. ``Those imprisoned before the agreement was signed (in
1993) should be released.''
</P>
<P>
   Karaka says that includes the release of prisoners such as
Khaled Azrak.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Azrak led a Fatah cell that threw a bomb at a car full
of Israelis, causing the car to overturn, killing one passenger and
injuring the others, according to the elder Azrak.
</P>
<P>
   ``These prisoners are the soldiers of Arafat_ he is the high
commander of the Palestinian revolution,'' said Tibi, adding that
he believes even Hamas prisoners should be released.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are part of the struggle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Daoud Azrak said earlier this week that he planned to be one of
the hunger strikers, along with thousands of other parents of
prisoners who were expected to participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're letting out drug dealers and car thieves,'' he said,
raising his hands in the air in frustration. ``But they don't let
out those who fought for their country. It's something
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Horan is a free-lance journalist based in Jerusalem. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
