<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3433 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HOLIDAYS-SOHO06-CO     12-04 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOLIDAYS-SOHO06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL DECEMBER 6
 &HT;    SoHo Grand coddles the hip and well-heeled
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The SoHo Grand Hotel is the kind of place where those
often surreal encounters one has in the Big Apple are an inevitable
experience, part of the script. Take this scene, in the hotel's
chi-chi Canal House restaurant, for example.
</P>
<P>
   On a sunny afternoon, diners are nibbling on grilled tiger
shrimp and crab cakes flecked with Jerusalem artichokes. One is a
childlike young woman who looks like she lay down on a bolt of
drapery fabric, rolled over like a cannoli, and had someone cut it
off _ raw edges intact _ just under her armpits. Why . . . it's the
Icelandic rock queen, Bjork.
</P>
<P>
   At the table next to her, a very large black man with a shiny
shaved head is sipping a hot cup of tea. Whoa . . . it's Geoffrey
Holder, the actor probably best known for playing the voodoo witch
doctor in the 1976 James Bond film ``Live and Let Die.'' Sixties
survivors will also recall him as the deep-voiced man who hawked
7-Up as the ``Un-cola'' in all those television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Bjork and the Un-cola guy.
</P>
<P>
   This meeting of hip, hype, money and fame is the essence of this
ultra-chic hotel at 310 West Broadway in the heart of the city's
booming SoHo art district. Since opening in 1996 _ the first major
hotel built in the area since the 1800s _ the 15-story brick
structure has been embraced as a cutting edge alternative to the
mainstream lodgings of Midtown Manhattan. That's no doubt because
the place caters to their tastes for luxury, service and the
never-ending search for the next new thing.
</P>
<P>
   But the SoHo Grand is more than a here-today, gone-tomorrow pop
hangout. Designer David Helpern has created a stunning setting,
from the brick columns dominating the open lobby to the thick, Coke
glass-and-iron staircase flanked by two carved dogs. This place
drips luxury, from leather chairs laced up like tight bodices to
gallery-quality photographs on the walls to the tiny bowls of
cashews that dot glass tabletops.
</P>
<P>
   The airy main floor is like a scene out of a 1920s Paris bistro.
To the right, an eclectic crowd, mostly in black, chats over
martinis and cigarette smoke. To the left, there's the Canal House,
specializing in American cuisine such as roasted Muscovy duck,
grilled veal and Yankee pot roast. Running through all this is a
wait staff that could have been trained to serve Leona Helmsley,
taking care of your every need like good and faithful servants.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this all translates into $$$. Rooms start at a hefty
$359 a night, and are smaller than comparable accommodations
uptown. However, from Dec. 20-27, the SoHo Grand is shaving the
prices of its rooms for the holidays, to $279 a night. There will
also be a special holiday dinner menu in the restaurant, and
seasonal entertainment in the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Decorated in muted tones of beige, taupe and gray, the rooms are
built around the cool lines of metal _ copper lighting, iron racks,
porcelain pedestal sinks and stark black and white photographs
framed in silver.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the SoHo Grand's real drawing card, however, is out the
window. If you request a room on the hotel's north side (which you
should), you gaze out upon the imposing Manhattan skyline _ not the
glass obelisks so common on the Upper East Side, but the underbelly
deco buildings that ring the south side of Manhattan like something
out of a 1930s crime novel. It looks a lot like the Naked City, or
the old opening shots on ``The Edge of Night.''
</P>
<P>
   It puts you in the mood to explore the streets, which are lined
with art galleries and tiny restaurants tucked inside iron-fronted
warehouses. Spend an evening just wandering from gallery to
designer shop to bar, nibbling on cheese and wine.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect the slick shopping/dining experiences of the Upper
East Side or Fifth Avenue. The entire SoHo district is much more
like the city's nonfiltered, Bohemian cousin _ block after block of
steamy espresso bars, independent bookstores, designer shopping
(Dolce to Todd Oldham), and galleries filled with provocative
pieces. The area is still undergoing the transformation from
warehouse zone to tourist destination, and your stroll through the
neighborhood will take you by as many gritty loading docks and
boarded-up doors as avant-garde window displays. But with the SoHo
Grand as a welcome anchor, this rejuvenated part of the city is
ripe for exploring and offers a fresh, alternative perspective on
New York's skyline, food and art.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: The SoHo Grand is at 310 West Broadway at Canal
Street. Reservations: 212-965-3000. Online, you may view the the
hotel and make your reservations at http://www.sohogrand.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
