<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAYFILMS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL DECEMBER 6
 &HT;    Holiday movie season: Stars name of the game
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's beginning to look a lot like a ``Psycho'' Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   No, no one's saying the remake of the Hitchcock classic will
necessarily overwhelm the competition at the box office this
holiday season. Indeed, director Gus Van Sant's updated version of
the 1960 black-and-white chiller just opened two days ago, so the
jury's still out on whether ``Psycho'' is anything more than a
really big name capable of pulling folks into theaters.
</P>
<P>
   That's this month o' movies in a nutshell: From Robin Williams
to John Travolta (twice), from Julia Roberts to Meg Ryan (twice),
the names attached to many of the season's movies are big. And so
are the questions about what, exactly, we'll see up there onscreen.
Like a pile of gaudily wrapped gifts during the December holidays,
this film season surely will contain a few surprises _ both good
and bad. What follows is a sneak peek.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday Film Guide
</P>
<P>
   Haven't we already seen this?
</P>
<P>
   ``You've Got Mail''
</P>
<P>
   No longer sleepless in Seattle, this time Tom Hanks and Meg Ryan
are feuding bookstore owners in this remake of the 1940 movie ``The
Shop Around the Corner.'' Will their shared animosity make for as
cute an eventual
</P>
<P>
   coupling as the cross-country, radio-spawned romance of
``Sleepless''? On the plus side: We already love them together. On
the minus side: That could make the sense of disappointment worse.
</P>
<P>
   Starts: Dec. 18
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Trek: Insurrection''
</P>
<P>
   Boldly going where no man used to go until they started churning
out umpteen ``Star Trek'' TV franchises and movie sequels to
sequels. At least this one features Patrick Stewart, Jonathan
Frakes and many of the superior (translation: still spry and
believable as space pioneers) ``Next Generation'' crew. Plus: No
William Shatner to laugh at. Minus: No William Shatner to laugh at.
</P>
<P>
   Starts: Friday
</P>
<P>
   ``Mighty Joe Young''
</P>
<P>
   Just in time for Christmas, the ultimate ``I brought someone
home with me and everything went wrong'' story. Actually, this tale
of a kindly gorilla guardian (Charlize Theron) whose hairy charge
gets loose in L.A. is a remake of the 1949 film. Plus: Getting to
watch the ape Joe outsmart the human scientist (Bill Paxton) who's
on his trail. Minus: With Disney behind the special effects this
time, it can't possibly be as cheesily campy as the original.
</P>
<P>
   Starts: Dec. 25
</P>
<P>
   Look who's talking . . . er, singing
</P>
<P>
   ``The Prince of Egypt''
</P>
<P>
   Sort of ``The Greatest Story Ever Told'' _ by a cartoonist.
DreamWorks hopes the combination of hot voices (everyone from
actors Val Kilmer and Michelle
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer to singers Mariah Carey and Whitney Houston) and
resurgent interest in spirituality will make for a hit animated
tale of Moses. Plus: The Carey-Houston duet alone is making for
plenty of advance buzz. Minus: DreamWorks' animated ``Antz'' was
pretty much an ain't.
</P>
<P>
   Starts: Dec. 18
</P>
<P>
   ``Little Voice''
</P>
<P>
   A shy young woman builds a show business career by replicating
the singing of Judy Garland and other revered voices of years past.
Plus: Stars Ewan McGregor for the Gen X'ers and Michael Caine and
Brenda Blethyn for the older cineastes. Minus: There was only one
Judy Garland. Maybe that's enough.
</P>
<P>
   Starts: Dec. 25
</P>
<P>
   You think your family's mixed up . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Stepmom''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Sarandon plays a divorced mother of two whose ex becomes
engaged to the younger, sexier Julia Roberts. But wait, that's not
even the really bad news. When Sarandon's character gets a
life-threatening illness, she has to learn to get along with
Roberts for the kids' sake. Plus: The promise of fabulous acting,
tinged with just a hint of a catfight. Minus: If Meryl Streep
couldn't make us get into this whole dying mom reconciling with a
younger, successful woman thing in ``One True Thing,'' what hope is
there for ``Stepmom''?
</P>
<P>
   Starts: Dec. 25
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack Frost''
</P>
<P>
   If you believe that a successful musician would really yearn to
spend more time at home, then you'll probably also believe he could
come back as a snowman after perishing in a car accident. Plus: Jim
Henson creatures and a welcome return to films of the too-long-gone
Michael Keaton. Minus: First we had to see Keaton largely obscured
by his ``Batman'' suit; now he's largely obscured by snow and
(presumably) a carrot nose.
</P>
<P>
   Starts: Friday
</P>
<P>
   ``Dancing at Lughnasa''
</P>
<P>
   It's the ultimate Chick-Mick flick as Streep heads a stellar
cast in this tale of five Irish sisters sharing a house and a
socially and morally restricted life. Culminates in an Irish dance
scene that, if done right, will make entire theaters feel like
Riverdancin'. Plus: the cast, the clogging! Minus: A house full of
dour Irish sisters? Sounds about as exciting as a convent.
</P>
<P>
   Starts: Dec. 25
</P>
<P>
   ``Down in the Delta''
</P>
<P>
   A family riven by crime and drugs in big-city Chicago moves back
to small-town Mississippi to try to repair their lives. Plus:
Fabulous cast includes Alfre Woodard and Wesley Snipes. Minus: Maya
Angelou's an incredible writer, but that doesn't guarantee she can
direct as well.
</P>
<P>
   Starts: Dec. 25
</P>
<P>
   Money changes everything
</P>
<P>
   ``Waking Ned Devine''
</P>
<P>
   First the holder of a winning lottery ticket in a small Irish
town doesn't step forward. Then, he turns out to be dead. But that
doesn't stop anyone from trying to get the money anyway. Plus:
David Kelly and Ian Bannen reportedly score as a couple of
septuagenarian schemers who'll even go buck naked to try and score
big bucks. Minus: ``The Full Monty'' was one thing, but do we
really want to see naked 70-year-olds?
</P>
<P>
   Starts: Friday
</P>
<P>
   ``A Simple Plan''
</P>
<P>
   When a couple of no-good brothers discover a downed airplane,
they valiantly save . . . a duffel bag containing some $4 million.
Which simply turns them no-good-er and upon each other. Plus: Funny
premise stars Bill Paxton and Billy Bob Thornton. Minus: Can
one-note actor Paxton and the somewhat outrageous Thornton remain
amusing without wearing on us?
</P>
<P>
   Starts: Friday
</P>
<P>
   Well, why not?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Faculty''
</P>
<P>
   In which we learn that we weren't crazy as teenagers . . . high
school really was a scary, dangerous place to be. A group of
super-smart teenage students do battle with an evil pod of alien
(and we're not talking about the type with green cards) teachers.
Plus: script by Kevin ``Scream'' Williamson. Minus: Young, hip cast
(Elijah Wood, Salma Hayek, Usher) raises concerns about occasional
misfires from Williamson (``I Know What You Did Last Summer'').
</P>
<P>
   Starts: Dec. 25
</P>
<P>
   ``Gods and Monsters''
</P>
<P>
   And you thought Dr. Frankenstein had a strange relationship with
his creations. Wait'll you see this story about ``Frankenstein''
director James Whale's relationship with his young gardener. Plus:
Director Bill Condon has already picked up some film festival
awards for ``Gods,'' and the Oscar buzz is big for star Ian
McKellen. Minus: Its status as an art house film could keep
audiences away.
</P>
<P>
   Starts: Dec. 18
</P>
<P>
   ``Patch Adams''
</P>
<P>
   Robin Williams plays a onetime mental patient who becomes a
doctor and takes on the HMOs. We wish. No, seriously, Williams'
patient-turned-doctor has an unconventional approach to healing.
Plus: Williams has ably walked this comedy-drama fine line in
``Good Will Hunting,'' ``Dead Poets Society,'' etc. Minus: Williams
has stumbled over that same line in ``Being Human,'' ``Fathers'
Day,'' etc.
</P>
<P>
   Starts: Dec. 25
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare in Love''
</P>
<P>
   Gwyneth Paltrow stars as the bewitching young actress with whom
the playwright falls in love as he's struggling to finish ``Romeo
and Juliet.'' Plus: Paltrow was surprisingly good in ``Emma,''
another English costume drama. Minus: Audiences may be tired of the
overexposed Paltrow. Not to mention Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   Starts: Dec. 25
</P>
<P>
   When are we gonna see this, already?!
</P>
<P>
   They're two of the year's most hotly anticipated movies, but you
won't be able to see either of them before 1999 _ unless you live
in New York or Los Angeles. Getting Oscar consideration is the
thinking behind these limited Christmas Day releases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Thin Red Line''
</P>
<P>
   Pity poor Terrence Malick. The renowned (``Badlands''),
semi-reclusive director finally decides to work again, and he has
the misfortune of making a World War II movie in the same year as
Steven Spielberg's ``Saving Private Ryan.'' Plus: a James Jones
novel for inspiration and an all-star cast, including John
Travolta, Sean Penn and Nick Nolte. Minus: Unless the Allies lose,
nothing can top
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan's'' drama and poignancy.
</P>
<P>
   Starts: Dec. 25 in New York and Los Angeles, January in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Civil Action''
</P>
<P>
   Taken from the best seller, the true, gut-wrenching story of
eight Boston-area families whose children die of leukemia _ most
likely linked to toxic chemicals in the water. It's a case of the
little guys up against two powerful corporations accused of doing
the leaking, until lawyer Jan Schlittman (John Travolta) takes the
case at great personal and professional risk to himself. Plus: Cast
includes Robert Duvall and Travolta, who hasn't done a
down-and-dirty lawyer before. Minus: Science, suffering kids and
legal jargon could make for a squirm-inducing experience.
</P>
<P>
   Starts: Dec. 25 in New York and Los Angeles,
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 8 in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
