<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3479 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTMAS-KITSCH-HNS &LR;      12-04 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMAS-KITSCH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING OF CHRISTMAS KITSCH KEEPS ON SINGING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Nobody knows better than Dr. Elmo how much
listening to ``Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer'' is like hearing
cats yowl on the back fence, yodeling their moon love to the whole
neighborhood. That's why his new album, ``Dr. Elmo's Twisted
Christmas,'' includes the song, ``Don't Make Me Play That Grandma
Song Again.''
</P>
<P>
   But as sales for ``Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer'' reach 5
million _ the single passed the quadruple platinum mark a dozen
years ago _ Dr. Elmo is laughing all the way to the savings and
loan.
</P>
<P>
   Every year Elmo finds himself looking at new pretenders to the
throne of Christmas Hoot, and every year he outlasts them all.
</P>
<P>
   RuPaul's ``Ho Ho Ho'' album, featuring ``I Saw Daddy Kissing
Santa Claus,'' is in the race, along with ``Jingle Cats,'' ``Jingle
Babies,'' ``Bachelor Pad Christmas,'' ``Punk Rock Christmas,''
``Kazoo Christmas'' _ which comes with its own plastic kazoo _ and
``Tales from the Crypt, Christmas,'' including the catchy, ``Deck
the Hall With Parts of Charlie.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Elmo, aka Elmo Shropshire, is ready for the challenge. A
veterinarian who once owned the Arguello Pet Hospital in San
Francisco, Elmo has settled in Larkspur, Calif., where he still
works at making animals feel better while, some would say, making
human beings feel worse.
</P>
<P>
   When he first recorded ``Grandma'' in 1979, said Elmo, the owner
of the studio thought he was crazy. So did a whole bunch of people
who listened to the song the first time it was played on the air,
by disc jockey Gene Nelson on San Francisco station KSFO. Nelson,
told to stop playing the tune, kept at it, picking it up again the
year after, and the year after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``For five years, we never did have a record label on it,''
Elmo, 62, said in a telephone interview during a Christmas tour
through Illinois. ``But people kept calling in to request it, just
like people kept calling in to say they hated it. It took about
four or five years for it to break through.''
</P>
<P>
   Once it did, the royalties started rolling in, and Elmo became a
regular at Christmas concerts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grandma'' seems to increase in sales every year, Elmo said.
``When it first caught on and sold four hundred to five hundred
thousand copies, I thought that would be it. But it's been selling
progressively more each year.'' and it's on almost every Greatest
Christmas Hits album.''
</P>
<P>
   It was touch and go at the start, though, said Elmo, who
remembered that when he played the old Boarding House in San
Francisco, ``I was picketed by the Gray Panthers. They were
carrying signs that said, `What's so funny about a dead grandma?'''
</P>
<P>
   The dead-grandma theme, Elmo said, came from a friend, Randy
Brooks. ``His grandmother used to overindulge a lot at Christmas,
so I think the reindeer was probably a metaphor for overindulgence.
Grandma just got run over by overindulgence.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, when the song first came out, Elmo said, ``I
was primarily interested in playing the banjo in a bluegrass band.
I really didn't want to sing, especially after I heard myself sing,
but this thing kind of fell in my lap. Everyone laughed at me
anytime I tried to do a serious song, so I decided to go with the
flow.''
</P>
<P>
   Going with the flow led to a monster hit and an album with
Elmo's ex-wife, Patsy, that included ``Senor Santa Claus,''
``Rudolph, the Red-Nosed Reindeer'' and ``Percy, the Puny
Poinsettia,'' the flip side of the ``Grandma'' single. Once he hit
the charts, Elmo never stopped producing songs, including
``Grandma's Killer Fruitcake'' and ``Granpa's Going to Sue the
Pants off Santa,'' from ``Dr. Elmo's Twisted Christmas,'' as well
as his latest tune, ``Kenneth Starr Is Coming to Town,'' with
lyrics that include, ``He's making a list of every affair,
especially those involving big hair,'' and ``You'll see him on the
TV, and waving from his car, you'll know more than you'll want to
know about what to do with a cigar.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't be hard to identify Elmo's voice on any of those songs.
It's not hard to identify Elmo's voice, period _ that strange,
grating gargle with a Kentucky twinge is the way Elmo sounds, all
the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny,'' he said. ``I always think I sound like everyone
else, but when people hear me talk, they can tell that I'm the guy
who did `Grandma.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once again Elmo's ``Grandma'' is being challenged in the stores,
but this year's crop of oddness is pretty bland. ``Bachelor Pad
Christmas'' has no life to it; RuPaul is good for maybe one
playing; and Swingin' Barnyard Christmas, with 12 animal versions
of ``Jingle Bells,'' is a sad attempt to cash in on cat and dog
Christmas ditties.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbin's Equestrian Orchestra is nothing but noises set to a
``Jingle Bells'' background, ditto for the Monkey House Yuletide
Choir and Porkchops and Applesauce. The only unaccompanied animals
on the album are the Moo-Tones, and it's hard to tell whether
they're cows or very clever humans. Other novelty albums, such as
``Kazoo Christmas,'' are too sane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bummed Out Christmas,'' on the other hand, may give Elmo a run
for his money. In addition to the Everly Brothers' ``Christmas Eve
Can Kill You,'' ``Christmas in Viet Nam'' and the Staple Singers'
``Who Took the Merry Out of Christmas?'' the album offers the
singular ``Christmas in Prison'' by Doug Legacy and the Legends,
which includes immortal lines like, ``Her heart is as big as this
whole goddamned jail, she's as sweet as saccharin at a drugstore,
wholesale'' and ``She reminds me of a chess game with someone I
admire, or a picnic in the rain after a prairie fire. ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Elmo can take his hat off to that kind of inspired singing, but
he feels secure in the knowledge that ``Grandma Got Run Over by a
Reindeer'' will stay at the top of the novelties list. Each year
there seems to be more call for Elmo.
</P>
<P>
   It's the live shows, though, that are closest to Elmo's heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wonderful, to be up on stage, to feel the energy of the
audience,'' he said. ``It brings a lot of old codgers to life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Bill Monroe at the Grand Ole Opry once. He was old, 84
or so, and could just barely move. But the minute he stood in the
spotlight he completely came to life, dancing and everything. And
once he stepped off the stage, he reverted back to being old
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Elmo is hoping stage shows keep him young, and he expects to be
performing under the lights as long as there's a demand for it.
Which, in Monroe years, would mean at least two more decades of
listening to ``Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer,'' the
blackboard-scraping, cat-yodeling classic of Christmas that has
made Elmo one happy man.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
