<TEXT>
<P>
   PageExpress budget for the week of Nov. 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   PageExpress, a new service from The New York Times Syndicate,
consists of paginated pages built with content from Cox Newspapers
and The New York Times News Service. The pages are easy to retrieve
from a web site. You can use them just as they are or customize any
or all of the elements -- text, fonts, photos and graphics -- to
suit your needs.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on these pages, or to view a sample, use
your web browser to visit http://nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   For the password to download and use the pages, call John
Gardner, pagination consultant for The New York Times Syndicate, at
917-224-4381 or e-mail him at pages &LR; nytsyn.com.
</P>
<P>
   Unless otherwise noted, all pages are available for download at
the website now.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS -- When you cozy up with one of Jan Brett's exquisitely
detailed childrens books, it's almost like you're being let in on a
secret: that you're really still a kid who yearns to believe in the
magic,in the fairy tale. Which is precisely what the New England
author-illustrator, whose books have sold more than 12 million
copies, intends. WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS --The strange relationship
between the late Raymond Carver and Gordon Lish, as D.T. Max wrote
recently in The New York Times Sunday Magazine, raises issues that
could almost be calledtruth-in-labeling. WITH: REVIEWS -- The
seventh and latest novel in Albert's China Bayles mystery series,
``Chile Death,'' shows maturation through strength of dialogue.
Also, Summer vacation turns into a time of healing in ``Summer at
Little Lava.'' WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS -- (Available by 2 p.m. Friday, Dec. 4) -- Like Santas
elves, some White House staffers regard Christmas preparation as a
never-ending job. First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton will unveil the
1998 Christmas theme and decorations at the White House, beginning
a traditional round of seasonal tours and parties at the
presidential home. During the following three weeks, about 15,000
guests will marvel at Christmas trees laden with 50,000 lights and
handmade ornaments from across America, hear seasonal songs of
musicians from every state, and consume 50,000 cookies, half a ton
of fruitcake and 250 gallons of eggnog. Such festivities take a tad
of forethought. The fruitcake, for instance, was baked in June and
stacked in refrigerators in two-pound blocks to await the holiday
parties.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT -- (Available by 2 p.m. Thursday, Dec. 3) -- Few
things are less telegenic in a made-for-TV world than the opening
each business day of the New York Stock Exchange. But CNBC, the
gimlet-eyed cable network, is shattering TVs business news
conventions with its eccentric blend of financial insight and
workaday loopiness. Each morning it counts down to the opening
bell, shows it being rung, then analyzes it with the wry skewering
the tradition invites. WITH: CD REVIEWS --A look at new releases
that ring in the holiday cheer.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD -- When it comes to all things pastry, even adventurous
home cooks can be backed into a corner by the Pillsbury Dough Boy.
So when the holidays roll around and its time for the required
pumpkin and pecan pies, cooks have played it save with crusts
straight from the freezer at the grocery store. Until now. WITH
SIDE: a review of store-bought piecrusts. WITH: RECIPE -- A flaky
cream cheese piecrust made easy.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY -- Just 20 years ago the choices for a
telephone for your house were simple: Console or wall; Black or
white. But today, consumers can go to the electronics store and
find a selection of about 50 cordless phones, 30 corded phones, at
least a dozen cellular phone models and a separate display rack
full of telephone/answering machine combinations. WITH: DIGITAL
DIVIDE: The once lofty goal to open up the high-tech glories of the
Internet to all of Americas schoolchildren has degenerated into an
increasingly nasty partisan squabble. WITH: TECH BRIEFS So far,
most computer games have been devoted to digitizing what we do:
paying taxes, playing football, flying planes and hunting deer.
Now, companies are coming out with games for your PC that make fun
of what we do. WITH: TECHNOBUDDY -- If the bright kids are any
indicator, mechanical kits are out these days. Instead, childrens
experimental energy goes into creating Web pages and learning about
the Internet and playing video games, but there is a whole
generation growing up missing the delight of actually creating a
gadget from pieces of bell wire, pencil leads and razor blades.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE &AMP; HEALTH -- When Jean Dible dies, shes going to college.
Specifically, to the Medical College of Georgia. Dible has decided
to donate her body to medical science. Not only does she see it as
practical, but also a way to leave a legacy. Whole body donation is
a vital and age-old practice for medical schools and other
programs, such as those for physical therapists, nurses,
chiropractors, researchers and surgeons. However, the need for
whole bodies isn't as well publicized as the need for organs for
transplants, and many people don't know about this end-of-life
option. WITH: Raising children with positive mental health is ``not
wishful thinking,'' but can be accomplished through concrete
measures and actions, according to a mental health expert. WITH:
What looks like a lollipop, tastes like a cough drop and has some
doctors concerned? Answer: A new product called Cough Pops. This
cough drop on a stick is aimed at children and adults who need
temporary relief from minor cold and sore throat discomfort. WITH:
The southern United States accounts for more than half of all AIDS
cases among people in rural areas, according to a recently released
report by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL -- This time of year, the magnificent sounds of the
Mormon Tabernacle wrap listeners in their warmth. Highlights of the
world-famous Mormon Tabernacle Choir are the annual performances of
traditional Christmas carols and choral works. WITH: VERONA, ITALY
-- Theres no shortage of romance in this town where reminders of
the star-crossed love between Romeo and Juliet are everywhere. Its
warming to stroll the streets and piazzas that the two of them
prowled, looking for alcoves and passageways where they could
snuggle and kiss. WITH: TRAVEL NOTES -- Boston has Monet,
Washington has Van Gogh. While these are the hottest tickets in the
museum world now, they are not the only great art shows available.
WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS -- And there go the Beanie Babies in their
bobsleds! This riotous race is just one way youngsters learn while
having fun at the new Winter Science Program at Smugglers Notch,
Vt., others.
</P>
<P>
   WHEELS -- While other sport and sporty coupes in a variety of
performance and price levels have come and gone (remember the Dodge
Stealth, Ford Probe and the recently axed Acura NSX?), Mitsubishi's
tidy little Eclipse rolls on with a popularity anchored by its
versatility. Want a looks-good, feels-good sporty car with an
entry-level price? Check out the Eclipse. WITH: SHARP DRIVING -- As
if just plain old everyday traffic wasn't bad enough for most
folks, how are you to deal with the additional pressures of holiday
travel? Plan ahead.
</P>
