<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Austin woos Legislature with parking
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If you spend half your life making change so you
can park downtown, you've probably got several questions about the
new City of Austin policy that exempts Texas lawmakers from being
ticketed at parking meters.
</P>
<P>
   Like, for example, how do you get a cushy deal like this?
</P>
<P>
   Simple. Run for office.
</P>
<P>
   The parking perk was just one of several announced Monday by
Austin Mayor Kirk Watson and other city officials. The city also is
giving each state representative and senator a fancy $35 snow globe
from Saks Fifth Avenue and free golf at city courses.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for these gifts, Mayor Watson says, is to make it
easier for Austin to work with the Legislature, not because the
city is afraid the Legislature will clobber Austin during the
coming session for annexing 27,700 mainly ticked off suburbanites
against their will.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, sure. And I'm a Hungarian ballerina. This is a snow job
with snow globes, OK? But let's forget the souvenirs and answer
your questions about this new free parking program.
</P>
<P>
   Question No. 1: Do state lawmakers everywhere get to skate like
this?
</P>
<P>
   Nope. Jeff Tolbert, a parking meter reader with the City of
Albany, N.Y., the New York state capital, said New York state
representatives' cars parked at expired meters in Albany get
ticketed just like anybody else's.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it expires, you have to give it a ticket no matter what car
is there,'' Tolbert said. ``Except for a police car. I don't want
to mess up my paycheck.''
</P>
<P>
   Question No. 2: Will this program help Austin's needy?
</P>
<P>
   It should. Since the lawmakers don't have to feed the meters,
they'll have plenty of quarters in their pockets to hand out to the
panhandlers.
</P>
<P>
   Question No. 3: Should a lawmaker parking at a City of Austin
meter mark his car for immunity from ticketing by leaving his new
$35 Saks Fifth Avenue snow globe on the dashboard?
</P>
<P>
   No, that's not the way the state lawmakers' cars will be
identified as being exempt from $15 parking tickets, said John
Hrncir, government relations officer for the City of Austin. The
license number of the lawmaker's car _ one car per lawmaker _ will
be fed into the city's parking systems computer, Hrncir explained.
</P>
<P>
   Question No. 4: Will this parking perk tick people off?
</P>
<P>
   Of course it will. This is Austin, international center of the
chronically riled.
</P>
<P>
   Question No. 5: Does this mean state lawmakers will also get
their names on the guest list of Austin clubs such as Liberty
Lunch?
</P>
<P>
   I don't know, because when I asked that question, Hrncir just
laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Question No. 6: If a lawmaker wanted to, could he park his car
at a meter downtown in front of his favorite restaurant and leave
it there until, say, March?
</P>
<P>
   Hrncir wasn't sure. So maybe somebody should try it and see what
happens.
</P>
<P>
   Question No. 7: Now let's just say, for argument purposes, that
a state legislator was driving down, uh, South Congress Avenue, and
that the, uh, hookers returned to South Congress for the coming
session, and the legislator decided to pull over. Under the new
rule, could he park for free at a South Congress parking meter?
</P>
<P>
   No. But only because there are no parking meters on South
Congress Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso's humor column appears on Sundays, Wednesdays and
Fridays. He can be reached at 445-3606 or at jkelsostatesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
