u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILNER-COLUMN05-COX     12-04 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILNER-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Annual Book Fair was like old times for Mad Dog, Inc.
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the Third Annual Book Fair in Austin, Texas, recently it was
like old home week for me and a rabble of my old running buddies.
In case you haven't heard, I've got a new book just out and in
discerning book stores across the state;
</P>
<P>
   so, I was invited to this year's Book Fair as a ``featured
author.''
</P>
<P>
   Title of my new book is ``Confessions of a Maddog,'' (U. of
North Texas Press) referring to a group of Texas writers (writers
of song and story) who in our younger and friskier years in the
1960s and '70s formed a sort of social and literary club called Mad
Dog, Inc., Motto: ``Doing indefinable services to mankind.''
</P>
<P>
   Our slogan was: ``Anything that's not a mystery is guesswork.''
</P>
<P>
   Members included such stalwart ``famous authors'' as Bud Shrake,
Gary Cartwright, Dan Jenkins, Jerry Jeff Walker and his wife,
Susan, Willie Nelson, and...well, you get the idea, I suppose. As
someone has written somewhere lately we were, ``a group of
hard-working and harder living writers of story and song.''
</P>
<P>
   We did enjoy ourselves much of the time back then and, due to
the rather eccentric character of most, if not all, the Mad Dog
membership, a close observer could recall, if he chose to do so, a
whole bunch of, shall we say, amusing tall tales that were mostly
true.
</P>
<P>
   I chose to do so, and my new book is the result.
</P>
<P>
   So, anyway, I was invited to participate in the Third Annual
Texas Book Fair thing in Austin, an event chaired by Laura Bush to
raise money for state libraries from book sales and a high priced
dinner the opening evening. The dinner this year starred Larry King
as master of ceremonies and famous authors David Halberstam and
Frank McCourt reading from their books.
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam is a Pulitzer Prize winner who has written several
best sellers and McCourt's latest book, ``Angela's Ashes,'' has
been on most best seller lists for months.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't attend the dinner. Even us famous authors had to pay
$200 per for that deal so I chose to pass it up. But my sources
told me it was a success. Bud Shrake, who's nobody's patsy as far
as expressing his opinions, what ever they are, told me Halberstam
was ``very interesting'' and McCourt was ``a real performer.'' This
equaled a rave review because Shrake bores pretty easy.
</P>
<P>
   My appearance was on Saturday in a room in the capital
building's new extension, which was described by the same Bud
Shrake as looking like it was designed by Albert Speer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is Albert Speer?'' I asked simply.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one who was Hitler's architect,'' Shrake explained kindly.
``Not the one who lives over in Woodville.''
</P>
<P>
   We were at the time searching for the conference room in the
capital extension where we would help form a panel to discuss the
``Mad Dogs'' discussed in my book, ``Confessions of a Maddog.'' We
were to be accompanied on the stage for the panel discussion by
other Mad Dogs: Gary Cartwright, Larry L. King and Jan Reid, all
fairly well known writers of one sort or another.
</P>
<P>
   I was amazed by the enthusiastic response we got. I remembered
that after
</P>
<P>
   my first book came out some time ago, granted and in different
circumstances, my autographing sessions at bookstores were less
than crowded. In Waco at one bookstore there, the manager had free
Cokes set out beside the table where my books and I sat, ready with
pen in hand to smile and autograph, and the only person who paid
any attention was a small boy who wanted a Coke and was jerked away
by his father who frowned as if I might be a child molester.
</P>
<P>
   But in Austin at the Book Fair, the room where we told our Mad
Dog tales held a standing-room-only crowd, and in the signing tent
afterward all my books available were sold, and during our panel
discussion the crowd actually laughed out loud time and again and
broke into applause once or twice.
</P>
<P>
   My wife said she had more fun that day than she's had since our
wedding, which was attended by the same people who were on the Mad
Dog panel.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know for sure what that means, but it's probably
significant in some fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes for Cox newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
