<HEADER>
A3506 &Cx1f; ttj-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-04 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRINKING PROPOSAL IS NO PICNIC IN THE PARK 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ All this time I've been hiding my bottles of
Ridge Zinfandel in the picnic basket and drinking out of paper
cups. I didn't know it was legal to drink in the park.
</P>
<P>
   You mean I could have been drinking out of real wine glasses and
not drinking my beer like a bum from brown paper bags?
</P>
<P>
   That was my first reaction when San Francisco Supervisor Amos
Brown introduced an ordinance banning alcohol in certain San
Francisco parks with a history of alcohol and drug abuse problems.
He said it's aimed at chronic drunks, those who ``don't have
getting up on their mind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mission Playground, Garfield Park, all the parks in the
Mission have a problem with drunks sitting down all day,'' said
Ethel Newlin of the St. John's Educational Center in the Mission
District.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being drunks, they urinate, defecate and do all the things you
have to do if you sit in one place all day, and in a real small
area where these little children play.''
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like a no-brainer to ban drinking in such parks,
right? Wrong. This is San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's going to be a fight,'' said Brown, whose
proposed drinking ban in parks goes before the board on Monday.
``It's interesting that people are asking for an increase in the
quality of life, and yet you have groups that don't want it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If this ban is adopted, will it be uniformly applied?'' said
John Crew of the American Civil Liberties Union, sounding like a
guy who'd love to go to court if some yuppies were allowed to sip
Chardonnay in the Panhandle while a guy on Thunderbird got rousted
and sent on his way with a $76 citation.
</P>
<P>
   Crew demolished a previous ordinance against sitting on
sidewalks by arguing that it would have to apply to yuppies
drinking caffe lattes on sidewalks on Chestnut Street.
</P>
<P>
   He suggests that the poor will be unfairly targeted by banning
drinking in homeless haunts like Boeddeker Park but allowing it in
tourist spots like Washington Square Park.
</P>
<P>
   Crew said there are already laws against urinating in public and
public inebriation. ``People need to think very long and hard
before we pass new laws.''
</P>
<P>
   I've got a feeling we will. Or at least we'll talk very long and
hard.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, publicity about the proposed ban on drinking in
parks will let people know it's legal to drink in parks _ certain
ones, at least until the ACLU goes into action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never knew drinking was allowed in parks until recently,''
said Lou Maunupau, the energetic director of the Mission
Playground. ``The people who were drinking didn't even know.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, some of them did. Police Officer Steve Thoma, who works
with Maunupau to make the once-troubled little park a haven for
kids, said, ``Guys drinking on the sidewalk would suddenly jump
into the park and say, `Hello, officer.'''
</P>
<P>
   He made a gesture of a drunk raising a bottle in toast.
</P>
<P>
   As the law stands, people can't drink on sidewalks, but they can
in parks. They just can't be inebriated in parks, or drink in park
buildings, playgrounds, restrooms or pools.
</P>
<P>
   Mara Raider of the Coalition on Homelessness said they
discovered this a few years ago when the police were citing
homeless for drinking in parks. ``The police were p----d,'' she
said. ``They began saying `How can we let tourists drink wine in
the park, and cite homeless for drinking 40-ouncers?'''
</P>
<P>
   The solution was simple, she said. ``Drinking would be banned in
the Panhandle and Stanyan Meadow at the end of Haight Street, where
historically the homeless drink. It wouldn't be banned in Sharon
Meadow where picnickers drink.''
</P>
<P>
   She says the ban is political. This is a town, after all, where
two mayors have lost elections because of the homeless and the
homeless still haven't gone away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's (Mayor Willie) Brown's third year in office, and it makes
it look like he's doing something so he can get re-elected,''
Raider said.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Brown denies that the proposed ban on alcohol in
parks is aimed at the homeless. He says it's the result of careful
study and much input from a public concerned about its parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's aimed at those who are a clear and present danger,'' he
said. ``We want safe and clean parks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Alcohol is a trigger to more problems,'' said Maunupau,
director of the Mission Playground. He wants to coach and teach
kids in safety, and his bottom line is: ``No booze, no guns, no
knives. I don't care what you do, but don't do it here.''
</P>
<P>
   Maunupau runs a great little park. I just wonder what happens
when masses of al fresco drinkers are told to move along. I mean
before the ACLU takes the city to court.
</P>
<P>
   The city's legislative analyst says the ordinance may increase
``the safety and enjoyment of certain parks for responsible park
users.''
</P>
<P>
   But the analyst also says, ``This ordinance may have the
unintended effect of increasing the number of persons drinking in
adjacent streets and public places due to displacement from park
areas covered in the ban.''
</P>
<P>
   The homeless and the drunk are always with us, and now they may
be moving to our doorways, or joining our picnics in Sharon Meadow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that pate de fois gras? I believe it goes with my Night
Train red.''
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, this ordinance is doomed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
