<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3521 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CROATIA-TORAH-$ADV05-     12-04 1810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROATIA-TORAH-$ADV05-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: in 21st graf, corrects to read 'In April 1996, ...' sted of
'1995'
 &HT;    CROATIAN JEWS RETURN RELIGIOUS TREASURES TO THEIR RIGHTFUL HOME
 &HT;    With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Dec. 5 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By Susannah A. Nesmith and Mary Ellen Flannery 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBROVNIK, Croatia _ For almost five hundred years, through
earthquakes and war, the tiny Jewish community here protected a
cherished and precious deerskin torah from the 13th Century.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, they wrapped it like a baby and safely hid
it beneath roof tiles, along with 17th- and 18th-Century Venetian
wraps, a pair of gold-crowned Torahs and even a candelabra taken
down from the ceiling of the synagogue. In 1991, when the synagogue
took a direct hit from a Serbian shell, the religious treasures
were unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1995, the treasures of Dubrovnik were lost, not to
foreign armies or Croatian Nazis, but to a Croatian-American Jew
living in Manhattan. Dr. Michael Papo, now living on Singer Island
in South Florida, arranged for their restoration and display at
Yeshiva University in New York City, and then fought their return
to here to Dubrovnik.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after three years spent in court battles in New York and
the Croatian capital, Zagreb, the Jewish community here is quietly
celebrating the successful return of the treasures.
</P>
<P>
   Members are also celebrating the support they got from the
Croatian government at a time when its leaders, both officially and
unofficially, are reviving symbols reminiscent of its Nazi past.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, at the same time a priest widely regarded as a Nazi
collaborator was being beatified, the Croatian government was
paying the legal fees of a New York law firm fighting Papo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We owe a large debt of gratitude to the Croatian government
for helping,'' said Sabrina Horovic, daughter of the president of
the Jewish community here. ``We could not have succeeded without
that help.''
</P>
<P>
   Papo wonders at this success -- it might be a victory for
Horovic, but not for the Jewish community, he said. The treasures
are hidden away in Dubrovnik, where visitors aren't allowed a
glimpse of the famous Sephardic characters. There is no public
display, which is what Papo wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always planned to return them, providing the war ended and
they would be safe,'' Papo said. ``It's sad that people perceive
this as a fight between the Jews. It's a fight between a
congregation and an opportunist. Those people saw an opportunity to
make money.''
</P>
<P>
   Papo traces his lineage to a courtesan in Queen Isabella's
court, who left Spain with the torah when Isabella expelled the
Spanish Jews -- the Sephardic Jews -- in 1492. (One theory has
Christopher Columbus as an expelled Jew.) Along the spine of this
torah is the word Tolentino, Papo's family name, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those Jews came to Dubrovnik, after stopping in Italy, and found
an established synagogue, built on top of a narrow stone house.
It's one of the two oldest in Europe, built in 1408, and about the
size of the vestibule of the nearby Catholic cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a host of anti-Semitic rules -- Jews could only hire
older women for housework -- Jewish merchants came from all over
Europe to settle in Dubrovnik, a thriving city-state on the
Adriatic Sea. For three centuries, they thrived and kept homes
decorated with European tapestries and embroidery from the finest
textile houses of Venice, Paris and Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   But after World War II began, and Croatia joined forces with
Nazi Germany, there were less than a dozen Jews left in Dubrovnik
-- including Papo's aunt and uncles. Papo and his father survived
an Italian concentration camp, his mother did not, and Papo vowed
to care for the treasures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been the guardians for 500 years, now it was up to me
to keep it safe,'' Papo said. He was elected in 1987 as president
of the Dubrovnik Jewish community -- although he never moved back
to Dubrovnik after World War II -- for a two-year term. No
president was elected after him, until the mid-1990's.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how Papo managed to get the religious treasures
out of Croatia. What is clear, however, is that in late 1994 and
early 1995 he somehow had them removed from the synagogue and sent
to Yeshiva University to be placed on display in its museum.
</P>
<P>
   Papo, who apparently removed the treasures without the
community's blessing, dismisses most of the Jews living in
Dubrovnik now as non-religious. He calls Sabrina Horovic ``an
ethnic rabble-rouser, and a thief,'' whose eye is only on the money
that can be raised using the Jewish treasures.
</P>
<P>
   ``He presented himself as the president of our community when he
went to the museum,'' she said. ``That wasn't true. But he said
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, when the exhibition was scheduled to close, Horovic's
father, Dr. Bruno Horovic, began writing the director of the museum
to arrange a way to bring the treasures back to Dubrovnik. Dr.
Horovic had been elected the community's president in late 1994,
and was re-elected both in 1996 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got an answer in January 1995 and it gave us concern,''
Sabrina Horovic said. ``The director's question was, 'With all
respect, I don't know who is in charge of the Jewish community of
Dubrovnik, Dr. Horovic or Dr. Papo?'''
</P>
<P>
   She ended her letter with the message, ``let peace come to your
community.''
</P>
<P>
   In April 1996, the museum agreed to return the treasure and Dr.
Horovic went to New York to accompany it home. But when he got
there, museum officials said they couldn't turn it over to him.
Papo had threatened to sue the museum if the treasure was returned
to Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   The next month, Papo did sue in New York State court.
</P>
<P>
   Claiming he was the sole living descendant of the Sephardic Jews
who acquired most of the treasures, he said neither the Croatian
government, nor Dubrovnik's tiny Jewish community could properly
protect the treasures.
</P>
<P>
   For the next three years, the Jewish community of Dubrovnik, the
Croatian government and Papo fought in court, both in New York and
in Zagreb, which is where a New York judge ruled the case should be
heard.
</P>
<P>
   When the case was moved, the case was lost, Papo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my fault that I couldn't get more public outcry. But I
tried. I spent three years of my life trying to protect it and I
failed,'' Papo said. ``The only good thing -- maybe people are
aware now of the Dubrovnik treasures and maybe nobody will be able
to steal them.''
</P>
<P>
   Still Papo is sad that the treasures are hidden far from the
public's eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``He claimed my father wasn't really very religious, that he
wasn't Jewish enough,'' Sabrina Horovic said, showing the pictures
of Dr. Horovic's 1937 bar mitzvah that were filed with the
</P>
<P>
   courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Papo) claimed the synagogue was completely destroyed and
wasn't a suitable place for the treasures,'' she said, showing
pictures of the fully intact roof which were filed with the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was repaired immediately after the war here by the Croatian
government because it was an important historical and cultural
monument,'' she said. ``In 1996 (when Papo filed suit), there was
nothing wrong with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The war between Serbs, Croats and Muslims in the former
Yugoslavia ended in December 1995 though there was no fighting in
Dubrovnik after 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish community hired the lawyers to argue the case in
Zagreb while the Croatian government paid a law firm in New York to
handle the case there. It was the same Croatian
</P>
<P>
   government that had revived the use of the checkerboard shield
on flags and official documents. The shield had been the symbol of
the Nazi puppet regime during World War II when Croatian fascists
had killed thousands of Serbs and many of the Jews who lived in
Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the ethnic wars after the break-up of Yugoslavia,
nationalistic feelings are
</P>
<P>
   on the rise here and they have often turned discriminatory
towards minorities. Recently, Miss Croatia was dethroned after it
was discovered that she is Muslim. And one of the political parties
here used a picture of a Croatian Nazi leader on its posters during
recent elections.
</P>
<P>
   Most in this fiercely Catholic country celebrated in October
when Pope John Paul II beatified a World War II priest often
accused of standing idly by while thousands were massacred.
Cardinal Alozije Stepinac converted hundreds of Jews and Orthodox
Christian Serbs to Catholicism during the war, leading some to say
he did what he could to save their lives and others to argue he
collaborated with the regime which had as its slogan, ``Kill a
third, expel a third, convert a third.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jews have not been the target of any recent discrimination
here and the government fought hard to recover the Jewish
treasures. The Horovics don't want to talk about the official and
unofficial nationalism in Croatia right now. Instead, they repeat
that they would not have recovered the treasures without the help
of the government.
</P>
<P>
   As each court in Zagreb agreed with the Horovics, Papo appealed
to the next higher court, until finally, in mid-1998, he had
exhausted all the courts in Croatia. A New York judge the decided
that the ruling from the Croatia Supreme Court would stand and the
treasures had to be returned to Dubrovnik. In mid-October, they
came home.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Horovic won't show them to visitors. As he climbs the narrow
staircase up to the
</P>
<P>
   synagogue, he talks about how carefully they must be protected.
He points out the cabinet where the most important torah will be
kept, once it is unpacked. He shows a visitor the bare hook hanging
from the ceiling where the candelabra will return. High on the
walls, grates hide small chambers where the community used to
insist women sit, hidden from the men of the congregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the women sit in the back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That is, when they have services. There is only one rabbi in all
of Croatia, a country where there are only about 5,000 Jews --
living among 4.5 million predominantly Roman Catholic Croats.
Occasionally the synagogue in Dubrovnik holds lay services, without
a rabbi. But usually only for special holidays. With so few
members, many of them intermarried, there isn't much demand for
regular services.
</P>
<P>
   But Horovic and his daughter aren't concerned that the community
will die out. It's been
</P>
<P>
   smaller before. There were only about 10 Jews in Dubrovnik in
the 1980s. And no matter
</P>
<P>
   what, the tiny community will protect its treasures, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jewish community of Dubrovnik has protected these
treasures for hundreds of
</P>
<P>
   years,'' Sabrina Horovic said. ``And we will protect them for
hundreds of years more.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
