<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-PREDICT-$ADV07-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE ARE MORE WRONG PREDICTIONS FOR 2000 AND BEYOND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the next millennium (which apparently still will have two
l's, two n's and two separated m's and i's) approaches, we are
likely to get all kinds of bad advice and unreliable predictions
from all kinds of folks _ as well as from the usual suspects. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's more than likely. It's as much of a certainty as
Bill Clinton's next fib, as Saddam Hussein's next outrage, as
commercial television's next bad network sitcom. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But at least David Kristof and Todd W. Nickerson have saved us
some time by collecting a lot of wonky (and engaging) predictions
in a new book from Andrews McMeel Publishing, ``Predictions for the
Next Millennium.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They sent out some 6,000 postcards to world famous people asking
for their forecast of what would happen between 2001 and 3000 (the
latter, as you know, being the year that the statute of limitations
runs out on Don King's hair as well as the year Ken Starr's
investigation of the Clintons is scheduled to be wrapped up). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kristof and Nickerson got some 650 of these cards back, of which
some 250 made the book. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So on page 164 you've got the late author James Michener (who
was still alive when he answered the postcard) saying he has ``not
much hope'' that humanity will avoid war or crime. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And on page 187 you find novelist Peter Straub predicting
``devastating new viruses and diseases.'' To say nothing of author
Joseph Wambaugh's prediction on page 169 that the printed word will
vanish and ``with it the act of sober reflection.'' (Maybe, but if
you ask me there are plenty of printed words around today _
including some in this very newspaper _ that reveal a complete lack
of sober reflection or even much inebriated reflection.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there's former baseball manager Earl Weaver on page
249, full of wild pessimism, predicting a pennant for my team, the
Chicago Cubs, some time before 2500. Earl is way off. The Cubs will
win a pennant before 2000. You heard it here first _ or second, if
Harry Caray's ghost beat me to it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But maybe best of all is comedienne (which is French for
comedian) Joan Rivers on page 9 predicting that ``in the new
millennium interest rates will be higher and my breasts will be
lower.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, for my money Rivers is one of the few in this book who
really understands the world. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the things that's clearest about the future is that no
one can predict it worth a hoot. Why, professional meteorologists,
using equipment that sucks up the electrical juices of whole dams,
can't even tell us with much accuracy whether it's going to rain
tomorrow. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So it's easy for me to predict with a high degree of accuracy
that most of the predictions in ``Predictions for the Next
Millennium'' will be proved wrong _ unless I mean proven wrong, in
which case you'll have to send me a note about the difference
because I can't remember and barely even care any more. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But that leads me almost directly (nothing is entirely direct in
this column) to my new millennium predictions. You can take these
to the bank. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ People will write books full of predictions for each new
century. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Other people will find employment writing semi-interesting
newspaper columns about these books of predictions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Almost no one will ever check to see which predictions came
true. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Absolutely no one will remember what the columns about this
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This column is for use Monday, Dec. 7, and thereafter.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
