<HEADER>
A3527 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     12-04 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENT COUNSEL LAW: A GOOD IDEA, BUT ...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's time for devotees of the independent counsel law to throw
in the towel.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, way back there in the aftershock of Watergate,
the idea seemed to make sense. We have a government official who is
suspected of official wrongdoing; we set up an investigation by an
individual who owes no allegiance to the official being
investigated; and we give the investigator free rein and unlimited
resources to gather evidence and pursue appropriate prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   We call the investigator an ``independent counsel'' to formalize
his status as someone who is beholden to no one except the public
that pays his salary.
</P>
<P>
   It made sense.
</P>
<P>
   There's only one drawback to this seemingly sensible idea: It
doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   As we saw just the other day when a Washington jury found former
Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy not guilty of all 30 corruption
charges against him, independent counsels too often turn out to be
nothing more than runaway freight trains fueled by political
agendas and outrageous sums of taxpayer money.
</P>
<P>
   Independent counsel Donald Smaltz spent four years and $17
million prosecuting Espy on charges of freeloading off the
bankrolls of businesses he regulated, and what was the result?
Well, the result was exactly the same as it is with so many of
these out-of-control witch hunts conducted by independent counsels:
Oops!
</P>
<P>
   Or as Gilda Radner used to say: ``Never mind.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no question that Espy violated appropriate standards of
conduct by accepting gifts such as Super Bowl tickets and trips
from people he should have kept at arm's length. Espy has admitted
as much.
</P>
<P>
   Even Washington's resident Mr. Ethics, President Clinton, could
see that Espy had messed up when reports surfaced about his
penchant for grabbing all the freebies he could get his hands on.
Less than two years into the Clinton presidency, Espy was shown the
door.
</P>
<P>
   As some voters might recall, Clinton had promised during the
1992 campaign that he would assemble the most ethical
administration of all time. Students of Clinton's performance as
governor of Arkansas were still guffawing over that one when Espy's
ethical lapses cost him his place among Clinton's ethical
all-stars.
</P>
<P>
   But even though Espy may have demonstrated the ethics of a
cockroach, he apparently was smart enough to conduct his risky
business within the limits of the law. Prosecutors took two months
to present their case against Espy; jurors took just two days to
determine that the prosecution's case didn't cut the mustard.
</P>
<P>
   Was this a good investment of 17 million public dollars?
</P>
<P>
   Why, if we'd given that money to Ken Starr, he might have turned
up another Clinton sex partner or two.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is another story, needless to say, but he is also a
spectacular example of the rampant lunacy that has been unleashed
by the independent counsel law. Starr was supposed to investigate
Clinton's involvement in a long-forgotten Arkansas real estate deal
and ended up rooting through the president's sex life.
</P>
<P>
   The tab for Starr's independent counselship is frequently
estimated to be somewhere in the neighborhood of $40 million _ and
growing larger by the minute.
</P>
<P>
   It would be fascinating to watch Starr prosecute Clinton in a
real American courtroom before a jury of real American citizens.
Would Starr's seemingly endless investigation justify itself _ or
at least rationalize itself _ by producing a conviction for perjury
or some such crime?
</P>
<P>
   Or would the defendant walk, just as Espy did the other day?
</P>
<P>
   But even if the allegations against Clinton were to be validated
by a jury, would the conviction be worth the cost of obtaining it?
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't be.
</P>
<P>
   The Iran-contra investigation wasn't worth what it cost. The
Espy investigation wasn't worth what it cost. Starr's investigation
can never justify its cost, no matter what happens from here on in.
</P>
<P>
   This law that once seemed like a good idea has turned into a
national disaster. There has to be a better way to keep our public
officials honest.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
