<HEADER>
A3537 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REDGRAVE-TEX     12-04 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REDGRAVE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDGRAVE SISTER GETS THE ATTENTION SHE DESERVES IN `GODS AND
MONSTERS'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The woman looks, well, severe: scowling face, hunched
shoulders, quick-shuffling walk, Hungarian accent that seems
designed to make the horses whinny.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't match the other woman: tall, refined, casually
elegant in a beige pantsuit, speaking with a British accent as
soothing as a kitten's purr.
</P>
<P>
   They're the same woman: Lynn Redgrave as Hanna the housekeeper
in ``Gods and Monsters,'' the acclaimed new film; and Lynn Redgrave
the actress, gently complaining about the lack of heat in Dallas'
Inwood pub.
</P>
<P>
   Redgrave has been trying on different characters for more than
30 years, from her pudgy-girl-looking-for-love breakthrough in
1966's ``Georgy Girl'' to the badinage of the early '80s sitcom
``House Calls'' to her role as a patient companion in 1996's
``Shine.'' ``Gods and Monsters'' stands among her best movies, a
delicately witty story about the last days of James Whale, the
director of the first two Frankenstein movies.
</P>
<P>
   Ian McKellan, in one of the year's best performances, plays
Whale, who is openly gay in 1957 Hollywood _ a time when most
show-biz homosexuals were staying safely in the closet. Redgrave
plays his devoutly Catholic housekeeper, who is fervently loyal to
Whale even though she believes that his lifestyle is condemning him
to hell. Brendan Fraser rounds out the leading cast as a straight
gardener who strikes up an unlikely friendship with Whale.
</P>
<P>
   Redgrave drew on her own childhood nannies for inspiration, one
from her early years in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``My nanny _ she wasn't Catholic, but she said her prayers every
night.'' Redgrave says.''She was often quite irreverent about what
God was up to, but she very devoutly believed in God and the
speakings of the church, though not a Catholic. And she had that
kind of salt-of-the-earth wisdom that Hanna certainly has. She may
not have had a formal education, but she knows things. And she may
not understand them, and she may not like them, but she's loyal in
spite of it all. My nanny was like that; my nanny had that kind of
loyalty.''
</P>
<P>
   In the movie's best scene, Hanna and Whale are watching a TV
airing of Whale's ``The Bride of Frankenstein'' while Fraser and
his buddies watch the movie at their favorite bar. Director Bill
Condon examines the characters' reactions, including Hanna's moral
disapproval of the 1935 monster movie. Condon imbues this and other
scenes with a bemused affection for Hollywood history and for
moviemaking.
</P>
<P>
   Redgrave's participation in the project seems appropriate, with
her family's own potent Hollywood connections. Father Michael
Redgrave made his first film in 1938 and came to Hollywood in 1947;
sister Vanessa was most recently seen in ``Deep Impact''; brother
Corin and nieces Jemma Redgrave and Natasha and Joely Richardson
are also busy actors. While making ``Gods and Monsters,'' Redgrave
thought most about her father, especially with the movie's
references to closeted gay director George Cukor.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was in Hollywood first in the '40s, doing `Mourning
Becomes Electra,' and I knew George Cukor,'' she says. ``And my
father was very much part of the George Cukor circle and the
parties and the whole thing. And so it was, suddenly reading all of
that, and realizing that my father must've known James Whale, he
just must've. But my father's gone; my mother's 88, and she doesn't
remember.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the family remains cordial, but not that close. Much
has been made of the differences between the relatively sedate Lynn
and the fiery Vanessa, who rose in movies almost simultaneously.
But Redgrave says that she and her sister are getting on fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think either of us knows how the other one ticks, but
that's not unusual,'' she says. ``I think that most families find
out that it's actually rare for brothers and sisters to be close,
close friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Redgrave has remained busy, she has kept a
relatively low profile, acting on stage and appearing in
commercials for Weight Watchers, a program that she says she firmly
believes in and that she credits with helping her through a rough
patch after getting fired from ``House Calls.''
</P>
<P>
   When not working, Redgrave enjoys the quiet times; she even
built a cabin on her land where she can get away from family when
she needs time to think or write or just listen to music, her
favorites being British composer Ralph Vaughan Williams (her
cousin), opera diva Cecilia Bartoli, pop-rocker Sting and
Renaissance music. Although she is a child (and a sister and an
aunt) of show business, Redgrave's favorite activity doesn't seem
very Hollywood at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely love to spend time with my husband. I really just
love the times when we do nothing, I love the early mornings, I
love having cups of tea and talking. We've been married 31 years,
and he's still the most interesting person I could ever talk to.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Gods and Monsters''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Bill Condon
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Ian McKellan, Brendan Fraser, Lynn Redgrave
</P>
<P>
   Rating: R
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
