</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAYS-STRESS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO MANAGE WHEN STRESS WON'T TAKE A HOLIDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Holiday bliss or the same old annual anxiety?
</P>
<P>
   What with church pageants, school plays, visits from
cheek-pinching relatives and the pressures of dividing time between
different members of families that have split, what should be a
time of great cheer often becomes extremely stressful for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think particularly during this time, a lot of core issues
... the difficulties we have with families tend to come up,'' said
Phillip Mountrose, author of ``Getting Thru to Kids: Problem
Solving with Children Ages 6 to 18.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All the issues we haven't resolved come to the foreground, and
the unfortunate part is, we usually don't have the additional tools
needed to get through those,'' he said. ``We know we're unprepared,
and so we get anxious.''
</P>
<P>
   Mountrose and others say it becomes all the more important for
parents to pay attention to signs of stress so that they can better
manage their anxiety and that of their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the holidays simply happen around them, children
undoubtedly will be stressed,'' said Diane Arnold, vice president
of education at Children's World Learning Centers. ``If children
have an opportunity to participate in all the facets of making your
holidays special, then holidays will be a joyful time and will
impart precious memories that will be remembered.''
</P>
<P>
   To ease the holiday stress, Mountrose and Arnold offer parents
these suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Learn how to listen better.
</P>
<P>
   _ Avoid lecturing. Share your thoughts and feelings in a way
that will help your child, in a way that is not domineering.
</P>
<P>
   _ Find ways to appreciate your child, regardless of any
problems.
</P>
<P>
   _ Encourage children to make gifts for special friends and
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use gentle humor at every possible turn to help children
reframe their stressful thoughts and feelings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Talk about a problem situation and acknowledge the child's
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
