<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV06-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1999 ACURA TL3.2: SMART CAR WITH A STUPID NAME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (For release Sunday, December 06, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R.WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Technology brings us wondrous things, not all of which are worth
the effort it takes to deal with them. For example, let us consider
the automobile navigation system, at once a wonder, a distraction,
a frustration, a convenience, and a hazard. The most sophisticated
among them rely on satellites aloft and computer hardware with a
prodigious bank of computer memory on the ground to pinpoint your
car's location on the planet within a couple of feet and guide you
unerringly to your destination. Yeah, right!
</P>
<P>
   Some systems are tied in to cellular telephone networks, can
detect trouble such as a crash or hijack and summon aid. Some are
just navigation tools. Today's case study is the Acura Navigation
System, this time installed on Acura's newest, the 1999 TL 2.5, a
very smart car with a very stupid name.
</P>
<P>
   It is Thanksgiving morn and I am heading north to a dinner
appointment. Way north. I know the main route, the alternate
routes, the shortest of shortcuts as well as I know the way to my
refrigerator. So, what better test for a guidance system than to
match its electronic expertise against hard knowledge (and besides,
I carry a bulging map case that would make AAA envious). The
weather is . . . dubious.
</P>
<P>
   Turn on the ignition and the VCR in center dash wakes up,
displays Mother Earth aglow amid the twinkling firmament. Select
the menu and commence the exercise; punch in the destination a
letter at a time by touching the appropriate members of the
alphabet displayed on the screen. The computer Imp refuses to
recognize anything but York, Maine, which is not where I want to
go.
</P>
<P>
   I drive a bit, park, resume negotiation. Nada. I'll try later; I
do not have time to waste and I've already spent more time than it
would take to copy a Delorme map by hand. I select ``map'' and let
the illumined array track my progress _ my way.
</P>
<P>
   The TL is a handsome four-door equipped to the nines _ the
navigation system is the only option offered. The car derives half
of its idiotic moniker from the 3.2-liter, 24-valve VTEC engine
under the hood, a quiet 225-horsepower mill that has one drawback;
if you try running on an interstate without using cruise control,
you are asking for a ticket _ the TL's a creeper, as in creep up
the speedometer dial. The 4-speed automatic transmission with its
fuzzy logic is already adapting to my driving style and the
handling is quick, precise. I like this car.
</P>
<P>
   In Gray, Maine, I have gained a little time in the light
traffic, stop to program a route _ success! The Imp admits to
knowing the whereabouts of Kingfield and the little animated arrow
points me north on Interstate 95. In Auburn, I pull onto Route 4 _
OK so far _ and then left onto East Hardscrabble heading for Hotel
Road. This is not exactly wilderness; it runs along the edge of an
airfield. But, I am off the ``digitized road,'' thank you _ as far
as the Imp is concerned, I am in Terra Incognita. Shades of Henry
the Navigator!
</P>
<P>
   The things this instrument knows _ in view of what I'm learning
it doesn't know _ are surprising. It recognizes Crash Road, not
where I really want to drive in the rain and it's raining. The
windows suddenly begin fogging up and I need to jack up the air
conditioning to clear them _ which means hitting the AC button next
to the screen, thus turning off the Navigator Imp and bringing up
the work order for the Comfort Elf. One must tap the appropriate
boxes on the illuminated screen to effect ``climate changes''
within and I might as well be trying to change the weather without.
Visibility clouds to urgency and I pull over while madly rubbing
the windshield with a sleeve. After a while, the climate control
begins to cooperate. I prefer knobs to this high-tech tactile
switching nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   At New Vineyard I notice a change in weather character _ snow is
falling and there is an accumulation of something viscous
underfoot, demanding a reduction in speed. But the Imp does guide
me into Kingfield. End of Test I.
</P>
<P>
   Test II is finding Rochester, N.H. You may recall that on a
previous encounter, it didn't seem to be listed. Today, it exists,
if you have time and patience enough to wade through all the
options offered before the Imp will recognize it. But the
Navigation Imp and I disagree mightily on how to travel there and
the Imp finally gets annoyed with the number of recalculations
asked and quits in a huff. Just as well; no matter how low I adjust
the screen illumination, it's still an annoying distraction glowing
at me.
</P>
<P>
   Test III is finding a route from the Globe to the Museum of
Transportation, a veritable urban maze that challenges the stoutest
of tourists. The Imp is on top of the game; he points me south to
Gallivan Boulevard, along Morton, the Arborway, directly to target
_ except the Imp miscounts the exits at a traffic circle. The
reverse is a flop. On exiting the museum, I am directed to go to
the ``designated route,'' which is undecipherable on the maze
presented _ you can zoom these little things into big things but
I'm in traffic now. And although I'm retracing the route in, I am
now ``off the route.''
</P>
<P>
   I reprogram for Rochester, N.H., and, am directed to make a
``slight left turn'' where there is no turn, then another ``slight
left turn,'' which is a Y intersection, and then I'm off the route.
Recalculate. This pattern continues until finally the Imp goes to
lunch and the map freezes. Somewhere on I-95, the system shuts down
and I am able to coax the Imp out of his snit and find South Main
in Rochester. The Imp succeeds but selects the wrong exit off the
turnpike from a traffic perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Navigation systems, folks, are wonderful for negoiating
well-known dense urban areas _ boy, does the Imp know Portsmouth,
N.H., well! But, if it's to the boonies you are trekking, buy a
map, Bunkie. The Imp does not do boondocks.
</P>
<P>
   The TL3.2 is roomy enough, has a decent trunk, some interior
storage and, with the exception of climate controls with the
navigation option, is fairly convenient to operate. At $27,950 plus
$455 delivery, without the Imp, it's the equal of some much
higher-priced iron. Add $2,000 for the navigation system if you
like expensive, aggravatiing toys _ but two grand would buy a heap
of maps.
</P>
<P>
   The Acura TL3.2 scores on performance, luxury, handling, and
fuel economy; it delivered 26.44 miles per gallon over 928 measured
miles. Thus, it would seem to score fairly well on value, too.
</P>
<P>
   Final insults. It is overcast; I turn on the headlights and the
navigation screen goes dark, showing nothing but accumulated finger
smudges. No amount of fine-tuning the light levels and screen
brightness results in sufficient illumination. Good thing I know
how to get where I'm going. Coming home, the Imp plots the course,
guides me faithfully to within six miles, then falls asleep. I jar
him with the recalculation prod. Great car, lousy pathfinder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
