<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-$ADV06-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCIAL SECURITY DEBATE SHIFTS INTO HIGH GEAR THIS WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Dec. 6)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The debate over saving Social Security shifts into
high gear this week at a two-day White House conference, but
already groups are hardening their positions on the most
controversial remedy _ adding individual retirement savings
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, a new alliance of 39 business and conservative
groups urged Congress to allow Social Security payroll taxes to be
diverted into such accounts, which could then be invested in the
stock market and government securities. Private accounts would
``give every single working American a piece of the American pie,''
said Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, an opposing alliance of some 170 leaders of
organized labor and groups representing minorities, women and the
disabled condemned ``those who would turn Social Security over to
Wall Street,'' as AFL-CIO President John Sweeney put it. ``This
isn't a debate over how to reform Social Security,'' he charged.
``It is a faceoff over whether Social Security should exist or not
exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Well-worn doomsday projections undergird the debate: By 2013 if
nothing is done, the Social Security payroll tax alone will not be
sufficient to cover benefits, and the government will have to dip
into the interest on the system's trust fund. By 2021, it will have
to dip into the fund's principal, and by 2032, the fund itself _
now valued at about $756.9 billion _ will be depleted, and the
payroll taxes will provide only enough to pay 75 percent of the
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is demographic. More people are retiring early and
they're living longer. And the payroll taxes of the 40 million
members of Generation X _ born between 1965 and 1980 _ will not be
sufficient to finance the 76-million strong Baby Boom generation _
born between 1946 and 1964 _ when it begins retiring in large
numbers around 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on the fence in the middle is the conference's
host-in-chief, President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Despite opposition from several Democratic constituencies, the
president has said he will keep an open mind on private accounts.
And he has argued that projected budget surpluses should be
preserved until the nation decides what it wants to do on Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   But otherwise Clinton has kept silent, much to the consternation
of key Capitol Hill Republicans such as House Ways and Means
Committee Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas. Fearful of getting
blindsided on a touchy social issue, Republicans such as Archer
want to see the White House play its hand first.
</P>
<P>
   The conference is the climax of Clinton's year-long cautious
strategy of taking part in nationwide town meetings about Social
Security, hearing the debate but making no commitments.
</P>
<P>
   At a briefing for reporters last week, White House economic
adviser Gene Sperling called the conference a ``pivot point''
designed to ``bring people together'' and avoid ``polarization.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Clinton wants to forge a consensus on Social
Security and avoid the 1994 health-care debacle. That year the
White House in secret created a complicated plan to extend coverage
to the uninsured, only to see it plummet to a spectacular death in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and congressional
leaders will open the conference. Some 50 senators and House
members will attend along with some 250 experts and advocates from
universities, organized labor, business and senior-citizen and
youth groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Security Administration will beam the proceedings via
satellite into some 60 mini-conferences being held in all 50
states.
</P>
<P>
   In touting the idea of private accounts, business and
conservative groups and organizations such as Third Millennium
(representing Gen-Xers) call them as a logical panacea for what
ails Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``For too many Americans there is no `three-legged stool,'''
said Richard Thau, head of Third Millennium, referring to the
traditional triad of retirement income: personal savings, pension
benefits and Social Security. ``It's just a pogo stick called
Social Security. Personal accounts will give tomorrow's retirees
the ability to draw from Social Security plus savings. All their
retirement eggs will not be in one basket.''
</P>
<P>
   Third Millennium is co-sponsoring a ``Billion Byte March,'' an
online march on Washington in which pro-private-account messages
from ``demonstrators'' will be released en masse to congressional
offices next month.
</P>
<P>
   Retirement account advocates have strong allies on Capitol Hill.
In addition to most Republicans, Democrats such as Rep. Charles
Stenholm of Texas and Sens. Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York and
Bob Kerrey of Nebraska are outspoken supporters of such accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Backers deny that they want to abolish Social Security. They say
that even with private accounts, a government-run safety net of
traditional Social Security benefits would remain in place.
Retirees would continue to receive some income from the government,
and Social Security benefits for the disabled and elderly surviving
widows and widowers would remain untouched, they argue.
</P>
<P>
   Employers fear that without the private accounts, the government
might hike the Social Security payroll tax, which is now 12.4
percent, split evenly between employer and employee.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech last week, Social Security Commissioner Kenneth
Apfel said Clinton has ``strong reservations about a major
payroll-tax increase.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the private accounts dispute assurances that
society's most vulnerable citizens _ elderly widows and widowers,
the disabled and orphans _ would not be harmed by them.
</P>
<P>
   Under several privatization plans now before Congress, they
note, retirement ages would rise to 70, cost-of-living allowances
would drop and middle-class Americans would be subject to a 35
percent or more cut in guaranteed benefits, leaving them little
margin for error if the stock market nosedives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Privatizers are basically saying `trust us,''' said Roger
Hickey, co-director of the liberal Institute for America's Future.
``They have not specified how their plans would work, and the poor
or middle-class (people) unlucky with investments would be
subjected to a welfare-level `safety net' benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Hickey added: ``That's not what Social Security is about. Social
Security is about having enough to retire on with dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   Other opponents such as the Rev. Jesse Jackson borrow the
language of fiscal conservatives in arguing that the nation could
grow its way out of a projected Social Security deficit through a
booming economy that adds workers and employers paying payroll
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these opponents support a plan offered by Robert
Reischauer, former head of the Congressional Budget Office now at
the Brookings Institution, and Henry Aaron, a senior fellow at
Brookings, a Washington think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Under this plan, the government would continue to pay Social
Security benefits, but the trust fund would be bolstered through
government investment in an array of assets, including stocks. A
quasi-independent agency similar to the Federal Reserve Board would
oversee all investments.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With an impeachment vote likely in the House this week,
relations between Clinton and Congress have hit bottom. But both
sides clearly want to fix Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans are anxious to overcome the hurtful
image emanating from last month's elections that GOP lawmakers are
obsessed with scandal and do not care about issues important to
average Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is anxious to put his stamp on what will be landmark
legislation, if only to offset the stigma of the Monica Lewinsky
sex scandal. ``He needs a legacy,'' said Sharon Canner, a Social
Security expert at the National Association of Manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats appear to agree that 1999 provides the
best political window to do something about Social Security. As
Sperling put it, next year _ coming at the close of Clinton's
second term with a relatively strong economy and no national
elections until November 2000 _ ``offers a unique opportunity to
address this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
