   SOCIAL-SECURITY (Washington) _ The debate over saving Social
Security shifts into high gear at a two-day White House conference
starting Tuesday. Groups are already hardening their positions on
the most controversial alternative _ individual retirement savings
accounts. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-RENO (Washington) _ Despite President Clinton's recent
victories in his fight against impeachment, he faces another legal
land mine Monday when Attorney General Janet Reno decides whether
to appoint an independent counsel to investigate his role in
possible campaign law violations. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MARS-MISSIONS (Undated) _ Armed with growing evidence that water
once flowed abundantly over the now frigid, desert-like Martian
landscape, the United States plans new robotic missions to Mars in
search of frozen remnants. Launches of the Mars Climate Orbiter and
the Mars Polar Lander are scheduled for Dec. 10 and Jan. 3,
respectively. By MARK CARREAU. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   MARS-MICROPHONE (Undated) _ A small privately-funded microphone
installed aboard the Mars Polar Lander will offer Earthlings their
first opportunity to sample extraterrestrial sounds. The device was
assembled from a hearing aid sensor, the sound processor used in
popular talking toys and a computer chip. By MARK CARREAU. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   With: MARS-FACTS
</P>
<P>
   DEATH-ROW (Huntsville, Texas) _ We look at the Ellis prison
unit's work program that began in 1986 but was suspended this week
after the escape of death-row inmate Martin Gurule. By KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PRISONERS (Aida Camp, West Bank)_ For most of the past 17
years, Daoud Azrak has journeyed twice a month from his home in
this West Bank refugee camp to one prison or another in Israel to
visit his son Khaled. Azrak hoped peace would end those treks, but
his journeys continue. By DEBORAH HORAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ If strangers from another planet
were to study the policy stands taken by Democratic and Republican
presidential hopefuls, they might wonder what, if any, the
differences are between the two parties. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
(Filed Wednesday.)
</P>
