<SLUG> BC-JERSEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNEXPECTED JERSEY CITY DISCOVERY WHETS APPETITE  
 (ADV: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, DEC. 6) 
</HEADLINE>
 CITY-TRAVEL-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERSEY CITY, N.J. - Jersey City hasn't changed much, it seems.
Oh, the ethnicity has changed from when my great-grandmother lived
there with a whole community of Norwegians.
</P>
<P>
   Now, buildings are scrawled with Spanish words and stores
occasionally flash some Korean.
</P>
<P>
   But the streets and buildings look the same: brownstone
apartments, old three-story wooden homes, and streets lined with
first-floor shops.
</P>
<P>
   Bus fumes and knotted traffic add to the nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   I mention these because _ although travel writers tend to wax
eloquent about the big tourist destinations and travel sections in
the nation's newspapers tend to cover mainstream events with
``what-to-see'' stories emphasizing places with giant smiling mice
or beachfront hotels _ a great deal of our travel is in between the
places we actually want to be.
</P>
<P>
   Thus I came to New Jersey to find cheap lodging for the nights
while spending the days in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   But travelers learn that sometimes there are treats where you
least expect them, that come unbidden to you while you wait for
something else.
</P>
<P>
   Jersey City sits at the western ends of the Lincoln and Holland
tunnels. Buses collect commuters in the mornings and ship them
through the din and stench of the tunnels into the Port Authority
Terminal at 42nd Street, where they herd down the stairs into the
subway station.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, the whole process reverses.
</P>
<P>
   Jersey City is a long, skinny town, built along the crest of the
southern end of the Palisades, those high, black basalt cliffs that
line the Hudson River on the Jersey side.
</P>
<P>
   It is old, with alternating layers of autumn leaves and
fast-food litter, like the strata of archaeology, bound together
with soot.
</P>
<P>
   It is connected to Newark by the Pulaski Skyway, that archaic
two-mile bridge _ a black web of girders and struts across the
lower end of the Hackensack River and one of the great monuments
from that great age of American highway building in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   My motel was reasonably clean and nice, much nicer really than I
had expected in Jersey City _ I was prepared for a real dive _ but
though it was nice, it still displayed the standard New York/New
Jersey grime-and-dried sputum-covered concrete, complete with a
garnish of cigarette butts, along the stairs and sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Later that evening, I ventured out into the sea of cars once
more to find supper for real.
</P>
<P>
   At the crest of the hill, I found a tiny Puerto Rican restaurant
on J.F. Kennedy Boulevard. It is called the Candlelite Cafe, and it
is about 10 feet wide, with a white tile floor. Along the left wall
runs a counter with some stools and a display case filled with
pastries.
</P>
<P>
   Along the right wall runs, well, the right wall. There is no
room for anything more. They managed to squeeze in some travel
posters, but anything thicker than that and there'd be no room for
paying customers.
</P>
<P>
   I knew right off it was worth it: The smell was thick and spicy
_ the combined fragrance of hot cooking oil and (begin ital)
achiote. (end ital) The woman behind the counter was smiling and
friendly. An older man sat at the last stool dividing his attention
among the newspaper spread out on the counter, the Spanish-network
news on the TV up on the wall, and a cup of coffee. He turned out
to be the cook's husband.
</P>
<P>
   These little shops are what make a place like Jersey City. The
city is old; it is not one of these new plasterboard and stucco
cities that seem to pop up all over the West. These cities were
built when to build still meant to build to last. So, instead of
tearing things down and putting up yet another Denny's, they use
the old buildings and recycle the businesses in them.
</P>
<P>
   The front window displayed a pan of fried chicken, some pork
chops and several varieties of bread that I'd never seen before,
along with a menu sign that listed the day's specials in chalk. The
(begin ital) biftek encebollado (end ital) looked good, so I went
in, sat down on a stool and ordered it.
</P>
<P>
   The woman looked at me funny. My Spanish is not good, but I
didn't think it was that bad. I repeated it in Spanish and then in
English _ beef with onions?
</P>
<P>
   She didn't have that, she said, looking at me funny. I pointed
to the chalkboard, and she laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was yesterday,'' she said, figuring out what I meant.
``Today, we have stew.''
</P>
<P>
   I let on that stew would be quite nice, so she served it up: a
plate piled high with yellow rice, beans and fried plantain, with a
side bowl of stewed beef and potatoes. It smelled heavenly.
</P>
<P>
   I downed it with a bottle of Goya Malta, a beverage whose
existence had eluded me until then. It is sort of like an unbrewed
beer drink, only very, very sweet. It had the flavor of a
carbonated iron tonic. It sounds terrible; it looked terrible. But
when I tasted it, to my surprise, it was very good, and, what is
more, it was the perfect accompaniment to my Puerto Rican beef
stew.
</P>
<P>
   We talked over the meal, and the husband chimed in periodically,
pointing to something interesting on the TV news. A hurricane
headed for Honduras, someone he knew knifed at a service station, a
political ad for Al D'Amato, aimed at the Hispanic voter. The
husband laughed.
</P>
<P>
   I answered their questions about Arizona. They were eager to
tell me about Puerto Rico. He loved it; it was his motherland. She
was a little more skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her name was Nelly Cintroan. Her non-Hispanic name was the name
of the nurse in the hospital where she entered this planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone to Puerto Rico. It's beautiful, but I never want to
drive there again; the traffic is worse than here. The roads are
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' the husband admitted. His name was Angel. ``Puerto Rico
is only 100 miles long and 70 miles wide. To drive that far here
takes what? I made a delivery last week to Hartford (Conn.), and it
took me two hours to get there. In Puerto Rico, you're lucky if you
get there by next week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that bad,'' Nelly responds, ``but it's close. And the
road over the mountain. It's all up and down and around.'' She
makes her hand into a karate chop and wiggles it around like a
fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cars go around the corners like this and this and you
don't know what is around the curve'' _ at this point, her left
hand makes an alternate wiggling fish and plunges into her right
hand _ ``like that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to go there sometime,'' Angel says. ``You'll love
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' she says. ``You'll love it.''
</P>
<P>
   The meal leaves me stuffed like a salami. It is the best thing I
have eaten in five days on the road and sets me back an entire
$5.75. ``That's too cheap,'' I complain. ``You can't stay in
business that way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no. It's fine. We Puerto Ricans know how to get the most
from a dollar,'' Nelly says.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless I leave behind a very fat tip.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you cooking tomorrow?'' I ask just before leaving. &QL; 
Richard Nilsen can be reached at richard.nilsen(at)pni.com &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
