<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Saturday, Dec. 5. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-U.S. (Washington) _ President Clinton's planned trip to
the Middle East is running into problems as Israelis and
Palestinians continue to argue over peace accord. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-ASSESS (New Delhi, India) _ The Hindu nationalists who
lead India's government were trounced in state elections last week
because of their failure to deliver on pocketbook economic issues,
but the defeats, which weakened their already tenuous grip on power
at the national level, are also likely to make it more difficult
for them to sign the nuclear test ban treaty. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ Developments on the House impeachment
inquiry into President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-POLITICS (Newark, N.J.) _ Ending months of speculation
about his political future, Bill Bradley, the former United States
Senator from New Jersey, said today that he would consider making a
bid to become the next President of the United States. By Jennifer
Preston.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   Related stories as needed.
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES (Miami) _ The way some neighbors tell it, the area on
the edge of Everglades National Park known as East Everglades has
all the charm of a swamp, but the same neighbors describe the
bright side of this lifestyle with words like ``magical'' and
``breathtaking.'' That way of life is about to end. The rural
neighborhood stands in the way of a multi-billion-dollar effort to
repair the vast expanse of unique wetlands that is the Everglades.
Last month, officials with the South Florida Water Management
District voted to spend up to $100 million to buy out about 1,400
landowners and clear out the 8 1/2-square-mile East Everglades area
by the year 2002, part of an $8 billion project to save the
Everglades. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Despite a fresh wave of corporate
downsizing and dire predictions that 1998 would turn out to be `the
worst year of the decade` for layoffs, the Government reported
yesterday that more Americans are working than ever. Even as
corporate giants like Boeing and Johnson &AMP; Johnson announced
thousands of job cuts this week, American employers as a whole
added 267,000 workers to their payrolls in November alone, the
Department of Labor reported By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
