<HEADLINE>
GALVESTON-SOCSEC-2TAKES-$ADV6 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  EDITORS: This story is a sidebar to SOC-SEC-$ADV6 
 
SOCIAL SECURITY IS A THING OF PAST FOR SEVERAL THOUSAND TEXANS 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 6) 
 
By KEVIN MORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALVESTON, Texas _ While millions of Americans worry and wonder
about the future of Social Security, the controversial federal
retirement program already is a thing of the past for several
thousand Texans.
</P>
<P>
   Almost unnoticed 17 years ago, employees of Galveston, Brazoria
and Matagorda counties collectively jumped through a loophole in
federal law that let them opt out of Social Security and save for
retirement through a private annuity program.
</P>
<P>
   The program's promoters and participants say employees have made
out like bandits, averaging a 7.25-percent annual return vs. less
than 2 percent for Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   The success of what is called the Alternate Plan has led the
federal General Accounting Office to study it as a possible model
for reform of the troubled Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   People who stay in the plan _ which offers guaranteed return
rates _ for 30 to 40 years will draw monthly benefits of $5,000 or
more when they retire, managers predict.
</P>
<P>
   The program's guaranteed disability benefits, along with death
benefits that are three times an employee's annual pay, beat the
federal retirement program hands-down, managers say. The annuity
plan is coupled with a state-run pension program that provides
substantial retirement income to long-term employees.
</P>
<P>
   After 15 years in the Alternate Plan, Carmella McTyre left her
job as Galveston County payroll supervisor in 1996 with about
$50,000 in cash savings on which to draw.
</P>
<P>
   For the 19 years she had spent in the Social Security program,
McTyre, now 62, gets $407 a month.
</P>
<P>
   She said she not only got more return on her investment in the
Alternate Plan but also had the comfort of knowing that no
politician could mess with her money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was there and it wasn't going to go into anybody
else's pocket but mine,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Breslin spent 11 years in the Alternate Plan before
retiring from her Galveston County probate court job in 1993. She
had about $40,000 in cash with which to ease into retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning I wasn't too happy about getting out of
Social Security, having seen how well it took care of my nephews
and my sister when her husband died,'' Breslin, 73, said. ``So I
was reluctant, but after I got into it and I received it and got my
end of the stick, I was real happy.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she has spent that money, which she took out in five
annual payments because she didn't know she could have extended the
payout over a longer period. Still, Breslin said, the money was a
big help.
</P>
<P>
   Each month now, she gets $580 in benefits from her 15 years in
the Social Security system, $360 in retirement from an early
railroad job and about $1,900 from the state-run pension program.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the Alternate Plan acknowledge that, if it were to
replace Social Security, safeguards would be needed to ensure that
people cannot withdraw their money over a short period and use it
up.
</P>
<P>
   Besides a payout designed to make benefits last through long
retirements, an annual cost-of-living increase would have to be
included to make sure inflation doesn't eat up retirees' benefits,
supporters say.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would make some adjustments to meet the needs of a
national plan instead of a local plan,'' said Richard Gornto, whose
Houston firm, First Financial Benefits Inc., manages the plan for
all three counties.
</P>
<P>
   First Financial Chairman Don Kebodeaux, who designed the
Alternate Plan with Gornto, said it also would need a requirement
that the money be put into safe investments such as treasury bills
or federally backed annuities.
</P>
<P>
   It was the late Galveston County lawyer Bill Decker who, spurred
by widespread concern in 1979 over the stability of Social
Security, began looking for what ultimately became the Alternate
Plan, former County Judge Ray Holbrook said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to admit, I thought it was kind of a hare-brained
scheme,'' Holbrook recalled recently. ``I was skeptical, but all
the numbers looked good.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike 401(k) investment plans familiar to employees of many
companies today, the plan precluded investment choices, thus
avoiding a situation in which some employees lose money while
others gain, Holbrook said.
</P>
<P>
   Some commissioners and some county staff members jumped on the
bandwagon. But Holbrook said opposition persisted from many elected
officials, labor leaders, minorities and Democrats simply opposed
to dropping a part of the legacy of President Franklin D.
Roosevelt. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
