<HEADLINE>
LAST YEAR'S TECHNOLOGY GOES OUT THE WINDOWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: The real story on computers these days is in
the way the software/hardware folks are forcing users to replace
satisfactory equipment. Examples: I was using TurboTax for years on
DOS. All of a sudden TurboTax only runs on Windows. I was using
Juno for E-mail with a 386 motherboard. All of a sudden Juno will
not run on less than a 486. My Print Shop files will not transfer
to the new model. You get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   _ Voice In The Wilderness
</P>
<P>
   DEAR WILDERNESS: So what should we do? Ignore any sort of
technological advance that might make your life a little bit
easier? You might as well sit in a cave, wondering why the fire
crashed and won't reboot (Hint: Add more random-access mahogany.)
</P>
<P>
   Innovation and obsolescence are integral parts of computing,
just as they are for every endeavor. They're a tad more obvious,
though, because the underlying technology seems to double every
couple of minutes. In fact, I've upgraded hardware three times
since beginning this paragraph.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's got a gun to your head, forcing you to use newer,
better computers and software. If you're happy with your
steam-powered clunker, just keep on using it, and pay no attention
to what's going on in the world. And if you can't find software to
do your taxes, find an accountant instead. Trust me, you'll be OK.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: What can the government really do to Microsoft?
</P>
<P>
   _ Concerned Taxpayer
</P>
<P>
   DEAR CONCERNED: Look, whatever the government does, you can be
sure it will take too long, cost too much and be exactly the
opposite of what the people really want.
</P>
<P>
   What the well-intentioned pinheads in the Justice Department
don't seem to realize is that even if Microsoft has been guilty of
strong-arming its way into every conceivable marketplace, any
attempt to break it up or restrain it will be disastrous for the
90-odd percent of the world that relies on Microsoft operating
systems and software. A monopoly has its advantages, especially
when you're trying to get all the computers in the world to speak
the same language.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Someone used my debit card number to purchase
$6.95 of online time with Playboy. His listed E-mail address was
(withheld)(at)usa.net (Playboy provided me with that). How can I
trace back to him?
</P>
<P>
   _ Bunny Boy
</P>
<P>
   DEAR BUN: Now you're sure you're not just writing this because
your wife saw the bank statement? If not, then you'd better figure
out who got hold of your debit card, and that should narrow it down
to a very few suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Always start at the domain, in this case usa.net, and see if
there's a home page. If you go to www.usa.net, you'll find one of
those companies that provide ``free'' advertiser-supported E-mail.
That means anyone in the world might own the account, but these
companies are just as concerned about fraud as you are. You can
fire off an angry letter to abuse(at)usa.net, but I prefer the
old-fashioned way: getting a real, live human on the phone. Find
their numbers on the site, and maybe they can help you nail the
little horndog.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay offers occasionally
accurate advice about most things electronic. He can be reached on
Internet at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com; via snail-mail at Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101; or fax: (817)
390-7257. His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
