u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GALVESTON-SOCSEC-2NDT     12-04 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GALVESTON-SOCSEC-2NDTAKE-$ADV6-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALVESTON-SOCSEC-2NDTAKE-$ADV6 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  GALVESTON, Texas: D. Roosevelt. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We were scared to death because it looked like it was
unpatriotic or something,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After holding meetings to explain the plan, Galveston County
employees voted 3-1 in late 1980 to adopt it. It took effect in
1982.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, Brazoria and Matagorda county employees followed suit.
Employees of Texas City and the Brazoria County Appraisal District
have plans similar to the Alternate Plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harris County and about 50 other counties were ready to join
when Congress passed a bill in 1983 to `save Social Security,' ''
Holbrook said. ``That bill increased taxes, gradually raised the
retirement age and closed the door on other local governments'
withdrawing from Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill was authored by then-U.S. Rep. Jack Brooks, D-Beaumont,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrook, a lawyer and engineer, was elected county judge in
1966. He decided not to run again in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the plan for 14 years before I retired and I was in
Social Security for 27 years,'' he said. ``What I get out of that
14 years is about two-thirds of what I get from Social Security. I
get about $1,100 from Social Security and about $700 from this
county plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the best things I ever did in 28 years as county
judge, although at the time it wasn't that big a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Alternate Plan has its critics, chief among them
Democratic County Commissioner Wayne Johnson, a lawyer who has been
invited to participate in a White House summit meeting on Social
Security that begins Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot outlive Social Security benefits and you can
outlive the benefits of the Alternate Plan,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have employees literally quit their county jobs so they can
withdraw their Alternate Plan money to pay off credit-card debts or
bills they owe or make down payments on houses,'' he said. ``This
plan will provide more cash when you retire on a monthly basis, but
that's the only major advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes Social Security will remain viable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 100 percent funded through the year 2032 and it would
take only a 2.2 percent increase in the payroll tax to make it
solvent for the next 75 years,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Galveston County workers pay 6.13 percent of their wages into
the Alternate Plan, the same percentage they paid into Social
Security in 1980.  &UR;  &LR; The Social Security tax is 6.2 percent of pay.
 &UR;  &LR; The county match is equal to 7.78 percent of each employee's
annual pay.
</P>
<P>
   The return on the Alternate Plan has ranged from 5.5 percent to
14 percent over the years. The insurance company from which First
Financial bought annuities in the early 1980s filed for bankruptcy,
causing delays in some payments, but employees lost no money in the
long run.
</P>
<P>
   The Alternate Plan reduces employees' taxes as well as providing
better benefits, Gornto said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a worker dies at a young age, in some instances the
spouse can't even get Social Security survivor benefits,'' he said,
noting that the Alternate Plan's minimum death benefit is $50,000.
``Under this, it's automatic, with three times the salary paid
immediately upon death.''
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that the Alternate Plan is a good retirement
program for most county employees, Johnson argues that Social
Security retirement, disability and death benefits are still more
reliable.
</P>
<P>
   While the Alternate Plan could pay a lump sum of as little as
$50,000 to the family of a young worker who dies, Social Security
provides such a family up to $250,000 in long-term benefits,
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Social Security does not pay money in a lump sum that can be
squandered or lost,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such problems can be fixed, Alternate Plan supporters maintain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the country had a fully privatized plan like we have in
Galveston, anybody who works 40 years will get payments five times
greater than Social Security would provide,'' Kebodeaux said.
</P>
<P>
   The Alternate Plan is expected to be discussed at the White
House summit. It ultimately could be the prototype of a new
national system, said U.S. Rep. Mark Sanford, R-South Carolina, who
will participate in the summit.
</P>
<P>
   Change is needed because young people, especially, will be
short-changed without it, Sanford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, for all workers paying into Social Security, the
average (annual) rate of return is 1.9 percent,'' he said. ``If you
go to people born after 1974, the rate of return is actually
negative. For every dollar they put in, they'll get less than a
dollar back out.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides politics and fear of change, transition costs are a huge
hurdle for those who would change the nation's retirement plan more
radically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you should just dump Social Security and put in
a privatized plan,'' Gornto said. ``You should phase it in over 10
to 20 years, possibly a generation. There would be less money going
into Social Security from people under age 40, say, and more money
going into a privatized fund as time goes on.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
