<HEADLINE>
INVESTING DIARY  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 6)
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NOT ALL MERGERS ARE CREATED EQUAL
</P>
<P>
   In these days of proliferating mergers, it's many an investor's
dream: buying a stock, then picking up the paper the next day to
read that the company is being bought by a rival _ for a fat
premium.
</P>
<P>
   But anyone hoping for such a payoff should pay attention to what
industry they are buying into, because the takeover premiums vary
accordingly. On average this year, through Dec. 1, the offering
prices for drug-company targets were 35 percent above what share
prices had been a week before the deals became public, according to
Securities Data Co. That compares with a 9.4 percent premium, on
average, in offering prices for food companies.
</P>
<P>
   What accounts for such differences? Thomas Burnett, director of
Merger Insight, a research firm, says the high premium for drug
companies reflects their prospects for steady growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're buying a highly confident growth-rate company, and
you're going to pay up for that,'' Burnett said. As for the food
companies, he suspected that they might have been bid up far ahead
of announcements.
</P>
<P>
   Another high-premium business, as far as takeovers are
concerned, was the Internet, at 34 percent. ``That just represents
the mania of trying to get into the Internet business,'' Burnett
said.
</P>
<P>
   _ RICHARD TEITELBAUM
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   SOME WORDS BECOME LESS FLEETING
</P>
<P>
   Corporate luminaries are often invited to address the monthly
breakfast meetings of the New York Venture Group held at the
Rainbow Room in New York's Rockefeller Center. Past speakers have
included Michael Bloomberg, founder of Bloomberg LP; Norman
Pearlstine, editor in chief at the Time Inc. unit of Time Warner;
John Sculley, former chief of Apple Computer, and Fred Joseph,
former chief of Drexel Burnham Lambert.
</P>
<P>
   For those who were unable to attend the past gatherings but want
to know what was said, the group sells audio tapes. Here's one the
Securities and Exchange Commission might want to hear: a speech in
March by Walter Forbes, former chairman of Cendant Corp., who
resigned after the discovery of some mighty creative accounting at
the company. Its title? ``Strategic Mergering: A Case History of
How One and One Make Three.''
</P>
<P>
   _ GRETCHEN MORGENSON
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS WATCH: STRONG CAPITAL STARTS A NETWORK OF ITS OWN
</P>
<P>
   Strong Capital Management of Milwaukee has tossed its hat into
the funds network arena with a service that offers investors the
funds of eight other no-load families, without transaction fees.
</P>
<P>
   The eight are Acorn, Ariel, Baron, Fasciano, Marsico, Oakmark,
Rainier and Warburg Pincus.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in the network, named Prime Managers, receive a
consolidated monthly statement with cost and performance data on
each fund.
</P>
<P>
   Strong, with about $31 billion in assets, is the smallest fund
company to offer such a network. ``Strong has had a desire to be a
big player in the mutual fund business, and this is what the big
players are doing,'' said Susan Belden, editor of No-Load Fund
Analyst, a newsletter. The networks of giant firms like Charles
Schwab, Fidelity Investments and Vanguard offer hundreds or even
thousands of funds to investors and will continue to offer any of
the Prime Managers funds they currently do. By contrast, Strong's
network offers just 79, more than half from Strong itself.
</P>
<P>
   But Geoffrey Mackey, marketing manager at Strong, said the
network would distinguish itself by offering service and guidance.
Morningstar Inc., the Chicago financial publisher, will provide
information on the individual funds. ``We expect to be able to talk
about the details of those funds as well as, if not better than,
our own funds,'' Mackey said.
</P>
<P>
   The network requires a $5,000 minimum investment per account,
charges a quarterly maintenance fee of $12.50 for accounts below
$10,000, and hits frequent traders with a $50 penalty for
non-Strong funds held less than 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   _ RICHARD TEITELBAUM
</P>
</TEXT>
