<HEADLINE>
LAWSUIT CHALLENGES PART OF ANTI-BILINGUAL LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Supporters of bilingual education filed a
lawsuit in federal court to block a provision of the voter-approved
ballot initiative that requires California students to be taught in
English.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit filed Thursday seeks to overturn a part of the
initiative, Proposition 227, that holds teachers, administrators
and school board members ``personally liable for fees and actual
damages'' in case of a civil lawsuit by parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Proposition 227 hangs over teachers' heads like the Sword of
Damocles,'' said Carole Shields, president of Washington,
D.C.-based People For the American Way Foundation, which is
co-counsel in the lawsuit. ``We should all be horrified that
teachers might be forced to lose their jobs, sacrifice their
families and even have their homes taken away.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Unz, the Silicon Valley entrepreneur who wrote Proposition
227, called the lawsuit ``a bit strange.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If teachers obey the law, nothing will happen to them,'' Unz
said. ``They only face risk if they willfully and repeatedly
violate the law. Individuals who refuse to obey other laws
certainly face consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Unz pointed out that a federal judge refused in July to block
implementation of Proposition 227, approved by 61 percent of the
vote on June 2. The law abolished most bilingual education programs
for California's 1.4 million children who speak little if any
English. It replaced such programs with English-only instruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not clear that these arguments are any different than
those raised before,'' Unz said of the previous lawsuit and appeal,
which is pending. ``I guess they feel if they repeat the same
argument enough times, they'll eventually find a judge who will
agree with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs in the suit, however, say the proposition is not
clearly defined. They point to the wording in the law stating that
classroom instruction must be ``overwhelmingly in English,'' but
does not explain what ``overwhelmingly'' is.
</P>
<P>
   Tim O'Brien, deputy director of the California office of the
People For the American Way Foundation, said the plaintiffs in the
suit are not attempting to argue the merits of Proposition 227.
Instead, he said, teachers need clear standards on how the statute
should be implemented, and need to know that if they make a
mistake, they will not face ``potentially devastating lawsuits.''
</P>
<P>
   Unz, however, said that it is unlikely teachers would be
penalized. ``We really have always felt the most appropriate
targets of our action would be the senior administrators and
elected officials of schools that are not complying with the law,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other plaintiffs in the suit, filed in U.S. District Court for
the Central District of California, include the California Teachers
Association, the Association of California School Administrators,
the Association of Mexican-American Educations and the National
Association of Bilingual Educators.
</P>
<P>
   The California Federation of Teachers, which is not a plaintiff,
also asserts that Proposition 227 is ambiguously written and poses
a risk to teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think folks who have been looking for vulnerabilities in 227
have found it in this provision,'' said Mary Bergan, head of the
55,000-member California Federation of Teachers. ``People have
questions about what `overwhelmingly' means. But, we've been
telling our folks to be very familiar with the law _ and obey it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
