   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-ELECTION-$ADV05 _ MIAMI _ Supported by millions of
peasants and shantytown dwellers, a failed coup leader is poised to
win the Dec. 6 presidential election in Venezuela, an important
South American country that provides most of the oil imported to
the United States. The prospect of a win by Hugo Chavez is
reopening old woulds in the armed forces and stirring worries that
the military may try to block his rise to power. The election is
being watched closely by the business community since Chavez has
run on a controversial platform that includes a pledge to stop
paying Venezuela's foreign debt. The Carter Center will be
monitoring the election that could prove to be a turning point in
Venezuela's 40 years of democracy. (Emling, Cox News Service).
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/VENEZUALA-BOX _ A primer on Venezuela. (Emling, Cox News
Service). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CROATIA-TORAH-$ADV05 _ DUBROVNIK, Croatia _ For almost five
hundred years, through earthquakes and war, the tiny Jewish
community here protected and cherished a precious deerskin torah
from the 13th Century. During World War II, they wrapped it like a
baby and hid it beneath roof tiles, along with 17th and 18th
century Venetian wraps, a pair of gold Torahs and even a candelabra
taken down from the ceiling of the synagogue. In 1991, the
synagogue even took a direct hit from a Serbian shell. But in 1995,
the treasures of Dubrovnik were lost _ not to foreign armies or
Croatian Nazis _ but to a Croatian-American Jew living in
Manhattan. Dr. Michael Papo arranged for their restoration and
display at Yeshiva University in New York City, and then fought
their return to Dubrovnik. Now, after three years spent in court
battles in New York and the Croatian capital Zagreb, the Jewish
community here is quietly celebrating the return of the treasures.
WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   WHITE-HOUSE-HOLIDAY _ WASHINGTON _ In a cramped hallway, about
eight tiny reindeer lengths from the Diplomatic Room fireplace,
White House cooks were merrily stamping out gingerbread men on an
autumn afternoon. ``Every slow day is a day we use for Christmas
preparation,'' explained pastry chef Roland Mesnier, guiding a
visitor past this culinary assembly line. ``If there is an empty
corner in the White House, you will find somebody rolling cookies
there.'' Like Santa's elves, some White House staffers regard
Christmas preparation as a never-ending job. On Monday, First Lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton will unveil the 1998 Christmas theme and
decorations at the White House -- beginning a traditional round of
seasonal tours and parties at the presidential home. (Dart, Cox
News Service 1250). WITH PHOTOS. MOVED MONDAY. WITH LAYOUT as
CoxNet Focus page.
</P>
<P>
   TRUCK-SAFETY _ WASHINGTON _ More than 5,300 people died in
highway crashes involving big trucks last year, the most in eight
years, a consumer group reported Friday. While some say that shows
the need for a crackdown on trucks, the trucking industry points
out that fatality rates have been declining for decades. (Dart, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   w/TRUCK-DATA _ for a chart, highway fatality statistics,
including all Cox states.
</P>
<P>
   JACKSON _ WASHINGTON _ The Rev. Jesse Jackson addresses the
National Press Club Friday. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-PARTNERS-$ADV05 _ WASHINGTON _ Even as tech firms such
as Apple and Intel testify for the government in the Microsoft
antitrust trial, they continue business partnerships with the
software giant. Are these relationships fraying, or do the tech
executives see such cross-currents as a normal part of doing
business? (Regan, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories for
release Saturday, Dec. 5.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CHURCH-BURNINGS _ ATLANTA _ After a meeting Friday with black
ministers, Jim Johnson, undersecretary for enforcement in the
Treasury Department, talks about progress in the efforts to solve
the burnings of black churches across the south and to track down
Eric Robert Rudolph for the Atlanta and Birmingham bombings.
(Martz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AUS-HEART-HOSPITAL _ Monday, just steps away from where the
Seton HealthCare Network has plotted its massive empire, the
region's first hospital devoted to heart care will open its doors.
Its top executives are thirtysomethings already thinking about
their next career moves, their bosses are financiers who know
little about health care, and their business model is young and
unproven. But make no mistake, the top hospitals in town are
worried about losing their most lucrative source of revenue _ heart
surgery _ to this upstart start- up from out of town. They will use
their dominance over health care in Central Texas to raise the
stakes with health plans and managed care companies. A look at
whether the $60 million Heart Hospital of Austin has a chance.
(Park, Austin Americanm-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   CARTER-FAULDER-DEATHROW _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Former boxer Rubin
``Hurricane'' Carter, who spent 20 years fighting to erase his own
wrongful conviction in a murder trial, is heading to Austin to make
the case for a Canadian man on Texas Death Row. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   UT-ENDOWMENT-GAS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Cheap oil prices are a boon
for consumers at the gas pump, but they are a bust for a Texas
university endowment that earns money from selling oil and gas
leases. (Roser, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   FENCE-BATTLE _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Joseph L. Howard became disabled
by post-traumatic stress disorder after three tours of duty in
Vietnam. He wants to find peace and privacy behind a 6-foot-high
fence around his Beavercreek home, and has recently filed a lawsuit
to fight the city's opposition to the idea. (Hills, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED
</P>
