<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLAGIO-TRAVEL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELLAGIO: A WORK OF ART  
 (ADV: EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 6) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVE WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Bellagio, the most expensive hotel ever built (for
now), stands on the western edge of an 8.5-acre artificial lake.
</P>
<P>
   At regular intervals throughout each evening, lyrical sprinklers
animate the water.
</P>
<P>
   Framed through the falling mist and the twinkle lights
decorating the lakeside foliage, Bellagio appears every bit as
enchanting, romantic, stately and dignified as its TV commercials
promise.
</P>
<P>
   Erected by casino magnate Steve Wynn for $1.6 billion, Bellagio
is a luxury hotel, packed with luxurious amenities, planted in the
heart of America's capital of garish excess and low-ball thrills.
</P>
<P>
   It rises 36 stories above a glass-enclosed conservatory filled
with flowers, an elegant shopping gallery filled with Rodeo Drive
retailers, a gallery filled with artworks by famous painters,
restaurants filled with food prepared by famous chefs, and a
theater filled with wonder.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a casino. But Bellagio, which opened to the public
in mid-October, aspires to be more than Sin City's newest hot-slot
destination. That's a fleeting niche, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Mandalay Bay, a $950 million hotel built around a tropical
theme, opens in the spring. The Venetian, a $2 billion resort
rising on the grounds of the fabled Sands, will debut shortly
thereafter. Later in 1999, Paris, a $750 million hotel fronted by a
50-story replica of the Eiffel Tower, will open across Las Vegas
Boulevard from Bellagio's front threshold.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn launched his empire by first rehabilitating the downtown
Golden Nugget. Then came an Atlantic City Nugget, the Las Vegas
Mirage, a property in Laughlin and Treasure Island, also in Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn knows that Las Vegas will grow ever-larger hotels. Mandalay
Bay will have 3,300 rooms; Paris, 2,900; The Venetian, eventually,
6,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bellagio, with 3,000 rooms, is his stab at distinction.
</P>
<P>
   The Dunes, a declining relic from Vegas' Rat Pack era, died to
make way for Bellagio, which ``is about things that are good for
the soul,'' Wynn has said. ``Fine art, gardens, flowers, fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Viewed from certain angles, Bellagio appears to be a departure
from the pedestrian-level temptations that still drive Las Vegas
life. Sufficiently bankrolled, it's likely possible to stay there
for days and never see a girlie-show pamphlet or be tempted to
indulge in a buffet pigout.
</P>
<P>
   The fine art may be the most striking diversion from the Las
Vegas ``style,'' defined until now by neon, lame and
cocktail-waitress cleavage.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn has assembled a fairly stunning little $300 million
collection of 19th- and 20th-century art, which is displayed in two
small rooms not far from the check-in desk.
</P>
<P>
   Short fences and honking motion detectors guard the artwork from
patrons who might not be conversant with the art world's
please-don't-touch-the-priceless-masterpie ces code of etiquette,
but the display otherwise is dignified and restrained, and would be
considered so even outside its context.
</P>
<P>
   Once you recover from the cultural whiplash of it all, it's
possible to establish a genuine relationship with the paintings,
which include a couple of Warhols and Renoirs, a Pollock, a
Matisse, a Monet, a Manet and a Gauguin, among others. Some are
from Wynn's personal collection; the house owns the others. Art
expert Edmund Pillsbury has advised Wynn on some of the
acquisitions, many of which are for sale. Reportedly for tax
purposes, Wynn is, technically speaking, an art dealer, and several
of the pieces displayed during the Bellagio's opening weeks already
have been purchased and removed.
</P>
<P>
   The collection's destination pieces, or the important paintings
that art lovers might travel long distances specifically to
inspect, include its Cezanne (``Portrait of a Woman,'' 1900), Miro
(``Dialogue of Insects,'' 1924-25), Picasso (``Portrait of Dora
Maar,'' 1942) and van Gogh (``Peasant Woman Against a Background of
Wheat,'' 1890), all of which still were displayed prominently
during ``The Arizona Republic's'' recent visit to the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Admission is $10, and the gallery is open from 8 a.m. to
midnight every day. Staggered reservation times are assigned in
advance (888-488-7111) to keep the gallery appropriately populated.
</P>
<P>
   According to a hotel publicist, the art has averaged nearly
2,000 visitors a day so far, and plans were launched almost
immediately to configure bigger quarters. The display's popularity
has forced Wynn _ whose voice you hear in your headphones if you
take the audio tour _ to visit the paintings after-hours.
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth _ and it's worth quite a lot, actually _
``Time'' magazine art critic Robert Hughes toured the gallery and
more or less deemed it not bad for a city ``where `Art' is normally
the name of someone's limo driver,'' he reported. ``And anyone who
looks down his nose at the whole enterprise as a piece of splashy
Vegas promotion ought to remember the origins of American museums
in the late 19th century, built up from nothing by self-taught
meatpackers and railroad kings who got good advice, took deep
breaths and opened their checkbooks.''
</P>
<P>
   Bellagio's art collection isn't completely contained by the
gallery.
</P>
<P>
   A floral glass sculpture by Dale Chihuly _ titled ``Fiori di
Como'' , it's supposedly the largest glass piece ever blown _
covers a massive expanse of ceiling in the main lobby.
</P>
<P>
   One of Bellagio's eateries, Picasso, is a shrine to the artist,
whose original paintings, sculpture and ceramics look down on the
Mediterranean cuisine of chef Julian Serrano, formerly of the San
Francisco restaurant Masa's.
</P>
<P>
   Edible art is another of Bellagio's compelling draws. There's an
annex of New York's Le Cirque, a version of San Francisco's Aqua
and Boston's Olives, plus Chinese, Japanese and Italian
restaurants, a high-end steakhouse, a 24-hour cafe that's not quite
a coffee shop, and the obligatory buffet.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn's good-for-the-soul flowers fill the conservatory, located
just off the main lobby. The room debuted with a harvest motif, but
now is being transformed into a holiday theme, highlighted by a
Christmas tree decorated by none other than Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   The theme will change with the seasons, and botany lovers will
flock to the flowers like bus-tour crowds to 99-cent shrimp
cocktails.
</P>
<P>
   There and in the shopping gallery, visitors can witness one of
Bellagio's oddest attractions: natural light, which streams into
these public, non-gaming spaces while the rest of interior Vegas
remains as perpetually sunless as a tomb.
</P>
<P>
   A tour of the upstairs accommodations revealed that the
Bellagio's just-folks guest rooms, which carry a publicized nightly
rate ranging from $159 to $459, rival a typical Ritz-Carlton in
understated swank, right down to the marble bathroom and oversize
soak tub.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these lower-story rooms already have been discounted
occasionally to $99, and a Bellagio spokeswoman said that rate
quotes can fluctuate several times in a day. Try your luck at
888-987-6667, and dig the Euro-pop music while you hold for an
operator.
</P>
<P>
   High rollers are housed on upper floors, where suites carry
listed nightly rates ranging from $375 to $1,400.
</P>
<P>
   Bellagio might have been designed to echo the resorts of the
Italian Lake District, but its room corridors are typical Vegas: a
hub of central elevators feeds loooong spoke wings. The design
maximizes guest rooms with Strip views, but can make for seemingly
endless trudging.
</P>
<P>
   As Las Vegas' newest attraction, Bellagio veers from the
luxury-hotel model in one important way: Its public areas generally
are packed with gawking visitors from all social classes, retired
pensioners to millionaire NBA stars.
</P>
<P>
   Local custom dictates that many of these visitors tote highball
glasses or beer bottles around with them at all times, and not even
the Bellagio can buck local custom. Also, Las Vegas is still a
place where smoking indoors is not only tolerated, but nearly
expected. It's hard to picture, but Bellagio's talented gardeners
no doubt regularly fish flicked butts out of the floral finery.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel's huge casino is new and nice, but for non-gamblers a
nerve-jangling casino nonetheless. If slots, cards, dice and the
wheel are your vices, the Bellagio won't turn you away.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you're pushing a stroller en route to the tables. It's
been reported widely that security staffers at Bellagio's entrances
block unsupervised children, as well as parents with kids in tow
who aren't registered guests.
</P>
<P>
   This practice would seem to discriminate against thrill-seeking
teens and the stroller patrol, which until recently had been a
prime target for Las Vegas marketers.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody got a problem with that? I didn't think so.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the anti-rugrats policy, the crowds mobbing Bellagio's
grounds on a recent weekend appeared to be only slightly more
upscale than comparable customers at The Mirage, Caesars Palace or
any number of class joints around town.
</P>
<P>
   As you tour the casino, lobby and conservatory, you say this to
yourself _ ``Hooker? Nah'' _ only slightly less frequently than the
Vegas norm.
</P>
<P>
   The quality of the crowd improved noticeably in the wait queue
at ``O'', the Bellagio's theatrical experience, where many male
patrons wore coats and ties, and the women clearly came dressed to
impress.
</P>
<P>
   ``O'' defies descriptive language. Its dramatic spell will feel
familiar to anyone who's seen one of the Cirque du Soleil's
traveling tent shows, or Mystere, the Canadian troupe's permanent
show at Treasure Island.
</P>
<P>
   The difference here is the ``O'' part, pronounced ``eau,'' as in
the French word for water.
</P>
<P>
   The Cirque's trademark acrobatics, clowning and surreal
storytelling occur in, above, beside and under a 1.5 million-gallon
pool of 85-degree water.
</P>
<P>
   Frequently, players make their exits (begin ital) into (end
ital) the stage. For the first time ever, anywhere, synchronized
swimming isn't goofy, but artful and cool.
</P>
<P>
   The ``O'' dreamscape, which unfolds in a theater built to
resemble a gilded European opera house, is flat-out magical.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the outrageous ticket prices ($90 for balcony seats and
$100 for the main floor, which largely explains the dressy crowd),
``O'' is one of the most aesthetically satisfying entertainment
values Las Vegas has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   The sprinkler show out in the front-yard pond is free, however,
and when the waters are dancing to the tune of an Italian aria or
Sinatra classic, the effect can be just as serene.
</P>
<P>
   At such times, Bellagio transcends, even escapes, its setting.
</P>
<P>
   No small feat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Contact Dave Walker at dave.walker(at)pni.com via e-mail, fax him
at 253-3734, leave telephone messages for him at 271-8974, or write
him at P.O. Box 2245 NF-19, Phoenix, AZ 85002. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
