<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYUNDAI'S NEW SONATA   LOOKS GOOD, PRICED RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R. WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hyundai rolled into the Museum of Transportation in Brookline,
Mass. to roll out its 1999 Sonata sedan for inspection by the New
England Motor Press. It looks good. It's priced right. The Korean
company is running hard to catch Japan, Europe, and Detroit in
quality while beating their ears off on price.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Halper, Hyundai's director of service,said the company
will ``concentrate on value and capitalize on quality improvement''
to improve its market position. Meanwhile, its Sonata is virtually
all new _ the cigar lighter is a carryover _ and while content has
gone up, O'Neill said, the price has not.
</P>
<P>
   (Content is a popular buzz word in the auto biz; it means the
standard equipment offered. When equipment is deleted, the car is
said to have been ``de-contented.'' To change equipment is to
``re-content'' while an upgrade is simply to ``add content.'' This
is all done in the name of ``adding value'' no matter which way the
contenting proceeds.)
</P>
<P>
   The standard version Sonata for '99 is available fairly well
equipped with a 2.4-liter 149-horsepower 16-valve I-4 engine and
5-speed manual transaxle for $14,999 plus $435 delivery. A 4-speed
automatic electronically controlled transaxle adds $800 to the
price. For the money you get front and side air bags, air
conditioning, AM/FM stereo/cassette, dual power mirrors, power
steering, tach, and power windows.
</P>
<P>
   If you require more, the GLS is available with a 170-horsepower,
24-valve 2.5-liter V-6 for $16,999 plus delivery with a 5-speed
manual, $800 more for the automatic. The GLS adds 4-wheel disc
brakes, heated mirrors, and some other niceties. Only the GLS
offers antilock brakes and traction control, and then only together
as part of a $3,225 option package including leather, power
moonroof, power driver's seat, and a CD player. That's still a lot
for the money, but it is viciously antisocial to tie availability
of vital safety options to purchase of nonvital, pricey luxuries.
After all, Hyundai's best customers are people on limited budgets
who can't afford pricey luxuries.
</P>
<P>
   The car looks good _ it's nicely styled _ offers reasonable room
for four adults, and appears well put together. The proof of the
pudding, as they say, is in the eating, so judgment is withheld
until after a taste test on the road.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The press announcements from Mazda about its Dec. 7 ``Out of the
Box'' awards party continue, bigger, bolder, and more informative.
In the latest installment, we learn that the six cutups listed here
last week are not the finalists; they are the judges. Previous
mailings failed to list the finalists (or the correct telephone
number).
</P>
<P>
   Some of the finalists sound like interesting people who have
accomplished something, but I really have my doubts about Leanne
Schmidt, a Kentucky photographer whose specialty is requesting
subjects to disrobe and leap into a hot tub so that she ``can
photograph them tasetfully in the buff.'' Or the New Jersey guy
whose major contribution to World Civilization is breaking into the
``Guinness Book of Records'' for organizing 43,000 people to do
``The Chicken Dance.'' Honest, I'm not making this stuff up.
</P>
<P>
   The info was accompanied by color photos, one of a very
attractive barefoot young woman clad in a ``tastefully'' low- cut
dress and lying atop a Mazda Protege. She was unidentified,
possibly because being very famous we're all supposed to know who
she is.
</P>
<P>
   So, what I'm anxious to know is why five people are willing to
come to a party in New York on Pearl Harbor Day for the chance to
be named oddball of the year by Dennis Rodman, undoubtedly an
expert on the subject _ and why do the other judges want to be seen
with this guy? And how does this sell cars?
</P>
<P>
   But this sort of ``Out of the Box'' publicity stunt is liable to
be one answer to the question: Why don't we automatically think
``great car'' when someone says ``Mazda''? After this escapade,
maybe General Electric should sue them for giving a light bulb a
bad name _ surely you remember GE's Mazda lamps?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CORRECTION
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The telephone number listed last week for Hemmings Motor News
was incorrect. The correct number is 802-442-3101, or fax
802-447-1561, if you want one of their collectibles catalogs.
</P>
