<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Dec. 6, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _ NATIONAL/GENERAL (Moving in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-MILITIAS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Frustrated and embittered
by their failure to stop abortions _ and a federal law protecting
clinics _ fringes of the anti-abortion movement are linking up with
a new ally: the right-wing militia movement. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   NY-STOCK-EXCHANGE-REVIEW (New York) _ To the surprise of almost
no one, the N.Y. Stock Exchange has decided to stay in New York.
Whether its officials really meant their many threats to move to
New Jersey will never be known. Government giveaways aside, there
are certain intangibles that add up to a strong case that they were
never really serious about leaving. By Charles V. Bagli.
</P>
<P>
   PACS-REVIEW (Undated) _ In today's fund-raising frenzy,
candidates and organizations have to be increasingly inventive in
thinking up ways to separate donors from their money. Although the
evidence is anecdotal, there are signs that patriotic, optimistic
or catchy names help political action committees raise more cash.
By Jill Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   PEARL-HARBOR-REVIEW (Undated) _ Excerpts from the diary of a
Pearl Harbor survivor, Henry Lachenmayer of Oxon Hill, Md.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-MYTHS-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at some recent
scientific and medical myths. Scientists may be no different from
lay people when it comes a message that strikes a chord in them. By
Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ FOREIGN (Moving in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-REVIEW (Johannesburg) _ Most wars in Africa since the end
of colonialism have been civil wars, but not the current war in
Congo. Troops from as far south as Namibia and as far north as Chad
are fighting inside the Congo basin. In one sense, what has
developed is a tribal war along lines that are almost biblical _
rulers from Nilotic ethnic groups in Rwanda, Burundi and Uganda
against Bantu peoples of central and southern Africa in league with
Arab rulers of northern Chad and Sudan. By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-FOOD-REVIEW (Moscow) _ The entire Russian diet is
lurching through a perestroika that mirrors the bust-and-boom,
future-vs.-past nature of the nation's economy and its mentality.
By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-FRANCE-BRITAIN-REVIEW (Paris) _ With allies like France,
does the U.S. really need enemies? Put another way: With allies
like Britain, who needs France? Exasperated U.S. policy-makers have
asked themselves questions like these over the years. By Craig R.
Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
