<HEADLINE>
REPORT POINTS TO MAJOR SHORTCOMINGS IN CALIFORNIA SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Despite the push to cut class size, California
ranks dead last among states in the number of teachers, counselors
and librarians per pupil, according to a study released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It is a distinction that is hardly welcome, but not surprising:
California's system of public education is bigger and more complex
than any other in the country. Still, California, one of the
wealthiest states in the nation, spends far less per pupil than
many other states.
</P>
<P>
   The study, ``How California Compares,'' was conducted by Palo
Alto-based EdSource, an independent, nonprofit, educational
research group. It ranks 50 states and the District of Columbia on
graduation rates, teacher salary, funding and the number of
teachers, administrators and computers per pupil, among other
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a common (misperception) that all the money that's
been added to the K-12 budget in the last few years has helped,''
EdSource research director Barbara Miller said. ``That's not true.
These invisible services, such as counselors and librarians, have
been cut. They're services that complement the classroom and have a
real impact on the education of youngsters.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov.-elect Gray Davis said this week that ``restoring
California's schools to greatness will be the cornerstone of my
administration.''
</P>
<P>
   The report paints a detailed, eye-opening picture of the
immediate needs posed by a surging student population, an aging
teaching force and inadequate, antiquated schools.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, California:
</P>
<P>
   _ educates about one in eight of the nation's children.
Enrollment, now 5.6 million students, is expected to grow by 15
percent during the next decade. Nationally, growth is expected to
be about 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ is ninth among states in average teacher salary _ $43,474.
Alaska is highest at $50,647 and South Dakota lowest at $26,764.
When adjusted for inflation, the average California teacher's
salary has dropped 0.8 percent in the past decade, compared with an
increase of 3.5 percent nationally.
</P>
<P>
   _ ranks 37th in high school graduation rates, with 65.3 percent
of students who enter high school graduating four years later.
</P>
<P>
   _ is 47th in revenue for public schools per $1,000 in personal
income. While most other major states increased their per-pupil
expenditures between 1990 and 1996, California's spending on public
schools was virtually flat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ranks 15th in students per teacher and principal, and 51st in
students per guidance counselor and librarian. California has
nearly three times more students per district administrator and
twice as many per counselor as the national average. The paucity of
librarians is stunning: one for every 6,334 students, compared with
the national average of one per 885 students.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of other states in the same boat, but
California is experiencing the pressure of recruiting and retaining
new teachers sooner than most and on a scale greater than most,''
said Elizabeth Fideler, vice president for policy and research at
Recruiting New Teachers Inc., a Belmont, Mass.-based nonprofit
organization.
</P>
<P>
   California will need about 300,000 new teachers during the next
decade to keep up with projected enrollment growth and teacher
departures. The average age of California's more than 236,000
teachers is 43; one of seven is over 55. About 50 percent of new
teachers leave the profession within the first five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are reasons to be guardedly optimistic about
California's efforts to recruit new teachers,'' Fideler said,
pointing to Cal Teach, a statewide program established by Gov. Pete
Wilson in 1997 to remedy the dearth of qualified teachers.
</P>
<P>
   There are other glimmers of hope, according to the EdSource
report:
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1997, 47 percent of the state's high school graduates took
the SAT, 4 percentage points more than the national average. Scores
have climbed for four straight years, and in 1997 were the highest
since 1973.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1998, 13.4 percent of all juniors and seniors passed
advanced placement exams, compared with the national average of 9.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Under Wilson, California adopted new and rigorous standards for
what children should know in math, history, science and English.
The new statewide Standardized Testing and Reporting program, given
last spring to California students in grades 2 through 11, is being
aligned to those standards.
</P>
<P>
   Still, to improve the state's academically inferior schools,
policymakers and the new Davis administration will have to do more
than implement reforms enacted by Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   As outgoing state Board of Education president Yvonne Larsen, a
Wilson appointee, said, ``I hope Gray Davis will build on the
reforms we've made. What his administration has going for them is
that everyone is talking about improving education.
</P>
<P>
   ``All eyes and ears are on the state to move schools forward. We
can't let this moment in our lifetime pass by without making major
reforms for kids in the classroom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
