<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANYON-FISHING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISHING'S THE BAIT, GRAND CANYON'S THE HOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RON DUNGAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND CANYON, Ariz. - I don't hike much anymore. I (begin ital)
walk (end ital) a lot because I like to fish mountain streams all
over Arizona, or for that matter whatever state I happen to be in.
For some reason the fishing always looks better around the next
bend, which means I wind up going on some fairly long and
interesting walks, but I rarely just hike for the sake of hiking.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago I was invited by some friends to backpack the
Hermit Trail in the Grand Canyon. I started sorting through various
pieces of gear that I had stored in corners and closets throughout
the house but had not actually used in quite a while.
</P>
<P>
   This seems strange to me now, because when I moved to Arizona
about all I had besides some clothes and books was a pair of hiking
boots and a backpack. They got a lot of use, but after a few years
the boots started to break down from wading a favorite stream a
little too often, and the pack took a beating once when my camp was
ransacked by a bear.
</P>
<P>
   Over time the boots were retired, the pack was hung in the
garage and new toys took their place: waders, fly rods, float
tubes. For one reason or another, I simply stopped backpacking,
though from time to time I thought I might take it up again.
</P>
<P>
   When the invitation came, I dusted off the pack and started
taking running and trips to the gym a lot more seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Getting in shape for any trip down the Canyon is a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   The Hermit Trail begins, logically enough, at Hermits Rest. From
there it goes pretty much straight down for about a mile. There are
plenty of books about the Hermit, and they will tell you that along
this first mile there are cobblestones that formed the early mule
trails, but I happen to know that the park service put those rocks
there to keep people from sliding over the edge, and that mules
never actually went down that trail because mules have more sense
than that. You don't realize how steep it is until you make the
hike up, but it is one of the more challenging parts of the trail.
</P>
<P>
   I got in good shape, but as it turned out I needed a little
something extra to keep me going. Most people do. I told myself
there was great fishing at the bottom and cold beer on top; that
was all the mental edge I needed.
</P>
<P>
   Backpacking is one of those odd pleasures that, for most people,
involve a little pain, but you still feel pretty good about the
whole thing. After the first day, you make a lot of jokes about how
stiff you are and how you are going to lie down and die right
there, but they are just jokes. In the morning when you wake up,
you may be sore, but you have a whole day ahead of you, very little
time in a very special place, and hopefully, fish to be caught.
</P>
<P>
   Every now and then you hear a rumor that the Grand Canyon is one
of those places where the trout are as long as your arm and not too
particular about what they eat. I knew enough to regard these
rumors with a certain amount of skepticism and, as it turned out,
we didn't get a single bite.
</P>
<P>
   A ranger we saw on the trail said that Hermit Creek didn't have
the best fishing in the Canyon anyway. Never mind where he said
(begin ital) does (end ital) have the best fishing. He said not to
tell anyone when he told my friend, who told me. That's as far as
it gets.
</P>
<P>
   I tried the usual assortment of dry flies, scuds, nymphs and
midges, dragged woolly buggers through the deeper holes and
basically threw out every fly in my box, but I didn't have much
hope because the river was pretty muddy, which will put fish off
from feeding. Fishing is like that. You can spend a lot of time and
effort getting to a lake or stream, only to hear someone say,
``Well, you should have been here last week.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference this time was that, even though the fish weren't
biting, we were in the Grand Canyon. I've been a lot of places
where I've been told I should have been there a week ago, or maybe
next week, or whatever, and they've all been nice places, but they
weren't, well, they weren't the Grand Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Things get real quiet late in the day. The light begins to fade,
hikers stop moving around and you have the place _ and everything
that comes with it _ all to yourself. The view at sunset. The
starry nights. The first light of dawn. And as you leave, you
figure out what has been missing _ the best part of any backpacking
trip is reaching the top.
</P>
<P>
   When you hike the Canyon, you don't do this until the very end.
And you begin to realize what you knew all along. You didn't come
here to fish after all, and even if you had, you're glad you came
anyway. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
