<HEADER>
A3731 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-PSYCHO-BOS &LR;      12-04 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PSYCHO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAKE `PSYCHO' NOT WHAT IT SHOULD BE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Psycho,'' Gus Van Sant's nervy remake of the 1960 horror
classic, is less a film than a vague curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   It is, in the most strident, unbending sense of the word, a
remake. Van Sant used Joseph Stefano's original script and
painstakingly re-created virtually every camera angle, every shot,
every trick first used by Alfred Hitchcock. Van Sant himself has
called his film ``a forgery. Like we're making a copy of the Mona
Lisa or the statue of David.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, raises the question: Who wants to see a
forgery when you can see the real deal?
</P>
<P>
   ``Psycho,'' Van Sant's $25 million remake of Hitchcock's
$800,000 movie, brings practically nothing new to the party. This
is the film equivalent of karaoke. Van Sant uses color, and a few
modern touches like push-button phones _ as one might add a shaky
melismatic swoop to Aretha Franklin's ``Respect,'' at a late-night
bar _ but it adds nothing significant, and only deepens the longing
for the still-stunning original.
</P>
<P>
   Even the opening credits, with Bernard Herrmann's shrieky,
string-laden score, are the same, except, of course, the names of
the actors have changed. Anne Heche takes over for Janet Leigh as
the world's most unfortunate motel guest, Marion Crane, and we
first see her the same way audiences saw her 38 years ago _ in a
Phoenix hotel room, catching a little afternoon delight with her
lover Sam Loomis (Viggo Mortensen). Marion is tired of their
no-tell hotel trysts and wants to get married, but Sam's deep in
debt, and has little to offer other than a threadbare life in the
back of his father's hardware store. With his cowboy boots and
dopey stare, at least Mortensen looks more like the poor hick
Stefano's script imagined than John Gavin's woodenly gorgeous,
well-dressed Sam in the original.
</P>
<P>
   Heche is said to have watched each of Leigh's scenes before
re-creating the role, and does it ever show. She apes every
movement, every smirk, every eye roll, using none of her
considerable talents to make the role her own. Then again, she was
probably just following Van Sant's (Hitchcock's?) direction.
</P>
<P>
   The same problems are apparent in Vince Vaughn's performance as
murderous momma's boy Norman Bates. Certainly any actor attempting
that role after Anthony Perkins would be in trouble; Perkins's
performance was so indelible it pretty much ruined his career,
since few could accept him playing anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   But like Heche, Vaughn, an interesting actor, is never given the
chance to put his stamp on the role. He's hamstrung by Van Sant's
lunkheaded decision to literally remake the film, and his turn as
Norman Bates is less a performance than a Rich Little
impersonation. Like Perkins, he is first shown in an ill-fitting
corduroy jacket with the collar turned up. He carts out Perkins's
nervous laugh when he's expected to, but it never really works, and
he almost seems to be spoofing the role.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't help that Vaughn lacks the boyish innocence that
duped the first ``Psycho'' audiences into believing such a lovely
young man truly would never hurt a fly. As Norman, the strapping
Vaughn always seems as if he may do damage. Even if audiences
weren't already familiar with Norman's true disposition, Vaughn
just oozes danger and malice _ among other things 1960s censors
never would have allowed Hitchcock to get away with.
</P>
<P>
   Less problematic are the small roles of William H. Macy as
private investiagtor Milton Arbogast, and Julianne Moore as
Marion's sister, Lila. Moore does manage to bring a feisty feminist
spark to her performance. Robert Forster plays the psychologist who
explains Norman/Mother, here named Dr. Simon, a nod to the late
actor Simon Oakland, who played the role in the original.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine the target audience for this film. If Van
Sant fancied capturing the teenage audiences that made the
``Scream'' films hits, he should have upped the body count, the
cool pop references, and the gore content. There are still only two
murders, there's no profanity, and even in color, the blood is kept
to a minimum. And for anyone familiar with the original, well,
where's the suspense? You already know about the shower scene, and
Norman's penchant for taxidermy and cheap wigs.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is a shame, since Van Sant has often brought a
distinctive bravura to his films such as ``My Own Private Idaho''
and ``To Die For.'' The mind boggles at what the filmmaker could
have done with this fertile material if he hadn't been so committed
to slavishly copying Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Van Sant's ``Psycho'' may imitate Hitchcock's in a way
he probably wasn't striving for: The original was panned by
critics. While history has proven them wrong, don't expect the same
reversal of fortune for Van Sant's wholly unnecessary rip-off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
