<HEADLINE>
SPORTS BROADCASTING NEEDS A DOSE OF REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The football is heaved deep, the receiver has a
step on the defensive back, the ball falls into his hands, then
drops harmlessly to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   How often have you heard this: ``He has to catch that ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Often. Maybe every game. Conversely, if the ball is thrown
behind him, there's this: ``He's gotta make better throws than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Football analysis is dead. Going into the pro football games
this weekend, you can expect to hear the same things your father
heard all those years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sports has always been littered with cliches. It's part of the
charm and part of the contract with fans. Terminology and
description become common because an announcer can convey to a fan
exactly what he or she is thinking as the action unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the problem. See anything familiar in this list?
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got to step it up.'' ``He's under a lot of pressure
tonight'' (pressure and momentum being two of the most overused
words in broadcasting). ``You could hear that hit up here.'' ``He
turned it up another level.'' ``That's a big line.'' ``This team
has so many weapons.'' ``Here's where experience pays off.'' ``On
any Sunday, any team in the NFL can win.''
</P>
<P>
   The question that needs to be asked is, when did broadcasters
begin to frown on original description and simply fall back on
familiarity? You'd think that if it was your job to add ``color''
to a football broadcast, you'd study for it. Maybe think about new
ways to say things. Try to be thoughtful or informative.
</P>
<P>
   This problem exists in most sports, of course, but the current
football season has been uncommonly bad. One of the worst trends
this year is spending a quarter of each broadcast talking about the
officiating. If it's bad, say so and move on. Come back to it once
or twice, but harping on it only shows you're bored or on
autopilot.
</P>
<P>
   A problem with any kind of sports broadcast is that true fans
are educated through years of watching and reading. ESPN's pre- and
post-game shows are the best at illustrating new ideas, dissecting
events. Ron Jaworski's game-film breakdowns are the finest examples
of this.
</P>
<P>
   Yet virtually every other network pre-game show is little more
than ex-athletes or coaches talking fast and saying nothing.
Whatever happened to substance?
</P>
<P>
   Sideline reporting is the worst offender. At this point in the
season, the only mystery is what kind of hat and jacket combination
Leslie Visser is going to throw together. It's safe to say that
Visser _ and her sideline peers _ have added nothing of value this
entire season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just talked to the coach, and he says the team is going to
stick with the game plan despite being down two touchdowns.''
``Coming out of the locker room, the coach said his team's
confidence is high but they need to retain their focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Some real gems come out of those reports.
</P>
<P>
   Even though ESPN has vaunted pre-game and post-game shows, the
network still has a lot of work to do in the booth. It's not good
enough to just tell us how the safeties couldn't get back in
coverage or that playing off receivers during a blitz is a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   There has to be something more.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the trick is in telling viewers what they didn't see,
not what they could so easily see a moment earlier. Is that so
hard? Anyone can say, after the fullback plunged 2 yards for the
first down, ``He bulls his way for two and looks to have picked up
the first down.'' Yeah, got it.
</P>
<P>
   What's the solution? A revolution. And those are never easy. The
comfort factor in sports is part of the reason people watch.
</P>
<P>
   We've been programmed since childhood to like repetition. John
Madden has repeated the same broadcast for more than a decade, and
nobody seems to mind. Hearing about those fat bellies and socks
falling down and muddy uniforms _ not to mention the ubiquitous
``boom!'' _ is like wearing comfortable jeans and an old sweat
shirt.
</P>
<P>
   One day three guys in a booth will have sat down the previous
night, talked about a way to do things differently, executed the
whole thing in front of a national audience and _ boom! _ we'll be
a changed country.
</P>
<P>
   To pull it off, they'll have to stay focused, take it one game
at a time and give 110 percent. Is that asking for too much?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
