<HEADLINE>
VH1 DOES SOME BUSINESS WITH R.E.M. ROCKUMENTARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Recently, Variety magazine ran an article on the market power of
``Behind the Music.'' Turns out VH1's beautifully executed
rockumentary series sells CDs _ and not just CDs from the artist's
catalog of music, which matter, but the newer product, which
really, really matters. It's no surprise, then, that ``Behind the
Music'' is choosing to flex its newfound muscle these days by
telling the stories of still-vital musicians who just happen to
have a new album out _ usual suspects like Madonna, Metallica, and,
Sunday night at 9, R.E.M.
</P>
<P>
   Since these performers are abundantly present on the pop scene,
they make for only mildly compelling documentary fare. I mean do we
really need yet another look at the many faces of Madonna? Their
stories are still in progress, and their promotional instincts
remain in play, unlike more interesting and historical ``Behind the
Music'' subjects like the Mamas and the Papas, the Grateful Dead,
John Denver, and Jim Croce. While the trumped-up voiceover
narration of R.E.M. ``Behind the Music'' tries to instill drummer
Bill Berry's ``tragic brush with death'' and his departure from the
band with all the drama of a Lynyrd Skynyrd plane crash, the
unfortunate events are not enough to lift R.E.M.'s story to the
level of true rock-biopic pathos.
</P>
<P>
   Which isn't to say that the R.E.M. ``Behind the Music'' is not
worth a good look. As usual, the filmmakers have stuffed their hour
with fantastic clips _ and the R.E.M. clips are particularly
eye-popping as they chronicle Michael Stipe's long hair journey
from romantic poet to space egg. (Stipe's eyeglasses, too, make for
quite the parade.) Also worthwhile are recent interviews with the
band, including comments from Berry about his aneurysm (``It felt
like a bowling ball hit my head'') and his decision to leave R.E.M.
to spend his days crop farming. Stipe shares some thoughts about
his ``queerness,'' as well as his shift from shy boy with bangs to
bold, bald front man. In one old clip, Stipe is actually seen
hiding from a greeting by David Letterman after singing ``So.
Central Rain'' on the late-night talk show.
</P>
<P>
   On the new R.E.M. ``Storytellers,'' which VH1 premieres at 10
p.m., Stipe reveals a little of his look-at-me-don't-look-at-me
bashfulness, stumbling through explications of his songs and
admitting ``I think I'm a little nervous _ I just realized that.''
But who expects clarity and directness from Stipe, who is famous
not only for hiding his lyrics behind muddy pronunciations but for
obscuring his meaning with gorgeous but impenetrable phrases? It's
amusing, though, to hear him finesse his descriptions of songs like
like ``Fall on Me'' and ``Losing My Religion,'' which some people
think is a theological inquiry. ``It's not,'' Stipe says. ``It's
just a song about having a crush.'' And at moments he is quite
eloquent, introducing ``Man on the Moon'' with a touching reverence
for comic Andy Kaufman, ``the greatest Elvis Presley impersonator
of our time.''
</P>
<P>
   The band's musical performance on ``Storytellers'' is fine, if a
little uninspired. Without Berry, some of the older songs seem to
take on a mechanical, hurried drive. The exception is Berry's
``Perfect Circle'' from ``Murmur,'' which Stipe sings beautifully
and with clear affection for the former drummer. The cuts from the
new album, ``Up,'' are more dynamic, including ``Daysleeper,'' with
some energetic piano playing from Mike Mills and ``At My Most
Beautiful,'' with its Beach Boys-like purity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
