<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-RENO-$ADV06-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO NEARS DECISION ON ANOTHER SPECIAL COUNSEL FOR CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Dec. 6)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno faces a Monday deadline
to decide whether to seek an independent counsel to investigate
possible campaign law violations by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Reno must determine if there is evidence that Clinton knowingly
violated election laws when he directed a multi-million dollar
advertising campaign by the Democratic National Committee that
might have improperly benefited the Clinton-Gore presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   If Reno asks the U.S. Court of Appeals to appoint an independent
counsel and if the court agrees with her, it would be the 11th time
she has sent a case to a special prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Reno also could delay her decision by asking the court for more
time to study the question, though she has been mulling it for two
years. Late last month, Reno came right up to the deadline in
another case and ended up asking for more time to study it. That
case involved allegations that Harold Ickes, a former top Clinton
aide, lied to federal investigators about his efforts on behalf of
the teamsters to get top administration officials to intervene for
the union in a labor dispute.
</P>
<P>
   In the case with the Monday deadline, Reno is investigating
whether Clinton and top White House advisers illegally controlled a
DNC television advertising blitz that began in the fall of 1995.
Those ads touted Clinton's stand on the budget showdown with
congressional Republicans that year.
</P>
<P>
   She must determine if the DNC commercials were in reality
re-election ads for the president's campaign, masquerading as
issue-advocacy spots that political parties can legitimately
produce. Because the ads were placed by the DNC, they could be
largely paid for with so-called ``soft-money'' _ big, unregulated
contributions from individuals and corporate and union treasury
funds that couldn't be contributed legally to an individual
candidate's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole issue boils down to trying to keep big donors from
influencing candidates,'' said Viet Dinh, an expert on campaign
finance law at Georgetown University.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton may be helped by a report issued last week by the
Federal Election Commission staff that investigated the issue of
campaign advertising for both the Clinton campaign and Republican
challenger Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Although FEC staff auditors concluded that both Clinton and Dole
improperly coordinated with the DNC and the Republican National
Committee on nationwide television advertising blitzes during the
campaign, the auditors stopped short of alleging criminal
activities on either candidate's part.
</P>
<P>
   The auditors recommended that Clinton and Dole pay fines of $7
million and $17.7 million, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Since Reno often looks to the FEC for guidance on how to
interpret election laws, some legal specialists say the auditors'
report should help Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reno may find a lot of comfort in the fact that the FEC staff
isn't alleging criminal conduct and use that to dismiss the whole
matter,'' said former independent counsel Joseph E. diGenova.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the attorney general also may put off her decision
on an independent counsel until the FEC's full commission makes a
final ruling on whether to accept, reject or modify the staff
audit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the full commission is something of the final word on
all of this, it wouldn't be that surprising if she just waited for
its decision on the staff report,'' diGenova said.
</P>
<P>
   Trevor Potter, a former FEC commissioner, agreed, saying in an
interview that the laws governing campaign advertising are often
``vague'' and that Reno may be waiting for more clarification from
the FEC.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the need for clarification was obvious at a Thursday
meeting of the full commission to discuss the staff report on the
Clinton and Dole campaigns. Several of six commissioners admitted
that even they could not fully understand the statutes.
</P>
<P>
   Acting Commission Chairman Scott E. Thomas called the laws
governing campaign advertisements ``less than clear.'' He said
previous FEC rulings had allowed advertisements that told viewers
not to vote for a certain candidate even though the commercials
were supposed to promote only generic party themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, how you say that doesn't help that candidate's opponent
is something I don't fully understand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner David M. Mason who called the statutes ``fuzzy.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Reno has refused to comment on either the FEC
staff audit or the views of the commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Reno decided against appointing an independent
counsel to investigate whether Vice President Gore lied to Justice
Department officials during an investigation last year of
fund-raising phone calls he placed from his White House office
during the 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Her decision drew fire from Republicans who said there was
abundant evidence to justify the appointment of a special
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   They pointed out that Reno's hand-picked campaign-finance
prosecutor, Charles La Bella, who left the job last July,
recommended appointing an independent counsel to look into possible
campaign law violations by Clinton. In addition, they noted that
FBI Director Louis Freeh also recommended a special prosecutor to
investigate the matter.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., chairman of the House
Judiciary Committee, said no evidence of impeachable offenses
against the president were found in a review of secret memorandums
on campaign fund-raising written by La Bella and Freeh.
</P>
<P>
   Dinh said the committee's abandonment of the campaign finance
issue relieves some of the pressure on Reno to appoint an
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans lose their ability to point to the
recommendations of Freeh and La Bella and say, `You must be
covering up something,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dinh added: ``Clinton could very well walk away without a
scratch _ again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
