A3758 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-12-05-COX     12-04 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-12-05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JACKSON CALLS INCOME GAP 'DIRTY LITTLE SECRET'
 &HT;    430 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Rev. Jesse Jackson vowed Friday to ``set the
pace'' in the campaign for the 2000 Democratic presidential
nomination by focusing the nation's attention on income inequality
and the unbroken cycle of poverty in Appalachia.
</P>
<P>
   In a televised luncheon speech to the National Press Club,
Jackson said his recent visits to poverty-stricken communities of
Appalachia have expanded his views, most of which were formed in
the civil rights struggle of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, I am driven by the moral imperative to leave no
American behind,'' he said. ``That's why I am more convinced than
ever that the single most important issue facing our nation as we
move into the next century is the ever-widening gap between the
haves and have-nots in our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, noting that other prominent Democrats have tested
campaign themes this week, said he was ``pleased to be able to
participate in this important exercise.'' But he did not commit
himself to running what would be his third presidential campaign
for his party's nomination. He ran in 1984 and 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I have not yet decided whether or not to enter the race,
I do intend to set the pace,'' he said. He would do so by
challenging the Democratic candidates to come with him to such poor
Appalachian communities as Mud Creek, a tiny town in hills of
eastern Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   The ``test'' of Democratic presidential candidates in 2000 is
``Do you matter to Mud Creek?'' Jackson said. ``Do you have
anything to say that is relevant to the people of eastern Kentucky
and central West Virginia and Appalachian Ohio, where good people,
working hard, have tried to break the cycle of poverty?''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said ``America's dirty little secret'' is how the gap
between the richest and poorest Americans has grown over the past
two decades. According to the Census Bureau, the bottom half of the
wage-earning population has seen its income stagnate over the past
20 years, while the top 5 percent of households have seen their
income double.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't hear presidential candidates talk about this much,
if at all,'' Jackson said. ``We need to talk about this gap. We
need to confront it. We need to resolve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has persuaded President Clinton and House
Speaker-designate Bob Livingston to participate in a two-day
conference with Wall Street executives in New York next month to
examine ways to promote private investment in inner cities and
rural areas. It is the second such event hosted by Jackson. Both
have been timed to commemorate the late Martin Luther King Jr.'s
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
