   BBN-BRAVES _ ATLANTA _ An analysis: Perhaps no team in baseball
has improved as much with offseason moves as the Braves. And more
could be on the horizon. (Stinson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BB0-MEETINGS _ The major-league baseball meetings have resumed
after a two-year layoff caused by halls filled with too much
bartering and too many agents. (Stinson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-AUGUSTA _ Four holes at Augusta National were reworked this
summer, mostly to add some distance and put more of a premium on
accuracy. An update on how the changes have been received by some
Augusta members. (Most of the tour pros don't know any more about
it than what they've read). Hopefully, some comments by chairman
Hootie Johnson. (Sheeley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FBO-PREPFOOTBALL _ ATLANTA _ To many Georgia high school
communities, winning football programs is of paramount importance.
Schools and their backers go to great lengths to assure that trophy
cases in the campus lobby will fill up. In the '90s, the vehicle
for providing the resources for success is well-financed booster
clubs who provide first-class facilities and equipment and
well-paid coaches to the schools. While many urban schools toil in
run-down stadiums, a few of the booster-driven teams play in spiffy
areans with ``luxury boxes'' and fancy clubhouses outside the
gates. A look at how booster clubs operate and how counties and
schools across the state compensate football coaches. (Fish,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/sidebars on three schools that represent stages of booster
clubs
</P>
<P>
   VALDOSTA _ The originator of booster clubs, founded in 1944.
It's no coincidence that claims the most football victories
nationwide. But because it's a city school in an area where other
schools are gaining on them, times have been tougher in recent
years. The club has 1,300 members, down from 1,800, but still pays
for a two-week camp before the season for players, a car for the
head coach and a coaches fund to slip the staff bonuses after the
season. (Fish, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BROOKWOOD _ The model for metro Atlanta. Brookwood has quickly
become a statewide power since its birth in the mid-'80s, and other
schools in Gwinnett are imitating the Broncos. The head coach has
his own TV show and is treated royally. He teaches no classes and
boosters gave him and his wife a trip to Hawaii. The touchdown club
has been a rallying point for affluent parents who donate their
time and money to the football program. (Fish, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WESTSIDE _ The new kid on the block. The Macon, Ga., school,
just two years old, was created in part to draw students back from
the dozen or so private schools in the city. And the lure is
football. Parents and Bibb County school officials see football to
better things in the community. Officials claim the school system
has been in decline since integration. The new superintendent from
football-crazy Odessa, Texas, convinced the board of education to
increase coaching stipends to $22,000. Enrollment at the school is
1,700 and growing, and the team is winning. (Fish, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) w/charts, runs with main
</P>
