<SLUG> BC-SMITH-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET COMPANY BROKERS GOOD IDEAS FROM EMPLOYEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the corporate world's most undervalued assets is the
employee idea bank.
</P>
<P>
   Most companies aren't very good at cultivating this resource.
They may encourage employee suggestions, for example, but they
don't follow through on them. Or they fail to reward employees when
suggestions save money. Either way, employees get the message their
ideas don't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies do sometimes have ideas that go unheard,'' said
Barry Lawrence, director of the Society for Human Resource
Management in Alexandria, Va. ``It's a crying shame.''
</P>
<P>
   Andre Laurin wants to change that.
</P>
<P>
   Laurin, 37, used to develop employee suggestion systems for
several management consulting firms before striking out on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I'd meet smart people with great ideas, and they
were just stifled,'' he said. ``The mechanics of getting ideas
approved in organizations killed a lot of innovation.''
</P>
<P>
   So a year ago, Laurin founded the internet company BrainBank
(www.brain-bank.com) to serve as a kind of idea broker.
</P>
<P>
   He solicits cost-saving suggestions from people, then takes them
back to the companies they work for. If the company uses the idea,
both BrainBank and the employee who came up with the suggestion get
to share in the savings.
</P>
<P>
   So far, BrainBank, which is headquartered in Montreal, claims to
have brokered more than 30 ideas, some of them worth six and seven
figures in savings to companies and a tidy sum to the people who
came up with them.
</P>
<P>
   Melanie, who wouldn't give her last name or the name of the
business she worked for, said she used BrainBank to get her company
to save money on overnight delivery costs.
</P>
<P>
   She works for a company that wholesales tour packages to travel
agencies. Many times, the company would send multiple overnight
packages to the same address, she said. She figured the company
could save $37,000 a year in carrier costs by consolidating its
deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of going directly to the company with her idea, she went
to BrainBank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew if I were to bring it up (to the company,) I wouldn't
get the recognition or monetary reward,'' she said. ``It's not a
part of our pay scheme. There's no real incentive to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The company agreed to put her plan into action, and she pocketed
$13,875 for the idea, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt great,'' she said. ``It felt like I actually made a
contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   For each idea that a company agrees to implement, BrainBank
takes 12.5 percent of the net first year's savings. The employee
who suggested it gets 37.5 percent of the first year's savings. The
company that implements the idea gets the rest of the cost savings,
plus 100 percent of future savings.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some initial success with BrainBank, however, Laurin
said it quickly became clear that companies weren't always eager to
pay a middleman for their own employees' ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We encountered increased resistance,'' Laurin said. ``What we
saw is companies want to manage this process themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurin took the suggestion. Now BrainBank has developed intranet
software that allows clients to form their own in-house idea
management systems, and it is gathering momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence of the Society for Human Resource Management said many
companies are looking for a fresh approach to soliciting employee
ideas.
</P>
<P>
   The old suggestion box systems have a lot of stigmas attached to
them, he said. ``People feel like they're beating their heads
against the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   The BrainBank software allows employees to make their
suggestions anonymously. Using software applications developed by
BrainBank, the employee does a complete cost-benefit analysis on
his idea. Then the idea goes into a central file. Department
managers can peruse all the ideas, but they won't know where they
came from.
</P>
<P>
   That allows the ideas to be evaluated solely on their merit,
Laurin said. If a manager likes an idea, he can ``take ownership of
its implementation.''
</P>
<P>
   When ideas are turned into programs, both the employee and the
manager who implemented the program get to share in the rewards, he
said. BrainBank, which licenses the software, also gets 10 percent
of the savings for the first year only.
</P>
<P>
   BrainBank is testing the intranet software at several companies
and said demand has been encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   The old notion that ideas come from top management is changing,
Lawrence said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the best ideas come from the bottom of the pyramid,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Listening for solutions. That's the whole idea.
</P>
</TEXT>
