<HEADLINE>
SYNTH-POP BAND DEPECHE MODE FINDS ITSELF BACK IN FASHION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Martin Gore, guitarist, keyboardist and background vocalist for
Depeche Mode, is enjoying the live, visceral power of the English
synth-pop band's first concert tour in five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing a musician sitting there behind us at a drum kit and
feeling that physical sound coming from the drums is very different
for us,'' Gore said in a phone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time we've used a drummer for the whole set.''
</P>
<P>
   And thanks in part to an array of sophisticated computers, the
shows are running smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're running computers for the first time on this tour,''
Gore added. ``And we've got this really good guy running them. So
we haven't really had one problem on the whole tour, which is
pretty amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   The current tour supports ``The Singles: 1986-1998,'' a 21-song
double album that includes the new single, ``Only When I Lose
Myself,'' but excludes early hits by Vince Clarke, now with
Erasure.
</P>
<P>
   There's a definite advantage to a tour based on a retrospective
album, Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to go out and play songs that most people know,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we go out on tour with a new album, a lot of our fans are
obsessive, so a lot of them know the songs anyway. But there's an
element in the audience that won't have bought the new album.
</P>
<P>
   ``On this tour, I think everyone in the audience knows every
song we play.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he is proud of the album, and quite satisfied with how
it turned out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been looking forward to putting out this album for some
time,'' he said. ``From 1986 until now, we've pretty much liked
everything we recorded. I think we started getting things right in
about 1986. But we put off releasing the album at least a couple of
times, so it's good to finally get it out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Depeche Mode, which very loosely translates as ``quick fashion''
in French, formed in 1980. The group discarded its guitars in favor
of synthesizers and jumped headlong into London's stylish ``new
romantic'' scene.
</P>
<P>
   When Clarke left the group in the early '80s, Gore took over the
role as chief songwriter. A run of hit singles featuring Gore's
moody, introspective lyrics transformed the group into an
arena-size act with a legion of fans.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Black Celebration'' in 1986, the group reintroduced
guitars and increased its profile in Europe. The 1987 album ``Music
for the Masses'' lived up to its title by turning the group into a
major concert attraction in the United States. The band's 1988 U.S.
tour, later captured on the 1989 double live album ``101,''
concluded with a concert at Pasadena's Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Depeche Mode now enjoys newfound popularity in the United States
as electronic-based music increases in profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly America got electronica and everybody wants to know
about it, whereas in the rest of the world it's been accepted for a
long while,'' Gore said with a touch of disdain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I think too much importance, especially over here,
is being paid to the instrumentation.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the synth-pop pioneers were the subject of a tribute
album featuring current techno artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's one of the greatest honors a band can have,''
Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   The group's previous album was ``Ultra,'' a dark, redemptive
techno-rock collection. Its release followed singer David Gahan's
1996 drug overdose, which delayed the group's plans to tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had actually been clean for about six months at that
stage,'' Gore said. ``We just thought it would be a bit precarious
for him to be going out into a really unstable environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apart from that, we'd been in the studio for 15 months on and
off making `Ultra,' and we weren't really in the right frame of
mind for going straight into rehearsals and straight out on tour.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to core members Gore, Gahan and keyboardist Andy
Fletcher, the tour includes keyboardist Peter Gordeno (replacing
Alan Wilder, who left in 1995) and Austrian drummer Christian
Eigner, as well as gospel singers Jordan Bailey and Janet Cooke.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the band has no immediate plans to return to the
studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking a relaxed attitude about the next album,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have lives outside of the band and there are times when
we want to do things that normal people do. After the tour, we'll
sit down and decide what to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
