<SLUG> BC-TRUCK-SAFETY05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TRUCK CRASHES KILLED 5,335 PEOPLE LAST YEAR
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Crashes involving large trucks killed 5,335 people
nationwide in 1997, the highest toll in eight years, a consumer
safety group reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Government transportation agencies need to step in to make the
highways safer from these big rigs, Joan Claybrook, chair of
Citizens for Reliable and Safe Highways (CRASH), warned. She
announced the results of the study, which is based on U.S.
Department of Transportation (DOT) data, at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trucking remains America's most dangerous commercial
enterprise,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the trucking industry said that ``the risk of being
killed in a car-truck collision is at an all-time low.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of trucks and cars on the highways has increased
dramatically over the past two decades. So while the total number
of deaths rose slightly last year _ from 5,142 in 1996 to 5,335 in
1997 _ the number of deaths per miles driven has dropped steadily
for decades, said Walter McCormick, president of the American
Trucking Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any death on our nation's highways is a tragedy,'' said
McCormick. ``But the hysteria being orchestrated cannot hide the
facts. ... Miles driven are up. The fatality rate is down.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past 20 years, the fatality rate in crashes involving big
trucks has fallen from 6 deaths to 2.4 deaths per million miles
driven, the DOT figures show.
</P>
<P>
   But Claybrook said the fact that more Americans are being killed
in truck-related crashes is reason enough for tightening government
controls on the industry. She called for reforms including:
</P>
<P>
   _ Restricting the size of trucks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reducing fatigue by limiting drivers to eight-hour workdays.
</P>
<P>
   _ Subjecting trucks to more inspections.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mandating better training for all drivers and tougher
penalties on bad drivers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Requiring better reflectors on trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people are being killed by increasingly heavier trucks
driven by increasingly fatigued drivers,'' charged Michael Scippa,
executive director of CRASH, a non-profit advocacy group devoted to
``working to make the highways safer for all motorists, including
truck drivers.''
</P>
<P>
   McCormick, whose group represents the trucking industry, issued
a written statement disputing the CRASH conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is doing more than the trucking industry to make our
highways safer. We have to. The roads are where our nation's 3
million truck drivers live and work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The CRASH report said there were 444,000 highway accidents
involving big trucks in 1997, resulting in 5,335 deaths and 133,000
injuries. This is the highest number of deaths since 1989, when
5,360 people where killed in crashes involving trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
