<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTORS-UNION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS, OTHER PROFESSIONALS AT VETERANS HOSPITAL VOTE FOR UNION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Physicians at the Veterans Affairs Medical
Center in Kansas City on Wednesday became the first doctors in the
Kansas City area to unionize.
</P>
<P>
   They, along with nurses, physical therapists and other
professional care providers, voted for the American Federation of
Government Employees to represent them over the National Federation
of Federal Employees.
</P>
<P>
   But a protest filed by the national Federation of Federal
Employees kept the election results from being certified Wednesday
night by the National Labor Relations Board.
</P>
<P>
   Union supporters had complained that a sweeping reorganization
of the hospital over several years had left the 500-member
professional staff with little say in how it was run.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital's staff joins a growing number of physicians and
other health professionals participating in unions as managed care
takes away their independence and cost-cutting undermines their
financial security.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only about 2 percent to 3 percent of nation's 700,000
doctors belong to unions, according to the American Medical
Association. Sixteen percent of nurses are unionized.
</P>
<P>
   But the ranks of unionized medical professionals are growing
rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Two unions, one in Florida and another in California, together
represent about 10,000 physicians and dentists nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Organized doctors have been challenging health maintenance
organizations in New Jersey and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   And in the Department of Veterans Affairs system, the American
Federation of Government Employees has organized professional
bargaining units at about 10 hospitals in the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Professional workers in the past had some control over the
quality of their work,'' said Eugene Martin, the union's national
organizer. ``Now they see decisions being made that the people
actually doing the work don't think should be happening.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kansaas City, Veterans Hospital Director Hugh Doran said he
would work with the union, but he was puzzled as to why his
professional employees would want to unionize.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me to accept or understand...the need to have a
union,'' he said. ``You have the Number 1 hospital in the (regional
VA) network in terms of quality and patient satisfaction. Our
accomplishments here in the past couple of years have been
exceptional.''
</P>
<P>
   Although doctors at Veterans Hospital are the first to unionize
locally, they may not be alone forever.
</P>
<P>
   Some Kansas City area orthopedic surgeons in private practice
have met with the Federation of Physicians and Dentists, based in
Tallahassee, Fla., for information on organizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still some general discussion whether they want to
move in that direction,'' said union Executive Director Jack
Seddon.
</P>
<P>
   As managed care has grown in recent years, doctors have felt
like David against a medical Goliath.
</P>
<P>
   Because large health plans often cover many of their potential
patients, doctors feel compelled to sign contracts with the plans
to stay in business. Often those contracts call for large discounts
on fees and other concessions from doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors hope that unions will give them the clout to resist the
repeated cuts in reimbursement that some health plans are
demanding. And they foresee improvements in patient care if unions
can give them more authority over medical decisions.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the downside of unionizing for patients is more
hypothetical than real.
</P>
<P>
   Federal employees aren't allowed to strike, so VA hospitals
aren't threatened with closure.
</P>
<P>
   And doctors in private practice haven't proven they have the
clout to seriously take on managed-care plans. Antitrust laws
forbid them from collective bargaining with health plans. Unions
expect legislation to be introduced in Congress next year to
eliminate that prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   The managed-care industry doesn't appear threatened. As long as
physicians stay within existing antitrust laws, it's ready to work
with unions, the American Association of Health Plans says.
</P>
<P>
   Organizing at the Kansas City VA hospital started about 18
months ago when professional workers in Kansas City approached
union officials at the VA Medical Center in Leavenworth, Kan.,
which already has a professional union.
</P>
<P>
   The VA system has been undergoing several years of
reorganization that has consolidated the services of hospitals in
Kansas and Missouri. The result has been a more cost-efficient and
``patient-centered'' form of care modeled after health maintenance
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Although patients appear pleased with the results,
administrators say, many professionals at the hospital have worried
about their job security.
</P>
<P>
   Some medical professionals complained that they no longer had
the ear of the administration. That's because the number of medical
people in management was reduced as the hospital streamlined its
operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us feel we're being reorganized into oblivion,'' said
Al Schmidt, past national president of the National Federation of
Federal Employees. ``Years ago, professional staff was looked at as
part of management, but now management looks at professional staff
as a cost factor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
