<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPLETIVES GOT WORKER DELETED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Charles Corry admits he swears like the Marine he used
to be. He contends that criticizing him for swearing is ``morally
comparable to criticizing a Catholic for going to church.''
</P>
<P>
   But criticize him his co-workers did. One associate was
particularly upset when Corry repeatedly used ``God'' and ``Jesus
Christ'' as expletives.
</P>
<P>
   Corry's supervisors were notified. Meetings were held. Within
weeks, Corry was dismissed from his computer job.
</P>
<P>
   In Denver, a federal trial is under way this week to decide
whether Corry, who says he is a Buddhist, was a victim of religious
discrimination, as he contends.
</P>
<P>
   The Rocky Mountain News quoted Corry as saying that being fired
``touched one of my deepest fears...people being terminated on the
basis of their religious beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   Corry contends that a supervisor told him to study and follow
the Ten Commandments. Attorneys for the supervisor's company,
Analysts International Corp., say the supervisor merely explained
to Corry that his co-worker believed in the Ten Commandments'
prohibition against taking the Lord's name in vain.
</P>
<P>
   However Corry's lawsuit turns out, its existence shows what
happens when co-workers have different beliefs and different
standards about what constitutes acceptable workplace language.
</P>
<P>
   On any given day in the American workplace, words that some
workers consider profane will flow from co-workers' mouths.
Sometimes the words have religious ties. Sometimes they're sexual
in nature. Sometimes they're scatological or just plain gross.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their nature, words that are offensive to others' ears
put great strain on workplace relationships. I know co-workers who
visibly cringe, like Corry's co-worker, when fellow workers pepper
casual discussion with profanity. Others are less bothered.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that foul language slips past many co-workers with
nary a raised eyebrow. That doesn't mean it's right or acceptable.
It means cussing is a part of the American vernacular that is rife
in many workplaces.
</P>
<P>
   For those who are truly offended, there are two options:
Complain directly to the swearer or complain to management. The
latter course is what eventually brought Corry's case to court.
</P>
<P>
   Corry says he never intended to offend anyone. He says he
offered to move his desk away from the offended co-worker. But
after his firing, he wouldn't back down on the religious freedom
issue. No supervisor, no workplace, he contends, should impose one
religion's doctrine as a workplace guideline.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Corry's former employer say Corry's cries for
religious freedom are poppycock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asking someone to watch his language, to act professionally,
to avoid offending others, is not a form of religious
discrimination,'' the employer's attorney said at the trial's
outset.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see what the jury _ which includes a
Baptist minister _ decides. Meanwhile, it occurs to me that freedom
to (ital)hear(end ital) may be as important as any other freedom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-04-98 1734EST &QL; 
