<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPTIMISM FACES A LONG, COLD NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) The icy fist of winter has closed around the Arctic
regions of Russia, whose 8 million inhabitants now face an ordeal
of privation and suffering like none they have known since the last
great war.
</P>
<P>
   The general outlines of the dreadful situation are contained in
a sheaf of stories clipped from newspapers and magazines, or
received in the mail from friends.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, datelined more than a month ago, told of a
freighter racing the season along the Arctic coast, carrying half
the year's food supply for a large area of Siberia. The ship was
ordered to turn back because the freight bill couldn't be paid.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the order was rescinded, and the ship was allowed to
unload at the port of Tiksi. The cargo was to have remained under
seal there, but local officials ordered the goods loaded on barges
for transport up the Lena River to needy villages.
</P>
<P>
   I have been in that part of the world, not this deep into
autumn, but as the season turned. Tiksi is a raw outpost of
civilization, clinging to the upper rim of the Asian continent.
There's nothing to the north but the polar sea and the cap of
Arctic ice.
</P>
<P>
   And I know the Lena. An expedition of us Americans and four
Russian companions traveled the river's whole 2,700-mile length,
from the mountains above Lake Baikal to Tiksi, the year before the
Soviet empire fragmented and the economy collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   During its summer season free of ice, the Lena is a major artery
of transport and supply for a region of Siberia larger than all of
Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, after the worst Russian harvest in nearly a
half-century, the shipments of food and also of diesel oil were
meager _ by some accounts less than half the amounts needed for the
long winter.
</P>
<P>
   With the Russian icebreaker fleet immobilized by lack of fuel,
the shipping lanes along the Arctic coast are freezing shut. And,
in any case, the north-flowing rivers are icebound now.
</P>
<P>
   So the normal avenues of supply have closed. Food reserves are
exhausted. Power in some regions is rationed to only a few hours a
day. With rivers frozen, the only means of relief will be by air.
</P>
<P>
   Russian television has described the situation in the most
isolated and desperate areas as catastrophic, and there is talk of
the possible need to evacuate many thousands of the
worst-threatened villagers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will be freezing, and they are already. People will go
hungry _ it's a fact,'' one newspaper account quoted a government
official as saying. And that was weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Always, as the long night of the far northern winter commences,
my thoughts are with our Siberian friends, who must attempt somehow
to make lives for themselves and their families in such
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   They were young when we negotiated the Lena together. They were
strong then, and filled with optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times are hard, and will get harder,'' one of them said as the
old, despised system unraveled and the economy began falling apart.
``But it's the price we pay to be free.''
</P>
<P>
   Now they're well on in middle-age. Their strength must be less.
The price of freedom, in terms of hardship, has increased by
multiples.
</P>
<P>
   About the durability of their optimism I cannot know.
</P>
<P>
   For years, one of them corresponded with fair regularity,
telling of provision he was making for himself, his wife and two
sons, against that time when the situation could become even worse.
</P>
<P>
   But some months ago his letters stopped. I think it must mean
the worst is upon them now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
