<SLUG> BC-ADAM-CARTOONIST-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTOONIST BRIAN BASSET HAS EVOLVED WITH HIS COMIC STRIP
CHARACTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Earlier this year, cartoonist Brian Basset
changed the name of his daily comic strip from ``Adam'' to
``Adam &LR; home.''
</P>
<P>
   Gee. What trends could have been his motivation?
</P>
<P>
   Basset started drawing ``Adam'' in 1984. At the outset, there
was a ``Mr. Mom'' flavor to the strip, which chronicled the woes
and joys of a stay-at-home dad.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Basset _ who admits to being a lot like his comic
character, Adam Newman _ decided to emphasize the evolution of Adam
into an everyman for the explosion of home-office workers and
Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   Adam still deals with his children while his wife, Laura, is off
at work. Ditto the Basset family, where his wife, Linda, works
outside their Issaquah, Wash., home and Basset sometimes has more
face time with his two sons.
</P>
<P>
   That's ``sometimes'' because Basset has found what many
home-based workers know: Creativity often flows from interaction
with others. That, and the infusion of caffeine _ another recurring
theme in the strip.
</P>
<P>
   Basset's strip often shows Adam in a neighborhood coffeehouse
these days. There, surrounded by other laptop-toting professionals,
``home workers'' do their stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Basset made a publicity tour through Kansas City recently with a
publicist from Universal Press Syndicate, which distributes his
strip to more than 200 newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Very rarely, he said in an interview, he gets a letter or e-mail
blaming him for the breakdown of traditional family values.
Usually, though, fans write that Adam reflects the push-pull
between work and home lives they feel.
</P>
<P>
   Such themes are universal, Basset said. His ideas come from his
experiences and any he can borrow from others.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife thinks I ask how her day went out of compassion,''
Basset joked. ``But I'm just fishing for ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Because working at home can be isolating, he relishes his daily
escapes to a local coffeehouse. In the Pacific Northwest _ the
original Starbucks land _ Basset finds plenty of compatriots.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Starbucks executives have said they pointedly set out
to create that kind of ``third space'' _ a place that's not home
and not office but a place where people congregate _ in their
coffeeshops.
</P>
<P>
   Even with his coffeehouse forays, Basset said, he's still the
parent who's most available to run car pools and midday errands.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's also what makes working at home a lot harder than
what most people think,'' he added. ``You need tremendous
self-discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the very flexibility that says you don't have to be
dressed up for a 9 a.m. meeting also says you can work at 3 a.m. if
you need to. That's the problem when your work is always there and
you can't leave it at the office.''
</P>
<P>
   Basset says he fights two other home-worker challenges: getting
enough exercise and keeping track of what day it is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-04-98 1736EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981204.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3796 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-SEC-2TAKES-$ADV6-     12-04 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-SEC-2TAKES-$ADV6-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOC-SEC-2TAKES-$ADV6 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 6 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Donna Withers' father has a hard time making ends
meet on his $350 a month Social Security check.
</P>
<P>
   So the 26-year-old waitress was not thrilled to learn that when
she reaches retirement age Social Security is predicted to be in
poor financial health.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to think what they expect us to live on then,'' said
Withers, who is now on maternity leave and lives in Clute, Texas,
in Brazoria County south of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   But does she believe lawmakers in the nation's capital will fix
the problem soon?
</P>
<P>
   ``They are more worried about who is sleeping with whom,'' she
said, referring to the White House sex and lies scandal that has
preoccupied lawmakers and the media for the past year.
</P>
<P>
   This week, however, President Clinton will try to convince
Americans such as Withers that he and members of Congress are
willing to tackle the technically and politically daunting task of
reforming the system conceived during the Great Depression and
which now covers 43.6 million people, most of them elderly.
</P>
<P>
   The president will host a two-day summit to discuss various
options to shore up a program that is predicted to be in trouble in
the next century when the aging baby boom generation will have
drained the reserves built up over the years.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing is done, Social Security officials have said, the
system will be able to pay out only three-quarters of current
benefits beginning in 2032.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers from both parties along with representatives from
interest groups and academics will debate a menu of possible
solutions including the most radical one _ letting people take some
or all of their Social Security contributions and invest them in
the private markets. Groups at sites in all 50 states, including
Houston, will be able to watch the panel discussions through
satellite hookup.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who first raised the issue of preserving Social
Security in his State of the Union address in January, has yet to
endorse a specific plan. The president has said he is opposed to
raising taxes and is open to the suggestion of private investment.
He also has said that he hopes to devise a solution in the next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that the prospect that lawmakers will expend the
political capital and make the controversial changes necessary to
overhaul a popular program are remote.
</P>
<P>
   Already the president is facing pressure from unions and many in
the more liberal wing of his party who vehemently oppose
privatization of Social Security, claiming it will put low income
and vulnerable people at the mercy of an unpredictable stock
market.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans also are wary of getting too far out front on
an issue that has long been associated with Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   A leading House Republican, Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman
of the House Ways and Means Committee, said the president must go
first in offering a detailed plan if he wants anything to get done
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a quarterback and not a punter,'' said Archer, whose
committee must consider any Social Security legislation. Like the
president, Archer has not proposed a specific plan but rather
backed broad principles that include no tax increases, fairness for
future and current retirees and new options for younger workers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the skeptics, there are those who believe there is a
greater chance now than in the past that the program can be
overhauled.
</P>
<P>
   They say both the scandal ridden president and Republican
controlled Congress in pursuit of him may be looking for an
accomplishment that will improve their image with voters fed up
with Washington politics.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a budget surplus and a sound economy means there is more
money to fix the system.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show an increasing number of voters, particularly younger
people, willing to accept changes in the system that has long been
considered sacred.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do have some stars that are aligned in the right
direction,'' said Evelyn Morton, the legislative director of the
AARP, the nation's largest senior citizens advocacy organization.
</P>
<P>
   While AARP is one of the most influential lobbying groups in
Washington, it has not yet endorsed or opposed any of the options
to shore up the program.
</P>
<P>
   Those alternatives include the methods that have historically
been employed to keep the system solvent, such as raising the
payroll taxes, increasing the age of eligibility or reducing
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Currently workers and employers each contribute 6.2 percent of
an employee's wages up to $68,400 of income. The retirement age for
full benefits is 65 but is slated to gradually rise to 67.
</P>
<P>
   Other traditional options include reducing cost of living
increases and enlarging the pool of contributors to the system by
forcing state and local government employees, who now have their
own retirement programs, to join Social Security. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But some lawmakers are tiring of what they believe are the
short-term fixes that do not address the long-term demographics _
far fewer workers supporting a bulging generation of retirees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who promises you can fix it with a nip and tuck here is
misleading the public,'' said Will Marshall, the president of the
Progressive Policy Institute, a centrist Democratic group that has
joined with others in embracing more dramatic solutions that
involve to varying degrees using the private market to increase the
rate of return on taxpayer investment.
</P>
<P>
   One option considered by those who do not want to change the
basic structure of Social Security but would like to see its
reserves stretched further, is to have the federal government
invest at least part of that money in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security has amassed $757 billion in reserves which are
invested in low-interest-bearing government securities.
</P>
<P>
   However, critics say that such an option would give government
officials far too much power to influence corporate decisions since
Social Security would own huge blocks of stock.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, they fear that government officials could use the
stock ownership to push social positions. They cite public employee
pension funds that have tried to punish certain companies for their
products, such as tobacco, or their policies, such as benefits for
partners of gay employees.
</P>
<P>
   Archer dismissed such a proposal is a ``non-starter'' because it
means ``the federal government would own control of most of the
major corporations in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   By far the most intriguing and controversial proposals would
allow individuals to divert some of the taxes they now pay into
Social Security and invest them in stocks and bonds, much as many
workers do now with 401K plans, where employees and employers
contribute to market-invested tax-free retirement accounts.
</P>
<P>
   This approach has been embraced by a broad spectrum of
lawmakers, ranging from conservatives such as Sen. Phil Gramm,
R-Texas, to moderate Democrats including Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan of New York.
</P>
<P>
   They argue that such an approach would give younger people, in
particular, the opportunity to get far better return on their
retirement contributions while making it unnecessary to raise taxes
or cut benefits in the future. They add that while the stock market
has its ups and downs, over time it still earns a higher rate of
return than Social Security, where many workers will barely get
back what they put in.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the plans would maintain a certain degree of government
involvement, allowing current retirees to remain in Social Security
and guaranteeing everyone else minimum retirement benefits even if
their investments don't do well.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm said that the conversion to private accounts ``won't make
people instant millionaires'' but it will eventually ``make
everybody better off than they are now.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics argue that while the concept of allowing people to
invest their Social Security money in the stock market may have
superficial appeal, it is a risky proposition that will not only be
a nightmare to administer but will create vast income inequities.
</P>
<P>
   They suggest that people who have the misfortune of retiring
when the stock market is in a slump will suffer with much smaller
retirement income than those who hit old age during a bull market.
</P>
<P>
   They note that such an investment system will not help the
disabled and children and widows of deceased workers who also
depend on Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Social Security provides vital support for vulnerable
groups,'' said Robert Reischauer, a senior fellow at the Brookings
Institution, who opposes private investment accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The battle lines over privatization became increasingly clear
last week when the National Federation of Independent Businesses
came out in favor of personal accounts one day and a coalition of
labor, women and minority groups met the next day to rail against
such proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights activist Jesse Jackson warned that politicians,
Democrat or Republican, who jumped on the privatization bandwagon
would suffer at the polls and join departing House Speaker Newt
Gingrich ``on the midnight train to Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   Convincing the public to accept private accounts in a year when
many have nervously watched the stock market behave like a yo-yo
could be a tough task.
</P>
<P>
   Even Withers, the waitress from Clute who wants lawmakers to
deal with Social Security, expressed doubts that most people have
the sophistication to successfully play the stock market with their
retirement savings.
</P>
<P>
   She noted, ``In my high school class I was the only who passed
the section on the stock market.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
