<SLUG> BC-411-CHARGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACIFIC BELL SEEKS HIGHER CHARGES FOR DIRECTORY ASSISTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Several consumer and interest groups have
sternly criticized Pacific Bell's proposal to double what it
charges for 411 directory assistance calls.
</P>
<P>
   In a public hearing on the matter Thursday, opponents of the
rate increase said Pacific Bell shouldn't be allowed to raise 411
charges from 25 cents to 50 cents per call.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the groups told the state Public Utilities
Commission that Pacific Bell shouldn't be allowed to lock in a
ceiling price of $1.10 per 411 call. That would be the maximum
amount the telephone company could charge in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a rate increase of this magnitude,'' said
Sylvia Siegel, director of Consumers Cable Cop, a watchdog group in
Mill Valley. ``It's the height of chutzpah.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Berzok, who represented the San Francisco chapter of the
American Association of Retired Persons, also criticized the
proposed rate increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``This amounts to nothing more than unjustifiable price
gouging,'' he said. ``There are no options for consumers to get
(411) service elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Cain, a Pacific Bell operator services director, said
competition did exist because companies like AT&AMP;T and MCI also
offered 411 service and charged much higher prices to customers.
</P>
<P>
   But Kelly Boyd, an attorney in the PUC's Office of Ratepayer
Advocates, said the vast majority of residential customers got 411
service from Pacific Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Cain said Pacific Bell has been subsidizing the cost to provide
411 service for years. However, Cain wouldn't disclose the actual
cost of the service, saying the figures are proprietary.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Stein, an attorney with The Utility Reform Network, a San
Francisco-based watchdog group, said he had seen Pacific Bell's 411
service cost figures and said ``no price increase is justified.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein said Pacific Bell had originally wanted to raise rates to
33 cents per call. As a result, he said, ``50 cents (per call) is
not reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite opposition to the proposed rate increase, some who
attended the hearing spoke in favor of the increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pac Bell is losing money on every call,'' said Margie Marks,
president of Local 9410 of the Communications Workers of America,
which has 200 Pacific Bell directory assistance operators as
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pac Bell has made a commitment to having live operators to
handle calls,'' Marks said. ``They're making a commitment to
keeping jobs here.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell's proposal _ which was filed with the PUC in May _
states that the number of free 411 calls for residential customers
would drop from five to three calls per month. This means that
Pacific Bell, which is owned by SBC Communications Inc. of San
Antonio, would charge customers 50 cents per call after the first
three.
</P>
<P>
   A PUC vote on the proposal is expected next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
