<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3805 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WASTE-TESTS-$ADV06     12-04 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASTE-TESTS-$ADV06 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FAULTY TESTS PROMPT NATIONWIDE FEDERAL REVIEW OF POTENTIALLY
DANGEROUS WASTE SITES
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for release Sunday, Dec. 6
 &HT;    By JANET JACOBS and ELLIOT JASPIN
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON The federal government is re-examining the danger
posed by hundreds of hazardous waste sites nationwide after the
discovery that two Texas labs allegedly provided thousands of
incorrect test results over a six year period.
</P>
<P>
   The labs tested for cancer-causing chemicals in the soil, water,
air and tissue. Such tests are routinely used by government and
industry to determine if toxic wastes are, for example, leaking
into drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   Federal environmental officials said they have opened a criminal
investigation into operations at the two labs, which were owned by
Intertek Testing Services, a British company that specializes in
various kinds of testing. Intertek discovered the faulty tests a
year ago. Both labs are no longer in operation.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials would not name specific sites involved in the
investigation. But Mary Adler, head of criminal enforcement for the
Environmental Protection Agency, said that the government has not
yet found any instances where the public was placed in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kelly, an attorney for Intertek, also said that his
company's review has not turned up a single case where the faulty
test data resulted in any danger to public health. However, Kelly
acknowledged that the company has reviewed data from only about 25
percent of the affected sites.
</P>
<P>
   Despite company and government assurances, the faulty test data
already has become an issue in at least one lawsuit involving the
defunct Longhorn Army Ammunition Plant in Karnack, Texas. Because
it is considered among the most dangerous toxic waste sites in the
country, EPA says part of the cleanup costs will come from its
so-called Superfund.
</P>
<P>
   A group of people near the abandoned plant has sued the federal
government and numerous contractors in federal court in Marshall,
Texas, asserting that leaking toxic chemicals from the Longhorn
facility made them ill and killed 27 people over the last ten
years. A lawyer for the group alleged that a number of these people
died of cancer or lupus, a disease that attacks the kidneys and
liver.
</P>
<P>
   The suit says residents were repeatedly told by state and
federal officials that contamination from the plant could not have
caused these injuries. However, lawyers filing the suit argue that
because of the unreliable testing, the government doesn't know how
bad the contamination is.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly denied in an interview Thursday that the Karnack case
represented an instance where Intertek's test data missed a major
environmental threat. He said that his company's tests there, which
were performed for the Army Corps of
</P>
<P>
   Engineers, proved to be accurate and showed ``extremely high
levels of pollution.''
</P>
<P>
   This was disputed by an Army spokesperson who said tests done by
Intertek and other companies have repeatedly shown only limited
pockets of high pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Intertek and government officials face a substantial challenge
as they try to reconstruct how decisions were made, which tests
were relied upon and what risks were run in hundreds of complex
pollution cases dating back to the beginning of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of tests is in the thousands,'' said Dave Barry,
spokesman for the Environmental Protection Agency in Dallas. ``It
was pointed out that the (questionable test data) goes back to
1991.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said his company traced its current troubles back to one
employee who allegedly ``cut corners'' to speed up the time it took
to complete various tests.
</P>
<P>
   At the time the employee began working at the lab in the early
90's, the environmental testing service consisted of four
laboratories run by a company called Inchcape. When Intertek
purchased the Inchcape labs in December 1996, Kelly said his
company had no idea tests were not being properly performed. In
fact, Kelly said the labs were certified by several professional
organizations, as well as by some states, to do environmental
testing and were routinely audited.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said that the faulty testing procedures were discovered in
December 1997 by new managers from Intertek. Kelly said that
Intertek immediately notified its clients and the EPA. While the
lab never did work for EPA itself, whoever was responsible for the
cleanup would submit the lab's test results to the EPA to be used
in deciding how to deal with toxic wastes.
</P>
<P>
   While Kelly said the ``shortcuts'' caused only minor variations
in the test results, Barry said the faulty data may have caused the
government to do too little or too much pollution cleanup at some
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials declined to talk about exactly how serious the
situation might be.
</P>
<P>
   ``A criminal investigation is ongoing,'' Adler said. ``The
agency would not at this point want to comment on the extent of the
data integrity problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What the agency is doing right now is conducting a systematic
review of its case files and action files to try to identify where
we might have relied on its (Intertek's) data and then make an
assessment of how that data
</P>
<P>
   was used.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jacobs is a reporter for the Longview News-Journal in Texas.
Jaspin is a correspondent in the Cox Newspapers Washington Bureau).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
