<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981204.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3827 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAZZ-KRALL06-2TAKES-C     12-04 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAZZ-KRALL06-2TAKES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL DECEMBER 6
 &HT;    Jazzed up and crossing over
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE _ Seamless decorum will not be part of the program
on this evening at the Jacksonville Jazz Festival. Behind the
stage, the smell of grilled meat drifts over the dull roar of a
hundred conversations in the roped-off VIP area. Children shriek.
Partyers jostle. Beers slosh.
</P>
<P>
   Diana Krall winces. Or is she trying to summon her telepathic
powers? Leading her trio from behind a piano, she can't hear a
thing above the din. But as she gazes out at the thousands of fans
scattered across the downtown Metropolitan Park, the vocalist
suddenly smiles, nods to guitarist Russell Malone and bassist Ben
Wolfe, and they slip into a ballad that's intimate and candlelit.
</P>
<P>
   You're thinking how warm and cozy it all is. But Krall isn't
thinking that at all. ``How do you connect with somebody you can't
see because you have a light in your eyes, like you're Mildred
Pierce, like you're being interrogated?'' she asks later.
</P>
<P>
   Though she identifies with Joan Crawford's 1940s film heroine,
the 34-year-old pianist and vocalist stands accused only of growing
popularity, of crossover success that's uncommon for a jazz artist.
</P>
<P>
   Krall's most recent CD, ``Love Scenes'' (Impulse), has become
that rare mainstream jazz title to sell nearly 500,000 copies _ a
feat that has kept the singer at the top of the traditional jazz
charts for more than a year. (She's been there before: ``All for
You,'' Krall's 1996 tribute to the Nat King Cole Trio, sold more
than 200,000 copies.) She's scored a few other coups as well:
touring with Sarah McLachlan's Lilith Fair; gigging twice on
``Melrose Place,'' where she played as herself in the show's
fictitious bar; and backing up Celine Dion on the ``Titanic''
diva's Christmas album.
</P>
<P>
   The singer, who performs Friday and Saturday at Variety
Playhouse, is a long, long way from the Oak Room in New York's
fabled Algonquin Hotel, one of those venerable establishments,
redolent of a certain fussy prestige, where Krall made her name.
It's a name associated with the vintage aura of American popular
song as practiced by so many other names, such as Frank Sinatra and
Ella Fitzgerald and Billie Holiday and Nat ``King'' Cole. Names
with voices that came to define a shared national experience: a
timeless time, a placeless place, at once as fixed and as fluid as
a dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has this honey-laden voice with a touch of whiskey,'' says
Deb Moore, a longtime fan who also hosts the ``Midday Renaissance''
program on WCLK-FM (91.9), an Atlanta jazz station. ``She has a
wonderful way of setting a mood.'' Not one of those Killer B type
of jazz singers _ the brassy, brazen, boisterous, blazing,
bodacious kinds _ Krall prefers a light touch. When she wants to
insinuate ``I've Got You Under My Skin'' with an ounce of extra
sass, she lets the melody percolate as a wispy bossa nova. When she
wants to cry the blues, well, she cedes the urge to former Atlantan
Malone, who unleashes some startling gutbucket runs with a
knowingly arched eyebrow.
</P>
<P>
   It's an approach that has even notched a hit single of sorts.
Krall's version of veteran hepcat Dave Frishberg's ``Peel Me a
Grape'' (which includes such inspired couplets as ``Never outthink
me/Just mink me'') has found airplay on contemporary jazz stations
where smoothies such as Kenny G are the norm. Within the rigorously
fixed constellation of jazz stardom, Krall has the buzz of a
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever anyone who would be considered a jazz musician hits
in this way, it's a little bit of a strange alchemy that we can't
figure out,'' says Larry Blumenfeld, editor in chief of Jazziz, a
national music monthly that splashed Krall across its cover last
year. ``In terms of her appearance and the way she uses jazz
tradition, she's more accessible to a broader audience than a lot
of other artists are, without necessarily dumbing things down. One
thing that really works in her favor is she's able to straddle that
fence between what a real jazz fan wants and what a popular
audience needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Relaxing after the recent Jacksonville show in her hotel's
lobby, Krall sips a glass of cabernet. She's tired. She's hungry.
She just finished a two-week swing through Europe and craves
nothing more than an honest, all-American meal: steak, on the rare
side of rare. Though she's still wearing the black Donna Karan gown
and high heels she had on onstage, Krall comes off less like a
newly anointed diva than an exceedingly well-traveled girl next
door. Her idea of a folk hero is Garrison Keillor, whose invitation
to play ``Prairie Home Companion'' ranks as a career high point.
And though she indulges her love of designer clothes, the proudest
item in the singer's closet may be an outdoorsy jacket from Roots,
the back-to-nature Canadian clothing brand.
</P>
<P>
   When someone wanders over to a nearby piano and begins to play,
Krall is quick to note that, until four years ago, she was still
commuting to Boston from New York every week to play in a hotel
lounge. Sometimes for one person.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me, what makes you different? I have no clue,''
says Krall, who's encountered the media enough in the past year to
ably conduct a bit of a self-interview. ``Sometimes they're pushing
my buttons: Well, is it because you're a half-decent looking young
woman or is it marketing? I always find that kind of insulting,
because I put so much passion into it. I'm sure that's part of it,
but you can't see me on the radio. I tend to get a lot of flak from
that, and it irritates me.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have said to me,'' she continues, inflating her tone
with mock pomp, `` `You have to go out and be grand, and you have
to be a vision, and you have to be this.' Forget it! I couldn't do
that if I tried. I'm going to go out and trip on my dress! I'd
rather be able to just be myself. I talked to Rosemary Clooney
about that. She said it's always better to tell the audience
exactly how you're feeling. The audience is like my family in the
living room. You don't have to distance yourself or put up a
mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE: a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   That's apt advice. The singer, who was born to an extremely
musical family in the seaside town of Nanaimo, British Columbia,
was virtually weaned on her accountant father's collection of old
78s. When Krall reels off a dozen names, like a New Deal hit
parade, you realize she could moonlight as a soundtrack consultant
for Woody Allen _ or win really big at musical ``Jeopardy!''
</P>
<P>
   `` `Hard-hearted Hannah' and `Ain't Misbehavin' ' were things we
sang at Christmastime,'' says Krall, who frequently flies home even
for brief visits, though she keeps an apartment in Manhattan's
Chelsea neighborhood. ``I thought everybody else's households were
like that. I used to play (piano) at the rest homes, and I thought
that all the old people, because they were old, would love Fats
Waller.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, she discovered, they wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   But it's one of the rare occasions when Krall misjudged her
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interesting part of all this is you can really tell where
the talent lies,'' says Tommy LiPuma, Krall's producer and chairman
of her parent label, GRP. The concept ``is right on the borderline
of walking into a piano bar and hearing someone sing standards. But
the difference is, it's on the other side of that fence. It's got
style and the manner _ her interpretation _ that takes it 180
degrees from being (lounge music). But you've got to be careful
because you're always right on the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   LiPuma signed Krall after she had recorded her first album,
1993's ``Steppin' Out,'' for the Canadian Justin Time label,
encouraged by a video he saw of the singer alone at the piano. The
fact that she has been gigging in clubs since age 15, and had been
schooled by jazz legends Jimmy Rowles (Billie Holiday's pianist)
and bassist Ray Brown, also meant that Krall had absorbed a lot of
tradition firsthand. But it was a few months into the contract,
when Krall recorded ``And I Love (Him)'' for a Beatles tribute,
that ``suddenly I realized the full potential of what she had,'' he
says. ``She worked two or three hours trying to get the right feel,
and she dropped this performance that was amazing. It gave her a
lot of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   As Krall's career continues its upswing _ a new album, with
arrangements by Johnny Mandel, is in the works _ that confidence
will count for a lot. Happily ensconced at a riverfront steakhouse,
the kind that serves brick-size baked potatoes ushered to the table
by courtly, bow-tied old gentlemen, Krall can bubble away with
amusing family anecdotes. Her grandparents' diner, lovingly kept
intact by new owners. Her sister Michelle, the drug enforcement
cop. Her buddy the Canadian astronaut, who carried a copy of her
album onto the Space Shuttle. How her love for Willie Nelson's
music was a major, unacknowledged influence on her last album.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not out to please the jazz police,'' she'll say, all too
aware that success can have its repercussions, ``nor am I out just
to win an audience. I'm just out to make the kind of record that I
would love to put on and listen to.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone, who's been collaborating with Krall since they met four
years ago at the now-defunct New York after-hours hang Bradley's,
puts it even more succinctly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I like about her singing,'' he says, ``is she just
sings the song.''
</P>
<P>
   DIANA KRALL FILE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Born: Nov. 16, 1964.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hometown: Nanaimo, British Columbia. ``I'm as much at my mum
and dad's house as I am in New York. Even if it's for one day, I'll
go.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Home away from home: An apartment in Chelsea. ``It's a great
place for a single girl,'' says Krall, who lives about three blocks
from the Village Vanguard, New York's famous jazz haunt.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mentors: Pianist Jimmy Rowles (who worked with Billie
Holiday); bassist Ray Brown (Ella Fitzgerald's first husband).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Career opportunities: ``I wanted to be an astronaut when I was
a kid. I have a friend who's an astronaut now _ I don't think I've
ever heard anyone utter those words before. His name is Bob Thirsk.
He's a fan. He took my CD in the space shuttle. He sent me a photo,
all the patches to the suits.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Playing the Lilith Fair: ``It was wonderful to hear teenage
girls (yell for) `Peel Me a Grape.' And `Go, Russell!' I was
sitting at the press conference with these women (Sarah McLachlan
and others), going, `Oh my God, these people are just as serious
about what they do as we are.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What her guitarist says about her: ``She's a very shy
person,'' says Russell Malone. ``Sometimes that's misconstrued as
being aloof or haughty, but she's not. She's a very giving
person.''
</P>
<P>
   ALBUMS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Stepping Out'' (GRP/Justin Time, 1993): The singer's debut
on a Canadian label has been reissued by GRP. It hints at things to
come with an early version of ``Frim Fram Sauce.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Only Trust Your Heart'' (GRP, 1994): Major-label debut
features an all-star band, with legendary bassist Ray Brown and
saxophonist Stanley Turrentine.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``All for You'' (Impulse!, 1995): This tribute to the classic
Nat King Cole Trio established Krall as a mainstay on the jazz
charts. ``Krall's singing adds a sense of seductive mischief to
what could easily have been a cabaret cakewalk.'' _
</P>
<P>
   ``MusicHound Jazz: The
</P>
<P>
   Essential Album Guide.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Love Scenes'' (Impulse!, 1997): Another theme album rounds
up a can't-miss batch of standards (by Irving Berlin, Harry Warren,
Percy Mayfield and George and Ira Gershwin), done up in the same
drummerless trio style as ``All for You.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Have Yourself a Merry Little Christmas'' (Impulse!, 1998):
Billed as a ``holiday gift pack,'' this three-song CD sampler is
packaged with a jewel box that doubles as a pop-up 1999 calendar,
complete with glamour shots of Krall.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you like her, you'll probably like: Carmen McRae, Shirley
Horn, Nat ``King'' Cole, Holly Cole and Blossom Dearie.
</P>
<P>
   -Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal- Constitution.
</P>
