<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV06-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB WILL WEIGH IN FOR 2000 ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 06, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So how much did the Internet affect last month's elections?
Some, but nowhere near as much as the PC webheads say it will alter
the voting in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The invisible but not-yet-invincible PC network that eliminates
geography in politics, as in everything else, helped re-elect a US
senator by a handful of votes, enabled a wrestler sans college
degree to become governor by running under the old media's radar
screen, and sparked a grass-roots rebellion that dampened the
impeachment campaign when Congress saw the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Internet does not yet pack the political wallop of
television. And as older heads recall, radio did not kill off
newspapers, TV didn't kill radio, and the Internet, while an
impressivly dynamic new collection of mediums, will probably not
obliterate the old mediums, but will instead layer over them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, everyone in the room at Harvard Thursday, where the
Kennedy School of Government convened its third Politics on the Net
conference, seemed convinced that the Internet will change
campaigning, eventually move votes by the ton, and therefore alter
the way politics controls our governance.
</P>
<P>
   Nevada Senator Harry Reid's eyelash-wide victory (by 400-odd
votes) came after about 10,000 hits on his Web site. Jesse
Ventura's followers tracked his campaign for governor in Minnesota
closely on the Net. One of the fastest ramp-ups in Net history (if
history can refer to a phenomenon that is barely five years old) is
credited to an outfit titled MoveOn.org, which ignited a virtual
prairie fire of middle-of-the-road discontent over the Republicans'
impeachment drive.
</P>
<P>
   On the simple premise of urging Congress to censure President
Clinton and then get back to the nation's real business,
MoveOn.org's version of an electronic chain-letter went from a
handful of e-mailers the first day to 3,000 the next to 10,000-plus
the day after, mushrooming rapidly to a 300,000 strong virtual
movement organized in 200-plus congressional districts inside of a
week, something never done before.
</P>
<P>
   There's new lingo to go along with this: ``ad-hocracies,'' for
the spontaneous coalitions erected over the Web; ``cheap
eyeballs,'' for the masses it's possible to spin with ``banner
ads,'' the strips of overlines that net-users click on. Television
is still the medium that is ``mass-iest,'' i.e., corrals the most
humans paying attention at any given time. The Web people still
have to figure out how to make a splash, without being disdained
for spin, or as spam.
</P>
<P>
   If you invest campaign cash unwisely in the Net world, you may
become part of the bleeding edge, instead of the leading edge.
Democratic consultant Andy Brack of South Carolina described the
difficulties in organizing ``interactive mouse potatoes,'' and
displayed a business-card sized, $2 CD-ROM that can put a
campaign's whole story before a contributor or volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   There were hundreds of Internet political sites this year, a few
of them state-of-the-art creations with all the bells and whistles,
most just electronic bulletin boards featuring mundane candidate or
cause ``brochure-ware.'' Among the most cited fancy sites were
those of Jeb Bush, elected governor in Florida, and Roy Barnes,
elected governor in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Harlan Barnes, Web master for his father's winning campaign,
used the Net to help a staff of just six full-timers win the
primary, and there were only 20 full-timers to win a $10.5 million
general election campaign. He lined up volunteers, delivered press
releases, high-resolution campaign photos, and video and audio
soundbites to small papers and rural radio stations across Georgia
_ all via the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Wellesley Prof. Marion Just said her work for the Markle
Foundation's voter education experiment, called Web White and Blue,
turned up voters who liked access to specific, targetted and local
political information. Still, some users complained that
``basically a computer is more work than reading a newspaper . . .
you gotta click . . . television is more relaxing . . . using a
computer is just less convenient'' than absorbing political dope
from newspaper or tube.
</P>
<P>
   But as a way of quickly and cheaply recruiting crowds,
volunteers, and attention from smaller newspapers, distant
broadcast outlets and sometimes even your competitors spying on
your schedule or speech texts, the web is the way.
</P>
<P>
   The model is still that of the carnival barker: you have to get
the customers inside your tent before you can sell them the show.
Said one private-sector marketing consultant: ``The political
people are about a year-and-a-half behind the private sector.
Campaign consultants still talk about building their web sites. he
private sector has learned from e-commerce that you have to get
people to your site.''
</P>
<P>
   To Republican consultant Robert Arena Jr., ``the critical mass
is not there yet.'' Despite promise for organizing volunteers and
harvesting credit-card contributions over secure computer-moden
hookups, the Internet is still no match for television _ network,
local, cable _ when it comes to moving votes en masse. If you build
it, you have to advertise it, said one panelist.
</P>
<P>
   But ``the new political machine of the future will be the
personal computer,'' claimed Harvard Prof. David King. Kennedy
School Dean Joe Nye opened the show asking: ``Are we with the
Internet about where we were with television in 1952?'' and ``Will
it transform the political process?'' The emerging consensus seems
to be yes, and probably yes, respectively. But to close the
conference Nye quoted an aphorism: ``When information is free, the
scarce commodity becomes attention.''
</P>
<P>
   The e-commerce crowd will show the way, one listener said.
``'The political sites are like storefronts, little campaign
headquarters, hoping people will show up. They are not yet
marketing or advertising on line, the way cutting-edge private
sector firms are doing. But when they do that, they will move large
numbers of voters.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
