<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV06-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GIFT OF HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 06, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   However analytic they may be, most business people enjoy knowing
about the history of the markets in which they make their livings.
It is no accident; they know, as the poet wrote, that ``Yesterday
this day's madness did prepare. Hope, passion, anger and despair.''
So business folk dote on stories, especially stories that point the
way to possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   This year has seen the publication of a number of very good
business history books. Some of them especially suitable for
holiday giving because of the compass of their aspirations. They
are software for the mind that, once installed, should last a
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wealth and Poverty of Nations: Why Some Are So Rich and
Some So Poor'' by David Landes (W.W. Norton, $30). This is the the
distillation of the famous Harvard course that Landes has been
teaching for 20 years, nicknamed by students ``the West and the
rest.'' The professor relates the economic history of the world
since 1000 A.D. in 29 chapters that are shrewd, acerbic, and
unfailingly entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``A History of Molecular Biology'' by Michel Morange (Harvard
University Press, $39.95). The foundations for today's medical and
biotechnology boom were laid in the 1950s, when Harvard, the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, the University of Chicago,
and a handful of California universities hired the young scientists
who had solved the mystery of the gene. This elegant telling of the
story, translated from the French, ranges from the early influence
of the Rockefeller Foundation to Kary Mullis's 1983 discovery of
the reaction that permits DNA to be amplified practically without
limit. Long on science, but short on color.
</P>
<P>
   ``A History of Modern Computing'' by Paul E. Ceruzzi (MIT Press,
$35). Ceruzzi is curator of the Department of Space History at the
Smithsonian Institution in Washington, and he has a good eye for
history's shapes. This book is intended more for nostalgia buffs
than for Net-heads: thereare plenty of pictures of perforated tape
and old machines. But, especially combined with, say, the next
book, it gives a vivid picture of how unforseeable are
technologies' twists and turns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rescuing Prometheus'' by Thomas P. Hughes (Pantheon Books,
$28.50). The subtitle tells it all: this is ``the story of the
mammoth projects _ SAGE, ICBM, ARPANET/Internet and Boston's
Central Artery Project _ that created new styles of management, new
forms of organization and a new vision of technology.'' Hughes is
convincing in his argument that the Cold War had a profound effect
through technology on social organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paths of Innovation: Technological Change in 20th Century
America'' by David C. Mowery and Nathan Rosenberg (Cambridge
University Press, $27.95). Rosenberg and Mowery are among the
nation's premier historians of technical change. They relate the
sagas of four technologies _ the internal combustion engine, the
chemical industry, electric power, and the electronics revolution
that followed the invention of the transistor in 1947 _ and look
for patterns that repeat among the details that do not.
</P>
<P>
   ``A History of Economic Theory: Classic Contributions
1720-1980'' by Jurg Niehans (Johns Hopkins University Press,
$25.95). It is eight years old now, but this history by a retired
theorist of thought is still the best guide there is to how
economics came to be the way it is today. Fifty profiles of the
greats, from Smith and Ricard to Samuelson and Friedman, compolete
with textbook-grade exposition of their ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titan: The Life of John D. Rockefeller Sr.'' (Random House,
$30). Author Ron Chernow has a knack for finding new relevance in
old lives. This utterly absorbing biography of the man who created
Stantard Oil paints the 19th century brilliantly and at the same
time illuminates the 21st _ in which Rockefeller's oil companies
are being re-united, and parallels of Rockfeller to Microsoft's
Bill Gates are inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Billion Dollar Monopoly Swindle: The True Story Behind
Monopoly'' ($17) by Ralph Anspach. Anspach is the entrepreneur who
marketed a send-up of Parker Brothers Monopoly in the early 1970s
and then spent the next 25 years fighting the company in the
courts. Here he relates the story of how he discovered that Parker
Brothers stole the game itself, fair and square, from groups of
Quakers around the country who had devised it to illustrate the
principles of single-taxer Henry George. It can be ordered on the
Internet from www.antimonopoly.com
</P>
<P>
   ``Smart Choices: A Practical Guide to Making Better Decisions''
by John. S. Hammond, Ralph L. Keeney, and Howard Raiffa (Harvard
Business School Press, $22.50). There are all kinds of practical
roadmaps here for decision-making: how to think of problem-choice,
objectives, alternatives, consequences, tradeoffs, uncertainty,
risk tolerance, linked decisions, and pysychological traps. This is
deeply grounded advice from one of the world's great decision
theorists, Raiffa.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Competition'' by Michael Porter ($35.95, Harvard Business
School Press). What is so interesting about this brainy expositor
of the economics of growth? Instead of sprining for the handsome
new three-volume set ``strategy'' series, you could settle for this
well chosen but overpriced selection of his shorter pieces.
</P>
<P>
   ``EVA: The Real Key to Creating Wealth'' by Al Ehrbar (John
Wiley &AMP; Sons, $29.95). ``Economic value added'' is the latest
approach to evaluating corporporate performance. Ehrbar, a veteran
financial journalist, explains the framework lucidly, illustrates
it with plenty of examples drawn from the experience of companies
like Coca-Cola, Eli Lilly, and Siemens, and links it all to the
well-known yardsticks published by Stern Stewart &AMP; Co., where he
now works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Information Rules: A Strategic Guide to the Network Economy by
Carl Shapiro and Hal Varian (Harvard Business School Press, $tktk
). Two reigning experts on network economics explain the ins and
outs of the Internet and how it differs from the great networks _
railroads, telephones, airlines -- of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Last year I mentioned an unusual sort of a wish book. ``The
Catalogue for Philanthropy'' showcases a blue-ribbon list of
little-known but well run foundations, organized by purpose: the
amelioration of poverty, education, the environment, the arts, and
so. The organization behind it makes giving appreciated securities
easy. To receive a copy of the Massachusetts version, call
800-298-7141 or e-mail www.catphilanthropy.org.
</P>
<P>
   I have saved the best for last _ or worst, if you have no
discipline with your credit card. The Internet market for used
books has had a banner year. Three huge networks of used bookstores
can be found on line: Advanced Book Exchange (abebooks.com);
Bibliofind.com; and Interlock.com. These search services show Web
commerce in its very stage, before the relentless efficiency of the
medium eliminates all the bargains: prices, in other words, are all
over the map. For those of who love books, this is the equivalent
of a rainy afternoon in Bath, England, every day of the week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
