<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3871 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHUTTLE-LAUNCH-HNS &LR;      12-04 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-LAUNCH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENDEAVOUR SOARS INTO ORBIT TO DELIVER SPACE STATION COMPONENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ The shuttle Endeavour soared into orbit
on Friday, its six U.S. and Russian crew members eager to assemble
the first components of the new U.S.-led international space
station.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle and its cargo, a 33-foot-long module called Unity,
was on a course to reach the station's orbital construction site
late Sunday. The nearly 13-ton, U.S.-built module is fitted with a
half-dozen docking ports intended to link future station
components, including living quarters, research laboratories, power
generating equipment and an airlock.
</P>
<P>
   With a series of carefully timed maneuvers, the Endeavour crew
plans to rendezvous with the Russian-built Zarya propulsion and
power module. Launched from Central Asia on Nov. 20, the
41-foot-long, 21.5-ton Zarya serves as the new station's orbital
cornerstone.
</P>
<P>
   Using the shuttle's long robot arm and at least three
spacewalks, the Endeavour crew plans to link Zarya with Unity,
forming a permanent structural bridge between the station's future
U.S. and Russian segments.
</P>
<P>
   The new global outpost represents the sixth and most complex of
the human spacecraft developed by U.S. engineers and the first to
include substantial foreign contributions. Mercury, Gemini and
Apollo enabled Americans to reach the moon; Skylab, to experiment
with space station activities; and the shuttle, to pioneer the
operation of a reusable spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   Substantial contributions from the Europeans, Japanese and
Canadians as well as the Russians will be incorporated into the
station over its six-year construction.
</P>
<P>
   Endeavour thundered from its coastal launching pad at NASA's
Kennedy Space Center at 3:33 a.m.,EST, skirting a passing threat
from rain showers. Trailing a spectacular exhaust that lit up the
darkened skies, Endeavour climbed steeply and steered a northerly
course before settling into a near 200-mile high orbit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great show,'' mission control told the astronauts. ``Welcome
to orbit.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton issued a statement after launch, calling it
``a bold and exciting step toward a permanent U.S. presence in
space.''
</P>
<P>
   The astronauts were especially eager to liftoff after a
momentary drop in the pressure of the shuttle's hydraulic system
stalled the first attempt on Thursday with only seconds left in the
countdown. Engineers traced the difficulty to the system's sluggish
response to a cockpit activation switch, and Friday's countdown was
flawless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's do this tonight,'' urged Endeavour commander Bob Cabana,
who displayed a ``thumbs up'' as he crawled into the cockpit.
``We're ready to start on a new era in international cooperation in
space and get this space station built.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those present for the launching was U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stupendous work,'' Albright told space agency workers,
offering her endorsement for NASA's efforts to fold the
contributions of 16 nations into the project. ``It was really
inspirational.''
</P>
<P>
   The mission was originally scheduled to blast off a year ago.
Chronic problems with the Russian economy, however, have stalled
the production of a still-to- be-launched module that has an impact
on the launch of other components. Now slated for launching no
sooner than July, which is 15 months late, the Russian service
module will furnish living quarters for the first resident
astronauts and cosmonauts.
</P>
<P>
   Cabana's crew includes pilot Frederick ``Rick'' Sturckow, flight
engineer Nancy Currie, spacewalkers Jerry Ross and Jim Newman and
Russian cosmonaut Sergei Krikalev.
</P>
<P>
   Zarya soared 250 miles directly over Cape Canaveral, Fla., as
Endeavour lifted off.
</P>
<P>
   Aboard Endeavour, the astronauts spent their first hours aloft
carefully checking out the shuttle's long robot arm and the space
suits that will be crucial to the success of their flight.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, astronaut Nancy Currie was to take control of the arm
from her post in the crew compartment to carefully lift the 25,600
pound Unity module from the shuttle's cargo bay. Her task is to
re-orient the module into a vertical posture so that it can be
lowered atop the docking apparatus in the shuttle's cargo bay.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure is the first in a sequence of delicate steps
needed to join Zarya to Unity. Shuttle astronauts successfully
executed a similar operation in November 1995 as they fitted an
American docking module to Russia's Mir space station.
</P>
<P>
   But experts believe Endeavour's astronauts face a more difficult
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the difficulties are in the tight tolerances we are
talking about,'' Currie explained before the mission. She trained
two years for the tasks.
</P>
<P>
   To join Zarya to Unity, Currie has trained to rely on closed
circuit television views to first grab the large Russian module
with the robot arm and then to align it atop the smaller U.S.
component.
</P>
<P>
   Her alignments will be crucial because brief pulses of the
shuttle's steering thrusters will be required to drive the
components into the docking mechanisms that will latch them in
place.
</P>
<P>
   As Endeavour meets up with Zarya, Currie's view of the big
module from the window of her control station will be blocked by
the four-story-tall Unity module.
</P>
<P>
   Video cameras stationed in the shuttle cargo bay and on the
robot arm will replace her eyes, furnishing the televised views for
her to grab Zarya and position it above Unity.
</P>
<P>
   Ross and Newman are to begin the first of their spacewalks on
Monday. The excursions will enable the two men to hook up power and
computer data cables between the two modules, establish a
communications link with NASA's Mission Control Center in Houston
and stow tools and other equipment for future visitors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
