<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GAMBLING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA HIGH COURT BLOCKS INITIATIVE THAT LEGALIZED VIDEO GAMING
IN INDIAN CASINOS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KIM COBB 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   California's Supreme Court this week blocked enforcement of the
November ballot initiative that legalized video gaming in Indian
casinos, pending two lawsuits that claim Proposition Five violates
the state constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits were not unexpected by the Indian tribes who backed
the proposition. But an attorney representing the tribes says the
federal government continues to threaten to seize gaming equipment
from reservation casinos while the legality of Proposition 5 swings
in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition Five was the most expensive ballot initiative in
U.S. history, pitting well-financed Indian tribes against wealthy
Nevada casinos in a nearly $100 million battle. But there's a huge
amount of money still at stake _ money the tribes stand to earn
from the already lucrative casino business, and business their
competitors in neighboring Nevada stand to lose.
</P>
<P>
   The state government of California has been battling with the
tribes for years over what kind of gaming is legal in the casinos,
all of which sit on reservation lands. Federal regulations restrict
Indian gaming to those types already legal in the state and
requires the tribes to sign compacts with the state.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the casinos started as bingo parlors, and evolved
into video slot machine palaces over the past decade without
compacts. California Gov. Pete Wilson recently negotiated a
restrictive compact with a handful of tribes, but the majority
refused to sign and backed Proposition 5 instead.
</P>
<P>
   California voters passed the ballot measure by a 63 percent
margin last month. Subsequent lawsuits filed by a homeowners group
and a state union claim the ballot measure violates a
constitutional ban on casinos like those operating in Nevada and
New Jersey, a ban approved by voters in 1984 when they authorized
the state lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson applauded the Supreme Court's decision to stay
Proposition 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a stay, this state would have begun its transformation
into a Nevada-by-the-sea, populated with dozens and dozens of new
Las Vegas style casinos in violation of our constitution's ban,''
Wilson said. ``Few people recognized that without the court's
action, the tribes' sovereign immunity could have prevented the
state from stopping tribes' operation of these illegal casinos once
they took effect regardless of how unconstitutional the courts
later found the initiative to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Levine, a Los Angeles attorney representing the tribes,
said he believes the ballot measure will pass constitutional
muster. The constitution prohibits the legislature from authorizing
Nevada or New Jersey style gaming, he said, but does not prohibit
the voters from authorizing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it is read more broadly, we don't think that what's
authorized by Proposition 5 authorizes (that) type of gaming,''
Levine said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we weren't surprised that Nevada continued in its
relentless attempt to strip these programs from the tribes,''
Levine said. ``Nevada seems to be consistent in its concern for
retaining its business interests, even if it means putting lots of
Californians out of work and injuring tribal programs.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-04-98 1811EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
