<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1999 1/2 is a good year for Saab
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Not content with turning its 5-year-old 900 models
into the frisky 9-3 coupe and sedan for 1999, Saab _ whose North
American headquarters is in Norcross, Ga. _ now moves on in the
automotive race toward the millennium with mid-model-year '99 1/2
versions.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just a marketing or public relations ploy, either. Saab
has made significant changes _ mostly underneath and inside _ to
the front-drive cars. The test 9-3 SE sedan, with a base price of
$31,700 pushed to a total of $32,775 by $500 for heated seats and
$575 for delivery, performed more strongly and carried noticeably
more comfort/convenience features than the original '99 model
tested earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   But first, in accordance with Saab tradition, there's the matter
of quirkiness. You think after all these years the Swedish/Finnish
carbuilder is going to eliminate ``quirky'' from its list of
standard features? So the ignition switch remains on the center
console between the front seats, turbo lag is still an irritant,
there's an airplane wing in the slotted front grille and it's
virtually impossible to use the center-mounted parking brake
without first raising the new folding center armrest.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with its avowed dedication to improving the safety of
its cars, Saab has given the reworked '99 9-3 more overhead padding
for additional head protection. Other safety features shared with
the coupe (starting at $25,650) and convertible (starting at
$38,150) include dual front air bags and an active head-restraint
system. The latter uses an impact-sensitive headrest that moves up
to catch the head and, hopefully, reduce whiplash injuries in
rear-end accidents. The system doesn't make the multi-adjustable
front seats sit better, but it does seem an idea whose time has
come. Regardless, the seats lack thigh support.
</P>
<P>
   The ``B'' or center-of-the-car pillars are given a pendulum
design intended to disperse energy in increasing amounts from top
to bottom in case of a side-impact. The theory is this will lessen
impact energy potentially directed at the head and channel it to
the lower part of the torso. (It's a grim subject, but crashes are
just that.)
</P>
<P>
   Performance, which isn't exactly shabby with the regular
2.0-liter turbocharged four-cylinder (185 horsepower), is boosted
by raising the hp rating to 200 for the high-output turbocharged
engine, available only in the line-topping SE cars.
</P>
<P>
   The 9-3 SE, it quickly becomes apparent, now is certifiably
zippy _ once turbo lag is overcome _ and more challenging to the
pep of competing Acura, Audi and Volvo cars.
</P>
<P>
   Interior updates include the addition of a four-spoke steering
wheel with redundant stereo controls that are actually easier to
operate than those on the dash-mounted unit. Revised heater/air
conditioning controls also are easier to adjust.
</P>
<P>
   There's a new and convenient pop-out drink holder on the dash,
and while it won't accept large containers, the unlidded storage
cubby on the center console will take jumbo cans, bottles and
glasses. It's also deep enough to keep them stable.
</P>
<P>
   The '99 1/2 naturally retains improvements given the regular
'99, including a tighter steering system and barely noticeable
changes to the front and rear lights and a grille borrowed from the
larger, costlier 9-5. The upshot is owners of the '99s introduced
in May may feel slighted by Saab's midyear updates. There's no
question they make the 9-3 a better and more driveable car.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
