<SLUG> BC-HOUDINI-MAGIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TNT FILM TRIES TO UNLOCK MAGICIAN'S LORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ More than 70 years after his death, Harry Houdini
remains our most famous magician, his name still a synonym for the
astonishing escape.
</P>
<P>
   His ability to somehow worm out of straitjackets, prison cells
and sealed water tanks created an enduring myth little dimmed since
his 1926 death, not from a failed stunt but a ruptured appendix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houdini,'' the made-for-TV movie about the magician that
premieres at 8 tonight on TNT, explains some of Houdini's secrets,
but it also takes some unexpected, even unlikely leaps that
nonetheless provide a substantial emotional payoff.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, writer-director Pen Densham's script holds that
Houdini's most impressive escape might just have occurred after he
died.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is constructed around flashbacks by his wife
(``Chicago Hope's'' Stacey Edwards) and other close associates at a
seance in a Hollywood theater, conducted during a live radio
broadcast 10 years after his death.
</P>
<P>
   Those flashbacks fill in the magician's life, starting as a poor
immigrant youth whose father died while he was still a teen,
forcing the lad to work as a sweatshop cloth cutter to support his
emotionally distant mother and his younger brother (Mark Ruffalo).
</P>
<P>
   His brother's discovery of a book by magician Jean-Eugene
Robert-Houdin started Ehrich Weiss (``That Thing You Do!'s''
Johnathon Schaech) on the road into illusion, and gave him the
inspiration for his stage name.
</P>
<P>
   It shows how he met his wife at a vaudeville audition and how
they eventually persuaded Martin Beck (George Segal) to become
their manager after Houdini concocted a death-defying escape stunt
that riveted a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Densham (``Moll Flanders'') sets for himself a difficult
narrative task, trying to show the basis for Houdini's tortured,
sometimes explosive personality and quirks (he used a former
electric chair as his den chair). Surprise, surprise, it was
because his mother never told him she loved him.
</P>
<P>
   This attempt to show Houdini's inner life is the most difficult
and least satisfying part of an otherwise engaging film. Movies as
a medium struggle to portray the mind's inner workings, and Densham
is only moderately successful in this regard. But it helps explain
other parts of Houdini's life _ and death.
</P>
<P>
   His absence at his mother's death led him to try to contact her
through spiritualists. But he soon became disillusioned, believing
that they were frauds, and dedicated much of his later life to
unmasking them, sparking hundreds of libel suits.
</P>
<P>
   At his own deathbed, however, Houdini promises his wife that if
he can, he will escape one more time and contact her.
</P>
<P>
   Densham said the series of seances that Mrs. Houdini then held
during the next decade to contact her dead husband really occurred,
as did a climactic one on Halloween night on Hollywood Boulevard
(where a seance is annually held each year since in commemoration).
And for a time, Mrs. Houdini did say she had contacted her husband
in a seance before disavowing it.
</P>
<P>
   Rhea Perlman plays the medium who attempts to contact Houdini
two decades after his death, and there is a scene where she appears
to contact the spirit of someone who claims he would find an escape
from the great beyond if one possibly existed.
</P>
<P>
   But whether the other events of that night really happened as
the movie portrays them, Densham won't say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you can look at it three ways: Either he dreamed it, or
she dreamed it, or it really happened,'' Densham said. ``I have my
own theory, but I'd prefer not to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Watch the movie yourself. The acting is uniformly good, and the
story is well done, if not a perfect evocation of an interesting
life. But with a dramatic payoff in the end, Densham has pulled his
own death-defying escape.
</P>
<P>
   endit &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
