<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3915 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YANKEE-GUNBOAT-HNS &LR;      12-04 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YANKEE-GUNBOAT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN'S DISCOVERY OF YANKEE GUNBOAT CONFIRMED; EXCAVATION DENIED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN MAKEIG 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SABINE PASS, La. _ Pentecostal preacher Bruce Lockett gets
almost starry-eyed as the dozen white plastic tubes come into clear
view not far from the old Sabine Pass lighthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been searching for this for two years,'' he explained,
standing on the bow of the tugboat The Legacy. ``And now we're
close to finding two others, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The white tubes sticking out of the muddy water are markers set
up by Lockett's Texas Archaeological Studies Association that has
prowled the Louisiana side of the Sabine River in search of the
sunken remains of the USS Dan, an old Yankee gunboat.
</P>
<P>
   What has Lockett, 49, excited nowadays is a letter he received
from a Louisiana archaeologist, Dr. Chip McGimsey, verifying that
beneath the dozen plastic markers does, indeed, lies the USS Dan.
</P>
<P>
   Most people would have a hard time getting thrilled about a
bunch of lumber and two rusted cannons that have been buried under
a mound of oyster shells a few feet underwater for 135 years, but
Lockett is no mere passerby.
</P>
<P>
   He admits to being obsessive about the USS Dan, saying there is
something ``addictive'' about digging around in Civil War history
and actually finding something worthwhile. He started off years ago
reading historical accounts about the Alamo and since has evolved
into a fan of shipwrecks.
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens of them hereabouts, but Lockett is focused
wholly on the Union and Confederate wrecks around Sabine Point, in
particular the USS Dan, the paddlewheeler that terrorized the
rebels along the Sabine River until it finally was destroyed Jan.
8, 1863.
</P>
<P>
   Lockett and his 65-member band of amateur archaeologists have
been wading in the mud on the Louisiana side of the river and
getting a big thrill every time they uncover an old bottle or a
rusty scrap of metal.
</P>
<P>
   What others might consider worthless junk are, to Lockett and
his group, priceless artifacts containing clues to the past. They
treasure the chunks of coal that came off the USS Dan, long pieces
of metal plate, wooden remnants of the paddlewheeler and nails with
square tops.
</P>
<P>
   If they get formal permission from the state of Louisiana to
begin further excavations, they no doubt will be ecstatic if they
find the USS Dan's Parrott cannons, its bell and whistle. They
could even find the bones of Yankee troops killed when the gunboat
sank.
</P>
<P>
   Under Texas rules on historic shipwrecks, people are not
supposed to disturb even the silt around the wreckage. Louisiana's
rules, according to Lockett, allow amateur archaeologists to dive
and poke around until they find actual wreckage, and then the state
must be notified before anything is removed.
</P>
<P>
   McGimsey and Texas Historical Commission officials say they have
appreciated having Lockett and his workers find the USS Dan, but
beyond that telling him to let well enough alone has been
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason to excavate it,'' McGimsey said.
</P>
<P>
   That hardly deters Lockett, who has grand plans about restoring
the vessel and sailing it around. That would require countless
hours of work and permits from the Navy Department and Louisiana.
It might cost $1 million or more.
</P>
<P>
   The destruction of the USS Dan was among the Confederacy's last
hurrahs.
</P>
<P>
   The vessel originally was a cotton-hauling paddleboat, 199 feet
long and weighing 112 tons, that cruised the Sabine River. Once the
Civil War started, the equipment-hungry Confederacy confiscated the
Dan along with other ships and the Union began blockading Southern
ports to keep out supplies.
</P>
<P>
   In 1862, after chasing the Confederate paddlewheeler around for
weeks, Union troops found it hidden in a bayou and took it over
without firing a shot. One of their first actions was installing
twin Parrott guns on the bow. The guns had rifled bores and fired
rounds that had twice the range of the cannonball-firing Southern
guns and exploded on impact.
</P>
<P>
   The USS Dan could blithely sail up the Sabine River and shoot up
Sabine City and Southern positions without worrying about getting
hit by the weaker Confederate weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the USS Dan had barely arrived here before it caught a
Southern blockade runner, the Mary Ann, and burned it up. Then it
caught two more Confederate ships, the Conchita and the Eliza.
</P>
<P>
   The USS Dan spent the next three months annoying and harassing
Confederate troops and civilians living in Sabine City.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 30, 1862, exasperated rebel cavalrymen began firing
rifles at the gunboat. The next day, troopers from the USS Dan
retaliated by burning down a sawmill and homes in the area. A few
days later, they burned down Confederate barracks and stables.
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughly unhappy over all this, Confederate First Sgt. H.N.
Connor got permission to go directly after the pesky USS Dan that
was causing so much trouble.
</P>
<P>
   On their third try, Connor and his soldiers sneaked through a
fog bank and found the USS Dan anchored not far from the lighthouse
across from Sabine Point.
</P>
<P>
   Pulling alongside, they used torches to set the gunboat afire.
The Confederates pulled back to safe distance and watched for an
hour as the USS Dan burned down to its waterline. The blast that
accompanied the explosion of the USS Dan's magazine must have been
gratifying.
</P>
<P>
   A drawing from the October 22, 1863 Harper's Weekly suggests
that the better-known Battle of Sabine Point _ one of the final
bright moments of the war for Dixie _ was fought on the river close
to where the USS Dan had sunk nine months before.
</P>
<P>
   In the Battle of Sabine Pass, a Houston saloon keeper,
Confederate First Lt. Dick Dowling and 47 other Irish immigrants,
using cannons, routed a force of 26 Union vessels carrying more
than 4,000 troops intent on capturing Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Dowling became a serious Confederate hero by sinking two ships,
killing 30 Yankee troops and capturing 350 more. What they
accomplished was to keep Texas from being invaded by Union troops.
</P>
<P>
   All this is background for Lockett, who combs such accounts
looking for wreck locations. From the Battle of Sabine Pass
stories, he now is hot to locate two Union blockade vessels, the
Morning Light and the Velocity.
</P>
<P>
   It was while looking for the Morning Light's location, in fact,
that Lockett found the clues that led to the USS Dan. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
