<SLUG> BC-BOX-KING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON KING BACK IN THE FRAY IN ATLANTIC CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY _ Don King returns to Atlantic City Saturday night
with a band and a bang.
</P>
<P>
   It has been eight years since King last promoted a boxing match
in New Jersey. He had been banned from doing business with the
state's casinos in 1990 following a federal indictment on insurance
fraud charges. Never convicted, King nevertheless had his
promoter's license revoked in New Jersey while he battled the
government through a hung jury and finally an acquittal in a
retrial this year. Now he is back with a card that could produce
fireworks at the new Atlantic City Convention Center, a building
that was not even standing when King last ran a show on the
Boardwalk.
</P>
<P>
   With King will come two-time junior bantamweight champion Johnny
Tapia, newly crowned World Boxing Association welterweight champion
James Page, two fierce opponents, and a marching band empowered to
launch what King called ``a homecoming parade.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to be a total American again,'' King said after
having his license reinstated. ``This is like a homecoming. It'll
be like a pep rally for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``When your presumption of innocence is denied, you can throw
bricks, but that changes nothing. I'm sensitive now to the fact an
allegation can end your existence in New Jersey. That's why I got
to go back to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe some good can come of this. Maybe an unreasonable
situation will be corrected for those who come after me. Maybe this
rule will be revisited, revised, reassessed, and removed from their
books because of what happened to me. The only way you can cure an
evil is to expose it to the light of day. That's why I'm back. I'm
back to let New Jersey see the kind of fights I can put on here.''
</P>
<P>
   The kind he's putting on Saturday night could be hot flashes of
violence if they go according to form. In the first, Page defends
his 147-pound WBA title for the first time since he won the then
vacant crown by stopping No. 1 contender Andrei Pestriaev with one
thunderous hook to the head two months ago in Paris. No one
expected Page to do what he did there when he lifted his record to
22-3 and kept his five-fight winning streak alive. But Saturday
night he will be in with an even tougher opponent, who was supposed
to fight Pestriaev in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Luis Lopz (42-3-2, 33 knockouts) is one of the toughest
welterweights in the world, a guy who won the World Boxing
Organization title in 1996 by destroying Eamonn Loughran in one
round and twice had then-WBA champion Ike Quartey on the deck
before fighting him to a technical draw.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez was supposed to have fought Pestriaev, but King's
behind-the-scenes maneuverings with WBA officials blocked that
until Lopez's lawyers went to court and forced the WBA to at least
make Lopez Page's mandatory challenger.
</P>
<P>
   Now Lopez is back for another shot at a title he thinks he
already won once. Because of that, he fervently believes he will do
unto Page what Page did unto Pestriaev. An old ally in his corner,
trainer Lou Duva, refused to disagree with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Page is a pretty good puncher,'' Duva said this week. ``But my
guy is a good puncher with guts. Lopez can be a hell of a fighter
on the nights he wants to be one. (Oscar) De La Hoya has already
said he won't even get in the ring with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``People understand how strong this kid is. He cold-cocked Yory
Boy (Campas, the current International Boxing Federation 154-pound
champion). He can do the same to Page.''
</P>
<P>
   WBA bantamweight champion Nana Yaw Konadu intends to do the same
to Tapia in the main event. Tapia is one of the most gifted
fighters in the ring today, but at 115 pounds, he has gone all but
unnoticed except on the nights he's had run-ins with the law. Early
in his career, there were as many of them as there were fights in
well-lit arenas. But Tapia has righted himself in recent years
despite a mercurial personality that has caused a half-dozen top
trainers to come and go.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night Freddie Roach of Dedham, Mass., will be in his
corner when Tapia moves up 3 pounds from junior bantamweight after
having defended the WBO's version of the 115-pound title 13 times
since winning it from Henry Martinez in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Tapia also won the IBF junior bantamweight title with a
surprisingly efficient 12-round decision over heavily favored Danny
Romero a year and a half ago. Since then, Tapia has twice fought at
the bantamweight limit before King finally maneuvered him into a
position to challenge the hard-punching Konadu.
</P>
<P>
   Konadu (39-3-1, 32 KOs) is as heavy-handed as Page and Lopez,
having first won the title in 1996 by stopping Veerapol Sahaprom,
then losing it in his first defense, only to win it back again a
year ago in the same knockout fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Konadu is a product of Ghana who not surprisingly believes Tapia
is too small to adequately test him before the hammer falls. That
might, but Tapia is undefeated in 46 fights for a reason. He is
resourceful, resilient, and reactionary, and all three
characteristics might be of use to him against the rocket launching
of Konadu. They certainly didn't hurt his promoter these past eight
years.
</P>
</TEXT>
