<DOCNO> NYT19981204.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3919 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHURCH-BURNINGS05-COX     12-04 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCH-BURNINGS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Better investigations help snuff out high number of church
arsons
 &HT;    By Ron Martz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ More thorough investigations and tougher prosecutions
have significantly cut the number of church arsons over the last
two years, a top official with the U.S. Department of the Treasury
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   James Johnson, Treasury's undersecretary for enforcement, said
during a visit to Atlanta that since the National Church Arson Task
Force was formed in mid-1996 in response to concern over the number
of churches being burned, church fires have decreased by about 30
percent each year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, fires were reported at 297 churches nationwide, 119
with predominantly black congregations and 178 others.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the total dropped to 208 fires, 53 at black churches
and 155 at other churches.
</P>
<P>
   Through Sept. 8, 1998, 114 church fires were reported, only 28
at black churches. Those numbers represent fires that were
investigated as arson, bombings or attempted bombings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal was to prevent additional fires and to bring those
responsible to justice and that is being done,'' said Johnson, who
is also co-chairman of the task force and oversees the
investigative efforts of the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms on church arsons.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the task force has opened 690 investigations of
church fires, about 230 of which have been closed with the arrests
of 320 people.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest rate in cases investigated by the task force, 34
percent, is more than double the 16 percent national average in
other arson cases.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who presented these figures during a speech to the
National Church Burning Status meeting in Atlanta this week,
reiterated previous findings that there is no evidence of a
nationwide conspiracy in the church arsons.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we found is that only a handful of fires actually
involved conspiracies of more than two or three people, the largest
one being about five,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Motives for the arsons were widely varied in the roughly 30
percent of the cases in which a motive could be determined,
according to Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   They ranged from racism to insurance fraud to bias against
religion to mental instability of the arsonists.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
