<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3925 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSEXP-EAGLE-BOS &LR;      12-04 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSEXP-EAGLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERIACN EAGLE BUYING BUSINESS EXPRESS AIRLINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Business Express Airlines, New England's largest regional air
carrier, said Friday it is being bought by American Eagle, the
commuter-airline affiliate of American Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The sale, by a Philadelphia investment firm that rescued
Business Express from bankruptcy in 1997, could radically alter
commercial aviation in the region, people familiar with the
industry said, as American Eagle makes expected changes.
</P>
<P>
   The price paid to Dieling, Schreiber &AMP; Park was not disclosed.
The investment group took over ownership in May 1997, settling a
Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceeding begun when Business Express
defaulted on aircraft lease payments in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   With 330 flights daily out of Boston and LaGuardia Airport in
New York, to points as diverse as Philadelphia; Washington, DC;
Presque Isle, Maine; and Halifax, Nova Scotia, Business Express
draws most of its passengers from arrangements it has with
American, Delta Air Lines, and Northwest Airlines, to provide
connecting service to smaller cities.
</P>
<P>
   But it was unclear whether Delta and Northwest will continue
that relationship once the American Airlines unit that operates
American Eagle, AMR Eagle Holding Corp., takes over Business
Express. ``We would like to maintain those,'' an AMR Eagle
spokesman said, for the ``significant revenues'' they provide.
</P>
<P>
   In Manchester, N.H., where Business Express displays Delta's
emblem at its check-in counter, airport director Alfred Testa Jr.
said the deal ``has implications on implications.'' Even with no
other changes, he said, it marks the first time American has ever
had a formal presence north of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   In Bangor, Maine, where Delta earlier announced it is ending its
daily jet service to Atlanta and replacing it with commuter flights
to a Cincinnati hub, officials cheered. ``This plugs Bangor right
into a much larger network of schedules,'' Bangor International
Airport spokesman Jeff Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Dover, N.H., Business Express has about 1,200 full-time
employees, and, with 1.3 million passengers, was ranked as the 19th
largest US regional carrier last year. A spokeswoman said revenues
in 1997 were about $150 million but declined to disclose profits.
She said ridership this year is expected to exceed 1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   American Eagle, based in Fort Worth, Texas, is the largest US
regional airline, reporting 12.1 million passengers in 1997 and
11.9 million for the first 11 months of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's deal includes Business Express's schedules, route
system, operating certificate, and a fleet of 43 leased Saab 340
aircraft, each with 34 seats.
</P>
<P>
   It also includes 20 firm orders and 40 options Business Express
holds for Brazilian-made, 37-seat Embraer jet planes, scheduled for
delivery starting next August.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
