<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-MIAMI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMS TAKE THE FIELD WITH FIESTA BOWL IN MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Usually, game days in college football are clear-cut.
Winners, losers. Move on.
</P>
<P>
   Not this season. The controversial Bowl Championship Series
rankings have sent this message: While it's important whether you
win or lose, how you play the game also matters.
</P>
<P>
   All of that will come to some sort of conclusion this weekend,
beginning with Saturday three ``championship'' matchups involving
the three unbeaten teams who are vying for a spot in the Fiesta
Bowl Jan. 4 that will ostensibly determine the national champion.
</P>
<P>
   Here No. 3 UCLA (10-0) will perform its final audition for one
of the two leading roles in the Fiesta Bowl when it takes on Miami
in the Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, No. 1 Tennessee (11-0) hopes to continue its
championship run with a victory over No. 23 Mississippi State (8-3)
in the Southeastern Conference title game.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Louis, No. 2 Kansas State (11-0) will try to persuade
both voters and computers that a win over Texas A&AMP;M (10-2) is good
enough to merit a trip to Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   The way it stands now, Kansas State, mainly because of a weak
nonconference schedule, is the odd team out, sitting at No. 3 in
the BCS rankings, which will come out for the final time Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But the numbers crunchers who have studied the probabilities
should all three teams win are hedging on what the final BCS
rankings will reveal, saying it is too close to call and that any
of the three teams could finish No. 1 or No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't understand the system itself and the nuances,'' said
Kansas State coach Bill Snyder. ``But we do understand we're not
going to have any impact on how it all plays out.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. Kansas State, just like Tennessee and UCLA, will have a
big impact on how it plays out. If the Wildcats simply lose, they
will reduce the magic number of unbeaten BCS contenders to two.
</P>
<P>
   The odds say that is unlikely, since the Wildcats, Volunteers,
and Bruins are all double-digit favorites. If all win, the Fiesta
opponents would be determined based not only on how the coaches and
writers vote but also on computer printouts from Jeff Sagarin, the
New York Times, and the Seattle Times.
</P>
<P>
   So complicated is the procedure that even the results of the
Western Athletic Conference championship game between Brigham Young
and Air Force and the Mid-American Conference championship game
between Toledo and Marshall could have an impact, since opponents'
records are factored into the calculations.
</P>
<P>
   For UCLA, Miami is simply the latest speed bump in a season
filled with them. But the Bruins, to their credit, have not even
been slowed down.
</P>
<P>
   With a 20-game winning streak, the Bruins are the hottest of the
three contenders in terms of sustained success. Not that they
haven't had scares _ a wild 41-38 win over Oregon and
come-from-behind victories over sub-.500 teams Stanford and Oregon
State have somewhat tarnished the Bruins' reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been through some battles,'' said UCLA quarterback Cade
McNown, ``and come out on top.''
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, Miami should not prove to be the stumbling block
that sends the Bruins to the Rose Bowl instead of the Fiesta.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes are coming off a humiliating 66-13 loss to
Syracuse _ Miami's worst in more than 50 years _ and have beaten
only one team, West Virginia, with a winning record.
</P>
<P>
   But being in the Orange Bowl and playing the role of spoilers
appeals to the Canes' sense of pride. ``You've got to get excited
about the chance to spoil their chances for a national
championship,'' said linebacker Dan Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, UCLA has drawn a bad hand here. The Miami game was
originally scheduled to be played in September, but Hurricane
Georges ripped through the region that weekend, causing a
cancellation that turned into a postponement when UCLA officials
agreed to reschedule the game for December.
</P>
<P>
   Despite what happened last week in Syracuse, the Miami team UCLA
will see is much better than the one it would have faced in
September.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA coach Bob Toledo knows what's at stake as well as anyone.
And although the consolation prize for losing or getting bumped out
of the Fiesta Bowl by the computers is the Rose Bowl, Toledo
desperately wants the Bruins to at least have a chance to play for
the national title.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, the task is clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to understand it's a one-game tournament now for
us,'' Toledo said. ``If we lose, we're out.''
</P>
<P>
   The same messages no doubt are being delivered by Tennessee
coach Phil Fulmer and by Kansas State's Snyder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-04-98 1836EST &QL; 
