u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      12-04 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGINEST, COLLINS READY TO BOLSTER PATRIOTS' DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ When you have the 20th-ranked defense and
the 28th-ranked pass defense in the NFL, you have to do something.
That something is under wraps, but it appears the Patriots will
take a different approach to their defensive game plan against the
Pittsburgh Steelers Sunday at Three Rivers Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, who lost two heartbreaking games to the Steelers
last season, including a 7-6 decision in the AFC playoffs at Three
Rivers, are expected to get end Willie McGinest and linebacker Todd
Collins back, which could greatly bolster the defense.
</P>
<P>
   McGinest practiced Thursday and Friday and seemed ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good today,'' said McGinest, who has battled a chronic
groin injury. ``It's still a game-time decision, but the last two
days have been fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pete Carroll said after practice, ``We got through it
pretty well. Willie looked good.''
</P>
<P>
   The personnel additions should make things flow. McGinest _ if
he plays and doesn't have a relapse, as he did in Buffalo _ should
improve the pass rush, which has produced two sacks in five games
and has put extra pressure on the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started being known for the blitz and stuff,'' said
defensive tackle Chad Eaton. ``We have to go back to what we do
best, whatever that is.''
</P>
<P>
   Eaton, like Carroll and defensive coordinator Steve Sidwell, is
mum on just what ``it'' will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our emphasis has turned,'' said Carroll. ``We're trying to
improve and make something happen.''
</P>
<P>
   What?
</P>
<P>
   ``The safety blitz stuff is just not catching people off
guard,'' he said. ``What do you do now? That might be what those
changes are about.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll did say every team from Pittsburgh to Pottsville now
uses the strong safety blitz. But while it's preferable to have
Lawyer Milloy blitzing the quarterback than a lot of other people
in the Patriots' defense, the pressure on Kordell Stewart could
come from elsewhere, like cornerbacks Tebucky Jones and Steve
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we have some things to clear up,'' said Milloy,
``but we have a really good defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Willie Clay has been emphasizing this theme for a while: ``The
problem is they're spreading us out. We haven't been adjusting to
anybody. There are gonna be mismatches and they've found the
mismatches in our defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' defense was fourth in the league after their 4-1
start, but it's been a free fall since then. In their last seven
games, the Patriots have allowed an average of 363 yards. Beyond
that, they have had only three fumble recoveries. Their
sacks-per-pass ratio is 27th in the league, they are 23d in
third-down efficiency, and they've had only two sacks in the last
five games.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, the Patriots have gone six games without having all
their front seven available.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wheeler remains sidelined with a knee sprain. Henry Thomas
has played almost a month with a sore left ankle. Chris Slade is
said to be returning to full health after a month of ankle
problems. McGinest has been in for four plays in six games. Brandon
Mitchell, an up-and-coming pass rusher, was sidelined for the
season just when it appeared he was coming on. Collins (groin) has
missed three games. Eaton missed one game, was hurt for two more,
but is now at full strength.
</P>
<P>
   It appears the Patriots may be the healthiest they've been in
some time, and that, along with the changes, could restore their
effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would think it would help, but it all depends at what
level do these guys return at?'' said Sidwell. ``With Willie, it
turned out he was reinjured early, so what good does that do us?
It's just something you have to wait and see what it feels like.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody cares whether you have guys injured and playing out of
position. What they care about is, are you getting the job done?
We're a better team when we have all of our guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidwell said stopping the Steelers starts with the battles up
front and ultimately containing Jerome Bettis.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to get them into long third-down situations,'' said
Sidwell. ``That's the primary emphasis for us. In Pittsburgh, it
all starts with the run, so you have to stop that first.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidwell, who did a tremendous job changing the Patriots' defense
last December to make it much more unpredictable, shrugged off talk
of major alterations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been basically doing the same things for most of the
season, so you'll only see us make a couple of subtle things that
the average fan won't even notice,'' he said. ``You never make
major changes at this time of the year. To do that would be
confusing and difficult for the players.''
</P>
<P>
   But tendencies can be changed.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots may try blitzing from a different side with a
different player at a different time. They may try more
containment, spending more time in the basic defense. Or they may
try an all-out zone blitz in an effort to beat the Steelers at
their own game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only do things for so long before people pick things
up,'' said Collins, who will back up Tedy Bruschi. ``You try to
time it up when they least expect it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is, nobody's saying. What the Patriots are
acknowledging is that they're giving up too many yards, too many
big plays. And those things will get you killed in Pittsburgh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
