</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-ISRAEL-TECH-2TAKES-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MILITARY-TECHNOLOGICAL COMPLEX IS THRIVING IN ISRAEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 6) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JESSICA STEINBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Young soldiers with automatic rifles slung across
their backs are a familiar sight here, defending the country's
borders, boundaries and bus stops. With few exceptions, mainly for
medical or religious reasons, conscription at age 18 is universal,
and almost all Israelis serve a term in the Israel Defense Forces.
</P>
<P>
   But the draft hasn't only provided manpower for national
security. It has also given birth to thriving civilian industries
built by entrepreneurs who gained invaluable technical skills,
leadership abilities and personal connections in the military.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred new companies spring up every year in Silicon
Wadi, as the Israeli technology sector is sometimes called.
Analysts estimate that three-quarters of them grow directly out of
army service.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is arguably Israel's most important industrial
sector, accounting for a third of the country's exports and
absorbing half the foreign investment in the country. Electronics
exports totaled $5.7 billion in 1997 and are growing at 17 percent
a year; software exports, at $500 million in 1997, are growing at
25 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   As a proportion of its population, Israel has half again as many
scientists and engineers as the United States. Put them together
with the country's burgeoning venture capital industry, and the
result is an abundant crop of start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   One example is GEO Interactive Media Group, which makes
multimedia transmission software used by Web-site designers. Tzur
Daboosh, 32, and Sharon Carmel, 28, two of the founding partners,
met in the army in the late 1980s when both were working on
multimedia combat simulators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gained experience in technologies that went to market five
or six years later,'' Daboosh said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, after several other business ventures, the men teamed
up with another former army technical specialist, Eli Reifman, and
began turning out software in a Tel Aviv apartment. They brought in
a more experienced businessman, Naftali Shani, 49, to serve as
chairman, and took the company public in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Still a development-stage company, GEO lost $9.9 million in 1997
on just $3.1 million in sales. Its London-traded stock, which
peaked above $3 last summer, plummeted in late July when the
company warned that profits were being hampered by production
delays; it closed on Friday at 26.6 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Though its products have little direct military application, GEO
continues to benefit from its army links, and vice versa. Carmel
and Daboosh serve as reserve officers in technical units, teaching
young draftees software design and programming. And while they
teach, the two executives can scout the class for future hires. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most able-bodied 18-year-old Israelis are drafted after
completing high school. Women serve a minimum of one year, nine
months; men spend a minimum of three years on active duty and
remain in the reserves until age 45, taking time out from civilian
life to serve 24 to 30 days a year.
</P>
<P>
   Ambitious draftees compete furiously to gain assignment to the
military units where their experience will be worth most in later
life: army technology units, paratroop units and the air force.
``If you get in there, it's like getting a bachelor's degree in
computer science plus five years of work experience,'' said one
programmer who served in an electronics unit and now works at an
Internet telecommunications start-up.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, an impressive army profile on a resume carries weight
similar to that of an Ivy League degree in the United States.
Informal networks of veterans of special units open doors the way
alumni networks do for graduates of American colleges.
</P>
<P>
   That is how Joseph Ackerman got into the technology business.
After completing army service as a flight test engineer in 1975,
Ackerman was farming near Haifa when some army buddies persuaded
him to join Elbit Computer, now Elbit Ltd., to oversee one of its
new projects. He is now chief executive of Elbit's military
electronics business, which was spun off as a separate company,
Elbit Systems, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Elbit Systems, which had $397 million in sales in the most
recent four quarters and is growing at about 10 percent a year,
makes a helmet-mounted display system that helps tank gunners and
combat pilots aim radar and missiles. The engineers who developed
the technology get to see it in action firsthand during their
annual reserve call-ups, Ackerman said.
</P>
<P>
   While the government restricts exports of some kinds of military
technology, it generally supports such trade. Domestic demand,
after all, is not large enough to support fully an industry it
wants to see thrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ministry of Defense has a finger in this success, so it
can't be unhappy with it,'' said Aharon Beth-Halachmi, head of
Federman Enterprises, a management and investment firm.
Beth-Halachmi, an electrical engineer by training, capped a 30-year
army career as the ministry's chief administrator.
</P>
<P>
   Military technology was the first, and for many years the only
sector of Israeli industry with the technical sophistication to
develop globally competitive software and systems, said
Beth-Halachmi, whom the army sent to graduate school in the United
States in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Military experience also gives Israelis an eye for shortcuts and
a penchant for aggressive innovation, said Shaul Shai, 36, a
reserve major and executive vice president for marketing at Aladdin
Knowledge Systems, a security software maker based in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the IDF, there's a great imbalance between the size of
tasks that must be accomplished and the available resources,'' he
said. ``It's such a huge gap that one needs to think smart all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   But military service is no panacea, and starting a company is
not the same as leading a fighter squadron, observed Shlomo Kalish,
founder and chief executive of Jerusalem Global, a technology
investment bank. Kalish spent five years flying combat jets in the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a great CEO,'' he said, ``you have to be a natural
leader, and that can't be taught.''
</P>
<P>
   Army veterans can be autocratic and somewhat inflexible,
especially when it comes to the culture of titles, said Eran Goren,
a reserve officer and the chief executive of Nessuah-Zannex, an
investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   But while rank matters in the army, so does personal initiative,
said Shai, of Aladdin. And that, too, can cause problems, he said,
``when everyone thinks they're a general.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the army's approach seems to breed success in civilian
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned how to live with constraints, and that's an added
value,'' said GEO's Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   Daboosh agreed: ``We learned flexibility in the army. The IDF is
huge, but it listens to young soldiers. Things were always
changing, which is good and bad, but very Israeli.''
</P>
</TEXT>
