<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-INSPECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAQ GOES ON OFFENSIVE AGAINST INSPECTION TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The Iraqi government shifted its propaganda
campaign against the UN arms experts into high gear Friday,
accusing UN inspectors of spying on the regime and using its access
to Iraqi arms facilities to help US war planners identify potential
military targets.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations, made by Iraqi deputy prime minister Tariq Aziz,
come as the UN Special Commission, charged with disarming Iraq,
accused Baghdad of impeding its efforts to uncover evidence of a
clandestine chemical and biological weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats and analysts say that Baghdad is pursuing a carefully
calculated strategy to undermine the credibility of the inspectors
while providing them with just enough cooperation to weaken
American efforts to gain international support for military action
against Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Iraqis are well aware that the best way to keep the US
threat of force at bay is to keep the Security Council divided,''
said James Placke, an analyst at the Cambridge Energy Research
Associates. ``The lesson Baghdad has drawn is that it will lose its
support in the council if it throws the inspectors out of the
country or blatantly interferes with their work.''
</P>
<P>
   A review by UNSCOM of Iraqi compliance since the last crisis
shows a mix picture. While Baghdad has offered to cooperate with UN
teams searching for evidence of 500 mustard shells and the remains
of 500 additional chemical and biological bombs, they have hampered
the inspectors efforts in a variety of ways.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the Security Council, UNSCOM's deputy director
Charles Duelfer complained that an Iraqi escort helicopter flew
dangerously close, within thirty feet, of a UN helicopter on
November 23. ``The threat to the safety of the UN personnel caused
by this action was brought to the attention'' of the Iraqi
authorities. Baghdad said that incident was unintentional.
</P>
<P>
   Duelfer also said that the inspectors discovered a number of
undeclared dual-use items: a bio-safety cabinet used to prevent
contamination of microscopic material and some filter presses used
to separate cells. ``Frankly there are a hundred and one perfectly
legitimate civilians uses, but it would also be nice for testing
anthrax,'' said UNSCOM spokesman Ewen Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iraq has an obligation to declare all dual use equipment,''
Buchanan added. ``This has been a persistent problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Duelfer also told the council that Iraq denied the UN teams
access to a camp used by pro-Iraqi Iranian rebels. Duelfer said the
UN team was withdrawn after Iraqi officials insisted that the camp
was the property of the Iranian group. The UN continues to
negotiate access to the site with Iraqi officials and the Iranian
rebels. ``We cannot have sanctuaries in Iraq,'' said Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest Iraqi verbal thrust against UNSCOM, Aziz Friday
appealed to UN Secretary General Kofi Annan to sever links between
UN arms inspectors and western intelligence agencies. The arms
inspectors have received extensive help from US, British and
Israeli intelligence services, according to current and former
UNSCOM officials.
</P>
<P>
   Aziz charged that the UN inspectors provided intelligence to the
Pentagon used to select targets for a planned military attack on
Baghdad earlier this month. The attack, which was ordered by
President Clinton and Prime Minister Tony Blair, was aborted at the
last minute because Baghdad capitulated to UN demands to permit
unfettered access to UN arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that urgent steps will be taken to stop the links
between the Special Commission and intelligence apparatuses,
especially of countries with a hostile policy towards Iraq,'' Aziz
wrote in a letter to the UN chief.
</P>
<P>
   The charge follows earlier allegations by Aziz that Charles
Duelfer, UNSCOM's top American official, met with Iraqi opposition
leaders seeking to topple the Hussein regime. Duelfer, who was in
London on Nov 24, the same day, that the opposition leaders were
meeting with Martin Indyk, Assistant Secretary of State for Near
Eastern Affairs, denied he met with the Iraqi opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, new evidence emerged this week concerning Iraqi
efforts to acquire banned missile technology since the Gulf War.
Romania's defense ministry admitted Friday that a number of
Romanian companies had signed several contracts between 1994 and
1996 to supply missile components to Iraq, which is subject to a UN
arms embargo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
