<HEADLINE>
MILD WEATHER HAS RETAILERS IN A SWEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mild weather in December may be great for golfers and outdoor
enthusiasts, but it has some retailers distraught and disconsolate
as the all-important holiday season approaches.
</P>
<P>
   For retailers who rely heavily on sales of overcoats, scarves,
and snow tires, ``you couldn't get a weather scenario much worse
than this one,'' said James Gagne, a vice president of Strategic
Weather Services, a Pennsylvania consulting firm that advises
merchants about the weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a choice between playing golf or going shopping,
which are you going to do?'' said Gagne, before permitting himself
a rare gloat. ``Our long-term forecast accurately predicted this
warm weather.''
</P>
<P>
   The ideal holiday weather report for many retailers? Cold
temperatures and several light dustings of snow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snow really puts consumers in a Christmas frame of mind,''
Gagne said. ``Ideally, you want some snow, but not enough to keep
people off the roads and out of the stores.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, several retailers blamed unseasonably mild
weather for disappointing November sales.
</P>
<P>
   Among this group was J. Baker Inc., the Canton, Mass. company
that operates such chains as Casual Male Big &AMP; Tall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Due to unseasonably warm weather in November, sales of our
cold-weather related product, which represents a large portion of
our sales at this time of year, were negatively impacted,'' said J.
Baker president and chief executive Alan I. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne and retail analysts hasten to add that one retailer's loss
from warm weather may be another's gain.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of boots and overcoats, a consumer might be inclined to
spend money on home furnishings or a new DVD player or a computer
and a big-screen TV.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to holiday sales, ``weather is only part of the
story,'' said Kurt Barnard, president of Barnard's Retail Trend
Report.
</P>
<P>
   While some apparel retailers struggled in November, others
excelled. The Gap, for one, was hotter than Miami, and balmy
breezes did little to slow the momentum of Wal-Mart Inc.
</P>
<P>
   If November results are any guide, warm weather did little to
dissuade the customers of Talbots Inc. from buying its classic
women's clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Many department-store chains turned in lackluster November
results, but that's been the case for much of the year, even in
some months when weather patterns were normal, Barnard said.
</P>
<P>
   By his lights, it's not so much unseasonable weather that's
keeping consumers out of department stores, but it's a search for
bargains and good value that draws consumers into stores operated
by discount merchants and off-price retailers.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say warm weather will have no effect. As
cold-weather gear stays piled up on store shelves, retailers are
forced to slash prices and spend more money on advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg News quoted one portfolio manager who speculated that
slow clothing sales from warm weather could shave a nickel off the
fourth-quarter earnings of Federated Department Stores Inc., which
operates such chains as Macy's, and May Department Stores Co.,
which operates Filene's, among other chains.
</P>
<P>
   But the extent of warm-weather damage on earnings _ if any _ may
not be fully known until retailers issue fourth-quarter results in
February and March.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
