<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-APPROP-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        PENNSYLVANIA TO LOSE SENIORITY ON APPROPRIATIONS COMMITTEE
</HEADLINE>
 By LISA FINE  
 &HT;    c.1998 States News Service   WASHINGTON, Dec. 4 -- Over the
<TEXT>
years, Reps. John Murtha and Joseph McDade gained a reputation in
the Capitol for knowing how to bring home the bacon for their home
state of Pennsylvania.
<P>
   But when the new Congress convenes next month, Murtha,
D-Johnstown, will have a new partner on the House Appropriations
Committee, a perch from which he and McDade snared their funds.
</P>
<P>
   McDade, who was the second highest ranking Republican member of
the committee, is retiring after representing the Scranton region
for 36 years in the House. Joining Murtha, who will move up to be
the second highest ranking Democrat on the committee, from
Pennsylvania will be Rep. John Peterson, R-5th District.
</P>
<P>
   Just reelected to his second term, Peterson was tapped last
month to join the committee that, along with its Senate
counterpart, determines how federal money is doled out for
projects.
</P>
<P>
   What does the change in the makeup of the committee mean for
Pennsylvania?
</P>
<P>
   Seniority is very important,'' said Elizabeth Morra, a spokesman
for Republicans on the committee. ``But there were a lot of people
who wanted to get on to the committee, and Peterson did. That is
really good for Pennsylvania even though they did lose McDade.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Democrats on the committee, Kori Hardin,
said simply, ``the higher the rank, the more power members have for
their states.''
</P>
<P>
   Murtha will miss the rapport he had with McDade, and the clout
his seniority brought for Pennsylvania, Murtha's spokesman Brad
Clemenson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will the state be affected by the loss of seniority with
McDade's retirement? Oh definitely,'' Clemenson said. ``Now the
seniority will be more spread out. Murtha has said McDade will be
missed. We were very fortunate in Pennsylvania to have had two
members who were so high-ranking.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his appointment Peterson said it ``gives rural
America a more persistent voice in Congress to protect programs and
initiatives that will preserve our culture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is beneficial for a state to have a member on that
committee, but to have had two, and at such high ranks was a status
that will have to be rebuilt,'' Clemenson said.
</P>
<P>
   Murtha and McDade had a formula that included dropping their
partisan politics with each other, developing statewide priorities
for which to push jointly, and also individually in their different
parties, Clemenson said.
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisan tag-team of Murtha and McDade on the committee
was held up by members from other states as an effective model of
how to pull the federal purse strings.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone in Washington saw Murtha and McDade as a dream
team.
</P>
<P>
   A congressional watchdog group, called Citizens Against
Government Waste, criticized the two Pennsylvania members for being
``porkers.''
</P>
<P>
   Murtha and McDade ``prove that pigging out at taxpayer expense
can be a bipartisan affair,'' the group said when it handed out
it's 1995 ``Pig Book Award.''
</P>
<P>
   That year, according to the group, their combined tally in
fiscal year 1995 alone topped an estimated $78 million.
</P>
<P>
   The projects for which they garnered funding that year included
$10.5 million for the renovation of the Philadelphia Naval
Shipyard, $1 million for a pilot health program for the needy at
Misericodrdia Hospital, and a $1 million grant to the Small
Business Development Institute in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Murtha's spokesman, Clemenson, said Murtha would surely reach
out to Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   Already some common priorities have emerged for Murtha and
Peterson for the next Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson said he will fight in the next Congress to keep the
federal budget balanced and to preserve Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security, Clemenson said, was a priority for Murtha as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they will work together,'' Clemenson said. ``It would
be in the best interest of the state.''
</P>
</TEXT>
