<HEADLINE>
ENVIRONMENTAL THREAT TO PENGUINS DOUBLES, PANEL SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In just two years, the number of species of penguins facing
possible extinction has nearly doubled, an international panel of
researchers warned Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the threat to one of people's most beloved forms of
wildlife, the penguins' rapidly worsening situation may be serving
as an indicator of accelerating human damage to oceans and remote,
fragile areas where penguins breed.
</P>
<P>
   Of 17 principal species of penguins, nine are now considered
``threatened or vulnerable,'' up from just five two years ago when
IUCN-The World Conservation Union conducted its last survey.
</P>
<P>
   At a New England Aquarium conference in Boston Friday,
specialists cited several apparent factors harming populations:
global climate changes, including this past year's wild El
Nino-related weather, oil spills that destroy penguin feather
waterproofing, overfishing of penguin food species, snagging of
penguins in trawler nets, and damaging human development of
Southern Hemisphere coastal areas where penguins live.
</P>
<P>
   The growing threat to penguins is alarming because ``first of
all, they're cute, but aside from that they are a good flagship''
in spotlighting threats to ``other species that people aren't
interested in,'' said Heather Urquhart, a senior aquarium
researcher who has studied penguins in South Africa extensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real problem brewing not just for penguins, but for
the world marine environment,'' said Urquhart. She was joined by a
panel of penguin specialists from Australia, South Africa, and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, four species have moved onto the list of
``vulnerable'' species that face a 10 percent chance of extinction
within 100 years: the 179,000 remaining African penguins found off
Namibia and South Africa; the 12,500 Humboldt penguins that live on
the coasts of Peru and Chile; and two species that live on islands
north of Antarctica, the Rockhopper and the Royal, which together
total 1.8 million breeding pairs.
</P>
<P>
   Two other species that were considered vulnerable two years ago
are now considered endangered, meaning they face a 20 percent risk
of extinction in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   They are the Erect-Crested Penguin, native to the Antipodes
Islands south of New Zealand, whose 170,000 breeding pairs are
threatened by rats eating eggs and chicks, and the 3,000 to 6,000
Galapagos penguins. The fish they eat have been displaced or killed
by El Nino currents.
</P>
<P>
   Extinction threats are calculated based on observed or estimated
population declines in recent years, said Susie Ellis of the IUCN
group.
</P>
<P>
   One mixed blessing for penguins is that more and more people are
traveling to exotic parts of the Southern Hemisphere to see them.
Annual visits to Antarctica, for example, have grown more than
18-fold since the 1950s, to 5,500 people annually, and daily visits
to the famed penguin colony at Punta Espinosa in the Galapagos have
grown by 100 times, according to studies presented at a 1996 Cape
Town conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a double-edged sword,'' said Peter Dann, research manager
at the Phillip Island Nature Park in Australia. Well-meaning
visitors can disrupt breeding or trample on nests, but the
increasing number of visitors creates a bigger constituency for
efforts to protect penguins. ``It is possible for large numbers of
people to visit these penguin colonies without causing
destruction,'' Dann said.
</P>
<P>
   While human activities are devastating penguins in some areas,
elsewhere people are helping save them. Over the last decade,
environmentalists have pressed for turning old pasturelands on the
south island of New Zealand into prime penguin-nesting territory,
Dann said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, an oil spill off South Africa contaminated 10,000
penguins, but more than 4,000 were saved when rescuers cleaned
them, and half of those successfully bred later, said Tony Williams
of Cape Nature Conservation in Cape Town.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
