<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Saturday, Dec. 5. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Despite a fresh wave of downsizing
announcements that is expected to lead to tens of thousands of
layoffs in the months ahead, the government reports that more
Americans are working than ever. While corporate giants from Boeing
to Johnson &AMP; Johnson are being forced to eliminate large numbers of
workers because of various business difficulties, the overall
economy continued to advance at a healthy clip, with American
employers expanding their payrolls by an estimated 267,000 workers
in November alone. By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   reefer photo: SCI-SHUTTLE (Kennedy Space Center, Fla.) _ The
planet's most daring construction job begins as the shuttle
Endeavour carries into orbit six astronauts and the first
American-built part of an international space station that is
expected to cost more than $100 billion. An overview of the mission
highlights. By William J. Broad. 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-POLITICS (Newark, N.J.) _ Ending months of speculation
about his political future, Bill Bradley, the former U.S. senator
from New Jersey, says he will consider making a bid to become the
next president of the United States. By Jennifer Preston.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CENSURE (Washington) _ President Clinton's fate in the House now
hinges on the decisions of a small group of Republian moderates who
could tilt an impeachment vote either way. With Republican leaders
likely to prevent any vote on censure, both Republicans and
Democrats who are trying to count votes say that a House vote on a
single count article of impeachment, on perjury, is too close to
call. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   With: IMPEACH (Washington) _ Developments on the House
impeachment inquiry into President Clinton. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-U.S. (Washington) _ President Clinton's planned trip to
the Middle East is running into problems as Israelis and
Palestinians continue to argue over peace accord. By Steven
Erlanger. 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   GIRL-KIDNEY-TRANSPLANT (Undated) _ The saga of a young, girl in
San Franciso, born with one kidney, who received a kidney
transplant from her father, who is in prison, two years ago. Now
the kidney is failing and he desperately wants to give her his
second kidney. At first the hospital refused, but now the case has
gone before the University of San Francisco's ethics committee for
review. The girl will die without the kidney and so far, only her
father is a match. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES (Miami) _ The way some neighbors tell it, the area on
the edge of Everglades National Park known as East Everglades has
all the charm of a swamp, but the same neighbors describe the
bright side of this lifestyle with words like ``magical'' and
``breathtaking.'' That way of life is about to end. The rural
neighborhood stands in the way of a multi-billion-dollar effort to
repair the vast expanse of unique wetlands that is the Everglades.
Last month, officials with the South Florida Water Management
District voted to spend up to $100 million to buy out about 1,400
landowners and clear out the 8 1/2-square-mile East Everglades area
by the year 2002, part of an $8 billion project to save the
Everglades. By Mireya Navarro. With map. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-ASSESS (New Delhi, India) _ News analysis: The Hindu
nationalists who lead India's government were trounced in state
elections last week because of their failure to deliver on
pocketbook economic issues, but the defeats, which weakened their
already tenuous grip on power at the national level, are also
likely to make it more difficult for them to sign the nuclear test
ban treaty. By Celia W. Dugger. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   CRIMINAL-STUDIES (Newark, N.J.) _ Criminal justice studies is
the fastest growing major in the country. But it's not like your
father's major; and many of the students have family members in
prison. By Fox Butterfield. 1,600 words. (MOVED)
</P>
