<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Saturday, Dec. 5. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
BELLAGIO-TRAVEL (Las Vegas) - Bellagio, the most expensive hotel
ever built (for now), stands on the western edge of an 8.5-acre
artificial lake. At regular intervals throughout each evening,
lyrical sprinklers animate the water. Framed through the falling
mist and the twinkle lights decorating the lakeside foliage,
Bellagio appears every bit as enchanting, romantic, stately and
dignified as its TV commercials promise. By DAVE WALKER, Story
moved in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
JERSEY CITY-TRAVEL (Jersey City, N.J.) - Although travel writers
tend to wax eloquent about the big tourist destinations and travel
sections in the nation's newspapers tend to cover mainstream events
with ``what-to-see'' stories emphasizing places with giant smiling
mice or beachfront hotels, a great deal of our travel is in between
the places we actually want to be. Thus, I came to New Jersey, to
find cheap lodging for the nights while spending the days in
Manhatta. But travelers learn that sometimes there are treats where
you least expect them, that come unbidden to you while you wait for
something else. By RICHARD NILSEN. Story moved in the ``L''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
FANTASY-FOOTBALL (Phoenix) - I dozed on the couch Monday night,
watching the wretched Giants flounder against the 49ers. My
thoughts were filled with fluttering passes and stumbling running
backs, missed field goals and blown coverages. In other words, the
National Football League. As I drifted off, I thought about how all
those bad teams had turned my fantasy league into a disaster. How
the Thursday night game didn't include a single player that anybody
cared to start on a fantasy team. Ick. Ptooey. By BILL MULLER.
Story moved in the ``S'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CANYON-FISHING (Grand Canyon, Ariz.) - Even though the fish weren't
biting, we were in the Grand Canyon. I've been a lot of places
where I've been told I should have been there a week ago, or maybe
next week, or whatever, and they've all been nice places, but they
weren't, well, they weren't the Grand Canyon. By RON DUNGAN. Story
moved in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
