<HEADLINE>
LINEBACKERS COULD DECIDE BIG 12 CHAMPIONSHIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ A broken collarbone has reduced Texas A&AMP;M
quarterback Randy McCown to the role of interested bystander during
today's Big 12 Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   But before Thursday's X-rays ruled him out as a participant,
McCown spent hours studying videotapes of the Wildcats' defense.
The more he saw, the more it reminded him of the unit he faced
every day in practice.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of both defenses, said McCown, will be the
difference-makers who will tell the tale of today's matchup between
Texas A&AMP;M (10-2), ranked 10th in The Associated Press poll, and No.
2 Kansas State (11-0) at 3:30 p.m. in the Trans World Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of the top linebackers in the nation will be on
that field,'' McCown said. ``I think they'll determine the game.
Their defense goes like their linebackers go. If they play well,
their whole defense plays well. It's the same with our guys. The
rest of the team feeds off of them.''
</P>
<P>
   McCown's observation is far from classified information. Of the
seven starting linebackers in today's contest, five were chosen as
all-conference performers by Big 12 coaches.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M's Dat Nguyen, who leads the league with 130 tackles, is a
finalist for the Butkus Award, given annually to the nation's top
linebacker. All three of Kansas State's starters were nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the statistics of both starting units and you've got 598
tackles, 96 of them for losses. That doesn't even include the 34.5
sacks. Or the 14 forced fumbles, 11 recoveries and six
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes in the battle of Linebacker U. vs. Linebacker U.,
where the majority of big plays among the Big 12's two stingiest
defenses tend to be made by the guys who bridge the gap between the
defensive line and the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the teams are different in their approach. Kansas State
plays a 4-3 alignment, A&AMP;M a 3-4. The Wildcats blitz continually,
leaving their cornerbacks in man-to-man coverage throughout most of
the game. A&AMP;M picks its spots with its blitzes, allowing defensive
backs to vary between man and zone coverages.
</P>
<P>
   Other than aggression and talent, the common thread for both
units is experience. Kansas State's starters _ middle linebacker
Jeff Kelly and outside linebackers Mark Simoneau and Travis Ochs _
have played together for the past 24 games. A&AMP;M has two first-year
starters in its four-linebacker set (Roylin Bradley and Cornelius
Anthony), but the two standouts, Nguyen and Warrick Holdman, have
played together for the past 40 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no substitute for experience,'' Kansas State coach
Bill Snyder said. ``Our guys have a great understanding of our
defense. They know how to tie the back end together with the front
four. I expect our linebackers to play extremely hard and be
extremely responsible for what we do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the A&AMP;M people feel the same way about their guys.
You look at them on film and they play hard. They run extremely
well. All of them are good at handling their responsibilities.
There's no weak link among them.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum echoes similar sentiments about the Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire the way K-State plays, especially at linebacker,''
Slocum said. ``They'd be very comparable to ours, and we're real
proud of ours. Of the teams we've played this year, no one's had a
better group of linebackers than Kansas State.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly and Nguyen, the emotional leaders of the respective units,
try to downplay comparisons. But both agree the matchup adds luster
to the game. Shane Lechler, the A&AMP;M punter, is intrigued enough
that he intends to focus most of his attention on the movements of
the linebackers rather than the movement of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm done playing football, I want to be a coach
somewhere,'' Lechler said. ``So, I like to watch the great players
on both teams to try to learn from how they play and how they
react.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game will be a straight dogfight on defense, and the
linebackers will be at the heart of it. They've got Kelly. We've
got Dat and Warrick. There should be a lot of big hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Enough, Lechler suggested, to produce a Big 12 version of one of
those ``NFL's Greatest Hits'' videos.
</P>
<P>
   But the bottom line is earning a Big 12 championship. And, if
this matchup will determine today's winner, as McCown suggests, one
question remains unanswered: which group is better?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're equal,'' A&AMP;M tailback Dante Hall said. ``I just hope
our guys play better on that particular day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
