<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4021 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SODOMY-LAWS-BOS &LR;      12-04 1415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SODOMY-LAWS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-SODOMY LAWS BEING CHALLENED IN MANY STATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ With pink-and-white curtains and a flowered
comforter, Elena Picado's bedroom seems an unlikely place to launch
a revolution.
</P>
<P>
   But because Picado sleeps there with a woman, her bedroom is
regularly the scene of a crime _ an illegal act of lovemaking and,
in effect, civil disobedience. As often as they choose, Picado and
her partner, April Armstrong, flout an Arkansas law that bans
homosexual sex.
</P>
<P>
   In theory at least, a conviction on the misdemeanor charge could
cost Picado her two children and her job as a junior high school
Spanish teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``This law says that because I am a lesbian, the government can
simply come in and take away what is most important to me in the
world. That is a terror to me, a terror I live with every day,''
said Picado, 43, one of seven plaintiffs in a lawsuit challenging
Arkansas's anti-sodomy law.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas is one of five states that ban sexual contact between
consenting members of the same sex. Another 13 states outlaw
consensual oral and anal sex, regardless of participants' gender or
sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   But those anti-sodomy statutes, which existed in all 50 states
as recently as the 1960s, are coming under unprecedented pressure
from a wave of legal and legislative attempts to repeal limits on
sexual behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Though prosecutions are rare, gay and civil rights activists say
the laws can be used as a threat by overzealous prosecutors.
Moreover, they say the laws are a jumping-off point for
discrimination in areas such as housing, child custody and
employment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gay people living in these states have to live constantly with
the fear of enforcement and the risk that their lives could be
turned upside-down at any point by an arrest for engaging in sexual
intimacy with a loved one,'' said Suzanne B. Goldberg, a lawyer
with the Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund, which is
representing Picado and the other plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative groups have taken note of the recent challenges and
have responded with alarm. They praise the use of anti-sodomy laws
to keep children out of homosexual households, and to discourage
behavior they say undermines traditional marriage bonds and may
increase the risk of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anti-sodomy laws are sound laws, designed to promote behaviors
that are profitable, beneficial and fruitful, and to discourage
behaviors that are damaging to both the society and to the
individual,'' said Steven Schwalm, senior analyst with the Family
Research Council in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But after long bouts of frustration and setbacks for activists _
most notably a 1986 US Supreme Court ruling that said the US
Constitution does not protect private homosexual conduct _ attempts
to repeal anti-sodomy laws have recently gained momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Georgia Supreme Court overturned that state's
anti-sodomy law, a ruling that was particularly notable because the
Georgia law was the subject of the US Supreme Court's 1986
decision. Although the US Supreme Court found no constititutional
protection for homosexual conduct, the Georgia Supreme Court said
the state constitution does offer such protection for private,
consensual sexual conduct.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia ruling followed similar decisions in Tennessee,
Kentucky and Montana, as well as actions by voters in Nevada and
the District of Columbia to repeal anti-sodomy laws.
</P>
<P>
   Court challenges also are pending in Louisiana, Maryland and
Minnesota, and gay activists have been buoyed by what they consider
an ideal case to test the law in Texas. In September, a false
report of an armed intruder led authorities to a Houston apartment;
when a deputy sheriff walked through what he said was an unlocked
door, he saw two gay men having sex and promptly arrested them. Gay
activists say the case underscores the threat to privacy; their
challenge to the law could take several years.
</P>
<P>
   Schwalm, meanwhile, said he was suspicious that the Texas
incident was a setup designed to test the law, though he had no
evidence to back that assertion. He also decried the Georgia
ruling, noting that it was based on a case involving a man who had
oral sex with his 17-year-old niece.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Georgia court says that's fine and gay activists cheer. I
don't understand why that's a cause for celebration,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all repeal efforts have succeeded, however. Previous court
challenges have failed in Texas, and a Missouri court said the
state had the right to ban oral and anal sex to protect public
health by slowing the spread of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, legislative efforts are under way in several other
states, including Massachusetts, where attempts to remove the
anti-sodomy law have failed repeatedly in the Legislature. Another
effort will be made when the new legislative session begins next
month, said Gary Buseck, executive director of the Gay and Lesbian
Advocates and Defenders in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts has two laws at issue: one called a ``crime
against nature'' statute carries a punishment of up to 20 years in
prison; the other is a ban on ``unnatural and lascivious acts''
punishable by up to five years in prison and fines of up to $1,000,
gay activists said.
</P>
<P>
   In Arkansas, the law under challenge is a misdemeanor punishable
by up to 12 months in prison and a fine of $1,000. For the seven
plaintiffs, the immediate concern is less about prosecution than
the message the law sends.
</P>
<P>
   ``This law is an attack on my very being,'' said Vernon Stokay,
38, a graphic designer. ``I am a homosexual. What other kind of sex
am I going to have? The very moment I decide to do this very
private thing, they say I am a criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiff Robin White, 42, a technical writer, has a lease that
says she could be evicted for committing any criminal act in her
apartment; a sodomy case against her, she said, could land her on
the street. ``The message is that you are a second-class citizen,
even though you pay the same taxes, contribute to the community and
are a good person,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiff Randy McCain, 42, a minister at a nondenominational
Christian church, said he was dismissed from a different church
several years ago when he declared his homosexuality. He said
anti-sodomy laws contribute to efforts to keep gays in the closet.
``When you have a good, wholesome, loving relationship, you want to
celebrate it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A significant factor in the drive to repeal anti-sodomy laws was
a 1996 case in which the US Supreme Court said a Colorado law was
unconstitutional because it effectively categorized homosexuals as
``unequal to everyone else.'' Gay activists quickly recognized that
that language could be used to build the case against the
anti-sodomy laws in Arkansas, Kansas, Missouri, Oklahoma and Texas,
where the statutes apply only to homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   That avenue is not open to activists in Massachusetts and the
other 12 states because their laws are applied regardless of sexual
orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Some prosecutors have defended anti-sodomy laws as a useful
secondary charge in rape and other sexual assault cases: If a
defendant admits to an allegedly forced sex act, but claims it was
consensual, he or she could still face penalties for violating the
anti-sodomy law.
</P>
<P>
   Other supporters of anti-sodomy laws are more blunt about their
perceived value. When the Georgia ruling was announced, the
top-ranking Republican in the state Senate told reporters: ``I
think we ought to be able to ban gay sex.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arkansas case is now before the state Supreme Court, which
is being asked to rule on procedural grounds whether to allow a
trial on the issues. Arkansas officials have yet to take a public
position on the merits, said Tim Gauger, an assistant attorney
general who is handling the case.
</P>
<P>
   He noted, however, that his office could find no instances of
prosecutions under the law for private, consensual acts in the last
70 years.
</P>
<P>
   That is not good enough for Picado and the other plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if there was a slavery law on the books that was never
implemented? Do you think any black person could sleep at night?''
Picado asked. ``I wish the people who want this law would step into
my house. I'll invite everybody into my bedroom. They would find
the same things they find in their own bedrooms. Maybe that would
help them understand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
