<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4032 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-U.S.-NYT &LR;      12-04 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE 747 OR THE HELICOPTER? WHAT'S A PRESIDENT TO DO? 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ So does President Clinton arrive in the Palestinian
Authority on his big 747 or on a little helicopter? Does he balance
his visit to the Gaza Strip with one to Masada, the Alamo of
Israel? And then must he balance that with a quick tour of
Bethlehem? After all, it is the Holy Land, however disputed, and
it's Christmastime.
</P>
<P>
   If the problems of the Middle East are about land and blood, the
diplomacy that tries to resolve them is often about language and
symbolism. In the case of Clinton's upcoming trip to Israel and the
Palestinian Authority, designed to promote and advance the
agreement between the Israelis and Palestinians reached in Wye,
Md., in October, it's also about airplanes and sightseeing.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue at the core of these questions was never settled
at Wye: will the Palestinians declare statehood unilaterally on May
4, 1999, when the Oslo peace process formally runs out, or are they
simply threatening to do it, as their best leverage on the
Israelis?
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, struggling to keep
his government together following the Wye agreement, was taken
aback by the warm reception given Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
in Washington last week. Not only was Arafat showered with money at
an international donors' conference hosted by the Americans, he was
treated indulgently when he spoke frankly about his intention to
declare Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Other Palestinian officials have done the same at the United
Nations and elsewhere, which the Israelis regard as a violation of
the Oslo accords and of promises at Wye not to take unilateral
steps that would foreclose negotiations between the parties.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Netanyahu says he has frozen further implementation
of the very Wye agreement Clinton is going to Israel to celebrate,
causing the Americans to criticize Netanyahu further for setting
``new conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian Authority needs to commit itself ``unequivocally
to abandoning its intention to unilaterally declare a Palestinian
state'' and ``to conducting continuous negotiations with Israel
until an agreement is concluded'' _ and needs to publish that
intention in the Palestinian media _ for Israel to continue carry
out the Wye agreement, an Israeli Cabinet statement said.
</P>
<P>
   American officials have done little to criticize Arafat or his
officials, other than to say that ``unilateral steps are not
helpful'' and that ``Palestinian statehood must be addressed in the
negotiations themselves.'' And the Americans have refused to say
what they would do or say if Arafat does declare statehood
unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
   One senior American official said Friday: ``There's a difference
between saying you're going to declare statehood and actually doing
it. There's a lot of posturing on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   But what is clearly bothering Netanyahu is that the Clinton
visit will provide powerful new pictures and symbolism of a new
American-Palestinian relationship _ including the arrival of the
American president at the new Palestinian international airport
opened with great fanfare as a result of the Wye accord.
</P>
<P>
   David Bar-Illan, Netanyahu's chief spokesman, has now formally
asked Clinton not to arrive in the Gaza Strip in his big, baby-blue
747 emblazoned with the huge seal of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said Friday that they are likely to heed the
Israeli request, but on the grounds of pragmatism. The trip from
Tel Aviv to the Gaza Strip is a short one, analogous to the
distance from Washington to Baltimore, one official said, and
``chances are we wouldn't use a 747 but a helicopter.'' To use the
larger plane, the official said, would also require ``bringing in a
lot more people to upgrade the airport.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, when the Israelis suggested a presidential visit to
Masada, the Americans agreed. But now Clinton is contemplating a
stop in Bethlehem, which is controlled by the Palestinian
authority, further upsetting the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   The Wye agreement, reached after nine days of intense
negotiations _ including nearly 90 hours of Clinton's own time, set
out a three-month timetable under which Israel would withdraw from
another 13 percent of the West Bank in return for specific, phased
steps by the Palestinians to combat terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   It was supposed to be followed immediately by intensive
negotiations on a final settlement between Israel and the
Palestinians, which would resolve fundamental questions like the
future of Jerusalem and whether the Palestinians will have a state.
Under the original Oslo timetable, that final settlement is
supposed to be complete by May 4, 1999, providing urgency to the
process.
</P>
<P>
   But final status talks have yet to get under way. One quiet
procedural meeting between Israeli and Palestinian officials, at
which no Americans were present, has not been followed up.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and American officials concede that with all the furor
over the implementation of the Wye agreement itself, there has been
little energy to focus on the final status talks, which would offer
the best answer to Arafat's claims.
</P>
<P>
   After all, one American official said sardonically, ``May is
months away.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, American officials are worrying about the few days of
the Clinton visit, which begins Dec. 12, and what exactly is to be
celebrated in the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
   At Wye, Netanyahu's demand that the Palestinian National Council
formally revoke all the clauses in their charter calling for
Israel's destruction was handled with an Israeli-originated
compromise. Arafat would gather a quorum of the council, surround
them with lots of other, less radical Palestinians, and confirm the
revocation of the old charter in some form of mass vote, by hand or
voice.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, the Israelis have called for something more
formal, and an American official said: ``We want to make sure that
what happens in Gaza meets the Israeli needs.'' At the same time,
however, the Americans are nervous that Netanyahu will continue to
change his requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Yoel Marcus, writing Friday in the Israeli newspaper Haaretz,
described Netanyahu as ``in a panic'' to consolidate his political
position, broaden his government and act toughly ``while the
Palestinian state is being established right under his nose.''
</P>
<P>
   But Netanyahu ``will not be able to halt the hurricane known as
Clinton's visit and the American recognition of a Palestinian state
that it implies,'' Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
   American officials insist that Clinton's visit implies no such
thing. Yet as Marcus suggested, the symbolism argues otherwise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
