<HEADLINE>
JAGR TO BRING POWERFUL PENGUINS GAME TO BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Farm life figures into Jaromir Jagr's greatness. He
grew up in what was then Czechoslovakia, in Kladno, and the Jagrs
worked the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you do that,'' Jagr said recently, ``you work every day .
. . and you work hard.''
</P>
<P>
   And therein lies the source of those powerful, explosive Jagr
legs, that strong back. Pitch hay. Push livestock. Work from the
moment dawn breaks and till the sun edges its nose below the tree
line. Jagr today is the National Hockey League's most exciting
performer, farm boy turned phenom, and he'll be in Boston Saturday
night with the Penguins when they take on the Bruins at the
FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   Now 26, Jagr stood tied with the Flyers' Eric Lindros Friday for
the league lead in points (33). There may be some agrument as to
who is better or more valauble to his team _ Jagr or Lindros _ but
there is no disputing that the Penguins' superstar is the most
electrifying performer in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got all those different speeds,'' said Bruins assistant
coach Bobby Francis. ``He's got that uncanny ability to freeze the
opposition with his cutbacks _ the way he changes his speeds _ and
his quick, quick hands. He's like a (Wayne) Gretzky the way he'll
cut back with the puck and look for the late man. And then he's
like a (John) LeClair, using that long reach of his to wrap around
the net. He's like a (Sergei) Samsonov with those hands. You're
talking about a lot of key components, and Jagr's got 'em all.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jagr jumps over the boards Saturday night, coach Pat Burns
will make sure he has at least one of his biggest defensemen _ Hal
Gil, Kyle McLaren, or Ray Bourque _ as part of his five-man unit.
Up front, he'll try to counter with his top scoring line, the Jason
Allison-Dmitri Khristich-Samsonov combination, or his Tim
Taylor-Rob DiMaio-P.J. Axelsson checking trio. When Jagr's on
patrol, everyone on the other side of the puck is turned into a
defensive player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want him with the puck at all,'' said Burns. ``I don't
want him with it anywhere at all, if possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon joining the Penguins in the fall of 1990 at age 18, Jagr
instantly became another jewel in what already was a dazzling
lineup. The Penguins, led by Mario Lemieux, won their first Stanley
Cup in the spring of '91 and repeated the following year. In only
some 20 months on North American soil, Jagr owned two Cup rings and
already had established himself as one of the NHL's premier
game-breakers.
</P>
<P>
   There is little left of that core group. Lemieux has retired.
Ron Francis is the aging cornerstone of the Carolina Hurricanes.
Kevin Stevens wears a Ranger blueshirt. Larry Murphy lugs the puck
for the Red Wings. Other than his recent foray overseas for Team
USA, Joe Mullen is off skates. Only netminder Tom Barrasso and Jagr
remain from the glory days.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr no longer is just the long-haired, angel-faced, extravagant
ornament best known for his love of Kit Kats, video games, and fast
cars. He wears the captain's ``C'' for the first time and has
matured into a significant leader on the ice and in the dressing
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong,'' said Jagr, reflecting on his acceptance
of the captaincy. ``I didn't go to the coaches and say, `I want to
be the captain.' No way. ``They asked me, like, `Would you want to
be the captain?' That's what really happened. It's not something
I'd thought about, but I was here for nine years _ since 1990 _ and
I didn't know, but I figured the chances were 50-50 that it might
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Gone are those flashes when a churlish Jagr, upset at his play
or disgruntled with the numbers on the scoreboard, could be seen
pouting at the end of the bench. For the last couple of seasons,
and especially this year, he has matured into a dependable,
consistent, and frightening force on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's his strength and size, that whole combination,'' said
Bourque. ``He has such good ability and he has that reach that
helps him protect the puck really well. You play him too close, you
get too aggressive, and he'll just spin right off you and he's
gone. His speed certainly has something to do with it, but it's
everything else, too. Every time he touches the puck, he's a
threat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
