<HEADLINE>
JOBLESS RATE CONTINUES TO DROP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The US economy, which most analysts had thought was
stumbling, put on another show of strength last month, creating
hundreds of thousands of new jobs and driving the unemployment rate
back down to a near-generation low of 4.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpectedly strong jobs growth came as the economy entered
its 93rd month of expansion, topping the 92-month Reagan-era boom
and becoming the longest period of peacetime growth on record,
according to the Cambridge-based National Bureau of Economic
Research, the official score-keeper of the nation's expansions and
contractions.
</P>
<P>
   The jobs figures offered the most powerful evidence to date that
even as the roiling global financial crises of the past year have
taken their toll on US manufacturers, they have turned out to be
good news for the American economy as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Falling interest rates due largely to a flood of foreign capital
seeking safe havens and tumbling food and energy prices due to
slackening foreign demand have helped fuel a consumer spending boom
that _ at least so far _ has shielded this nation from most of the
economic troubles around it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party's not over yet,'' said Diane C. Swonk, deputy chief
economist with Bank One Corp. in Chicago. ``The US economy is
proving very resilient.''
</P>
<P>
   Corporate America added 267,000 nonfarm payroll jobs in
November, the Labor Deparment said Friday. That was substantially
more than the 169,000 that most analysts had been expecting, and
helped drive the unemployment rate down two-tenths of a percentage
point to 4.4 percent, just above its 28-year low set last April and
May.
</P>
<P>
   The fraction of the American population holding jobs rose to
64.1 percent last month from 63.9 percent the preceding month to
come within a hair's breadth of its all-time high of 64.2 percent
reached earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The figures show there is no cause for concern on the jobs
front,'' said Allen Sinai, chief global economist for Primark
Decision Economics in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Investors took the numbers to mean there is less cause for
concern on the financial front as well, and drove stock prices up.
The Dow Jones industrial average rose 136.46 points, or 1.5
percent, to close at 9016.14. Broader market indexes rose even more
substantially. The increases partially offset a week of declines
fueled in large par by investor worries that American consumers
might be coming to the end of their long spending spree.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that November's jobs growth may have been
partially fueled by temporary factors and may thus overstate the
economy's robustness. Among industries adding workers, for example,
was construction, where employment jumped 47,000. Analysts said
most of the gain is traceable to the peculiarly warm autumn, which
extended the construction season.
</P>
<P>
   The new jobs numbers show the toll that the Asian financial
crisis and its globe-girdling aftershocks have taken on US
manufacturers. Factory employment fell by 47,000 in November,
extending a string of losses since last March that have eliminated
245,000 manufacturing jobs and reduced manufacturing's fraction of
the American work force to less than 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Those declines seem certain to continue as a string of major
employers signaled this week that they plan major layoffs, mostly
becuase of the Asian crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Co., the world's biggest jetmaker, said it will slash
48,000 jobs by the end of the year 2000 because of weakening
foreign sales of its 747 aircraft. Exxon Corp, the nation's biggest
oil company, announced plans to buy its No.2 rival, Mobil, in a
move to consolidate an industry hammered by the falloff in demand
from emerging nations in Asia and elsewhere. Analysts estimate the
combined firm will cut 9,000 to perhaps 20,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The manufacturing sector is going the way of agriculture. It
is shrinking, shrinking, shrinking,'' said Sinai.
</P>
<P>
   Neverthless, the economy as a whole seems to be doing
spectacularly well, especially when measured against what most
analysts and policymakers were predicting until recently.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts began the year saying that US growth would slow at
least moderately from its feverish pace of 1996 and 1997 because of
the impact of the Asian crisis, but it has shown almost no signs of
doing so. Growth through the first three quarters of the year has
averaged 3.7 percent, barely slowing off its 1997 rate of 3.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as last month, the Federal Reserve was making the
last of three interest rate cuts aimed in part at protecting the
economy from slumping. Analysts said the new jobs figures make the
chance of further Fed rate cuts remote.
</P>
<P>
   Having topped the Reagan-era record for longevity, the current
boom's next challenge is beating the longest expansion of the
post-war period, the 106-month growth spurt of the 1960s.
Technically, the 1960s is not considered a peacetime boom because
it included the buildup for the Vietnam War. To match its record,
the economy will have to keep growing until April of 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
