<SLUG> BC-PLUNDERED-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM TO NOTE FRENCH FAMILY'S CLAIM TO MONET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WALTER V. ROBINSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Boston Museum of Fine Arts Friday added a special
panel to a Monet waterlily explaining that the work has been
claimed by descendants of Paul Rosenberg, a French Jewish collector
and dealer whose art was looted by the Nazis in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   The painting, on loan from a French museum, also acknowledges
information the MFA did not disclose when its Monet exhibition
began in September _ that the painting is among about 2,000
artworks in French custody whose owners have never been found. Many
of the works, the museum now notes in the panel, ``belonged to
victims of the Holocaust and were stolen.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday, the Globe reported that some Jewish leaders were
critical of that omission. The label merely reported that the
painting had been ``recovered after World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, The Globe disclosed that Nazi art looters had likely
taken the Monet along with the rest of Rosenberg's collection just
after he fled France for New York in 1940; and that the artwork had
spent the war years in the possession of Nazi Foreign Minister
Joachim von Ribbentrop. The MFA was unaware of the painting's
history.
</P>
<P>
   The French museum system, which has had the painting for a half
century, has said it was unaware of the identity of the previous
owner, or the von Ribbentrop connection. Yet even the official 1947
French list of unrestituted artworks lists the Monet as having been
looted by the Nazis from Rosenberg.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Rosenberg family formally notified the French
government of its claim, even as the director of the French
national museum system, Francoise Cachin, said she was uncertain
whether the Monet had been looted or sold by Rosenberg.
</P>
<P>
   A Rosenberg family spokesman, however, said the family has
records showing the German looters catalogued the painting as
stolen after taking it from a Rosenberg home in Bordeaux.
</P>
<P>
   The MFA's new panel notes that many of the estimated 2,000
``homeless'' artworks were sold on the Paris art market during the
war. Specialists in the wartime art looting have said many of those
were sold under duress, or entered the legitimate market after
being traded to dealers by Nazi looters for Old Master paintings.
The French, and other nations, have long considered any sales to
Germans during the German occupation to be void.
</P>
<P>
   French officials, including Cachin, have acknowledged that until
the existence of the artworks became a French national scandal in
1995, the French museum system had long since abandoned any real
effort to locate the owners of the artworks. In fact, the Monet in
question, ``Water Lilies 1904,'' has been in a museum in Caen in
Normandy since 1975, and on the French list of missing paintings
for all that time.
</P>
<P>
   MFA Director Malcolm Rogers said this week that seeking the
owner of a painting with a suspicious background is like looking
for a needle in a haystack. Yet specialists in looted art noted
that a photo of the painting appears in a book, ``Art as Politics
in the Third Reich,'' that details the looted art held by von
Ribbentrop.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Petropoulos, the historian at Loyola College in
Baltimore who wrote the book, said there was a ``red flag'' on the
Monet from Caen that should have prompted the MFA to perform some
diligent research before borrowing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not accusing the MFA of malfeasance, or trying to deceive
anyone. They just wanted the piece for the exhibition and they
didn't do all their homework,'' Petropoulos said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
