<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4042 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-EXCAPE-HNS &LR;      12-04 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-EXCAPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRISON OFFICIALS SAY ESCAPEE MIGHT HAVE BEEN DRIVEN INTO CREEK TO
GET AWAY FROM DOGS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE _ Murderer Martin Gurule's desperate bid to escape
the executioner's needle ended when he drowned in a turbid,
fast-flowing creek just a mile from Texas' death row, autopsy
results released Friday show.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe he might have been driven into the creek in an
effort to escape from the dogs,'' prison spokesman Larry Fitzgerald
said. ``It appears that he wasn't a very good swimmer.''
</P>
<P>
   Gurule's bloated body was found late Thursday afternoon by two
off-duty prison employees who were baiting trotlines on the creek
near its confluence with the Trinity River.
</P>
<P>
   Only one wound was detected on the body _ a shallow,
``graze-type'' bullet injury on the back just below the neck.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County Medical Examiner Dr. Joye Carter, whose office
performed the autopsy, said the bullet wound was non-lethal.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities believe Gurule, 29, who was sentenced to die for the
1992 murder of two men during a Corpus Christi, Texas, robbery, met
his death just hours after escaping from the Ellis Unit early last
Friday. The body was identified through dental records.
</P>
<P>
   Six other death row inmates were captured as they attempted to
reach the double razor wire-topped fences that line the prison's
perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   In a preamble to Friday's final news conference in the case,
Fitzgerald stood in front of prison system headquarters in a
driving rain and ripped to shreds a wanted poster bearing Gurule's
photo and vital data.
</P>
<P>
   ``You all have seen this,'' Fitzgerald said. ``Gurule is no
more. Our record is clear of escapes.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Department of Criminal Justice Executive Director Wayne
Scott praised the hundreds of prison system employees who scoured
the dense forest that adjoins the Ellis Unit, where death row
inmates are housed, in a seven-day search of the fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your collective and individual actions prove once again to me,
and to the public at large, just what a committed, dedicated and
diligent group of employees the great state of Texas has protecting
its safety,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prison spokesmen said the cost of the manhunt has not been
calculated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is relieved,'' said Sophia Piperis, a first cousin
by marriage to Mike Piperis, the Corpus Christi restaurant owner
Gurule killed. ``He had to get what he deserved and I guess he got
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The victim's daughter, Sofia Piperis, expressed pity for
Gurule's family. ``He was a person and that's no way for any person
to die,'' she told the Corpus Christi Caller-Times.
</P>
<P>
   Other family members were less charitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he suffered,'' said Brian Piperis, a nephew of the
victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad he's dead,'' said another nephew, Bill Piperis.
</P>
<P>
   Elsie Carey, the mother of restaurant cook Anthony Staton, who
also was killed in the robbery, expressed relief on learning of
Gurule's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel as if justice has been taken care of now,'' she said.
``It is all over and I can rest tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Gurule's decomposing body was found about 5:30 p.m. Thursday
floating in about 12 feet of water in Harmon Creek. The corpse
still was swaddled in several layers of clothing and armored with
sheets of cardboard and magazines held in place with elastic
bandages _ apparent protection from the razor wire-topped fences.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Smith, 41, and Mark Humphrey, 39, the off-duty employees
who found him, said the creek, filled with tangled trotlines and
brush, would be treacherous for swimmers at the best of times.
</P>
<P>
   They initially thought they were viewing a floating mannequin
until they noticed Gurule's fingernails.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is a dispatcher for the Wynn Unit; Humphrey, a truck
driver.
</P>
<P>
   While Fitzgerald called the pair ``heroes of the hour,'' a
spokeswoman for Texas Gov. George W. Bush noted they will not be
eligible to claim a $5,000 Texas Crime Stoppers reward posted in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Edwards said state law stipulates the reward is to be paid
only when information leads to an arrest. Secondly, she said, a
proper claim was not filed with the Walker County Crime Stoppers
office in Huntsville, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   However, she later added that Bush's office is exploring
alternate ways of providing a reward. ``These men met the spirit of
the requirements for the reward,'' Edwards said. ``We're just
awaiting word from our lawyers to see what we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Humphrey, who earlier expressed optimism they would
receive the reward _ ``The check's in the mail!'' one quipped _
later expressed disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a raw deal,'' said Smith on being told about the
Crime Stoppers regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Friday, Allan Polunksy, chairman of the Texas criminal
justice board, announced the members of a fact-finding committee
appointed to investigate the escape. John McAuliffe, retired prison
intelligence chief, will head the panel, which is to report to
criminal justice Commissioner Alfred ``Mac'' Stringfellow before
the board's Jan. 4 meeting in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe spent 22 years with the FBI before joining TDCJ as
head of its internal affairs division. He retired earlier this year
after holding that job five years.
</P>
<P>
   Other members are Texas Ranger L.C. Wilson of Beaumont and TDCJ
officials Gary Gomez, director of Gulf Coast area prisons; Larry
Johns, senior warden of the Michael Unit at Tennessee Colony; Steve
Mugg, facilities division; Sandy Murphy, operations review; Joe
Nesmith, internal affairs; and Ron Steffa, executive services.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
