<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4045 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX     12-04 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRSTRIKE MAY _ OR MAY NOT _ RELEASE TOXINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: If the United States bombed biological weapons factories in
Iraq, could toxic substances get into the atmosphere and cause
illnesses in other parts of the world?
</P>
<P>
   _ C.R., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: ``The majority of the chemical or biological threat is
destroyed by fire, so you're not looking at any type of effect'' to
surrounding areas, said Suzanne Fourier of the U.S. Army's Soldier
and Biological Chemical Command.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the case of germs, they have to be kept in a very
climate-controlled environment to be maximized or disseminated,''
Fourier said.
</P>
<P>
   Others say a bombing attack risks the release of deadly airborne
agents such as anthrax. ``Anything short of a major fire-bombing or
a nuclear detonation would fail to guarantee that the germs would
be killed before they spread,'' the New Statesman reported on Feb.
20, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   During the Persian Gulf War, 50 Iraqi guards reportedly died of
a ``rapidly progressing disease'' after an airstrike on a
biological facility, military security journalist Christopher
Bellamy wrote in The Independent of Feb. 2, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What information is available about Christian Payton from
``The Temptations'' movie? He was terrific as Paul Williams.
</P>
<P>
   _ L.C., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Payton, 23, is a Chicago native who appeared in two film
projects before landing the ``Temptations'' role. He appeared in
``Hoodlum'' with Larry Fishburne and in the CBS miniseries ``To Sir
With Love 2'' with Sidney Poitier.
</P>
<P>
   ``He arrived in Los Angeles two weeks before the `Temptations'
auditions,'' said his manager, Calvin Mason. ``Since then, the
phone has been ringing off the hook.''
</P>
<P>
   Write to Payton in care of Calvin Mason Management, 3313 1/2
Barham Blvd., Los Angeles, CA 90068.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to the producers of ``Hercules: The
Legendary Journeys'' and ``Xena: Warrior Princess'' about their
depiction of centaurs, and also to one of the actors who portrayed
one?
</P>
<P>
   _ S.W., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Renaissance Pictures, 100 Universal City Plaza,
Universal City, CA 91608.
</P>
<P>
   This address can be used for the show's producers and members of
the casts, including Kevin Sorbo, Lucy Lawless and Renee O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   Actors who have portrayed centaurs include Tony Blackett
(Ceridian), Cliff Curtis (Nemis), Mark Ferguson (Craesus and
Dagnen), Paul Gittens (Calipus) and Peter Muller (Deric).
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
