<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-PRESIDENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY FORMS CAMPAIGN FUND-RAISING COMMITTEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill Bradley, the former basketball star and US
senator, took a major step Friday toward seeking the Democratic
presidential nomination, forming an exploratory committee that can
raise money for a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by family and friends at a low-key announcement in
Newark, N.J., Bradley said: ``I want to provide the kind of
leadership that doesn't stand in the spotlight, but that calls
attention to the actions of millions of Americans who shine every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who has spent the last several months touring the
country to promote his new book, ``Values of the Game,'' faces the
daunting task of challenging Vice President Al Gore. Gore already
is the favorite of many within the party and has enormous
fund-raising power at his disposal.
</P>
<P>
   The move also puts pressure on other potential candidates,
including Senator John F. Kerry of Massachusetts, to make up their
minds soon. Indeed, Bradley's announcement signals that the a
pre-campaign phase known as the ``money primary'' is under way,
with potential candidates rushing to sign up supporters and raise
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley called Kerry Friday to explain his intentions, and Kerry
said through a spokesman that he welcomed his former Senate
colleague as a possible candidate. ``He thinks Bradley will make a
very good contribution to the national dialogue if he runs for
president,'' Kerry spokesman Jim Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry, who has said he will make a decision on whether to run
for president by February, plans to discuss the matter with his
family later this month during a vacation in Sun Valley, Idaho.
Kerry also is making plans for a January visit to Iowa, which holds
the first presidential caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats who have said they are considering a
presidential bid include Senator Bob Kerrey of Nebraska and Senator
Paul Wellstone of Minnesota. Another possible candidate, House
Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, is widely expected to drop out of
contention in order to concentrate on becoming speaker of the House
after the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first but very serious step. It is moving forward
from here,'' said Bradley spokesman Eric Hauser.
</P>
<P>
   A formal declaration of candidacy could come within weeks,
especially if Bradley is successful in getting donations for his
exploratory committee.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, a former Rhodes Scholar, rose to fame as a member of
the gold-medal-winning US basketball team in 1964 and as a forward
on the New York Knicks, which won two National Basketball
Association championships when the man nicknamed ``Dollar Bill''
was on the team.
</P>
<P>
   As a senator, Bradley initially played down his sports celebrity
and focused on a series of weighty issues, from tax reform to civil
rights to the environment. Considered a moderate on many issues,
Bradley sometimes displayed displeasure with his party, such as in
1981 when he was one of three Democrats who voted for the
then-President Reagan's budget.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts said Bradley is a longshot, but he should be
taken seriously. For starters, the analysts said, he is well-known
and liked nationally, as evidenced by his book making many
best-seller lists. The book, which contains essays on the common
values of life and basketball, celebrates his days as an athletic
star, a time still remembered fondly by many of his fans.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic pollster Peter Hart said Gore is clearly the
front-runner, yet the Democratic Party has a tradition of embracing
outsiders _ not establishment figures such as a vice president. The
last two Democrats to be elected president were governors, Jimmy
Carter and Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats tend to look toward the challenger, the outsider,
while Republicans tend to look to the establishment,'' Hart said.
``From that point, Bill Bradley would have a better chance of
competing against a sitting vice president on the Democratic
side.''
</P>
<P>
   But political analyst Stuart Rothenberg doubted Bradley can gain
enough support and money to beat Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a hard time taking it all that seriously,'' Rothenberg
said. ``Yes, he is Mr. Clean, thoughtful and serious but I don't
see where the wedge is. I don't see in the party where he competes
with Al Gore. They are on the same side of the issues. Both are
(moderate) New Democrats, both are free traders.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Friday announcing the exploratory committee,
Bradley played down any comparisons with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about Vice President Gore and me,'' Bradley said.
``This is about telling the country what I believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he might seek the nomination because he wants to
``help unleash the enormous potential of the American people. I
want to help take that energy and channel it, not only toward
further economic vitality, but also toward finishing our agenda of
obligations that we have to one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley considered running for president in 1992 and 1996. He
did not seek reelection as a senator in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
