u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDUCATOR-HIRED-BOS &LR;      12-04 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATOR-HIRED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-ADELPHI CHIEF TO ASSIST BU PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE EBBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Their names have been linked, for better or worse: John
Silber, former Boston University president, and Adelphi University
President Peter Diamandopoulos, were ranked one and two,
respectively, in pay among all university presidents in the nation
five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Silber, who was seen as something of a mentor to Diamandopoulos,
helped set Diamandopoulos's pay as an Adelphi trustee. And he
fiercely defended it when that compensation became a bone of
contention in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they're together again. This fall, the man some considered
a Silber protege landed a job at BU, where Silber remains
Chancellor. As special assistant to president Jon Westling,
Diamandopoulos is assigned to handle special projects in the
president's office, specifically in development, international
education, and educational policy.
</P>
<P>
   But BU Friday remained mum on one aspect of his new position:
His salary.
</P>
<P>
   BU spokesman David R. Lampe said the hiring was ``a personnel
matter'' and that details would remain confidential.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a person with a wealth of experience in many different
aspects at the university,'' Lampe said. ``This was an opportunity
to take advantage of that experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The news of Diamandopoulos's hiring comes just three weeks after
a $4.3 million settlement in the fracas over his Adelphi pay, which
involved the New York State attorney general's office, and over the
university trustees' failure to control Diamandopoulos'
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Diamandopoulos and all 18 Adelphi trustees, including Silber,
were ordered to repay the university for some of his compensation
and legal fees, after the New York State Board of Regents faulted
the trustees for overpaying the president. A new board of trustees
ousted the president and sought the settlement, attorneys said.
</P>
<P>
   Diamandopoulos could not be reached for comment and Silber was
unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   Their reunion at BU was no surprise to some, who saw Silber as
one of Diamandopoulos' most strident supporters in the New York
Board of Regents hearings that emerged over the compensation
package.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're telling me as far as the hiring does not surprise
me at all,'' said Kathy A. Ahearn, counsel and deputy commissioner
for legal affairs for the board of regents. ``Now that a settlement
of all the lawsuits has finally been reached. . .it's kind of
interesting and fitting that they both end up at the same place.''
</P>
<P>
   Beth Margolis, an attorney representing the Committee to Save
Adelphi, a student and faculty group that opposed the compensation,
called Diamandopoulos' appointment ``outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that what happened at Adelphi raised some incredibly
serious questions _ and actually answered them _ about his capacity
to serve in the administration of a not-for-profit institution,
much less an aceadmic one,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The fracas began when the Committee to Save Adelphi complained
that Diamandopoulos' compensation _ $523,636 in salary and bonuses
in 1994 _ was excessive. Silber was the only higher-paid university
president at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Silber, who testified at the Regents hearings, was one of the
his fiercest supporters on the board, and one of the most
instrumental in assuring his compensation, Ahearn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense was that Silber was very much a mentor to
Diamandopoulos,'' Ahearn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You almost got the sense from listening to the testimony that
Silber was supporting him very vigorously in the fight that was
going on because some of the similarities that existed would be a
victory for Silber,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Margolis called Silber the trustees' ``ringleader'' setting
Diamandopoulos' pay. Indeed, Silber even testified that he weighed
his own salary when determining Diamandopoulos,' according to press
accounts at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the problems he faced at Adelphi were the same I faced
when I came to Boston University,'' Silber was quoted as saying at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   A three-member panel of the Board of Regents found the trustees
had neglected their duty in setting Diamandopoulous's compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Before he took the helm at Adelphi, Diamandopoulos was dean of
faculty at Brandeis University, president of Sonoma State
University, and studied philosophy and the history of classical
thought at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   But Diamandopoulos became best known for his perks. By 1996, he
was earning $837,000 a year in pay and benefits. He had reportedly
received $360,000 in travel expenses for annual trips with his wife
to Greece, a Mercedes-Benz, and a Manhattan condominium worth $1.3
million _ with an option to buy it for $905,000.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported that Silber was also involved in
some of the costs: When the crisis sparked a meeting of the board
of trustees, Diamandopoulos allegedly began taking out trustees and
billed Adelphi $546 for a dinner with Silber.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, Diamandopoulos and the trustees were forced to
pay a settlement worth about $4.3 million to the university _
including $1.45 million from an insurance claim. Diamandopoulos was
ordered to return almost $650,000 cash and $90,000 rent for his
apartment, and he and his fellow trustees were ordered to repay
$225,000. The other trustees independently were ordered to return
$800,000 cash, Ahearn noted; a breakdown of their individual
expenses was not available.
</P>
<P>
   Diamandopoulos was also ordered to relinquish his rights to
deferred compensation, sabbatical, and the Manhattan apartment _
claims worth $765,019.
</P>
<P>
   The trustees, including Silber, resigned in Feburary 1997, and
the new board replaced Diamandopoulos.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
