<HEADLINE>
SCHUMER BLAMES `RADICAL RIGHT' FOR IMPEACHMENT PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES M. ODATO  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLONIE, N.Y. _ President Clinton is in bigger trouble of
impeachment than most people know, a Democratic member of the House
Judiciary Committee said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles E. Schumer of New York, who will become a member of
the Senate in January, blamed ``radical right'' Republicans for
manipulating the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who are pushing impeachment, they're letting their
hatred of Clinton exceed their love of the country or their
obligation to people of the country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer singled out Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, for trying
to induce impeachment votes from reluctant GOP representatives and
blamed speaker-elect Bob Livingston, R-La., for failing to control
DeLay and other conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Livingston has refused thus far to assert the slightest
scintilla of leadership whatsoever,'' said Schumer, who captured a
Senate seat by defeating incumbent Republican Alfonse D'Amato.
``Tom DeLay ... he is pushing people left and right ... to vote for
at least one article of impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee is holding hearings to determine what
action to take against Clinton for lying under oath about his
sexual relationship with a White House intern. The committee will
make a recommendation to the full House, which must then vote on
the action. There are 21 Republicans and 16 Democrats on the
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time I'm truly worried,'' he told the Albany
Times Union. An impeachment trial, he said, ``would be a disaster''
tying up all three branches of government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trial is going to be brought to you by the same people who
conducted these wild goose-chase hearings, the Judiciary
Committee,'' he said, describing committee Republican leaders as
``the radical right.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for DeLay said Schumer seemed to be acting as
Clinton's defense lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why doesn't he stand up and make a case that the president
didn't commit perjury?'' Mike Scanlon said. He added that Schumer
appeared to want it both ways: He blamed departing House Speaker
Newt Gingrich for pushing the impeachment inquiry and now blames
Livingston for staying out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Find me a Republican who says they have been in any way
influenced or pressured by Tom DeLay. They don't exist. We're
totally hands-off,'' Scanlon said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Michael P. Forbes, R-N.Y., said Schumer has reason to fear
an impeachment vote in the full House. But he added: ``Many
Republicans are uncomfortable with the way this has evolved ... I
think it is going to be an extremely close vote. There are upwards
of 20 Republicans who have suggested they might not be comfortable
with impeaching Bill Clinton over what they have characterized as
sexual improprieties.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said Clinton, who helped him raise hundreds of thousands
of dollars during his successful campaign against D'Amato, should
be censured _ a formal rebuke _ for lying under oath about his
affair.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer will become a member of the Senate Judiciary Committee
when the new Congress convenes in January. As a member of that
panel, he would serve as a juror in a trial of the president if the
House votes for impeachment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
