<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGIONS FIND A HOME ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As should be clear to anyone who has looked into what
the Internet offers by way of religion, cyberspace has become a
comfortable and expansive home for a vast number of faith groups.
</P>
<P>
   Christians, Jews, Muslims, Hindus, Buddhists and many others
have set up Web sites describing national organizations and
individual houses of worship. Such sites may seem to serve a kind
of billboard function, advertising and providing information for
the groups that sponsor them. Some Web sites can work as meeting
grounds as well.
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be the goal of an organization affiliated with the
Lubavitch movement, the Hasidic Jewish group, which announced this
week that it had created a site dedicated to Hanukkah, the
eight-day Jewish festival of lights, which begins on Sunday, Dec.
13, at sundown.
</P>
<P>
   The organization, the American Friends of Lubavitch, said the
site _ www.chanukah98.com _ would feature broadcasts of the
lightings of menorahs in Jerusalem, Moscow, New York and Paris, all
taking place at 3:15 p.m. Eastern time on that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do is be lamplighters in cyberspace,''
said Rabbi Levi Shemtov, director of the Washington office of
American Friends. The organization mounted a more modest site
during the holiday last year, and received enough encouragement to
expand, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Menachem Mendel Schneerson, the spiritual leader of the
Lubavitch movement who died in June 1994, urged his followers to
use the tools of modern technology, including toll-free telephone
lines, radio broadcasts and fax machines, to reach out to all Jews
to encourage people at all levels of observance to increase their
commitment to the faith. The Lubavitch movement has world
headquarters in Crown Heights, Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, long before the Internet came into widespread
use, Shemtov said, his father, Rabbi Abraham Shemtov, began a
project for the Lubavitch in which menorah lightings around the
world were televised live via satellite linkup. It was undertaken
with the approval of Schneerson, the younger Shemtov said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, it was pretty eye-opening,'' he said, adding that for
members of Lubavitch, as for many among the more rigorously
Orthodox Jews, ``television is not very popular.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Internet may be a different matter. It holds the
possibility of being ``a great educational tool,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the Internet, users could read that the Evangelical
Lutheran Church in America had reported its membership to be
``stable.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the nation's largest Protestant denominations suffered
heavy declines in membership in the 1970s and 1980s. But some
recent statistics indicated that the losses had moderated in this
decade, and the Lutheran report seemed to fit the pattern.
</P>
<P>
   David Alderfer, the church's director for rosters and
statistics, said membership declined by 2,308 people in 1997 (the
latest year for which figures were available), less than one half
of 1 percent of the church's 5.2 million members.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was substantially less than that for 1996 and 1995,
when the church lost about 9,000 members each year, or for 1994,
when it lost 13,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   But Alderfer, who noted that the church gained members in 1990
and 1991, said it was too early to discern a trend. ``I'd want to
see two more years of data,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
