<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGERS MAY NOT BE MUSIC TO INVESTOR EARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (For release Sunday, Dec. 6)  
(rl) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They've only just begun to merge.
</P>
<P>
   That's the view of many market watchers after an extraordinary
week of corporate combinations. The 78 deals announced in the first
four days of December had a value of $89.9 billion, almost as much
as was generated during all of November.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that the same economic factors driving Mobil Oil
into the arms of Exxon _ and Bankers Trust to join with Deutsche
Bank _ cut across many industries today. So more and more mergers
tomorrow are a certainty.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest factor is excess capacity. And it's all over the
map, affecting banks, retailers, computer makers and producers of
commodities like steel, paper and chemicals. When too many goods
chase too few consumers, combining corporate forces and turning off
some of the supply spigot is a natural response.
</P>
<P>
   Excess capacity has driven merger booms before. A century ago,
price declines similar to the ones seen in this decade created a
wave of corporate consolidations that turned 1,800 companies into
about 150.
</P>
<P>
   While increased merger activity may right the supply-and-demand
scales in some industries, megamergers are not necessarily good
news for shareholders. The fact is, most mergers are bad news for
shareholders, because the merged company's stock usually
underperforms its peers long afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the findings of Mark Sirower, a professor of mergers
and acquisitions at New York University's Stern School of Business.
Sirower is the author of ``The Synergy Trap: How Companies Lose the
Acquisition Game'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   Studying 168 deals among large public companies in the 1980s and
an additional 100 combinations valued at more than $500 million
apiece from the 1990s, Sirower found that roughly two-thirds lost
money for shareholders, relatively speaking. For example, a
portfolio of the 100 major acquisitions completed from 1994 to
1997, with each stock bought five days before the relevant deal was
announced and sold five days after, would have produced returns
that lagged behind other companies' in the merging entities'
industries by an average of 2 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   What about the longer-term performance of the merged companies?
The numbers are similar. Indeed, the loudest message from Sirower's
research is that investors' initial reaction to a merger turns out
to be uncannily prescient. ``The market is a pretty good predictor
of what we'll see a year later, or even four years out,'' Sirower
said.
</P>
<P>
   He reached this conclusion by splitting the merged companies
into two portfolios: those whose shares went up when deals were
announced and those whose stock fell. One year later, the positive
portfolio was still positive and the negative still an
underperformer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's particularly interesting that those that stay positive do
even better than their industry, and negatives that stay negative
do even worse,'' he said. The mergers that the market liked from
the start rose 18.51 percent; the ones that investors disliked fell
22.58 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Sirower hastened to add that these figures were averages, and
that some mergers that initially displease investors can and do
turn around later. But the consistency of the market's mood on
these combinations is pretty remarkable. Some 59 percent of those
merged companies whose stock began in positive territory stayed
there, while 67.3 percent of those whose stock hit the skids early
remained down.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at market reactions, Sirower concluded, ``you
need to take them seriously.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
