<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 6) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's really behind Exxon's takeover of Mobil? ``Exxon was
insanely jealous of Mobil's sponsorship of `Masterpiece Theater'
and its lock on a part of the Times Op-Ed page,'' joked Herbert
Schmertz, former vice president for public affairs at Mobil. ``They
were willing to pay $80 billion to get their hands on it, and you
know what? It's a good deal for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmertz is referring to two of the biggest publicity coups he
engineered in his 18 years as guardian of Mobil's public image: the
company's sponsorship of public television and its use of
advertising slots on the New York Times Op-Ed page for biting
essays on public controversies that often drove oil-industry
critics crazy.
</P>
<P>
   It all helped to make Mobil seem bigger in relation to Exxon
than it really was. Now, 10 years after Schmertz left Mobil to open
his own consulting business, $11-a-barrel oil is forcing his old
company into what, culturally at least, seems to be a shotgun
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Schmertz says he is not bothered personally by the merger,
though the new name, Exxon Mobil, is ``dreadful'' and ``sounds too
much like Austro-Hungary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel sorry for the thousands of people who will lose
their jobs,'' he added. ``I'm sure most will be from Mobil.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barnaby J. Feder &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charities are already fretting now that Mobil, an avid patron of
museums and public television, is merging with Exxon, which makes
less of a splash in philanthropy circles. Now they have another
merger to worry about. Sanford I. Weill, the co-chairman of
Citigroup, the new financial behemoth, has chosen the
charitable-giving program of his old company, Travelers Group, over
the more free-spending plan at the old Citicorp.
</P>
<P>
   Weill prefers Travelers' money-for-time program, which makes
grants only to charities where employees donate their time.
Citicorp has a matching gift plan that doubles any employee's gift
to a favorite charity, to the tune of $7 million in 1997. The new
policy won't take effect until next year, and Citigroup promises to
honor any multiyear commitments made by the old Citicorp. Weill is
a big giver himself, recently pledging $100 million to Cornell
Medical School. ``But he feels strongly that people should be
involved, not just write checks,'' a Citigroup spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Kahn &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can almost hear the bureaucrats at Japan's Ministry of Trade
and Industry gnashing their teeth: Queen Elizabeth has knighted
Nobuhiko Kawamoto, the former president and chief executive of the
Honda Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, when the ministry was trying to protect Japan's auto
industry leaders, Toyota and Nissan, it discouraged bankers from
lending to Honda, then a motorcycle maker. The strategy failed, and
Honda is now a global giant, producing 150,000 vehicles a year in
Swindon, England, with plans to increase capacity by 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 31 other Japanese executives, including Soichiro
Toyoda, chairman of Toyota, have also achieved British knighthood.
</P>
<P>
   After his investiture early next year, Kawamoto will be entitled
to style himself Sir Nobuhiko and print the initials K.B.E. _ for
Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire _ on his
meishi, or business card. But, his spokesman said: ``I think he
just wants to be referred to as Kawamoto-san. And he's not
reprinting his meishi.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Strom &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to initial public offerings, the word
``unprofitable'' seems to be excused by the word ``Internet.'' Add
Barry Diller, the media impresario, to the list of people who just
got rich _ well, in his case, richer _ from the suspension of
disbelief, which appears to fuel stock trading related to things on
line. Tossing the Diller name into the mix didn't hurt, either.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, his Ticketmaster Online-Citysearch Inc. raised $98
million with the sale of seven million shares, with the opening
price of $14 a share tripling by the end of the day. The
ticket-sales and city-guide venture isn't expected to turn a profit
until 2002. USA Networks, of which Diller is chairman, holds a 62.5
percent stake in the online venture.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Murphy, editor of Overpriced Stock Service, a
newsletter, called the $3.5 billion valuation for the fledgling
enterprise ``excessive.'' But unlike most other Internet
entrepreneurs, Diller hasn't nested all his eggs in one basket.
</P>
<P>
   He also has, among other things, his stake in USA Networks,
whose properties include the Home Shopping Network, to offset any
slide this online foray may suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Napoli
</P>
</TEXT>
