<SLUG> BC-FBC-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNMUZZLED KANSAS STATE QUARTERBACK SPEAKS OUT  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Finally, he talked. About the Heisman Trophy. About
Ricky Williams. About his volatile temper.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bishop, Kansas State's mercurial quarterback, spoke to
everything except the fact that college football has three unbeaten
teams and only two national title slots.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least that's the case heading into Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   When Saturday slips into Sunday and brings to close a memorable
college football season, there's a good chance that's all anyone
will be talking about: The Bowl Championship Series rankings that
will determine which two teams get to go to the Fiesta Bowl and
play for the national title.
</P>
<P>
   At least the coaches poll's version of it.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what will decide the Fiesta invite. The Wildcats, 11-0
and ranked No. 1 by the coaches, versus Texas A&AMP;M, 10-2, in the Big
Twelve championship game. The Tennessee Volunteers, 11-0 and the
media poll's No. 1 team, against Mississippi State, 8-3, in the
Southeastern Conference Championship game. And UCLA, 10-0 and
everyone's No. 3, facing Miami, 7-3, in a game Hurricane Georges
cancelled earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe not. If all three teams win, the computer rankings _
including The New York Times _ and a formula measuring strength of
schedule will separate the fractions and decide the top two.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need to win. It's all we can do,'' said Bishop, who
was made available by conference call earlier in the week for the
first time since the Colorado game in October.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State Coach Bill Snyder, who muzzled his quarterback so
his emotional soundings wouldn't distract his team, echoed that
sentiment here Friday and summed up the state of confusion
surrounding college football's newfangled ranking system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea,'' said a befuddled Snyder of what Kansas State
needed to do to improve it's No. 3 BCS ranking. ``I do know we need
to win here to have the opportunity for the Fiesta Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   As it stands now, Snyder's Wildcats have 6.31 BCS points
compared to the Bruins 5.03 and the Volunteers 4.99. To add
legitimacy to the title game, the coaches have agreed to award it's
final No. 1 ranking to the winner. If Kansas State is shut out of
the Fiesta, the coaches are in the odd predicament of crowning a
champion they didn't think was worthy during the season.
</P>
<P>
   Each team has much to recommend, as well as discourage those
weighing their title campaigns. Kansas State's defense allows the
second fewest yards of any team in the nation and it's offense is
ranked ninth in yardage. But it's schedule is ranked the 62nd
toughest by the BCS due to early season games with Northern
Illinois, Northeast Louisiana and Indiana State. A win over the
Aggies will improve that but probably not enough to creep forward.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's statistics, on the other hand, are solid but hardly
spectacular. They have the 23rd ranked defense, 31st ranked offense
and a schedule considered the 29th toughest by the ranking system.
Still, the Volunteers have wins against high profile teams _
Florida, Georgia, Arkansas and Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA is the team that most refuse to recognize as title worthy.
Their high powered offense, 12th in total yards, bails out a
defense ranked 91st.
</P>
<P>
   They've needed late-game finishes to beat lowly Stanford and
Oregon State, but have been assigned the seventh toughest schedule
because of a competitive PAC 10 schedule, beating Arizona (11-1),
as well as having the best opponents record of the three: 60-42.
</P>
<P>
   None of this statistical hair splitting, however, appears to
deter Bishop. He is 46-1 as a collegiate starter who is perhaps two
games away from completing his third perfect season _ twice he led
undefeated teams to national junior college championships at Blinn
Junior College.
</P>
<P>
   He said he knows Texas A&AMP;M ``would like to spoil our perfect
season and national title shot'' but, in the sort of statement that
makes Snyder wince, indicates that isn't going to happen. ``I don't
think we've played our best game yet. Our confidence is high,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop said he wasn't too concerned that his banishment to the
media sidelines have hurt his Heisman Trophy chances despite the
kind of versatile and impressive numbers that have pro scouts
moving him up the draft ladder. He has run for 13 touchdowns and
passed for 21 more and 2,503 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media is not going to make me perform. I had more time to
concentrate. It helped me more than hurt me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of his penchant for initiating unnecessary hits at the end or
runs and berating himself and teammates in an animated on-field
fashion, the senior shrugged that off, too. ``Sometimes I tend to
get overexcited. I get psyched up too high. I play on sheer
emotion,'' he conceded. ``
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done it all my life. It carries me a long away.''
</P>
<P>
   He also says he is comfortable sharing the dais in New York with
the player he says should win the Heisman Trophy. ``I'd vote for
Ricky. He did some great things for his team. He broke the
record,'' he said of Williams NCAA career rushing record. ``I'll
take the opportunity to play for the national championship over the
Heisman any day.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-04-98 2007EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
