<DOCNO> NYT19981204.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4095 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-U.S.-TRADE-520     12-04 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-U.S.-TRADE-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA TO REDUCE BARRIERS AGAINST U.S. FARM PRODUCTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.D., Ill.)  (lb) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Moving to head off a border blockade by angry
American farmers, Canada agreed Friday to lower barriers to farm
exports from the United States but not to reduce its own shipments
of meat and grain.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, reached after months of negotiations
between Canadian and U.S. trade and agriculture officials, Canada
promised to let U.S. farmers export grain by rail more easily, to
revise its health regulations on imported livestock, and to
eliminate burdensome testing requirements for a wheat disease
called karnal bunt.
</P>
<P>
   A weakened Canadian currency has helped lower prices for
Canadian grain and meat that have been pouring into U.S. markets
for months, frustrating farmers in the United States who have
threatened to set up blockades at the border in the next few days.
American wheat farmers temporarily held up shipments from Canada
this summer, contending that the wheat was unfairly priced.
</P>
<P>
   As the new deal was announced, farm leaders called for an end to
the threat of a blockade. ``Given the success of these
negotiations, an imminent blockade of ports of entry is totally
unwarranted,'' said Dean Kleckner, president of the American Farm
Bureau Federation. ``The last thing U.S. farmers can afford is an
irresponsible action that would shut down, even temporarily, trade
with one of our best customers.''
</P>
<P>
   And the U.S. trade representative, Charlene Barshefsky,
commented, ``This is a first step, but for American farmers and
ranchers it is good news in a trying year.''
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture Minister Lyle Van Clief of Canada said, ``I think
both countries have had a victory.'' He praised American
negotiators for taking ``the path of trade enhancement and not
trade restriction.''
</P>
<P>
   Canada and the United States are each other's largest trading
partners. American officials said that in the fiscal year that
ended on Sept. 30, the United States shipped $7 billion of
agricultural products to Canada and Canadian farmers exported $7.7
billion of goods to the United States. But in commodities such as
wheat, the imbalance was greater.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a lot easier for Canada to ship agricultural
products to the United States than it's been for the United States
to ship to Canada, which has caused great frustration among our
farmers and ranchers,'' a senior administration trade official
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dana Hauck, chairman of the international markets committee of
the National Cattlemen's Beef Association, said, ``We have Canada's
attention,'' and he called for ``continued aggressive action'' from
the Clinton administration to lower Canadian trade barriers.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. growers have been faced with a spate of bad news. Asian
nations, immersed in their own economic crises, can no longer
afford to buy as much food as they did before from the United
States. At home, U.S. farmers have had to contend with lower prices
and supply gluts caused in part by the Canadian imports.
</P>
<P>
   Congress increased farm aid at the insistence of the Clinton
administration, but lawmakers from the northern Plains states have
said that their constituents continue to face an economic crisis.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It would be our hope that farmers and governors and elected
officials in this region would see that they now have a mechanism
in place to address problems, and it's not just a lot of talk,''
the senior U.S. official said in a briefing for reporters.
</P>
<P>
   But North Dakota's Sen. Byron Dorgan, a Democrat who has called
for cuts in Canadian exports, said the agreement was an
``illusion'' and that the United States should press a trade
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Although the agreement did not restrict imports from Canada, it
contained several provisions meant to make it easier for the United
States to detect unfairly priced goods, especially wheat, U.S.
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States will begin to monitor imports of Canadian
grain more closely, requiring Canadian shippers of wheat to provide
more information to Customs.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Flory, president of the U.S. National Association of Wheat
Growers, said the new data would ``lift the veil of secrecy'' that
has allowed the Canadian Wheat Board, a monopoly state trading
enterprise, to sell more wheat in the United States. U.S. farmers
have complained for years that the board has used discriminatory
pricing to penetrate U.S. markets and to undercut American grain in
overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
   Canada also agreed to drop immediately its requirement that hogs
shipped live from the United States be held in quarantine for 30
days. The pork industry in the United States has been plagued by
oversupply, driving prices to 18{-year lows; eliminating the
quarantine should provide something of an escape valve for the
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Reifschneider, a hog producer from Illinois who is
president of the National Pork Producers Council, praised that
provision, saying that ``the choice of sending hogs north will be
very significant for certain producers, particularly in border
states.''
</P>
<P>
   But she said she did not expect a significant number of hogs to
be sent north right away, and she added that about 4 million
Canadian hogs, one-fifth of Canada's production, would be exported
to the United States this year, adding to the backlog at
meat-packing plants.
</P>
<P>
   Canada also said it would expand agreements allowing cattle to
be shipped north for fattening under less burdensome regulations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-04-98 2013EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
