<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4099 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-     12-04 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM RETHINKS ITS VANS AND COMES UP WITH WINNERS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by CARS-GLANCE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chrysler may have defined the minivan with its highly successful
products, but General Motors conceded a huge share of the market by
rolling out its futuristic ``Dustbuster''-looking models in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   After virtually ignoring the minivan phenomenon for six years,
then coming out with such a controversial product, GM allowed
Chrysler to gain a strong position as minivan market leader.
</P>
<P>
   By most standards, the GM products _ the Chevrolet Lumina APV,
Oldsmobile Silhouette and Pontiac TransSport _ were competent
vehicles. However, their radical styling never caught on with
consumers, and the products failed miserably in competition with
Chrysler.
</P>
<P>
   The styling controversy is over, however, thanks to the
conventional redesign of all three products for the 1997 model
year. Anyone who buys a minivan today without giving the GM vans a
look is just not shopping very wisely.
</P>
<P>
   Our test car this week, the 1999 Oldsmobile Silhouette Premiere
edition ($31,175, including $570 transportation), is arguably the
best minivan ever built. And compared with similarly equipped
sport-utility vehicles, the Silhouette Premiere is quite a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Silhouette's annual sales have doubled since the redesign, and
the other GM minivans are doing well, too. But buyers still aren't
taking to the new GM vans the way they do Chrysler products, and
that's a shame.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Oldsmobile should have changed the name of the
Silhouette to help people forget their bad impressions of the odd
predecessor. Chevy did that with its new model, calling it the
Venture. Pontiac finally dropped the TransSport designation this
year and is calling its minivan the Montana, a name that has been
used the past two years on a highly successful sport-utilitylike
version of the TransSport.
</P>
<P>
   The Silhouette now is every bit as ``normal'' as the industry
sales leaders, with huge added measures of style, performance,
luxury and convenience that the competitors don't offer.
</P>
<P>
   The Silhouette, as well as the rest of the GM minivans, has two
sliding doors _ driver's and passenger's side _ just like the
competition. But these vans go one up on the competition with their
electrically operated passenger-side sliding door, an industry
exclusive that was introduced on the earlier Silhouette.
</P>
<P>
   That feature alone is worth buying a GM minivan, especially if
you've got kids who have a tough time closing the bulky sliding
doors found on most minivans. Those of you who have owned minivans
know how often you have had to come around the vehicle and open or
close the door for your rear passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, you can just push a button on the overhead console in front
of the driver, or by the door itself, or use the remote control,
and the side door slides open quickly and quietly. Another touch of
the button closes it just as easily. A locking switch on the
overhead console disables the electric operation, and sensors in
the door will stop it from closing if something gets in its way _
such as a child's hand.
</P>
<P>
   The Silhouette Premiere edition is the top-of-the-line
long-wheelbase GLS model with a special audio-video package that
includes a pull-down color LCD video screen in the center of the
roof behind the front seats. It is linked to a videocassette player
mounted at the bottom of the center dash console
radio/heating-air-conditioning stack.
</P>
<P>
   Our test car came with two videotapes, so the kids enjoyed
``Monty Python'' and ``Ace Ventura'' as we cruised through traffic.
The kids can hook up the headphones and listen in private as the
front-seat passengers groove on oldies radio or a favorite compact
disc. There are outlets for six headsets, each with its own volume
control, and they can be tuned to the radio, CD player, cassette
tape deck or video player.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first minivan that makes me feel like I'm in
sports car, not a domestic mom-mobile, and it makes me want to take
a long trip somewhere,'' my significant other remarked after a
couple of rides in the Silhouette.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't agree more. I was tempted to call the Olds folks and
ask them to send me the payment book; I just didn't want to give
the Silhouette up.
</P>
<P>
   All the GM minivans are powered by a peppy 3.4-liter V-6 engine,
rated at 185 horsepower and 210 foot-pounds of torque. They come
with a smooth-shifting, electronically operated four-speed
automatic transmission. The combination gives excellent pickup for
merging and passing, as well as plenty of power for high-speed
freeway driving.
</P>
<P>
   This is a vehicle made for cruising, and creature comforts
abound. The seats are as comfortable as an easy chair, and the ride
is so carlike that you'll forget you're in a minivan.
</P>
<P>
   The Premiere comes with two captains' chairs up front and two
more in the middle seating row; the third seat is a bench roomy
enough for three adults. Handling is rather sporty, too _ nothing
like a minivan, more like a midsize family sedan.
</P>
<P>
   This is the extended model, so there is more luggage space in
the rear than in the standard-length vans _ 24.2 cubic feet vs.
16.3.
</P>
<P>
   There are no options on the Premiere model; everything is
included in the sticker price.
</P>
<P>
   Among the standard features are leather upholstery, automatic
air-conditioning, antilock brakes, power windows/door locks, heated
power-operated outside mirrors with fold-in feature, remote keyless
entry, 15-inch aluminum wheels, steering wheel radio controls, and
rear controls for heating, ventilation and air-conditioning. Other
benefits include cruise control, rooftop luggage rack, halogen
headlights, cup holders for everyone and a touring suspension with
automatic leveling,
</P>
<P>
   There are front and side air bags for the driver and front
passenger.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel economy isn't bad, either. EPA ratings are 18 miles per
gallon in the city and 25 on the highway _ quite an improvement
over most comparably priced sport-utility vehicles. The tank holds
25 gallons of gasoline (extended-length model; 20 gallons in
standard length models).
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III writes on transportation issues for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. His mailing address is
Star-Telegram/Northeast, 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford,
Texas 76021; his E-mail address is chambers(at)star-telegram.com.
Fax: (817) 685-3883. Check out his Wheelin' new-car review column
weekly on the Internet at
ww.netarrant.net/today/news/opinions/necol.htm. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
