A4102 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      12-04 0366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Pinochet Plan Rejected
</P>
<P>
   British officials rejected a proposal for a Spanish judge to
interview Gen. Augusto Pinochet, the former Chilean dictator, in
London to spare him extradition to Madrid to face genocide charges.
Home Secretary Jack Straw must decide by Dec. 11 whether to proceed
with the judge's extradition request.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Argentina: Grenade in the Mail
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Martin Balza, the army commander, received a hand grenade
in the mail on the eighth anniversary of the military's last revolt
against investigations of its human rights record. The grenade,
which was not primed to explode, was the latest in a string of
threats against the general.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina: Bombing Suspect Charged
</P>
<P>
   An Iranian woman, Nahrim Mokhtari, was charged in connection
with the deadly bombings of the Israeli Embassy in 1992 and of a
Jewish center in Buenos Aires in 1994. Ms. Mokhtari was detained at
the Buenos Aires airport after she got off a flight from Paris that
was bound for Montevideo, Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   India: Christians Protest Attacks
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of Christians protested against attacks this
year by Hindus on Christians and Christian institutions in some
Indian states. The protesters held rallies and many Christian
schools closed for the day. India has 2.3 million Christians in a
population of about 970 million.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong: Erasing signs of Britain
</P>
<P>
   China is stripping away one of the most visible remnants of
Britain's colonial presence in Hong Kong. Workers are removing the
name from the Prince of Wales Building, which became the army
headquarters after China took control of Hong Kong 17 months ago.
The army said it had not decided on a new name.
</P>
<P>
   Cambodia: U.N. seat awarded
</P>
<P>
   The newly installed coalition government of Prime Minister Hun
Sen was awarded Cambodia's vacant seat in the U.N. General
Assembly. The coalition includes the opposition party of Prince
Norodim Ranariddh, who was driven out of office in a July 1997
coup. The seat has been vacant since September 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
