A4108 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS &LR;      12-04 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S LAWYERS CLAIM THEIR DEFENSE COULD PUSH IMPEACHMENT
INQUIRY INTO NEW YEAR, NEW CONGRESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As House Republicans prepared articles of
impeachment against President Clinton late Friday, his legal team
notified the House Judiciary Committee that three or four days,
plus several witnesses, will be needed next week to mount his
defense.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal outlined by Clinton's lawyers, who called the
committee's impeachment inquiry ``inadequate'' so far, threatens to
derail plans by Republican House leaders to complete the panel's
work late next week and put the issue before the full House at
least a week before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter delivered to the Capitol shortly after dusk, White
House lawyers outlined plans to summon three panels of experts to
explore the constitutional standards for impeachment, standards for
prosecution and prosecutorial misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was delivered to the House Judiciary Committee, where
the Republican staff was preparing articles of impeachment accusing
the president of perjury, obstruction of justice and abuse of
power. The articles mirror the allegations outlined against Clinton
in independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report to the House on the
president's effort to conceal his affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Committee GOP spokesman Paul McNulty said the White House
request to question witnesses over a three or four day period ``is
an obvious and desperate political ploy to push the inquiry into
the new Congress where the Democrats potentially have more votes.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart scoffed at the committee's
assertion. ``If we wanted to push this back we could have asked for
a lot more time,'' Lockhart said. ``If presenting a defense is seen
by the committee as a ploy, that indicates how political they've
become.''
</P>
<P>
   At present, the House has 228 Republican members, 206 Democrats
and one independent, who is expected to side with the Democrats on
impeachment. Democrats picked up five seats in last month's
elections, which means there will be a 223-211-1 division of the
House beginning in January.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Republican-controlled committee is expected to vote
along party lines to approve at least one article of impeachment,
the issue has a less certain future in the full House, where some
moderates have expressed reservation about pushing for removal of a
president on charges growing out of a civil lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of providing some form of punishment for Clinton's
admitted misbehavior, Democrats have begun composing various
censure resolutions they hope to debate before the committee late
next week and, failing there, on the floor of the House the
following week.
</P>
<P>
   A schedule provided by committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill.,
has part of Tuesday set aside for the president or his lawyers to
present his case to the panel. The rest of Tuesday and all of
Wednesday would be spent listening to presentations from the
committee's GOP and Democratic investigators. The committee would
then have the next three days to deliberate the articles of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter delivered to the House Judiciary Committee, White
House Counsel Charles F.C. Ruff and Special Counsel Gregory B.
Craig noted that the committee has held only two public hearings
and the president's lawyers were invited to participate in only
one, and then for only an hour. ``It is our view that the
proceedings to date have been inadequate and incomplete,'' the two
lawyers wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Incoming House Speaker Bob Livingston, R-La., has repeatedly
pressed the committee to complete its work in time for the full
House to vote before Christmas. If the full House votes to impeach
Clinton, the issue then moves to the Senate, where a trial would be
held. A two-thirds vote by the Senate would result in Clinton's
removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republican governors, who were in Washington to meet
with GOP congressional leaders, urged a quick resolution to
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people want this issue to be resolved one way or the
other and to move on,'' said Gov. Frank Keating of Oklahoma, chair
of the Republican Governors Association, during a news conference
with four other GOP governors.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Gov. John Rowland estimated that a half-dozen
Republican governors agree that Congress should censure Clinton _ a
proposal acceptable to the White House _ to avoid a lengthy
impeachment process so Congress can move on to other business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that we're not going to get back to all those
agenda items until we get this finished,'' Rowland said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
