<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PSYCHO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REMAKE OF `PSYCHO': TOO TRUE TO BE GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few hard-core film fanatics may be miffed that the new
``Psycho'' clocks in at a few minutes less the original's running
time, comes in color and tweaks its characters to bring them up to
date.
</P>
<P>
   But for the rest of us, the question is why make a virtual copy
of a classic movie.
</P>
<P>
   Director Gus Van Sant's hotly debated ``remake'' of Alfred
Hitchcock's sinister 1960 horror thriller is rigidly and
unabashedly faithful to its black-and-white predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there have been a few ``renovations'' at the Bates
Motel. Hitchcock made ``Psycho'' for a measly $800,000, keeping
costs down by using a TV crew to shoot the film. he only place in
which he refused to pinch pennies was the shower scene. Van Sant
spent somewhere between $20million and $25million. But his copy
still has a seedy, dingy look.
</P>
<P>
   Most people know the story: Marion Crane (Anne Heche) embezzles
money from her employer in Phoenix and heads to Fairville, Calif.,
to surprise her lover, Sam Loomis (Viggo Mortensen). She's stopped
by a Highway Patrol officer after falling asleep in her car by the
side of the road.
</P>
<P>
   She's a little nervous; he zooms in on her tenseness and follows
her. Marion trades in her car to cover her tracks and, as she
speeds toward Sam, notices the lines in the road blurring in the
heavy rain. She grows sleepy and pulls into the desolate little
Bates Motel, run by Norman Bates (Vince Vaughn) and his ailing
mother. And what would feel better after a rough drive than a nice,
long, hot shower?
</P>
<P>
   Van Sant toils shot-by-shot from Joseph Stefano's original 1960
screenplay adaptation of Robert Bloch's novel. Changes include a
few added zeroes in the amount of money Marion steals from her
boss; her lover, Sam, is now a dry-witted cowboy and her sister,
Lila, a no-nonsense feminist. There's even a scene where Norman
masturbates as he spies on Marion getting ready for her shower.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, it's business as usual. Van Sant's version
looks as textured and weathered as old wallpaper. His colors are
drab and muted and don't change the story's tension.
</P>
<P>
   The two shown incidents of violence _ the stabbing in the shower
and the murder of investigator Arbogast (William H. Macy) _ are
identical to those that shocked audiences and earned scathing
reviews from critics in 1960. In the shower scene, we still don't
see the knife touch skin. It's all implied, although the brutality
of the act is still terrifying. But it will probably prove way too
tame for today's audiences, saturated by cartoon violence in films
and on TV. The horror of ``Psycho'' is psychological and,
unfortunately, Van Sant drops the ball in this arena.
</P>
<P>
   The film's real problem is Vaughn. He's too arch and smug to
convey the skittish paranoia and panic lurking deep inside Norman
Bates. The role will always belong to Anthony Perkins, who had the
right mix of shyness and confusion. Vaughn is menacing, strong,
full of tics and he looks ridiculous, not horrifying, in a dress.
</P>
<P>
   So, is it worth it? As long as Heche's character is alive, it's
momentarily fun. But it's a fast, dull, downhill slide from there.
The tune-up proves so negligible that the remake isn't warranted or
necessary _ especially such a reverent, merely serviceable copy
that neither enhances nor builds on a film that has managed to
transcend time.
</P>
<P>
   Psycho. Directed by Gus Van Sant. Written by Joseph Stefano.
Cast: Vince Vaughn, Julianne Moore, Anne Heche, Viggo Mortensen.
Universal Pictures. 105 minutes. Rated R for violence, nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-04-98 2037EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
