<HEADLINE>
ENDEAVOUR IS LAUNCHED, AND THE CHASE BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ As the space shuttle Endeavour blazed a
spectacular pre-dawn trail across a clear starry sky out over the
Atlantic Ocean early Friday, Boeing's space station boss Doug Stone
watched in awe from his VIP location inside the fire control
center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all anxious to get this off,'' he told a reporter once
Endeavour and her crew of astronaut hardhats were safely in orbit
with a connecting node Unity, the first U.S.-made piece of the
space station. ``Now the fun starts ....''
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle thundered away from Pad 39A in the early Friday
morning. Eight minutes later it was in orbit.
</P>
<P>
   So began an around-the-world game of chase with the
Russian-built Zarya space station that was passing over central
Florida as 7.5 million pounds of thrust lifted Endeavor heavenward.
If all goes well, the shuttle will rendevous with Zarya, itself
launched only two weeks ago by Russia, Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   When astronaut Nancy Currie grabs Zarya with the shuttle's
50-foot remote arm and carefully pulls it toward Unity in the open
belly of Endeavour, construction can finally begin on a project
that has been likened to the building of the Pyramids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan is sound. ... We will just have to take this one step
at a time,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Stone was half way around the world, watching an
unmanned Russian rocket blast off with Zarya from the Baiknour
launch complex on the grassy steppes of Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
   Zarya has been circling the Earth every 92 minutes, awaiting its
mate Unity.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, Stone had butterflies in his stomach as the
countdown entered the final launch sequence before Endeavour's
liftoff. But his stomach was not churning any more than it had at
Baiknour. Stone is the manager ultimately responsible for Boeing's
success or failure as NASA's prime contractor for the $40 billion
space station. Zarya was built by the Russians under contract for
Boeing, and Unity was built by Boeing workers at Huntsville, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   ``The launch at Baikonur was absolutely awe inspiring, and the
launch of Endeavour was just as exciting, not only for me but for
everyone involved in the program,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm going to be holding my breath for the next several
days.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because astronauts Jerry Ross and Jim Newman must do what
no space-walking astronauts have ever done before. During three
complex walks outside Endeavour, they must successfully connect
Unity and Zarya. Like Earth-bound workers building a home, Ross and
Newman will lay the all-important foundation for future station
construction. If something goes wrong, the international project
could be in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Endeavour's mission will last 12 days. When the astronauts leave
the Unity-Zarya station, it will not be visited again until May,
when the shuttle Discovery will bring up supplies needed for the
next round of construction when a Russian service module, which
will provide living quarters for astronauts during the six years of
construction, will be connected to Zarya.
</P>
<P>
   The service module is scheduled to be launched on an unmanned
rocket from Baikonur in July, but that date is likely to slip. The
service module is not yet finished because Russia, on the verge of
economic collapse, didn't have the money. It's now getting funding
help from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The next piece of Boeing-built hardware for the space station is
a truss section built in Huntington Beach, Calif. it will be
attached after the service module.
</P>
<P>
   But it all depends on Endeavour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's go do this,'' Endeavour commander Robert Cabana said
just moments before launch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amen,'' launch control replied.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the first attempt to launch Endeavour early Thursday,
when a technical problem halted the countdown with just 19 seconds
to go, Friday's countdown was flawless.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeline Albright, witnessing her first
shuttle launch, applauded he 16-nation effort and told reporters:
</P>
<P>
   ``All day long I deal with disputes on the ground, countries
that can't get along, and it's great to look at this space station
endeavor.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Chairman Phil Condit, who had flown to the space center
for the first try at launching Endeavour early Thursday, was unable
to stay and missed the big show. But before leaving, Condit talked
about the station project at a Thursday breakfast with Boeing and
NASA workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are climbing a mountain,'' Condit told them, noting
that the first satellite was launched into space in 1957, ``it's
worth it to stop and look back and see how far you have come ....
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we are undertaking a project of amazing scope,'' Condit
said. ``When we are done, we will have created a new star. We will
have built something amazing and we will be able to go out into the
night and watch it pass overhead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
