<SLUG> BC-HALLOWEEN-ATTACK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALLOWEEN NIGHT FIGHT WITH YOUTHS HAS HOMEOWNER FACING TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DON HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The jack-o-lanterns at David J. McGee's
Appalachian Street home had been smashed the last couple of
Halloweens and he was determined that it wasn't going to happen
again this year.
</P>
<P>
   So the aerospace engineer-turned-furniture designer watched and
waited, then chased after a group of teens he thought were
threatening his property in Westlake Village, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Although authorities already have filed charges, deputies say
they are still trying to unravel numerous accounts of the Halloween
night incident that escalated into a series of confrontations that
has resulted in McGee facing a felony charge of assault with a
deadly weapon, in addition to four misdemeanor assault and weapons
charges. His arraignment is scheduled for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right at this moment, quite frankly, I'm flabbergasted,''
McGee said Friday, after prosecutors filed the felony charge, which
could bring him four years in prison if convicted. ``Originally,
the police wanted to file this as a felony. Then the (Ventura
County district attorney) changed it to a misdemeanor. And they've
changed it back to a felony.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're either stupid or they're bluffing,'' said McGee, 53.
</P>
<P>
   But the father of one of the teens involved in the Halloween
fracas said he is disappointed McGee is being charged with only one
felony.
</P>
<P>
   ``My reaction that they're dropping several of the charges down
to misdemeanors is it's questionable,'' said Nick Solare. ``I'm
just amazed that it's going to be one felony and the rest
misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   Solare said his 13-year-old daughter was trick-or-treating with
three friends when McGee, without warning, ``jumped out of the
bushes and whacked her in the abdomen with a hammer.''
</P>
<P>
   But McGee said he was not holding a hammer, but a stick, which
he grabbed when he chased after the group of teens who a neighbor
said had vandalized the pumpkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't my intention to punish anybody,'' McGee said. ``It
was my intention to catch them. ... I saw someone coming at me from
behind. In an instant, I flicked backwards and hit this person in
the breadbasket. All I saw was somebody who looked like they were
about to hit me.''
</P>
<P>
   According to both Solare and McGee, the girl ran to the nearby
Westlake Hills Elementary School campus, and reported the incident
to deputies stationed there.
</P>
<P>
   A group of youngsters gathered at the school then set out for
McGee's house, where a confrontation escalated into a fistfight,
both Mcgee and Solare said.
</P>
<P>
   One youngster ended up with several stitches to the back of his
head. Another reportedly suffered minor injuries to her back,
Solare said.
</P>
<P>
   As McGee retreated to his house, a small group of teens
converged on his home. One of the youths threw a can that missed
McGee, but hit his 9-year-old son, Trevor, in the neck. That set
off another fight and foot chase, McGee said.
</P>
<P>
   McGee returned home again only to see a large group of angry
youths headed his way, he said. McGee said his son called 911 at
that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you'd just had a violent confrontation with somebody and
saw 20 to 30 coming at you, what would you think?,'' said McGee.
``They weren't on a good will mission. I can tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not knowing when deputies would arrive, McGee said he armed
himself with two knives and an unloaded shotgun and went outside.
The group scattered.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, deputies arrived and handcuffed McGee.
</P>
<P>
   McGee said he was merely protecting his property when he armed
himself and stood up to the teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as a citizen, you have a duty to stand up to
intimidation,'' he said. ``If you relinquish your rights as a
citizen, if you relinquish your dignity, if you relinquish the
things you believe in to a roving gang of teen-agers on the street,
then where are we headed as a society?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, it's not the police who are going to help people.
It's people like me or anybody else who stands up and and says, No,
I'm not going to be intimidated,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
