<SLUG> BC-STANFORD-BURIAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINAL HONORS AT ARLINGTON FOR SEATTLE SCHOOLS CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Va. _ John Henry Stanford, the charismatic Army
general and Seattle schools superintendent who used even his own
dying as a lesson in courage and determination, was laid to rest
Friday alongside America's heroes.
</P>
<P>
   A riderless black horse with a boot backwards in the stirrups,
the traditional symbol for a fallen soldier, walked quietly behind
the creaking horse-drawn caisson that carried Stanford's
flag-draped silver casket through Arlington National Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Education Secretary Richard Riley, former Joint Chiefs of Staff
Chairman Colin Powell and four other four-star generals joined
Stanford's widow and their sons in an hour-long funeral celebrating
Stanford's life. Several hundred mourners then walked along roads
lined with leafless trees to the plot in Section 7A where Stanford
was buried.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore met with the
Stanford family at the White House after the ceremony. ``The
president is a great admirer of John Stanford,'' a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford, 60, died Saturday after a difficult and highly
publicized eight-month battle with acute myelogenous leukemia _ a
battle Stanford fought with typical optimism and remarkable
openness.
</P>
<P>
   ``He inspired not just the children ... but an entire city was
spellbound by the very presence and vision of John Henry
Stanford,'' the Rev. Dr. Elbert Ransom Jr. said in a eulogy at the
memorial chapel at Fort Myer. ``John went to Seattle, Wash., with a
mission to love the children and to lead the educational flight to
victory, and that he did by dreaming the dream, framing it, and
setting it on course. The rest, my friends, is up to us.''
</P>
<P>
   A native of Pennsylvania, Stanford spent 30 years in the Army,
retiring as a major general, before becoming manager of Fulton
County, Ga. In 1995, he was named superintendent of Seattle
schools, where he demanded a greater degree of courtesy to the
public, launched a citywide campaign to encourage reading, proposed
tougher graduation requirements and an end to busing.
</P>
<P>
   He was a local celebrity who enjoyed unusual adulation for a
public official. But his diagnosis with an often-fatal disease, and
the ups and downs of his treatment, touched a remarkable chord in
Seattle, provoking an outpouring of support and culminating in a
weeklong celebration of his life leading up to Friday's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford's lengthy service in the military entitled him to
burial at Arlington, the burial ground for more than 240,000
people, including former Presidents John F. Kennedy and William
Howard Taft, numerous Supreme Court justices, explorers,
astronauts, and even bandleader Glenn Miller. Stanford's grave lies
near that of boxer Joe Louis, occasioning some comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy who is a fighter, who symbolizes determination and grit
and heart and persistence _ that's Joe Louis and that's John
Stanford,'' said acting Seattle Schools Superintendent Joseph
Olchefske, who led a 14-member school delegation, including four
school board members.
</P>
<P>
   At the service, his friends recalled him as accomplished but
immodest, as an inspirational leader, as a devoted husband and
father. Ransom, the minister who met Stanford as a neighbor when
Stanford worked at the Pentagon, recalled how Stanford stopped by
his house one morning in a Superman costume, telling the children
he had been flying by and just though he would drop in.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cherished a great childlike imagination to do the
impossible, as if he were a superman, and what a splendid superman
he was,'' Ransom said. ``If the world that John Stanford passed
through would profit from all that he tried to do, all that he
tried to change, all that he succeeded in doing ... this would be a
better place for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Scott, a retired Army brigadier general who was Atlanta
City manager when he met Stanford, recalled Stanford as ``a
crusader who used his formidable leadership skills and talents to
build up rather than to tear down ... and to get things done,
rather than to talk about getting things done.''
</P>
<P>
   And a childhood friend, Fred Terrell, remembered Stanford, then
known as ``Sonny,'' as a member of ``The Backyard Gang,'' playing
basketball, swimming in the local creek, riding bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our athleticism was always competitive ... our dancing was
smooth, and our girls were fine,'' Terrell said. ``Sonny was always
the consummate player. His desire to give his at all at whatever
the undertaking would always assure him success.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford's status as a two-star general entitled him to an
escort by a bright red flag with two-stars, as well as a 13-cannon
salute.
</P>
<P>
   His affiliation with the Army brought him hymns played by the
U.S. Army Band and the attendance of the Army Chief of Staff, Gen.
Dennis Reimer, who escorted Stanford's widow, Patricia, to the
gravesite and ended the funeral by presenting her with the
ceremonially folded U.S. flag that had been draped over the coffin.
</P>
<P>
   Seven riflemen, silhouetted on a hilltop against an overcast
sky, fired three volleys over the grave, an historic battlefield
practice signalling that the dead have been cared for and fighting
can resume.
</P>
<P>
   A lone bugler played taps.
</P>
<P>
   Then silence fell on the funeral. The only sounds came from the
clicking of heels and clanking of swords as the red-hatted Army
Band and the black-hatted Honor Guard marched off. Mourners took
turns paying their final respects to Stanford, pausing to pray,
speak, or touch his casket, before they quietly turned and walked
away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
