<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4145 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BCSBCS05-COX     12-04 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BCSBCS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BCS: The final battleground
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tennessee fans making plans for a trip to the Fiesta
Bowl might consider this: Even if the Volunteers beat Mississippi
State tonight in the SEC championship game to go 12-0, UT still
could get ``decimaled out'' of the national championship picture.
</P>
<P>
   The top three teams in the Bowl Championship Series (BCS)
rankings _ Tennessee, UCLA and Kansas State _ all play crucial
games today, but what happens on the field might not be enough to
determine which two advance to the national championship game.
</P>
<P>
   If all three teams win, it will be the BCS standings _ a
complicated formula combining polls, computer rankings and strength
of schedule _ that determine who wins the trip to Tempe, Ariz., on
Jan. 4. Those final standings will be released at 3:30 p.m. Sunday
and Tennessee fans are nervous that even if the Vols win, the
numbers might not add up.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee is No. 1 in the BCS rankings with a 4.99 rating,
followed by UCLA (5.03) and Kansas State (6.31).
</P>
<P>
   But Kansas State's strength-of-schedule rating would improve
dramatically with a win over 10-2 Texas A&AMP;M in today's Big 12
championship game. According to computer guru Jeff Sagarin, the
Wildcats' strength of schedule rating would improve from 62 to 47.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's and UCLA's strength of schedule would improve only
slightly with wins over Mississippi State and Miami, respectively.
Factor in additional wins by Marshall and BYU today (both played
Tennessee opponents earlier this year) and the Vols' rating would
go from 29 to 22 while UCLA's would go from 7 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   With the new strength-of-schedule ratings factored in,
Tennessee's lead of 1.41 points over Kansas State would be trimmed
to a point _ close enough for the Wildcats to overtake the Vols
with favorable changes in the computer rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the two key questions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Can Kansas State pass Tennessee in both the Seattle Times and
New York Times computer ratings, which now have the Vols No. 2 and
Wildcats No. 3? The Seattle Times computer does not take margin of
victory into consideration, but it does count strength of schedule.
The New York Times computer factors in strength of schedule and
gives greater weight to good, late-season performances. If Kansas
State jumps over Tennessee in both ratings, that would create a
swing of 1.33 points _ enough to squeeze out Tennessee for the No.
2 spot behind UCLA. A change in just one of the computer rankings
would result in a swing of .27 points _ not enough to unseat the
Vols.
</P>
<P>
   _ Can Tennessee pass Kansas State in the USA Today/ESPN coaches'
poll? If Tennessee wins big over Mississippi State and Kansas State
struggles with Texas A&AMP;M, the Vols, now No. 2, could leapfrog the
Wildcats into the No. 1 spot. That would create a swing of a full
point _ enough to offset any change in the computer polls and keep
the Volunteers on the road to the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson for Tennessee tonight? Win and win big. Then hope.
``We are aware of the formula and what it means,'' Tennessee coach
Phillip Fulmer said, ``but we are also aware that the only thing
that we control is what happens on the field. We have to believe
that if we take care of business, the rest will fall into place.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the Volunteers led Kansas State by almost two
full points in the BCS standings. But UT's lead dwindled after a
victory over 2-9 Vanderbilt dropped its strength of schedule from
14th to 29th. Mississippi State's upset of Arkansas hurt the Vols'
rating, too _ instead of an SEC title game against a 10-1 Arkansas,
UT was left with a less-impressive matchup against 8-3 Mississippi
State.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State's strength of schedule, rated as low as 79th on
Nov. 7, has climbed steadily, as the Wildcats closed out the season
against Nebraska, Missouri and now Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   If one of the top three teams loses today, of course, the
remaining two clinch berths in the Fiesta. If two or even all three
lose, the scramble to determine the top two teams would seem likely
to short-circuit microchips from here to Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   Once the two Fiesta Bowl teams are figured, two other BCS bowls
_ the Sugar and Rose _ will fall into place. Under each of the
following three scenarios, the Orange Bowl matchup will be
Florida-Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   If Tennessee and UCLA are in the Fiesta, look for
Arizona-Wisconsin in the Rose and Kansas State-Florida State in the
Sugar.
</P>
<P>
   If Tennessee and Kansas State are in the Fiesta, look for
UCLA-Wisconsin in the Rose and Florida State-Ohio State in the
Sugar.
</P>
<P>
   And if it's Kansas State and UCLA in the Fiesta, look for
Arizona-Wisconsin in the Rose and Tennessee-Florida State in the
Sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
