<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUMMER-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Underdog sees game as chance of lifetime
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Be honest. Tonight's SEC championship game hasn't
occupied many waking thoughts. The buzz is barely above an annoying
hum, you say. The matchup is about as sexy as a seed catalogue, you
say. Considering the two-touchdown point spread, you're expecting
this one to be as one-sided as a eulogy.
</P>
<P>
   But then, you don't wear maroon, and the life, times and legend
of Rocky Felker is lost on you.
</P>
<P>
   The importance of this game can be dismissed only by the many
who neither know nor care about Mississippi State. Don't you know
that playing Tennessee for a conference championship can be a
life-altering experience?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just such an unusual situation,'' said the longtime
radio voice of the Bulldogs, Jack Cristil. ``(Bulldogs fans) don't
usually project championships. They say, `Give me a 7-4 or 8-3, get
in a bowl, and it's a great, great season.' They just don't think
on (the championship) level.''
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead and ho-hum and so-what. Just not around a program that
won its one and only SEC crown 57 years ago and never has finished
a season ranked in the top 10 by media, coaches or adding machine.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Bulldogs won that lone conference title, they
couldn't capitalize. The Japanese bombed Pearl Harbor shortly
thereafter, which kind of took the steam out of the bowl season.
</P>
<P>
   This is a game that dares modest expectation to get jiggy.
Tennessee has a bundle riding on tonight's outcome, like the
continuation of a national championship run. But for big underdog
Mississippi State, the Roy Kramer Bowl is a brief, blinding moment.
Around the Bulldogs there is the strong odor of once-in-a-lifetime
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   That's plenty to excite certain folk, some of them even
hereabouts. This game touches souls like Marietta's Guy McDowell, a
guard on Mississippi State's 1940 Orange Bowl team. ``(The
Bulldogs) have had their share of ups and downs. I'm sure glad to
get to see this come around,'' he said. ``Sure hope they have what
it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   The other guard on that team, Hunter Corhern, is back in
Starkville feeling all young again. ``I was brought up on
Mississippi State football. It has made me feel real good, the way
they've gone this season. They've really turned over a new leaf
from the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vols play big ones all the time. They routinely are in line
for some title or the other. The list of great defining games in
Mississippi State history is much shorter. Where to file this one
among, say, the 1980 victory over No. 1 Alabama or the 1941 victory
over Mississippi that secured the conference championship or the
1935 conquering of Army?
</P>
<P>
   ``Biggest game since '41, certainly the biggest one in my
lifetime,'' said Larry Templeton, a Starkville native who grew up
to become the Bulldogs athletics director. ``You don't get to knock
on this door often. When you do, you need to go through. Playing
for the SEC championship to us is the same as getting in the Final
Four or the College World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a New Year's Eve atmosphere for us in
Atlanta. Our people will be going full blast.''
</P>
<P>
   So, if you don't quite get this SEC championship game, just file
it away as a loud party to which you weren't invited.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
