A4148 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-MSTATE-SHERRILL05     12-04 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MSTATE-SHERRILL05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Out of Starkville, into national light
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He rubbed together what he claimed to be two Razorback
tusks and leaned back in his chair with a delicious, satisfied
smile. Just moments before, Jackie Sherrill had defied the experts
once again, in a Nov. 21 triumph over SEC West darling Arkansas
that put his Mississippi State team within reach of the conference
championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got these on a hunting trip in Texas a few years back,'' he
said, not caring whether the group of assembled reporters really
believed him. . ``You don't want to know where I shot him, but he
was running away from me.''
</P>
<P>
   That is Sherrill-style charisma, and that is as good as it gets
for the toast of Starkville, who finally has found a home after
years of dodging the NCAA and jumping through a series of legal and
ethical hoops, all for the sake of winning games.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a decade since he resigned from probation-bound Texas
A&AMP;M and spent a two-year exile selling used cars. But Sherrill has
rebounded at much-maligned Mississippi State, where his
ugly-duckling team in many ways typifies his ``us against the
world'' attitude.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 23 Bulldogs aren't being given much of a chance against
No. 1 Tennessee tonight, but predictions and public perceptions
aren't much of a concern to him. Sherrill has invigorated a
long-suffering program by finding players who agree with his
no-frills, unglamorous approach to football.
</P>
<P>
   ``He treats us with a lot of respect,'' center Eric Allen said.
``He's not really trying to impress anybody. He doesn't really care
what people think about him, but players love to play for him.''
</P>
<P>
   After eight years at a program that won its only SEC crown in
1941, Sherrill has added another chapter to his colorful but
checkered 21-year college coaching career. His 49 wins are just 13
behind State's all-time coaching record, and he has taken the Dogs
to three of their nine bowl appearances. Although he doesn't offer
a hint of excitement, he also can't hide relishing another chance
to bask in the national spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an old coach, it's a reward,'' said Sherrill, who turned 55
last week. ``It means you've been good for a long time. When you're
young, you don't always understand what success really means.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's how Sherrill defined success _ and the lengths he went
to achieve it _ that made him one of the most scrutinized coaches
in the 1980s. He won 50 games in five years and coached Dan Marino
at Pitt before bolting for College Station in 1982. The Aggies won
three Southwest Conference titles, but it happened under a
perpetual cloud.
</P>
<P>
   George Smith, once a star high school running back from Douglas,
Ga., accused Sherrill of paying him hush money to cover up a
previous payment from the coach, then recanted. Sherrill was
confronted at Hartsfield International Airport in 1987 by a
Journal-Constitution reporter and photographer chronicling his
meeting with Atlanta sports agent Jim Abernethy, who had given
money to two A&AMP;M players. Sherrill wanted to arrange a repayment in
order to get the players eligible for the Cotton Bowl, although it
never materialized.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, the NCAA found 27 rules violations and a ``lack of
institutional control.'' Sherrill, the head football coach and
athletics director, was not mentioned by name.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi State had drafted a mandate that its next coach
could not have been ``directly'' implicated in any improprieties.
That was the loophole school officials needed to hire Sherrill in
1991, although he hasn't been free from controversy. The NCAA
snooped around in Starkville in 1995 and didn't find anything
substantial.
</P>
<P>
   And most infamously, there was the helpless bull Sherrill had
delivered to practice before the 1992 season opener against Texas.
The animal was castrated for what the coach called ``motivational
and educational'' reasons. State beat the Longhorns that Saturday,
but Sherrill later apologized when even some Bulldogs fans took
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been blown way out of proportion,'' said Allen, who
heard plenty about the incident as a high-school player in tiny
Water Valley, Miss. ``That happens thousands of times every day on
the ranch.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherrill refuses to rehash the past, denying that he gets
pleasure from confounding those who declared his career essentially
was over when he left Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has never entered my mind,'' he said. ``Those aren't the
things I talk about with my players. I stress the positives with
them. If you look at the downside, you'll never be successful. I
don't dwell on things I don't want them to do.''
</P>
<P>
   That thinking, perhaps more than any other quality, has
underscored his endurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a players' coach,'' defensive back Tim Nelson said.
``When you get to know him, he's a great guy. He's not for
everybody, because he likes perfection. If you're not getting it
done right, he's really on you. But that's what I like about him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
