<SLUG> BC-FBC-TENN-FULMER05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Going for a ride with Vols' Fulmer
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like all football coaches, Phillip Fulmer is driven.
But last Saturday night, he decided to do the driving himself.
Earlier, Fulmer had shivered in glee in the Vanderbilt Stadium
twilight when his players doused him with icy-cold Gatorade. Later,
as the first coach to lead Tennessee to an 11-0 regular season,
Fulmer celebrated by turning I-40 into memory lane.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of accompanying the Vols back to Knoxville, Fulmer drove
home with his wife, Vicky, and their daughters Courtney, 15,
Brittany, 13, and Allison, 12, all exhausted after UT's 41-0 win.
The trip promised three hours of quiet, quality family time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just kind of take a deep sigh and relax a minute,'' Vicky
said. ``Phillip and I had a good conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Midway between Nashville and Knoxville, the girls spied a sign
on I-40 and suggested they stop for dinner in Cookeville. Outside
of the state of Tennessee, Phillip Fulmer has a decidedly low
profile, especially for a man with the highest winning percentage
(.855, 65-11) of any active coach in college football. Many coaches
might have celebrated at a fancier joint than a Cracker Barrel
restaurant. But that's what the kids wanted.
</P>
<P>
   When the girls were much younger and Fulmer an ambitious
assistant coach at his alma mater, he took them to the Cracker
Barrel in west Knoxville every Friday for breakfast. They loved the
pancakes. They're older now and, like their father, have hectic
schedules. Fridays with Daddy are a memory. But last Saturday, in
the wake of UT's first 11-0 start in 60 years, the girls ate
pancakes again. As usual, nothing fancy for Dad. Meatloaf and
vegetables. The only toast offered? From a waitress, who served
Vicky's toast and hot cocoa.
</P>
<P>
   It was a lot like the old Fridays, with two differences: The
state trooper who escorted them from Nashville and the steady
stream of well-meaning customers, UT fans who stopped by the table
to offer congratulations and say, ``Go, Vols!''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very satisfied,'' Vicky said. ``Just content, very
content. But not in a mood of elation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to be undefeated in the regular season, in the
conference, it just doesn't happen very often,'' Fulmer said. ``In
our case, since '56. And nobody had ever won 11 games in the
regular season at Tennessee. From a program standpoint, it's very
satisfying. And very gratifying to me personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something I wanted very much. Now, you enjoy it a lot
more later than you have time to enjoy it now. Our focus _ and
we've done a very good job of this _ is, how do we beat Mississippi
State?''
</P>
<P>
   If they do in the SEC Championship Game, the top-ranked Vols
will be 12-0 for the first time in school history and a 13th win
away from their first national championship since 1951. If so,
Phillip Fulmer will have accomplished in his seventh season as head
coach what no Tennessee coach _ not
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
