<HEADER>
A4154 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEART-HOSPITAL05-COX     12-04 1350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-HOSPITAL05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Special hospital for heart patients ready to open its doors
 &HT;    By Andrew Park
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ From his office at 38th Street and North Lamar
Boulevard, Mike Zucker envisions a place where guests rave about
the food, family members can spend the night and a concierge is
open 24 hours a day to cater to his guests' special needs.
</P>
<P>
   Zucker is not thinking of a luxury hotel for Central Austin but
a small hospital for heart patients, of which he is the president.
Monday, that hospital will open its doors on a bet that hotel-style
service and efficiency will lure physicians and patients _ and a
lot of money _ from the larger local facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the city's two largest groups of heart doctors have
invested in the new Heart Hospital of Austin, which sits just a
block from the city's biggest medical complex, Seton Medical
Center. Seton and St. David's, Austin's major hospital systems,
know those doctors will take patients and revenue from them but
won't hand over heart care in Austin quite yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know that there's going to be a battle for the current
providers to preserve as much as they can and for the new player to
grab as much as (it) can, and the battle's going to be fierce,''
said Tom Young, who helped run Brackenridge Hospital and the Travis
County Medical Society before becoming executive administrator at
Austin Regional Clinic in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   And in a city known as a mecca for managed care, health plans
may decide the fate of the Heart Hospital. The involvement of
health maintenance organizations and other managed-care companies
will be essential to attracting patients to the Heart Hospital.
When it opens its doors, only a handful of HMOs will have signed
on, and one, Humana, has said it won't cover its 70,000 Central
Texas members there because its contract with St. David's forbids
it.
</P>
<P>
   To understand why the battle for our hearts is so fierce,
consider that cardiac care generates 25 to 40 percent of a
hospital's revenue. Americans spend $160 billion a year treating
heart disease, the nation's No. 1 killer, and as diagnosis and
treatment become more sophisticated, they become more expensive,
too.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Charlotte, N.C.-based MedCath Inc. developed the first
hospital devoted to heart care and put it in McAllen. Since then,
the company has opened heart hospitals in Little Rock, Ark.,
Tucson, Ariz., and Phoenix. When the new facilities lost money,
MedCath sold out to two private investment firms last spring. The
buyout has not dampened MedCath's plans to open three more heart
hospitals across the country next year.
</P>
<P>
   In MedCath hospitals such as McAllen's, Medicare patients
account for as much as 70 percent of the business compared with
about half that at Seton and St. David's hospitals. Travis, Hays
and Williamson counties , which have younger populations _ all have
lower percentages of Medicare enrollees than Hidalgo County _ will
be a more challenging market, though executives say aging baby
boomers and retirees moving in will generate plenty of business.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, MedCath will also have to quickly win the loyalty of
health plans, which are increasingly influencing the way health
care is delivered. Nearly three of every four insured people in
Austin are covered by managed-care plans, most of which already
have relationships with the Seton and St. David's networks.
</P>
<P>
   `Focused factories'
</P>
<P>
   Zucker says the Heart Hospital's focus on efficiency was
developed with managed care's cost-cutting in mind. The health-care
industry calls MedCath's hospitals ``focused factories'' because
they treat only one part of the body. Last year, the Renaissance
Women's Center introduced the idea to Austin and quickly began
taking business from Seton and St. David's. Seton eventually bought
30 percent of the facility, which specializes in pregnancies,
births and women's health.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage both facilities enjoy is expertise. With an
emergency room and some noncardiac specialists, the Heart Hospital
will be able to care for nearly any patient who comes through its
doors, but its drive will be to serve heart patients.
</P>
<P>
   When patients arrive, they will be assigned a small team of
nurses and physicians to follow them throughout their stay. They
will stay in rooms that are only steps from the nurses stations,
come stocked with prescription drugs and are large enough to handle
intensive care equipment. So instead of moving patients from place
to place for different treatments, most of the care will come to
the patient's room. In the rooms, chairs convert into beds for
guests and everyone is encouraged to join in for meals. Heart of
Texas red corn spinach enchiladas or baked Atlantic cod are just
two of the many entrees to choose from.
</P>
<P>
   ``A cardiac hospital stay can be an incredibly stressful time
for patients and their families,'' said Melissa Paschal, the
hospital's vice president of business development. ``We'll offer a
sense of comfort and personal touches to ease the stress.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the emphasis on patients, the physicians will play the
biggest role in encouraging patients to be seen at the Heart
Hospital, especially those 50 doctors who are limited partners in
the venture. Their ownership gives them a measure of control they
don't have in traditional full-service hospitals, plus the chance
to make a profit. And the hospital is betting that even physicians
who didn't invest will appreciate it as an alternative to hulking
general hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a certain frustration on the part of all
physicians these days,'' said James Goolsby of Austin Heart, one of
the cardiology groups that invested in the hospital. ``They do feel
a bit pushed aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Goolsby says that overcrowding of diagnostic labs and operating
rooms has also frustrated cardiologists and heart surgeons in
Austin. Often they do procedures late at night because space is
limited, he says. The Heart Hospital will cater directly to
cardiologists and cardiac surgeons rather than making them compete
with oncologists, pathologists and pediatricians.
</P>
<P>
   Older hospitals skeptical
</P>
<P>
   But executives at Seton and St. David's balk at the idea that
Austin's hospitals are strained by the demand for cardiac care.
With many beds empty, their strategy lately has been to develop
outpatient and short-stay facilities in areas that are underserved
instead of increasing their stock of hospital beds. They are
skeptical that Central Austin needs another hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't see it adding any new technology and new
capacity,'' says Charles Barnett, Seton's chief executive, who
asked the state to reject MedCath's plans to lease land on the
state's Central Park parcel when they were first discussed. ``It's
in a location where there's already adequate capacity to provide
that kind of care.''
</P>
<P>
   The 500 physicians who have privileges to practice at the Heart
Hospital will continue to work at the other hospitals in town, but
seeing patients at the new facility will be hard to resist. In
McAllen, the Heart Hospital has already taken half of the area's
heart business away from the older hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   In response to that potential threat, Seton and St. David's are
stepping up marketing of their own cardiac-care facilities,
executives of both systems said. Already this year, Seton has
touted its 40 years of cardiac care in Austin, stretching back to
the first heart surgeries performed at Brackenridge Hospital, and
it claims the only sites in town for heart transplants and
pediatric heart catheterization. St. David's runs three sites for
open heart surgery _ St. David's Hospital, South Austin Hospital
and North Austin Medical Center _ and also offers an extensive
cardiac rehabilitation program.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the competitive nature is going to make all places
better as well,'' says Goolsby, who calls himself ``a Seton
doctor'' even though his office will be on the third floor of the
Heart Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
