<HEADER>
A4155 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ESCAPEE-DROWNED05-COX     12-04 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESCAPEE-DROWNED05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Death row escapee drowned, autopsy report reveals
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ Mark Humphrey and Doug Smith were out on the
johnboat, hoping to snare some catfish on their trotlines, when
Smith saw something odd in the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark, look at that,'' he said as the flat-bottomed boat glided
over the surface of Harmon Creek. Smith thought it was a mannequin
at first. He could make out a face and hands breaking the surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I saw it had fingernails,'' Smith said Friday. ``And a
mannequin doesn't have any fingernails.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday evening, the manhunt that started with blaring
sirens and barking hounds early Nov. 27 ended on a swampy waterway
near the Ellis Unit, when two fishing buddies who happened to work
for the prison system found the most sought-after man in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Gurule, the escaped death row inmate whose body Smith and
Humphrey found Thursday, drowned, according to autopsy results
announced Friday by prison officials. Gurule also was grazed by a
bullet, the autopsy showed.
</P>
<P>
   According to a preliminary report from Harris County Medical
Examiner Joy Carter, whose office performed the autopsy, Gurule
suffered a gunshot wound to his back, but the injury was considered
superficial and not the cause of death.
</P>
<P>
   Carter estimated he had been dead for seven days when his body
was found, which means he probably died shortly after his escape.
</P>
<P>
   The autopsy report said Gurule was wearing several layers of
clothing, plus magazines bandaged to his arms with elastic. He also
had cardboard wrapped around his torso with elastic bandage.
</P>
<P>
   ``That probably led to the sinking of the body,'' the report
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think he went to the bottom and nature did its work on the
body,'' prison spokesman Larry Fitzgerald said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thanksgiving day, Gurule and six other inmates cut through a
recreation yard fence, climbed to the prison roof, then sprinted
for the twin 10-foot perimeter fences, which are topped with coils
of razor wire.
</P>
<P>
   Gurule's comrades surrendered under a hail of gunfire from the
tower guards. But the 29-year-old Gurule, on death row for
murdering a Corpus Christi restaurant owner during a 1992 robbery,
clambered over both fences and into the woods, launching a massive
manhunt that had dragged into its seventh day when Humphrey and
Smith decided to go fishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I thought he was long gone,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   But there he was, bloated and very dead, lashed to the side of
Smith's boat Thursday night. Their bosses in the prison system had
been right all along, Smith said. Gurule had never left their
17,000-acre search area. Prison officials said Garule's body was
found about a mile from the prison. But at least one map of the
area showed the distance as about 2 1/2 miles, though still well
within the search perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   Humphrey is 39, a driver for the Texas Department of Criminal
Justice's transportation department. Smith, is two years older and
works as a dispatcher. Like many men and women in and around
Huntsville, both have worked for the prison system most of their
adult lives. For ten years they have fished the creek together. Now
they have a fishing story no one in Huntsville can top.
</P>
<P>
   The pair almost didn't go fishing Thursday. They wanted to
launch the boat in the morning, but Smith's motor wouldn't start,
so he took it to Riverside Marine, a shop a few miles east of the
Ellis Unit. Clogged carburetor. The boat was ready in a few hours.
</P>
<P>
   They hit the water sometime before 3 p.m., let a few trot lines
sink to the bottom, then ran out of weights. After heading for
shore to collect some rocks to tie to the lines, they decided to go
back and check on their first two lines.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, around 5 p.m., Humphrey was pulling out his
cellular phone and punching 911 to report that they had a body on
Harmon Creek. They pulled in Gurule _ his face unrecognizable _
with a fishing gaff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unreal,'' Humphrey said, recalling his initial reaction.
``Couldn't believe it. It's a human, and he's dead. I don't care
who it is, that's a bad feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   It got worse. The authorities wanted them to stay put, because
this was now a crime scene and the police needed to photograph
where Gurule was found. So they tied Gurule to the boat with
string, and tied the boat to one of the trees poking up through the
water.
</P>
<P>
   Humphrey said he almost begged the police to let him take the
body to shore: ``Let me load this guy and bring him in. It's
getting dark.''
</P>
<P>
   A brilliant full moon was rising over the pines by the time the
game warden could reach them in his boat. A day later, prison
officials were introducing them at a press conference as
``heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're real proud of them, we're glad (prison) employees found
Gurule,'' prison spokesman Larry Fitzgerald said, before tearing up
a wanted poster of Gurule. ``It's over.''
</P>
<P>
   The searching is over, anyway. Two separate investigations into
the escape _ one directed by the prison board, another by the Texas
Rangers at the request of Gov. George W. Bush _ are just beginning
to dig into how seven murderers could breach death row. ``There's
not going to be any whitewash here, I can assure the public of
that,'' said Allan Polunsky, chairman of the state board of
prisons. ``Mistakes have been made. That's quite obvious. We just
need to identify why they were made, and what needs to be done to
remedy whatever caused the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Polunsky appointed a former prison official who also
worked 22 years for the FBI to head an eight-member panel of prison
and law enforcement officials to review the escape. Retired prison
internal affairs director John McAuliffe, who lives in Boerne, will
head the panel, whose first meeting is Monday. Many Hunstville
residents, relieved that the escaped killer has been found, are now
eagerly awaiting the results of the inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to have anything like that (escape) come to a
close,'' said Jim Standefer, who owns several downtown properties
and runs a finance company. After Gurule escaped, Standefer said he
kept a pistol in his desk drawer just in case.
</P>
<P>
   ``But him getting out is indicative of this William Wayne
Justice crap that went on here,'' he added, referring to the
federal judge who put the Texas prison system under federal control
during a landmark inmates rights civil case filed by a prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials have said that the lawsuit, known as the Ruiz
case, forced them to start the work program that Gurule and the
other six escapees participated in. The program, which was
indefinitely suspended after the escape, let inmates work in a
garment factory or do janitorial duties and gave them greater
freedom within their cellblock.
</P>
<P>
   Staff reporter Denise Gamino contributed to this article, which
includes material from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
