<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOBLESS RATE SLIPS TO 4.4 PERCENT, NEARING 3-DECADE LOW
</P>
<P>
   Despite fears that 1998 still could turn out to be the decade's
worst year for layoffs, more Americans than ever are working, the
government said. U.S. employers added 267,000 workers to their
payrolls in November as the jobless rate slipped to 4.4 percent,
near a three-decade low.
</P>
<P>
   It was the biggest gain in payrolls in three months and matched
the pace of the year's first half, when many on Wall Street were
more fearful of an overheated economy than of a recession.
</P>
<P>
   MYLAN SAID TO FACE FTC LAWSUIT
</P>
<P>
   The federal government is preparing to accuse Mylan
Laboratories, a big generic drug maker, of anti-competitive
practices. The staff of the Federal Trade Commission has
recommended filing a civil action against the company, which it
said sharply raised the prices of its products after trying to
corner the market on the drugs' raw materials.
</P>
<P>
   UNOCAL QUITS PIPELINE PROJECT
</P>
<P>
   Unocal has withdrawn from a consortium that planned an $8
billion energy pipeline system traversing war-torn Afghanistan, a
company official said. The consortium, which brought together
companies from Saudi Arabia, Japan, South Korea and Pakistan, had
planned to build twin oil and gas pipelines from Turkmenistan to
the Pakistan port of Gwadar.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBLIC HIRES SEARS MARKETER
</P>
<P>
   Republic Industries hired a top Sears, Roebuck marketing
executive to be its president as part of its drive to raise the
profile of its Autonation USA unit. John Costello will be
responsible for developing the marketing for the company, which
owns the United States' largest chain of franchised new and used
automobile dealerships. He will also oversee its automotive retail
and rental operations.
</P>
<P>
   HOLLINGER SELLING 45 NEWSPAPERS
</P>
<P>
   Hollinger International, the second-largest newspaper group in
the United States, will sell 45 newspapers, including 28 dailies,
to Community Newspaper Holdings of Birmingham, Ala., for $475
million. Hollinger, which is based in Chicago, said the papers to
be sold are scattered among 14 states.
</P>
<P>
   BUYERS BID UP UBID INITIAL OFFER
</P>
<P>
   The stock of the online auction company Ubid ended the first day
of trading with its shares closing at $48 _ more than three times
the $15 offering price. Coming in the aftermath of several run-ups
by Internet initial public offerings in the last month, Ubid was
able to offer the stock at a price beyond the original estimated
range of $12 to $14.
</P>
<P>
   IN EUROPE, A STEP FORWARD FOR AT&AMP;T
</P>
<P>
   European antitrust officials approved AT&AMP;T's proposed merger
with Tele-Communications, but they plan to look further into the
proposed global venture between AT&AMP;T and British
Telecommunications, AT&AMP;T said. Both decisions had been expected.
</P>
<P>
   $1.5 MILLION AWARD IN AIR BAG DEATH
</P>
<P>
   A federal jury in New York awarded $1.5 million to the estate of
a 5-year-old boy killed after an air bag deployed in the front seat
of a Dodge minivan where he had been riding without a fastened seat
belt. DaimlerChrysler, the minivan maker, called the verdict
unfair.
</P>
<P>
   STRUGGLE OVER KENYA BEER MARKET
</P>
<P>
   The maker of Kenya's best-selling beer, which was named Tusker
after one of the brewery's founders was killed by an elephant, is
facing another behemoth. South African Breweries has taken on East
African Breweries and its partner, Guinness, in what has quickly
become a war over more than beer.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO BANK BAILOUT HELD UP
</P>
<P>
   After nine months of grueling debate, Mexican lawmakers have
reached broad agreement on measures to refinance the government's
troubled $61 billion bank bailout. But a final accord has been
stymied by a high-stakes dispute over the resignation of a top
government finance official.
</P>
<P>
   RISES FUEL INSURANCE SPIRAL
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 16 million people under 65 who have to buy their own
health insurance are facing increases of 40 percent or more this
fall. The big increases for these individuals are creating a
dynamic that appears likely to send prices even higher, as
healthier consumers decide they can do without coverage.
</P>
</TEXT>
