<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, DECEMBER 5
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-INTERNET-GUIDELINES-NYT (moved on Sunday, Nov. 29)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Nov. 29,
Monday about the Clinton Administration's policy report on Internet
commerce omitted a passage in an estimate by Ira Magaziner, a
presidential adviser, on how long it would take to determine
whether industry self-regulation is effective. Mr. Magaziner said
he believed it would take until the end of 1999, not the end of
1998.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-SCIENTISTS-FILM-NYT (moved on Monday, Nov. 30)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Nov. 30,
about science and the movies misidentified the place where the
particle physicist Leon Lederman did his Nobel-prize winning
research. Dr. Lederman and his colleagues discovered that an
elusive subatomic particle known as the neutrino had a cousin,
dubbed the ``muon neutrino,'' during experiments in the early
1960's in Upton, N.Y., at the Brookhaven National Laboratory _ not
in Batavia, Ill., at the Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory,
known as Fermilab.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBITUARY-DEMIKHOV-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Nov. 24)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of the pioneering Russian transplant surgeon
Vladimir P. Demikhov sent by the New York Times News Service on
Nov. 24, misstated the given name of a Case Western Reserve
professor who praised the surgeon's work. He is Dr. Robert J.
White, not Richard.
</P>
<P>
   In some copies the obituary also misstated the date of an
achievement ascribed to Dr. Demikhov by the Russian news agency
Itar-Tass. The agency said he performed a lung transplant on a dog
_ the first on an animal _ in 1947, not 1952.
</P>
<P>
   The obituary included an incorrect reference from the agency to
the history of heart transplants on dogs. Dr. Demikhov's, in 1946,
was not the first; Dr. Alexis Carrel, at the University of Chicago,
performed the first one in 1905, according to a spokesman for the
hospitals there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
