<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ORIOLES SIGN DeSHIELDS AND SURHOFF  
 (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Intent on keeping the New York Yankees within sight, even if
they need binoculars to do it, the Baltimore Orioles continued
scratching and clawing Friday to put together a starting lineup.
They filled two positions in a matter of hours, signing Delino
DeShields to play second base and re-signing B.J. Surhoff to play
the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   It was a day of relief for the Orioles, who have not had many
this off season, even though they signed Albert Belle and acquired
Charles Johnson last Tuesday. On that same day, they were shocked
to learn that Rafael Palmeiro rejected their five-year, $50 million
offer and accepted $45 million for five years from the Texas
Rangers. The next day, Robin Ventura agreed to the same offer with
the New York Mets that the Orioles had made, saying, ``I felt it
was a better fit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had also been negotiating with Surhoff, and their
signing of Ventura made it easier for the Orioles to keep him. The
Orioles had hoped to sign two players from the
Palmeiro-Ventura-Surhoff group.
</P>
<P>
   Surhoff, a 34-year-old New York native, had been offered a
guaranteed four-year contract by Pittsburgh, and the Orioles
belatedly offered to match it. But Surhoff opted to take three
guaranteed years with an option for a fourth year that will vest if
he plays in 120 games or has 372 plate appearances because the
salary for the fourth year would be higher. He is guaranteed $14
million for three years.
</P>
<P>
   With Belle more familiar with left field, Surhoff will most
likely switch from left to right, but Orioles general manager Frank
Wren said Belle has offered to play right so Surhoff could stay in
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's for the manager to decide,'' Wren said by telephone
from Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   DeShields, who will turn 30 next month, will replace Roberto
Alomar _ who went to Cleveland as a free agent _ at second base and
in the leadoff spot in the batting order. The Orioles lured him
from St. Louis with a three-year, $12.5 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   The left-handed hitter batted .290 last season and had a .371
on-base percentage. He had 26 stolen bases, lowest of a nine-year
career that he has spent with Montreal, Los Angeles and the
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Surhoff, a versatile player defensively, achieved career highs
with the Orioles last season with 22 home runs and 92 runs batted
in.
</P>
<P>
   Wren said he would continue his search for a first baseman, a
starting pitcher and a right-handed reliever. Will Clark is one of
the possibilities for first.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles would like to sign Kevin Brown as the starting
pitcher they seek, but the price will be high. ``They're still
sorting through their thing for another week or so,'' Wren said of
Brown and his agent, Scott Boras.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
