<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4183 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-WWI-LEGACY-NYT &LR;      12-04 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WWI-LEGACY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 COLUMN: CLOSING A RING: FATHERS, SONS AND OLD WARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 BY DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In 1968, Thomas Fleming went to France, to see
firsthand the Argonne forest where his father, Teddy Fleming,
fought alongside thousands of doughboys in the fierce battle that
helped end World War I. That clash routed the Germans and started
Teddy on a new life. He had gone over there as a sergeant, but came
home an officer after a battlefield commission. His exploits caught
the attention of Frank Hague, the mayor of his hometown, Jersey
City, who suggested the young man enter politics. He did, and by
1945 he had become sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor gave him an onyx and gold ring to mark that
accomplishment. It was inscribed: ``From Mayor Frank Hague to
Sheriff Teddy Fleming 1945.'' Teddy gave it to his son in 1957
shortly before he died, and Fleming was still wearing it when he
went trooping through the Argonne. While climbing an embankment at
the site of one battle, he noticed that the ring had slipped off
his finger. Desperate, he clawed at the dirt, throwing clumps into
the air. Nothing. The very ground that had claimed the bodies of
countless young Americans had exacted its revenge on the son of a
man who survived.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks ago, Fleming, a successful novelist and historian, got
a call at his home on the Upper East Side. Gene Scanlon, a friend
who worked for the current mayor of Jersey City, had a question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever lose a ring in France?'' Scanlon asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Fleming said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get ready for a shock,'' Scanlon said. ``Some French guy found
it and he wants to give it back to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Gil Malmasson, a young French photographer who liked to sweep a
metal detector over old battle sites, had discovered the ring in
1985. The inscription that commemorated Teddy Fleming's rise from
wartime heroics to peacetime politics prompted Malmasson to ask
U.S. diplomats and soldiers about its owner. No luck. In October,
he finally tracked it down to Jersey City through a Web page that
mentioned Hague's tenure as mayor. Last week, Fleming returned to
the Argonne to retrieve his ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was deeply, deeply moved,'' Fleming said. ``I had this
indelible rush of emotion that my father was in some sense in my
life again in this mystical way I didn't understand. The more I
thought about it, the more I thought there has to be some meaning
to it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is. On one level, Malmasson's urge to find the ring's
owner was a reaffirmation of the ties of friendship and duty that
have bound France and the United States since the Revolutionary
War. It was also a way to make a real connection to history, which
Malmasson said has always inspired his hunt for buried bits of the
past.
</P>
<P>
   All jewels get their own history, full of love and sometimes
hate, but always fully emotionally charged,'' he said in an e-mail
message. ``If I'm happy to find such treasure, it's quite
frustrating not to get any clues about the story of each object.
For me, it's just gold and stones. But for those who lost it,
sometimes it's a great part of their life.''
</P>
<P>
   He found the ring _ as he has rifles, bayonets and shell casings
_ quickly that day in 1985 when his metal detector beeped an alert.
He pried it out of the ground with a quick sweep of a pickax. When
he saw the inscription, he knew he had to find the owner. Over the
years he went to the U.S. Embassy in Paris and U.S. military
offices in Germany. Everyone was too busy to help. He clung to the
notion that he could find its owner, since it had been a gift from
one politician to another. That prompted him to search the Web in
October.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept it in my mind to locate him one day,'' Malmasson said.
``A quest is never finished when you don't have the whole story.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleming can relate to that approach, especially in his
historical novels. Rather than see history as a list of dates and
great events, he recasts it as his-story, writing about how plain
people were caught in momentous times. Professional historians, he
said, have often ignored the role that memory plays in history, but
people want to have some tangible link to the past. That's why he
visited the Argonne. That's why he wore his father's ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``A ring has such symbolic power,'' Fleming said. ``They are put
on by popes and kings when they are crowned. It is a very powerful
symbol of connection and of blood. That was what my father was
trying to do when he gave me this ring in '57.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he and Malmasson stood on the side of the road not
far from where the ring was lost and found. Malmasson presented it
to him in a blue case decorated with a tiny sticker of the Stars
and Stripes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt a sense that my life as a historian was being
validated,'' Fleming said. ``That history, my interest in history,
Gil's interest in history, had come together in that moment and
restored a connection that I had to my father. A connection of
love.''
</P>
<P>
   His father, ``one tough Mick'' as he described him, never talked
much about love. But he never stood in his son's way when the young
man decided to become a writer rather than go into the law and get
rich through his father's political connections. The ring reminded
him of that. A few days ago, it reminded him of another battle,
too, the kind waged between fathers and sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 15 and not getting along with him,'' Fleming recalled.
``We were in the car one day and he asked, `How come I'm taking you
for a ride and you're reading a book?' I said: `What do you care?
You don't love me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   His father slammed the brakes and jumped out of the car, crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``You said I didn't love you,'' his father said. ``You and your
brother are all I got.''
</P>
<P>
   Decades after that fight, Fleming's own recollection came back
haltingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't get along with my mother,'' he said with a catch in
his voice. ``It was a terrible moment.'' He paused again.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' he finally said. ``You can see why I went to France.''
</P>
<P>
   He beheld the ring, a noble token of debts to France and
fathers. The stone was chipped, but it looked perfectly glorious on
his finger. He and Teddy had beaten the Argonne again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
