<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOME-WINEMAKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACCHUS IN THE BRONX: HOME WINEMAKING OF A CERTAIN VINTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MOLLY O'NEILL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are two kinds of home winemakers. There are
those who choose to make wine. And there are those who can't help
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   John Salvo is definitely one of the latter. And as a cold
November breeze whipped up his block in the Country Club section of
the east Bronx last week, Salvo was not pleased. The air was cold
enough to dull the smell of decaying leaves in his neighborhood,
cold enough to erase the scent of Neapolitan cooking that usually
emanates from its kitchens, cold enough to keep 50 gallons of his
1998 vintage from fermenting.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the driveway behind the tidy stucco home where he
and his wife raised their two children and have lived for 47 years,
Salvo pulled up the collar of his blue jacket, shook his head and
predicted a space heater vintage.
</P>
<P>
   His most significant contribution to the art of home winemaking,
he said, is his technique for providing the constant 72 degrees
that crushed grapes require to ferment. The Salvo innovation
involves swaddling the 50-gallon fermenting vats in blankets and
positioning a space heater close by when it gets cold outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wine is like the woman you marry,'' Salvo said. ``You want
to make a baby, you got to stay close and get her warm. That's the
same way with the wine. You got to keep her warm or else she does
nothing but sit there.''
</P>
<P>
   The 73-year-old retired building contractor is one of the last
of the neighborhood's old-time home winemakers. He scoffs at the
high-priced winemaking equipment and technical manuals that today's
food-obsessed, vintage-savvy younger set buy to feed their dreams
of making award-winning varietal wine.
</P>
<P>
   Salvo does things the old-fashioned way. He retools and
jury-rigs his winemaking tools. He follows his senses, not a
recipe.
</P>
<P>
   His instinctual approach to winemaking is one reason that people
like Ronnie Palumbo apprentice themselves to Salvo. Palumbo, 52, is
young and affluent enough to appreciate fine varietal wine. But he
is also old enough to worry about the passing of the vintners of
his father's generation and the wine they made from recipes handed
down from Bacchus.
</P>
<P>
   Salvo's brown-eyed, white-haired puckishness makes him almost as
difficult to resist as his thick red wine _ ``not too sweet, not
too dry, 3 cases white seedless grapes, 7 cases Alicante grapes,
that's my recipe that everybody love,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   After decades of making their own wine, neighbors who have
gotten too frail for the ritual call on Salvo to set their annual
stores. He is happy to oblige _ up to a point. ``The first ton of
grapes, I can handle,'' he said. ``After that, I need help.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a procession of apprentices including his son
Joseph and grandson Johnny, friends and fellow retirees like Vito
Poveromo and Lochy Conlon have established themselves as the
winemaker's constant assistants. In fact, so large is the Salvo
consortium that, when he retired five years ago, Salvo moved his
center of operations from a tiny cloakroom near the front door of
his home. What he calls his new center is actually his former
garage.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the particulars of home winemaking have become the
organizing principle of his life.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer, he scours bars for empty bottles. It takes all
afternoon to wash, sterilize and sun-dry the bottles. By Sept. 1,
Salvo has entered the grape-buying stage.
</P>
<P>
   He and his consortium pile into his light blue 1983 Chevy and
cruise the Conrail freight yards in Mount Vernon, in Westchester
County. Various vendors sell California grapes directly from
freight cars, cash only.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the Bronx, the winemaker and his assistants also drop by
Jerry's Nursery &AMP; Wine Grapes Co. on Boston Road. Salvo is a big
believer in comparative shopping and Jerry's is his personal
commodity price index.
</P>
<P>
   Salvo claims that more than 65 years of winemaking, beginning
with his apprenticeship to his grandfather in Salerno, Italy,
helped him refine his blend. But his main purveyor suspects that
price is a significant factor in Salvo's formula.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old guys like John and my father aren't going to pay $34 a
box for merlot grapes or $35 for cabernet when they can get
Alicante for $20,'' said Carmine Cipolla, son of Jerry Cipolla,
founder and owner of Jerry's Nursery &AMP; Wine Grapes Co.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to shopping for the best price, said Cipolla, ``the
old guys think the way they do it is the only way, because it is
the only way they ever did it and no way they're going to change.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he said, the old-timers tend to be immigrants who may
be loyal to their fathers, or may think that $20 for a bottle of
wine is highway robbery, or may be too wary to drink any wine they
haven't made themselves.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reason, their response to autumn is to begin the
wine, quickly, instinctually and, after they have settled on the
price of the grapes, without question.
</P>
<P>
   They make hot, sturdy wine that cannot be aged and begins to
sour within a year, wines that might cause a sommelier to sniff.
But in wines like Salvo's, the contradiction between their fleeting
fragility and their full, rough body is their charm.
</P>
<P>
   The younger, more enlightened winemakers of today, said Carmine
Cipolla, aim to make fine wines, distinct wines, wines that can be
aged. ``The newcomers are full of science and social ambition,'' he
said. ``They tend to belong to wine-tasting clubs and drive their
BMWs to Jerry's to buy princely varietal grapes and designer-priced
winemaking equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Berens, the editor of Wine Maker, an annual magazine
that premiered last summer, said home winemaking is one of the
fastest-growing hobbies in America.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Cipolla isn't so sure. ``When I started this business 60
years ago, I had 10 competitors within 3 blocks,'' he said. ``Now
I'm the only guy and I lose a customer every couple weeks. They
die.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't trust the youthful hobbyists with their ready cash
and vinicultural vocabulary. In an economy that runs deeper than
dollars, Jerry Cipolla knocks a couple cents off his price to Salvo
every time the winemaker loses a customer.
</P>
<P>
   The gesture is not lost on Salvo, who is uncharacteristically
specific when it comes to cost and quantity. He purchased 3,780
pounds of grapes this year, which cost about $2,160 and made
precisely 315 gallons of wine, just under the legal limit for
personal consumption. He makes wine for himself first, and then for
the neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   After blanketing the fermenting vat and firing up the electric
space heater one recent afternoon, Salvo rubbed his hands together
over the glowing coils and surveyed his world.
</P>
<P>
   The expanded Chateau di Salvo is a cinderblock structure with
one glass brick window, two walls of wood shelving that accommodate
giant barrels for aging, and an eclectic assortment of vodka and
scotch bottles as well as grinders, filters and clear plastic
tubing.
</P>
<P>
   The spine of the room is a platform that is about 36 inches high
and houses two 50-gallon fermenting vats. Both of the grape presses
bolted to the concrete floor were gifts. One is a 150-year-old,
hand-cranked metal model from a neighbor who had gotten too old and
weak to turn the massive handle.
</P>
<P>
   Inhaling one of those precious moments between raw grapes and
vinegar, Salvo rocked contentedly in his running shoes. Then he
started to giggle like a madman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last June, some doctor tell me I'm going to die in one month.
I say to him he better be wrong or else he's not going to taste my
wine! Now he's calling me asking for his wine. Who else is he going
to call?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
