<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: BRADLEY HASN'T ANSWERED THE `WHY' QUESTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Minn., Mo., Neb.)   (With BRADLEY-POLITICS)  
(rl) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Vice President Al Gore had expected that his incumbency and
financial strength would discourage serious challengers, that
assumption faded with Bill Bradley's announcement that he may seek
the presidency in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday afternoon, Bradley was among a half-dozen Democrats
who were talking about joining the presidential hunt next year.
While the field might be relatively large, with Democrats stirred
by the perception of the Republican Party in disarray, Gore
continues to be viewed by Democrats across the nation as the
overwhelming favorite. And even in announcing that he might seek to
topple Gore, Bradley served to underline the difficulty that he _
and, for that matter, any Democrat _ is going to have running
against a man so closely identified with a popular president.
</P>
<P>
   The former senator from New Jersey declined to offer any
criticism of Gore, or even offer any differentiation of views
between himself and Gore. He instead spoke in the broad, esoteric
style that has for a decade excited some Democrats about the
prospect of a Bradley presidential bid, but has struck more than a
few others as quirky and distant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about telling people what I believe,'' Bradley said.
``Going out and talking to people, as I have been doing for 30
years. It will not be a campaign related to the past. It will be a
campaign related to the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The cautious posture was in keeping with the style of a man who
has always tried to present himself as a cut above the common
politician. But many Democrats said that such a campaign, by
itself, might be less than effective against Gore, a sitting vice
president who has spent these past seven years accumulating huge
amounts of political good will and campaign contributions in
preparation for this run.
</P>
<P>
   In this kind of environment, even Bradley _ the former
basketball star and best-selling author _ is going to be under
increasing pressure to offer Democratic primary voters a reason to
discard someone who has been such a loyal soldier to President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big question is the Roger Mudd question: Why? Why is he
running?'' said George Stephanopoulos, the former senior White
House aide who helped engineer Clinton's victory in 1992. ``All
things being equal today, Gore is in as strong as position as you
can imagine for the nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   William Carrick, a California-based Democratic consultant, said
that while Bradley might have stirred interest among Democrats with
a cerebral discussion of the problems facing the nation, ``a lot of
that is on a very cosmic plane and needs to be fleshed out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have got here is a situation where it's not clear
what the rationale is, other than he wants to talk about things
like race relations, the need for community and how government and
people are connected,'' Carrick said.
</P>
<P>
   With his announcement, Bradley now becomes one of two Democrats
who have taken the step of forming an exploratory committee, the
first formal step toward joining the race. The other is Sen. Paul
Wellstone of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   In the hours after Bradley's announcement, four other Democrats
reiterated their own interest in the contest. Sen. John Kerry of
Massachusetts will announce in January what he intends to do, an
aide said. Sen. Robert Kerrey of Nebraska has invited friends to
Omaha later this month and is is expected to use the occasion to
declare he will run for president a second time. The Rev. Jesse
Jackson told reporters in Washington Friday that his son has urged
him to run again. And Richard Gephardt of Missouri, the House
minority leader, is also seriously considering another run for the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Such a crowded field would almost surely play to the benefit of
Gore, dividing whatever opposition to the vice president exists. On
the other hand, several Democrats predicted that Gephardt would
chose to remain in the House, where he might become speaker in
2000. That would leave Bradley as the leader in a second tier of
candidates trying to unseat Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But then what? Bradley has identified himself with campaign
finance reform, an issue on which Gore, given the investigations
into the fund-raising activities of the White House, might be
vulnerable. But there is no evidence that American voters are moved
by the question of how candidates finance their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has a unique position in American politics _ the Rhodes
scholar and star basketball player _ but he has yet to identify
himself with with a major proposal or theme of discontent. More
than a few Democrats wondered Friday whether that was enough to win
an election in this kind of environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell me what Bill Bradley's big idea is,'' said Terry
Michaels, a former communications director for the Democratic
National Committee. ``I don't think he stands for much. I don't
think you can do a personality-based campaign and knock off a
sitting vice president for the presidential nomination. I think it
has to be a real ideas based campaign, one that can really move the
rank and file and caucus participants.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years is a long time. Clinton's popularity could fade.
Democrats might decide they have had enough of this president,
particularly if the threat of impeachment passes, and Gore could
pay the price for that. The investigation into Gore's campaign
finance practices could turn for the worse. Or Gore could make the
kind of graceless mistake that front-runners so often make,
creating an opening for Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, that was a point Stephanopoulos made Friday, recalling
the relatively unknown field of Democrats who put themselves
forward to run against President Bush in late 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are kicking themselves because they thought
George Bush was unbeatable in 1992,'' Stephanopoulos said. ``Bill
Clinton didn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
