<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4191 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-04 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD CALLS HURT FLUTIE IN THE WALLET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The biggest loser in last Sunday's fiasco between Buffalo and
the Patriots will not be Bills owner Ralph Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson got flagged for $50,000 by NFL commissioner Paul
Tagliabue for criticizing the officials after they made two calls
at the end of the game that took a victory away from the Bills.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest loser will most likely be Doug Flutie. As we
wrote several weeks back, the Bills quarterback is playing for the
minimum base salary, which was raised from $250,000 to $300,000
when the new collective bargaining agreement became official
recently.
</P>
<P>
   His opportunity for big money is in bonuses. Flutie has picked
up about $500,000 extra for the number of plays and wins he has
been involved in to date.
</P>
<P>
   However, the big boosts come into play with win No. 9. If
Buffalo had won last week, which it should have, Flutie and the
Bills would have eight victories, with some seemingly easy pickings
left on the schedule _ Cincinnati and New Orleans on the road,
Oakland and the Jets at home.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie needs two more wins to pick up $250,000 more in bonuses.
With each additional win beyond nine, another $250,000 kicks in.
</P>
<P>
   Also, he has a clause in his contract that if the Bills make the
playoffs, he gets an additional $100,000, and if they make the
second round, he gets another $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   If he had won last week, Flutie would have four shots to make
the first $250,000. And if the Bills had prevailed here, they would
have been odds-on to win the AFC East.
</P>
<P>
   Plus _ and this is a huge plus _ all the bonus money this year
will be added to his base salary next year. If he makes $1 million
in bonuses this year, his base salary next year would start at $1.3
million.
</P>
<P>
   One could easily say that if the Bills miss the playoffs, those
calls here last Sunday may cost Flutie at least $750,000 over the
next two years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Your favorite Patsies, doormats more than dominators during
their 39-season existence, will be No. 1 soon. You can count on it.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean they are going to win the Super Bowl. What is
sure to happen, if and when they are safely ensconsced in Hartford,
is that they will be the top revenue-generating team in sports. Not
just the NFL. All of sports.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes magazine this week tabbed the Dallas Cowboys as the top
team in the NFL financially because they take in more money than
any other, some $118 million per season. The Yankees, according to
Forbes, take in the most overall, $144 million.
</P>
<P>
   Move over, 'Boys and Yanks, there will be a new leader in the
clubhouse soon. If, as planned, our New England Patriots get to
Hartford in 2001, they will be top dog. When the stadium opens, the
Patriots will gross more than $170 million a year, and in their
fifth year, 2005, they will gross more than $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a football team playing about 20 games each year taking
in more money than any baseball team playing 162.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If we read it right this week when the state of Connecticut,
made public the economic feasibility study it commissioned, the
state expects to make a score starting in the 30th year of the
30-year lease with the Patriots. Someone should tell those people
that in 30 years that stadium will be outmoded. And then, instead
of cashing in, the state will have to start building another
stadium for the Patriots, if they're still in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   The stadiums built in the 1960s _ RFK in Washington, Three
Rivers in Pittsburgh, Veterans in Philadelphia, and Riverfront in
Cincinnati _ are all dumps from which their teams are trying to
escape. The Redskins have moved to a new stadium they built
themselves. Cincinnati, Pittsburgh, and Philly are all trying to
get new stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years seems to be about the life expectancy of a stadium,
and Connecticut will find that out. All the stadiums mentioned
above were built for less than $50 million. It now costs four times
as much. Hartford's will cost $280 million. Multiply that by four
and see if the state makes $3.8 million in 2031. It will never
happen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of new stadiums, the Red Sox had a group of Boston
experts on the West Coast this week looking at the plans for the
stadiums to be built in San Francisco, Seattle, and San Diego, to
name a few. The Red Sox expect to have their entire stadium plan,
including the financial feasibility study, ready to present to the
public in February . . . The officiating crew that got in trouble
here last Sunday is the same one that the NFL had to apologize for
early in this season when two terrible calls they made helped San
Francisco beat Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the last NFL annual meeting in March, the return of instant
replay as an officiating tool was defeated by two votes, with 23
yeas needed for passage. Next year, with Cleveland coming in as the
31st team, 24 votes will be needed.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland is already on record as favoring replay. Plus,
Buffalo's Wilson and Pittsburgh's Dan Rooney, whose teams voted
against it in March, now say they are ready to vote for it.
</P>
<P>
   When replay was discontinued after 1991, opponents claimed it
slowed down the game. Recent history shows how flawed that theory
is.
</P>
<P>
   Time of game with replay _ 1990: 2 hours 58 minutes 25 seconds;
1991: 3:01.40. Without replay _ 1997: 3:02.38; 1998: 3:04.50 (to
date).
</P>
<P>
   The point is, the games are taking longer now without replay
than they did with it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue informed Bill Parcells recently that there was no
merit to the charges that he was tampering when he called Drew
Bledsoe for a friendly conversation following the Jets' win over
the Patriots in Foxborough. The Patriots triggered the protest . .
. Mo Money was great this week, wasn't he, talking about his
``misfortune''? I guess he was referring to his time with the Red
Sox, when he made a fortune. Look at Vaughn's life. He grew up with
nice parents, went to a fancy prep school (Trinity-Pawling in
Connecticut), attended a good college (Seton Hall), and will make
$100 million before age 40. He has sure had a lot of
``misfortune,'' hasn't he? . . . We forget about the other people
hurt by the NBA lockout, like the local chapter of the B'nai Brith.
For years, it has put on the Celtics' season-opening dinner for
charity, netting $70,000 last year, all going to good causes. This
year: no games, no team, no dinner, no money . . . As we think of
all the great high school championship games on tap, we ask this
trivia question. Can you name the high school football player who
holds the national record for kickoff returns for touchdowns in a
game? He did it four times in a game for Shanley High in Fargo,
N.D., in 1951. Ten years later, he broke Babe Ruth's home run
record by hitting 61. Roger Maris.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
