<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LAWYERS SAY THEY'LL NEED 3-4 DAYS BEFORE PANEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amid growing anxiety that the House may have the
votes to send at least one article of impeachment to the Senate,
White House lawyers said Friday they will need three or four days
to present their defense of President Clinton next week.
</P>
<P>
   That request would interfere with the House Judiciary
Committee's plan to set aside Tuesday for Clinton's defense and
begin the debate and vote on possible articles of impeachment later
in the week.
</P>
<P>
   The White House immediately sought to dismiss speculation that
it was trying to delay a House impeachment vote until the next
Congress is seated in January, when Republicans will have a
majority of only six votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we can get this done by the end of next week, and
that should leave them plenty of time to wrap up their
proceedings,'' spokesman James Kennedy, a White House special
counsel, said Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   But the committee's GOP spokesman, Paul McNulty, said, ``This is
an obvious and desperate political ploy to push the inquiry into
the new Congress where the Democrats potentially have more votes.''
Democrats picked up five seats in last month's elections.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers unveiled their new defense strategy on a day
when White House aides criticized Judiciary Committee Chairman
Henry J. Hyde for his previous statements about perjury. At the
same time, the White House sent its strongest signal to date that
the president is willing to accept a congressional censure and
perhaps a fine rather than have the Senate conduct an impeachment
trial.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the committee, White House lawyers Gregory B.
Craig and Charles F.C. Ruff said they plan to call witnesses to
testify about constitutional standards for impeachment; standards
for prosecution, perjury, obstruction of justice and abuse of
power; prosecutorial misconduct; and the impact of tainted
evidence; and then present closing arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipate that we will require no more than three to four
days of the committee's time to deal with the topics...at which
time counsel for the president will present a final argument as to
why, given the law, the facts, and these circumstances, this
committee should not report out articles of impeachment,'' the
letter said.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining their request for ``some modification'' of the
committee's schedule, the laywers wrote: ``Should the House of
Representatives approve an article of impeachment against the
president and send it to the Senate for trial, the impact on the
national government and on the American people as a whole would be
profound. For that reason alone, this process must be deliberate,
thorough, fair and expeditious.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Democrat on the Judiciary
Committee, said the panel could give Clinton's lawyers four days to
present a defense and still wrap up its work by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the White House wants this wrapped up this year so
we can hit the ground running next year,'' Meehan said. ``If in
fact, the White House wanted to carry this all into the next year,
I would be very disappointed, and I would speak out against that
strategy. I think that would be a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, when asked about the House impeachment vote,
White House Press Secretary Joseph Lockhart said, ``We would like
that to happen today. If it can't happen today, we would like it to
happen tomorrow. If next week is the date they set, we would like
that to happen next week.''
</P>
<P>
   While Republican leaders have been counting the House votes in
favor of impeachment, the White House has been taking the
temperature of Democrats and moderate Republicans to find out where
they stand. Both legal and political aides have been involved in
that effort, as well as Cabinet members who have served in
Congress, such Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   With the House vote, slated for the week of Dec. 14, too close
to call, White House aides Friday openly embraced the censure
option as part of an effort to sway about two dozen moderate
Republicans who think Clinton should be punished for lying about
his relationship with Monica S. Lewinsky but not impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said administration officials were ``aggressively
listening'' to congressional alternatives to impeachment the closer
the vote gets.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the president would be willing to pay a fine, if
part of a censure resolution, he said: ``If members in good faith
want to pursue that option and approach representatives here at the
White House with that option, we will listen and take anything they
say seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the House minority leader, Richard A. Gephardt, moved to
consolidate numerous Democratic plans to advance a censure
alternative by tapping Representative Rick Boucher of Virginia, a
senior member of Judiciary Committee, to lead the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher is seen as one of the Democrats most able to reach
across party lines on the deeply divided committee. He is expected
to work closely with Representative William D. Delahunt, a Quincy
Democrat who last week became the first committee member to
publicly announce he would propose an alternative resolution short
of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   In an indication of the intense friction on both sides, the
White House pounced on comments Hyde reportedly made about perjury
in 1987 during the Iran-Contra scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seems to me too simplistic to condemn all lying,''
Hyde was quoted as saying in a Los Angeles Times article. ``In the
murkier grayness of the real world, choices must often be made.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Lockhart: ``I think the chairman shows remarkable dexterity
in applying standards when it comes to the subject at hand. I think
in 1987 he made a rather impassioned and convincing argument that
circumstances allow lying.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Hohler of the Globe staff contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
