<HEADLINE>
HYDE'S REMARKS ON PERJURY ARE DEFENDED AND ATTACKED 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CENSURE, IMPEACH, IMPEACH-TEXT) 
(lb) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House and Republicans investigating
President Clinton traded snide remarks on Friday over what the
chairman of the House Judiciary Committee has said about perjury
and how he really feels about it.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman, Rep. Henry Hyde, unwittingly set the stage for the
exchange on Tuesday, in his solemn and seemingly uncompromising
remarks about the evils of lying under oath.
</P>
<P>
   ``If citizens are allowed to lie with impunity _ or encourage
others to tell false stories or hide evidence _ judges and juries
cannot reach just results,'' said Hyde, R-Ill. ``At that point, the
courtroom becomes an arena for artful liars and the jury a mere
focus group choosing between alternative fictions.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's remarks about the sanctity of words given under oath were
delivered in the investigation of the president's affair with
Monica Lewinsky and his attempts to keep it secret.
</P>
<P>
   But some people recalled what Hyde said in 1987, in Congress'
inquiry into the Iran-contra affair. Defending the Reagan
administration, Hyde said condemnation of all lying ``just seems to
me too simplistic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the murkier grayness of the real world, choices must often
be made,'' Hyde said of the Reagan administration's covert aid to
anti-communist rebels in Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's spokesman, Joe Lockhart, said Friday that Hyde ``shows
remarkable dexterity in applying standards,'' and that the
difference in his views over 11 years shows ``more about politics
than about conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Republicans on the Judiciary Committee replied Friday
night, ``Context does matter, and the facts of the Iran-contra
affair and President Clinton's affair with Monica Lewinsky could
not be more different.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one lied under oath, after swearing to tell the truth, and
no one ever lied for personal gain,'' said the Republicans'
statement, issued by their spokesman, Paul McNulty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
