<HEADLINE>
FLIGHT COMPUTERS BRING JETS TO BRINK OF CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration is investigating a near
mid-air collision between a Northwest Airlines jet heading from
Detroit to Bradley International Airport in Connecticut and an Air
Ontario commuter flight flying from Providence, R.I. to Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The close call Tuesday evening was caused by on-board computers
designed to prevent mid-air collisions, but in this case put two
aircraft on a collision course.
</P>
<P>
   It took human intervention _ a sudden call of ``traffic!'' from
an air-traffic controller in the Boston FAA center in Nashua, N.H.
_ to avert a possible tragedy. The two planes were flying at about
22,500 feet about 30 miles southwest of Albany, N.Y., FAA officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The computer system, known as TCAS for Traffic Collision
Avoidance System, is required by the FAA to be on passenger planes
with 10 or more seats. TCAS, designed to give warnings of nearby
aircraft, is praised by pilots as a safety tool, and since its
widespread introduction, reported near collisions have dropped
dramatically even as the number of flights have increased.
</P>
<P>
   FAA officials said the two planes came as close as they did _
within 300 feet of vertical separation and less than a mile
horizontally _ because the on-board computer systems told one plane
to climb and the other to descend.
</P>
<P>
   FAA spokesman Jim Peters said the investigation will include
examining how TCAS worked in this case.
</P>
<P>
   The TCAS system, which was in use in both planes, gives escape
directions by issuing only vertical commands _ ``climb'' or
``descend.'' Future systems will include horizontal commands.
</P>
<P>
   William Johannes, the National Air Traffic Controllers
Association representative on TCAS issues, said the association
``certainly believes that TCAS can provide an extra margin of
safety in some circumstances. However, in this case, the safety
system nearly caused a tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   The near collision occurred in an area that is heavily congested
with north-south flights from the New York metropolitan area and
flights heading to and from Boston, Hartford, Conn. and Providence.
But the two planes _ and a third taking off from Albany Airport _
were safely separated until the TCAS alerts prompted course changes
by the flight crews.
</P>
<P>
   The incident began when the TCAS on board the Air Ontario Flight
1445, a de Havilland Dash 8-100, flying from Providence with 21
people on board, warned the flight crew that traffic was
approaching. The traffic, officials said, was USAirways Flight 885,
a Boeing 737 traveling from Albany to Pittsburgh, that was on its
climb from the airport to a flight level of 21,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Adequate separation between planes in that airspace is 1,000
feet vertically or five miles horizontally. Because of that, the
USAirways flight, when it leveled at 21,000 feet as directed by
controllers would have posed no hazard to the Air Ontario flight.
But the on-board computer only saw a plane climbing toward it. That
prompted the Air Ontario TCAS to issue an alert and direct the
pilot to climb.
</P>
<P>
   When TCAS issues a command, flight crews react immediately,
rather than first requesting a course deviation from air-traffic
controllers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a situation where it was a busy traffic area and TCAS
advised the pilot that there was an aircraft in the area,'' said
Debra William, manager of corporate communications for Air Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest Airlines Flight 1186, an Airbus A-320 that seats about
150 people, was making its initial descent into Hartford from
Detroit and was at 23,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   According to Peters and officials at the Boston FAA center, the
TCAS on the Northwest plane then told that plane to dive.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our preliminary review, it would appear the closest
proximity between the Northwest plane and the Air Ontario plane was
300 feet vertically. Air traffic control working that airspace
advised the aircraft of traffic in the area.''
</P>
<P>
   The planes were so close that the targets on radar scopes in
Nashua merged into one, a controller told officials.
</P>
<P>
   Said Johannes, who is also the Boston Center local president of
the controllers association, ``The actions of controllers working
this airspace resulted in the pilot being alerted to the impending
mid-air collision and resulted in him taking corrective action
needed to prevent that collision.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Austin, a Northwest spokesman, said no report had been filed
by Flight 1186's flight crew and the airline was not aware of the
incident. Airline officials were attempting Friday to contact
members of the crew to ask them about the flight. Austin did not
have an actual passenger count, but said about 60 people were on
the flight.
</P>
<P>
   There is newer software for TCAS that can filter out air-traffic
patterns so that aircraft traveling on the same horizontal plane _
that are not on a collision course _ will not result in a cockpit
alarm going off.
</P>
<P>
   But the FAA has yet to mandate that the software be installed.
It was unclear whether the upgraded TCAS would have prevented the
near collision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
