<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4205 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-CONSTITUTION-UN     12-04 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-CONSTITUTION-UNVEILED05- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Higher education perks top features of Constitution rewrite
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser and Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The proposed new Texas Constitution unveiled
Friday would funnel more money into the University of Texas and
Texas A&AMP;M University to help them remain nationally competitive
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   University officials said the proposal, part of a longshot
effort to rewrite the state's patchwork Constitution, sounds like
it will help, but they want to hear more.
</P>
<P>
   The higher education overhaul is included in what could be the
most ambitious legislative effort of the upcoming session, which
begins Jan. 12. San Angelo Rep. Rob Junell and Mount Pleasant Sen.
Bill Ratliff, who chair the budget-writing committees, want to
throw out the 1876 Constitution and replace it was a streamlined
one packed with controversial proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone would agree that times have changed, the
world has changed,'' said Ratliff, who sees the effort as a
longshot worth taking. ``Texas needs an updated constitution to
guide us into the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   The retooled Constitution, about a fifth as long as the current
one, was filed as a single proposed constitutional amendment. It
would take a two-thirds vote in each chamber to send it to the
ballot on Nov. 2, 1999 for voter review.
</P>
<P>
   The higher education plan would not have an immediate financial
impact on the schools but would shift colleges in two higher
education funds so that state aid to the flagships and to Prairie
View A&AMP;M would ultimately go up, said Ratliff. At the same time,
some of the other schools in the UT and Texas A&AMP;M systems that are
now being shortchanged would get more aid.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to preserve the flagships as world-class
universities and to more fairly distribute money among Texas
colleges and universities, Ratliff said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over time, it becomes a dramatic change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   UT-Austin President Larry Faulkner said, however, he was not
expecting a windfall but didn't know enough to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the changes pitched by Ratliff and Junell would
remove six UT academic institutions, one A&AMP;M school and six A&AMP;M
agencies from the $7.2 billion Permanent University Fund endowment.
Those entitites would be shifted to the Higher Education Assistance
Fund, which, like the PUF, helps finance construction and academic
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, first discussed publicly earlier in the fall, does not
say what would happen to the six UT health-related institutions and
A&AMP;M's medical school. Ratliff said he and Junell are producing a
separate plan for financing the facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The Higher Education Assistance Fund, or HEAF, is made up of 23
schools, including the University of Houston, Texas Tech and
Southwest Texas State in San Marcos.
</P>
<P>
   Schools in the HEAF and the PUF have long been at odds with each
other over which fund provides the most support. UT System
Chancellor William Cunningham has argued that the PUF, with its
sharp spending limits, is not the cash cow that HEAF schools
believe it to be.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff said Cunningham is right. Some schools in the PUF get
half of what their counterparts in the HEAF get, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I need to learn more about the details,'' Cunningham
said, ``this proposal seems a very positive step in solving he
PUF/HEAF problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The PUFwould continue to pay the existing debt obligations on
construction bonds already issued. Because such bonds can 20 years
to pay back, Ratliff said the plan's financial benefits would
evolve over time.
</P>
<P>
   He expects all schools to gain money except for Tartleton State
University. Dennis McCabe, the school's president, said he was not
aware of the plan but ``would have trouble supporting something
that would hurt the students at Tarleton State.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Supple, president of Southwest Texas State, said unlike
some of his colleagues, he supports the plan. ``It's a myth that
the PUF schools get more money,'' he said. ``As long as it doesn't
do any harm to the HEAF schools, I support this.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff said the $175 million HEAF would be increased to $225
million under the plan, with another $25 million going toward an
endowment that is being formed for the HEAF schools. He expects the
HEAF to net $25 million more a year under the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the proposed new Constitution would give Texas
governors more authority and responsibility. Governors would
appoint all judges (who later would face voter review) and the
state comptroller, agriculture commissioner, land commissioner and
railroad commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   Junell and Ratliff had discussed converting the 15-member State
Board of Education from an elected to appointed panel, but opted to
make no changes.
</P>
<P>
   On the judicial side, the proposal calls for combining the Texas
Supreme Court and Texas Court of Criminal Appeals, which now each
have nine members, into a 15-member panel.
</P>
<P>
   The Bill of Rights is untouched, but the proposed Constitution,
for the first time, defines marriages as something that only a man
and a woman can enter into. State law currently bans homosexual
marriages. Putting it into the Constitution would make it more
difficult to end the ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm deeply saddened our Constitution would be cluttered up by
discriminatory language. It's a terrible sign they might be willing
to attack minority rights,'' said Diane Hardy-Garcia, executive
director for the Lesbian and Gay Rights Lobby.
</P>
<P>
   The current constitution established the concept of community
property but does not say who has the right to that provision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like once and for all we need to say who it is has the
right to access that constitutional provision,'' said Ratliff.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
