<DOCNO> NYT19981204.0456 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4213 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATRIOTS-MOVE-BOS &LR;      12-04 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-MOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS WEIGHING ANTITRUST ASPECTS OF PATRIOTS MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The day before Robert Kraft signed an agreement with
Connecticut to move the New England Patriots to Hartford, he met
with NFL brass in New York, and was assured that no other team
would replace the one leaving Foxborough, giving him exclusive
operating rights in the region.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what Kraft said publicly earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Attorney General Scott Harshbarger said Friday, his
office is investigating whether that promise violates state
antitrust and restraint-of-trade laws by unfairly stifling
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``My office is researching the possibility of legal action
involving the announced relocation of the New England Patriots from
Massachusetts to Connecticut and the NFL's policies involving such
relocations,'' Harshbarger said at a press conference Friday. ``I
asked my staff to look into this matter, especially with regard to
the NFL's reported assurances to the Patriots owner that if the
team left the state the league would not allow another team to
relocate to Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   However, a New England Patriots lawyer, the NFL, and even US
Representative Martin T. Meehan, who has filed a bill in Congress
to remove the threat of antitrust cases for the league, immediately
denounced any possible legal action by Harshbarger.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 19, the day Kraft signed the agreement with Connecticut
to move the team, he said he met with NFL Commissioner Paul
Tagliabue in New York the day before and was told the league would
not try to block the move, nor would it put another franchise in
the region.
</P>
<P>
   Such a promise would be unusual because the league generally
affords its franchises a 75-mile marketing radius. Boston, which is
99 miles from Hartford, would be considered a separate marketing
area. There are exceptions to those rules, however, and they are
subject to change by a vote of the NFL owners.
</P>
<P>
   NFL spokesman Joe Browne said Friday he is ``not aware of any
such conversation'' between Kraft and Tagliabue, ``and that is not
our policy.'' He also said the league does not have territorial
restrictions on franchises, citing the metropolitan New York area
where the Jets and Giants play in the same New Jersey stadium; and
California, where the Oakland Raiders and San Francisco 49ers play
across the bay from each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not have any policy that would restrict another team
into going into Boston,'' Browne said. ``However, it would seem
that after nearly 40 years of different Patriots owners struggling
to get a stadium in Boston that it might be a stretch to think that
the city fathers would build one for an outsider.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' lawyer, Atty. Daniel Goldberg, said Harshbarger's
legal argument is groundless.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is simply no basis to proceed,'' Goldberg said. ``I
think it's unfortunate that by issuing this press release he might
have created some false hope, and I think it's unfortunate that the
time, effort, and money that might be devoted to pursuing a legal
question were not devoted to moving the political process only a
matter of several months ago, to a point where the state might have
been able to keep the Patriots here.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the conversation Tagliabue and Kraft reportedly had:
``What was said is that New England has a team,'' Goldberg
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Harshbarger's motives may be less than pure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that, to some extent, they are designed as a
poke in the eye to the politicians who did not _ and it would be a
very long list _ do what was necessary to keep the Patriots in
Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger shrugged off questions suggesting the legal threat
was a slap in the face to the man who defeated him in November's
gubernatorial race: Paul Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   However, he did say that as attorney general, ``I feel I have
the responsibility to look at this matter and take some leadership.
But it's unfortunate it had to get to this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger said even if there were no other team waiting in the
wings to move here, the state should ``make sure this market is
open.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci appeared caught off guard by Harshbarger's action,
first reported Friday in The Boston Globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I really don't have a response,'' the governor said. ``I
think it's an uphill fight, let me put it that way. I'd have to
have my legal counsel take a look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Middlesex District Attorney Thomas F. Reilly, the man who will
replace Harshbarger on Jan. 20, said Harshbarger's office first
notified him Friday that he was looking into the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be cautious until I saw legal theory that would justify
that kind of action,'' Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Anthony, who runs the Consumer Protection Division in
Harshbarger's office, said she thought a decision would be made
before he left office as to whether a suit had merits.
</P>
<P>
   Any breach of the antitrust law would be an unfair trade
practice, which would violate state consumer protection laws,
Anthony said.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Hatfield, an assistant district attorney in Missouri,
agrees.
</P>
<P>
   Hatfield was on the legal team that threatened the NFL with an
antitrust case when the league refused to let the Rams leave Los
Angeles for St. Louis, where a stadium had been built in hopes of
luring a team.
</P>
<P>
   The case never went to trial because within several months the
NFL _ worried about losing the suit and being held liable for
treble damages _ backed down, allowing the transfer.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots case ``sounds anti-competitive to me, too,''
Hatfield said. ``The NFL has a history of attempting to intimidate
communities into not pursuing these teams. And they have, at times,
backed down. They've lost cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Meehan filed legislation last May that would remove the prospect
of antitrust liability for the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the league needs three-fourths owners' approval to
allow a team to move,'' Meehan said. ``If a renegade owner
threatens suit, they back down on the antitrust case, out of fear
for treble damages.'' He said the bill would allow the league to
make decisions based on merits, not concern for being hit with huge
damages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-04-98 2157EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
