u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUR-Q&AMP;A06-COX     12-04 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUR-Q&AMP;A06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL DECEMBER 6
 &HT;    Fur no longer an endangered species in fashion
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Not so long ago, when fashion folks spoke of ``the fur
flying,'' they were referring to the battle between mink coat
manufacturers and the anti-fur activists led by People for the
Ethical Treatment of Animals.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if the fur industry is to be believed, the anti-fur
movement has PETA'd out and the only fur flying is off the retail
floor.
</P>
<P>
   During their recent trunk show at the Phipps Plaza Saks Fifth
Avenue , husband-and-wife mink merchants Andre and Lisa Bisang
seemed to have shaken off all the residue from the past decade in
which their industry was shackled with the label, ``Politically
Incorrect.'' They said, with confidence, that their segment of the
apparel market has never been more competitive. And statistics
provided by the Fur Information Council of America support their
faith in fur's future.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1985, according to the council, the number of major
designers who showed fur in their fall/winter collections increased
fivefold: from 42 to more than 200. Citing ``three primary factors:
the economy, weather and fashion,'' council statistics showed fur
sales in the United States increasing slowly and steadily from
$1.20 billion in 1990 to $1.27 billion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss-born Andre Bisang grew up in the industry, but he
graciously fielded fur-related questions from the point of view of
someone who can't easily distinguish ``faux fur'' from real.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How would you explain fur's fashion resurgence?
</P>
<P>
   A: It started with the couture. And when fur came back to
ready-to-wear _ as an accessory, or just as an addition to garments
_ that really brought fur back to the streets and the magazines.
Fashion is almost unthinkable without fur anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What advances have taken place in fur manufacture in terms of
colors and textures?
</P>
<P>
   A: Color has never been more important that it is now. We dye
almost all furs in all the current fashion colors. Furs really dye
very well; sometimes they even look better when they're dyed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Have you noticed how people are less bashful about wearing
anything but fur-lined coats?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's very warm to have fur on the inside, and during the
period when it maybe was not so correct to wear fur, people wore
their fur on the inside. But this has turned into an attitude of,
``Why should I hide my fur? I have a beautiful fur. I want
everybody to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you design differently depending on the type of fur you
use?
</P>
<P>
   A: Chinchilla is the more fancy fur. It's not for everyday. It's
more dramatic, more glamorous. Mink is more of an everyday fur. We
do a lot more with mink; dyeing it, shearing it, plucking it. We do
all kinds of things to make (mink) look different and fancy and
fun. Chinchilla we leave as is, except for maybe dyeing it in
fashion colors.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How should a woman select her first fur coat?
</P>
<P>
   A: When it comes to buying her first fur coat, I think she
should buy a mink. Sheared or longhaired, dark or light, mink is
really the fur she'll probably get the most use out of.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whatever happened to PETA and the anti-fur movement?
</P>
<P>
   A: Their energy died out. The press is not interested in them
anymore. They don't make news anymore, and when they do they make
bad news. And I don't think they get the financial support anymore.
People realize that we have a lot more serious issues to worry
about and devote our energy to than being against fur. Being
against fur doesn't really help anyone at all.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the fur industry expanding, or is it controlled by a
select few companies such as yours?
</P>
<P>
   A: When you look at the list of designers who are using fur,
it's at least tripled over the last three years . . . a very short
period of time. I think there are 180 designers using fur now. They
start with a little trim here, some more trim there, a lining, then
an accessory piece. . . . You look to Paris and see fur handbags,
fur shoes, fur everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where in the U.S. are you most likely to see women wearing
furs?
</P>
<P>
   A: It used to be that Chicago was by far No. 1, then came New
York and so on. But now, since everybody's traveling and everybody
wants beautiful furs again, it doesn't matter where you live. We do
better in Florida than we do in New York. It's not where you live,
it's your lifestyle that matters.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
