<HEADER>
A4226 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKUBE-COLUMN06-COX     12-04 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL DECEMBER 6
 &HT;    A fall from grace, in postmodern style
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago, a man named Alan Sokal lured the emperor into the
public square and, by speaking in a mysterious tongue, goaded him
into removing every stitch of clothing he had on. He stood there
buck naked, the whole world laughing.
</P>
<P>
   It's still laughing, and the emperor wonders why.
</P>
<P>
   Sokal is a physicist at New York University. Politically, he
places himself left of center. But you can be left of center
without going completely over the edge. It amused Sokal to see
postmodern literary critics masquerading as people who knew
something of science. No one likes impostors, and Sokal set out to
expose them. He submitted to the cultural studies journal Social
Text an article arguing that quantum gravitational theory and
postmodernist philosophy were a perfect fit. He titled it
``Transgressing the Boundaries: Toward a Transformative
Hermeneutics of Quantum Gravity.'' Albert Einstein meets Jacques
Derrida, you could say.
</P>
<P>
   The journal's editors thought Sokal's piece profound, and it
appeared in the spring/summer issue of Social Text. Alas, on the
very day the issue came out, Sokal announced it as a hoax _ a
parody of the gibberish that passes for scholarship in the
humanities these days.
</P>
<P>
   Delicious malice in `Fashionable Nonsense'
</P>
<P>
   To say that the journal's editors had egg on their face doesn't
say enough. The entire culture that has grown up around
postmodernism, particularly in the humanities departments of
American universities, was dripping with yolk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like the genre it is meant to satirize,'' Sokal wrote in a
subsequent, nonparodic piece that the journal's editors rejected
(it didn't meet their rigorous standards), ``my article is a
melange of truths, half-truths, quarter-truths, falsehoods, non
sequiturs, and syntactically correct sentences that have no meaning
whatsoever (Sadly, there are only a handful of the latter; I tried
hard to produce them, but I found that, save for rare bursts of
inspiration, I just didn't have the knack.).''
</P>
<P>
   Writing like a modern literary critic is harder than people
think _ imagine yourself a cow standing on its hind legs and doing
the jig. Sokal is too modest; he brought it off with real panache.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Jean Bricmont, a physicist at the Universite de
Louvain in Belgium, he has reprised the ludicrous affair in
``Fashionable Nonsense: Postmodern Intellectuals' Abuse of
Science'' (Picador, $23),
</P>
<P>
   setting forth more fully his complaints with pseudo-scholarship.
In an appendix, he includes the parody that has made him a kind of
Salman Rushdie of postmodernism.
</P>
<P>
   Delicious malice, but why should it matter? It matters because _
in diluted form _ this is the intellectual climate in which
American college students are being educated. The first principle
of postmodernism is that there can be no objective truth and no
hierarchy of value. One consequence is that literature has become a
part of ``cultural studies,'' with no book or author better than
another. They are merely ``different.'' Or, as Professor Houston
Baker of the University of Pennsylvania felicitously put it a few
years ago, ``It's no different from choosing between a hoagy and a
pizza.'' And then, between bites: ``I am dedicated to the day when
we have a disappearance of those standards.''
</P>
<P>
   He should be doing cartwheels. The standards are out the window.
Sokal proved that.
</P>
<P>
   Fertile ground in Duke department
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't Sokal who made fools of these pretenders. They've
made fools of themselves, appropriating words and ideas from
sciences they scarcely understand and bankrupting what intellectual
integrity they can still claim. Theorists such as Derrida, Michel
Foucault and Jacques Lacan had become departmental pinup boys,
fawned over like rock stars.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere was it more hilarious than at Duke University, where the
English department became a hothouse for the newest French
fashions. For one brief shining moment, Duke was the place for
literary theory. The brightest star in the firmament was Fredric
Jameson, a comparative literature professor and Marxist critic. Red
Fred found that the more impenetrably you write, the more disciples
you attract. He has droves of them.
</P>
<P>
   It was at Duke that the inanities Alan Sokal parodied took
deepest root. The ground had been well fertilized.
</P>
<P>
   Then, two Saturdays ago, The New York Times reported on the
front page that Duke's once-celebrated English department had been
placed under what amounts to academic receivership, supervised by
the dean of the botany department. The gentleman may not be up on
his Derrida, but he is described as an authority on plant
respiration. The university has done what any of us would do. When
the yard's been taken over by weeds, you call in a specialist.
</P>
<P>
   It could have saved itself the trouble by spraying the first
shoots that appeared, but it cultivated them instead. It thought
they were flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-04-98 2202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
