<DOCNO> NYT19981204.0464 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4227 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUYING-GLASSES05-COX     12-04 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUYING-GLASSES05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Savvy buyers look into glasses
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eyeglasses often make it on the list of holiday purchases _ not
as presents, but as a way for patients to squeeze out the last
dollars of their yearly health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   As more employees participate in medical flexible spending
accounts _ a pool of tax-free funds they can use for health-related
expenses _ some discover they did not use as much money throughout
the year as they'd anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   And that means they must find ways to spend it by the end of the
year, or lose it _ one of the few conditions of the fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see an upswing in business as individuals search for ways
to use their spending accounts,'' said Dr. Peter Gordon, an
ophthalmologist with Eye Physicians and Surgeons. ``Sometimes, they
just buy the frames and wait to buy the lens.''
</P>
<P>
   Others might take the money to buy prescription sunglasses or an
extra pair to have in case they lose their contact lenses, said
Joanne Chambers, manager of Winn Way Opticians.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, patients can expect to spend at least $300 for an eye
exam and a pair of moderately priced glasses. A complete eye exam
by an ophthalmologist should cost from $80 to $100, according to
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no family history of eye disease, patients can have
an exam every year or two, he said. If there is history of problems
_ such as glaucoma _ patients should be examined annually.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that many health plans will pay for the exam,
he said, leaving patients only the price of the glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Patients have a variety of glasses to pick from, depending on
their vision needs and their aesthetic desires:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Basic frames cost between $80 and $160.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Single plastic lens, with a scratch coating and a ultraviolet
filter, range between $150 and $200.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bifocal lenses cost between $200 and $250.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Progressive lenses, bifocals with no telltale lines, cost
between $250 and $300.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, progressive lenses are the hot item among baby
boomers. Although they are more expensive, ``everybody wants to
look younger,'' Gordon said. Typically, customers will agree to
progressive lenses, unless they have had a steady, bifocal
prescription for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers said the progressive lenses are nice, but ``you don't
want to be cheap on this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably 50 brands,'' she said. ``But you need to
pick a good one, so you have less distortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Walt Cherniak Jr., spokesman for Aetna-US Healthcare, said
eyeglasses account for a significant number of flexible spending
claims, ``especially among people whose health plans do not offer
vision coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said the insurer doesn't see the paperwork for the
purchases by the end of the year. Instead, the insurer's busiest
time is in February and March, when employees file all the needed
paperwork before the cutoff dates employers have set for
reimbursing their workers.
</P>
<P>
   Eyeglasses aren't the only vision wear customers seek at the end
of the year. Many patients also buy contact lenses or inquire about
corrective laser surgery for far or nearsightedness, which costs
about $2,300 per eye.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
