<HEADER>
A4228 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEEMAY-COLUMN05-COX     12-04 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEEMAY-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Garden proves to be gourmet fare for wild creatures
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MCCAYSVILLE _ It all started with the azalea. I had bought one
of those dwarfs that bloom red around June. Newly propagated when I
got it, the little shrub didn't have much of a root system. So I
left it in its container, nursing it through the summer and
planting it in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   By September, the plant had developed a full head of buds, which
I envisioned bursting into flower next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, some other creature saw the buds as a meal; I learned this
one morning when I saw that the azalea's head had been sheared as
if by machine, cutting the plant in half, down to a 3-inch nub.
</P>
<P>
   That was in late October. Since then, I've made similar gruesome
discoveries throughout the garden. Some animal or animals _ and
I've yet to catch any in the act _ are feasting their way through
my hard-built space. As Lyn put it, ``Your garden is like a gourmet
restaurant with a view. The creatures probably stand on the hill
and tell their buds to come on in.''
</P>
<P>
   So it goes. Just as I was enjoying gardening in a place where
squirrels were not a problem, I get set upon by a hungrier menace.
For years, squirrels in Atlanta have unearthed small, new
plantings, occasionally chomping off pansy blooms. But, in the
mountains, I'd seen only a few squirrels cavorting in the woods,
none hanging around the garden. Rabbits are another story; I've
seen a lot of them, brown and wiry, bouncing along with abandon.
</P>
<P>
   And, at night, I've heard something that sounded much larger
turning over a metal garbage can. Possum? Coon? Bear? Is one of
them the hungry visitor? I don't think so. Could it be deer? (One
friend says he plants ``some for the deer, some for me.'') Or the
rabbit that hopped to within 10 feet before scampering away
guiltily when he saw Lyn and me sitting on rocks near the creek?
</P>
<P>
   The culprits remain a mystery, but the evidence grows.
</P>
<P>
   After the azalea, I noticed several horsetail stems cut to two
joints above ground. As time went on, more and more went down,
until nothing was left of the clump but stumps.
</P>
<P>
   With colder weather and scarcer greenery on trees and shrubs in
the woods, the feeding intensified. Pansies, of course, had their
smiling faces bitten off as soon as my back was turned. Purple
coneflower, surprising in its persistence, met its match as several
flowers got chopped off and left to rot.
</P>
<P>
   Whacked in half in rapid succession: a baby burning bush, a
4-foot butterfly weed, and a little pine with the misfortune of
having a tender top.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the favorite grazing plant was the dwarf mondo. I had
planted a new patch of it, which was spreading nicely, putting out
much new green. The other day, all of some two dozen clumps had
been chewed down to their roots. Strangely, the black mondo grows
untouched.
</P>
<P>
   Even stranger, new plantings of prickly pear were chomped and
even pulled out of the ground _ obviously by some mad eater
tolerant of pain.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, it is understandable that wild creatures feast on
these plants, many of which amount to exotic ``gourmet'' dishes
compared to what they get in the wild. Thus, the losses amount to
the price we pay for our need to mark the land with plants from the
outside.
</P>
<P>
   I'm hoping the damage isn't permanent. Meanwhile, the mystery
continues, with rabbits and deer my prime suspects. But, knowing
their cunning history, I also keep my eyes on the squirrels.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: leemay(at)bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
