<HEADER>
A4229 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOSES05-COX     12-04 1487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOSES05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Multifaceted character's life defies simple storybook portrayal,
some Bible scholars contend
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's a larger-than-life figure whose biography is the stuff of
one of the best-selling books of all time, whose figure is famous
in Renaissance art, and whose image as a liberator is invoked in an
anthem of the civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   He's Moses, a k a ``The Prince of Egypt.'' That's the title of
an animated depiction of his life scheduled for release Dec. 18 by
DreamWorks, the studio founded by Steven Spielberg, Jeffrey
Katzenberg and David Geffen.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-minute feature, nicknamed ``Zion King,'' stars the voice
of Val Kilmer in the Charlton Heston role of ``Ten Commandments''
fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's excellent. It is superb,'' says Rabbi Levi Meier, 52,
chaplain of Cedars-Sinai Medical Center in Los Angeles and one the
religious leaders invited to preview the film for theological
correctness. Meier's new book, ``Moses _ The Prince, the Prophet,''
is one of several new volumes on Moses timed to capitalize on the
DreamWorks film.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to create a lot of interest internationally about
the figure of Moses and how he takes people out of hardships
despite obstacles and impediments,'' Meier says. ``It's like we
need a Moses right now.''
</P>
<P>
   But other Bible scholars predict that, although the film may
provide child-friendly entertainment, it is unlikely to portray
fully the complex character of the man or myth whose story takes up
more of the Hebrew Bible than any other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a visually beautiful work, but it's the Sunday school
version of Moses,'' says Jonathan Kirsch, 48, book columnist for
the Los Angeles Times and author of ``Moses _ A Life.'' ``It's a
bland, highly simplified version of Moses just as the ones we get
in children's books and other stories. But that's not the Moses in
the Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirsch, a Conservative Jew, says he does not fault DreamWorks
for eliminating the more troubling portions of the life of Moses.
``After all, priests, rabbis and ministers have been doing it for
years.''
</P>
<P>
   From storybook pictures in primary colors, little children learn
about the baby whose mother fashioned a basket for him and floated
him down the river to save him from certain death. They see him,
staff in hand, beside a burning bush. They color pictures of the
Red Sea miraculously parting for his people to cross. They probably
don't hear that Moses ordered the murder of 3,000 apostate
Israelites who chose to worship a golden calf, or that he issued a
command to kill the women and children of the Midianites, the
people of a country where he once lived and where he met his wife.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bible, the story of Moses is scattered through Exodus,
Leviticus, Numbers and Deuteronomy. It is a remarkable tale of a
man whose relationship with God, or Yahweh, was so intimate that it
changed his very countenance, forcing him to wear a veil in the
presence of mere mortals. Although there are apparent
contradictions (three different names for his father-in-law, for
instance), Moses' resume as outlined in the Bible goes like this:
</P>
<P>
   He was born more than 3,000 years ago in the heyday of the
Egyptian empire to Amram and Jochebed, an Israelite couple of the
tribe of Levi. He had a sister, Miriam, and a brother, Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Pharaoh _ possibly Ramses II _ had ordered that all
newborn Hebrew boys be thrown into the Nile River, Jochebed made a
little basket for her baby, coated it with pitch, and set him
adrift. A daughter of the Pharaoh who had come to the river to
bathe found the baby, named him Moses and took him to raise.
Miriam, who was watching, offered her mother as a nurse.
</P>
<P>
   Moses grew up in the midst of royalty _ as a prince of Egypt,
but as an adult he identified with the Israelites and killed an
Egyptian for beating a Hebrew slave. When word of his action got
out, he fled to Midian where he married a woman named Zipporah,
with whom he had two sons, Gershom and Eliezer.
</P>
<P>
   While Moses was tending the fields of his father-in-law, the
Bible says, Moses saw a bush burning but not being consumed. Once
he had gotten Moses' attention, God told him to go back to Egypt
and lead his people out of slavery.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of plagues, Pharaoh let the Hebrews go. The Red
Sea parted for them to cross, then flowed back to drown the
pursuing Egyptians.
</P>
<P>
   In 40 years of traveling through the wilderness, when the
Hebrews were hungry, God sustained them with manna and quails, and
when they were thirsty, he made water flow from rocks. To establish
a framework for their society, he gave Moses the Ten Commandments.
</P>
<P>
   At times when the Israelites whined and backslid, Moses
intervened on their behalf with God. At other times, he became
furious with them himself. When they made an image of a calf to
worship, he ground up the idol, put it in water and made the
Israelites drink it, then ordered many of them slaughtered. And
when the Israelites killed all the Midianite men, Moses ordered
them to go back and kill the women, too.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all his efforts, Moses himself was not permitted by God
to enter the Promised Land. He died at 120 years old outside
Canaan.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, Kirsch sums up the figure of Moses this way:
``Moses is the most haunted and haunting figure in all of the
bible. To be sure, he is often portrayed as strong, sure and
heroic, but he is also timid and tortured with self-doubt at key
moments in his life. He is a shepherd, mild and meek, but he is
also a ruthless warrior who is capable of blood-shaking acts of
violence, a gentle teacher who is also a magician and a
wonderworker, a lawgiver whose code of justice is merciful except
when it comes to purging and punishing those who disagree with him,
an emancipator who rules his people with unforgiving authority.''
</P>
<P>
   The amplification of the biblical events of Moses life
chronicled in the midrash, a series of rabbinical commentaries
explaining biblical texts, adds even more layers to the
many-faceted Moses.
</P>
<P>
   Old Testament scholar Walter Brueggemann of Decatur's(Ga.)
Columbia Theological Seminary makes a distinction between what he
calls the ``historical Moses'' and the ``theological Moses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth of the matter is we know almost nothing about the
historical Moses,'' says Brueggemann. ``A great deal more can be
said about the theological Moses.''
</P>
<P>
   The theological Moses, says Brueggemann, is ``the quintessential
character of faith because, on the one hand, he trusts God
completely and, on the other hand, he has this enormous chutzpah in
the face of God. There is nothing docile about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Brueggemann talks in terms of two ``trajectories'' of the story
of Moses and the Israelites. One is liberation, as exemplified in
the spiritual ``Go Down, Moses'' sung by anti-segregation
protestors. The other is the obedience God expected when he handed
down laws to Moses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people get free of the sovreignty of pharoah, which is
oppressive, and come under the sovreignty of Yahweh,'' said
Brueggemann. ``It's very important that when you have the
liberation from Egypt, that Israel is not free simply to go off and
be free, but that Israel is liberated precisely for obedience to
Yahweh and Yahweh's commandments.''
</P>
<P>
   Each event in the story of Moses signifies something about God
and God's people, according to Brueggemann. The fate of the baby in
the basket shows God's hand at work through the women involved in
the incident and the helplessness of pharoah to counteract the will
of God. The burning bush illustrates how God's interventions
disrupt the status quo. The parting of the Red Sea shows that God
can use the forces of land and sea to bring about necessary
political liberation. And the imperfect Israelites and their leader
show that God's acts are not meted out only on behalf of those who
are somehow qualified.
</P>
<P>
   Moses's death outside Canaan is a metaphor for Israel,
Brueggemann says. ``Moses is the true definer of Israel. Israel is
characteristically a people that does not have land, but hopes for
land. It is theologically important that Moses's great enactment of
faith is an enactment of hoping but not having.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirsch says modern day readers can learn from Moses. ``I think
it's very refreshing to know that Moses was willing to get in God's
face and take him on,'' he said. ``I think that suggests that we
have much more freedom in the relationship between human beings and
God than is often suggested.''
</P>
<P>
   And Meier ends his books with ``central lessons'' that include:
Don't perceive yourself as a victim. Face your challenges. And,
have an ongoing dialogue with God.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all in our own Egypt,'' he said. ``The question is how
we get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
