<HEADER>
A4231 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RADKO-ORNAMENTSO5-COX     12-04 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADKO-ORNAMENTSO5-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From a Christmas fiasco, designer Christopher Radko builds an
empire _ one ornament at a time
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He's been called the Saint Nick of the '90s, the czar
of Christmas present _ the man responsible for restoring the magic
of nostalgia to a commercially corrupt holiday.
</P>
<P>
   In 12 years, New York designer Christopher Radko has created
more than 3,000 glass ornaments that are scarfed up annually by
millions, including more than 30,000 official collectors. Elton
John's tree is trimmed with them. So are Barbra Streisand's, Whoopi
Goldberg's, Katharine Hepburn's and Arnold Schwarzenegger's.
</P>
<P>
   And in Atlanta, John Marcum's Christmas tree is laden with more
than 1,000 of the hand-painted ornaments, inspired by holiday
folklore, children's stories, nostalgic Santas and whimsical
characters. ``Once you start collecting them and like the look, you
want to see a tree full of them,'' said Marcum, 39. ``It's that Old
World beauty that makes you want to cover a tree with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Retailing for $12 to $200 each (the average cost is $36), Radkos
are riding the wave of a huge revival in blown glass ornaments.
It's a voyage that's taken the former mailroom clerk for a New York
talent agency from a lunch-hour enterprise to a merchandising
conglomerate with $50 million in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   And to think it all started when the 37-year-old ruined
Christmas for his own family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was horrible,'' Radko said, recalling the tragedy that's
become legendary among his followers.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, it was his job to clean the Christmas tree stand for
his family in Scarsdale, N.Y. In 1983, Radko, then 22, decided it
was time to replace the rusted contraption with a new red and green
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the day after we put up the tree, one of the legs cracked
and the tree buckled and fell over,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Correction: The 14-footer crashed _ shattering more than half of
the 2,000 mouth-blown European ornaments his family had collected
for generations _ many from his great-grandmother's day. ``In a
sense, our tree was like a family diary, because everyone had
memories associated with their favorite ornament,'' Radko said.
``So when it crashed, we lost a connection with our heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone blamed me, and I felt really awful. So I realized I
had to make good and bring Christmas back to our family.''
</P>
<P>
   At that time, though, the only ornaments Radko could find in
this country were ones made from plastic or Styrofoam _``ones
without any heart and soul,'' he said. To add to his frustration,
while visiting relatives in Poland, he discovered the workshops
that once produced the beautifully crafted ornaments had closed
decades earlier.
</P>
<P>
   To solve the problem, Radko sketched some traditional designs
that hadn't been used since before World War II _ Victorian
icicles, umbrellas, balls, finials _ and hired a glass blower to
create several dozen ornaments from them.
</P>
<P>
   They never made it on the family tree. Friends bought them all.
After a second trip to Europe and more designs, he was bought out
again. Radko began showing his designs to Manhattan department
stores, and within a year sold $25,000 worth. By his second year,
he rang up $75,000.
</P>
<P>
   Today, more than 1,000 employees craft his designs in cottage
factories in Poland, Germany, Italy and the Czech Republic. Each
ornament _ some made from antique molds Radko found in his travels
_ takes seven days to produce. ``There's one woman who does nothing
but paint on eyelashes,'' Radko said.
</P>
<P>
   The ornaments are sold in Radko showrooms throughout the
country, including one in Atlanta, and more than 3,000 retailers,
such as Neiman Marcus and Saks Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Radko attributes their appeal to one thing _ nostalgia. ``The
memories of past Christmases are held in glass ornaments,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The more popular Radko's work becomes, the greater the demand
grows for his earliest ornaments. (One, ``Partridge in a Pear
Tree,'' which originally sold for $38, recently fetched $1,000 on
the collector's market.) Their value is enhanced because every year
Radko retires one-fourth of his designs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people started saying things like, `What happened to the
Santa with the purple hat?' I realized they were tracking what I
did year after year,'' Radko said.
</P>
<P>
   So several years ago he formed the Starlight Family of
Collectors. For $50 annual dues, members receive a list of dealers
and a magazine. Marcum, the Atlantan with 1,000 Radkos, is featured
in the current issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I thought I'd buy a few a year, but it sort of
snowballed that first year as Christmas approached,'' Marcum said.
``By then, I had a respectable treeful.''
</P>
<P>
   What Marcum admires most about the ornaments, made from stronger
Pyrex as opposed to scrap glass, is the craftsmanship. ``When you
touch the glass you immediately know the difference,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also realizes his investment is a far cry from the $10 he
used to balk at paying for a Hallmark ornament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can get very pricey,'' said John Veazey, another collector.
</P>
<P>
   He and Sid Stafford have collected more than 500 ornaments for
their tree. But the Loring Heights residents don't buy every design
just because it's a Radko _ only the ones they like.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, storage can be a problem. So far, they've removed all
shelves from their hall and bedroom closets to make room for the
boxes. ``Next, they'll go under the bed,'' Veazey said.
</P>
<P>
   He and Stafford also collect Radko's Halloween and Thanksgiving
decorations.
</P>
<P>
   Halloween and Thanksgiving? In recent years, Radko expanded his
merchandise to include decorations for other holidays, including
Valentine's Day, Easter and July Fourth. Yet, he scoffs at
criticism that he's overextending himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``My motto is too much of a good thing can be wonderful,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Radko's also quick to point out his work with charities. This
year, he donated a tree, valued at $50,000, to the Egleston
Children's Hospital Festival of Trees, which opens today at the
Georgia World Congress Center. (He appears in the festival's parade
at 10:30 a.m..) And for the past six years, he's raised more than
$1 million by designing ornaments sold to benefit a variety of
causes including AIDS _ a disease that took the life of one of his
sales representatives last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He helped me to realize the spirit of Christmas is something
that transcends the holiday itself and can be shared with people
year round if we just open our hearts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Away from the drawing board, Radko, who lives alone (``I'm still
taking resumes'') in Westchester County, decorates his own tree
with ornaments from next year's collection. He also trims one with
bird, fruit and vegetable ornaments for his parents.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he's back in the family's good graces. Just don't ask him
to clean the tree stand.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Egleston Children's Hospital's
</P>
<P>
   22nd Annual Festival of Trees
</P>
<P>
   When: 10 a.m.-9 p.m. today through Dec. 13 (noon-6 p.m. Sundays)
</P>
<P>
   Where: Georgia World Congress Center, Exhibit Hall A
</P>
<P>
   Admission: $8
</P>
<P>
   Information: 404-325-6635
</P>
<P>
   Danny Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
