<DOCNO> NYT19981204.0469 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4232 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-PSYCHO05-COX     12-04 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-PSYCHO05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The shock value of Van Sant's `Psycho' experiment
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The peculiar, new, shot-by-shot remake of ``Psycho'' is a good
demonstration of Norman Bates' hobby: taxidermy. It's a respectful
simulacrum, slavishly faithful to Alfred Hitchcock's storyboards
and camera movements. But despite the red stuff now splashing the
formerly black-and-white shower scene, the movie often feels
bloodless.
</P>
<P>
   Director Gus Van Sant has said he wanted to remake the 1960 film
for the same reason purists howled against the idea: because it was
a classic. His rationale is that pop songs are always being covered
by different artists.
</P>
<P>
   There's a difference, though: A singer brings a new
interpretation, a different voice, an altered musical arrangement.
The only significant changes in ``Psycho'' are its skillful cast
and the color stock. Since the shots are the same, and Bernard
Herrmann's brilliant, skittery score still infuses the movie with
spidery dread, it's weird to see Van Sant's name appear in the
opening credits. The prime pleasure of the movie is the way it
reminds you of how remarkable the original was _ the way it
completely reversed audience expectations halfway through, and of
course the astonishing angles and camera movements Hitchcock chose.
</P>
<P>
   OK, but enough about Hitch. Does the remake work or not?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, absolutely. And no, of course not.
</P>
<P>
   It's suspended in a weird time warp between the repressed,
Freud-obsessed end of the '50s, and our own funky, fluid-swapping
'90s. Marion Crane (Anne Heche) and her colleagues in her Phoenix
office wear '60s-flavored clothes (including Rita Wilson in the
receptionist role originally played by Hitchcock's daughter Pat).
But, while keeping most of it verbatim, original screenwriter
Joseph Stefano tweaks his script with more contemporary references.
</P>
<P>
   The change means Marion's sister Lila (Julianne Moore) can say,
``Let me get my Walkman.'' But in the next scene, the sheriff's
wife has a switchboard operator patch a call through to the Bates
Motel in old-fashioned style.
</P>
<P>
   In the remake, the sexuality simmering beneath the original's
surface is front and center, starting with the sound of loud
lovemaking in the motel room next door to Marion and her boyfriend
Sam (Viggo Mortensen), who walks around nude. And purists, beware:
Norman (Vince Vaughn) masturbates while he spies on Marion.
</P>
<P>
   These updates don't hurt, but Van Sant never seems to decide if
his movie is unfolding in the moral landscape of the '60s or the
present. What keeps you watching is the pleasant tension of
familiar scenes, shots and lines replayed by the new actors; it's
like an odd waking dream. Of the cast members, only Moore and
Vaughn really make the roles their own. She gives Lila a tough,
compelling edge that's a far cry from Vera Miles' shrill original.
</P>
<P>
   But Vaughn is the best thing about the movie. Making Norman's
sexuality palpable, he also gives an endearingly goofy,
giggle-filled performance. He makes this particular monster all too
believable as a guy you might meet on a long road trip. And he puts
his own mark on famous lines (``a boy's best friend is his
mother,'' etc.) without veering into camp.
</P>
<P>
   Van Sant generally follows Hitchcock's blueprint with great
self-effacement. That makes it even more shocking when he throws in
personal imprints at exactly the wrong moments. In the shower
scene, he inserts shots of swirling clouds (a fave image of his
``My Own Private Idaho''). Worse, in the staircase stabbing, he
throws in a wacko shot of a masked woman, and what appears to be a
windshield view of a large animal crossing a road.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do these nearly resemble ``Monty Python''-style visual
non sequiturs, these additions take us out of the scene, exactly
when the horror of what's happening should make us feel trapped.
Van Sant also slows down the fruit-cellar revelation of Norman's
mother, depriving it of its shock.
</P>
<P>
   The new ``Psycho'' is lovingly made and highly watchable. That's
not exactly the same thing as being good. It's an interesting
experiment with one big problem: It doesn't know what it's
intending to prove.
</P>
<P>
   ``Psycho''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Vince Vaughn, Anne Heche and Julianne Moore. Directed
by Gus Van Sant. Rated R for violence and sexuality/nudity. 1 hour,
38 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Slavishly faithful to Hitchcock's original shots
and storyboards, this remake is bloodless.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
