<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4246 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENDEAVOR-CURRIE05-COX     12-04 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENDEAVOR-CURRIE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flawless Endeavor takeoff makes up for delays
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KENNEDY SPACE CENTER, Fla._ Nancy Currie and her five crewmates
began chasing down a Russian spacecraft Friday after an
early-morning launch that lit up the Atlantic coastline here.
</P>
<P>
   Endeavour shook off weather worries and Thursday's scrubbed
countdown to lift off in the middle of a brief launch window while
its quarry, the Zarya space station module, sailed over the launch
site in its 240-mile-high orbit. Endeavour will slowly catch up
with the module to connect it with its own payload, the Unity
connecting node now stowed in Endeavour's payload bay.
</P>
<P>
   The orbital chase is the first step in an assembly process that
will span more than five years to create the International Space
Station.
</P>
<P>
   Currie is a 1977 Troy High School graduate, and at least one
faculty member was in Florida to watch her lift off on her third
and most challenging space mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was absolutely amazing. Everything happened so quickly and
then it was gone,'' said Carl Tompkins, who received an invitation
from Currie to watch the launch from a NASA viewing area about five
miles from the launch pad.
</P>
<P>
   A chemistry teacher who has won three teaching grants from the
Troy school district under an incentive program named for Currie,
Tomkins was impressed because of his science background.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got that much (more than 535,000 gallons) of
liquid oxygen and liquid oxygen (in the shuttle's external tank,)
you're basically sitting on a bomb,'' he said. ``The force pushing
the shuttle skyward must be incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   At liftoff, Endeavour's three main engines and two solid rocket
boosters were putting out about 7 million pounds of thrust.
</P>
<P>
   Launch managers said Friday's countdown and launch were nearly
flawless.
</P>
<P>
   ``The countdown went extremely well, especially when you account
for having to turn the vehicle around in 24 hours,'' launch
director Ralph Roe said.
</P>
<P>
   One of Endeavour's three auxiliary power units had to be shut
down when it overheated, but launch integration manager Donald
McMonagle said engineers believe the power unit's cooling system
simply iced up. He said it should clear up by itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got effectively a perfect vehicle in orbit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The on-time launch ended more than a year of delays for the
mission, which was originally scheduled for December 1997. Most
delays were caused by other schedule problems in the space station
program, but Thursday's scrub resulted from a false cockpit alarm
that halted the countdown just long enough for the shuttle to run
out of launch time.
</P>
<P>
   Zarya, Russian for ``sunrise,'' will provide propulsion and
power during the initial phases of space station construction.
Unity is a connecting node for future modules.
</P>
<P>
   Once the units are connected, members of Endeavour's crew will
be able to enter them without spacesuits, but nobody will remain
aboard it when Endeavour leaves near the end of the mission.
However, Endeavour crewmember Sergei Krikalev, a Russian cosmonaut,
is scheduled to return to the station in January 2000 as part of
the first three-person crew to live on it.
</P>
<P>
   Mars Climate Orbiter: 1:56 p.m. Thursday, Boeing Delta 2 rocket,
Cape Canaveral. Scheduled to begin orbiting Mars in September.
</P>
<P>
   Mars Polar Lander: 3:21 p.m., Jan. 3, Delta 2 rocket, Cape
Canaveral. Scheduled to land near Mars' south pole on Dec. 3, 1999.
Payload includes two microprobes that are to smash into the Martian
surface, testing new technologies and searching for traces of
subsurface ice. Key events of mission
</P>
<P>
   While Endeavour slowly closes in on the orbiting Zarya module,
former Troy resident Nancy Currie will be busy today preparing the
orbiter's main payload _ the Unity connecting node _ for docking.
Three spacewalks and work inside the mated units are scheduled as
first orbital International Space Station assembly work. Here are
approximate times for key events coming up on the nearly 12-day
mission:
</P>
<P>
   Later today: Currie uses Endeavour's robot arm to lift Unity
from its berth and install it on the orbiter's docking system.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday: Endeavour closes to within several feet of Zarya. Currie
grapples the module with the shuttle arm about 7:45 p.m.
Endeavour's jets are fired about 8:15 p.m. to dock the two units.
</P>
<P>
   Monday-Tuesday: 3 p.m. to 12 a.m., first spacewalk to make
connections and mount equipment on the space station. Currie uses
the robot arm to position astronauts Jerry Ross and James Newman.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday: 4 to 11 p.m., second spacewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday: 2 to 6:30 p.m., crew members enter space station
modules and check out systems.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday: 4:30 to 10:30 p.m., third spacewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 13: 2:30 p.m., Endeavour undocks from space station.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 15: 10:56 p.m., Endeavour lands at Kennedy Space Center.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
