<HEADER>
A4249 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILLIE-NELSON-HONORED     12-04 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLIE-NELSON-HONORED05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Willie Nelson receives Kennedy Center Honor
 &HT;    By Michael Barnes
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Willie Nelson won't wear the cowboy hat and
Indian beads.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely. But you never can tell.
</P>
<P>
   When the unconventional Austin singer-songwriter accepts his
Kennedy Center Honor tonight at a black-tie dinner, hosted in
Washington, D.C., by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, he
becomes only the second Texan to win the arts award.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Nelson will be praised through additional word and song
from the stage of the Kennedy Center Concert Hall in another
glittering ceremony that will air on CBS-TV on Dec. 30. He will be
joined as an honoree by actor and comedian Bill Cosby, the Broadway
composer and lyricist team of John Kander and Fred Ebb, composer
and conductor Andre Previn and actress Shirley Temple Black.
</P>
<P>
   Yet few people, even those who regularly watch the televised
gala, understand the purpose and criteria for the Kennedy Center
Honors, bestowed on 110 writers, musicians and other performing
artists since they were established in 1978 by producer George
Stevens Jr. and the late television variety producer Nick Vanoff.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, the gala is a fund-raiser and marketing tool for
the Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts, the megalithic complex
of theaters built 27 years ago on the Potomac River. Christened as
a memorial to President John F. Kennedy, who championed the arts
during his years in office, the center presents more than 2,800
performances a year to 2 million people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point, in terms of ticket sales, is to raise money,'' said
Larry Wilker, president of the Kennedy Center, regarding the
honors. While a certain number of tickets will be set aside for
dignitaries, the press, honorees and their parties, the remaining
seats will go to the center's corporate sponsors. ``They can't buy
tickets if they are not donors,'' Wilker said.
</P>
<P>
   The gala raises $2 million to subsidize the center's other
functions, but the program, one of the few such events broadcast on
a commercial network, does much more. It helps draw 3 million
visitors who tour the complex each year and allows the center to
maintain a high national profile.
</P>
<P>
   The selection begins early in the year when a committee of 132
artists makes recommendations for possible honorees. This group
runs the gamut from former Librarian of Congress Daniel Barenboim
to country singer Johnny Cash, with several former winners such as
Paul Newman and Sidney Poitier included on the panel. Most members
nominate only a few artists each year, Wilker said.
</P>
<P>
   Well in advance of the ceremony, the executive committee of the
Kennedy Center chooses a minimum of five honorees from the
recommendations. Only one artist has ever refused the honor, said
Wilker, declining to name that artist. A deliberate attempt is made
to mix artists from different fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to get a broad representation of the arts,'' Wilker
said. Many years, a popular actor and a representative from the
folk, rock, blues or pop fields comes up with an honor.
</P>
<P>
   The center simply defines the award as honoring ``individuals
who throughout their lifetimes have contributed significantly to
American culture through the performing arts.''
</P>
<P>
   Although TV producer Stevens is on the executive committee, no
attempt is made to boost ratings by choosing marquee names, Wilker
said. ``That has never entered the discussion as long as I have
been here,'' he said, citing dancers Fayard and Harold Nicholas, a
team of brothers who never achieved broad celebrity, but were
honored in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   While the younger National Medal of the Arts, conferred by the
president, has stolen a little of the glow from the honors, Wilker
believes his awards are still perceived as a prestigious national
honor.
</P>
<P>
   The only other Texan to receive the honor was the late Alvin
Ailey, the pioneer dancer and performer who was born in Rogers near
Temple. Most honorees were born in the Northeast, and many
immigrated from Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't look at geographic representation,'' Wilker said.
``Maybe we should.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, 65, maintains homes on Lake Travis and in the tiny town
of Abbott, where he was born. The multi-Grammy winner has released
more than 200 albums and acted in several movies. Known as a
touring road warrior with a generous heart, Nelson played a benefit
performance at Gruene Hall on Thursday night for Central Texas
flood victims before heading to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Kudos are nothing new to Nelson, but the Kennedy award reminds
of the broad reach of his music. His fans span the musical
spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Willie Nelson's impact on American music is indelible,'' says
rock guitarist Carlos Santana. ``He stands at the crossroads of all
the sounds and colors of his country. What he reflects is true soul
and sincerity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If America only had one voice,'' says country singer Emmylou
Harris, ``it would be Willie's.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
