<HEADER>
A4252 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRADLEY-POLITICS-ART-     12-04 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-POLITICS-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY OPENS `TRAINING CAMP' FOR HIS PRESIDENTIAL BID 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Expanded version with minor editing changes.)  (rl) 
 By JENNIFER PRESTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Bill Bradley, the former New York Knicks
basketball star who represented New Jersey for three terms in the
Senate as a Democrat, took the first major step Friday toward
running for president in the year 2000 and said he could foresee
nothing that ``would derail me at this stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Describing himself as rejuvenated in the two years since he left
office and now ``on top of my game,'' Bradley, 55, said he believed
he could offer the leadership needed to address the nation's
problems _ from the lack of affordable health care insurance to
childhood poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can unleash the potential of the American people,''
he said, standing in the gymnasium of a community center here. ``I
see the energy out there every day that makes the economy run,
makes the technological breakthroughs. I want to turn that energy
toward dealing with the problems in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who resisted efforts by supporters to persuade him to
run in 1988 and 1992, would most likely face a difficult fight for
the nomination. Despite his celebrity and track record raising
millions of dollars in previous campaigns, he would need to
overcome the well-financed organization that Vice President Al Gore
has built across the country over the last six years and the
inherent advantage Gore has as the nation's second-highest
official.
</P>
<P>
   Another challenge for Bradley would be in finding a message to
differentiate himself from Gore, and other possible Democratic
contenders. And Friday, Bradley resisted making such a distinction.
``This is not about Vice President Gore and me,'' he said. ``This
is about telling people what I believe, going out and talking to
people, as I have been doing for 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley took the first step toward a presidential bid by
formally creating a Bill Bradley Presidential Exploratory
Committee. He will meet with fellow Democrats in New Jersey over
the weekend to begin putting together the apparatus for a
presidential campaign, which will be based in New Jersey. Early
next week, he will travel to Los Angeles and San Francisco to meet
with supporters and begin fund-raising, his aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley will need to raise between $22 million and $25 million
in the next year to be able to successfully compete for the
nomination, particularly now that the presidential primary process
is likely to be front-loaded with contests in New York and
California on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley left little doubt that he was seriously committed to the
race. Although his family did not join him at the announcement, he
noted that he had the full support of his wife, Ernestine, and his
daughter, Teresa Ann, a junior at New York University.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is training camp,'' he said. ``This is when you get your
team together. You see how you relate to each other, try to work
out some plays, and the regular season is when you form the
official campaign. I can tell you that I have never gone to
training camp without expecting that I would be playing in the
regular season.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's advisers said they expected he would wage an
``anti-political'' campaign with an ``outside-the-Beltway'' message
that would seek to reach voters directly and tap into voter
frustration over the recent scandals in Washington. But Bradley,
trying to paint his campaign as a positive mission, said he would
not make the president's recent troubles an issue in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he spent 18 years in Washington, Bradley sought to
portray himself as an outsider. He often operated outside the
traditional party structure in the Senate as well as in New Jersey.
In the Senate, Bradley focused most of his efforts on overhauling
the tax system, and on Third World debt, race relations, the
environment, health care and education.
</P>
<P>
   When he left the Senate two years ago, Bradley declared that the
political system was broken. He said Friday that his complaints
then were about the amount of money in politics, the sensationalism
of the news media, and about politicians who did not believe in
core convictions. ``I am not sure that it has been proven what I
said,'' he said. ``But I think it is important to try to make
changes.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, he left open the possiblity of running for the
presidency. He had thought about it in 1988 and 1992, but both
times, he said in a recent interview, he had decided he was not
ready. In one of his books, ``Time Present, Time Past,'' he wrote
that he was partly concerned about privacy for his family, as well
as a fear of failure.
</P>
<P>
   He said he recently made up his mind to run because he had the
full support of his family and because he truly believed that he
was prepared this time. He described reaching a certain level of
peace within himself. He said he intended to tell the American
voters ``what I believe and take my chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Bradley left the Senate two years ago, he has played
various roles from professor to best-selling author. He taught at
Notre Dame, Stanford University and the University of Maryland. He
has also appeared on national television as an essayist for the CBS
Evening News.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also spent much of his time cultivating a network of
friends and supporters whom he will now try to rely on for money
and organizational help. Although Gore presents stiff opposition,
some political analysts said that Bradley's celebrity should assist
him and he would probrably lead other possible contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats considering making a bid include Sens. John
Kerry of Massachusetts, Bob Kerrey of Nebraksa and Paul Wellstone
of Minnesota, and House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt of
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic political consultants who represent Gore and other
possible contenders said they welcomed Bradley into the race.
``I've always thought it's going to be a big field,'' said Bob
Squier, a Democratic political consultant who is handling Gore's
campiagn. ``It's a prize worth fighting for.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, Mr. Gore is such a prohibitive favorite that it is
difficult to imagine any of the other candidates justifying a race
at the moment,'' said Larry Sabato, director of the University of
Virginia's Center for Governmental Studies. ``That can change
quickly. And Bradley is a genuine celebrity in the age of celebrity
of all sorts, real and phony. He has established his credentials in
the field of politics, and outside of it. He has a good issue base
that ranges from campaign finance to economic issues.''
</P>
<P>
   A former star basketball player at Princeton, Bradley went on to
win an Olympic gold medal. He was also a Rhodes scholar before
joining the New York Knicks. He played for the team from 1967 to
1977, helping them win two championships in 1970 and 1973 and
earning a reputation for his integrity by refusing to endorse
products.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
