A4253 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH05-COX     12-04 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP calls White House request of 4 days to craft Clinton defense
a stall tactic
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House angered House Judiciary Committee
Republicans on Friday by requesting most of next week to mount its
defense of President Clinton against possible articles of
impeachment and seeking to call witnesses that cover ground the
panel has already examined.
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde (R-Ill.) said he would
consider the request and respond as early as today. Hyde had set
aside Tuesday for the White House to present its case and planned
for a committee vote on articles of impeachment at the close of the
week.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans widely viewed the White House request as a stalling
tactic because the Republican majority over Democrats will shrink
to six when the new Congress convenes in January, offering a better
chance to defeat an impeachment vote on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly this is a desperate political play to push the
impeachment inquiry into the next Congress where the Democrats hope
to pick up a few more votes,'' said committee spokesman Paul
McNulty.
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers, noting that Hyde said when hearings began
last month that they could have ``unlimited time'' to present a
defense of the president, wrote a letter to the committee seeking
three to four days of hearings to cover the constitutional
standards for impeachment; standards for prosection of perjury,
obstruction of justice and abuse of power; and prosecutorial
misconduct of tainted evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The committee has already held hearings in each of those areas,
but White House Counsel Larry Craig and Charles Ruff state in a
letter delivered to the committee Friday evening that they have
been ``foreclosed from playing any role'' in those proceedings. The
White House said it was essential to the president's defense to
call several panels of witnesses, none of whom have been
identified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Short of a declaration of war, there is no more significant or
grave constitutional process than the impeachment inquiry,'' Craig
and Ruff wrote. ``This process must be deliberate, fair and
expeditious.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee Republicans indicated a reluctance to allow the White
House more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just stall tactics,'' said Georgia Republican Rep. Bob
Barr, a member of the committee. ``There is no way we will spend an
entire week listening to the White House attack Ken Starr and
raising vague legal theories.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House must have taken a vote count on the likelihood
of impeachment in the House and not liked the results, said Barr.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we get closer and closer to a floor vote they recognize
they are in serious trouble and they will do everything they can to
delay and avoid an impeachment vote,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House contended it was requesting the hearings because
the committee has treated Clinton unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our view that the proceedings to date have been
inadequate and incomplete in their exploration of certain important
issues relating to the proposed impeachment of President William
Jefferson Clinton,'' the attorneys' letter states. ``We feel it is
essential to the president's defense that we be able to call our
own witnesses and present our own arguments.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans on the Judiciary Committee will meet with
committee staff Monday to discuss the wording of three articles of
impeachment. At this point, those articles allege that the
president committed perjury, obstructed justice and abused his
presidential powers in an attempt to conceal his affair with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is widely expected to approve at least one article
of impeachment along party lines and forward it to the full House
for debate.
</P>
<P>
   That would require House Speaker Newt Gingrich (R-Ga.) to call
members back to Capitol Hill for a vote. Committee officials are
planning for that vote the week of Dec. 14, but it may be postponed
if Hyde gives the White House the time it has requested.
</P>
<P>
   If the House approves any articles of impeachment, the Senate
would immediately convene to hold a trial. Under its rules, the
Senate would have to convene at 1 p.m. the day after receiving
articles of impeachment from the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the White House is in the desperate mode,'' Barr said.
``They can spin the vote on impeachment all they want. But the fact
is he will go down as the second president to face impeachment in
the House and that's staring them into the face.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House proposal came at the end of a week of bitter
partisan feuding over the prospect of impeachment. The chances that
the full House would approve articles of impeachment appeared too
close to call.
</P>
<P>
   Vote counters predicted that the Republicans were gaining
momentum for impeachment after the way Clinton responded last week
to 81 questions from the committee. Moderate Republicans who had
been wavering said they were upset by Clinton's legalistic and
evasive answers.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Democrats believed they had enough votes from
moderate Republicans to stop the impeachment train in the House and
avoid a Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 20 Republicans had indicated they were seriously
considering not voting for impeachment. A smaller number of
Democrats were considered possible votes in favor of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   But censure motions that were being floated did not seem to
catch hold this week. And by Friday, even Democratic Rep. Charles
Schumer of New York, a staunch Clinton advocate, was saying in
interviews that it was no more than an even bet that Clinton could
avoid impeachment by the full House.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
