<SLUG> BC-WEIRDSHOP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (editors: note UNDERSCORE symbol should be used in place
of  `(UNDERSCORE)' in Web address   The Web's Weird Little Shops 
 &HT;       
 By Jamie Beckett 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
If your loved ones are hankering for ``Jerry Springer Trailer
Trash'' T-shirts this holiday season, the Internet is the place for
you.
</P>
<P>
   Along with standard fare such as books and toys, the Web is a
treasure trove of off-beat merchandise such as Loch Ness monster
salt-and-pepper shakers and a freeze-dried ice cream sampler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adventuresome shoppers can find a lot of unique products
available from smaller merchants on the Net,'' said Vernon Keenan,
a principal at Keenan Vision, an Internet research firm in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The low cost of getting on the Web _ putting up a site can cost
as little as $15 a month _ gives small, niche businesses a national
presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have is somebody with a passion selling to others
with a passion,'' said James Roche, chief executive of Fort Point
Partners, an e-commerce consulting firm. ``When you pile all of
these people together _ which you can do on the Web _ you can
create critical mass.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the specialty sites don't advertise, and many don't show
up in online shopping guides provided by Yahoo, Excite and other
Internet portals. But if you're looking for a specific item, it
will probably turn up in a general online search. If you just want
to be surprised, do what we did _ ask a few frequent Web surfers to
point you to some of their favorite sites for off-the-wall stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to dazzle a stargazer? At  &LR; www.moonshop.com &LR; , you can
snag some of ``the cheapest real estate in the universe'' _ a chunk
of lunar property for $15.99.
</P>
<P>
   Is your mate an Aussie (or Aussie aficionado)? Try
 &LR; www.coop-bookshop.com.au  &LR; for a tome you probably won't find at
Barnes and Noble: ``The Aboriginal Naming Book _ Australian Guide
to Naming Your House or Boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking to spice up that relationship? A bottle of Rigor Mortis
hot sauce, along with dozens of other fiery tongue-tinglers, can be
had at  &LR; www.hothothot.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Folks shopping for Hanukkah presents are unlikely to find many
menorahs at the mall. But at  &LR; www.jewishmall.com &LR; , you can choose
from a selection of traditional menorahs as well as one sporting
the colorful image of Curious George the monkey and another shaped
like a racing car.
</P>
<P>
   For ``The Rugrats' Book of Chanukah'' (and companion video), go
to  &LR; www.jewishstore.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Shopping for a space fan? Check out &LR;  st1.yahoo.com/nasa &LR; , for
freeze-dried ice cream (like the astronauts eat), a mini-space
shuttle that talks or a Kennedy Space Center cap.
</P>
<P>
   For the revolutionary on your list, there's
 &LR; www.unamerican.com &LR; , where two San Franciscans sell ``We're
Doomed'' stickers, ``Drug Me'' mugs and ``Wage Slave'' T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   For those who want to do good this holiday season, United Way of
the Bay Area has  &LR; www.helpakid.com &LR; , where you can grant gift
wishes for disadvantaged Bay Area kids. Toys for Tots, together
with Visa and eToys, has a similar program on a national scale at
 &LR; www.etoys.com/html/et(UNDERSCORE)promo135et.shtml. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Feeling adventuresome? You might explore  &LR; www.biganimals.com &LR; ,
where a San Francisco photographer offers adventure trips to
far-flung spots to photograph great white sharks, killer whales and
other predators. You'd better be feeling flush, too: Prices range
from $950 to $5,200 per person.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for something unique for that pal who has everything?
How about Commuter Voodoo, a soft doll and a collection of pins for
those road rage days. The site,  &LR; www.mcphee.com &LR; , also offers
Nunzilla, the fire-breathing wind-up nun, the Loch Ness
salt-and-pepper shakers, a plastic hopping pig head and lots of
other silly stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our product is perfect for the Web because you can't get it in
stores,'' said Sherrie Holdridge of Archie McPhee &AMP; Co., which has
a traditional store in Seattle. McPhee, which has been in business
for 19 years, set up its Web site three years ago. This year,
Holdridge said, is the company's biggest on the Web so far.
</P>
<P>
   Not all specialty sites are small businesses. That Jerry
Springer T-shirt, along with Rosie O'Donnell's biography, a South
Park Dead Kenny beanie and an Andy Griffith Show Trivia Game can be
had at the E Entertainment Television site,  &LR; www.eonline.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
