<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOFA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BofA to Try Spin Tactics  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
BankAmerica Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Hugh McColl will
meet with state and local officials next month in an attempt to
mend fences amid a growing furor over the North Carolina bank's
treatment of California communities and female employees.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the bank announced it will eliminate 300 brokerage
jobs nationwide _ one of the first big job cuts &UR;  &LR; since McColl's
NationsBank's acquired BankAmerica and took its name in September.
The bank has said it ultimately will cut 7,000 to 8,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   McColl plans to meet with California Assembly Banking and
Finance Committee Chairman Louis Papan, D-Millbrae, and other
legislators during a previously scheduled trip to the state, BofA
spokesman John Keane said.
</P>
<P>
   The new BofA chief is also trying to arrange meetings with local
elected officials in California, Keane said, including possibly San
Francisco supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting with state lawmakers ``will give us an opportunity
to assure local legislators that our commitment to the state is
steadfast and that we will conduct ourselves as a community-minded
bank, as BofA and NationsBank always did,'' Keane said.
</P>
<P>
   In other efforts to make peace, BofA officials met with
representatives of California advocacy groups this week, including
San Francisco's Greenlining Coalition and California Reinvestment
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The bank's conciliatory gestures come as Papan's committee
threatens action that could lead the state to withdraw business
from BofA.
</P>
<P>
   The committee early next week will send letters to the state
treasurer and state comptroller asking for a list of all state
contracts, investments and deposits held by BofA, Papan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a big customer of BofA,'' Papan said. ``It could get to
the point where BofA begins to worry about doing business with the
state.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco supervisors may push for similar action at the
municipal level, Supervisor Michael Yaki said in an interview
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Moves to sanction BofA come on the heels of complaints by
activist groups that the bank won't negotiate formal agreements
governing its community lending and charitable giving.
</P>
<P>
   California officials are also angered by a Chronicle report that
all 10 of the old BofA's top female executives were demoted or
resigned after the new bank offered them lower-ranking jobs.
</P>
<P>
   BofA has countered by stressing its pledge to earmark $350
million for community development nationwide over the next 10 years
and increase its charitable donations in California.
</P>
<P>
   To defuse criticism about the departures of female executives,
McColl yesterday sent a memo to employees emphasizing his
commitment to promoting women at the bank and describing reports on
the subject as ``inaccurate and inflammatory.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout my career, I have made it a personal commitment to
coach and mentor women officers,'' said the memo, copies of which
were made available to The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the bank said the 300 brokerage job cuts it announced
represent 28 percent of its total brokerage workforce.
</P>
<P>
   The bank made the move because of a slowdown in business and to
eliminate overlapping operations as it combines the brokerage units
of the old BofA and NationsBank, spokesman Chris Schildz said.
</P>
<P>
   Positions will be eliminated in San Francisco, Charlotte, N.C.,
and other locations, Schildz said, though he declined to specify
how many employees would get pink slips in the Bay Area. The bank
will complete the cutbacks by the end of March.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-04-98 2240EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
