<DOCNO> NYT19981204.0485 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4258 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PACBELL-SFCHRON &LR;      12-04 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACBELL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Ad Campaign By Pacific Bell Attacks AT&AMP;T  &HT;       
 By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Just days after being told it had not sufficiently opened
California's telephone market to competition, Pacific Bell is
waging an attack against AT&AMP;T Corp., saying the long-distance giant
is stifling competition in the long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   In an ad campaign that begins Saturday, Pacific Bell accuses
AT&AMP;T of thwarting competition by funding a California consumer
group that lobbies against Pac Bell. Pac Bell said the group wants
to prevent competition in order to protect AT&AMP;T's long-distance
market share.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell and AT&AMP;T have been sparring during the past three years
as each company has tried to move onto the other's turf. Pac Bell
wants to enter the lucrative long-distance business, and AT&AMP;T wants
to get a slice of the local market. Both companies have accused
each other of thwarting competition and denying customers a choice.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a state Public Utilities Commission judge said Pac
Bell had not sufficiently opened the local market to competition
and should not be allowed into long-distance.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't stop the company from placing blame on AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   The ads, which will run on TV and in newspapers, say if AT&AMP;T
supported competition, ``they would not hide behind `grass roots'
groups to fight it.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads refer to Californians for Telecommunications Choice, a
statewide, nonprofit group that pitches itself as ``dedicated to
giving Californians true freedom of choice when it comes to
deciding which phone company they want to use.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of CTC's money comes from AT&AMP;T and other Pac Bell
competitors. The group is one of Pac Bell's harshest critics and is
lobbying against several Pac Bell initiatives, including its
attempt to provide long-distance service in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that California's consumers deserve to know the truth
about who is trying to influence them,'' said John Britton, a
spokesman for Pac Bell. ``The purpose of CTC and AT&AMP;T is to limit
consumer choice and keep Pac Bell out of long-distance for as long
as possible because AT&AMP;T knows that Pac Bell will be a formidable
competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads challenge AT&AMP;T to ``stop playing name games and focus on
what we're focused on: open, honest competition.'' They will run on
TV in the Bay Area and Sacramento beginning today and in print ads
across the state on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Kathi Oram, a spokeswoman for AT&AMP;T, said the ads are an attempt
to divert attention from the fact that Pac Bell has not opened its
local market to competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue is that they're still a monopoly and that they
haven't opened the market to competition,'' Oram said. ``This is
not about AT&AMP;T versus Pac Bell. It's about what state regulators
have said _ that Pac Bell has not opened the market to
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Britton said the judge's proposed ruling on Pac Bell's
long-distance application had nothing to do with the company's
decision to run the ads. He said the company wants to shed light on
CTC and its backers.
</P>
<P>
   Regina Costa, a telecommunications analyst with The Utility
Reform Network, said Pac Bell is the company that's thwarting
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is kind of like the classic example of the pot calling
the kettle black,'' Costa said. ``Pacific is saying we're committed
to open and honest competition and the commission has just ruled
that ... they didn't comply with federal law and have been
operating in ways that would ensure we don't have a choice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
