</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS KNOW STAKES ARE HIGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ UCLA practiced in the rain Tuesday for the first time
this season. The balls were wet and heavy. Part of Spaulding Field
looked like a tractor-pull surface, and players were caked in mud.
</P>
<P>
   When the coaches gathered that evening to review video, they
expected to see slop _ and sloppiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pouring rain, and we looked at practice and thought,
`Oh, gosh,''' Bruins coach Bob Toledo said. ``But they blocked the
right guys and they didn't drop the ball. They were doing things
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``That showed focus. They know what's at stake. They've got
great leadership. I can't feel any better than I do now.''
</P>
<P>
   How will he feel this morning before kickoff against Miami, when
the weight of history descends? How will the Bruins feel when they
enter the storied Orange Bowl? Six times in the venerable stadium _
and seven times overall _ the Hurricanes have stopped winning
streaks of 10 games or more. UCLA's stands at 20.
</P>
<P>
   And how will the Bruins feel at kickoff, with an undefeated
season and probable berth in the Fiesta Bowl at stake _ not to
mention $6 million for the Pacific-10, a Rose Bowl bid for Arizona,
a Holiday Bowl invite for Oregon and immeasurable prestige and
exposure?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we play better when the stakes are high,'' captain
Larry Atkins said. ``When there's more on the line and there's more
to lose, we play with a sense of urgency. We concentrate harder,
because we can't afford to make a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Washington game was a chance to clinch the Rose Bowl. USC
game was our rival and a chance to go through the conference
undefeated. This time, our motivation is to play in the Fiesta
Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins prepared 2{ weeks for this game, their first visit to
Florida in 57 years. They practiced one week in September, before
Hurricane Georges caused the cancellation. They worked out three
days last week, before Thanksgiving break. Add this week, and
they've prepared more for Miami than they do for bowl games.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the stakes and the opponent, the time was justified.
The Hurricanes are talented and unpredictable. Will they play like
the improving young team that was 7-2 before Thanksgiving, or like
a team devastated by a 66-13 loss to Syracuse Nov. 28 _ the
second-worst loss in school history?
</P>
<P>
   Beyond their talent _ senior quarterback Scott Covington (a
Laguna Hills native), powerful tailback Edgerrin James, swift
receiver Santana Moss and standout defensive end Derrick Ham _ the
Hurricanes will test UCLA's emotional resolve.
</P>
<P>
   They will come fast and they will come hard, with a defense as
athletic as USC's. They will posture and they will insult. They'll
taunt UCLA like it hasn't been taunted before. Probation or no
probation, rebuilding or no rebuilding, the Hurricanes have not
lost all of their South Florida swagger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be interesting to see how we react,'' said injured UCLA
receiver Freddie Mitchell, a Lakeland, Fla., native. ``It'll test
our mental state and our heart. Miami's going to talk some noise.
They're fast, and they know they're good. If we come in with our
minds in a certain place, we can easily be upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``I already talked to (tailbacks) Jermaine (Lewis) and DeShaun
(Foster). I told them to get ready to get hit hard, and don't go
thinking it's an automatic win.''
</P>
<P>
   Note: Toledo, 52, is negotiating a new contract that will make
him one of the highest-paid coaches in the Pac-10 and keep him at
UCLA for the rest of his career, athletic department sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo's current salary ($453,000 per season) will rank ninth in
the league if Arizona coach Dick Tomey's new $500,000-per-year deal
is approved next month. USC's Paul Hackett is the league's
highest-paid coach, reportedly making $640,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo and athletic director Peter Dalis met with administration
officials Nov. 25 and hope to have the contract completed this
month, one source said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
