<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIG12NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART IMPRESSES WILDCATS' COACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Kansas State coach Bill Snyder said he has spent
most of the past 24 hours watching videotapes of Texas A&AMP;M's
victories against Oklahoma State and Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the last games in which A&AMP;M quarterback Branndon
Stewart, an emergency replacement for the injured Randy McCown
(broken collarbone), competed. Stewart, a fifth-year senior from
Stephenville who will start in today's Big 12 championship game,
was 18-of-28 for 292 yards and three touchdowns in those games and
didn't throw an interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw exceedingly well,'' Snyder said of Stewart, who was
elevated to the starting role when McCown was scratched Thursday
night. ``I personally don't sense any difference in their two
quarterbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's last snap came on Nov. 7, when he played the entire
game in a 29-0 victory against Oklahoma. A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum said
he is confident that Stewart, who has a career mark of 19-10 as the
Aggies' starting quarterback, will not be affected by his prolonged
inactivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Branndon is relaxed. He's reached a point in his career where
he doesn't let a bunch of outside distractions keep him from doing
what he's trying to get done,'' Slocum said. ``He's looking forward
to the game, and I think he'll play well.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Slocum said he is comfortable placing the pressure on
Stewart and the offense, which ranks 95th nationally among 112
teams in Division I-A.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a chance in this game if everything comes down
to defense,'' Slocum said. ``We've got to maintain possession of
the football, make some first downs and do something on offense.''
TWO WILDCATS RETURN Kansas State coach Bill Snyder said yesterday
that two players considered doubtful earlier this week will start
today. Tailback Eric Hickson, the team's leading rusher (888 yards,
nine touchdowns), and cornerback Gerald Neasman (one interception,
five pass breakups) made enough progress during practice to regain
their starting jobs. Both players sat out the team's Nov. 21 game
against Missouri because of injuries. COUNTING ON EXPERIENCE
Although his team was swamped by Nebraska, 54-15, in last season's
Big 12 title game, Slocum said the experience should prove
beneficial today.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got to the game against Nebraska, we were all eyes,''
Slocum said. ``That won't happen again. Kansas State may win, it
won't be because our guys are in awe of Kansas State. Having played
in this game last year gives us an advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that has an impact on our players and this
program,'' said Snyder, whose team will be playing for Kansas
State's first conference championship since 1934. ``When you get
between the lines, it all seems to even out.'' EXTRA POINTS Snyder
said he would meet with Mike Stoops, the Wildcats' defensive
coordinator, after today's game and discuss Stoops' interest in
joining staff of his brother, Bob, who was named the coach at
Oklahoma Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder, on having an extra week to prepare for this game than
A&AMP;M: ``You never know about open dates. We had an open date before
our game against Colorado \Ra 16-9 victory\S and played our worst
game of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Solcum on A&AMP;M's season: ``This could've been a 6-5 team if not
for the character of the players. We had plenty of chances early to
get separated. Just playing on ability, this team is not going to
win 10 games, The chemistry is as solid on this team as any we've
had in a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
