<DOCNO> NYT19981204.0509 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4292 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEBRETON-TEX     12-04 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBRETON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M WIN WOULD AVOID WASTED YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ In Aggieland, where tradition marches to its own
drum, the old dogs are barking again _ and we don't mean Reveille.
</P>
<P>
   Add it up, math majors. Take one golden season, multiply it by a
seven-point beating of mighty Nebraska, then divide nearly
everything by a two-point loss to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M's once-glittery season has lost its luster. And even
before his Aggies face a Kansas State team brimming with purpose
today, coach R.C. Slocum has heard his name taken in vain again.
</P>
<P>
   A loss to the Wildcats today would leave the Aggies on a
two-game losing streak going into a bowl game. Worse, it would
remind Slocum detractors of a tired, old statistic _ the one about
R.C.'s record against teams in the Top 10. One win in 10 seasons,
if you're keeping score at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could care less about that,'' Slocum barked back, as A&AMP;M
prepared for its date in the Big 12 Conference title game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've won a bunch of games that you could classify as big
games. If somebody wants to take this game and write about it that
way, I could care less. I'll take our record and put it up against
anyone else's.''
</P>
<P>
   A 10-2 record, granted, is nothing to launch a witch hunt over.
Slocum's problem is that the second loss came at the hooves of the
dreaded Longhorns. All that bonfire wood wasted.
</P>
<P>
   Losing to Florida State in August is one thing. But losing to
Texas on Thanksgiving weekend remains an Aggie's worst stomach
ache.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still won 10 in a row,'' said injured quarterback Randy
McCown. ``It's been a good year. We beat Nebraska. We got into the
Top 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``But around here, you always remember when you lose to Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The concern at A&AMP;M is that those memories haven't followed the
Aggies to the banks of the Mississippi. Tight end Dan Campbell of
Glen Rose confessed that after the loss to Texas, he and his
brother drove back to College Station in complete silence. Campbell
locked himself in his apartment for two days, before finally
emerging for last Sunday's practice.
</P>
<P>
   The A&AMP;M team, therefore, that answers the roll call against
undefeated Kansas State today could be filled with either
square-jawed resolve or untimely self-pity. You wonder if the
confidence has run dry since beating Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say we can't win big games,'' Slocum answered, ``the logic
in that statement is missing.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, this is another big one, in a manner of speaking. Only
three years in existence, the Big 12 championship showdown has yet
to be embraced as the football Armageddon it was once hyped to be.
The Trans World Dome is expected to sport ample elbow room.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State needs to win _ and, likely, to win impressively.
The Wildcats need to send signals to pollsters and computers that
they are every bit as No. 1-worthy as the two teams that presently
``rank'' ahead of them, Tennessee and UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M, in essence, is playing today in hopes of rekindling their
season's flame. K-State, on the other hand, wants to win by a
hundred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beating Kansas State can salvage the season,'' McCown said.
</P>
<P>
   The words still ring from last season, when the Aggies dropped
their final two games, to Nebraska in the Big 12 title game and to
UCLA in the Cotton Bowl, and star linebacker Dat Nguyen called it
``a wasted year.''
</P>
<P>
   Great teams are defined by the big games they win. The losers
find other adjectives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a great season,'' Slocum said. ``We're 10-2. We're
happy to have another game to play. We're playing a team that one
poll has ranked No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``So there are a bunch of motivating factors here.''
</P>
<P>
   The specter of another ``wasted year'' hangs like a khaki cloud
over Slocum's team. Whether he has convinced his McCown-less team
otherwise will be one of the things worth watching today.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't the Fiesta Bowl, but for the Aggies, it's worth trying
to light another fire with.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge of rekindling his team prompted Slocum to search
for a country comparison this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like the old earthworm,'' Slocum said. ``He's
digging around in the dirt all day, and it's not much fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it beats the heck out of going fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's digging starts at 3:30 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-04-98 2257EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
