<HEADLINE>
JUNIOR COLLEGE RIVALRY REACHES BOWL GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CALAWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEDFORD, Texas _ Two of the top football teams in the National
Junior College Athletic Association will renew their rivalry today
in the second annual Red River Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Northeastern Oklahoma A&AMP;M College (8-3), ranked 12th in the
final regular-season NJCAA poll, meets Coffeyville (Kan.) Community
College (6-3) at 1 p.m. today at Pennington Field in Bedford.
</P>
<P>
   The matchup has tradition and a history of rivalry.
Northeastern, from Miami, Okla., and Coffeyville have combined to
win nine NJCAA national titles, and they are located within 50
miles of one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are not playing for a national championship, this is the
next best thing,'' Northeastern coach Dale Patterson said. ``This
is a renewal of the Coffeyville rivalry. Even though we haven't
played in awhile, there is a rivalry still there because the
schools are so close and you want to win for recruiting purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to win this game and finish the year 9-3. It sounds a
lot better than 8-4. Any time you go out and play a game, it is a
matter of pride. We want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the series dates to 1925, the game today marks their
first meeting in a bowl game and their first meeting since 1995.
They were chosen for the bowl as at-large teams.
</P>
<P>
   Northeastern, which has six national titles, owns a 23-9-2
advantage in the all-time series.
</P>
<P>
   Northeastern has won six consecutive games and is led by a
balanced offense. Tailback Josh Scobey has 1,067 yards rushing and
quarterback Sherad Poteet has passed for 1,680 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Coffeyville freshman Thad Ward leads the Red Ravens' I-formation
offense. He has rushed for 871 yards and scored 10 touchdowns. Ward
is one of 10 freshman starters for Coffeyville.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great opportunity for the kids,'' Coffeyville coach
Skip Foster said. ``I have heard Bedford does a great job with the
Red River Bowl. I know the kids are looking forward to going down
there and playing. Most important, it gives the kids a chance to
play in one of the postseason bowl games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
