<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REFEREES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE ANNUAL COMPLAINTS ABOUT NFL REFEREES WORTH A FLIP?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE FISHER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Some officials' calls in the NFL are by
nature so close that they come down to ``a flip of a coin.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine, but shouldn't NFL referees be able to keep the actual
flips of the coins straight?
</P>
<P>
   The quality of NFL officiating is the centerpiece of an annual
debate that's raged ``since the beginning of football time,'' NFL
scouting guru Gil Brandt said. Therefore, accusations from league
executives, players and observers suggesting that officiating is at
an all-time low is definitely not new and probably not accurate.
</P>
<P>
   The most glaring example of NFL refereeing being all too human
came on Thanksgiving Day in the Pittsburgh-at-Detroit meeting. The
two clubs were tied after regulation, so a coin toss was needed to
determine which team would get the ball first in overtime. Detroit
was given the ball _ and, in the minds of the Steelers, given the
game _ because of an apparently mishandled toss of the coin.
</P>
<P>
   That call was one of a handful in the Detroit-Pittsburgh game
that TV cameras showed to be questionable. The presence of the
media might be one reason officiating seems worse than it was in
previous eras.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had that coin-flip thing happened in a Colts-Bengals game,
nobody might've noticed,'' Brandt said. ``But you've got cameras
everywhere, you've got technology everywhere. I still say it's a
shame we can't harness the available technology to help officiate
the games.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandt remains a champion of the use of replay, a measure of
reviewing controversial calls after the fact that continues to be
voted down by NFL owners. Some calls, such as pass interference,
weren't subject to review when instant replay was in effect. But
how much would replay cameras help gauge pass interference, the
most commonly disputed call in the NFL today?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the toughest judgment call there is,'' Cowboys
quarterback Troy Aikman said. ``And not specific to any call made
for or against us, it's tough because nobody is really sure what
constitutes interference.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the rules, purposeful contact on the part of a
defender after the receiver has gone 5 yards beyond the line of
scrimmage, and before the ball has been touched by the receiver, is
illegal. But the line is fine between purposeful contact and
incidental contact, and both receivers and defenders have learned
how to gain subtle advantages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, it's not just the cornerbacks who initiate
contact,'' said Cowboys defensive backs coach Mike Zimmer. ``It can
become a wrestling match.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Brandt: ``Because the game is so much faster,
well-conditioned officials find themselves unable to catch up.
Watch closely, and you'll even see the umpire used on purpose as a
pick \Rreceivers running their defenders into the official, hoping
to `pick off' the defender\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent NFL rule changes seemed to have given the advantages to
the offense, including allowing blockers to extend their arms on
blocks and the no-contact-beyond-5-yards rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to clutch, you've got to grab, you've got to gain
any edge you can against these receivers, who are now the
thoroughbreds of the sport,'' Minnesota Vikings coach Dennis Green
said. ``I don't think it's a matter of poor officiating; I think
it's a matter of some teams not taking advantage of the edges
available.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo Bills would disagree. They lost, 25-21, on Sunday to
New England because of what they call a ``phantom'' interference
call. The trailing Patriots tossed a ``Hail Mary'' pass into the
end zone on the game's final play, the pass caromed off receiver
Terry Glenn's chest, and the Bills began to celebrate. But while
replays seem to indicate incidental contact at worst, officials
ruled that Bills safety Henry Jones nudged Glenn and called pass
interference. New England then scored the game-winning TD.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if the NFL fines me,'' said Bills owner Ralph
Wilson, usually a good and quiet NFL soldier. ``This was the worst
officiating I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL did fine Wilson $50,000, but Wilson said the NFL then
apologized, admitting the officials made a mistake by calling Jones
for pass interference.
</P>
<P>
   All of which begs the question of how to improve the
officiating.
</P>
<P>
   NFL watchers will notice that there are no heavyweight NFL
officials; a strict conditioning program prevents that. That NFL
officials are not full time has long been a point of contention,
but most NFL executives see no advantage to changing the present
structure.
</P>
<P>
   And the league doesn't take its responsibility here lightly. On
Sunday nights, a staff of experts collects in the league offices in
New York to review the work of the NFL's 112 striped shirts. The
league demands the officiating teams make the correct call at least
90 percent of the time. Their studies indicate that the officials
make an average of three poor calls per game.
</P>
<P>
   And the coin-toss dispute has resulted in a change: The player
will now call ``heads'' or ``tails'' before the flip, rather than
while the coin is in the air. And two other officials will join the
referee in observing the process.
</P>
<P>
   NFL senior director of officiating Jerry Seeman has a motto.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make Super Bowl decisions,'' Seeman said, ``not Woolworth's
calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, from coin tosses to pass interference, some NFL teams
seem to feel like the officiating is causing them to get
nickel-and-dimed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
