<SLUG> BC-SCOTTISH-POWER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOTTISH POWER AND PACIFICORP SAID TO DISCUSS DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scottish Power PLC, which has been seeking an electric utility
in the United States, is in discussions to acquire Pacificorp, a
major provider of power in the Northwest, people close to the talks
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   They said executives from the two companies were discussing a
possible combination over the weekend, and while those discussions
could fall apart at any time, it was expected that a deal could be
announced as early as Monday.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a deal, it would be the first purchase of an entire
U.S. utility by a foreign company.
</P>
<P>
   The value of the transaction under discussion was not known. But
two British newspapers, The Sunday Times and The Sunday Telegraph
of London, first reported last month that Scottish Power was
interested in buying Pacificorp for $6.6 billion. Both companies
have declined to comment on any possible discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Scottish Power, based in Glasgow, Scotland, supplies electricity
to about 5 million homes in England, Wales and Scotland. It also
has operations in telecommunications, water and waste services.
</P>
<P>
   The company has been interested in expanding into the U.S.
electricity market, which is opening to competition. It was
reported to have discussed possible purchases of Florida Progress
Corp. and Cinergy Corp., a Midwest utility based in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   A takeover of Pacificorp would complete a big reversal for the
company, which was viewed as a potential buyer of a British utility
earlier this year. It lost a bidding war for Energy Group PLC of
Britain to Texas Utilities Co. in August.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Pacificorp's stock has fallen sharply and the company
has become the subject of considerable takeover speculation. Its
shares closed Friday at $20.75, up $1.3125, and the highest in
nearly three months.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than try to grow through acquisition, Pacificorp has said
it will focus attention on its 1.4 million customers in the Pacific
Northwest. Its subsidiaries, Pacific Power and Light and Utah Power
and Light, operate in nine Western states. The company also owns an
Australian utility, Powercor.
</P>
<P>
   A purchase of Pacificorp by Scottish Power would require
approval of U.S. energy regulators and the shareholders of both
companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
