<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-CAPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPITALS SCORE FOUR IN FINAL PERIOD TO BREAK SLUMP 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They were the kind of routine shots Tommy Salo
allowed into the Islanders' net with frequency last season. Three
shots, all of which appeared to be stoppable, got through Salo in
the third period Friday night, and that was more than enough for
the Washington Capitals to beat the Islanders, 5-1, at the MCI
Center.
</P>
<P>
   It was Salo's worst performance of the season, and it could not
have come at a worse time. The loss was the fourth straight for the
Islanders, who are at the bottom of the Atlantic Division and
sinking.
</P>
<P>
   Salo, who faced 28 shots, allowed four goals in the third
period, three in the span of 1 minute 39 seconds. The first two
were scored on weak shots by Calle Johansson, giving the Capitals
leads of 2-1 and 3-1. Salo, whose solid play through the first two
months of the season elicited considerable praise from coaches and
opposing players, was not screened on either of those goals.
</P>
<P>
   The defending Eastern Conference champion Capitals, who were
playing without their captain, Adam Oates, also got goals from
Peter Bondra and Steve Konowalchuk in the third period. Oates was
sidelined with a nagging groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   Washington had lost three straight before Friday night, and in
an attempt to shake his team and its struggling goaltender Olaf
Kolzig out of their slump, Capitals Coach Ron Wilson benched
Kolzig. Kolzig, whose record has dipped to 6-10-1 with a 2.99 goals
against average and an .885 save percentage, was ranked 37th among
the 41 goalies who have played a minimum of 360 minutes. He was
replaced by Rick Tabaracci, who, in his fourth start of the season,
made 22 stops.
</P>
<P>
   Tabaracci's most impressive save came late in the first period
when he stopped the flashy Mariusz Czerkawski on a penalty shot.
Czerkawski, the Islanders' best stick handler, was awarded the shot
after he was pulled down by Joe Reekie on a breakaway with 39.8
seconds left in the period. Crzerkawksi faked left, right, then
left again on the penalty shot, but the elastic Tabaracci stopped a
backhand attempt and kept the game scoreless.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams scored once in a fast-paced and exciting second
period. Robert Reichel gave the Islanders a 1-0 lead at 4:39 when
he deflected a shot from the point by defenseman Zdeno Chara. Ken
Klee scored for the Capitals at 14:48 by beating a screened Salo
over the glove from the middle of right circle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
