<SLUG> BC-NY-POLITICIAN-ARREST-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTY'S GOP DEBATES FUTURE OF ACCUSED CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOHEMIA, N.Y. _ Faced with a leadership crisis, Suffolk County
Republicans closed ranks Friday as they privately debated the
future of their party chairman, John Powell, after his arrest on
Thursday on federal bribery and truck-theft charges.
</P>
<P>
   While party officials expressed shock and dismay at Powell's
legal problems, there was a notable absence of praise from those he
had helped put in office.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki, who once credited Powell with delivering the
votes from Suffolk County that won him the governor's mansion, said
Friday: ``Obviously, it was very shocking. Beyond that, the process
will have to go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor, who was in Washington meeting with congressional
leaders and other Republican governors, was asked whether he
thought Powell should resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``While these charges are pending,'' Pataki said, ``it's going
to be very difficult for him to exercise any real leadership role
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before his arrest, Powell was criticized by some state and
local Republican leaders for failing to produce the same hefty
voter turnout in the November election as he had in the past and
was blamed by some for losses, including the apparent defeat of the
Republican state attorney general, Dennis Vacco. Republicans
outnumber Democrats 2-to-1 in Suffolk.
</P>
<P>
   While stressing that Powell was innocent until proved otherwise,
political insiders here and in Albany said the county party needed
to quickly find a new leader who could oversee the selection of
candidates for several important elections in the next year.
</P>
<P>
   They also said that the federal case against Powell, which was
based on a yearlong investigation that spanned three states and
involved wiretaps by numerous informers, appeared to be too strong
to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're waiting for the dust to settle before we make our next
move,'' said one highly placed Republican official at county
government offices in Hauppauge. ``It's all anyone has been talking
about all day. The phones are ringing and the wires are hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Party leaders said they were surprised to learn that agents of
the FBI showed up at Powell's home in Medford at dawn on Thursday
and led him away in handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is going to give me back my reputation?'' Powell asked as
the agents later escorted him into U.S. District Court in
Uniondale.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, 38, who dismissed the charges as ``a joke,'' was back at
home Friday morning, having posted a $100,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   He told friends that he was stunned by the arrest and, as a
political realist who became one of the youngest top Republican
leaders in the country when he took charge of the county
organization in 1995, was questioning his chances for survival.
</P>
<P>
   He was arraigned on charges including trading in stolen trucks
and taking bribes to allow illegal landfill dumping in Brookhaven,
the largest town in Suffolk County and the base of Powell's
political power where he once worked as a payload operator in the
Department of Public Works.
</P>
<P>
   As Powell reviewed the 76-page federal complaint filed against
him with his lawyer, Raymond Perini, Friday morning, workers at
party headquarters were trying to carry on as usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I brought in a half a gallon of milk for our coffee and we're
hanging out doing what we usually do, figuring out how to win
elections,'' said Alan Eysen, the chief spokesman for the party and
Powell.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Powell planned to finish his current two-year term
as party chairman, which runs through next September.
</P>
<P>
   Eysen issued a brief statement signed by the party's executives,
including its vice chairman, Frank Volz, and treasurer, Marietta
Seaman, saying that while Powell ``is now accused of a variety of
allegations, none has been put to the legal test.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement added: ``The presumption of innocence is a basic
tenet of our democratic society, and this applies to Powell. He,
therefore, will continue to carry out his duties as party chairman
into the foreseeable future.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   How long that foreseeable future lasts rests with top Republican
elected officials, including the Suffolk County executive, Robert
Gaffney, who spent much of the day discussing the matter privately
with party members on Long Island and in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, he issued a brief statement saying, ``Obviously, I am
shocked and dismayed by the charges, which, if true, constitute
serious violations.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaffney, a former agent of the FBI, noted that the charges
against Powell had been brought jointly by the U.S. attorney for
the Eastern District, the FBI and the Suffolk County Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   After a careful reading of the complaint, several political
insiders said the demands of preparing a legal defense would leave
Powell with little time for party business.
</P>
<P>
   The first test of the party's effectiveness will come next month
during a special election in Suffolk's 5th Legislative District,
recently made vacant by the departure of a popular Democrat, Nora
Bredes. Candidates remain to be chosen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fallout is bound to affect the race in the 5th District,''
said legislator Steve Levy, a Democrat. ``You won't even have to
raise the subject of John Powell. It will just be there, an
undercurrent that the voters won't ignore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
