<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALIAN HURT; SWEDEN TAKES COMMANDING LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; MILAN, Italy _ The Davis Cup has long made a habit of transforming
mundane encounters into memorable ones, and that habit was not
broken Friday night, which ended with Sweden leading Italy by 2-0
in the Davis Cup final. The nearly five-hour opening match came to
a close abruptly and prematurely with Andrea Gaudenzi in great pain
and Magnus Norman in great spirits after a 6-7 (9-11), 7-6 (7-0),
4-6, 6-3, 6-6 (30-0) victory.
</P>
<P>
   Gaudenzi, Italy's top player, had rallied from a 4-0 deficit in
the fifth set with a lot of help from the nervous Norman to take a
6-5 lead. But on the final point of that 11th game, Gaudenzi hit a
serve and felt a tendon crack in his fragile right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   As Norman's return missed, Gaudenzi hunched over at midcourt and
clenched his fists. At first, it appeared he was merely expressing
emotion, but it soon became clear that he was hurting. Gaudenzi has
undergone two operations on his right shoulder, most recently on
Oct. 1 when he had arthroscopic surgery to clean out the joint and
to alleviate the pain that had forced him to take cortisone
injections during Italy's semifinal victory over the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't even lift a cup on the changeover,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gaudenzi lifted himself out of his chair and returned to the
court but not for long. Norman held at love to even the match at
6-6. Gaudenzi then gamely attempted to serve. He lost the first
point when Norman greeted his soft second serve with a huge
forehand return winner. In the middle of the next exchange, the
Italian stopped playing, shook his head and trudged toward the net
to retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played with the pain for five hours, and I couldn't stand it
anymore; at that stage the pain was just too big,'' Gaudenzi said.
</P>
<P>
   Norman had prevailed, and Sweden's excellent chances of
capturing this final only got better when Magnus Gustafsson crushed
Davide Sanguinetti, 6-1, 6-4, 6-0, in the second singles match.
</P>
<P>
   The Swedes now need only one victory in the final three matches
to defend their title and earn their seventh Davis Cup
championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Italians, who are seeking their first title since 1976, will
have to rely on Sanguinetti to play with Diego Nargiso against the
fine Swedish doubles team of Jonas Bjorkman and Nicklas Kulti on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The tennis that Norman and Gaudenzi played was not always pretty
_ there were unforced errors and missed opportunities aplenty _ but
it was always earnest. When Norman met Gaudenzi at the net, the two
baseliners with streaks of clay across their shirts embraced and
exchanged compliments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt very, very sorry for Andrea because he was playing an
unbelievable match,'' Norman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-04-98 2332EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
