<DOCNO> NYT19981204.0525 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-04 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4414 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-SHUTTLE-2NDTAKE-N     12-04 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SHUTTLE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CAPE CANAVERAL: million apiece.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a May 22 report, the General Accounting Office, the
investigative arm of Congress, estimated the station's building
cost at $53 billion and its total including operations at $96
billion _ not including the cost of decommissioning by sending it
plummeting into the ocean, for which NASA has no estimate so far.
</P>
<P>
   Added to that are the contributions of the international
partners, such as $6.7 billion from the European Space Agency and
an amount from Russia that is still uncertain because of Moscow's
financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, experts put the estimated cost at no less than $110
billion, adding, however, that it could well be higher and that
only time will tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than the Manhattan Project but less than Apollo,''
said John Pike, head of space policy at the Federation of American
Scientists, a private group in Washington. The Manhattan Project to
build the atom bomb cost about $20 billion in today's dollars, he
said, and the Apollo program that repeatedly put men on the Moon
about $125 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Pike backs the station as smart politically if it helps
stabilize Russia. But many scientists fault it as an enormous waste
of money, saying its huge costs and growing budget overruns have
already hurt NASA programs and are destined to spread pain further.
</P>
<P>
   Leif Robinson, editor of Sky and Telescope, a top astronomy
magazine, based in Cambridge, Mass., in the current issue strongly
criticized how America killed the half-built Superconducting
Supercollider, an $8 billion project meant to illuminate the
building blocks of matter, but backed the international space
station, or ISS, which he ridiculed as a ``flying fiasco.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the atom smasher's ghost, he wrote, ``will rise up and
drag the ISS down to the hell it deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   Backers hail the outpost as a foreign-policy coup and a stepping
stone to human exploration of Mars and more distant worlds, saying
its studies of human physiology are a must for learning how people
can venture far from Earth.
</P>
<P>
   If it is ever completed, that is. Some experts doubt that the
political wherewithal exists to finish its dozens of assembly
flights over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. McClain of NASA headquarters said that at least in
terms of U.S. gear, some 70 percent had already been finished and
that fabrication work was well under way on the remaining 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Private analysts say that with hundreds of tons of hardware
already in the assembly pipeline, and tens of billions of dollars
already spent, the project, though controversial, probably has the
political momentum to keep pushing ahead for many years to come.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
