<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICERS CLEARED IN SHOOTING OF YOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two police officers who shot and critically wounded a
teen-ager who was carrying a water pistol last August acted
appropriately, since they mistook the toy for a gun, the Brooklyn
district attorney said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The youth, Michael Jones, 16, was hit by six of the 16 shots
fired at him during an Aug. 23 encounter on a Bedford-Stuyvesant
street about 2:30 a.m. The officers, Sgt. Michael Jacobellis and
Officer David Gross, who were working in plain clothes, had
confronted the teen-ager after they were alerted to a report of a
gun-brandishing bicyclist.
</P>
<P>
   Michael was hospitalized for two months and is still unable to
walk, a spokesman for his family said.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting was one in a series of incidents in which
teen-agers and younger children were shot by police officers who
said they mistook toy guns for real ones. It led to renewed
arguments that highly realistic toy guns were still easy to buy
despite laws banning their sale and possession.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney, Charles Hynes, said an investigation by
his office of the shooting strongly upheld the officers' actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sequence of events initiated by Michael Jones created a
volatile and dangerous condition causing these officers to take
appropriate police action,'' Hynes said, referring to a report that
the youth, who had no criminal record, had been pointing what
appeared to be a type of particularly lethal semiautomatic handgun
at passing cars.
</P>
<P>
   Hynes said the water pistol ``closely resembled a real weapon''
and he also cited Gross' statement that when he shouted, ``Police,
freeze!'' Michael ``pointed the gun at him.''
</P>
<P>
   The finding and the methods of Hynes' investigation _ evidence
was not presented to a grand jury _ were immediately denounced by
the spokesman for the Jones family, the Rev. Al Sharpton, who said
the finding was political.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you have a situation with 16 shots and it doesn't
warrant a grand jury investigation?'' Sharpton asked, adding that
such an investigation would have been more effective in getting at
the truth. Hynes' reasoning ``does not make sense to me,'' Sharpton
said, because ``I don't know how he justifies the 16 shots,'' 15 of
which investigators said Gross fired.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton also said he did not believe the officer's statement
that Michael pointed the gun at him. ``Why would you brandish a gun
at the police when you know it's not a real gun?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton said that he would ask the U.S. Justice Department to
review the case and that the Jones family planned to file a lawsuit
against the city.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Hynes, Patrick Clark, said the case was not
presented to a grand jury, because the district attorney ``reviewed
the evidence and determined it did not warrant presentation.'' As
for Sharpton's contention that Hynes had made a ``political''
finding, Clark said his conclusion was based ``solely on the
evidence and the law.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The teen-ager told investigators that he had heard the officer
shout ``Freeze,'' but that ``before he could respond there were a
hail of bullets,'' Hynes said. The youth also said that while he
was on the ground, wounded, one of the officers approached and
fired twice more into his legs, Hynes said.
</P>
<P>
   But ballistic and other forensic evidence and the account of a
civilian witness indicated that this was not the case, Hynes said.
``The overwhelming evidence is that it did not happen,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
