<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-CARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLE REVERSALS FOR TEAMS AND QUARTERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ When the Giants met the Arizona Cardinals on
Oct. 12, 1997, Kent Graham was the starting quarterback for the
Cardinals and Danny Kanell was making his first start as the
Giants' quarterback, substituting for the injured Dave Brown.
</P>
<P>
   A little more than a year later, the Giants have returned to
Arizona and now Graham is their starter and Kanell has been demoted
after an unceremonious disintegration this season.
</P>
<P>
   Jake Plummer is a rising star of the Cardinals, perhaps of the
league. Brown is his backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of irony in this game,'' Graham said this week.
``It's all over the place. Now let's not have the ultimate irony
and I get hurt in this game like I did last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham was forced from the game in 1997 with an ankle injury,
and the Giants won easily. He never got his starting job back
because his absence opened the door for Plummer, who won the job
with an unorthodox yet efficient and exciting style.
</P>
<P>
   It was a crossroads game for the Giants, too. Kanell played well
in his first start that day, the first of seven victories in 10
games he orchestrated. Kanell played well again later in the season
against the Cardinals, and that ultimately made Brown expendable.
</P>
<P>
   In the off season, each team decided that it had a young
quarterback worth building around. Each team also decided it wanted
Graham as the backup.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals offered more money, but Graham, who had been
drafted by New York and played there between 1992 and 1994, chose
the Giants. Graham may have also determined that the Giants would
give him a better chance to play in the long run, although he will
not admit that this was any part of his thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Graham guessed that Kanell was on shakier ground than
Plummer. If so, then he guessed right. Graham is making his third
consecutive start Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who had few options other than signing with Arizona, has
played only once this year as Plummer's backup _ against the Giants
in October in a 34-17 rout by the Giants. Brown came in during
mop-up time to a chorus of boos from the Giants Stadium fans.
</P>
<P>
   As Brown said after the game: ``The Giants fans got what they
wanted today. I got to play and the Cardinals lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The two teams have done more than just switch quarterbacks in a
year's time. They have nearly switched roles. Last year, when the
Giants defeated the Cardinals they were on their way to a playoff
appearance. The Cardinals would finish 4-12.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the 6-6 Cardinals are trying to solidify their
tenuous hold on the final wild-card spot in the National Football
Conference. The 5-8 Giants are trying to avoid double digits in
losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wonder sometimes how so much can change in a year,''
Graham said. ``But this game picks you up one day and humbles you
the next. Or vice versa.''
</P>
<P>
   And Graham did acknowledge that playing well this Sunday would
have extra meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it means a lot to me,'' he said. ``Having the
opportunity to go back to a place you left just a year later is
unique and you want to make a good memory for yourself in that
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much that they didn't want me, because they made a
nice offer to keep me; it's that you're playing against guys you
know well and coaches you know well. You want to show that you're
doing a good job. And it means a lot because I really want to win
this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham then stated the obvious, given the recent history of
these two teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no telling how our quarterback situation is going to
play out,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   But he added: ``I'm pretty sure this is true: If we win, I get
to keep the job. So I want to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
