<SLUG> BC-BKC-STJOHN'S-ARTEST-830&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RON ARTEST: ALWAYS AT WORK AND READY TO PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In Queensbridge, the section of Long Island City
where Ron Artest grew up, not being tough means being run over. Not
depending on others can mean not surviving, and the easy road
almost always ends in disaster. Through fistfights and athletic
competition, those lessons were embedded into Artest's mentality.
So excuse him if he expects nothing less than the ultimate effort
from himself and his St. John's teammates on the basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where I came from, and the way I grew up, made me tough,''
said Artest, the sophomore forward who will lead the 25th-ranked
Red Storm into its Big East season opener Saturday at Boston
College (2-3). ``Fighting all the time, every day. That's how I got
to be like I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Having a fiery, uncompromising teammate like Artest can often
lead to tense moments. But it can also make a squad aggressive,
confident and unyielding. In winning five of its first seven games,
coach Mike Jarvis' Red Storm has seen both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after a second straight late-game collapse cost St.
John's a victory over 14th-ranked Purdue in the Chase Preseason
National Invitation Tournament, Artest loudly vented his
frustration in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just talked about trying to stay mentally tough,'' Artest
said of the incident. ``It was all positive, nothing negative. But
it got pretty emotional. I was yelling.''
</P>
<P>
   In its next two games, though, the Red Storm righted itself,
running away from St. Francis of Brooklyn and Hofstra without
looking back. Doing the same against Boston College, an opponent on
its level, will serve as proof that Artest's declamation got
through.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis, who in his first season at St. John's seems to have
developed a great rapport with his players, likes Artest's
willingness to step forward and lead. But like his predecessor,
Fran Fraschilla, he is trying to get Artest to be more tactful when
trying to get the best out of his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to help him further develop his leadership skills
by doing a better job of leading by example and not leading so much
in a vocal manner,'' Jarvis said. ``Because emotions can sometimes
get the best of you.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that Artest does not provide a fine example
for his teammates to follow. The muscular 6-foot-7-inch, 246-pound
small forward is a study in confident, hard-nosed play. Constantly
in motion in the Red Storm's hectic and fast-paced style, Artest
sprints up and down the floor, plays near the rim, and pounds
bodies with opponents until the whistle blows.
</P>
<P>
   And though he was only a second-team all-Big East preseason
selection, he considers no opponent to be better than he is. Fully
convinced that he could excel against Stanford's big and ballyhooed
front line, he scored 15 points and grabbed 7 rebounds in the
heart-wrenching 55-53 loss to the Cardinal last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't go home and have people saying, `You played soft,'''
said Artest, explaining the reason for his ruggedness on the court.
``When I go home and talk to everybody, I want them to say, `Yeah,
you represented.' I try to represent where I'm from.''
</P>
<P>
   Not just in games when the cameras are rolling, but in practice
as well. Jarvis, who has coached high school and college basketball
since 1968, said he has had only two players with a work ethic
equal to that of Artest _ Patrick Ewing and Rumeal Robinson, both
of whom played for Jarvis at Rindge and Latin High School in
Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronny would certainly fit in their class,'' Jarvis said.
``They worked hard in every drill and that's what made them
special. He doesn't work hard occasionally or once in a while; he
works hard every day, all of the time. That's why Ronny has a
chance for greatness.''
</P>
<P>
   Artest's tremendous potential has not been disputed since his
days at Manhattan's LaSalle Academy, where he earned all-America
status as a senior. Though only a part-time starter last season, he
showed that he could one day become one of the nation's top
players.
</P>
<P>
   In his first career start, he scored 24 points and tied a school
record with five 3-pointers in a victory over American University
of Puerto Rico. He also torched Boston College for a career-high 26
points and became perhaps more of an inspirational leader than the
seniors Felipe Lopez and Zendon Hamilton during a late-season
winning streak that helped the Red Storm advance to its first
National Collegiate Athletic Association tournament since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Averaging 14.8 points and 6 rebounds this year, Artest would
probably score more on a lesser team. But the Red Storm has five
players averaging double figures in points, a fact that excites
Artest more than having the team's highest-scoring average.
</P>
<P>
   That much was evident on Wednesday, when the freshman Erick
Barkley stole the spotlight by sinking five 3-pointers and scoring
25 points against Hofstra. Far from being upset about not leading
the club in scoring, Artest was raising his hands every time
Barkley hit a jumper.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Like the toughness, the confidence and the work ethic, the
unselfishness comes from his experiences in Queensbridge.
``Everything happens for a reason, and I guess fighting for my
friends all of the time made me a team player,'' Artest said. ``I
just don't want to be selfish. I put the team first, way ahead of
individual statistics.''
</P>
<P>
   A byproduct of Artest's unselfishness is his versatility.
Because he wants to be prepared to do whatever is necessary to help
the team win, he has not left any part of his game undeveloped. His
strength and leaping ability enable him to rebound and score
inside, and he handles the ball well enough to lead the fast break
and penetrate against halfcourt defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Though his build makes him look like a low-post player, he leads
the Red Storm with 15 3-point makes in 33 attempts. And, as he did
in limited duty last season, he leads the team in blocked shots and
is second to Barkley in assists (4.1) and steals (2.3).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got an unbelievably versatile game,'' Jarvis said. ``In a
year or so, he will legitimately vie for college basketball's
player of the year award if he continues to grow and develop and
keeps the same work ethic.''
</P>
<P>
   Being from Queensbridge, he probably will. After all, anything
less would not be representing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
